<SLUG> BC-GAS-EXPENSIVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPLIES, TEMPERS SHORT IN GAS-HUNGRY L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like a runaway bull market, gasoline prices in the
Los Angeles area continued their rapid rise on Thursday and in some
cases jumped 10 cents from the previous day's level.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden price surge, which saw the cost of a gallon of gas
jump by 25 cents during the past 14 days, could last for at least
two more weeks or possibly a bit longer, analysts and industry
officials predicted.
</P>
<P>
   A gallon of premium gasoline was selling for more than $1.70 a
gallon and regular unleaded for more than $1.40 a gallon at a
number of stations on Thursday, stunning market watchers and
commuters alike.
</P>
<P>
   Prices have been going up from 4 cents to 10 cents a day for the
past two weeks, according to Auto California, a trade group that
represents the state's service stations and repair shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the largest increase in the shortest amount of
time that we've ever had,'' said Susan Garfield, a spokeswoman for
the California Energy Commission, which keeps tabs on production at
the state's 13 refineries.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is so frustrating that a coalition of community
groups, including the Minorities for Tobacco, Alcohol and Drug Free
Cities; the Adoptive Families Foundation; and Congress of Racial
Equality today will stage a protest downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe Barry, pastor of the California Christian Center in
Compton, Calif., said that the coalition will call for a federal
investigation into the sudden price hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to lay out several recommendations for government
regulation on gas price increases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But industry officials rounded up the usual suspects in doling
out blame for the recent increases: a shrinking supply, increased
demand because of the holidays, production stoppages at refineries
in Northern and Southern California and an OPEC production cutback
that started Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies, including the region's leading retailer,
Atlantic Richfield Co., are now restricting the amount of gasoline
they will sell to dealers.
</P>
<P>
   For the next month, Arco dealers will only receive the same
amount of gas they sold in March instead of being able to buy
however much they think they can sell, according to Paul Langland,
a spokesman at Arco Products Co., the big refinery's marketing arm.
</P>
<P>
   Arco's gasoline production was recently interrupted several
times because of equipment problems at its refinery in Carson,
Calif. As a result, the refinery could not produce gasoline for one
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found ourselves ... short on gasoline. We're hoping to make
it to the end of the month without running out of gasoline to sell
to our stations,'' Langland said.
</P>
<P>
   To help ease the shortage, Arco is bringing gasoline in from the
Gulf Coast on tanker ships. He declined to say how much fuel the
company was importing.
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, doubt that supplies had slipped enough to cause
such a big price spike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Current gasoline production levels will not continue to
support the high prices consumers have been paying at the pump,''
Energy Commission Chairman William J. Keese said in a statement
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's assessment of state supplies found that March's
production of 880,000 barrels per day was 96 percent of normal for
the month. And 12 of the state's 13 refiners are producing gasoline
for the state's passenger vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This marker has been fueled by speculation during tight
supplies over the past two weeks, and consumers are feeling the
pinch,'' Keese said.
</P>
<P>
   Will Woods, Auto California's executive director, said that
distributors who sell to independents worried about severe
shortages, and this contributed to the run-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically bid up the price on the spot market,'' he said.
``It's basically an overreaction to conditions that may result from
the factors in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices could start sliding back down in about two weeks, Woods
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
