u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      04-02 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY TO RAISE MONEY FOR POTENTIAL DEMOCRATIC RIVAL FOR N.Y.
SENATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton has agreed to appear at a
fund-raiser for Rep. Nita M. Lowey, another potential candidate for
a Senate seat from New York, in an effort to allay concerns that
the first lady's prospective candidacy is disrupting the
fund-raising efforts of other Democratic hopefuls, party officials
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lowey's aides said she anticipated raising $500,000 from the
planned $1,000-a-plate dinner appearance by Mrs. Clinton on May 24
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The monetary goal is a testimony to the first lady's
fund-raising appeal and strong standing among New York Democrats.
By way of comparison, Ms. Lowey's entire political bank account was
$842,000 as of December.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual for a prospective candidate to help a possible
rival raise money for a campaign. Mrs. Clinton's agreement to help
Ms. Lowey is the latest indication of the ways that the first
lady's interest in elective office has tangled the political
situation in New York as Democrats prepare for the 2000 Senate
race.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton announced earlier this year that she was
considering seeking the nomination for the seat held by Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring next year at the end of his
fourth term. Ms. Lowey, a representative from Westchester County,
has also said that she would like to run for Moynihan's seat but
would not seek the nomination if Mrs. Clinton enters the race.
</P>
<P>
   Although the election is about 18 months away, the unusual
prospect of the first lady moving out of the White House and to New
York to run for office has created a potential problem for
Democrats, who are intent on not losing Moynihan's seat to the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Clinton's prospective candidacy has generated
considerable interest among party leaders, it has also effectively
halted Ms. Lowey's early fund-raising efforts, New York Democrats
say.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Clinton runs, that would not matter. But if Mrs. Clinton
announces later this year that she will not run, Ms. Lowey _ who is
not well known outside Westchester, and does not have much of a
fund-raising base _ would be left on a ledge. Normally, now would
be a time when Ms. Lowey would be tending to fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   While he was a representative from Brooklyn, Sen. Charles E.
Schumer spent almost six years raising the $12 million he used to
defeat Alfonse M. D'Amato last year.
</P>
<P>
   The leading Republican who has expressed an interest in the 2000
Senate race is Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who, if he won the
nomination, would probably not have difficulty raising money, given
his political stature in New York, Democrats and Republicans say.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hope, chairwoman of the state Democratic Party, said she
and Mrs. Clinton had discussed the problem and the first lady had
suggested that she was prepared to do something now on Ms. Lowey's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fully aware of the consequences of her taking some time
to consider whether or not to make this race,'' Ms. Hope said
Thursday. ``And she is fully willing to do whatever is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She expressed her concern _ and I concurred _ that this is an
issue that needs to be addressed,'' Ms. Hope said. ``She was quick
to assure me that however this turns out, she will aggressively
raise money for the Democratic nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said Mrs. Clinton's decision to raise money
for Ms. Lowey should not be taken as any indication of what the
first lady might do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it means anything with regard to her own
intentions,'' said Howard Wolfson, Ms. Lowey's spokesman. ``It
means everything with regard to her keeping the Senate seat
Democratic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
