<HEADER>
A3382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KNICKS-CAVS-NYT &LR;      04-02 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KNICKS-CAVS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL THE STARTER RIDES THE BENCH DURING KNICKS' RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Latrell Sprewell absorbed a glorious introduction,
with laser lights and flashbulbs as his escorts, when he jogged
onto the court as part of the Knicks' starting lineup. This is what
he had campaigned for, the thrill of being a starter.
</P>
<P>
   But this is where his fulfillment ended Thursday night. Sprewell
was not apart of the grandeur when a collection of B-movie players
_ guys like Marcus Camby and Chris Childs _ scrambled to make up a
13-point, third-quarter deficit and picked up the pieces around
Patrick Ewing's forgettable night from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, nursing a sore Achilles' tendon, hit only 2 of 12 shots,
but Childs came through and scored 9 fourth-quarter points, while
Camby came up with 5 rebounds and a key block in the final 10
minutes of a 78-74 victory against the Cleveland Cavaliers at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in place of the injured Larry Johnson, Sprewell was on
the bench for the last eight minutes of the game and missed the
bulk of an 18-9 run that erased the Cavs' 13-point lead in the
third. Sprewell ended the game just 3 of 9 for 11 points, and he
had 4 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Jeff,'' said Sprewell, when questioned on why he wasn't in
the game at the end. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy had a simple answer. He played the hottest
hand. Childs, who scored 11 points, changed the mood of the game
when he parlayed a driving layup into a foul and 3-point play; and
then, as an encore, delivered a 3-pointer to give the Knicks a
lead, 66-65, with 5 minutes 39 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   To get to that point, the Knicks forced seven turnovers in 10
minutes and forced their way inside on offense to get to the
free-throw line. In the fourth quarter, the Knicks hit 10 of 11
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ewing, who re-injured his Achilles' against Indiana in
his 37-point performance on Tuesday, was not hitting his shot, he
did sink two free throws with 39.4 seconds left in the game to give
the Knicks a 75-73 lead during a back-and-forth finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers, led by Shawn Kemp's 25 points, had a chance to
win the game on an open 3-pointer by Derek Anderson with 6.9
seconds left. He missed, the Cavs got the rebound, but Brevin
Knight was off on an 18-foot jumper. For the second game in a row,
the Knicks escaped a defeat at the buzzer. Perhaps their fortunes
are starting to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed strong mentally,'' Van Gundy said. ``We're going to
struggle offensively when our main players don't shoot well, but I
felt the other guys stepped it up. I liked the way we came back in
the fourth. You have to win games like that when your best
offensive players aren't scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sprewell experiment sent the Knicks into a dysfunctional
tailspin for much of the game. With Sprewell starting and stirring
up the system by pushing the ball at every turn, Ewing and Houston
were thrown off their games.
</P>
<P>
   With Sprewell on the floor, the Knicks were down by 11 points
two minutes into the second quarter before he was taken out for the
remainder of the half. After the Knicks pulled to within 39-35 at
the half, Sprewell came out as a starter in the third quarter and
the Cavaliers went on a 15-8 run.
</P>
<P>
   With four turnovers, Sprewell was the common element as the
Knicks trailed by as many as 13 in the third, but he was by no
means the only reason the crowd turned on their team and sent a
cascade of boos down to greet them.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp was not Sprewell's responsibility. Not only did Kemp bump
Ewing outside and away from the basket, he scored 14 first-half
points. Meanwhile, Ewing missed 8 of his first 10 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Once Kemp went to the bench for a break, the Knicks capitalized
on the vulnerable Cavaliers, who turned the ball over five times in
the final 4:24 of the third quarter. The Knicks stumbled
themselves, but pulled to within 59-52 entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Sprewell made his exit. Mostly, he was a
distraction to the Knicks' half-court ways with Ewing on the floor.
Camby entered the game for Ewing with three minutes left in the
first quarter and the Knicks down by 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   Things just grew worse before Camby found his groove during the
game. After Kemp hammered away inside against a collection of
Knicks and Danny Ferry darted to the perimeter in front of Camby
for two straight jumpers to start off the second quarter, the
Cavaliers took a 26-17 lead. That lead grew to 12 points before the
Knicks returned to their normal offense.
</P>
<P>
   Without Sprewell and Camby on the floor for the last 10 minutes
of the first half, the Knicks leaned on Ewing and Houston during a
10-2 run that was topped by a 3-pointer from Charlie Ward. Ewing
was just 2 for 8 in the first half and the Knicks shot just 33
percent in the half.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   PATRICK EWING was spared the worst of the league's punishment
following his fracas with Indiana's JALEN ROSE during the second
quarter of the Knicks' victory Tuesday. After ROD THORN, the vice
president of basketball operations, reviewed the incident Thursday,
Ewing was fined $2,500 for escalating the tension by charging
toward Rose after he was intentionally tripped by the Pacers'
forward. Rose was suspended for one game and fined $5,000 for
tripping Ewing and throwing a forearm that inadvertently struck the
official, DICK BAVETTA, and broke his nose. ... LATRELL SPREWELL's
starting job may be short-lived. LARRY JOHNSON was churning the
stationery bike in the back of the Knicks' training room before
Thursday night's game with surprising freedom. An hour earlier, he
ran up and down the Madison Square Garden court without feeling too
much discomfort less than 48 hours after he sprained the medial
collateral ligament in his right knee against the Indiana Pacers.
``It feels pretty good,'' said Johnson. ``It feels better than I
expected. It looks good for Sunday.'' The Knicks play Indiana on
Sunday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
