<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-HAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS WIN A BIG ONE, BUT WILLIAMS IS LOST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ These are ill-fated times for the Nets.
After numerous injuries, the firing of their coach and
disappointing play, their finest victory of the season Thursday
night was overshadowed by a season-ending injury to Jayson
Williams, their top rebounder and spiritual leader.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has played all season with a broken nose and
damaged left thumb, broke a bone in his right leg when he collided
with Stephon Marbury with 50.9 seconds left in the Nets' 90-85
victory over the Atlanta Hawks (19-13) at Continental Arena. After
laying on the floor for several minutes, Williams was helped off
the court and taken on a stretcher to the Hackensack Medical Center
for X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   Williams suffered a displaced tibial plateau fracture and is
likely out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we're snakebitten,'' said Kendall Gill, who
sparked the Nets to their sixth victory. ``Things finally go right
and still something goes wrong. We're happy with the win. I hope
that Jay is all right. I know he's hurt because Jayson doesn't get
hurt. Even if he's hurting he'll get up. That's the first time I've
ever seen him not get up. Hopefully, he's okay.''
</P>
<P>
   With Rony Seikaly (right foot) and Jim McIlvaine (left shoulder)
already injured, the Nets' top three centers are out indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who grabbed 10 rebounds in 39 minutes, was injured
doing what he does better than anyone in the National Basketball
Association _ attacking the basket for an offensive rebound. After
outscoring the Hawks by 29-14 in the third quarter, the Nets were
leading by 85-83 when Marbury sliced through Atlanta's defense to
sink a running 7-footer.
</P>
<P>
   When Marbury left his feet to put up a shot, Williams began
getting into position for a rebound. While in the air, Marbury was
brushed by Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo and then run into by the
hard-charging Williams, who hit him in the back with his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury landed awkwardly on Williams' right leg, forcing the
6-foot-10-inch center to the floor. While the Hawks ran the ball
upcourt, Marbury and Williams laid beneath the basket nearly
motionless with their legs tangled.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury had the wind knocked out of him and got up after a few
minutes. At first, he appeared to be just as seriously injured as
Williams, and his mother, Mable, ran across the court from her seat
to see if he was OK. The two hugged when Marbury arose, and while
his mother walked back to her seat, Marbury ran after her and
hugged her at midcourt, to the cheers of 14,348 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary,'' said Marbury, who provided a clutch
performance by scoring 11 of his game-high 27 points in the fourth
quarter. ``I got caught in the back and usually you get the wind
knocked out of you from the front. I was trying to recover my
breath. I couldn't breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was just worried. That's just how she is. I told her I
was all right and she said she doesn't care about me playing
basketball as long as she has me.''
</P>
<P>
   Though excited about beating Atlanta, the best road team in the
league with a 10-5 record, the Nets were distraught about losing
their heart and soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you lose a player of his caliber, it hurts,'' said
Keith Van Horn, who had 24 points and 9 rebounds after missing two
games with a sprained right ankle. ``But to lose Jayson, who has
fought through everything this year is really tough. It's going to
be hard to replace him because he might be the hardest-working guy
in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   STEPHON MARBURY wrote ``KG 21, I See U'' on his ankle tape
Thursday night in honor of his former Minnesota Timberwolves
teammate, KEVIN GARNETT. ``I just wanted to say what's up to him,''
Marbury said &UR;  &LR; . . . ERIC MURDOCK, who has been on the injured list
with a sore left knee since March 12, was recently told by a doctor
in Miami that the knee has a stress fracture. He was told to rest
for another week and a half and then attempt to return . . . JAMIE
FEICK &UR;  &LR; was signed to his second 10-day contract Thursday. WILL
CUNNINGHAM &UR;  &LR; will be signed to his second 10-day contract Friday and
MARK HENDRICKSON will be signed to one on Sunday . . . SCOTT
BURRELL (sprained right ankle) said he expects to be activated from
the injured list early next week. RONY SEIKALY &UR;  &LR; (plantar fasciaitis
in right foot) will then be placed on the injured list. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
