<HEADER>
A3387 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-CLIPPER     04-02 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-CLIPPERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS STICK WITH REGULARS, PUT DOWN CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks have their self-esteem back, thanks to
the NBA sending the lowly Los Angeles Clippers to Reunion Arena
last night.
</P>
<P>
   And, thanks, also to Mavericks coach and general manager Don
Nelson for holding off on that youth movement at least for a game
or two.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson played his five starters 34 or more minutes, and the
Mavericks needed every ounce of their energy to slip past the
Clippers, 93-84, before an announced crowd of 13,336. The victory
was the Mavericks' third in the past 11 games, and that it came
against the league's worst team didn't go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a nightmare,'' guard Steve Nash said of a
potential loss to the 3-27 Clippers. ``I hate to say it, but a lot
of times you say it can't get any worse, and it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have actually gone way down on the scale. So it's
best to get this win. It was immeasurable for our confidence _ at
least salvaging it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks shot 50.7 percent from the field _ only the third
time they eclipsed the 50 percent barrier this season _ and snapped
a three-game losing streak. Dallas takes an 11-22 record into their
one and only three-day break of the season before taking on the
Minnesota Timberwolves on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson didn't take many chances dabbling with his bench. He
played four reserves a total of 48 minutes, as he wanted to make
sure the Clippers team that racked up wins over Utah, Minnesota and
Sacramento wasn't going to sneak into town and wreck this team even
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard-fought game for us, and we had to do whatever we
could do to win this one tonight,'' Nelson said. ``If I had to play
five guys 48 minutes each _ whatever it took to win this game _ I
thought it was important that we do that, and we did that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bench didn't get that much of an opportunity tonight, but
there will be other games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers didn't go quietly into the night. They erased an
early 12-point deficit, led at one point by six points and only
trailed 81-80 with less than five minutes left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Finley scored eight of his 22 points down the
stretch as the Mavericks increased their home record to 9-8. It's
their best home start after 17 games since going 11-6 in the
1989-90 season.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks forward Gary Trent had 11 points, six rebounds and
three assists in dominating the first quarter, which ended with the
Mavericks nursing a 28-18 lead. But the Clippers fought back to
lead 46-44 at the half, only to see the Mavericks regroup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to play within the flow of the offense,'' said
Trent, who finished with 23 points, 11 rebounds and six assists.
``We had a balanced attack, and the biggest thing is we helped each
other a whole lot on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash finished with a flourish, totaling 12 points (5-of-6
shooting), nine assists, a season-high seven rebounds and three
steals. Shawn Bradley had 16 points, 13 rebounds and five blocks,
and A.C. Green collected 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a game that we thought we should win and get this
monkey off our backs,'' Nelson said. ``We just approached it as we
have to figure out a way to do that, and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley said focusing on the task at hand was somewhat difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for us to get in and have intensity going up against
a team like the Lakers,'' Finley said. `'But when you're going up
against a team like the Clippers, who have been struggling,
mentally you have to be focused. And I think for the most part we
were like that tonight.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
