<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-SEHORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEHORN TESTS KNEE (JUST DON'T TELL GIANTS) 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jason Sehorn, recovering from major reconstructive knee surgery,
didn't tell the Giants he was planning to defend his championship
in the Superstars competition when it was held last month in
Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want them to get all worried,'' Sehorn said from his
California home Thursday. ``You know, I'm a big investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants Coach Jim Fassel admitted Thursday that had he known
Sehorn was competing, ``my heart might have been in my mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I trust Jason,'' Fassel said. ``He's smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently _ despite tearing the anterior cruciate and medial
collateral ligaments in his right knee in a preseason game last
Aug. 20 _ he's also fit.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn won the competition again, defeating a collection of
athletes from various sports, including the Olympic decathlon
champion Dan O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy's got to do what a guy's got to do,'' Sehorn said,
laughing. ``I knew what I was doing. It was fun to get out and be
an athlete again instead of inside some gym riding a stationary
bike.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Sehorn stood at the start of the swimming portion of
the competition, his stomach was in knots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea if I could swim,'' he said. ``I hadn't swum
since the Superstars last year. What if I jump in the water and the
knee doesn't work? What if I can't kick? I was nervous and I never
get nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran down the beach, jumped in and I was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   He won the swimming competition, and the biking part of the
competition and the kayaking. He was second in weight lifting to
the Tampa Bay defensive lineman Warren Sapp, second in the
half-mile run and the jet-ski race, and third in golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite amazing, isn't he?'' Fassel said when he heard Sehorn
had won the Superstars competition again.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors in the event, which will be televised by CBS
Saturday and Sunday, are required to enter seven of 10 events.
Because of his knee, Sehorn chose to avoid the 100-yard dash, the
basketball competition and the obstacle course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up doing the obstacle course anyway,'' Sehorn said.
``I was showing some other people how to do it and next thing I
knew I was climbing up and over the 15-foot wall anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn expected O'Brien to be his chief competition and was
flabbergasted when he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dan finished fourth over all,'' Sehorn said. ``To beat
him was nice. He's the world's best athlete? Yeah, well, don't take
him off the track. He was a nice guy, I'll say that. But Joey
Galloway smoked him in the 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway is a Seattle Seahawks Pro Bowl wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn called his time in Jamaica a beginning to another stage
of his long comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't give me any false hope when it comes to football,''
Sehorn said. ``My knee felt great but I wasn't playing football. I
know there's a big difference. The Superstars was a venue for me to
get started. I had told my trainers in rehab in November that I was
going to defend my title.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were like, `Yeah, sure, whatever.' But I put March in my
mind for motivation. Next I'm looking forward to minicamp in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn estimated his knee was 85-90 percent of what it needs to
be for the rigors of his cornerback position. He said he has been
working out so often that he's added 10 pounds of muscle and now
weighs 222 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never worked this hard before in my life,'' he said.
``I'll be just as quick and agile but I can't promise you I'll be
100 percent this season. I know I'll feel pain. I wake up some
mornings and my knee is sore. It's not like I don't know which knee
had the operation. But it's a process and I don't have to play a
game for another five months.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said the Giants doctors have given him nothing but
positive reports on Sehorn's progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been running on the beach and roller blading and lifting
weights,'' Fassel said, ``so the Superstars thing wasn't any
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that New England running back Robert Edwards sustained
what may be a career-ending knee injury in an exhibition event on
sand in January, Fassel said:
</P>
<P>
   ``He was playing touch football in the sand. Jason wasn't
playing football. He was running on sand. Some people will tell you
that's the best thing for your legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn, always optimistic and upbeat, seemed especially
energized by his success in the Superstars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a blast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But before the event, he didn't want publicity about his
appearance in the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that was then, now it's OK,'' Sehorn said Thursday. ``If
I'd got hurt, I'd be down at CBS telling them, `You can't air
that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But hey, I won.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
