<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3398 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-JAZZ-HNS &LR;      04-02 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-JAZZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SALT LAKE CITY _ This time, there was no way the Rockets would
allow John Stockton to launch another shot to beat them. Stockton
cut behind another pick, and the Rockets refused to relive the
heartache of the 1997 Western Conference finals when Stockton hid
behind a screen and nailed a 3-pointer to complete a stunning,
improbable comeback.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time, Charles Barkley jumped out and cut him off. Stockton
took a step back and drove the lane. Hakeem Olajuwon slid over.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had let a 15-point fourth-quarter lead slip away
before regaining a one-point edge, but visions of Stockton's
celebration had begun haunting again. The Rockets were all over the
Jazz point guard as the last few seconds ticked away.
</P>
<P>
   This time, instead of shooting, Stockton passed to Karl Malone
to complete a stunning, improbable comeback. All by himself in the
corner, Malone took the pass and swished his jumper with 2.7
seconds left, lifting the Jazz to an 88-87 win Thursday night and
ending the Rockets' winning streak at nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hakeem can't leave Karl Malone, plain and simple,'' Barkley
said. ``We left him open. We're not supposed to leave him. We made
an error on that play.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was what the play was designed to force the Rockets to
do, unless they allowed Stockton an open jumper from the free-throw
line or a pass to Thurl Bailey, who set the pick, near the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what's happening,'' Utah coach Jerry Sloan said
of the position the play put the Rockets in. ``Any time John starts
his penetration, what are you going to give?
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually don't tell what our plays are called, because
they're so secret. Only 29 teams know what that play is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley also said that was not why the Rockets lost their
fifth consecutive regular-season game to the Jazz, which continues
to haunt even beyond the playoff defeats of the Rockets the past
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets led by 15 with eight minutes left. Even after a 23-5
Jazz run turned the 15-point deficit into a three-point Utah lead,
the Rockets recovered. They regained the lead and had a chance to
take a three-point edge, but an Olajuwon jumper with 13.6 seconds
left was off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon had 32 points, but that shot from 14 feet out missed.
Malone's didn't. But it was all the shots the Rockets missed after
building their lead that cost them their latest defeat to the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We blew the game,'' said Barkley, who made just two of 11
shots for nine points. ``We can't blow a lead like that. Dream
carried us, but me and Scottie (Pippen, who had 10) have to help
him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't throw it in the ocean. We couldn't score. I blame
that on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But though Barkley missed four shots, all on good looks, during
the Jazz run, he was far from alone.
</P>
<P>
   After Othella Harrington had scored on a drive for a 78-63
Rockets lead, the Jazz had to commit to double-team inside and the
Rockets were unable to make them pay. Michael Dickerson, Brent
Price and Pippen missed open 3s, and the Jazz began its comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Price hit a 3, but after a turnover by Olajuwon and two missed
jumpers by Barkley, the Jazz had run to within 81-79, with a 16-3
spurt in four minutes. The Rockets had blown leads to the likes of
the Mavericks, Kings and Raptors. But once on a roll, the Jazz
remains far too polished to waste that sort of chance, no matter
its recent struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in many games we had leads, but we always let them
get back in it,'' Olajuwon said. ``This is a lesson. When we have a
team down, we have to put them away.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the Rockets did not seem to let up too soon,
enjoying their success prematurely. Instead, they missed shots they
would expect to make, then let the Jazz beat them down the court to
get their previously struggling offense going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were in control of the game,'' Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``You can't ease up on a good team. If you can be
up on somebody, you can stay up on somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense was the big deal. All we have to do is make some
stops. We let this one get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Olajuwon interrupted the Jazz run with 3:45 left, the
Jazz kept coming, finally taking the lead with 1:57 left on a
Shandon Anderson layup off a Stockton pass and pushing the lead to
three on a Malone fast-break layup, also from Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had seemed to recover, however. Olajuwon hit a pair
of free throws, then a hook with 45.7 seconds left for an 87-86
lead. But his jumper with 13.6 seconds fell short, and with 8.5
seconds left, the Jazz called time out to set up a last play.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were left with 2.7 seconds to try to steal the game
back. Tomjanovich put three guards in with Pippen inbounding,
hoping for a pass to at least an open shot.
</P>
<P>
   They got the open shot, but with the guards unable to work free,
Pippen was forced to go to Olajuwon, just inside the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good look,'' Olajuwon said of his last shot at the
buzzer. ``I thought I got a clear look. At that point, I just
wanted to get the shot off.''
</P>
<P>
   By that point, it was too late, another big lead lost, the Jazz
running Stockton around another pick to torment the Rockets again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one more play, one more offensively or one more
defensively, and we get a win,'' Tomjanovich said. ``But we
couldn't do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
