<HEADER>
A3414 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-02 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARS OF LOSING UNDER ASSAULT BY HOLMGREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND _ If the NFL were horticulture, the Seahawks would be
on their way to becoming one well-mowed lawn. No weeds, no moss,
all green, all even, all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you have read that the local pro grid unit has its
chinstraps buckled, its jerseys tucked, its penmanship corrected
(no happy face circles over the i's) and its grammar spiffed.
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying exactly how this will translate into dropping
Barry Sanders 4 yards behind the line during the season opener five
months from now. But since Mike Holmgren is insisting upon these
matters, they are being done.
</P>
<P>
   The new coach is Mr. Max Credibility, and when he requires
someone to drop and give him 20, well, even the secretaries and the
janitors are floorbound.
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessarily the stereotypical drill-sergeant approach,
although he's all that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you drop a ball, you'll hear about it, if you miss an
assignment, you'll hear about it,'' said Cortez Kennedy, the
Seahawk defensive dean. ``If I mess up, he's not afraid to get in
my face.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good. I respect the man so much. I've been here 10
years, and he calls me an old guy, but I feel like I'm 21 again
because of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's assertiveness and his insinuation into the details
are his ways of making inroads into the Seahawk culture of losing.
</P>
<P>
   Probably no one at this week's mini-camp, despite 10
playoff-free years, will acknowledge that there has been such a
thing. Then again, that's what the Packers believed seven years ago
when Holmgren arrived in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was they really believed they were playing at a
championship level, that how they were playing was OK,'' Holmgren
said recently.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude wasn't confined to players. It permeated the front
office and all the non-player personnel.
</P>
<P>
   So before his first season, Holmgren invited every Packers
employee _ groundskeepers, video guys, cooks _ to a meeting where
he introduced himself. He explained that each of them had a
contribution to make to reaching the Super Bowl, and they could be
no less diligent about their responsibilities than he or any of his
coaches and players was.
</P>
<P>
   Corny, right? Holmgren had done a little research. It had been
28 years between the last season of Vince Lombardi's legendary
Green Bay career and Holmgren's takeover. Amazingly, 30 employees,
nearly half of the non-playing personnel, had been there the entire
time, a period pickled with mediocrity, coaching staff turnover and
a whole bunch of meaningless ``The Pack is Back'' bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see it,'' he said Thursday after practice. ``These
people had seen the furniture and the pictures on the wall changed
about every four years, and they looked at me and said, `We'll
still be here when you leave.'''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting began to break the chain of diminished expectations.
Five years and much good football later, the Packers won the Super
Bowl, the franchise was the darling of the American sports world
and Holmgren made sure every employee was in on the traveling party
to the unofficial national holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren makes no claim to the NFL invention of inclusiveness.
He saw Bill Walsh do the same thing when Holmgren was an assistant
coach under Walsh with the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   It helped in San Francisco. It helped in Green Bay. So a few
weeks ago, Holmgren staged a similar kind of pep talk at Seahawk
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get them as fired up as I was,'' Holmgren said.
``They need to know they're an extension of the team on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``A football franchise sometimes is not a healthy environment,
where you're working hard for seven or eight months in a stressful
situation. People need to enjoy being a part of it, being emotional
about wins and losses.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, talking up the staff is a little thing. It's
way early to judge any impact, particularly in Seattle, where a
number of employees are also working for Seahawk owner Paul Allen's
other sports enterprise, the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   But any effort to reconnect a team that has been on a
decade-long drift from the NFL spotlight, its fan base and even
itself has to be worthwhile. Ending the culture of losing begins to
get done in the offseason one little thing at a time, so that they
are second nature when the ``unhealthy environment'' sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy offered up an example from the football field:
</P>
<P>
   ``When a meeting is supposed to start at 9 a.m., it's 9 a.m.,
not 9:05,'' he said. ``When the meeting is over, we have exactly 15
minutes to get out on the field and practice what we just talked
about in the meeting. Nobody's sitting around for an hour,
hour-and-a-half, forgetting stuff and getting out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   How such things manifest into wins is part of the alchemy of
sports. But if Kennedy says his considerable bag of bones is
feeling 21 again, Holmgren appears to be on to something.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
