<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3415 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     04-02 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ It was a blast from the past. It was just like old
times.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trip down memory lane. Ancient and recent. Good
memories and bad memories.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon carved up the Jazz like a chainsaw going through
butter, dropping in soft jumpers from the baseline and the wing,
curling down into the lane and spinning around defenders to drop in
his jump hook.
</P>
<P>
   It was a third quarter that might as well been a greatest hits
reel cued up on the VCR. Greg Ostertag couldn't stop him. Todd
Fuller couldn't stop him. The Mormon Tabernacle Choir and the
entire Osmond family couldn't have stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   He scored from here. He scored from there. He grabbed key
rebounds, and he lifted off like one of those Titan rockets at Cape
Canaveral and swatted back two Utah offerings at the basket.
</P>
<P>
   With 7:54 left in the third quarter, Olajuwon took a feed from
Scottie Pippen, turned and stabbed a 13-foot jumper over Ostertag
to become the 12th player in NBA history to cross the 25,000-point
threshold. He wound up with 32 on the night.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   But Karl Malone came wide open in the left corner, took a pass
from John Stockton and, with 2.7 seconds left in the game, drilled
a 19-footer of his own and slipped another dagger across the
throats of the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   So it ends 88-87 Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the bad old days.
</P>
<P>
   Utah didn't have an answer for Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets didn't have an answer for the Jazz at crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 25,000th point is something I forgot about by the time the
game ended,'' Olajuwon said. ``It was nice when they stopped the
game and made the announcement. But it would have been so sweet if
we could have held on.''
</P>
<P>
   For yet another night, the center moving toward middle age
showed he is still capable of being most of the things he once was.
</P>
<P>
   For yet another frustrating evening, the Rockets showed that
they are quite capable of building a big, impressive lead and then
letting it slip away like a greased pig.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to get sloppy and let teams like the Clippers
and Mavericks and Nuggets and the rest of the garbage get a flicker
of hope before finally making the winning plays down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   However, when you're playing the likes of the Jazz, a flicker
can quickly become a spark and a spark a raging fire and, before
you know it, everything you worked so hard to build is nothing more
than a pile of ashes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the shooting of Bryon Russell on a 25-point night that
led the Jazz attack. But it was the way the Jazz attacked the
offensive boards and the way the Rockets became soft on defense
that turned the game around.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets led 76-61 when Pippen finished off a fast break with
a layup with 9:05 left in the game. And it was 87-86 when Olajuwon
made his last jump hook over Thurl Bailey with 45.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen blocked an inside attempt by Malone. Then Olajuwon missed
a 14-footer from the left side.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz called time, and all those bad memories came rushing
back. Suddenly it was June 1997 and you could feel the sense of
dread in your throat.
</P>
<P>
   Two years too late, the Rockets finally remembered to keep
Stockton covered. But after Bailey set a pick and Charles Barkley
came over to help on Stockton, Olajuwon set his sights on Bailey,
who was cruising toward the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   That left Malone wide open in front of the Jazz bench. He scored
just 16 points on the night, but he wasn't going to miss that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned my head away,'' said Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich.
``I wasn't going to look. I didn't have to. I listened to the
crowd, and I knew what happened. That guy's a great player. I've
seen him have off nights before and make the big play at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy T has seen Olajuwon pull the Rockets out of the fire so
many times in so many games, too.
</P>
<P>
   After two timeouts, the best the Rockets could get was an
off-balance shot by Olajuwon from beyond the top of the key. It
never hit the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the nine-game winning streak. Gone was the chance to
overtake the Jazz in the Midwest Division standings.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all that came out of it was a painful lesson finally
hammered home with an exclamation point.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times have we lost leads like that?'' Tomjanovich
said. ``I think it's a horrible trait for a team to have. If you
can build a lead, then you can finish the game off. I've been
talking about it, preaching it. Maybe if we learn the lesson,
something good comes from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon reflected on the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Records and games are the same,'' he said. ``They happen, and
you move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving just the memories. The good ones and the bad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
