<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3416 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      04-02 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONIC SLIDE REACHES .500 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ There was no 29-point deficit this time. No slow
starts, frantic comebacks, or Vin Baker aggravating an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's Sonic game against the Denver Nuggets included
just two simple subplots: Revenge and the Sonics' eighth different
starting lineup this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics coach Paul Westphal again sent guard Hersey Hawkins to
the bench in favor of Billy Owens. The move came after Hawkins
requested it and Westphal acknowledged a need for the team to
create mismatches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever chemistry means, we seem to have a lot better
chemistry with that lineup than other stuff we've had to try this
year,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, though, ``we were 6-0 with that lineup _
starting with a big two-guard,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Make that 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Despite trying yet another way to jump-start what is left of the
regular season, the Sonics fell 113-110 to the Nuggets at McNichols
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Sonics' second straight loss, and third in four
games. Friday doesn't get any easier when the Sonics complete this
five-games-in-six-nights road trip at Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics (15-15) could conceivably fall below .500 for the
first time this season. They are just 4-11 on the road, and have
not had a sub-par record since the 1990-91 season when the Sonics
were 15-16 after 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do is keep picking ourselves up off the floor and
come out swinging,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their first meeting here, when the Sonics fell behind by
29 in the first half, they were at least in the game until the end.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had a chance to tie the game when Antonio McDyess
missed a pair of free throws that could have sealed Denver's win.
However, Dale Ellis' 3-pointer bounced off the rim as the clock
expired.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Detlef Schrempf could have tied the score with 21
seconds left in the game. But Schrempf split two foul shots,
leaving the Sonics with a 109-108 deficit. McDyess made two free
throws seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a decent look,'' Ellis said of his last shot. ``McDyess
jumped out at it and blocked the basket a little bit. ... They play
against us with a great deal of confidence. We didn't have much of
an answer for (Chauncey) Billups and (Nick) Van Exel.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver's starting backcourt smacked 63 points in the Sonics'
mug. Billups finished with a career-high 32 points, including four
3-pointers. Van Exel made six 3-pointers and tallied 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton was the Sonics' biggest retort to the
unconscious-shooting Nuggets. He scored 33 points on 13-of-26
shooting. Owens, who played just 13 minutes, managed just two
points and couldn't keep up with Billups.
</P>
<P>
   So that left a much quicker Hawkins to play 33 minutes off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shot the ball well, and that's the only reason that they
won,'' Sonics center Olden Polynice said. ``It wasn't about their
defense or anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics did enough to win. They matched the Nuggets with
46-percent shooting. The Sonics won the rebounding battle, 43-31.
They recovered from deficits of seven and eight points in the first
half. The team also roared back from an 11-point deficit in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics just didn't make enough free throws (27-for-37) and
3-pointers (3-for-10). Conversely, Denver missed just six foul
shots. The Nuggets killed the Sonics with rally-thwarting bombs _
mostly tough shots _ from Billups or Van Exel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Billy Owens can't stay with me so I tried to use that
to my advantage,'' Billups said. ``If they start a 6-foot-9
two-guard, they try to use it to their advantage and post me up. So
I try to use my speed and ball-handling abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, you know which scheme worked best.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to happen every night,'' said Hawkins, who
volunteered to go to the bench after the Sonics' loss at Detroit
last Sunday. The Sonics will stay with Owens in place of Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   Without Baker, the Sonics have had a difficult time establishing
a post-up game. Owens and Schrempf should give the team a height
advantage at their respective positions on most nights.
</P>
<P>
   With Hawkins coming off the bench, Schrempf started at small
forward and rookie Vladimir Stepania started at power forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting off to such slow starts that I told him if he
feels he needs to do anything to spark the team, then I'd be
willing to come off the bench,'' Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins' 13 points combined with Ellis' 12 and Aaron Williams'
14 gave the Sonics a decided advantage off the bench. The Sonics'
reserves outscored Denver's, 41-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when (the Nuggets) make fade-away threes and off-balanced
shots, they're feeling it. Things are just not going for us,''
Schrempf said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Sonics, that has been the one constant
this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
