<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, April 2.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Allied forces Thursday destroyed
a bridge over the Danube River in Serbia and attacked a Serbian
mechanized column that had been involved in the purges in Kosovo,
Pentagon officials said. By Steven Lee Myers and Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ Western officials are
discussing a plan under which NATO troops would escort ethnic
Albanians back into Kosovo after Serbian forces there have been
routed by bombing, and would set up a self-governing enclave under
allied protection, a senior NATO diplomat said Thursday. By Michael
R. Gordon. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Three American soldiers
captured along the border with Macedonia will appear before a
Yugoslav military court that could charge and try them, the state
news agency, Tanjug, said Thursday. But the main evening broadcast
in Yugoslavia led with another news event, an unexpected meeting
between the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, and a prominent
leader of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians, Ibrahim Rugova. By Steven
Erlanger. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Norfolk, Va.) _ Denouncing the Serbs' capture of
three American soldiers, President Clinton vowed forcefully to
pursue the Balkan bombing campaign and appealed to the nation for
``determination and resolve.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ In a chilling display of
force, Serb gunmen are systematically emptying Kosovo's capital
city, Pristina, marching its ethnic Albanians out through gantlets
of masked, heavily armed Serbs, refugees crossing the border today
said. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SOLDIERS (Undated) _ A dreaded symbol of war began to
mark the landscape in three communities Thursday, as friends and
family of the American soldiers captured along the border of
Macedonia and Kosovo hung yellow ribbons on their clothing, in
their yards and along the streets. By Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Talks adjourned
inconclusively in Northern Ireland, but Prime Minister Tony Blair
of Britain said he thought they had established a ``satisfactory
basis'' for a final settlement. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-NUNAVUT (Iqaluit, Nunavut) _ A bold attempt to right past
wrongs and bring hope to an entire region was launched as Thursday
began and the map of Canada was redrawn to make room for the new
territory of Nunavut, a self-governing entity for Eskimos. By
Anthony DePalma. With map.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-WARCRIMES (London) _ In Britain's first war crimes
trial, a retired railway worker from Belarus who now lives in
London was found guilty of murdering Jews during World War II. By
Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ORIGINS (Aomori, Japan) _ When he was a boy, Tomihiro
Yoshizaki used to dig for arrowheads in some strange mounds of
earth outside this city in northern Japan. Now those mounds have
been excavated, resolving crucial mysteries about the ancient
hunter-gatherers who lived here 5,000 years ago. Just one mystery
remains: to what extent are Yoshizaki and other modern Japanese
descended from those ancient people? By Nicholas D. Kristof. With
photo and locator map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-WORKERS (Yakima, Wash.) _ When federal immigration agents
came to central Washington recently, there were no sudden raids, no
emergency deportation hearings, no buses waiting to take the
hundreds of illegal immigrants found working back to the Mexican
border. When the investigators left, though, more than 560 people
were fired, under orders from the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, because they possessed forged or otherwise improper work
documents. By Sam Howe Verhovek. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MO-CONCEALED-WEAPONS (St. Louis) _ In what both sides of the gun
debate are calling a momentous showdown, Missouri will be the first
state to let voters decide in a statewide referendum next week
whether to allow people to carry concealed weapons in public. By
Dirk Johnson. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COYOTE-PARK (New York) _ A coyote was first spotted Tuesday
night in Central Park by an alert police officer. The next night,
he was spotted again, and dozens of officers were called in to join
the search. As a police helicopter buzzed overhead, he emerged from
the brambles, running furiously. Then, he was gone. By Douglas
Martin. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Undated) _ Researchers have isolated a master
cell from adult bone marrow that can be directed to grow bone,
cartilage, tendons or another vital bone component, a feat that
experts call a major step toward learning to make replacement parts
for ailing or aged bodies. By Nicholas Wade
</P>
<P>
   NM-TORTURE (Elephant Butte, N.M.) _ In the 10 days since a young
woman ran terrified and naked down a gravel street here and told a
harrowing tale of rape, torture and escape, the authorities have
repeatedly hinted at even worse horrors inside the double-wide
trailer home at 513 Bass Road. By Don Terry. With locator map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCH-MALONE (Undated) _ Rupert Murdoch is taking a strong
step toward increasing his hold over sports programming, buying out
the 50 percent stake owned by John Malone's Liberty Media in a
venture that controls a dozen regional sports networks, according
to people familiar with the transaction. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   BP-ARCO (Undated) _ BP Amoco, which is still integrating the oil
giant Amoco, officially announced its acquisition of Atlantic
Richfield Co. Thursday and said it would cut about 2,000 jobs. By
Agis Salpukas. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   COHEN-PROFILE (Undated) _ Arnold Cohen is a charismatic salesman
who works at a frantic pace _ traits that have repeatedly made him
attractive to companies looking for management talent. Each time,
Cohen has persuaded his superiors, and apparently himself as well,
that daring initiatives to expand or reorganize would lead
inexorably to success. Each time he was wrong. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   RATES (Undated) _ Since October 1998, mortgage rates have been
ever so slowly crawling upward. If they continue to rise from their
current level _ still quite low in historical terms _ sales of
homes will drop off. Furthermore, a significant increase in
interest rates would weigh on stocks and could provide some drag on
the overall economy. By Robert D. Hershey Jr. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   PAYMENT-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The 15 percent commission on media
spending that clients pay advertising agencies as their fee was
once standard in the advertising business. Now it is about as dead
as the three-martini lunch. By Patricia Winters Lauro.
</P>
