   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROSENTHAL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Buoyed by their role in helping
turn a Balkan civil war into shivering, desolate, crowds of
refugees, a political booby trap for America unmatched since
Vietnam, a perversion of NATO purpose and a planning debacle, the
15 nations of the European Union are now trying to export their
collective political wisdom to shape the Mideast, which may God in
Heaven forfend. By A.M. Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-KOSOVO-COLUMN (Washington) _ NATO's military objective
was clear: to ``degrade'' Yugoslavia's ability to drive the ethnic
Albanians out of its province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Some degradation. By William Safire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ENNIO-COMEDY (New York) _ Imagine, if you will, an evening with
Roberto Benigni, doing impressions of Stevie Wonder, Edith Piaf,
Fidel Castro, Marilyn Monroe, Barbra Streisand and the Pope. Now
imagine him impersonating them all in a lip-synching dumb show,
with paper headdresses, costumes and props affixed to his scalp and
torso. No, this wouldn't necessarily be your scariest post-Academy
Awards show hallucination. It would, in fact, be an approximation
of ``Ennio,'' an honest-to-goodness Off Broadway show starring
Ennio Marchetto that, ahem, unfolds like no other production in
town. By Peter Marks. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POLKE-ART-REVIEW (New York) _ There is new if temporary treasure
to be found at the Museum of Modern Art right now, and it lies at
the center of the engrossing, challenging exhibition of early
drawings by the German painter Sigmar Polke. The third gallery in
this show, which has been organized by Margit Rowell, curator of
drawings, and is devoted to works from 1963 to 1974, presents only
four drawings, all dated 1971-72. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column: Soon
after the baseball season starts, Joe DiMaggio will be remembered
in a ceremony at St. Patrick's and with the unveiling of a monument
at Yankee Stadium. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   CYCLING-DRUGS (Paris) _ The cycling scandal in Europe erupted
again Thursday, throwing one race into chaos and implicating a
major sports figure in another investigation. The final day of the
Trois Jours de La Panne race was canceled in Bruseels after the
police discovered drugs believed to be intended for the sport's top
racing team. Police said the race could continue without the
Mapei-Quick Step riders, but other team managers refused, and the
race was abandoned. By Samuel Abt.
</P>
