<HEADER>
A3435 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-CANADIENS-     04-02 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CANADIENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS, CARTER STING CANADIENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ For the first 20 minutes Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, the Bruins
looked sloppy, lethargic, and woefully out of sync. For the first
20 minutes, it was impossible to tell which team was playing for
jobs and pride and which was fighting for a postseason berth.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 20 minutes, coach Pat Burns looked as if he wanted
to spit tacks. After the Bruins surrendered two goals in the final
half-minute of the first period to fall behind, 2-0, Burns vented
his frustration at his players during intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The result? A 3-2 Boston victory over the Canadiens at the
Molson Centre that coupled with a Florida loss to Washington moves
the Bruins seven points ahead of the Panthers and idle Rangers with
eight games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were awful,'' said Burns. ``We were playing like we
finished the last couple of games. We didn't really get into their
faces, we weren't physical so we had to remind some guys about how
we should be playing and now how we were playing. I thought we
bounced back in the second and third periods.''
</P>
<P>
   The win ended the club's winless streak at three games (0-1-2).
</P>
<P>
   Steve Heinze and Anson Carter each notched a goal and an assist
and center Jason Allison, who has been hampered by a sore wrist,
had a pair of assists.
</P>
<P>
   Allison set up the winning goal by Carter at 8:48 of the third.
He dished a pass from the right circle to Heinze in the slot.
Heinze backhanded it toward the net, goalie Jeff Hackett tried to
grab it with his glove and missed, and Carter tapped it in from the
edge of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who weren't playing well early, thought they were in
good shape until late in the first. But the Canadiens scored 17
seconds apart to take a 2-0 lead. The problems started with 27.2
seconds left. Left wing Brian Savage teed up a slapper from the
right point that goalie Byron Dafoe stopped with his right pad.
Defenseman Grant Ledyard tried to clear away the rebound but it
bounced off center Sergei Zholtok. Both Dafoe and defenseman
Mattias Timander scrambled to get the puck out but right wing
Dainius Zubrus scampered down the right side and backhanded the
puck into the net at 19:32.
</P>
<P>
   The second goal came on as strange a play as you'll see.
Montreal's Turner Stevenson fired a long lead pass that glanced off
the stick of Bruins center Tim Taylor, who was trying to block the
feed. The puck bounced behind Ray Bourque and wound up right on the
stick of Savage, who charged in on Dafoe. Dafoe came way out of his
net, but Savage beat him to the puck and buried it into the empty
cage with 10.5 seconds left. Hackett was credited with an assist,
the first by a Canadiens netminder at home since Patrick Roy got
one April 17, 1995, in a 5-2 victory over Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burnsie gave it to us good and deservedly so,'' said Dafoe of
his coach's tirade between periods 1 and 2. ``We were sluggish
again and just not a very good effort by all of us in the first.
But responded great. I have full confidence we were coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins redeemed themselves in the middle period as they
fought back to tie it, 2-2, on goals by Heinze and Joe Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Boston got on the board with a power-play goal at 2:59. Bourque
teed up a shot from the left point, and with Allison running
interference in front of the net, Heinze crashed in for the rebound
and beat Hackett for his 21st goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Both clubs tried to get something going with a couple of
skirmishes. First it was Montreal defenseman Igor Ulanov going with
Bruins right wing Rob DiMaio, who gave up several inches and many
pounds but still held his own. Ken Belanger and Dave Morissette
also squared off but only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton pulled Boston even with 1:36 left in the period,
scoring his 14th of the season. Defenseman Kyle McLaren dished the
puck up through neutral ice to Carter, who gained the blue line and
fed the puck into the right circle for Thornton. Thornton lured
Hackett out, but the goalie blocked him. Thornton maintained
control, moved along the edge of the crease from right to left, and
fired it into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heinzie's goal was the big lift we needed and then two great
bouts by DiMaio and Belanger lifted the whole bench,'' said Dafoe,
who stopped 22 shots. ``Joe has been getting some big goals for us
this year and that was one of the biggest ones. We knew we were
going to come back in this game. We had a lot of confidence, even
though we played as bad as we did in the first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
