<HEADER>
A3436 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-NEWHAMPSHIRE-MICH     04-02 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-NEWHAMPSHIRE-MICHIGANSTATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNH OUSTS SPARTANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It's a first.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday evening, the University of New Hampshire will play for
the NCAA Division 1 hockey championship for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats knocked off Michigan State, 5-3, Thursday &UR;  &LR; night at
Arrowhead Pond to earn a spot against Maine in an all-Hockey East
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Four times, UNH had been to the national semifinals. And four
times, most recently last year when they lost to Michigan, 4-0, at
the FleetCenter, the Wildcats had failed to make the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just hitting me,'' said UNH coach Dick Umile.
``We're excited. We didn't play well in the second period and
(goaltender) Ty (Conklin) kept us in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Score this one for the scorers.
</P>
<P>
   UNH unleashed its powerful top line on Michigan State. And the
Spartans, who had the best defensive team the country has seen in
years, could not handle it.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Souza, a junior out of Wakefield, Mass., led the way with
two goals and two assists. Jason Krog had a pair of goals and
assisted on the winning goal by Jason Shipulski. And freshman
Darren Haydar, the linemate of Souza and Krog, had two assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a real quick team and we're able to capitalize on
poking the puck by defensemen once in a while,'' Souza said.
</P>
<P>
   UNH improved its record, already the best in school history, to
31-6-3. Michigan State closes out at 29-6-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats and Black Bears have split four games this year.
UNH won the two most recent meetings, 6-1 and 4-1, at Durham, N.H.,
on the last weekend of the regular season. Saturday's game (7:30
p.m., ESPN) is the mother of all rubber matches.
</P>
<P>
   Shipulski converted a perfect lead pass from Krog to put UNH up,
4-3, with 9:08 to play. Krog feathered a backhand across to a
streaking Shipulski. Souza also assisted.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats put the Spartans away with a power-play goal four
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   They were just nine seconds into the man advantage when Krog
scored on a rebound, Haydar and Souza assisting, and it was 5-3
with 5:20 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, UNH had taken the lead three times only to see
the Spartans tie it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we wore them out,'' Souza said. ``We'd get a
goal, they'd get one. It kind of went back and forth like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Krog opened the scoring with 1:11 left in the first period. And
38 seconds later, Rustyn Dolyny tied it.
</P>
<P>
   Souza scored his first when he put a shot through the legs of
goalie Joe Blackburn and the puck barely made it across the line to
make it 2-1 at 2:44 of the second.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Patchell got that one back just more than four minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed tied, with Michigan State taking the play to UNH,
through most of the period.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with 1:43 left in the period, Souza scored again, stealing
a defenseman's pass in the MSU end and making a nice move to get in
alone on Blackburn. The goalie made the first stop, but Souza beat
him with the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Conklin had 17 saves (and 32 for the game) and UNH got out of
the period up, 3-2. But the Spartans soon tied it again.
</P>
<P>
   Mike York sent a nice pass in from the sideboards to set up Adam
Hall in front to make it 3-3 at 3:44 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   UNH had a couple of chances to stretch its lead to two early in
the third, but could not convert on a pair of breakaways. Johnny
Rogers had the first and Blackburn stopped him. Blackburn then got
a leg on a Krog shot.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at 3-3 with Michigan State on the power play, Krog
stripped the puck from a defender and came in on Blackburn again
and ripped a shot that the goalie gloved.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, with Shipulski's linemates changing up,
Krog sent the junior from Saugus in for the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Umile was not surprised that the Spartans kept coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect to run people out of a game at this point,''
he said. ``Not with the teams we're playing. You just go back and
forth and give yourself a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was he surprised the game turned into a bit of a shootout.
Besides a great defense _ they had given up 1.44 goals per game and
only once had yielded five _ the Spartans have an underrated
offense, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it couldn't keep up with his Thursday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
