<SLUG> BC-HKC-NEWHAMPSHIRE-SOUZA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUZA MAKES POINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Two juniors from communities a tad north of
Boston played vital roles in New Hampshire's first win in five
trips to the national semifinals Thursday &UR;  &LR; night at Arrowhead Pond.
They were Wakefield's Mike Souza (two goals, two assists) and
Saugus's Jason Shipulski, who gave his team the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Souza was a one-man wrecking crew. He scored his 21st goal at
2:44 of the second period, clicked for his 22d at 18:47 when he
rammed home his own rebound, and assisted on Shipulski's winner at
10:52 of the third. He picked up his second assist on the insurance
goal by Jason Krog.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hobey Baker finalist Krog also made a contribution,
scoring his 33d and 34th goals of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's a threat to pick up a point every minute he's on the
ice,'' said UNH coach Dick Umile. ``He's been a steady force all
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the soft hands you like to see on a playmaker. Face it,
you don't score 22 goals and pick up 41 assists being lucky. Mike's
a hard-nosed player who goes all out every shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have a great player like Jason Krog, Mike would
be our Hobey Baker candidate. He's on the power play, he kills
penalties, and he sees every inch of the ice all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Producing points is a Souza trademark. While playing for Dave
McCarthy at Wakefield High, he recorded 206 points, a Middlesex
League record. He was a Middlesex All-Star four times and a Globe
All-Scholastic.
</P>
<P>
   Souza downplayed his accomplishment, instead praising teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just played hockey like Coach Umile told us to do,'' said
Souza. ``We are a quick team and we took advantage of that. We
forechecked well and we got some odd-man rushes and maybe stopped
them from getting odd-man rushes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the go-ahead goal, Souza said, ``Jason (Krog) made a great
pass and Jason (Shipulski) reacted quickly and put it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I am excited where we are. I'm on a great line, but
if our line doesn't score goals, we know the other lines are
capable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did celebrate the win on the ice after the game, but we
were quiet in the dressing room. We have another game to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipulski said, ``We just went at them like we were told to do.
I think we wore them down without forechecking.''
</P>
<P>
   Souza didn't want to talk about himself. He said, ``Every game
we play is a big game and maybe our toughest game. UNH is a solid
program and every team gets up for us. We expect that. So Michigan
State was our toughest game so far. But we all know that Maine will
be our toughest game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
