<HEADER>
A3438 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-MAINE-BOSTONCOLLE     04-02 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-MAINE-BOSTONCOLLEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART'S OT GOAL LIFTS MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ University of Maine hockey coach Shawn Walsh
had been acting like a Mississippi gambler the past week. He held
his cards close to his vest and talked about things his team might
do differently. He had a handful of cards _ all high ones _ and he
played them like the dealer with the visor, suspenders, and cigar.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a heart-throbbing 2-1 victory over Boston College
on Bobby Stewart's overtime goal Thursday &UR;  &LR; night in the national
semifinals of the Frozen Four at Arrowhead Pond before 12,582.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh dealt himself a straight flush and Boston College two pair
as the Black Bears advanced to Saturday's final and a shot at its
second national title.
</P>
<P>
   This encounter also was a bitter fight between two contestants
who were 180 feet apart. Maine goalie Alfie Michaud and BC goalie
Scott Clemmensen each made 35 saves. Both played winning hockey,
but only one could advance.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the pairing of two heavyweight coaches and two
heavyweight teams. Forget they were 2-2 in four early meetings this
season. It was the rubber game for lots of marbles.
</P>
<P>
   BC coach Jerry York won an NCAA championship with Bowling Green
in 1984. Walsh won a title in 1993 with his Black Bears. They knew
what had to be done. Both teams were fine-tuned and healthy and
sharp. Great matchup. Great game. Great ending for the winner.
Tears for the loser.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh was going to change his power play two weeks ago before
his Black Bears lost to BC in the Hockey East championship, 3-2. He
didn't. He did it a few days later and his troops KO'd Ohio State,
4-2, and Clarkson, 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   Then Walsh said, ``We'll do some things against BC but I'll keep
them in the locker room for now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Walsh's power play was a woeful 0 for 7 and BC was 1
for 6.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh's magic?
</P>
<P>
   It was there.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh had a sort of unsung kid from Somerville named Niko
Dimitrakos who, as a freshman right wing on the third line, tied
the game at 2:34 of the third period, then had the Maine fans in a
frenzy in overtime as he held the puck for a seeming eternity,
making a three-quarters loop through the zone before he backhanded
a pass to the front of the net that Barrett Heisten deflected to
Stewart, who scored the winner at 5:16 of the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   BC knew Hobey Baker finalist Steve Kariya (6 points last
Saturday against Clarkson) was a key. Kariya wasn't the main
factor. Dimitrakos, a Matignon grad, was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal was good teamwork,'' said Dimitrakos. ``On the
overtime goal I just kept possession and circled. I wasn't worried.
I saw Bobby break for the net and waited. I just sent him a flip
pass and it just grazed Barrett Heisten's stick before Bobby got
it. He put it away nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, one of Maine's five seniors who couldn't vie for
college hockey's Holy Grail the past three seasons because of NCAA
sanctions, beamed. ``It was a perfect pass. Niko is one of the
smartest players on the team. I knew he'd see me. Clemmensen went
down and I went high shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said, ``Niko is one of the most talented offensive players
in our league. I love to have him on the ice. He's a kid I wanted
on my team since I saw him playing for Matignon High School.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the first period, Maine's Brendan Walsh of
Dorchester took a hit from BC's Andy Powers of Arlington and Walsh
left with an injured knee. Sixth defenseman A.J. Begg took Walsh's
spot as second-line center.
</P>
<P>
   (Shawn) Walsh said, ``Begg didn't work out all that great. So
from the second period on, I double-shifted Niko and Steve Kariya
and they did very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine drew three penalties in a row in the second period:
Matthias Trattnig for interference at 1:02; Heisten for
interference at 3:01, and Doug Janik for hooking at 4:10.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears killed the first two and the BC power play was
successful at 5:34 when sophomore defenseman Marty Hughes of
Lawrence Academy scored his third goal of the season from 35 feet
to the right side of Michaud.
</P>
<P>
   Dimitrakos tied it, 1-1, at 2:34 of the third when he collected
a nifty pass out from Ben Guite and whipped home a high 25-footer
to the left side. It was his seventh goal and 25th point.
</P>
<P>
   Maine outshot BC, 12-8, in the nail-biting third period. BC
killed three penalties and Maine two.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for the fourth period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
