<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3439 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-02 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FABULOUS FLIGHT FOR FALLEN EAGLES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ For players like Chris Masters and Brendan
Buckley, it ended where it all began. The best part is that it
ended with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointing? Oh, absolutely. Losing in the semifinals of any
national championship competition is always disappointing. It is
now scant consolation, but some day these BC warhorses can tell
their progeny that they were defeated in the first NCAA hockey game
ever played under the official designation of ``Frozen Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now the BC players are dealing with the fact that it will
be Hockey East rival Maine, and not them, who will be playing for
the big prize Saturday evening. The Eagles could not build on a 1-0
two-period lead and finally lost the game when Bobby Stewart took a
feed from Somerville's Niko Dimitrakos and put it high on Scott
Clemmensen's glove side to give the Black Bears a 2-1 overtime
victory at the Arrowhead Pond.
</P>
<P>
   The Arrowhead Pond is a certifiably strange place for a Boston
College hockey player to conclude his collegiate hockey career, but
that's not the half of it. This also happens to be where seven BC
seniors, Masters and Buckley among them, began their careers in
something called the Great Western Freeze-Out in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a pleasant visit. Michigan State beat the Eagles,
5-2, the first night and Miami of Ohio blasted them, 7-1 the next
night. And Wally Szczerbiak didn't even play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought a team here four years ago and we got waxed,'' said
coach Jerry York. ``I remember the 7-1 game. But if you saw that
team play, and this team play, boy . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   A lot has happened to the Boston College hockey program in those
four years, and most of it has been good. Last year BC had a great
year from start to finish and wound up losing an overtime contest
to Michigan in the national final, the game hailed by no less an
authority than Wolverine coach Red Berenson as ``the best college
hockey game I've ever seen.'' This year BC suffered through a
112-day period in which its record was a mediocre 15-11-4 before
putting together one of the great stretches of concentrated two-way
hockey in the 81-year history of the program.
</P>
<P>
   What BC did to get itself here was phenomenal. ``We knocked off
the Nos. 3, 2, and 1 teams in the country,'' reminded Masters, an
assistant captain. BC wasn't supposed to win the Hockey East
tournament by defeating Maine and New Hampshire. BC certainly
wasn't supposed to defeat Northern Michigan one night and the
mighty Fighting Sioux of North Dakota the next night, especially
after being exiled to Madison, Wis., for the West Regionals. The
totality of BC's eight-game winning streak just to get to the
position it found itself in with 20 minutes remaining in Thursday's
game represents the artistic highlight of the entire Jerry York
regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' agreed the mentor. ``We've never played better
than in those games.''
</P>
<P>
   Any 2-1 game is, by definition, winnable, and this one was no
exception. Nothing happened in this game that anyone who has
witnessed even a little hockey hasn't seen before. Good goaltending
has an inordinate amount of influence in postseason hockey games,
and the fact is that BC had legitimate chances to go up by a 2-0 or
even a 3-0 margin and could not do so because Maine goaltender
Alfie Michaud would not let them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some great opportunities,'' said York. ``But if you
want to win a game like this you have to finish. We definitely had
enough chances in that second period to score some goals.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to reinvent the hockey wheel. This game yielded
no great mysteries. These teams have no secrets from each other.
This was, after all, the fifth time they have played this season.
Coming into the game, they were tied at 2-2. Coming out they are
tied with 16 goals apiece. Could it be they are sick of looking at
each other? Would Jerry York have preferred playing somone else
Thursday?
</P>
<P>
   No, he wouldn't. He is Jerry York. He dosn't ever whine or make
excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if this were the regionals, we'd like to play someone we
haven't seen before,'' he explained, ``but when you get this far
you kind of expect to see someone you know, given the strength of
our league.''
</P>
<P>
   They played and they lost. That's about it. Jerry York even
found time to praise referee Mike Schmidt for calling a
sensationally fair-minded and intelligent game.
</P>
<P>
   Each season brings something different for a coach to experience
and this year York had the satisfaction of seeing a team figure
something out with enough time left in the season to get dramatic
results from this new-found knowledge. ``In the middle of the
season we just weren't playing good, sound position hockey,'' York
explained. ``We were out of whack. We didn't have a good balance
between defense and offense.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 5-2 loss to Merrimack on Feb. 26, BC found itself. The
Eagles took care of archrival BU and that started an eight-game
joyride during which they kept playing one smart, aggressive, and
spirited game after another. It carried through into the third
period Thursday before Maine, now 30-6-4, demonstrated its own
class on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We competed hard,'' said York. ``Technically, we were solid,
and emotionally we competed very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The program is in very good shape, and always will be as long as
Jerry York is in charge. ``BC is an outstanding team,'' said Maine
coach Shawn Walsh. ``There are a lot of guys on that team who are
going to play in the National Hockey League, and other leagues
beyond college.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here playing great hockey,'' said Buckley, the team
captain. ``It was the best we had played all year, and we had
confidence going into the OT we would get the game-winner. But we
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a transformation from when I was a freshman to where we
are now,'' marveled Masters. ``It's been two straight Final Fours
for BC, and the best is yet to come.''
</P>
<P>
   BC lost to a great team, period. BC didn't do anything stupid.
BC just got beat. Jerry York can live with that, because, as
everyone knows, he will be back to more Frozen Fours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 0229EST &QL; 
