<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-MAINE-MICHAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAUD MAKES HIS MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ So what would be the opposite of an Unsung
Hero? A Most Sung Hero? A Heralded Hero?
</P>
<P>
   Pick the label and Maine goalie Alfie Michaud wore it Thursday,
putting up 35 saves and keeping his team in the game long enough
for the Black Bears to catch and then pass Boston College on the
way to a 2-1 overtime win Thursday in the NCAA semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   It was Wednesday afternoon and the Frozen Four teams had
finished their practices. The coaches were having a press
conference and each was asked to name their unsung hero _ the guy
who does the most without getting much recognition. Maine coach
Shawn Walsh wasted no time in mentioning Michaud, his junior
goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Michaud stepped up and grabbed the spotlight. Oh,
he'll have to share it, of course, with Bobby Stewart, who had the
winning goal in overtime, and Niko Dimitrakos, who had a goal and
set up Stewart's winner.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, Michaud was a most deserving hero in this
one.
</P>
<P>
   A win and a berth in Saturday's NCAA championship game in hand,
Walsh reiterated the Michaud theme Thursday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got no votes for the all-league team,'' Walsh said. ``Not
one. And look what he's done. He's so steady. But he doesn't make
flashy saves.''
</P>
<P>
   They were flashy enough Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There were a bunch when the Eagles led, 1-0, and were looking
for 2-0, which just might have been enough to put the Black Bears
away. There were a couple in the middle of the second period, first
on Andy Powers, sent in by a great pass from Brian Gionta. There
was one a minute later with Ales Dolinar in close. There was
another on Dolinar later in the period.
</P>
<P>
   And then, early in the third period, with BC on the power play
and still up, 1-0, Gionta was lying on the ice and with a great
effort got a good shot on net.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big save,'' Walsh said. ``He was in position.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaud was not much interested in differentiating between
saves.
</P>
<P>
   A save, the message was, is a save.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all stops, it doesn't matter how you do it,'' the
goalie said. ``Ask any goalie, it doesn't matter, you just want to
stop it. You watch Dominic Hasek, he's unbelievable, but nobody
knows his style. And Patrick Roy, he's a technician. I just stop
the puck. It's all a blur for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all about thinking for the moment, he said. Actually, the
second.
</P>
<P>
   It's a theory he picked up reading about Roy. And listening to
Maine assistant coach Grant Standbrook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love reading stuff about goalies,'' Michaud said. ``Patrick
Roy talks about getting ready for the moment. You can't worry about
the past. You can't worry about the future. All year long all I've
worried about is the exact second.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a concept he's been employing for about a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to limit the hills and valleys and make myself more
consistent,'' he said. ``It can be a roller coaster ride. I've been
more consistent so far this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaud is 27-6-3 this year. He lowered his goals-against
average of 2.39 and raised his save percentage of .904 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a typical Alfie Michaud game,'' Walsh said. ``He
didn't make any saves that were unbelievably spectacular, except
maybe the glove save (on Mike Lephart in the third period).
Everything hit him. He is as good a positional goalie as we have
ever had, and maybe that's why he doesn't get the accolades that
other goalies have gotten. He makes it look pretty simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a label: Alfie Michaud _ Man of the Hour, er, Second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
