<SLUG> BC-NY-GOTTI-TRIAL-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SURPRISE MOVE, GOTTI ASKS JUDGE TO END HOUSE ARREST AND RETURN
HIM TO JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Six months after he won a hard-fought
battle to be released on bail for $10 million, John A. Gotti
stunned a federal courtroom Thursday when he asked a judge to put
him back behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Why he did so, though, remained a mystery in a case already
bubbling with intrigue and surprising plot twists.
</P>
<P>
   Was it because Gotti could not afford the quotidian expenses of
a man who has to pay for the measures required to be under strict
house arrest? Was it because Gotti, confined to his home on New
York's Long Island, simply tired of living a restrictive life that
allowed him no unapproved visitors?
</P>
<P>
   Was it a signal of a plea deal or some kind of calculated move
to impress the judge on the eve of his much-anticipated trial on
federal racketeering charges?
</P>
<P>
   It was a question that Gotti did not seem eager to answer
Thursday. When his lawyer, Gerald L. Shargel, started to tell the
judge, ``He can no longer afford _ _,'' Gotti cut him off abruptly,
saying, ``Never mind, never mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, or reasons, the move jarred what had been a
routine pretrial hearing about jury selection procedures Thursday
in U.S. District Court here. And since there were no objections
from the U.S. attorney's office, Judge Barrington D. Parker Jr.
granted the request.
</P>
<P>
   So on Tuesday morning, the same day that hundreds of prospective
jurors will arrive here for jury selection, Gotti will leave his
wife and four children at home in Oyster Bay on Long Island and
surrender here to federal marshals.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti's move was particularly perplexing given the fact that
last fall he had to persuade two dozen friends and relatives to put
up their homes and businesses to secure his $10 million bail and
then wait as federal officials scrutinized each property to insure
that not one penny of that $10 million was tainted by organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, 35, was indicted in January 1998 and accused of acting as
the head of the Gambino crime family since 1992, when his father,
John J., was sent to prison after being convicted of murder. That
indictment named 22 other men as being Gambino associates, but only
five of them remain on the indictment. The others have all pleaded
guilty to drastically reduced charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, known as Junior, was first held at Westchester County
Jail in Valhalla. But he was released on bail in October, under
carefully monitored conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Confined to his house in Oyster Bay, Gotti has been wearing an
electronic ankle bracelet that tracks his movements. His calls are
monitored, and he has to pay about $24,000 a month for security
guards, posted outside his house.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In December, Gotti's lawyers sought unsuccessfully to ease his
bail conditions and regain assets, complaining to Parker that
Gotti's wallet was being unfairly pinched. Coming in was $11,000 a
month, mainly from autos parts and vending machine companies that
Gotti partly owns; going out, however, was $11,000 for mortgage
payments in Oyster Bay and Massapequa, N.Y., and property in the
Poconos in Pennsylvania; $1,600 for groceries; $1,100 for
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's broke,'' a lawyer for Gotti, Sarita Kedia, said at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after Thursday's pretrial hearing to explain what had
happened, the normally loquacious Shargel said only: ``There's
nothing to say. There's no need for an explanation. I did what my
client wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   He did say, however, that the request was most unusual, and one
that neither he nor two of Gotti's other lawyers _ Bruce Cutler and
Ms. Kedia _ had ever done, or had even heard of being done, before.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, meanwhile, said nothing at first as he left the
courthouse, surrounded by his lawyers and supporters. He smiled
faintly before telling trailing reporters that he had no comment,
and that even if he did, ``you're going to twist it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   And Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney for the
Southern District of New York, said that his office would have no
comment on the latest developments _ a response echoed by Parker's
office and the pretrial services department of the federal
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while Gotti's lawyers implied that it was primarily a
financial decision, some former and current FBI agents said the
decision might be a sign that Gotti was considering a last-minute
guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Gotti rejected a government offer of about six
years in prison in return for a plea to reduced charges. If he is
convicted of racketeering at a trial, he faces a 20-year prison
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Shargel and Cutler declined to comment on the possibility of a
plea. But they added: ``We are gearing up for the fight of our
lives. It has always been our position to fight and we are not
retreating. This was a personal decision by John to reinstate the
order of detention are we are not going into the reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
