<HEADER>
A3451 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-PHILANTHROPY-A     04-02 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-PHILANTHROPY-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN AMERICANS GIVE MORE, AND NOT HURT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, April 4) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago, Claude Rosenberg, a retired San Francisco
investment manager, began touring the country, telling Americans
that they could easily double their annual giving to churches and
charities without lowering their standard of living, or their
wealth, one iota.
</P>
<P>
   It was a controversial message, embraced by people like Ted
Turner, who pledged a billion dollars to the United Nations, and
ridiculed by others, who took comfort in the oft-repeated
observation by professional fund-raisers that Americans are the
most generous people in the world.
</P>
<P>
   After all, living Americans gave away either $109 billion or
$115 billion in 1997, depending on whose estimate is used, or about
$1 of every $40 of adjusted gross income.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rosenberg has updated his figures. Because of the booming
stock market, he says, Americans over all could nearly triple their
annual giving without reducing the quality of their life styles.
</P>
<P>
   Americans will give about $132 billion to churches and charities
this year, several studies indicate. Rosenberg said Americans have
the capacity to give an additional $242 billion, for a potential
total of $374 billion in gifts, money that he said would provide
enormous societal gain with no individual pain.
</P>
<P>
   Using income tax data for 1996, the latest year for which
information is available, Rosenberg calculated that a couple with
$50,000 to $74,999 of income, and investment assets of $118,000 _
the average for that group _ could afford to increase donations by
21 percent. That would raise their giving to $1,600, from the
$1,322 average shown in IRS data.
</P>
<P>
   A family with earnings of $100,000, and with $1 million of
invested assets, could give away $16,000 without curtailing their
life style, his economic model showed, which is about six times
actual average giving.
</P>
<P>
   And the roughly 111,000 families with annual incomes of more
than $1 million could increase their yearly giving more than
tenfold without cutting back their life style now or ever,
Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   That group had average adjusted gross income of $2.8 million and
financial assets of $21.2 million, Rosenberg estimated. Based on
those figures, he said, they could give an average of $1.2 million
a year, versus their actual average of $119,830 that year.
</P>
<P>
   In his calculations for that group, Rosenberg used IRS data for
1996 on dividend and interest income to estimate average financial
assets.
</P>
<P>
   But how could a tripling of donations, not to mention a tenfold
increase, not hurt a family? Because, he said, advisers urge
wealthy people to hold down taxable income while still financing
the life style they want, a policy Rosenberg said shortchanges
charity because assets are not considered.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg's message: Change how you look at your capacity to
give, focusing on what you have instead of what you make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main point,'' Rosenberg said, ``is that generosity has
been based too much on income. With capital for many people being
so much larger than income there is enormous untapped capacity to
give.''
</P>
<P>
   Many charitable endowments operate on the theory that they can
give away roughly 5 percent of assets each year, forever, and keep
pace with inflation. Rosenberg's estimates for individuals are
slightly higher, but, of course, individuals don't live forever.
</P>
<P>
   He said even that the relatively few people who tithe, following
the biblical injunction to give away 10 percent of income, are out
of step with modern finance because they ignore investment assets.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg's organization has trademarked the word ``newtithing''
for his concept of charitable giving based on assets and surplus
income. The idea was first outlined in his book ``Wealthy and Wise:
How You and America Can Get the Most Out of Your Giving'' (Little
Brown, 1994); it is also explained in detail at www.newtithing.org,
his organization's Web site, which will have a calculator to show
giving capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Newtithing grew out of ``my own experience soliciting
donations,'' said Rosenberg, whose family foundation has $32
million. ``I was disappointed, even angry, that people I knew were
giving little compared to their estimated wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to believe that some individuals he regarded as stingy
were simply listening to standard tax advice and then measuring
their capacity to give largely in terms of income. ``A lot of
people have been waiting for some validation that it is all right
to give a lot more,'' he said. ``I am giving it to them based on
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Schervish, a Boston College social work professor who has
studied the wealthy for 15 years, says assets are increasingly
being counted in calculations of the capacity to give, a dramatic
change that Rosenberg is helping to spur.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is attempting to mobilize the consciousness and the
consciences of wealth holders to appreciate how much wealth they
have and what good they can do with their wealth,'' Schervish said.
``And he is right that advisers focus on income, not wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Famed money manager Peter Lynch and former President Jimmy
Carter are among those who endorse his approach.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg advises people to first figure out how much they need
to maintain their life style, get them through any imaginable
turmoil and provide for their families.
</P>
<P>
   But after that, he said, many Americans even at the $50,000
income level have more wealth than they need. He recommends that
those people increase their giving now so that they learn how to
give in ways that accomplish goals _ whether more opera in their
cities or more after-school recreation for poor children. And as
they learn how to make a difference with their gifts, he said, they
should further step up their giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to convince people, especially wealthy people,
that it is very much in their interest to give away much more and
to create a society where they can live safer, happier, better
lives,'' Rosenberg said. ``They just need to change how they think
about how much they can afford to give.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
