<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CULTURE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CULTURE OF MONEY: WHO'S MIXING THE COLORS WE LOVE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, April 4) 
Daniel Akst is a novelist and financial journalist. His column on
the cultural dimensions of money and business appears the first
Sunday of each month. E-mail: culmoney(AT)nytimes.com. 
(bl) 
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Were we filled with envy? Tinted by our obsession with money?
Consumed with longing for a more natural life? Who knows why
everyone seemed to like the color green so much in the '90s?
</P>
<P>
   The point is, green is over. If gray is the new black, then blue
is the new green. And at the turn of the century, orange will be
the rage.
</P>
<P>
   So say America's color gurus, who preside over one of the
grandest intersections of money and culture. You may think that
your favorite color is yours alone, an expression of your bodily
humors or your inner paint chip. But when it comes to hues, no
consumer is an island.
</P>
<P>
   It matters who you are, where you live, and of course, what you
see. We influence one another's tastes, naturally. But we're
probably influenced most by the marketing messages, overt and
subtle, that bombard us every waking hour like gamma rays from
Planet Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, the wonderful world of color (remember Disney's
TV program?) is a mysterious one, where it is never quite clear how
or why a particular hue suddenly becomes popular and just as
quickly disappears. Why, for instance, were harvest gold, persimmon
and that scary avocado so widely embraced for so long? Was it part
of a larger movement in the 1960s toward reconnecting with the
natural world? Or were people just tired of the colors of the '50s?
</P>
<P>
   These questions are crucial in business, because the right color
can sell a product that the wrong color will kill. Much time and
treasure is spent trying to identify and promulgate the next hot
color. And such machinations lead naturally to questions on a
higher plane: Do the color gods really permit free will, or is
orange predestined somehow? The next time you buy a car, who really
decides what color you end up with? What do we mean by ``you?''
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Olympus of the world of color is an organization
called the Color Marketing Group, in which people from various
industries get together either to divine or dictate, depending on
your level of cynicism, the colors that people will like and want.
CMG says it's blue for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you have free will,'' said Harold Linton, a color
forecasting specialist at Bradley University in Peoria, Ill., who
projects orange as the blue for the new millennium. ``Yet at the
same time, you're tied to this massive industrial complex.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a complex that's hard to shake. Japan and Europe each have
a big organization analogous to the Color Marketing Group, which
also has a smaller competitor in America, the Color Association. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But where is the person so fatalistic as to suggest that color
choices reflect nothing beyond orchestrated indoctrination? Wasn't
Picasso on to something when he said, ``Colors, like features,
follow the changes of the emotions?''
</P>
<P>
   The colors of the moment change in part because times change.
Kenneth Charbonneau, a color consultant to Benjamin Moore &AMP; Co. and
former president of the Color Marketing Group, says it's the
economy: During hard times, people stick to conservative colors
like navy, burgundy and hunter green, but in more ebullient times,
people go for brighter hues. The yellow or red power ties of the
1980s were classic chromatic symptoms of a boom.
</P>
<P>
   Color specialists like Charbonneau look at economic as well as
other factors. Social trends like immigration and the growth of the
Sun Belt and Pacific Northwest all play a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate alone tells you you don't want green in Seattle,''
Charbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   Trends in business count, too. When fashion designers like Ralph
Lauren and Calvin Klein cross over into home furnishings, they
amplify the influence of fashion on color selection throughout the
consumer economy. America's car culture does the same thing for the
auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget technology. On top of color television and
color presses at newspapers, there are new construction materials
and paint formulations that create more kinds and combinations of
colors in home design and decoration. Look for more special
effects, like iridescence.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's hard to avoid suspecting that, at base, it's really
about planned obsolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, The Trend Curve, a newsletter for the home
furnishings industry, suggested that millions of aging baby boomers
might soon be holding yard sales to get rid of stuff that they were
inheriting from their parents. But what if consumers concluded that
yard-sale treasures were a fine way to furnish a home on a budget,
and decided to buy secondhand instead of new?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to guard against it,'' The Trend Curve warned,
``is to insure that home furnishings 10 years from now look
different than they do today.''(BOX) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
