<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIORITY: LEARNING THE AIR-FARE ROPES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, April 4) 
Fred Brock is an editor at The New York Times. His column on the
approach to and arrival at retirement appears the first Sunday of
each month. E-mail: fbrock(AT)nytimes.com. 
(bl) 
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Bittenbring says he knows one thing about air fares:
They are too complex for the average mortal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are absolutely unbelievable,'' he said. ``I can't figure
them out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bittenbring, 78, a retired civil engineer who lives in
Arlington, Va., has figured out how to use senior discounts to get
good deals on the major carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the discounts can be pretty sweet. But they all come
with conditions and restrictions, like blackout dates and limited
availability. And, occasionally, other discount or sale fares may
offer a better deal, depending on the route. As usual, it pays to
shop around.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best, and least restrictive, senior deals is offered
by Southwest Airlines, which now serves the New York area from
MacArthur Airport in Islip, on Long Island. For people 65 or older,
the airline offers discounts of 40 percent to 70 percent off
regular fares. The most it will charge for any one-way domestic
ticket is $129, meaning that a round-trip ticket from New York to
California can be had for $258. Of course, because of Southwest's
shorter-haul routes, the flight won't be nonstop, and you may get
nothing but peanuts and beverages along the way.
</P>
<P>
   No advance purchase is necessary, and tickets are fully
refundable. The number of senior-fare seats, however, is limited on
each flight. Information is available at www.southwest.com or by
calling Southwest at 800 435-9792.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest's deals may be hard to beat, but you can get discounts
on other airlines at an earlier age _ 62.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines offers 15 to 20 percent off its advertised
fares, depending on the day of travel. But to get those discounts,
you must pay to become a member of the airline's Freedom Flight
Club _ $75 a year for domestic travel or $125 for both domestic and
international flights. There are no limits on the availability of
these fares (www.continental.com; 800 248-8996).
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to join the club, Continental _ like many
other airlines _ will give you a flat 10 percent discount off most
advertised fares, no strings attached. But you have to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Continental also sells booklets of four or eight coupons, each
good for any domestic one-way ticket, to people 62 or older. A
four-coupon booklet is $579, making each round trip $289.50. An
eight-coupon book is $1,079, or $269.75 a round trip.
</P>
<P>
   Four-coupon booklets are also offered by American Airlines and
Delta Air Lines, both at $596; U S Airways, $579; Trans World
Airlines and America West, both at $548, and United Airlines,
$541.80.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's coupon books also include certificates for discounts on
flights to Europe and the airline's Getaway vacation packages.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the coupons are also good for trips to Canada and
certain destinations in the Caribbean and Mexico, as well as
Hawaii. But for Hawaii, it takes two coupons for a one-way ticket,
four for a round trip.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, you must use these coupons within a year, but you
should check with the airline. Of course, you can always redeem a
coupon at the last minute for a ticket that is good for a year, in
effect giving you two years.
</P>
<P>
   Regulations for traveling companions vary, but they often allow
a companion, even if under 62, to accompany you at the same
discount. There are also various taxes and fees that you may have
to pay when you redeem the coupons.
</P>
<P>
   United, American and Delta also offer rather extensive travel
clubs for seniors that include special fares and other discounts
for certain hotels and cruises. They charge fees, however, and
American's and Delta's are temporily closed to new members.
</P>
<P>
   Here are other Web sites (and toll-free numbers) of the various
major airlines:
</P>
<P>
   _ American: www.aa.com (800 237-7981).
</P>
<P>
   _ America West: www.americawest.com (800 235-9292).
</P>
<P>
   _ Delta: www.delta-air.com (800 221-1212).
</P>
<P>
   _ TWA: www.twa.com (800 221-2000).
</P>
<P>
   _ United: www.ual.com (800 241-6522).
</P>
<P>
   _ U S Airways: www.usairways.com (800 428-4322).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
