<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING Q&AMP;A: RUMOR MIGHT HAVE IT, BUT HAVE IT DEAD WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, April 4) 
Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds to
readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them by
e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, N.Y.
10036. 
(bl) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Help! I overheard on the way to a staff meeting that resumes
are being accepted for my job as managing editor of a quarterly
magazine for a nonprofit group. I know my performance isn't the
problem. After all, when I started two years ago, I organized my
department from scratch and have reformatted the magazine; reader
interest has increased and we receive nothing but raves with each
issue. Instead, the catalysts seem to be office politics _ a new
director of communications has arrived _ and the fact that I had to
be away for a week because of a family emergency. I'm still invited
to meetings and otherwise treated as if nothing is wrong, but I
have decided to look for other work. How should I be handling this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Planning a career move based on the weight of one rumor is a
little extreme. Before you start faxing your resume all over town,
get the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be completely not true,'' said Ronna Lichtenberg,
author of ``Work Would Be Great if It Weren't for the People''
(Hyperion, 1998). ``Someone could have been saying it to someone
else because they wished it were true, or it could have been a
moment of maliciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaine L. Pardoe, author of ``Cubicle Warfare'' (Prima, 1998),
is of the same mind. ``Generally speaking, if you're being pushed
out to `seek other career opportunities,' they start doing things
like not inviting you to important meetings,'' Pardoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, you may have the basic facts correct but may be
wildly misinterpreting the big picture. ``Heck, they may be
grooming you for a promotion'' and just looking for a replacement
for your current job, Pardoe said. In other words, it might not be
the right time to line up another job, waltz into your boss' office
and announce, ``I quit.''
</P>
<P>
   You also shouldn't try to confirm the rumor by quizzing
co-workers. Such questions, Ms. Lichtenberg said, would set the
entire office abuzz with unpleasant gossip.
</P>
<P>
   The best bet is to go directly to your supervisor. You don't
have to mention that you overheard anything, Ms. Lichtenberg said.
``Say, `I've been here a while and things seem to be going really
well, but I'd like some feedback on how you think things are going
and how I can do better,''' she advised.
</P>
<P>
   Pardoe also suggested a meeting with the boss: ``I think the
dumbest thing most employees do is not take it right to the
source,'' he said. ``They sit back and wait for the boss to
initiate some sort of action.''
</P>
<P>
   But if your subtle attempts to gather information don't bear
fruit, try the direct approach, Pardoe said: ``Go so far as to tell
the person, `This is what I heard.' What do you have to lose?''
</P>
<P>
   The worst your boss can do, he said, is to acknowledge that
she's looking to replace you. ``At that point, see if you can
negotiate,'' Pardoe advised. ``Say, `OK Cool. Give me a month to go
look for work.'''
</P>
<P>
   It may not be the outcome you want, but at least you won't have
to keep up a phony, everything's-just-fine smile while wondering
when the ax will fall.(BOX) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
