<SLUG> BC-R-BP-ARCO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: BP AMOCO PLANS TO BUY ARCO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas, Alaska)   (ART ADV: Graphic on details of deal is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BP Amoco, which is still integrating the oil giant Amoco,
officially announced its planned acquisition of Atlantic Richfield
Co. on Thursday and said it would cut about 2,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The combination would put BP Amoco in the league of a merged
Mobil-Exxon and the Royal Dutch/Shell Group. It would produce more
oil than either of them and would have 59 percent of the refining
capacity in the United States and 28 percent in Europe. It would
control 13 percent of the nation's retail gasoline market and 9
percent in Europe. It would be the largest oil and natural gas
producer in the United States and Britain and would be a major
petrochemical company.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission and European Union regulators must
approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, which has been approved by the boards
of both companies, stockholders of ARCO will receive 0.82 American
depository share of BP Amoco for each of their shares. Based on
Wednesday's closing prices, that is a 13 percent premium and values
the deal at about $26.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of BP Amoco fell $5.8125 Thursday, to $95.8125. ARCO fell
68.75 cents, to $72.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the job cuts will come from ARCO's headquarters in Los
Angeles, which will be eliminated, and others will come in Texas
and Alaska. Not all the cuts will come from ARCO.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings Thursday between analysts and company executives in
London and at the Pierre Hotel in New York, some analysts
questioned whether ARCO management had negotiated hard enough for a
company that has vast reserves of oil and natural gas and is the
largest retailer of gasoline in California.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO chairman and chief executive Michael Bowlin told the
analysts that with the uncertain future of oil prices and the
pressure coming from larger and leaner oil companies, it was a good
deal for ARCO stockholders to get shares in BP Amoco, whose share
price can hold up better under low crude oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bowlin said that ARCO could have remained independent,
some analysts were worried that unless crude oil prices recovered
the company would see its earnings decline and have trouble paying
its annual dividend.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of just how much pressure lower crude oil
prices have put on medium-sized oil companies over the last year,
executives of both companies said that the initiative for the
takeover came from Bowlin.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Chase, the deputy group chief executive of BP Amoco,
recalled in an interview Thursday that Bowlin came to the company
headquarters in January and to the shock of BP Amoco chief
executive Sir John Browne and himself, proposed that ARCO be
acquired.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Bowlin made it clear that he and other top
executives would not ask for a role after a takeover, assuming that
the overall deal was to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said that Bowlin would not have a position once ARCO was
taken over. Except for its brand name at its 1,760 gas stations on
the West Coast, the ARCO corporate identity, whose history goes
back to the 1860s, will also disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Under Browne, BP Amoco is already in the process of cutting
10,000 jobs over the next year as part of an effort to save $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   He said Thursday that the goal was to save an additional $1
billion after ARCO was acquired.
</P>
<P>
   The task of merging so much at first gave the top executives at
BP Amoco pause when Bowlin came with his proposal. ``He caught us
off guard,'' Chase said, and there was concern about taking on
another major acquisition while still trying to integrate Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   The more they looked, the more they realized that ARCO was a
good fit, with strong positions in natural gas in Indonesia and
China, where BP Amoco wants to expand.
</P>
<P>
   There was also Alaska, where both companies made major
discoveries, rode the good times of huge production and struggled
in recent years to stem the decline.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said the goal in Alaska was to combine operations and cut
the cost of production by about 80 cents a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   He said this would make it more attractive to invest in the
fields of Prudhoe Bay and Kuparuk, which now produce about 800,000
barrels a day for both companies. That argument has been used to
persuade officials in Alaska to support the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies will have to return to the state about 300,000
acres that they hold under leases and have not explored to comply
with limits of how much land can be held at one time.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, ARCO has built up a huge refining and marketing
system that uses Alaskan crude. The low transportation costs of
using the Alaskan pipeline and a plentiful supply made it one of
the lowest-cost producers of gasoline in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many of the stations there are older, have not
installed much of the pay-at-the-pump technology that exists
elsewhere and still rely on cash and debit cards, they are in one
of the prime gasoline markets in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Chase described the West Coast as the ``crucible of the world''
as far as selling gasoline, and acquiring ARCO's assets filled a
gap in BP Amoco's ability to compete nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   He added that about $3 billion in assets could be sold as a
result of the takeover, but no decisions have been made.
</P>
<P>
   The early phase of ARCO's integration will be overseen by Dr.
Byron Grote, a mathematician who got his start at Standard Oil of
Ohio and then came up the ranks to become executive vice president
at BP Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   He will be the man in charge because top ARCO executives will
have to survive based on their talent and whether they fit in the
new organization.
</P>
<P>
   An executive involved in the negotiations, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said of Bowlin's approach: ``This was not
him saying that it was about me and my job but about the
shareholders and the employees.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive added that Bowlin had seen several years ago that
the industry would consolidate and that the opportunities would
diminish the longer he waited.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing concerns about the ability of a British company to
manage such a huge operation in the United States, Chase said that
both he and Browne had spent long periods in the United States,
adding: ``We feel very comfortable here. This is a place we are
familiar with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
