<HEADER>
A3523 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENIUM-BOX     04-02 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENIUM-BOX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appropriated for the faith
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 4. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.)
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Christianity triumphed throughout Rome and the rest of
Europe, sites and monuments that were once pagan were co-opted to
Catholic use. Here are some examples:
</P>
<P>
   -- Pink obelisk: In the square of St. Peter's, the famous pink
granite obelisk where lovers meet and tourists mingle dates back
almost 4,000 years. It was built in Heliopolis, Egypt, by a pharaoh
to honor the sun some 2,000 years before Jesus was born, brought to
Rome by Emperor Caligula in 37 B.C., and moved to its present place
in 1586 at the direction of Pope Sixtus V. The move required 900
men and 140 horses. Originally engraved with dedications to
Augustus and Tiberius, the obelisk under Sixtus was dedicated to
Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   -- Baroque extension: On the edge of the the scattered ruins of
the ancient forum, a baroque extension rises above the columned
portico of a first century temple to the emperor Antonius and his
wife Faustina. The extension was added long after the building was
claimed as a church in the 11th century and dedicated to St.
Lorenzo, or St. Lawrence, who was believed to have been condemned
to death there.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Pantheon: Even this ``temple of all the gods,'' sitting
across a plaza from a McDonald's restaurant, was consecrated as a
church in 609 and still serves a local parish. Parts of the
Pantheon became Christian in other ways as well. In 1632, Pope
Urban VIII had bronze from the portico melted for Bernini's
baldacchino, or canopy, over the altar in St. Peter's Basilica.
Michelangelo studied the engineering of the Pantheon dome when
planning the dome of St. Peter's.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
