<HEADER>
A3524 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENIUM-CHRISTANITY     04-02 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENIUM-CHRISTANITY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sect defied persecutors and eclipsed an empire
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 4. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, Italy
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny morning, the distinctive dome of St. Peter's Basilica
casts a shadow that dominates the landscape as Catholisim still
dominates the life of modern Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors climb hundreds of narrow, curved stairs to St. Peter's
435-foot cupola for a perspective of Rome where riders on motor
scooters regard red lights as suggestions, cellular telephones ring
continually, and tourists line up outside Gucci and Prada.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate Easter, the holiest day of their year, tens of
thousands of Christians will gather outside St. Peter's, the home
church of a billion Catholics. With the year 2000 only months away,
the festivities are a foretaste of a yearlong birthday party
celebrating 2000 years of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is appropriate. The history of the faith can be
traced by a walk down these narrow streets.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a Palestinian Jew who, Christians believe, died
and was resurrected almost two millennia ago. Word of that belief
reached Rome, a center of commerce, government and religion, and
the seat of an empire that eventually stretched from Britain to
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, Christianity was tolerated in Rome along with
worship of gods and goddesses from throughout the conquered
territories. But unlike the other cults of the day, Christianity
required exclusivility of its followers. Persecution began when
Roman authorities demanded worship of the ruling emperor and
Christians refused to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Despite adversity, Christianity continued to grow and become
more organized until, in 381, Emperor Theodosius made it the
empire's official religion. For the most part, since that time,
Rome has remained the center of Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in Rome has given me a better perspective on the
history of the faith through the lives of the saints,'' said J.
Paul Kimes, 25, a native of Birmingham who is studying for the
priesthood at the Vatican's North American College. ``In the
States, the saints always seemed distant. But to know these people
walked these streets, that the blood of the martyrs was shed in
these streets, makes the saints stop being distant and become close
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   In its homeland, there are signs that Catholicism may be losing
influence: In a 1998 poll, a minority of Italians (47.6 percent)
said they are certain of the existence of God, while a majority
(51.9 percent) said they seldom or never attend religious services.
Yet for Christians around the world, Rome remains a pilgrimage
site. They come to study, worship or just to feel closer to their
religious roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come to see the universality of the church,'' Kimes said.
``There are people from all over the world here, and the only thing
we have in common is our faith.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday afternoon in the magnificent St. John Lateran
Church, the cathedral church of Rome, nuns in long habits, priests
in robes and lay people in the casual clothes of tourists make
their way in a procession around the geometrically patterned marble
floor of the sanctuary. Incense hangs in the air and light shimmers
off the gilding that seems to cover everything. At the center of
the church, a golden, haloed Jesus stares down.
</P>
<P>
   In a dingy building across the street, other nuns and tourists
make their awkward way up 25 marble steps covered in dark walnut
wood. These stairs, moved from Jerusalem, are said to be the ones
Jesus walked to the trial that led to his death. Small openings in
the wood show what are reputed to be bloodstains.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think Jesus walked up these stairs!'' exclaimed Mike
D'Onofrio, 50, a chemical engineer from Pittsburgh, who had just
made his way up with his wife Carole and daughter Lisa. ``That's as
close as I've ever come to him physically _ except for the
Eucharist, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very powerful,'' said Carole D'Onofrio, 50, a
fund-raiser for a hospital. ``It's breathtaking. It brings your
faith to life in a different kind of way.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Rome's churches claim at least one relic or remembrance
of a saint, but none is more bizarre than the small crypt chapels
of the Church of the Immaculate Conception, adorned with the bones
of dead Capuchin monks arranged in intricate patterns.
</P>
<P>
   A sign at the end of the tour says, ``What you are now, we used
to be: What we are now, you will be.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a telling reminder that mankind seeks immortality through
religion _ especially here in the Eternal City.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
