<HEADER>
A3526 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENIUM-VATICAN     04-02 2271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENIUM-VATICAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vatican is center of diverse and at times divided institution
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 4. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.)
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vatican City
</P>
<P>
   On the ancient gray-brown cobblestones of St. Peter's square,
with moss and trampled cigarette butts between them, gathers a
Sunday morning crowd that seems to be a portrait of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Under a sun that flirts from an overcast sky, American teenagers
in sports jerseys stand next to European women in full-length furs,
dark-faced African nuns in white habits, pale Irish nuns in black
habits and Asian tourists with cameras poised. Three dozen youths
from a church in Naples sing and dance the macarena. A man holds
his cellular telephone out to share the sound as bells begin to
ring out the 11 o'clock hour.
</P>
<P>
   Curved marble arms of a double colonnade seem to reach out from
the basilica to embrace them.
</P>
<P>
   This is ground zero for the largest Christian denomination in
the world, the center of a separate ``country'' with its own
government, newspaper, radio station and publishing house, home to
about 1,000 people. Decisions made here have changed the course of
Europe and the world.
</P>
<P>
   A church has stood on this site since the 4th century when
Christianity became the official religion of the Roman empire. The
facade of the present church is completely obscured by scaffolding
_ as are some 700 sites in the Vatican and Rome _ undergoing
cosmetic work to prepare for the estimated 25 million people
expected to visit in the year 2000. A joke around Rome says that
one church was scaffolded for so long that the scaffolding was
declared a historic structure.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, that does not matter. The attention of the
faithful and the curious is not on the magnificent center of the
building, but on a window above its right arm.
</P>
<P>
   A cheer goes up when a banner is flung out showing the papal
seal. Another, louder cheer follows several minutes later when the
long-awaited man himself appears, postage-stamp sized, to say a
blessing. He greets the school group from Naples, and the children
and their chaperones jump, scream and hug each other. He mentions a
group of Latinos, and they bring out a guitar and begin to sing. An
impromptu festival is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, the 263rd successor to St. Peter, is the
mortal head of a billion followers of Jesus Christ, considered the
immortal head of the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just, like, the center of everything,'' says Chris Uhl,
17, of Boston, who is wearing a Red Sox baseball cap backward as he
fulfills his ``lifelong dream'' to see the pope. ``He runs the
whole shebang.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul II presides over a diverse and sometimes divided
institution seeped in centuries-old tradition and facing modern
challenges. As the most visible, most traveled pope in history, he
has used modern transportation and communication techniques to
connect the planet's scattered population of Catholics, some of
whom are tied together more by sentiment than faith.
</P>
<P>
   While upsetting liberal Catholics _ especially many in the
United States _ by insisting that the church adhere to prohibitions
against contraceptives, married priests and women in the
priesthood, he has become a symbol of the church's endurance.
</P>
<P>
   CeCe Winter Khan, 35, of Ottawa, Kan., is here with her husband
Tariq and her 20-month-old daughter, Caroline. Khan describes
herself as a ``cafeteria Catholic'' who accepts some church
positions and rejects others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my child to attend Catholic schools. I'm active in a
parish. I gave up beer and chocolates for Lent. I go to Mass every
week,'' she says. ``I do not agree with everything the Catholic
church teaches _ I don't agree with the stance against birth
control _ but this pope is someone I really respect. He's a
wonderful, gentle man.''
</P>
<P>
   William DePriest, 28, of Greenbrier, Tenn., who is in the U.S.
Air Force stationed in Naples with a NATO unit, is United
Methodist, one of the denominations that grew out of the split with
Catholicism during the Protestant Reformation, but says he came to
St. Peter's because ``Protestants came from Catholicism, so he's my
pope, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Being here on Sunday ``is awesome. It's overwhelming. It's very
humbling,'' says Barbara Larkin, 63, of Philadelphia. ``The ability
to touch things that are such a part of your religion brings you
closer to it. It makes it seem real. We're where our religion
began.''
</P>
<P>
   To peel back the layers of the Vatican and of Rome is to trace
the development of mankind's beliefs through the epochs. What is
now the seat of Catholic Christendom was the center of a vast pagan
empire at the time Jesus was born in Palestine. As the faith he
founded grew, his followers were sometimes tolerated, sometimes
persecuted until eventually their beliefs became the official
religion of the empire.
</P>
<P>
   Even after they were generally accepted, Christians faced
internal disagreement, political struggle, and papal scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides of the empire _ the Latin-speaking west and the
Greek-influenced east _ came to a final falling out in 1054 when
the head of the church of Rome and the head of the church of
Constantinople formally excommunicated each other. The western
branch became known as the Catholic Church; the eastern is called
the Orthodox Church. In 1965, Pope Paul VI and Patriarch of
Constantinople Athaneagoras I finally canceled the orders but the
churches remain separate.
</P>
<P>
   As Rome became the center of Catholicism _ except for 1305-1377
when the papacy was snatched by the French to Avignon _ the bishop
of Rome evolved into the head of the church, called ``papa,'' or
pope. In the Catholic church, popes were known as sponsors of both
some of the world's greatest Christian art and some of the church's
most blatant abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Pope Sixtus IV, for example, is known for both the Sistine
Chapel and the Spanish Inquisition. The family name of the infamous
Borgia popes has become synonymous with corruption. And the attempt
to fund the construction of St. Peter's Basilica in the early 1500s
resulted in the crass sale of ``indulgences,'' or papal pardons,
that sparked the next major division in Christendom, the Protestant
Reformation.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, though not unscarred and unscathed, the Catholic
church has lasted.
</P>
<P>
   St. Peter's _ believed to be set on the site of the grave of the
apostle whose name it bears _ is the marble representation of the
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Peter's is more a place than a building,'' said Charles
Byrd, 35, who is studying at the North American College in Rome to
be a priest in the Archdiocese of Atlanta. ``People were praying
here long before there was a church.''
</P>
<P>
   A sovereign state
</P>
<P>
   While the mystical link between humankind and God is explored in
St. Peter's, more mundane aspects of the Catholic religion are
managed in offices nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican is a government with hundreds of thousands of
citizens spread throughout more than 2,500 dioceses around the
world. More than 160 countries have diplomatic relations with the
world's smallest country.
</P>
<P>
   Within its 108 acres are tennis courts, satellite dishes and a
cemetery. There is a small theater where, occasionally, the pope
watches a film _ most recently ``Vita e Bella,'' or ``Life is
Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   A Vatican gas station keeps the Vatican vehicles fueled. A
Vatican police force guards the buildings and takes reports on the
pickpockets who prey on the pilgrims. A Vatican bookstore sells
volumes in all the major languages. A Vatican post office takes
care of official mail as well as tourists' postcards. And a door
opening onto a narrow street inside the Vatican wall reveals the
ordinariness of an institutional kitchen, with the expected odors.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the walls is a marketplace of street vendors who try to
peddle religious medals, papal snow globes and Vatican refrigerator
magnets to tourists from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheaper than barbecue chicken,'' one yells to a group of
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Roger Roensch, who heads the office for North American
visitors to the Vatican, sees both sides of life in the center of
the Catholic Church. Roensch reads the Vatican newspaper in Italian
and English daily and listens to Vatican radio every morning in
Italian, French and English.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I'm shaving, I get the news,'' says Roensch, 66,
formerly a priest in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   He prays in St. Peter's. ``And,'' he said, ``it's great to be in
attendance at the Holy Father's audiences and get to hear him say
all those things most people only read about.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Roensch needs to go from his office, several blocks from
the Vatican, to conduct business inside its walls, he has to pass
through the Vatican police and the colorfully dressed Swiss Guards,
the special unit that guards the Pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I need to go to a special office, such as the Secretary of
State, I have to have a written pass,'' he said. ``It's like going
through Customs in the United States. When you go in, you realize
you're going into a sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   2000 a year to celebrate
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican bureaucracy is busy these days preparing for 2000,
declared a Jubilee year by John Paul II. Over the next year, the
city of Rome and the Vatican will host a calendar full of special
events for every segment of Catholicism: the disabled, laborers and
members of religious orders, to name a few. One of the largest will
be World Youth Day in August, expected to draw several hundred
thousand teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   In the Catholic tradition, a Holy Year, or Jubilee, is a year of
forgiveness, reconciliation and commitment to service. The idea
goes back to the days of Moses, when, according to the scriptures,
God told the Israelites to ``hallow the fiftieth year.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the faithful, Pope John Paul II wrote, ``Every
Jubilee Year is like an invitation to a wedding feast. ... The
present task of the Bishop of Rome, as the Successor of Peter, is
to make the invitation to the Jubilee celebration all the more
insistent (for the) two thousandth anniversary of the central
mystery of the Christian faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholics will begin the celebration on Christmas Eve this year
when the pope walks through a now-sealed Holy Door in St. Peter's
to symbolize a new beginning _ a metaphor for the new life
Christians claim in Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's a time of hope for the church,'' said Sister
Gilmary Kay, 32, a nun in the Michigan-based Sisters of Mercy who
works with Roensch. ``It's an opportunity to move to greater
holiness in whatever way God has called us.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the year 2000, there is a sense that although the church
remains firmly centered in the Vatican, its power increasingly lies
outside Europe. With Catholic leaders in various parts of the world
raising questions about birth control, clerical celibacy, women's
roles and lay involvement, some significant questions loom as an
aging and frequently ailing John Paul II and the church he heads
move toward a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Louis Dorn of Jefferson City, Mo., senses it. A church
history teacher, he speaks of the ``connectedness'' and
``universality'' he feels at St. Peter's with Catholics around the
world. But in that universality, he is aware of the breadth of the
church beyond its historical roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fascinating, absolutely fascinating, to see
what comes next,'' Dorn says.
</P>
<P>
   He has come here before sunrise on a recent Monday morning to
offer Mass with some friends in one of the small chapels around St.
Peter's periphery. The scene is much different than the day before
_ no dancing youths, no Latino guitar players, no papal photo
opportunities. Inside the cavernous church, oversized statues of
popes and saints watch over the treasures and tombs. Mosaic
cherubs, their faces made up of fingernail-sized tile, look down
from the heavenly heights above. In a chapel reserved for prayer,
eight nuns _ some in gray, some in blue, some in black _ kneel with
two other women and two men.
</P>
<P>
   On the right-hand side of the entrance to the church, in
Michelangelo's famous Pieta, a smooth-skinned Mary, mother of the
church, is alone with her lifeless marble son. Three dead roses lie
on the floor, their scattered petals blending with the deep pink
and brown marble of the floor. A maintenance man with a long broom
sweeps them away.
</P>
<P>
   But today is special. It is the Feast of the Chair of Peter, and
the statue of St. Peter is dressed as pope in red brocade robe,
gold crown, ring and pectoral cross. One foot remains bare, the
detail of its sculpture worn away by the lips of pilgrims who have
kissed it.
</P>
<P>
   Dorn stands near the adorned Peter as he considers the future of
the church that claims the saint as its first pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 20 years or less, a paradigm shift is coming,'' Dorn said.
``For the first time since we left Jerusalem, the Catholic church
is going to be majority Third World, Southern Hemisphere. Europe
has dominated the church since the end of the 1st century. Now,
it's not going to be the major stockholder.''
</P>
<P>
   When cardinals have to elect a successor to the Polish Pope John
Paul II _ himself the first pontiff from outside Italy in
centuries, there is some chance they will choose an African or a
Latin American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what they're going to do, including them,'' Dorn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics like to look at papal elections as politics as usual,
he said. ``But I think there's this sense of the spirit moving the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
