<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: There's no place like Lufkin,
Texas
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A fellow who moved here from the big city was
asking how best to describe our little hometown to folks who've
never been here.
</P>
<P>
   Not to brag, but people who have lived here all their lives and
never been anywhere else will tell you there's no place like
Lufkin.
</P>
<P>
   It's a country town that's grown to more than 30,000 pop. and,
as a result, likes to think of itself as a city.
</P>
<P>
   We have plenty of good restaurants here, and they're easy to
find. All you have to do is follow the traffic to the drive-through
windows.
</P>
<P>
   We have our share of crime. Just last week in the police
reports, the newspaper noted that somebody had burglarized a home.
Among the items taken were a gallon of whiskey and a bottle of
Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's a fun-loving place.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back a poll of the community asked residents how
they liked to spend their leisure time.
</P>
<P>
   The response was overwhelmingly consistent.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 was reading the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 was shooting guns.
</P>
<P>
   Praise the Lord and pass the ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   It's not our town motto, but I guess it could be.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of hunting and fishing hereabouts, and all sorts of outdoor
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Deer season, bird season, tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   I can remember when we even had bear season, some 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I was working at the newspaper and took the picture of the last
black bear killed in this part of the pineywoods, shot while trying
to escape, as I recall.
</P>
<P>
   I remember, too, the time an old boy came in to the newspaper
and wanted his picture made with a couple of wolves he said he'd
killed. We took the photo of him standing beside his pickup truck,
the dead wolves hanging off the back of the tailgate.
</P>
<P>
   We got a complaint the next day after the picture ran in the
paper, not from the fellow in the photo but from a farm neighbor of
his. It turned out they were his German shepherd dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Honest mistake. But I always thought the flea collars should
have tipped us off.
</P>
<P>
   Lot of pickups in Lufkin _ trucks, not tricks, you understand.
</P>
<P>
   Folks do love their trucks. They consider them a statement of
their lifestyle, particularly the bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   One I saw on the cracked back window of a dappled old truck with
a crumbled fender or two:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tailgate me I'll flick a booger on your windshield.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not our town motto, but I guess it could be.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's Lufkin like?
</P>
<P>
   That's something I'm asked regularly when I'm traveling.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot like Paris, I tell people.
</P>
<P>
   Paris has the Eiffel Tower. Lufkin has a water tower.
</P>
<P>
   Paris has the Arc de Triomphe. Lufkin has an underpass.
</P>
<P>
   Paris has the Louvre. Lufkin has a Jiffy Lube.
</P>
<P>
   Lufkin, the City of Lite.
</P>
<P>
   It's not our town motto, but I guess it could be.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
