<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3608 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN03-COX     04-02 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Television coverage of war can do much harm
 &HT;    By Roland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ World War I was started in the Balkans by a lone
gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Future generations may tell how World War III was started in the
Balkans by a lone television cameraman.
</P>
<P>
   Television cameras are a greater threat to world peace than
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear weapons in the hands of military generals are so
frightening that they restrain warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Television cameras in the hands of bleeding-heart ratings
hustlers are deadly. They are proven to cause nations to launch
missiles, rain down bombs, put assault forces on foreign beaches
and send soldiers home in flag-draped coffins.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to starting wars for personal gain, peace-loving
Americans should worry less about presidents and world leaders and
more about the executives in charge of television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, in ``Wag the Dog'' it was television that got the
nation to rally behind the war that the president was conducting
for noble reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The war was fictitious, but the point is that the politicians
knew they could manipulate public opinion by the pictures showed on
television.
</P>
<P>
   The real experts at manipulating public opinion by what is shown
on television are the professionals in charge of the television
cameras. They not only manipulate public opinion daily, they do it
by the hour, half-hour and even down to the split second when they
compete for ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Television coverage of the blood, guts, gore and suffering in
war is better than the typical TV fare of car wrecks and drive-by
shootings. There are no accusations ``if-it-bleeds-it-leads''
sensationalism in televised wars.
</P>
<P>
   War is conducted for moral and honorable reasons on our side of
the television cameras. In case public sentiment turns against the
war, as it did in Vietnam, then it's television coverage that is
moral and honorable.
</P>
<P>
   War is a career-making, ratings-boosting win-win situation for
television.
</P>
<P>
   No proof exists that any politician or television executive
purposefully started a war for personal gain. There have been
rumors, of course, when it comes to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   President Ronald Reagan, for instance, was accused of invading
Grenada to manipulate public opinion in his favor after a terrorist
bomb in Beirut killed 241 Marines and sailors.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's detractors accused him of doing the same
when he ordered attacks in Iraq and later in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   If television producers haven't been accused of starting wars
for private gain, they have been accused of whipping up the public
sentiment to send American troops into Somalia, Haiti,
Bosnia-Herzegovina and now into Serbia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It was the television pictures of starving women and children in
Somalia that moved Congress and President Bush to deploy U.S.
troops whose clandestine nighttime arrival was televised back home
by awaiting cameramen.
</P>
<P>
   When television pictures showed that things were going badly in
Somalia, the U.S. troops were pulled out. The television cameras
also left.
</P>
<P>
   In Haiti, television coverage of brutality, poverty and fleeing
refugees caused Clinton to send in U.S. troops, who now have left,
with the county in the same condition.
</P>
<P>
   The television cameras next rushed off to the former Yugoslavia.
Pictures of dead bodies and refugees have ginned up considerable
military activity.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than a threat, television might be the key to world
peace. Perhaps blanket global television coverage of brutality,
suffering and inhumanity will prompt U.S. troops to whip the entire
world into a permanent condition of peace and human kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. His column appears Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail:
RNethaway(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
