<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, April 2, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday,
Sunday and Monday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SLAIN-JOURNALIST (Colotlan, Mexico) _ Two men accused of killing
an American journalist have changed their story for a third time,
confounding investigators and their lawyer. It is the latest twist
in the frustrating story of the death of Philip True, the San
Antonio Express-News correspondent who died on a hike in western
Mexico late last year. By SUSANA HAYWARD. (For release Sunday,
April 4; photo available on Wieck database) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS-SISTERS (San Francisco) _ The Easter imbroglio between
the Roman Catholic Church and the campy Sisters of Perpetual
Indulgence, an often profane street theater group that targets the
church with its biting satire, is just as deeply dividing clergy of
other denominations. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-POW (San Antonio) _ Melissa Coleman, the first U.S. woman
taken prisoner during the Persian Gulf War, doesn't pay much
attention to the news. So when her mother told her about the three
U.S. servicemen who had been captured in the Balkans, Coleman said,
``Oh, goodness, here we go again.'' By CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-ATHEIST (San Antonio) _ Federal agents investigating the
disappearance of atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair have had extensive
talks with Gary P. Karr, a Michigan ex-convict charged with a
federal weapons violation, his lawyer said. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIAN-REFUGEE (Albany, N.Y.) _ If Anne Frank had survived the
Holocaust and lived to write another diary, she might have
struggled with the same questions that haunt Samira Huremovic, 18,
a refugee of the conflict between Serbians and Muslims in Bosnia.
How do you reclaim a childhood from the rubble of war, the darkness
of hiding, the press of a gun against your chest? How do you live
after a part of you has died? By CELINA OTTAWAY. (For release
Sunday, April 4.)
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-AMERICAN-VETS (San Francisco) _ The psychological wounds
suffered by Vietnam War veterans are well documented. But the
traumas of Asian American soldiers _ fighting in an unpopular war
against an enemy who looked like them _ are just now emerging. By
JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ A look at Diamond Multimedia's Rio
PMP300, which allows you to store tunes that you download from the
Internet, or copy from compact disks. It uses a format known as
MP3, which creates music files that are highly compressed and are
of reasonable quality. Although true audiophiles may turn their
noses up at MP3s, the sound is likely to please most listeners. By
DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader who recently installed an
older program that overwrote a crucial Windows 98 file wants to
know how he can avoid having Windows lock up when he turns on his
computer. Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-TOWNERS (Undated) _ Consider ``The Out-of-Towners''
to be confirmation that Steve Martin and Goldie Hawn never again
will be anything more than easy, safe amusement. One-time
progenitors of the comedic edge, they seem more willing to evoke
the slapstick of the 1930s screwball comedies than the kind of
irreverence that produced ``The Man with Two Brains'' and ``Private
Benjamin.'' By G. ALLEN JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CLEESE-PROFILE (Undated) _ John Cleese of Monty Python fame
talks about ``The Out-of-Towners,'' a new movie that also stars
Goldie Hawn and Steve Martin. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EDtv-PRODUCTS (Undated) _ Moviegoers who caught ``EDtv''
during its opening weekend couldn't help but notice the number of
name-brand products featured in the film. A look at this and
comments from director Ron Howard. By PAMELA MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SOPRANOS (Undated) _ HBO's ``The Sopranos'' is the best new
show on television. ``The Sopranos'' is a movie a week, better than
any movie-of-the-week, fueled by writing the quality of which is
rarely seen in a weekly series. On Sunday, it all wraps up after a
13-week run. The loss hurts, it's that good. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-TOONS (Undated) _ This is a tale of two toons, one embarking
on a very promising start, another that may have already peaked
after just two seasons. It's Fox's new ``Family Guy'' vs. Comedy
Central's ``South Park,'' which tries to rebound from a
disappointing second year. By MARK McGUIRE. (For release Monday,
April 5.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-WALK (Undated) _ In ``A Walk on the Moon,'' the
counterculture and the Catskills collide, with devastating results
for a middle-class Jewish family in the summer of 1969. These were
interesting times (as in the old curse, ``May you live in
interesting times'') and the film never lets us forget it, because
otherwise we might mistake the story for a simple domestic tragedy.
No, this is a tale of major cultural transition. By WALTER ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN-SHRINE (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ The artifacts in the
National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum are not of decades gone
by, but of the season past. They belonged to Sosa and McGwire and
Maris. Baseball is back. Cooperstown is back. How far did it have
to come? By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN-IFGO (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ This quaint town is in
fact a giant theme park, from its diners with baseball wallpaper
you would have killed for as a kid to the shops that offer
everything related to the sport. Still, it is not Disneyfied.
Cooperstown can be enjoyed for what it is, a comfortable upstate
village built for strolling its sidewalks, without even mentioning
the B-word. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Lorena Rodrigues Bottum writes
in the Wall Street Journal that ``so long as abortion is legal, it
will be neither an agonizing decision nor a rare one.'' In my
experience, the women who have been closest to me agonized aplenty.
By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Is New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, a man with political ambitions, willing to moderate his
tough-on-crime policies and see the violent crime rise in his city?
It's not a question that Giuliani was prepared to answer the other
night. But it had to be pretty much all he was thinking about. By
DAN LYNCH.
</P>
