<HEADER>
A3610 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN03-COX     04-02 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The best argument yet for strict gun control
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ A loyal reader called and asked me what she
should do about her possum problem which, as it turns out, wasn't a
possum problem at all but a gun control problem. I warn you now,
this column is going to sing the virtues of strict gun control. Be
prepared.
</P>
<P>
   But more about that in a moment. The woman called me as a last
hope _ I am often called as the very, very last hope _ about what
to do about the three-foot possum who wandered up on her porch
almost nightly to eat from her cat's food dish.
</P>
<P>
   I was tempted to tell her just to get rid of the kitty, name the
possum ``Snookems'' and pretend it was one of those ugly, hairless
cats, but she was serious. For a fact, a three-foot tall possum,
her description, not mine, is
</P>
<P>
   a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   I gave her all sorts of ideas, the most valuable of which was,
``Ask someone else,'' but none of them satisfied her. She had told
me up front that she lived in the country so I made one final
suggestion to just shoot the possum.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began a story that made me a life-long and firm believer in
gun control. It is a sad tale, really.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that years ago the woman did not have a possum problem
but, rather, an armadillo problem. The armadillo, it seems, loved
to eat from her garden. As anyone who has ever dealt with an
armadillo knows, they are not smart enough to be afraid of
anything. The woman found all manner of shooing and yelling
wouldn't move the armadillo.
</P>
<P>
   That is when she decided to get her husband's 12-gauge shotgun
and do the armadillo in. The only problem was that she didn't like
the kick in the shoulder from a 12-gauge, having gotten a nasty
bruise once. She had been told that she could simply hold the gun
to her side _ outstretched in her arms _ and fire. No kick. No
bruise.
</P>
<P>
   She fetched the gun, moved to within three feet of the
armadillo, held the gun out, closed her eyes and pulled the
trigger.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   She decided this was because the safety was on. She pushed the
safety button, held the gun out, closed her eyes and pulled the
trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred to her then that the gun might not be loaded. She
was right.
</P>
<P>
   She put a shell in the chamber, held the gun out, closed her
eyes and pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing happened. It was the darn safety thing.
</P>
<P>
   She pushed the safety button, held the gun out, closed her eyes
and pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   This time, something happened. First things first: the
armadillo's next meal came from that garden in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   But as the shot was being fired, it seemed as if that 12-gauge
shotgun had a life of its own. It leapt from the woman's hands and
seemed to fly away. By the time its trip was over, the barrel had
embedded in the ground and the stock had darn near broken the
woman's foot.
</P>
<P>
   It was near nighttime, but not dark enough for the woman, who
was dressed in her red-stripped holiday robe which made her appear
as if a giant, jumping peppermint stick had invaded the yard.
</P>
<P>
   She hopped and yelled for five minutes before the phone started
ringing in the house and she had to hop up the porch stairs to get
it.
</P>
<P>
   It was her neighbor on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeri Lynn (of course, I never got the woman's name, but she
sounded like a Jeri Lynn to me) I heard the gun go off. Did you
shoot yourself in the foot?''
</P>
<P>
   Between moaning and crying the woman assured the neighbor she
was fine but swore then and there she would never bear arms again.
</P>
<P>
   The gun stayed where it was until her husband got home, barrel
in the ground, sticking up like a pole. If she had had a piece of
sheet, she could have fashioned a truce flag.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the moral of the story. Without the proper
amount of gun control, firearms can be extremely hazardous to your
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall News Messenger.
His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
