<HEADER>
A3612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN03-COX     04-02 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He rues a late garden, but kangaroos on agenda
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ I was contentedly leafing through the
spring seed catalogs, dreaming of fresh butter beans and tomatoes
that don't taste like pink cardboard when she made her
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly and Bobby Mobley are going to Australia,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a shocker,'' I replied. ``Has Bobby joined the Army?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course he hasn't joined the Army,'' she said. ``Why do you
say a thing like that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I've never known of anybody going to Australia unless
they were in the Army and were sent there,'' I explained.
``President Roosevelt had to give General MacArthur a direct order
to make him go when the Japanese were about to take Corregidor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's not an old fuddy-duddy like you,'' she said. ``He
wants to see what the rest of the world is like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already been to Rock City and to Birmingham, and to
Alaska where he lost his suitcase and had to wear the same
underwear for a week. I don't think he's ready for extended world
travel,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, when Bobby's wealthy and sophisticated wife
wanted to go to a convention at Disney World, she asked me to give
him lessons on how to behave in high society. After several
sessions over coffee in the Waffle House, I convinced him to leave
his bib overalls and John Deere cap at home. He got by fairly well
except for reading Playboy in the hotel lobby and insisting that
the wine steward bring him a bottle with a screw cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Bobby have any idea where Australia is?'' I asked. ``They
could take half a dozen vacations in Panama City for the price of
one airplane ticket. The flight from Atlanta to Australia takes
longer than the Gulf War.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They want us to go with them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Australia!'' I exclaimed. ``No way. If we went to Australia
I wouldn't have time to plant English peas. I'd be late on the
butter beans and Silver Queen, not to mention setting out
tomatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another good reason to go to Australia,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we went to Australia what could we do other than look at
kangaroos?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly says they have tickets to hear the Sydney symphony
orchestra in Sydney's famous opera house,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   I was flabbergasted. ``You mean Bobby has agreed to go hear a
symphony orchestra?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said, ``he thinks Willie and Waylon are on the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How long are they going to be away on this excursion?'' I
inquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only about a month.'' she answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Won't they get tired of kangaroos and symphony orchestras?'' I
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't be in Australia all the time,'' she explained.
``They're also going to New Zealand and the Fiji Islands. If you
want to stay home and plant English peas, I can go by myself. It
won't be like I'm traveling alone. I'll be with Bobby and
Beverly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're saying Bobby is going to take care of both you and
Beverly for nearly a month in three foreign countries when he's
barely been north of Palmetto?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been to Las Vegas,'' she retorted.
</P>
<P>
   As a responsible spouse, I had to think about that. Bobby made
it through the upscale Disney World convention without serious
incidents, but his visit to New Orleans was a near disaster. It's a
long story. In a nutshell, he got caught in a hotel lobby trying to
dispose of a pistol just as President Clinton was arriving. Secret
Service dogs sniffed him out as a suspicious character, and except
for an incompetent New Orleans cop who let him off the hook, he was
looking at 10 to 20 in a federal penitentiary instead of planning a
trip to Australia, New Zealand and Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   I love my wife. I feel responsible for the mother of my
children.
</P>
<P>
   Against my better judgment, and after some negotiations, I
agreed to join Bobby and Beverly on their journey to the South
Pacific. A month is a good chunk out of what's left of my life, but
I just couldn't trust Bobby to look after two adventuresome women
on a continent infested with wombats and crocodiles.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for my promise not to complain about airplane food
and toilets that require an engineering degree from Georgia Tech to
operate, my wife agreed to let me plant an extra row of butter
beans and as many pole beans and as much Silver Queen corn as I
want. After what we're spending on this trip, even she understands
we'll need something to put up for winter.
</P>
<P>
   Against my better judgment, and even though we aren't in world
war like in 1942, we are off to Australia, New Zealand and the Fiji
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   I hope Bobby doesn't cause any problems I can't handle. After he
passed the security check at Hartsfield Airport I'm pretty sure he
left his pistol at home, but I don't know about the bib overalls.
If they show up at the Sydney opera house, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
