<HEADER>
A3614 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-SISTERACT03-COX     04-02 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SISTERACT03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams sisters coming of age
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILTON HEAD, S.C. _ Martina Hingis has heard the talk, and she
can't say that she likes it. Initially, it was mainly just the
Williams sisters and their eccentric father, Richard, who were
predicting that Venus and Serena would be 1-2 in the world soon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after the sisters' eye-popping performances the past few
weeks _ a pair of titles for each _ the idea is gaining popular
appeal. Even some of their rivals are admitted believers.
</P>
<P>
   But not Hingis. Stop to consider the facts, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they have been playing very well the last two
tournaments,'' Hingis said this week at the Family Circle Cup,
``but before it wasn't that great. They still haven't won a Grand
Slam or anything like that. So once they've done this, we can talk
about it then. But not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters didn't come to the Family Circle Cup, but their
memorable March remains a hot conversation piece here despite
Hingis' admonition.
</P>
<P>
   Venus has won 10 matches in a row, including a three-setter
Sunday against Serena in the final of the Lipton, the so-called
``fifth major.'' Serena, the little sister, has been perhaps more
remarkable. She had won 16 in a row before falling to Venus, and
she made Hingis, Lindsay Davenport and Monica Seles appear helpless
against her speed and power.
</P>
<P>
   In her victory over Hingis last week, Serena had more winners
than the No. 1 player, 48 to 11, and routinely stroked unreturnable
shots off Hingis' serve.
</P>
<P>
   What people are seeing are players with superior court coverage,
power off both wings, huge serves and the ability to end points at
the net. Who else brings the total package physically?
</P>
<P>
   Davenport and Seles lack speed, and Graf and Jana Novotna have
only defensive backhands. Hingis struggles to hold serve against
heavy hitters, who appear to be the future of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting better athletes in tennis _ bigger, stronger,
quicker and also more nimble,'' said Rick Macci, the Williamses'
first professional coach. ``That's what those two bring to the
table that no other players can match.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Macci who in 1991 first made the prediction that the
sisters would ascend to No. 1 before 2000. They were 10 and 11
years old at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be tough this year, but you can see where it is
headed,'' Macci said. It's as though the question is not if they'll
be No. 1, but who will get there first.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is they both will be at the top,'' said the
third-ranked Novotna, who has had more success than most against
Venus, holding a 3-1 career edge.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna won't choose between the two, but those who will are
going with Serena more and more. One is Amanda Coetzer, a former
top-five player who has lost to both sisters by identical 6-4, 6-0
scores this year. ``Serena's game, to me, is a little bit more
consistent,'' Coetzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Serena proponent is Graf, who picked her to beat Venus
at the Lipton.
</P>
<P>
   Irina Spirlea, who branded Venus as stuck-up after their 1997
U.S. Open semifinal, also favors Serena. ``Not that Venus isn't
playing well, but I think Serena is playing cleaner,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams, who once claimed Serena ultimately would
surpass her sister, has changed his opinion now. ``Venus is too
strong and too fast and hits the ball too hard,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, for once, agreed with Richard Williams. ``Venus has
always been the more dangerous of the sisters,'' she said. ``She's
more tough mentally to play and beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena has suffered moments of despair in the clutch, most
notably her collapses against Hingis at last year's Lipton and
against Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario at the 1998 French Open.
</P>
<P>
   For Serena, gutty wins over Hingis and Graf this year were
ghost-busters. They also earned her respect in the locker room. In
fact, the sisters, by backing up their brashness, are rarely
criticized for arrogance anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Spirlea, once a bold critic, has made peace. ``I think they've
changed a lot,'' she said this week. ``I mean, now we start making
jokes, and they can handle it. They are normal now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis remains curious to see how the sisters will handle their
latest success. They've always been the hunters, Hingis noted. Now,
rivals are beginning to lay low for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how it felt when nobody was beating me,'' said Hingis,
who opened 1997 with a 37-match winning streak. ``You feel
invincible. But at that stage, you have to keep motivating
yourself, because the other players are going to go after you.
That's what we're doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
