<P>
   MEXICO-BOTANICAL _ MEXICO CITY _ The Spanish conquistadors
talked about suffering for months because they had to eat local
``weeds'' as they marched through Mexico nearly 500 years ago.
Today, at Mexico City's Botanical Garden botanists are reviving an
appreciation for this country's vast native plant life and its
nutritional and medicinal value. In addition to a huge collection
of agaves and cacti, the garden grows plants loaded with vitamins
or known to ease childbirth, stomach ailments and other troubles.
Workers at the garden often help themselves to leaves of one plant
to brew a tea that fights anemia. The garden is run by Mexico's
National Autonomous University, where researchers are also involved
in international projects to develop medicines to treat AIDS,
tuberculosis and other diseases -- research that combines high-tech
science with the knowledge of traditional healers. (Ferriss, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (l) Lifestyle and (i) International categories.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ This column will resume shortly. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINECOXNET SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week.
This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH 0402 INFANT MASSAGE _ Massaging infants for
health benefits and to promote mother-baby bonding has been
practiced for centuries in other countries, such as India and
Russia. But now it's been getting around America where health care
workers are using it to calm babies born colicky, drug-addicted or
premature. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MEDICINE CABINET _ Open up your medicine cabinet. What do you
see? If you're like many people, what's there isn't reassuring.
Odds are that the contents wouldn't help someone who needed first
aid _ or even someone with a sore throat. A combo cleanup and
stock-up will mean you'll be ready when someone in your family
comes down with the flu, gets an insect bite or has food poisoning.
(Chan Santos, Austin American-Statesman.)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH BRIEFS _ (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CHOCOLATE _ Chocolate is now an essential part of a
balanced diet. Really. That is, if it's the kind that contains a
hefty dose of calcium, such as Viactiv Soft Calcium Chews, a new
product that delivers 500 milligrams of elemental calcium concealed
by chewy chocolate goodness. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BABIES-LEARNING _ How much do babies know and when do they learn
it? Parents may wonder and guess, but experts in child development
like those at the Children's Research Laboratory at UT are looking
for concrete answers. And they can't do it without babies willing
to sacrifice a few hours for science. Katie and I participate in a
study of infant perception. (Bonnin, Austin American-Statesman).
20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BABIES-SIDE _ Pullout of some of the questions/tests/areas of
research needed. (Bonnin, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   MILLENIUM-CHRISTIANITY _ ROME - On a sunny morning, the
distinctive dome of St. Peter's Basilica casts a shadow that
dominates the landscape below. Visitors climb hundreds of narrow,
curved stairs to the 435-foot cupola of the building for a
perspective of Rome. The shadowy shape adds symbolism to the scene.
This modern city _ where motorscooterists regard red lights as
suggestions, cellular telephones ring continually, and tourists
line up outside Gucci and Prada _ is defined by Catholicism. To
celebrate Easter, the holiest day of their year, tens of thousands
of Christians are here today to gather outside St. Peter's, the
home church of a billion Catholics. With the year 2000 only months
away, the festivities are a foretaste of what will take place here
as Christians hold a year-long birthday party. The setting is
appropriate. The history of the faith can be traced by a walk down
these narrow streets. (Gwhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 4.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MIILLENIUM-VATICAN _ VATICAN CITY _ On the ancient gray-brown
cobblestones of St. Peter's square, with moss and trampled
cigarette butts between them, a Sunday morning crowd gathers that
seems to be a portrait of the world. This is ground zero for the
largest Christian denomination in the world, the center of a
separate ``country'' with its own government, newspaper, radio
station and publishing house, home to about 1,000 people. Decisions
made here have changed the course of Europe and the world. (Gwhite,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 69. EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 4.
</P>
<P>
   MIILLENIUM-ORVIETO _ ORVIETO - You can see your breath in the
sanctuary of St. Andrew and St. Bartholomew Church on a drizzly
Saturday night during Lent. Half a dozen space heaters feebly try
to battle the chill of a temperature barely breaking the 30s as
older women, in wool or fur coats, gather on the hard, worn wooden
pews to pray the rosary. St. Andrew and St. Bartholomew is a
combined parish of about 400 families in the medieval part of this
hill town of 21,000 people in the region of Umbria about 90 minutes
from Rome. The church is one of hundreds of struggling
congregations off the usual path of tourists in Italy, the homeland
of Catholicism. Although some 80 percent Italians identify
themselves as Christian and virtually all are Catholic, Catholicism
is often more a matter of culture than of practice. (Gwhite,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).19. EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 4.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENIUM-TIMELINE _ Detailed look at highlights of Christianity
through the middle ages. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). EMBARGOED
UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 4.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENIUM-BOX _ As Christianity triumphed throughout Rome and
the rest of Europe, sites and monuments that were once pagan were
co-opted to Catholic use. We offer three examples. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 7. EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 4.
</P>
<P>
   PASSOVER-MARKET _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Rabbi Moshe Scheiner's
journey from Miami medical salesman to Palm Beach rabbi whose
synagogue, the Palm Beach Orthodox Synagogue, is the ballroom roof
garden of the Palm Beach Hotel. He is up against the celebrity
rabbi who threatens to come from Long Island. (Gushee, Palm Beach
Post). 22. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-EASTER _ ``He has risen.'' Those three words, found in
the New Testament, mark the beginning of the Easter story. For some
Christians, the bodily resurrection of Jesus is hard to believe.
For them Easter symbolizes that Jesus' teachings, like Beethoven's
music, lives on after his death. Others insist, however, that Jesus
literally rose from the dead. We examine the view from both camps
and see how the faithful at oppostive ends of the spectrum find
meaning in Easter. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   SALVAGE _ Wrought iron gates with rust around the edges. Pine
doors with scratches from a dog. Fireplace mantels with peeling
layers of blue, yellow and white paint. Stained glass windows with
rippling rich-colored panes. These objects, once destined for the
junk yard, are being transformed into trendy garden accents, wall
hangings and furniture. Homeowners are rummaging through antique
stores, used building supply stores and flea markets to find the
perfect piece of history _ one that will give their homes a flavor
different from the high-tech, high-gloss, modern world they
inhabit. (Villalpando, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
