<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3646 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN04-COX     04-02 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEADLINE: Eggs-actly what was needed for Easter
 &HT;    FOR RELEASE APRIL 4, 1999
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Ana Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people's Easter memories include boiled eggs; mine are over
easy.
</P>
<P>
   We were a large Catholic family blessed with Mexican heritage.
To us kids, the solemnity of Lent made Easter a much anticipated
time. We looked forward to it because we knew it was a time for
celebration and a time for great fun.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for cascarones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cascaron'' is the Spanish word for shell. Cascarones are dyed,
confetti filled egg shells we would crack over each other's head.
By the end of Easter Sunday, my long black hair would be glistening
with shiny bits of paper and egg shell. I'm sure my mother looked
so forward to shampooing it that evening.
</P>
<P>
   There's probably an explanation of this tradition somewhere but
I don't recall ever hearing it. Here's what I do remember.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning around Ash Wednesday, my sisters and I would
religiously begin collecting egg shells. At least one daily
collection opportunity existed: breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the usual whack in the middle of the egg, my mom
would carefully tap its narrow end against the frying pan. Her goal
was to make the opening large enough for the inside of the egg to
pass through but not so large that it wouldn't hold the confetti.
About 95 percent of the time, the yolk would catch a sharp edge,
and we would have scrambled eggs.
</P>
<P>
   I have nothing against scrambled eggs. In fact, my consumption
of all kinds of eggs has dropped considerably over the last several
years. But, like my dad and my siblings, I prefer mine over easy.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, as soon as we were old enough to handle the
delicate task, we helped wash the shells and left them to dry. Once
dry, we put them in egg cartons and placed those on the top pantry
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   We compared notes with neighborhood kids daily to see who had
collected the most, and demand for egg dishes rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Come Holy Saturday, we would make the dye for the boiled eggs
and for the cascarones. Meanwhile, one of us children would gather
a shoebox, scissors, crepe paper and leftover wrapping paper and
began snipping the colored paper into the smallest possible pieces.
Though it may sound tedious, it was rather soothing running the
scissors through the scraps and watching them become tinier and
tinier as they cascaded over your hand.
</P>
<P>
   Creating the glitter was a coveted task and usually a younger
sister would want to do it. We let her, but she would soon tire and
one of us older ones would sagely take over and complete the task,
being careful to reserve enough paper to make seals for the
cascarones.
</P>
<P>
   The seals were crepe paper circles which we glued to the
openings in the confetti filled shells. The ``glue'' was a
flour/water mixture applied with a toothpick.
</P>
<P>
   We then placed our finished creations back into the egg cartons
to dry overnight and await their Sunday morning fate.
</P>
<P>
   We still had to get through, I mean, attend Mass, but our
parents always consented to let us bring a portion of our treasures
along. The main arsenal had to be preserved for the egg hunt and
picnic that afternoon. Though the grown-ups never allowed us to
bring the cascarones into the sanctuary, we convinced them that no
kid worth her salt would come to Easter Mass unarmed. The egg
cartons waited in the car.
</P>
<P>
   After the service, mayhem reigned on the church grounds as we
kids chased each other and cascarones exploded like paper
fireworks. Soon, the church lawn bore its own colorful Easter garb.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, and for breakfast, we had eggs, over easy.
</P>
<P>
   (Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, P.O. Box 1792, Longview, TX 75606. E-mail:
awalker(a)coxnews.com)
</P>
