<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
RIO, MP3s DELIVER TUNES FOR OUR TIMES 
 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last couple of years, prognosticators have been saying
that simple Internet appliances would eventually do away with most
folks' need for a personal computer. Why put up with the
inefficiencies, cost and complexity of a PC when you can have all
the power you need in the palm of your hand?
</P>
<P>
   However, so far it appears that reports of the PC's death have
been greatly exaggerated. Internet appliances are few and far
between, and those that have made it to market are not
mega-sellers.
</P>
<P>
   That is, with one fascinating and surprising exception: the Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of Internet appliances usually tout e-mail, Web
surfing _ even online phone calls. But who would have thought that
the first really popular Net appliance would have been something
you use to listen to music?
</P>
<P>
   Diamond Multimedia's Rio PMP300 allows you to store tunes that
you download from the Internet, or copy from compact disks. It uses
a format known as MP3, which creates music files that are highly
compressed and are of reasonable quality. Although true audiophiles
may turn their noses up at MP3s, the sound is likely to please most
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MUSIC INDUSTRY SOUNDS ALARMS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both MP3 and the Rio have given the traditional music industry
fits, and are illustrative of the oft-quoted pronouncement that
``the Internet changes everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The big recording companies are alarmed at the explosive
popularity of MP3s because it undermines their control of music
distribution. Suddenly, thousands of previously unknown bands and
individual artists can get their work heard worldwide merely by
submitting MP3 files to Web sites such as MP3.com. This also means
that musicians who don't fit an easily defined commercial mold can
get a global hearing, even if they're not considered commercially
viable enough to land a recording contract.
</P>
<P>
   The industry also is concerned about piracy _ it's easy to
convert a CD track into an MP3 file, though the sound quality isn't
as good.
</P>
<P>
   The recording companies are attempting to come up with their
own, alternative music file format that will, in some way, prevent
piracy. But I suspect it'll be too little, too late _ the genie is
out of the bottle with MP3, and there's no stuffing him back in.
</P>
<P>
   If MP3 makes the music moguls nervous, then the Rio has given
them convulsions. They tried unsuccessfully in court to stop
Diamond from distributing it, arguing it would encourage piracy.
But Diamond correctly argued that, because the Rio only downloads
music and doesn't upload it to another PC, that piracy is not even
an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Although Diamond won with this argument, amateur, independent
software programmers have now produced programs that let you move
MP3 files out of a Rio and onto a PC's hard drive. Whether the
recording industry will take another legal run at the Rio as a
result is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUALITY PLAYS IMPORTANT ROLE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've been playing with a Rio for several weeks, and I understand
all the fuss. This is a pretty cool gadget, if a little expensive.
It has a list price of about $200 _ it needs to sell for half that
or less in order to be a true mass-market device. It also needs
simpler software.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio's black, plastic case is slightly smaller than a pack of
cigarettes, yet it has all the functions you'd find on a portable
compact disk player _ play, stop, fast forward, rewind, random play
and so on.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of storing music on disk or tape, it holds MP3 files
in 32 megabytes of computer memory. You can also insert the small
Flash Media cards that are used to hold pictures in some digital
cameras for extra storage.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, you can hold up to an hour's worth of music, but that
really depends on the quality of the MP3 files. When you record an
MP3, you can vary the amount of compression _ the more compression,
the more you lose in sound quality. At the full 60 minutes, most
music sounds like a decent-quality FM radio. If you decrease the
compression, it sounds more like a good portable tape player.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with headphones that are actually tiny speakers you jam
into your ears. It's a little uncomfortable, but I got used to it
after a while. The sound is not bad, but you can always replace
them with a more traditional headset.
</P>
<P>
   To connect the Rio to your Windows 95/98 PC, just plug the
accompanying adapter into your parallel port _ it has a
pass-through for your printer _ and then plug the Rio into the
adapter. I found the adapter conflicted with some other devices
that use the parallel port, such as an external, re-writable CD-ROM
drive I was testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio comes with software that lets you convert CD tracks to
MP3 files, as well as organize MP3 files into play lists. However,
this software is separate from the program you use to transfer the
tunes into the Rio.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Rio's software is its weakest component. I found it
confusing to use, with too many small windows. To use it, you first
must create a play list in one window, then copy the list,
file-by-file, into another window that represents the Rio's memory.
It can be complicated further if you are working with CD-based
music, which must be converted.
</P>
<P>
   This should all be one step _ I'd like to copy a CD tune
directly into the Rio, with the MP3 conversion process rendered
transparent. Or, how about a browser plug-in that can transfer a
file right from an MP3 Web site into the Rio.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, I suspect we'll see all this, and in similar
devices that cost much less _ in the $30-$40 price range. But for
now, the Rio gives a nifty glance into the intriguing future of
music.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
