<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3704 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-02 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S TOUGH CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ I really didn't expect New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani to say much about the Amadou Diallo killing. It's the
worst crisis of his administration _ seven straight weeks of daily
demonstrations at New York City police headquarters, more than
1,700 people arrested so far, including many bigtime New York City
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's poll numbers among both whites and non-whites have
dipped into the basement.
</P>
<P>
   If he did say anything significant on the topic, though, I
wanted to be there. So I went to Hudson Valley Community College
the other night to see Giuliani before he delivered his speech at
the annual dinner of the Rensselaer County Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cops have been indicted on second-degree murder charges
in this case,'' I said to him. ``As a former prosecutor, do you
think that's an appropriate charge? Do you see any indication of
premeditation in Mr. Diallo's death?''
</P>
<P>
   I won't try this case in the press, Giuliani responded. I don't
want anybody tried in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, though, that's where this disaster is being tried.
And it's not just the four New York City police officers who blew
away Diallo who are on trial. The entire department of 40,000 men
and women are under ferocious attack. So is Giuliani. In case
you've somehow missed all this, an immigrant from Guinea named
Amadou Diallo was standing in the vestibule of a building in the
Bronx around midnight on Feb. 4. Four members of the New York City
Police Department's Street Crime Unit happened by. They were
looking for a serial rapist in a neighborhood where guns are not
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York Post _ recounting a version that seems
to have come from one or more of the cops' lawyers or, possibly,
from the police union _ the officers approached the stoop of the
building wearing badges around their necks. The Post gave this
account: One officer had his pistol unholstered, pointed at the
sidewalk. They told Diallo they were cops and ordered him to,
``Hold it. Stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   Diallo turned and tried to enter the building. The police
ordered him to come out and show his hands. When he couldn't open
the door, he turned to his left and reached into his pocket. He
began to pull something black from the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   One cop shouted, ``Gun! He's got a gun!''
</P>
<P>
   The officer who had his gun in hand fired at Diallo three times.
In police vernacular, he ``triple-tapped.'' Then the cop who'd
fired stepped back and fell off the stoop onto his back on the
sidewalk. The other police officers, hearing the cry that Diallo
was armed, hearing the shots and seeing their comrade fall,
immediately drew and fired.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 41 police bullets flew into that vestibule. Nineteen
hit Diallo. The gun he supposedly had reached for turned out to be
a wallet. He wasn't the rapist they were after. He was, in fact, as
clean as a whistle.
</P>
<P>
   New York City is in a frenzied uproar over this. Part of what's
happening is a concerted effort by Guiliani's political enemies to
drive him from office or, failing that, to wound him grievously in
advance of the U.S. Senate run he would like to make next year.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this, however, is legitimate concern over the conduct of
the Street Crime Unit, a largely white force that works mostly in
minority neighborhoods in a huge city that's less than half white.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's cops, and primarily this unit, have adopted
aggressive crime-fighting methods. They've made stop-and-frisk
procedures the centerpiece of their tactics. In the last two years,
this unit has stopped and frisked 40,000 New Yorkers. They've found
grounds to arrest fewer than one in four of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution requires
cops to stop and frisk only when they have a ``reasonable
suspicion'' _ one they can clearly articulate _ that a crime has
taken place or is about to take place. That legal nicety seems
largely ignored in New York City. Last year, roughly half the
felony gun cases brought to court in Manhattan were deemed
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Street Crime Unit members sport T-shirts proclaiming that, ``We
Own the Night!'' Overwhelmingly, they're young and more courageous
than experienced.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is this: It works.
</P>
<P>
   The year before Giuliani became mayor, 2,200 New Yorkers were
murdered. Last year, New York had 600 murders _ fewer than Chicago,
with only one-third New York's population. Stranger murders, in
particular, are down. Bad guys who carry guns and kill on impulse
aren't carrying and killing the way they used to _ not with all
that stopping and frisking taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Also, statistics indicate that New York City's cops are not
trigger happy. Last year, they had a fatal shooting rate that was
only two-thirds that of Philadelphia's cops. It was half the rate
of the Dallas police, one-fourth the rate of Miami's and less than
one-sixth that of Washington's.
</P>
<P>
   From a public policy standpoint, the question is whether the
police can effectively deter crime with such tactics without the
collateral damage of an occasional Amadou Diallo. What's the
acceptable number of dead, innocent men required to maintain tight
police control over public spaces?
</P>
<P>
   The political question is whether this mayor, a term-limited
politician with obvious ambitions, is willing to moderate those
policies and see the violent crime rise in his city. It was not a
question that Giuliani was prepared to answer the other night at
Hudson Valley Community College.
</P>
<P>
   But it had to be pretty much all he was thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
