<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOONS-$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPING FOR A `SOUTH PARK' COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, April 5)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a tale of two toons, one embarking on a very promising
start, another that may have already peaked after just two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has such high hopes for ``Family Guy'' that it has slotted
it in the coveted 8:30 p.m. EST slot Sunday after ``The Simpsons''
starting this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Over on Comedy Central, ``South Park,'' which had one of the
greatest rookie seasons on record, tries to rebound from a
disappointing second year, starting with its third-season premiere
at 10 p.m. EST Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   First, let's go through the cultural references in the second
episode of the ``Family Guy,'' which returns to Fox after more than
a two-month absence following its post-Super Bowl debut:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sesame Street.'' The Wright Brothers. Driver's test. ``Star
Trek.'' William Shatner's overacting. The Road Runner and Wile E.
Coyote. The Amish. ``CHiPs.'' Fox reality shows (``Fast Animals,
Slow Children''). Rosie O'Donnell. Addiction to television.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, no, we are just getting started ... Bigfoot. Sneaking into
R-rated movies. The Vietnam War. Vacuous television anchors. See 'N
Says. AOL chat rooms. ``Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory.''
Dennis Franz's butt. James Woods. PBS. ``The Wonder Years.''
``Scooby Doo.'' ``The Wizard of Oz.'' ``Alf.'' ``Gilligan's
Island.'' ``Lost in Space.'' ``I Dream of Jeannie.'' ``Bewitched.''
Lifetime, CBS, UPN and Fox networks. ``Beverly Hills: 90210.''We're
in the homestretch ... Charles Manson. NBC reruns. Old Raisin Bran
commercials. ``Batman.'' Adolf Hitler's invasion of Poland and
takeover of Czechoslovakia. William Shatner's overacting. The
``Star Trek'' landing team guy in the red shirt always getting
killed. William Shatner's overacting. William Shatner's hairpiece.
William Shatner's gut. Klondike Bar commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to exhale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Guy,'' from the mind of 25-year-old Seth McFarlane,
chronicles the Griffins of Rhode Island. Dad is a lovable buffoon
in the Ralph Kramden/Fred Flintstone tradition. His wife, Lois, is
the moral center, as is the pet dog, Brian.
</P>
<P>
   High-schooler Meg and younger brother Chris try to get noticed,
while infant Stewie, the genius with the British accent (but
understood only by the show's viewers), is trying to take over the
world and make it safe from broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, open up for the airplane,'' mom says.``Never! Damn
broccoli,'' Stewie shouts. ``Damn you. And damn the Wright
brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   You will think of ``Airplane,'' watching this show. Don't laugh
too hard; you'll miss three or four lines. Guarantee at least two
or three will be good. Then there is ``South Park,'' the story of
four coarse little kids from Colorado, one of whom dies in every
episode.
</P>
<P>
   The show returns with Kyle, Kenny, Stan and Eric being placed in
an Up With People-style choir, ``Getting Gay with Kids,'' who
travel to Costa Rica to help save the rain forest. They are led by
a hippie music teacher (guest star Jennifer Aniston of
``Friends''), who soon develops a different take on nature.
</P>
<P>
   The episode is good. Not great, not even close, and certainly
not up to the stellar standards set in the first season. And
``South Park'' has been that way for a while.
</P>
<P>
   In sports, there is an expression called ``The Sophomore Jinx.''
It's an axiom that applies to a player who had a great rookie year,
but stumbled in his second. Some players recover from the sophomore
jinx, others don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park: The Movie'' is slated to come out in June. Before
then, I would like to see ``South Park,'' the series, make a
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
