<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARELESS ASSERTIONS ABOUT `CASUAL ABORTIONS' 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an impressive leap of logic on the Wall
Street Journal's opinion page, a Washington, D.C., writer named
Lorena Rodrigues Bottum made the following declaration:
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as abortion is legal, it will be neither an agonizing
decision nor a rare one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottum based this grotesque conclusion on two things:
</P>
<P>
   _ A single conversation with two unidentified neighbors, in
which both ``casually discuss their multiple casual abortions with
a stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   _ An erroneous account of Monica Lewinsky's admission to Barbara
Walters that she had an abortion while working at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who didn't watch the Walters program would have to take
Bottum's word for it that Lewinsky ``casually mentioned'' the
abortion and, ``like the rest of her conduct, it was nothing she
was ashamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone who did watch must wonder at the quality of Bottum's
cable reception. A dark look passed over Lewinsky's face when
Walters brought up the abortion. Then she nodded and said only that
it was ``a very sensitive subject.'' In a voice-over Walters said
that Lewinsky ``was clearly uncomfortable'' talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   So who knows about the accuracy of Bottum's chat with her
neighbors?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe one woman really did say she'd feared she was pregnant and
would have to have ``another abortion ... right in the middle of
packing'' for a move to Africa. And maybe the other woman really
did commiserate by saying: ``Oh, I know. It's so expensive and you
feel sick for days afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, from this single exchange _ and the skewed Lewinsky
account _ Bottum indicted all of ``modern America'' and ``the
current abortion situation'' for turning ``good, ordinary people''
into abject moral failures. Nothing short of a return to illegal
back alley abortions, she intimated, would drive home the gravity
of our deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Given the fact that some 1.3 million legal abortions are
performed each year in the United States, I would never presume to
characterize the attitude of all or even the majority of the women
who have them. Women being people, it's safe to say that their
attitudes vary and probably run the gamut from blase to
grief-consumed.
</P>
<P>
   What I can say since Bottum is so comfy with anecdotal evidence
is this: In the 26 years since Roe vs. Wade made abortion a
constitutionally protected issue of privacy, I have never heard a
single woman make a joke about her abortion. On the other hand, I
have seen a lot of women cry about having the procedure _ some,
many years after.
</P>
<P>
   I have heard a few women, usually unmarried and in their early
20s, harp upon the physical pain, expense and inconvenience of an
abortion. But I have heard many more women speak thoughtfully and
sadly _ not in regret for the choice they made but in regret for
ever needing to make a choice.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, in my experience, most women do not appear to
take abortion casually. Whether each ``agonized'' over her
decision, I don't know. I know that the women who have been closest
to me agonized aplenty.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week in San Francisco, the National Abortion Rights
Action League held its annual Power of Choice luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   The group's president, Kate Michelman, spoke at length about
people like Lorena Rodrigues Bottum _ people who want abortion to
once again be illegal and thus unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   By ``keeping the act of abortion, not the issue of privacy''
before the country's eyes, said Michelman, such people intend to
``deny and shame women in need'' and to ``spread ambivalence
throughout America.''
</P>
<P>
   If some of them have to do it with skewed truths and whopping
over-generalizations as Bottum did, so be it. They have a dream,
you see: To once again live in a nation where a woman has but two
choices _ to bear an unwanted child or find the right alley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
