<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOPRANOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SOPRANOS' TAKES AN INTERMISSION, AND IT'S MUCH TOO LONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call ``The Sopranos'' the best new show on television if you
want. You would be right, of course, but still off-base.
</P>
<P>
   No, ``The Sopranos'' is the best show on television, period. And
if you don't like it, I'll send Silvio, Paulie Walnuts and the rest
of Tony's crew over for a little talk.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's not even close, which says more about this
exhilarating drama than it does about the rest of television. ``The
Sopranos'' is a movie a week, better than any movie-of-the-week,
fueled by writing the quality of which is rarely seen in a weekly
series.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, it all wraps up (9 p.m. EST, HBO), a 13-week run that
began in January. If you think the first 12 left you stunned, be
ready to force your jaw back into joint when it falls to the floor.
The funny thing is, after watching Sunday's episode a fan will be
left with an empty feeling, a hunger, only because they know they
can't get a new fix next week. In fact, you will have to wait until
next January for new installments (the 13-episode season will be
rerun, in order, on Wednesdays at 9 p.m. beginning June 9). It
hurts.
</P>
<P>
   It's that good. Even those who don't subscribe to HBO have
gotten caught up in the show, trading tapes like Grateful
Deadheads. The appeal stems in part from the show's ability to turn
from comedy to violence to a skewed version of the ``The Waltons''
faster than a foot soldier can pull a gun from his ankle holster.
It's short of glorifying the Mafia, but certainly strikes a chord
of empathy that leaves people rooting for the boss, even as he is
snuffing a rival.
</P>
<P>
   For those playing catch-up: ``The Sopranos'' chronicles the life
of Tony Soprano (James Gandolfini), the power behind the North
Jersey mob. Sure, he is not above the stray shooting or strangling
for business purposes, but he has feelings, too. To deal with his
mounting pressures from The Family and his family, not to mention a
complicated childhood, Tony goes off to see a shrink (Lorraine
Bracco). The results are both therapeutic and lethal. Already,
devotees talk of episodes the way ``Sopranos'' characters talk of
the ``Godfather'' installments. Did you see in ``4'' when Anthony
Jr. figured out about what his dad does for a living? Oh yeah, what
about ``9'' and that secret Uncle Junior wants to keep? Sure, but
nothing beats ``5.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, ``5,'' officially titled ``College,'' when daughter Meadow
Soprano (Jamie Lynn Sigler) and doting dad Tony Soprano go off to
Maine to tour colleges. Unfortunately, he runs into an old mob
stoolie, so while daughter is meeting with college counselors dad
is introducing the rat to a dirt nap.
</P>
<P>
   It was in this episode that dad is also confronted with his
daughter's knowledge that he is not just in ``waste management.''
It is an uncomfortable moment, and the signature of this series:
The delicate balance between a man who genuinely cares for his
family, friends even ducks but is more than willing to kill.
</P>
<P>
   In short, ``The Sopranos'' works on every level, but here are
some particularly key components to its artistic and commercial
success:
</P>
<P>
   _ It's not (network) TV. It's HBO: The show was shopped to the
networks, which passed. Good thing, since even on Fox ``The
Sopranos'' could not have realized its full potential. While the
violence and nudity (at times, yes, excessive) would never fly on
the nets, it is the profane dialogue that is intrinsic, giving the
show a good deal of its atmosphere and dramatic shading.
</P>
<P>
   _ Location, location, location: You know if, say, ABC was making
this show, it would be shot on some back lot outside of Hollywood.
For HBO, the show is filmed on location in North Jersey. It is fun
to pick out Jersey haunts, like Paterson Falls. And you can't
replicate that Manhattan skyline.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mommie dearest: Nancy Marchand, as matriarch Livia Soprano, is
the character that has fans talking the most. She is either simply
the most overbearing, manipulative, nasty mother-from-hell you ever
came across, or simply pure evil. You make the call.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fat, bald and a sex symbol: One thing is for sure _ Gandolfini
never would have gotten the nod to play the lead if this were on
the networks. But given the role, his menacing presence grandly
offsets his bouts of vulnerability; at times he is a hulking shell
through which you could hear wind whistle. Men want to be him.
Women want to coddle him, or more.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the level of writing gets Shakespearean, as Tony's
business and family interests collide. It's a tragedy in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God,'' Dr. Melfi says. ``People are going to get
murdered, aren't they?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about those distractions,'' Tony Soprano says,
dismissing her concerns as Archie Bunker would Edith's. ``Keep your
eye on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' has all year. After Sunday comes the hard part:
Getting through the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
