u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-TROOPS-BOS &LR;      04-02 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE MOUNTS FOR US TO COMMIT GROUND TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the last thing President Clinton wants to announce to the
American public. But soon he may have no choice: Sending the
Marines into Kosovo may be his only way to salvage Operation Allied
Force.
</P>
<P>
   With Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic unfazed after 10 days of
NATO bombing raids, and the Serbian military and paramilitary
groups continuing to drive out Kosovo's Albanians, more and more
military analysts are calling the administration's Balkan strategy
a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing the war,'' Senator Richard Lugar, Republican of
Indiana and a leading voice on foreign policy, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lugar is one of many policy makers beginning to concur with
strategic planners who have warned for weeks that ground troops
must be part of an effective NATO campaign in Kosovo. Although
Clinton has given no indication that he has changed his mind on
using ground forces, which he maintains he has ``no intention'' of
employing, events unfolding in the Balkans may force his hand.
</P>
<P>
   The torrent of refugees, reports of the unabated Serb
terrorizing of ethnic Albanians, the capture of three US servicemen
on the Macedonian border, and the rapid depletion of the US cruise
missile inventory _ all make the NATO air operation look like an
expensive, noisy show with little effect on Serb actions.
</P>
<P>
   But how to launch a ground war without organizing a Desert
Storm-type operation, without putting 200,000 NATO troops into
position to invade?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I keep hearing out of the Pentagon,'' said Richard
Shultz, a specialist on military affairs at Tufts University's
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy. ``But I don't take it
seriously. That's the Pentagon putting out a number so high that
anyone in his right mind would say it's not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   A much smaller force, Shultz says, could do the job. He believes
that 20,000 to 40,000 NATO soldiers could do the job. Under cover
of tactical air support _ including A-10 Thunderbolts and AH-64
Apache helicopters, both of which could neutralize Yugoslav Army
tanks _ a NATO force of this size could easily outmatch the 20,000
Yugoslav troops in Kosovo, and the 20,000 just inside Serbia
proper, he says.
</P>
<P>
   As with virtually all NATO missions, US troops would constitute
the bulk of the operation, which most likely would be spearheaded
by a Marine air-ground task force based on Navy vessels in the
Adriatic Sea and quickly bolstered by the 82nd Airborne Division
based at Fort Bragg, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A modest aim would be to establish an enclave inside southern
Kosovo to protect refugees and possibly to mount a counterattack on
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Such a ``safe-haven'' would work on two levels, practical and
political, argues Lawrence Korb, a former assistant secretary of
defense and member of the Council on Foreign Relations in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While he does not think the Clinton administration has ``enough
credibility'' at home or with its allies to muster a massive ground
invasion in Kosovo, Korb calls an enclave strategy ``something that
would keep folks alive and have the merit of looking like we were
doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   That second point _ political face-saving _ may yet become the
biggest reason for Clinton to send in troops. Neither the White
House, the Pentagon, nor NATO can risk losing a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're coming up to NATO's 50th anniversary,'' Shultz said.
``It would be a rather somber celebration if Milosevic has emptied
out Kosovo and decapitated the elites of the province. What are we
going to celebrate? This is the kind of concern that says to me
that we are in a new environment where new options are going to be
considered.''
</P>
<P>
   What worries Pentagon planners and the White House is that there
are even more variables in a ground war than an air war. US
soldiers could become targets for Serb attacks, especially with
Serbs fighting on their home territory. NATO forces could get
caught up in a hit-and-run war between the Serb military and the
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a NATO-patrolled enclave of ethnic Albanians might play
right into Milosevic's hands, allowing him to drive the rest of the
Albanians into refugee camps in southern Kosovo while he makes
northern Kosovo an ``ethnically-clean,'' Serb-only province. Then
he could call the Russian Prime Minister, Yevgeny Primakov, back to
Belgrade and sue for peace.
</P>
<P>
   For those in the administration who continue to oppose the use
of ground troops, it is this last scenario that may become their
strongest ammunition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
