u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-TAXES-BOS &LR;      04-02 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TAXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-NATO PATRIOTISM TURNS INTO TAX QUEST IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As Russians rally around their leaders' protest of the
NATO bombing of Yugoslavia, the cash-strapped government is trying
to take advantage of the newly patriotic mood to get its citizens
to do something they have never done with much gusto: pay their
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you love Russia?'' begins a televised ad, part of a
campaign that has swept the country in advance of Thursday's
deadline for Russians to file their 1998 tax declarations.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will help us but we ourselves,'' declares a billboard
plastered all over Moscow and other cities in an effort to stem
rampant tax evasion that the government says has resulted in $6.9
billion in unpaid back taxes and crippled its efforts to run the
country.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, Georgy Boos, the federal tax minister, told
Russians that their tax rubles would go to support the country's
armed forces, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strong military is especially necessary when those events in
the Balkans are going on,'' Boos (pronounced Boss) said on Ekho
Moskvy radio.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that Moscow's harsh condemnation of the NATO
bombing of the Serbs _ Russia's traditional allies and fellow
Orthodox Christian Slavs _ has finally given Russians a reason to
be proud of their government.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, that surge of good feeling does not extend to the belief
that the Kremlin will do the right thing with tax money. Most
people fear that corrupt officials will steal or squander it. Ask a
Russian if he pays his taxes, and chances are the answer will be,
``Are you crazy?''
</P>
<P>
   Far more expressive of this mood than any billboard is the joke
about the Russian taxpayer who goes to see his psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you say you pay taxes regularly,'' says the shrink. ``Tell
me, when did this begin?''
</P>
<P>
   There has been plenty to back up this cynicism. After last
summer's financial collapse, many Russians saw their savings frozen
in insolvent banks amid rumors that government officials made huge
profits from the crisis and that banks sent huge amounts of dollars
to foreign accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were charges leveled in February by Russia's
prosecutor's office that the Central Bank managed the country's
hard currency reserves in a Channel Islands offshore company from
1993 to 1997. The investigation is a state secret, but some
legislators have produced documents showing that some of the money
was invested in Russian government securities _ indicating that
Central Bank officials were making profits by betting against the
ruble.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is a Russian who is happy that NATO is bombing
Yugoslavia, it is President Boris N. Yeltsin, who was facing
numerous charges of corruption among his family members and inner
circle before the Balkan crisis distracted public attention.
</P>
<P>
   Boos's ad campaign has centered on appeals to the statesman in
every Russian, showing poor pensioners, run-down schools, and
broken down ambulances, things that could be fixed if people paid
their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But the ads miss the point, said Scott Antel, a partner in the
Moscow office of the Arthur Andersen accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rusian people are ashamed about taxes,'' Antel said. ``They
want schools and ambulances and pensions. They're just convinced
the money won't go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no faith in the state. People don't believe that if
they pay the money it will go to the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Boos said he expects 6 million Russians to file declarations, an
increase of over 2 million from last year, and the highest number
since Russia began requiring citizens to file their taxes in 1992.
Boos hailed the increase as ``a sign that the country is acquiring
a tax culture.'' But that number is low in a country of 145
million, even in a system in which most people with one source of
income are not required to file declarations.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates vary on the amount, but economists agree that much of
Russian business is conducted in a shadow economy where receipts
are faked, deals are done in cash or barter, and the profits end up
under someone's mattress.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do the sensible thing and go underground,'' Antel said.
</P>
<P>
   The government says it has tried a number of ways to get people
to pay up. It started a hot line in 1995 so that Russians can drop
a dime on neighbors whom they suspect of making more money than
they declare. The tipster is promised a reward of 10 percent what
the tax cheat owes. There's been one catch, which probably explains
why this tactic is not more popular: The government rarely has
enough money to pay the reward.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has tried to raise tax revenue by writing letters to
schoolchildren to ask them to tell their parents to pay taxes. This
Big Brother approach has been highlighted by more billboards (``Are
you SURE you haven't forgotten anything''), and television ads
featuring a man who is too worried about his taxes to think about
sex.
</P>
<P>
   The government has also gone the heavy-handed route _ having
heavily armed Tax Police come crash through doors, arrest
entrepreneurs, and ransack their documents.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that most of the back taxes are owed by
companies, such as the gas and electricity monopolies, which
themselves are owed billions by their biggest client, the Russian
government.
</P>
<P>
   As for smaller businesses, they often have to pay protection
rackets and have little left over for taxes. But most Russians have
had a lifetime of practice in dealing with their government's
forceful methods. Each year, there is some new trick that lets
taxpayers get away with paying much less than they owe.
</P>
<P>
   This year's scam is an update of the old Soviet joke about how
workers pretend to work and the state pretends to pay them: The
taxpayers pretend to pay and the state pretends to collect the
money.
</P>
<P>
   A loophole in Russian law lets people pay taxes out of millions
of dollars in accounts that were frozen in last August's financial
collapse. All a taxpayer needs to do is show that he had money in a
bank and that he had requested the bank to make a transfer.
According to a ruling by Russia's highest court last October, the
money does not have to arrive in the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Because many Russian banks continue to operate even after they
have stopped paying depositors' their money, the tactic continues.
Businesses trade their debts to other firms who need to pay taxes
in return for cash payments.
</P>
<P>
   Boos last month estimated that $933 million in tax payments have
been made from frozen accounts with money that will never arrive.
His deputy, Sergei Shulgin, put the amount at closer to $5 billion.
That is a sizeable chunk of revenue for the country's $23.5 billion
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a form of thievery, but it is allowed because of the
lack of regulation,'' said Nikolai Gonchar, who sits on the budget
committee of the State Duma, the lower house of the Russian
parliament. ``In the current system, it is possible to steal
without punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Duma recently responded to the tax shortfalls by raising the
tax rate for its richest citizens. Now anyone who earns more than
$13,000 will have to pretend to pay 45 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
