<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3738 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-AZR &LR;      04-02 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIANS UNITE BEHIND MILO SEVIC  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE APRIL 2 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sweeping from village to village, ruthless Serb forces
continue to drive out and murder ethnic Albanians. In the past
week, 130,000 refugees have fled Kosovo in waves of human misery.
In response, the United States is stepping up its airstrikes on
Serbia _ although nine days of round-the-clock bombing and
cruise-missile attacks have, if anything, united the Yugoslav
people behind President Slobodan Milosevic and triggered even more
Serbian atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three American soldiers on reconnaissance patrol are
prisoners of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bruised and battered, they appear in footage run on CNN every 15
minutes. Anger over their treatment and concern for their safety
are further galvanizing American opposition to Milosevic. But the
trio's capture should suspend, once and for all, the ridiculous
belief that America can wage a war without casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the U.S.-led bombing campaign expands, there is a
growing realization that there are real limitations to waging a
high-tech air war against a well-armed, determined foe. At this
point, Serbian resolve and hundreds of years of nursing grudges are
proving more than a match for what amounts to limited American will
and steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to say that we have prevented one act of
brutality at this stage,'' Department of Defense spokesman Kenneth
Bacon admitted. ``This is being done very close-up and personal by
the Yugoslav army and special police forces in small groups of
armed, vicious people going out and shooting people at close range,
frequently burning them, shelling their houses.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how carefully calibrated the airstrikes, America's
B-1B bombers, F-15 jets and A-10 Warthog planes can only do so much
from on high. With bombs and precision-guided missiles failing to
force Milosevic to the conference table, talk is turning to whether
ground troops will be sent into action.
</P>
<P>
   Admonitions to pay heed to the ``lessons of Vietnam'' are flying
fast and furious. Among the lessons cited is the futility of
intervening in the civil war of another nation in another region.
Another lesson: The bombing of a people (which translates to the
limited use of military power) rarely produces victory.
</P>
<P>
   Our short-term objectives are clear: Protect the ethnic
Albanians and achieve a credible cease-fire. But our longer-term
objectives are unclear and our ability to achieve even the
short-term ones remains in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The broadening of bombing targets is aimed at further degrading
the Serbian military and forcing it to the bargaining table. The
number of Serb forces in Kosovo must be dramatically reduced,
either through force or an agreement, to allow the refugees to
return. NATO will need to maintain peacekeeping troops in the area.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and France reportedly are discussing commando assaults
into Kosovo to disrupt the killing and also smuggle out top
political figures. This makes sense and U.S. air power would likely
provide support. However, NATO allies are adamant in their
opposition to using ground troops. U.S. officials also have ruled
out the use of ground forces. The American public needs to face
facts: It will be difficult to attain our objectives without the
use _ somebody's use _ of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   If neither NATO nor the U.S. wants to send ground troops,
neither do they have the political will to wage a long, costly war.
Yet without ground forces, a protracted conflict seems likely. It's
an impossible Catch-22. Milosevic knows this, is counting on it.
Sadly, the world's strongest military alliance looks disturbingly
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the constant bombing will begin taking a toll and
Serbians deprived of many necessities will eventually clamor for a
cease-fire. Perhaps. But it likely will take something more than
added airstrikes to achieve our objectives in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   We're not sure President Clinton should have gotten the U.S. in
this war. But now that we're in it, it's important to U.S.
credibility and to regional stability that we win it. If the
airstrikes aren't enough, the next step may be deploying ground
troops. That's a reality we hope NATO and U.S. leaders will find a
way to avoid. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
