<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CELL-REPAIR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS FIND NEW SOURCE OF TISSUE-GROWTH CELLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving closer to the day when body parts can be regenerated,
scientists say they have succeeded in growing bone, cartilage, and
fat tissue at will, starting with as little as one precursor cell
fished out of an adult volunteer's bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said their achievement could ultimately give
doctors a way to repair the damage caused by a variety of
conditions, from arthritis and athletic injury to cardiac failure
and heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Because it uses cells from adults, the technique also sidesteps
a political controversy touched off last November when scientists
first reported that they had cultivated a different sort of
primordial cell thought to exist only in human embryos.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health subsequently said it will fund
research on these embryonic stem cells because of their vast
medical potential. But in February, 70 members of Congress
denounced federal funding as a violation of a law against fetal
research.
</P>
<P>
   The experiments involve a cell of a different sort, a
mesenchymal stem cell, that persists throughout adulthood, making
up about one of every 100,000 cells in the bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   While embryonic stem cells can give rise to any of the 210 or
more types of cells that make up the human body, mesenchymal stem
cells are the progenitors of only a half-dozen cell types. But that
crucial repertory includes the structural elements of the body:
bone, cartilage, muscle, tendon, fat, and connective tissue called
stroma found in many organs.
</P>
<P>
   Normally the body draws on its reservoir of mesenchymal stem
cells to repair injuries, but ``they're not always available in the
right amount at the right time,'' said Daniel Marshak, a coauthor
of the new report, which appears in this week's issue of Science.
</P>
<P>
   Marshak and his colleagues at Osiris Therapeutics, a small
Baltimore biotech company, have shown that they can induce the
growth of bone, cartilage, and fat cells by putting the mesenchymal
stem cells in different mixtures of growth factors and nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Muscle cells have proved more difficult to cultivate. ``We
haven't arrived at the right conditions yet, but we're working on
it, and we're pleased with the success we're having,'' said Mark
Pittenger, another Osiris scientist.
</P>
<P>
   The team has a grant from the National Institute of Standards
and Technology to inject stem cell-derived muscle cells into the
hearts of animals with experimentally induced heart attacks to see
if the damage can be repaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be complementary to others' efforts to promote new
blood vessel growth in the heart,'' Marshak said. ``Even if you
bring in new vessels, you'd still like to have new cardiac muscle
cells to provide the pumping force the heart needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Gearhart, a Johns Hopkins University researcher who was
one of two scientists to report the growth of embryonic stem cells
last fall, called the new work ``very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we get the go-ahead for federal funding in embryonic
stem cell work, these different approaches will have different
advantages and disadvantages,'' Gearhart said. ``Clearly,
mesenchymal stem cells are a quite viable alternative to embryonic
stem cells for certain tissues.''
</P>
<P>
   Animal experiments have already produced encouraging results in
regenerating bone and cartilage, according to Marshak, who is also
on the faculty of Johns Hopkins University Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   The Osiris team has used mesenchymal stem cells to repair gaps
in the bones of rats and dogs too large to heal spontaneously, and
to regenerate severed Achilles' tendons in rabbits.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to grow human fat cells would seem to be less
useful, but Marshak noted that plastic surgeons might find it
valuable for cosmetic and reconstructive surgery, if researchers
can find a way to ensure that there is only as much fat-cell growth
as desired. Another application might be to test drugs to inhibit
fat-cell growth.
</P>
<P>
   Although it takes special chemical recipes to induce mesenchymal
stem cells to form desired cell types in the test tube, animal
studies have shown that the right tissues develop automatically
when these versatile cells are introduced into the body where they
are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The body makes what's required,'' Marshak said. ``We're just
helping the body carry out a normal process.''
</P>
<P>
   Regeneration of needed tissues within the body is a different
approach than what other scientists are developing under the
heading of ``tissue engineering,'' the growth of skin cells and
other types outside the body. Both might have advantages in
different situations, Marshak said.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to repair cartilage in damaged joints would be an
important boon to many patients with athletic injuries and
arthritis, a disease that gradually destroys the cartilage lining
of joints. Unlike bone, cartilage does not regenerate
spontaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now if you play basketball and injure your knee, the surgeon
will remove the fragments and clean up the wound and give you
physical therapy and you may feel better, but the cartilage doesn't
heal itself,'' Marshak said. ``We're trying to direct the
regeneration of cartilage and bone and the cells in between.''
</P>
<P>
   The group also hopes to inject arthritic joints with mesenchymal
stem cells bearing special genes to halt the underlying
degenerative disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Osiris group has started human trials with breast cancer
patients who have undergone high-dose chemotherapy that has
destroyed their ability to produce blood cells.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
