u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     04-02 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV04-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A DYE STAIN FROM A BERBER CARPET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 04, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Shortly after we installed a new Berber carpet in our
basement family room, a downspout overflowed in a heavy rain and
flooded the basement. We pulled up the carpet so it could dry, but
in the process, we stained the carpet with black dye off some
slippers. What's the best way to get this dye out and do you think
the carpet can be relayed or has it shrunk so much in the drying
process?
</P>
<P>
   RICK AND PAM RUBY, Matthews, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try one of these tricks on the black dye: Rubbing alcohol.
Spray and Wash. Gonzo. A strong solution of baking soda and water.
Ammonia and water. Use these products separately, and do not mix
any with each other. I would not suggest bleach because it could
make the spot lighter than the rug.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think the Berber carpet has shrunk much. After all, the
rug is all wool, I believe, and many rug people suggest that
carpets, especially Orientals, should be washed, not drycleaned,
and one would not recommend this if the rugs shrank. It is worth
putting it back.
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, a professinal cleaner might help. Or, have
the carpet redyed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some large cracks have appeared in my small concrete
back-yard pond. Is there an easy way it can be repaired? It was
painted but I don't know what kind of paint was used. I hate to
think that the whole pond would have to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   DEBBIE JOHNSTON, Mountain Iron, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the cracks are quite wide, 1/8-inch or wider, I suggest
chipping them out wider and deeper, and installing hydraulic
cement, which will expand as it sets and might give you a good
closure. Sometimes you can put a swimming pool paint on the inside
of the pond, but I am not sure it will penetrate the cracks enough
to seal them, particularly if they are large as you describe. You
could do either of the above chores with the paint still on.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a Gunite pool dealer in your area, they could spray
Gunite, a sprayable concrete used for swimming pools, on the entire
surface of the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you could have a swimming pool company make a vinyl
liner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We have a park bench that is outside in all kinds of weather.
We want to renew all the natural wood slats and intend to put a
durbale natural finish on the wood. What is the best natural wood
to use on a park bench, and what is the best all-natural
weather-resistant finish we can use? We used a clear poly on last
time, and it just doesn't stand up.
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD JOST, Ocala, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. Most park benches for yard use are made of mahogany or oak,
both of which are strong and decay-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   You have two choices for a protective covering, and clear poly
is not one of them; varnish will not stand up outdoors, unless you
strip and renew it each year.
</P>
<P>
   One is a clear sealer, which will allow the wood to weather
naturally, and has to be renewed once a year or so. Only once coat
is needed at a time. Or, a semitransparent house stain of the color
of your choice. Only one coat is needed at a time, and one coat
will last three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to keep the wood new looking and unweathered, apply
one coat of CWF (Clear Wood Finish), sold in paint stores. Not ony
will it keep the wood new looking, but it will restore weathered
wood to a new look. It has to be reapplied every few years, or
whenever the wood starts to weather.
</P>
<P>
   But why bother doing this on a regular basis when you can let
the wood weather? Oak and especially mahogany will weather well. My
own bench is mahogany, untreated and left to weather, and it is now
a fine-looking silver color.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, if the bolts and screws are rusting out, replace
them with stainless steel ones. That will be one headache gotten
rid of.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Angela Hess of Lake Wales, Fla. is an intrepid handyperson, and
likes to save a buck.
</P>
<P>
   Wrote Angela, ``This week I reglued a small loose portion of the
refrigerator gasket. it seems to work since newspaper won't pull
through when I close the door. A new gasket is about $185 from
Sears, parts and labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess wasn't through, either. ``I used epoxy to devise a small
triangular-shaped piece about one inch at the base to replace a
piece missing in my valuable ceramic lamp which had been damaged in
storage. With airplane paint (better selection of colors), with
gold spray on areas not masked off, the new piece is absolutely
indistinguishable.''
</P>
<P>
   And thank you, Angela Hess. It only takes a little innovation to
fix something. Fromyour descreiption, it sounds like a Tsatsuma
lamp, a Japanese ceramic much in demand and expensive. The handyman
glued his broken one together, and it looks fine, but he does not
choose to look at it too closely.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the airplane paint used to be called dope in the
days when flying model airplanes were built by boys in the '30s and
'40s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
