<SLUG> BC-EASTER-ROOKIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CLERGY TACKLE FIRST EASTER MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- For Christian clergy, Easter week can loom like the
Super Bowl, Academy Awards, and presidential inauguration rolled
into one.
</P>
<P>
   For ``rookie'' ministers preparing their first Easter sermon,
the celebration brings with it no small amount of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from divinity school, new pastors say the challenge is to
say something compelling and novel about a religious holiday that
has been celebrated for centuries. More than anything, new clergy
say they do not want to disappoint their congregants _ who, after
all, voted to hire them _ on such a crucial day.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Renee Wormack-Keels, who became pastor of United
Baptist Church in Boston's Jamaica Plain neighborhood a little more
than three months ago, has been preparing all week.
</P>
<P>
   She has to write two sermons: one for her 6:30 a.m. sunrise
service at Southern Baptist Church in Roxbury, and another for her
service a few hours later at her own church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually haven't felt that much stress,'' says
Wormack-Keels. ``Maybe I don't have the good sense to feel that.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday, after mulling several ideas, Wormack-Keels had
decided to build her sunrise service sermon around the passage in
the Gospel of Matthew that describes the hours Jesus hung on the
cross, because ``Those six hours were the most critical hours for
all of humanity, and we need to reflect on what that means for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   For her main Easter service, Wormack-Keels will turn her focus
to women, using the New Testament story about how women first
discovered Jesus's empty tomb. ``I haven't completely thought it
out, but something along the lines of women carrying the message
that Christ had been resurrected.''
</P>
<P>
   At the First Congregational Church of Rowley, the Rev. Robert
Hagopian, who became pastor Jan. 1, is crafting his first Easter
sermon around the story in the Gospel of John about Mary
Magdalene's encounter with the resurrected Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question I'll have for the congregation is, `When do they
hear Jesus calling their names, and how do they recognize Jesus in
the people in their lives?' '' said Hagopian, 40. Hagopian was
first a banker, than a video producer and marketer, before deciding
to become a minister.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Week, which culminates with the celebration of Jesus's
resurrection on Easter Sunday, is both the most trying and
triumphant season of the ecclesiastical year for any clergy member.
</P>
<P>
   Trying, because of the logistics and rigors of services on
consecutive days starting with Holy Thursday, extending through
Good Friday, and typically culminating Sunday with a sunrise
service and a main Easter celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a triumphant time because Easter is the most
significant and joyous of Christian holidays, the commemoration of
Jesus overcoming death, the event that is the foundation of
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's thrilling and humbling to be the one ultimately
responsible for the whole thing,'' said the Rev. Ann Burgdorf,
pastor of Concordia Lutheran Church in Worcester since November.
</P>
<P>
   She has spent hours over the past week days hashing out Easter
sermon themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little tired, but excited, too,'' said Burgdorf, 59,
who, like Hagopian, decided to become a minister after trying other
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working through the idea of how on Easter we go from
darkness to light, from Jesus being dead to his being
resurrected,'' Burgdorf said. ``The resurrection means for us a new
relationship with Jesus. And church isn't a place where we come to
remember Jesus, but a place to come into a vibrant relationship
with him because he is working in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clergy members just starting out say Easter is a big test
because it represents taking what they spent years learning in
divinity school classrooms, and carrying it to the pulpit before
congregants who come to Easter service eager for a transcendent
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important week of the year for Christians,''
said Hagopian. ``The pressure is to be able to celebrate what
Easter means, to be able to convey the foundation of our faith in
the most powerful and effective way possible. That is a tall
order.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Manuel Cintron is relishing his first Holy Week and
eagerly awaiting Easter Sunday. Armed with a degree from
Gordon-Conwell Theological Seminary in Hamilton, he took over two
months ago as pastor of Christ the King Church in Bridgeport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I don't want to do is fill people's minds
with theology or big, complex terms, because this is about what
Jesus Christ did,'' said Cintron, 32, who is leading a congregation
where he has been worshiping for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cintron said he will emphasize the hope that Jesus's
resurrection represents for all Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Hope, he added, is an important word in his church, because it
is located in a largely poor neighborhood struggling with drug
abuse, alcoholism, and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people here are living day by day, taking things as they
come, but not looking for or expecting anything better,'' Cintron
said. ``But when we bring Christ into the picture, things can
change and hope becomes real. That hope is made possible through
the resurrection because the same power that caused the
resurrection to happen can also make our resurrection possible. The
story of Jesus didn't end on the cross. The story began on Easter.
We are part of that story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
