<HEADLINE>
RAPPER NAS IS LIKE . . . LYRICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the world of rap, it doesn't get any better than Nas. Some
call him a street prophet. He calls himself a thug poet. All that
hype doesn't get close to explaining the mastery of 25-year-old
Nasir Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Purely lyrical, he packs a lot of imagery into a few lines
without resorting to gimmicks. On his third solo album, ``I Am. .
.,'' out Tuesday, Nas proves his critics wrong _ he did not reach
his peak with his last album, the multiplatinum ``It Was Written.''
If anything, ``I Am . . .'' will appeal to underground music fans
and those who listen to so-called urban crossover radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   This album will undoubtedly knock TLC off the top of the
Billboard album chart, a release so widely anticipated that
Columbia Records did not give out advance review copies. A
spokeswoman said the label adopted that approach to prevent
bootleggers from snatching early copies. Instead, the label
released excerpts of several songs, all of them clever, original,
and edgy with rhymes about survival set to hypnotic rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Like many rappers, Nas speaks for a generation of young men who
know no other opportunity than peddling street drugs. The lyrics
are piercing takes on reality. On ``Hardest Thing To Do Is Stay
Alive,'' he raps: ``When you hear shells coming at you, hot ones
from a shotgun, I bet a (brother) runs faster. Lose a shooter, get
away from a blaster. Think about that casket . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Two singles have been released, ``Hate Me Now'' and ``Nas Is
Like . . .'' Both are masterpieces. ``Hate Me Now'' begins with a
haunting crescendo of voices sampled from choral music, and as
drums join in, Nas raps melodically to a keyboard riff. The album
version is different, said publicist Yvette Davis; it does not
contain the choral music intro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nas Is Like . . .,'' produced by DJ Premier, contains a
keyboard hook so catchy that listeners will like it the first time
around, then will get addicted to the sound. Nas takes advantage of
the music's almost heavenly quality to speak highly of his rapping
skills _ shtick that goes back to rap's earliest days. In between a
chorus of ``Nas is Like . . . my poetry's deep . . . half man, half
amazing,'' Nas drops deep lines like: ``Life is what you make it.
Suicide; few try to take it. Belt tied around their necks, in jail
cells naked. Heaven and hell. Rap legend's presence is felt.''
</P>
<P>
   So he's a little cocky. Nas has shown he has every right to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
