</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIJOU PHILLIPS: A JEWEL IN THE ROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bijou Phillips isn't just another angry rock female. She's the
daughter of John Phillips, the main papa of the popular but
troubled '60s group, the Mamas and Papas. Only 18, she is ready to
explode with ``I'd Rather Eat Glass,'' a dynamic, demon-exorcising
album in which she sounds like a mix of Natalie Imbruglia, Tori
Amos, and Chrissie Hynde by way of ``The Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   An awkward tenderness is mixed with naked aggression, as
Phillips works out the deep-seated vulnerability that comes from
having a space-hippie father who often wasn't around because of his
famed drug and alcohol sprees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go to the studio and play guitar and freak out and start
crying,'' Bijou says of the shakier moments in recording her debut
disc, produced by Jerry Harrison of Talking Heads fame.``Someone
from my label would come and I'd say, `I suck, why did you sign
me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, whose album was just pushed back to a mid-April
release, has led a highly unusual life, starting with being born
four weeks premature and delivered on a couch by her father. ``The
ambulance came an hour late and I went into shock,'' says Bijou.
``My mother (Genevieve Wait) said I was born on cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so much anger about parts of my life. I have enough
anger for the world, but I'm in therapy,'' she adds in a recent
phone interview from her Los Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   The anger bubbles up in the music. ``To have seen what I've seen
_ so tired, baby,'' she wails in the song ``So Tired.'' In the
autobiographical ``Little Dipper'' she sings about a ``sweet little
mind corrupted over time'' and ``I could watch you all night
drinking booze till the break of dawn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought myself up,'' says Phillips, who is the half sister
of actress-singer MacKenzie and singer Chynna Phillips. ``My dad
was there at times for me, but at times he wasn't because he was
using alcohol and drugs. Or he'd be in the hospital or, when he'd
be in the house, he'd be sick. Or he'd be on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd decide to go to school or not. Most of the time, I
didn't,'' says Phillips, a high school dropout. ``Other times I'd
go swimming or eat Jell-O or play with my animals. I had horses and
a pig and lots of dogs. The animals were my salvation. And I had a
lot of microwave meals and watched a lot of the Disney Channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has endured crazy times _ including a chaotic teenage
stay in Manhattan when she did some modeling and led a wild life
sneaking into clubs at night. But though she sings on the album
that ``I could be an alcoholic,'' she reports that ``I can't drink
much because I have kidney trouble. It's kind of good, because I
could have been an alcoholic. I can drink a little, but I never
really liked alcohol because I associate it with 1) my mom being
psychotic; 2) my dad having a liver transplant; and 3) I could die
from it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was a late-bloomer who didn't learn to play guitar until age
15 (her dad taught her) but who has been a quick study ever since.
As for musical influences, ``I listened to Rickie Lee Jones, the
Jackson 5, and Van Morrison _ he was cool. And I liked Joni
Mitchell and a lot of Hendrix and my dad's music and the Beatles.
And a lot of Patsy Cline, Billie Holiday, and Ella Fitzgerald.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an eclectic bunch, though this first record (she co-wrote
most of it) is mainly filled with urgent alt-pop, looped
percussion, and driving guitars and vocal harmonies (some from her
half-sister, MacKenzie). As for a tour, Bijou says, ``Maybe in a
month or two, but I really want to get out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More on Geils: ``I think we'll fit in just fine,'' J. Geils
keyboardist Seth Justman says of how the Geils reunion will jibe
with this summer's concert picture. ``There's always a place for
hard-rocking, funky rock 'n' roll. . . . It all goes back to James
Brown, Little Richard, Elvis, and Sly &AMP; the Family Stone. As long
as you're playing hard with sincerity, people will listen.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is going to question the Geils Band's sense of history.
According to singer Peter Wolf, the group's opening acts have
included U2, Billy Joel, and Fleetwood Mac.
</P>
<P>
   The Geils reunion is at the Tweeter Center in Mansfield, Mass.
June 23 and 24.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aerosmith's management shuffle: It was only three years ago that
Aerosmith had a falling out with Boston-based manager Tim Collins _
and now comes the firing of Collins's successor, New York-based
Wendy Laister. She has not commented this week, but a woman at her
office says Laister was ``taken completely by surprise.'' The
band's PR person, Luke Burland of the KSA Agency, then resigned,
partly because she's a friend of Laister and found it
``unbelievable'' that Laister could be fired.
</P>
<P>
   An aide with the band says the group wanted a manager who
``could take them to the next level,'' but after a year in which
Aerosmith performed at the Grammys and the Oscars, had its first
No. 1 single, and sold every ticket in sight, what is the next
level?
</P>
<P>
   ``The next level is down,'' says one industry observer.
</P>
<P>
   A source confirms that Aerosmith is signing with HK Mgt. in Los
Angeles, a goliath that also manages Jimmy Buffett, Mick Jagger,
Steely Dan, Lenny Kravitz, Boston, Stevie Nicks, Fiona Apple, Dan
Fogelberg, and Chicago. HK, named for Howard Kaufman, is big and
well-respected, but Aerosmith is used to a manager who only works
for them (neither Collins nor Laister had other clients). On the
bright side for fans: Look for Aerosmith to play an area date this
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
