<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TOWNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE DESERVE BETTER FROM `THE-OUT-OF-TOWNERS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider ``The Out-of-Towners'' to be confirmation that Steve
Martin and Goldie Hawn never again will be anything more than easy,
safe amusement. One-time progenitors of the comedic edge, they seem
more willing to evoke the slapstick of the 1930s screwball comedies
than the kind of irreverence that produced ``The Man with Two
Brains'' and ``Private Benjamin.''
</P>
<P>
   So this is what happens to an aging jerk and a ``Laugh-In''
girl.
</P>
<P>
   They make middling retreads of mediocre films. Heck, they don't
even achieve the pleasing, if vanilla results of ``Housesitter,''
their 1992 pairing in which Hawn especially excelled at creating
suspense and poignancy in her comic portrayal of a chronic but
needy liar to Martin's befuddled lonely architect.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the 1970 film written by Neil Simon and starring Jack
Lemmon and Sandy Dennis, ``The Out-of-Towners'' is about an Ohio
couple, Henry and Nancy Clark, who have just sent their son (Oliver
Hudson, Hawn's real-life son) off to Europe for a year abroad. They
head to New York for Henry's job interview at a high-profile
advertising firm. They have a daughter living in Manhattan, and
unbeknownst to Nancy, Henry has recently been fired from his job.
</P>
<P>
   (When she finds out, he gamely insists, like a true ad man, ``It
wasn't a lie. It was spin.'')
</P>
<P>
   Without children or work to define them, the couple must
discover each other all over again through a series of madcap
adventures. For starters, their flight is rerouted to Boston, then
after being mugged they find out their daughter has maxed out the
one credit card left to them.
</P>
<P>
   That means they can't check into their luxury hotel, and are
thrown out by the manager (John Cleese, in a hilarious ``Fawlty
Towers''-like supporting performance). They must prowl the streets
of Manhattan, looking for food and a good night's sleep. They
stumble upon a support group for sexually dysfunctional people,
make love in Central Park and tangle with armed robbers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is the requisite arrest and jail scene that,
like a combination jump at an ice skating competition, is a
required element in the normal-people-in-wacky-circumstances movie.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, questions might arise. Such as:
</P>
<P>
   What is New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani doing in yet another
film?
</P>
<P>
   To whom does the soundtrack, a gentle mix of Vaudevillian/Disney
music and easy listening hits, appeal?
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone really laugh at the abrasive New York cabdriver or
the Korean-shopowner-who-can't-speak-English stereotypes anymore?
</P>
<P>
   Why do we only see the daughter in a fleeting, wordless shot at
the end, even though she is constantly referred to, is integral to
the plot and lives in Manhattan? A scene with her would have also
helped resolve a major emotional subplot, which is left dangling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Out-of-Towners'' is competent, to be sure, with some good
lines. Director Sam Weisman keeps a fast pace. It's as slickly
produced (by Robert Evans) a Hollywood romantic comedy as
``Armageddon'' was an action flick _ all the money they want and
need, big-name cast and everything plays in Peoria.
</P>
<P>
   But so what? This kind of formulaic movie seems beneath the
talents of Martin, who has no use for the arrow through the head
anymore (unfortunately), and Hawn, who had her finger on the pulse
of women's issues in social comedies like ``Benjamin,'' ``Swing
Shift'' and ``First Wives Club.''
</P>
<P>
   There should have been a lesson to them in Marc Lawrence's
screenplay adaptation, in which parents with high expectations of
their children suddenly must step back and apply those expectations
to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They owe us one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
