<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPATIENT INVESTORS NOT WAITING ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People forget now, but legendary money manager John Neff had two
rotten years in a row when he ran Vanguard's Windsor Fund. In 1989,
he underperformed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index by 16 percentage
points; in 1990, he fell short of the index by 12 points. Yet
investors continued to put money into the fund on the belief _
later justified _ that Neff eventually would snap out of his slump.
</P>
<P>
   Neff's successor, Charles Freeman, wasn't as lucky. He turned in
some rotten numbers in 1997 and 1998, and investors reacted by
yanking billions of dollars from his fund. Last week, in a bid to
stop the bleeding, Vanguard named two new managers to help Freeman
run Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the story: Investors are not as patient as they
once were.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund buyers are pulling the trigger quicker than ever,
say industry executives. They are bailing out of funds that are not
keeping pace with the market averages and piling into funds that
are. ``People are chasing performance,'' says Thomas O'Neill, chief
investment officer at Fleet Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior flies in the face of all the accepted wisdom about
investing. You know the drill. Investing is a marathon, not a
sprint. The wise investor diversifies his holdings _ big stocks,
little stocks, growth stocks, value stocks _ and then waits for
good things to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is no one is waiting anymore. Consider a few
numbers. In the first two months of 1999, mutual fund investors
poured more than $16 billion into large-cap growth funds, according
to Boston-based Financial Research Corp. They put another $3
billion into science and technology funds.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because those funds did fabulously in 1998, thanks to the
super-charged returns of the Internet stocks and technology giants
like Microsoft and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   In the same two-month period, investors pulled money out of
value funds, small cap funds, international funds, and real estate
funds, all of which had mediocre to poor returns in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The impatient investor's motto seems to be: What have you done
for me lately?
</P>
<P>
   A number of different forces explain the new behavior. For one
thing, the gap between the stock market's winners and losers is
unusually large. Big stocks, as measured by the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500, returned nearly 30 percent last year; small stocks, as
represented by the Russell 2000, lost 2.2 percent for the year.
With that kind of spread, it's no wonder those on the losing team
want to switch sides.
</P>
<P>
   The media, including people like us, heighten the awareness of
the gaps by telling investors about performance on a daily basis.
And with the rise of mutual fund supermarkets run by Fidelity
Investments and Charles Schwab, investors can switch funds and even
fund families with a phone call or a click of the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Greenwald identifies one more culprit: fee-based financial
planners. Says Greenwald, a mutual-fund consultant from
Philadelphia, ``It's hard for these guys to justify that fee if
there is nothing positive happening in your account. They have a
strong motivation to make changes, sometimes just for the sake of
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Could this new quick-on-the-draw style of investing be a good
thing? The people at T. Rowe Price certainly don't think so. In a
special mailing sent to investors this week, the Baltimore mutual
fund company urges its customers to keep the faith in the old way
of doing business. ``Prudent investors believe in keeping their
assets sensibly diversified and avoiding knee-jerk decisions at
points of maximum pain,'' writes David Warren, an international
investing specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Adds his colleague, Preston Athey, a small-cap manager, ``Many
people are enamored of large-cap stocks and the Internet. But to
believe that they are the only places to put your money, and that
they will be the best places to have your money over the next 10
years, flies in the face of a century of experience of how stocks
behave.''
</P>
<P>
   Their advice? Stay diversified. Put some money into small-cap,
international, and value funds, even though those funds are doing
poorly today. Eventually the tide will turn and you will be happy
you had your eggs in more than one basket.
</P>
<P>
   The T. Rowe Price essay has an old-fashioned, almost fuddy-duddy
quality to it. It reminds you of a father handing the car keys to
his teenage son and urging him to drive safely and avoid speeding.
You just know the minute the kid is out of sight he is going to
step on the accelerator and zoom away at 75 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, too, are unlikely to heed the sensible advice _ at
least until their risky behavior sends them crashing into a wall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
