<HEADLINE>
GAY PARTY POLARIZES SAN FRANCISCO WORSHIPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Easter disagreement between the Roman
Catholic Church and an often profane street theater group that
targets the church with biting satire is dividing clergy of other
denominations.
</P>
<P>
   To some ministers, the etiquette of secular society is clear: It
is wrong to deliberately offend any religion on a spiritually
meaningful day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than have a culture war, which is what this is, I would
have preferred that people accommodate the church's concerns,''
said the Rev. Alan Jones, a Methodist minister.
</P>
<P>
   But to other members of San Francisco's clergy, free speech _
even ridicule _ must prevail. And so should a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have thought the Catholic Church would be big enough
to understand,'' said the Rev. Margot Campbell Gross of the
Unitarian Universalist Church. ``This protest is not worthy of
them; I think they make themselves less by protesting in this way.
It's important for different faiths not to take themselves too
seriously. Humor can be a way of generating tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   In the heartfelt quarrel that has roused all manner of secular
and theological debate, the San Francisco Archdiocese contends that
city officials should not have granted a street closing permit to
the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence for a public party on the
holiest of church days, Easter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sisters, however, who have strong ties to the gay community,
have partied on Easter for two decades and refused to budge from
their 20th anniversary bash on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Supervisors declined to rescind the permit the
street party.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate between two of the most influential blocs in San
Francisco _ the Catholic Church and the gay community _ has
generated national headlines and triggered a call for an economic
boycott by a conservative Catholic organization based in New York.
As Holy Week draws to a close, emotional debate continues among
various denominations even as clergy bustle with Easter
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   To some religious leaders, it's a simple matter of dignity and
respect for individual faith traditions. While acknowledging the
Sisters' charitable contributions, some clergy maintain that an
Easter fete by a group that mocks Catholicism is an affront not
only to Roman Catholics but all Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about their holding this on Easter,'' said the
Rev. Canon Frances Tornquist, a board member of the San Francisco
Interfaith Council and the vice dean of Grace Cathedral, the city's
largest Episcopal church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bit torn. My association with the Sisters generally has
been good. I try to look at it from both sides ... But I think it's
not a good thing to have this on Easter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Interfaith Council agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Representing about a dozen major faiths, including Christians,
Muslims and Jews, the council had urged the city supervisors to
honor ``the sanctity of Easter Sunday and help this group find
another day on which to have their celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Semel, executive vice chair of the Interfaith Council, said
the organization respects the rights of free speech and assembly,
but wishes the Sisters had gracefully chosen a different day to
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hardly a downtrodden minority anymore,'' said Semel, a
member of Temple Emanu-El. ``If you look at the political scene in
San Francisco ... the gay and lesbian community has plenty of
clout. One of the evidences of maturity is that you don't have to
win every battle.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city that epitomizes political correctness, some clergy
find galling the ribald presence of the Sisters, who with impunity
mock the Catholic faith _ among other activities, Sunday's party
features a ``hunky Jesus'' contest. For them, such disrespect
diminishes the considerable charitable contributions to gay causes
that the Sisters have made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should be ridiculing other people's faith,'' said
Iftekhar Hai, director of Interfaith Relations of United Muslims of
America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indicative of the polarizing nature of the issue, however, other
clergy members said they were ``embarrassed'' by the stance of the
archdiocese, which triggered the debate on the pages of its
newspaper, Catholic San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rather disappointed by the position the archdiocese has
taken,'' said the Rev. David Norgard, an Episcopal priest and
rector of St. John the Evangelist church in the Mission District.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to present themselves as having a monopoly, a corner
on Easter. They don't own it. The fact is we celebrate Easter, too,
and the Sisters are in no way hindering us ... or Catholics who
want to celebrate Easter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sisters are a valued part of San Francisco, a city of
great diversity, great pluralism in religion. Easter is a day to
celebrate and they are celebrating in their own way. I bet you it
will be their largest (turnout), their best party ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Other clergy who support the Sisters note the troupe's members
feel hostility toward Catholicism because the church teaches that
homosexuality is an ``objective disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, this really is about homophobia, not about
protecting Catholic rights,'' said the Rev. Mark Stanger, associate
pastor at Grace Cathedral. ``We Christians cannot expect the
secular order to bow down to us, to keep our sacred days. I'm
scandalized that other Christians would want the civil order to
enforce our beliefs. This kind of behavior is unworthy of
Christians and I'm embarrassed by it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
