</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOMER'S ODYSSEY BEGAN WITH AN EPIC FIGURE: RUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today we pay homage to the home run.
</P>
<P>
   Like free food, spring flowers, and funny jokes, homers are
good. Everyone loves home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Homers brought baseball back to prime time in 1998, saving the
national pastime from the fury and fallout of the 1994 World
Series-killing strike. Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa's version of ``I
Know What You Did Last Summer'' inspired a new generation of
hardball fans and fortified long-suffering seamheads who'd been
waiting for a sign that the game wasn't dead.
</P>
<P>
   In this spirit of diamond revival, it's important that we
remember the man who invented the home run, George Herman Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   OK, there were long balls and home run hitters before the Babe,
just as there were slam-dunk artists before Julius Erving and rock
singers before Elvis. But Ruth made himself synonymous with the
circuit clout. More than 60 years after he last played, long home
runs are still described as Ruthian shots.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs were not an integral part of baseball in the days
before the Babe. Outfield fences were designed to keep
gate-crashers out. There wasn't much expectation that balls would
be hit over the walls. Fans were just as likely to see an
inside-the-park homer.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth changed everything. He colorized the gray game and made it
America's favorite form of spectator recreation. He walked into a
game of pitching, speed, and defense, and took it over with his
oversized appetites and tape-measure homers. And just as McGwire
and Sosa brought baseball back from labor strife, Ruth's exploits
saved the game from the dark hours of the game's greatest scandal _
the fixing of the 1919 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   So many years later, it is almost impossible to comprehend
Ruth's impact on the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics help. It's dazzling to retrace the Babe's emergence
as baseball's ultimate home run king. Hank Aaron, Roger Maris, and
McGwire all eventually topped the Bambino's records, but their
margins were puny compared with the dominance Ruth held over the
sport at the peak of his powers. Think of Michael Jordan walking
into a Dr. Naismith peach-basket game in Springfield 100 years ago
and you have a perspective on Ruth's impact on baseball in the
1920s.
</P>
<P>
   As a pitcher/outfielder in his final season with the Red Sox in
1919, Ruth hit 29 home runs, shattering the American League record
of 16 (set by Ralph ``Socks'' Seybold in 1902), and the ``modern''
major league record of 24 (Gavvy Cravath, 1915 Phillies).
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he hit an astonishing 54 homers in his first year
with the Yankees (the big league runner-up hit 19). It was the
greatest single season of hitting in big league history. Try this:
Ruth had a .376 average with 54 homers, 137 RBIs, 158 runs, 14
stolen bases, 36 doubles, 9 triples and a (still) record slugging
percentage of .847. His homer total was 10 more than any other
American League team.
</P>
<P>
   In Ruth's second season with the Yankees, he hit his 139th
homer, passing Roger Connor to become the major league career home
run leader. The Bambino would hold this title until 1974 when Aaron
crashed homer No. 715.
</P>
<P>
   The Babe owned the home run. At the end of the 1928 season,
there had been 10 big league seasons of 40 or more homers and Ruth
had seven of them. He led the American League in homers 12 times
between 1918 and 1932. When he hit his 700th home run in 1934,
there were only two other players who'd hit as many as 300. He
retired with more than twice as many homers as any player and Aaron
didn't catch him for nearly 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with the Babe, it was never solely about statistics.
He was the largest figure in the country, bigger than any
politician or entertainer. Who else could stroll over to President
Harding during a game against the Senators and say, ``Hot as hell,
ain't it Prez?''
</P>
<P>
   He promised a boy in a hospital that he would hit a homer. Then
he delivered. He pointed to center field in the middle of an at-bat
in the World Series. Then he delivered. He hit the longest home
runs in every park. He delighted the kids wherever he went.
</P>
<P>
   His name became a synonym for ``best'' or ``biggest.'' Time
magazine reported that Willie Sutton was ``the Babe Ruth of bank
robbers.'' Japanese soldiers cursed the name ``Babe Ruth'' when
confronting American dogfaces on Guadalcanal in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   This is Jimmy Cannon in the New York Post on Ruth: ``The myth
celebrates American innocence in a good lost time, and Babe Ruth
was more than a man. He was a parade all by himself, a burst of
dazzle and jingle, Santa Claus drinking his whiskey straight and
groaning with a bellyache caused by gluttony.''
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, hundreds of thousands of kids play Babe Ruth
League Baseball. Muhammad Ali became the Babe Ruth of the '60s and
'70s, and Jordan was the Ruth of the '90s. At the end of this year,
ESPN will finish its countdown of the top 100 American athletes of
the century, and Ruth had better be No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, late House Speaker Tip O'Neill recalled a Cambridge
event from his youth attended by the Babe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never got into the hall,'' said the Speaker. ``The crowd
was so huge. That was an era in which there were idols, but nobody,
nobody in the history of this country was the idol that Babe Ruth
was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bambino. Still the one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
