<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEAKER SIDE OF THE BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A &UR;  &LR; bull market in a china closet. You could not tell that by
reading only the first words of the stories about the Dow closing
above 10,000 for the first time on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal said 10,000 symbolized ``the astonishing
success and giddy exuberance of the US economy this decade.'' The
New York Times said, ``The Dow achieved a perfect 10 Thursday.
Thousand, that is,'' reflecting ``the unparalleled strength of the
economy and the dominance of the world economic stage by American
corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post said the Dow underscored ``the optimism of
new investors dazzled by the high-tech boom and the nation's robust
economy.'' The Boston Globe said it highlighted ``a remarkable
period of economic growth in the nation.'' The Los Angeles Times
said it was a ``major milestone in a 17-year bull market fueled by
_ and now perhaps fueling _ the best US economy in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to go deeper into the stories to see that someone's
fuel is someone else's fumes, or that some dishes are falling. The
Post cited a ``performance gap,'' in which the 30 blue-chip stocks
of giant corporations in the Dow Jones Industrial Average had risen
in the past year by 8.99 percent, while the Russell 2000 index of
small stocks had fallen 5.26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underpinnings of the market are slowly getting whittled
away,'' said Mark Arbeter, chief technical analyst at Standard &AMP;
Poor's. Thomas O'Neill, chief investment officer of Fleet Financial
Group, said that unless the market shows a more uniform growth,
``it won't be a healthy long-term condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said about the human condition. This week,
United for a Fair Economy, a Boston-based organization that tracks
income and wealth trends in the United States, released a report
that shows that the boom has enriched only the top 5 percent of
households in America. An astounding 95 percent of households have
seen a decline in net worth.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``Shifting Fortunes: The Perils of the Growing
American Wealth Gap,'' found that between 1983 and 1995, the
richest 1 percent of households saw a rise in net worth of 17.4
percent, adjusted for inflation. The top 2 to 5 percent of
households saw a rise in net worth of half a percent.
</P>
<P>
   The households that would rank in the top 91th to 95th
percentiles of wealth saw a drop of 2.3 percent in net worth. The
households that would rank in the top 81st to 90th percentiles saw
a drop of 5.3 percent. The households that would place in the 61st
to 80th percentiles fell by 6.5 pcercent.
</P>
<P>
   Then the dishes really break into pieces. The households that
would rank in the 41st through 60th percentiles fell 11.5 percent
in net worth. The bottom 40 percent of American households saw a
collapse of 79.6 percent in net worth.
</P>
<P>
   The richest 1 percent of US households now hoard 40.1 percent of
America's wealth. That is double the 19.9 percent of wealth the top
1 percent held in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are many. Weekly wages for the average American are
12 percent below their inflation-adjusted levels of 1973.
Middle-income families are putting in the equivalent of eight weeks
more time on the job than in 1979. But over the last decade the
real pay for extra hours works out to $2.20 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Without a strong return on their labor, Americans are saving
less to keep up with costs that have risen way beyond inflation for
housing and college. Americans saved only 0.5 percent of their
income last year, compared to 8.6 percent in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are falling deeper into debt to purchase cars and
other big-ticket items. Debt as a percentage of personal income has
risen from 29.9 percent in 1949 to an estimated 84.8 percent in
1997. Credit-card debt in the US has more than doubled in the last
decade, from $243 billion to $560 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The poor bear the heaviest burden of credit cards. In 1995, 27
percent of families with incomes under $10,000 had bills that rose
above 40 percent of their incomes. Less than 5 percent of families
making more than $50,000 had such a burden.
</P>
<P>
   The wealth gap is so huge that Lester Thurow, professor at the
MIT Sloan School of Management and who wrote a foreword for the
report, said, ``the great American middle class has become a
nonparticipant in the American dream.'' It is so huge that the
report concludes that serious measures have to be taken to address
it, such as wealth taxation, capping corparate tax deductions and
stronger taxes for estates and capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   It is so huge that this bull needs a tranquilizer to save the
china closet. Ralph Acampora, chief strategist at Prudential
Securities, bragged that 10,000 is ``no longer a ceiling. It's a
floor. As time goes by, we'll be looking down at it.''
</P>
<P>
   And looking down at the debt-ridden masses who are searching on
the floor to pick up the pieces of their broken plates. If
investors could put aside their giddy exuberance for a moment, it
might be worth considering that the last time the top 1 percent of
Americans had this much wealth was in 1929, just before the crash
of Wall Street and the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
