u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOON-BOS &LR;      04-02 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG ACTING CARRIES `WALK ON THE MOON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A WALK ON THE MOON 
Directed by: Tony Goldwyn 
Screenplay by: Pamela Gray 
Starring: Diane Lane, Viggo Mortensen, Liev Schreiber, Anna Paquin,
Tovuh Feldshuh, Bobby Boriello, Joseph Perrino 
Running time: 106 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality, language and some drug use) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the summer of 1969? Screenwriter Pamela Gray does, and
so does Tony Goldwyn, making a convincing, handsomely crafted
directorial debut in ``A Walk on the Moon.'' It was, of course, not
only the summer of the moon walk but of Woodstock and flower power
and, in this film, the converging of those events to generate a
moonshine-filled, Catskills- bungalow-colony Madame Bovary. As the
film opens, Diane Lane's Brooklyn Jewish housewife and mother,
Pearl, who married young, is growing just old enough to be haunted
by the feeling that life is passing her by. There's a lively bustle
as she and her family jam their car full of stuff and set out for
the annual summer getaway. But director Goldwyn frankly tips his
hand when he has Lane look searchingly over her shoulder at a pair
of hippies they pass on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after she, her two kids and her mother-in-law are
ensconced in their modest summer quarters (Pearl's TV repairman
hubby, played by Liev Schreiber, commutes weekends). The little
frowns of discontent soften when an itinerant peddler known as
``the blouse man'' pulls up with his busload of merchandise and
begins shmoozing the women about how the colors in this or that
blouse match the colors in their eyes. It doesn't take Pearl long
to move from a new tie-dyed purple pullover to the Catskills
version of Trouble Right Here in River City _ skinny-dipping under
a waterfall with Viggo Mortensen's restless blouse vendor. It isn't
long before the whole nosy place knows what's going on and before
Pearl's mother-in-law begins nodding balefully.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the picture is the fact that Pearl's teenage
daughter (Anna Paquin) is discovering boys, dating, and sex, and
Pearl has lost the moral high ground when it comes to laying down
the law. But then one of the likable things about Goldwyn's
direction is that he lets the actors play against the action and
resist cliche. Thus, Lane's dissatisfied Pearl, in addition to
creating an impression of being unassumingly sexy, convinces us
she's a woman trying to retroactively sow a few wild oats, spurred
on by the example of the unfettered hippies en route to Woodstock.
Mortensen's blouse man, despite an anti-Vietnam bitterness (his
brother is missing in action there), projects a persuasive softness
that lifts him out of serpent-in-Eden stereotyping. Even Feldshuh's
mother-in-law skirts disapproving gorgon cliches to embody an
understanding family-oriented woman who avoids snap judgments and
only wants things to turn out OK.
</P>
<P>
   In short, there's enough nicely detailed acting _ this includes
Paquin's assertive and vulnerable emerging daughter, one of the few
believably faceted teens in recent Hollywood movies, and
Schreiber's deceived husband, convincing in his pain _ to carry the
film beyond what could have been a black hole of stiltedness. The
film is a little easy on consequences for everybody, but then it
just as believably empathizes with its characters. There also are
times when it seems more a manufactured object than a spontaneous
eruption of conflicting emotions. But the acting _ and the acting
out _ carry it. Clearly, Goldwyn has a future in directing if he
wants one. In the meantime, ``A Walk on the Moon'' is emotionally
complex enough to provide a satisfying helping of time travel that
gives us more to savor than the usual screenful of vintage cars.
</P>
</TEXT>
