<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TARZAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IN-DEPTH LOOK AT GODFATHER OF POP CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TARZAN FOREVER 
The Life of Edgar Rice Burroughs, Creator of Tarzan 
By John Taliaferro 
Scribner, 400 pp., illustrated, $30 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well past middle age, well past even Tarzan's prime, Edgar Rice
Burroughs was eating dinner in a Honolulu restaurant when he
spotted Ernest Hemingway and his wife, journalist Martha Gellhorn,
at another table. It was 1941 and Hemingway had just finished ``For
Whom the Bell Tolls.'' Burroughs was churning out pulp
``novelettes'' set on Mars and Venus. Burroughs's wife prodded him
to approach Hemingway, but he refused. She suggested the two
writers should get together sometime to compare notes. Burroughs
stayed rooted in his seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``As near as he had been to Hemingway,'' journalist John
Taliaferro writes in ``Tarzan Forever,'' ``he understood that they
were in fact oceans apart. . . . Reviewers would praise (`For Whom
the Bell Tolls') for its skill at balancing `delicacy' and
`brutality,' qualities Burroughs instilled in all of his heroes,
though none of his novels had ever received the serious attention
paid to Hemingway's. If Florence didn't realize the critical gulf
separating the two authors, Burroughs surely did, and his glowering
silence was as good as an admission.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Tarzan Forever,'' Taliaferro examines this respectability
gap as it runs through Burroughs's voluminous writings and diaries.
On one side, he finds a complex and insecure pulp adventure writer
stunned at his own success; on the other, he finds millions of
readers and moviegoers willing to embrace an Edenic ape man as an
American cultural archetype. Taliaferro is on a mission to
rehabilitate Burroughs from his ``undeserved ostracism.'' Indeed,
the book is a good-natured hagiography of a hack.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Burroughs wrote for pulp magazines (named
for their coarse paper) and was paid by the word. Although he
pretended not to mind his lowbrow status, he struggled all his life
to break into ``slicks'' like Collier's and the Saturday Evening
Post. ``I don't think my work is `literature,' I'm not fooling
myself about that,'' he told the Los Angeles Times. He placed
himself in the same class as ``the aerial artist, the tap dancer,
and the clown.''
</P>
<P>
   But Burroughs is nevertheless the rightful owner of a place in
20th-century American letters. His grip on the public imagination
is hard to deny _ by conservative estimates, he sold 30 million
books during his lifetime. He became one of the first writers to
incorporate, and in 1931, weary of middlemen, began publishing his
books under the ERB, Inc. imprint. He licensed Tarzan statuettes
and Tarzan ice cream, and started a national network of Tarzan
clubs for young people. All Burroughs lacked, it would seem, was a
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The character Tarzan was born in 1912, swinging in on a jungle
vine to rescue the career of his own creator. Burroughs was 35,
married with two children, and possessed of a tenuous employment
history. He was most successful as head of the stenographic
department at Sears, Roebuck in Chicago, but inexplicably quit to
sell pencil sharpeners.
</P>
<P>
   After checking ads for his product in several pulp magazines, he
took them home to read. He decided he could write stories ``just as
rotten as theirs.'' His first story, ``A Princess of Mars,'' was
the tale of a soldier who falls into a trance in Arizona and wakes
up on Mars. The All-Story magazine bought it for $400.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs's editor was eager for a sequel, and Burroughs wrote
back that he was working on another ``improbable'' tale: ``The
story I am now on is of the scion of a noble English house _ of the
present time _ who was born in tropical Africa where his parents
died when he was about a year old. The infant was found and adopted
by a huge she-ape, and was brought up among a band of fierce
anthropoids.'' In 1912, The All-Story bought his 504-page
manuscript for $700.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Taliaferro's biography seems overstuffed with details
of Burroughs's many plots, but taken together, they make their
point. Burroughs's writing is not all bad, and some of his
adventures are well paced and tightly structured. Too often,
however, he trots out threadbare literary devices. Most stories
feature scantily clad heroines who somehow remain pure, such as
Jane in the jungle or Dejah Thoris on Mars. Amnesia, trances,
mistaken identity, and improbable rescues are used again and again.
Burroughs's darker side comes through in his stories, as well. His
images of blacks are simple-minded and racist, and he wrote essays
advocating the extermination of ``moral imbeciles'' and the
deportation of Japanese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs and his first wife, Emma, were movie buffs, and he was
determined to break into the fledgling film industry. The courtship
began in 1914, but Tarzan at first was considered too difficult to
film. The first release of ``Tarzan and the Apes'' came in 1918,
under William Parsons and the National Film Corp. (The famous MGM
version, starring Olympic swimmer Johnny Weissmuller and
20-year-old Maureen O'Sullivan, would not come out until 1932.)
Author and main character would never be the same, Taliaferro
writes.
</P>
<P>
   Taliaferro doesn't gloss over Burroughs's flaws and florid
prose, but in the end, he provides an incisive read about a rogue
who became one of the godfathers of pop culture and one of the
first explorers in the American celebrity jungle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
