<P>
   SWEDEN-WALLENBERG (Stockholm) _ For as long as anyone can
remember, Sweden's business has been synonymous with the Wallenberg
family. Now, though, the family _ like Sweden itself _ must deal
with the competitive forces that have been unleashed by
globalization and by Sweden's late entry into the European Union,
four years ago. The Wallenbergs must redefine the means by which
they control an empire that stretches from heavy-truck production
to mobile phones and from engineering works in Asia to boardrooms
in the United States. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-INDEPENDENTS (Undated) _ The recovery in oil prices may be
coming too late to save some of the nation's independent oil
companies, which together account for about 40 percent of the oil
produced in the United States. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The airline industry is in a
public-relations tailspin. In just the last few months, the
airlines have come under strong criticism from the White House and
Congress, have been faulted by travel agents and have been raked
over the coals by angry passengers. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POWER (Mexico City) _ President Ernesto Zedillo faces a
tough fight as he moves to privatize Mexico's electric-power
industry. By Rick Wills.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPEND (Shanghai) _ Construction teams are still working
around the clock in Shanghai. But in a telling shift, they are
putting up fewer office and apartment buildings and, instead, are
working on municipal projects like highways, a subway line and a
new airport. Worried about slowing export growth, falling foreign
investment and weakening domestic demand, the Beijing Government is
spending heavily on public construction projects. And while that
spending may be all that is keeping construction workers from
joining China's growing ranks of unemployed, it appears to be
fueling a major portion of the nation's economic growth. By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, U.S. stock markets are closed for the Good Friday holiday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis' ``Abroad at Home.''
</P>
