<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TOWNERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVED `OUT-OF-TOWNERS STILL FLOUNDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE OUT-OF-TOWNERS 
Directed by: Sam Weisman 
Screenplay by: Marc Lawrence (based on Neil Simon's screenplay) 
Starring: Steve Martin, Goldie Hawn, Mark McKinney, John Cleese 
Running time: 96 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some sex and drug-related humor) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody is likely to accuse this ``Out-of-Towners'' remake of
desecrating a classic. The 1970 Neil Simon original about a married
couple chewed up by big bad Manhattan was both grating and tedious.
So this remake by Sam Weisman was in the coveted
nowhere-to-go-but-up mode. It doesn't go that far up, but it's
still an improvement on the original. Back then, Jack Lemmon and
Sandy Dennis played the unlucky couple. This time it's Steve Martin
and Goldie Hawn.
</P>
<P>
   They're operating under something of a handicap in that
Manhattan in 1970 was in much worse shape than the spruced-up and
less threatening Big Apple of the reinvigorated 1990s. But Martin
and Hawn are slightly better at deflecting us from the cold
mechanics of farce that ensue when everything goes wrong. They're
diverted to Boston, separated from their luggage, held up at
gunpoint and relieved of cash and credit cards and ID, rebuffed at
the hotel they're supposed to be staying at. Before long, they're
chased by police and thrown on the far from tender mercies of
Central Park at night. And all this on the eve of the morning he's
being interviewed for the big job he needs in order to stay
solvent.
</P>
<P>
   The original arose from Simon's own love-hate relationship with
New York. The answer to the Ohio couple's escalating troubles lay
in their learning to respond like New Yorkers and fight back.
Martin is a skilled farceur, although not so skilled that his
mechanics aren't at odds with the warmth that Hawn uses to work her
way around the heavy-duty contrivance that settles over the
proceedings like a noose. Still, there is chemistry between them,
even if it's only the chemistry of actors performing in sync rather
than that of characters who assume enough dimension to persuade us
they're interacting on any level.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the couple is supposed to be salvaging their
ennui-laden marriage as well as finding a new job to support it
strains credibility more than it adds to the farcical pressure. The
roadblocks they must hurdle are for the most part pretty flat ones,
except in the case of John Cleese, who calls upon a pocketful of
his ``Fawlty Towers'' moves as a snobby hotel manager who
sadistically power-trips the hapless couple until they find an
embarrassing way to strike back. He and everybody throw themselves
energetically at this unsympathetic material that paradoxically
grows more tepid the harder they hit it. ``The Out-of-Towners'' is
a decent try, competently executed, but it does make you wonder why
Hollywood bothers to remake flops when it hardly has figured out
how to remake hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
