<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3778 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DISCLOSURES03-     04-02 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DISCLOSURES03-1STLEDE-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. SHORTCOMINGS AN OPEN SECRET IN KOSOVO CONFLICT
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects name of Kenneth Bacon in 5th graf.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Among the rules for war-making, one of the most
ancient is never to let the enemy know your weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kosovo conflict, however, U.S. shortcomings are so openly
discussed that one was featured in David Letterman's ``Late Night''
monologue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things could not be getting worse in the Balkans,'' quipped
the comic, drawing from a report that the U.S. Air Force is running
out of cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shortage of bombs? Well, hell, call CBS,'' he chortled in a
poke at his own network.
</P>
<P>
   The joke wins few laughs from military experts, who find it
troubling that the Pentagon has admitted that the U.S. arsenal is
down to its last 100 air-launched cruise missiles, the $1 million
bombs that can be programmed to fly to targets. Spokesman Kenneth
Bacon told reporters this week that the dwindling supply was
``something that we do worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a public concession ``is very unfortunate,'' said Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., in a telephone interview from New Hampshire this
week shortly before he delayed announcing his presidential campaign
because of the Kosovo conflict. ``I can't help thinking it might
serve to encourage (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce A. Johnson, a scholar with the conservative Hudson
Institute, offered a harsher assessment. ``You've told the enemy,
'Hang in there, dude, we've only a few left to lob at you,' `` he
said. ``And it tells every other troublemaker in the world that the
United States has failed to build up its defensive arsenal of
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the U.S. Navy still has thousands of smaller,
sea-launched cruise missiles that could accomplish much the same
purpose as the Air Force's cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   But talk of the shortage is only one part of the public
hand-wringing over limitations that has marked the first week and a
half of NATO action against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has all but ruled out ground forces for the
present, saying that ``it is not my intention'' to deploy them.
NATO officials have debated over whether to deploy low-flying A-10
attack planes. And for days the allies have pondered the dangers to
civilians if the allies bomb the defense ministry in downtown
Belgrade, even as its occupants were reported to be moving
operations to safer sites, possibly including a monastery.
</P>
<P>
   Such public discourse could increase risks to NATO forces, said
former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld. ``I think the goal is to
complexify the problem for the enemy and not simplify it,'' he told
CNN on Thursday. ``And so when you begin to start ruling things
out, like ground troops, or say we're only going to hit these
targets and not those targets, the effect of that, it seems to me,
is to make the problem for the other side much simpler.''
</P>
<P>
   To other critics, the public disclosures are secondary effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger problem is there is no strategy,'' said Frank
Gaffney, who served as assistant defense secretary under President
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney said he was glad the public knows about problems such as
the cruise missile shortage. ``On balance, I think it's better for
the American people to know about this and catalyze them to take
corrective action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the open debate is a stark contrast with the
first wave of air assaults against Iraq in the 1991 Persian Gulf
war, during which the U.S. forces kept a tight lid of secrecy on
much of their operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a different era where information flows freely,''
McCain said. ``Maybe after this conflict is over, we ought to look
at it and see whether it did any harm or not.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
