<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-AARON-BOS &LR;      04-02 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-AARON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AARON'S 755 IS THE NUMBER TO SHOOT FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a few dare dream of surpassing Hank Aaron's career home run
record. The leading candidates are Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   But time is already working against any heir apparent. The
pressures that face modern-day challengers are in some ways even
greater than those Aaron had to deal with. As his 23-year career
wound down and Aaron approached Babe Ruth's mark, he had to battle
racial bigotry and an ungrateful public. Aaron beat Ruth's
unbeatable record of 714 on April 8, 1974, and wound up with 755
home runs but didn't really get proper recognition until about 10
years after he retired in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Next Thursday, there will be a celebration in Atlanta
commemorating the 25th anniversary of Aaron's 715th home run. This
is a good time to ask whether someone can break his record.
</P>
<P>
   The problems for the new generation of sluggers are almost the
opposite of what Aaron faced. Thanks to the revival of 1998 _ led
by McGwire and Sammy Sosa, who both broke Roger Maris's
single-season homer record _ there is now enormous attention and
pressure focused on long-ball hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Sluggers are being signed to massive contracts and being called
The Franchise. With such windfalls, players don't have to play 20
years to amass financial fortunes. So would anyone hang around long
enough to break the mark?
</P>
<P>
   ``They could catch it in a hurry if they continue to hit home
runs the way they did last year _ 50, 60, 70,'' said Aaron. ``It's
a new situation. With me, it was never a matter of money. Even with
endorsements, I never made more than $500,000. Today's players are
going to make so much money that they don't really need to stay
around as long as I did. But I hope they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Among active players, McGwire leads with 457 home runs, and he
has hit 52, 58, and 70 in the last three seasons. He's only
starting his 13th full season, but he's 35 and has a history of
back problems.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron thinks the guy with the best shot is Griffey, who is only
29 and in 10 seasons already has 350 home runs. If he plays in the
right park _ he is due to become a free agent after the 2000 season
_ the record could fall before he is 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a long way off,'' said Griffey, who last year hit
56 homers to become only the third player to reach 50 in
consecutive seasons. ``All I know is that I have to be consistent
the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that I will spend my entire career in Seattle or
how long I will play baseball. A lot of it has to do with how my
family feels and how I feel, should a decision have to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's manager is Lou Piniella, who played against Aaron in
the 1970s. He agrees that his center fielder has the best chance at
the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's going to be done, he's the guy,'' said Piniella. ``The
one thing in his favor is that major league baseball has become
homer-friendly. In the prior era when Aaron, Willie Mays, and Ernie
Banks played, the ball was pumped once in a while, but mostly it
was dead. I don't think you'll see that again because people enjoy
seeing the ball leave the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella thinks McGwire's destiny is somewhere in the 600 club;
all he has to do is stay healthy. Bonds needs to average 32 for
each of the next six years just to reach that level. Griffey could
get to 700 by averaging ``only'' 39 for the next nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that Griffey is capable of playing nine years,'' said
Piniella, ``and he loves to play the game. But then it always
becomes a question of how much a player wants it. Chasing a record
like that is something that could give some added incentive. But
everything has to come together _ the power, the experience, and
the thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   If someone is to break the record, he'll probably need another
player to push him, the way McGwire and Sosa pushed each other last
year. Aaron had competition in the 1950s and 1960s from Hall of
Famers such as Mays (660 career homers), Frank Robinson (586),
Harmon Killebrew (573), and Mickey Mantle (536). Aaron, Ruth, and
Mays are the only players to reach the 600 plateau.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my first five years, I had 165 home runs,'' said
Robinson. ``Hank started two years ahead of me and had only 140
after his first five. But once he started putting up the big
numbers, there was no catching him. The key was after age 30. The
rest of us started tailing off. Hank stayed consistent until the
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always wanted to keep pace with each other. That's just the
way it was. You'd read in the paper where Hank would hit a couple
or Willie had two more. That made you want to hit a couple. It was
friendly competition, not life or death. Remember, for a long time,
Mays was the top contender.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson agreed with Piniella that good health and
self-motivation _ not money _ will be the keys for future
challengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep talking about the salaries escalating, and how they
affect the future,'' said Robinson. ``Well, they're still going up.
It's still up to the individual if he wants to stay around. Players
have to be healthy and continue at a high level of hitting home
runs. That's what it is going to take, and I don't know how many
are willing to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone will surpass Aaron, said San Diego's Tony Gwynn, who
compares the home run chase to his pursuit of a .400 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll happen when the right guy comes along,'' said Gwynn.
``It has to be a guy who loves to play this game like they did in
the old days. He has to want that thrill that goes with just being
able to step out there and do what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor with McGwire, added Gwynn, is how the Cardinals
do as a team. It's easy to forget that it was McGwire who set the
home run record but Sosa who was National League MVP, chiefly
because the Cubs made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his team had been in the hunt last year,'' said Gwynn, ``I
don't think they'd have pitched to McGwire the same way _ around,
careful, or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter with Hank. He was so good because he could
hit the ball all over the place no matter how the team was going.
Today, there are a lot of guys who hit from line to line. But do
they have the power?''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron never hit 50 homers in a season but he had 40 or more
eight times. He batted .300 or better 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be remembered as a guy who could do more than just
hit home runs,'' said Aaron. ``I had an agenda. I always wanted to
do the best I could do, regardless of whether I was playing for a
team on the top or bottom. I thought that was my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I can compare myself to today's hitters. The
best thing to come out of all of this is that not only did McGwire
and Sosa get the recognition they deserved, but what they
accomplished put baseball on the front pages again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
