<HEADER>
A3783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HOMERS-VOICES-BOS     04-02 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOMERS-VOICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADCASTERS' CALLS TURN HOMERS INTO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)`It might be . . .''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   No three words ever expressed better the feeling evoked by the
crack of a bat. Harry Caray, the late Chicago Cubs announcer, must
have said those words a thousand times. Didn't matter. At the
moment bat met ball, they signaled hope, if only for a fraction of
a second sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``It could be . . .''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Home runs can be foiled by winds, foul lines, and miraculous
stabs by leaping outfielders. Even the sweetest of swings is not
immune from the laws of nature and defensive aptitude. But when the
ball stayed on its path, when the outfielder finally surrendered to
the inevitable, Caray captured a complicated act of physics quite
simply. And with a little relish.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``It is! A home run! Holy cow!''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Former Red Sox voice Ned Martin wasn't as flamboyant. As a
matter of fact, he was one of the most literate men ever to work in
a booth. But even he was moved to the spiritual when a significant
shot was hit by a Boston batter, exclaiming, ``Mercy!''
</P>
<P>
   Red Barber, the longtime Dodgers announcer, would summon a mere
mortal: ``Ooooohhhh, doctor.'' One of Barber's most famous calls
occurred during Game 6 of the 1947 World Series. The Yankees were a
game up on Brooklyn but trailed, 8-5, in the bottom of the sixth.
With two on, Joe DiMaggio hit a towering shot, and it looked as
though the score would be tied. But substitute outfielder Al
Gionfriddo sprinted ``back, back, back,'' as Barber called it,
until he caught the ball at the bullpen fence some 415 feet from
home. It was one of the few times that DiMaggio showed any emotion,
kicking the dirt as he neared second base.
</P>
<P>
   About a decade ago, ESPN's Chris Berman heard a replay of
Barber's call on the radio as he drove to work in Bristol, Conn.
Berman got an idea. He thought Barber's words would give a little
life, a little suspense, to his own highlight calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd try it,'' Berman said. ``I wasn't trying to
mimic him or have a catchphrase. I just liked it. It was a famous
call. It was history. So I just did it that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman has been saying, ``back, back, back, back, back . . .''
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part about it is that it describes the game,'' Berman
said. ``I'm not telling anyone that it's a home run yet. It could
be, `Back, back, back . . . caught on the warning track.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Berman doesn't use what has become his trademark on every home
run. ``You gotta be careful,'' Berman said. ``You never want to
outdo the actual act. But there are so many highlight shows and
games on television, everyone seems to want to top the next guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox announcer Joe Buck realized as much when he prepared for the
moment when Mark McGwire would beat Roger Maris's record. His
father, Jack Buck, had already made some of the more memorable
calls in baseball history. For instance, young Buck heard his
father call the first game of the 1988 World Series, when an ailing
Kirk Gibson smashed the game-winner off ace A's reliever Dennis
Eckersley. ``I don't believe what I just saw,'' Jack Buck said as
Gibson rounded the bases pumping his fists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing about home run calls is that it seems the more
memorable ones are the spontaneous ones,'' Joe Buck said.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with McGwire's 62d. Buck could not help
jotting down a few words the night before. ``I thought I knew what
I was going to say,'' Buck said. ``I had a little script, something
like, `McGwire rounds the bases and floats into the history books.'
''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Buck didn't stick with his script. When
McGwire belted that line drive over the fence last September, the
slugger missed touching first as he rounded the bases. ``Down the
left-field line!'' Buck started. ``Is it enough? Gone! There it is!
62! Touch first, Mark, you are the new single-season home run
king.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's Jon Miller called the McGwire homer that tied Maris. He,
too, prepared some words but ended up not using them. ``My style is
to try and capture what's right for the moment,'' Miller said.
``You can't plan that out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
