<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3785 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BO     04-02 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURY-PRONE GLENN SHAPING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He was asked how it came to be that he was
turning over a new leaf and committing to the offseason
conditioning program. And the answer he gave was _ as his answers
usually are _ honest, direct, and critical of himself.
</P>
<P>
   He came upon the decision on his own. The decision was made by
Terry Glenn, and only Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it day to day, but I will say I plan on being around
here for the duration of the workouts,'' Glenn said Thursday.
``Last couple of seasons I've been doing things on my own and I
don't think it got me anywhere. And I'm really looking for a change
right now and I think I just have to get back to the basics like
when I was in high school and in college where I work out
throughout the whole offseason. It'll work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said he's been thinking about committing to the program
for a while. He said it hit him as he was being carried off the
field in St. Louis last December after breaking his ankle, a freak
accident that had nothing to do with conditioning. Still he
wondered if a stronger body would prevent the injuries that have
plagued him, including a nagging hamstring problem. He also has
received encouragement from his friend and agent, Jim Gould, and
Patriots coach Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting around and seeing guys like Ty Law and Lawyer Milloy
and guys going to the Pro Bowl, it hurt me to see that,'' Glenn
said. ``It hurt me more to not be there for my team in the
playoffs. I think they really needed me when we really had a chance
in Jacksonville if I was playing. Seeing those things happen it
just changed my attitude. Right now this is my third day (of
working out). Consistency is the key word. Last year and the year
before that, I worked out a lot but it wasn't consistent and that's
the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody had to convince me. It's a matter of common sense. I
had a great season in high school and college and we always worked
out through the entire offseason. I never had problems like that
before. Those two years when I had those problems, I was on my own.
Now I'm ready to get back here and back to the basics.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did Glenn feel the need to be on his own the past two
offseasons?
</P>
<P>
   ``In college you have a sense of family,'' he said. ``You're
there. It's almost like you're in jail. When you get here, you have
all this money and you're on your own, you get to make your own
decisions and you don't have anyone telling you what to do. For a
guy my age and the things I've been through, I wanted to run and
experience that. It got me nowhere. Put it like this, I've
experienced that and now I'm ready to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said doctors have told him the right ankle fracture is
making solid progress. He has weighed in at 195, and has begun to
work with conditioning coach Johnny Parker in the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I like to be around this time so when I start
working out and get my body fat down, I can kind of trim it off and
be what I want to be,'' said Glenn, whose playing weight is listed
as 185.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said he doesn't know whether the team will recommend he
see a hamstring specialist to help avoid a recurrence of that
injury, as they have with Willie McGinest and his groin problem.
The team has purchased special equipment to help prevent the rash
of injuries that plagued the team last season.
</P>
<P>
   With his history of health problems, Glenn now seems to
understand what it takes to prepare himself. Even though he
contends he was in top shape when he arrived at training camp last
July, he admits, ``You have to tone your body for a while to where
it becomes almost like cement. I kind of was working out, took time
off, and then worked out again and I didn't give my body a chance
to be solid for a long time. By being consistent, it will do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn also says he is motivated by criticism about his
commitment to the game and the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear it all the time,'' he said. ``I can't go anywhere
without someone saying, `Hey, you need to be here,' like it's my
father. It really upsets me, but there's nothing I can do about it.
Hearing that over and over again, you get tired of it. I just want
to quiet it all down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, I think I have something to prove to myself and that's
the main thing that I have with everything. If I want to prove
something to myself and get something done, it'll take care of the
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   After missing nine games last season, Glenn has a simple goal
for '99: play them all.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn knows his importance to the team and the numbers bear it
out. Over his three-year career, the Patriots are 23-11 with Glenn,
7-7 without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't touched any part of my confidence,'' said Glenn. ``I
still think I'm one of the best wide receivers out there. If I can
stay on the field and prove it, I will show myself and to y'all
that I am one of the best ones out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet over the past two seasons, Keyshawn Johnson, Eric Moulds,
and even Marvin Harrison _ all drafted in the first round of the
1996 draft when Glenn was taken seventh overall _ have surpassed
his production. That has changed the perception of Glenn in the
eyes of some.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed from you guys' perspective and their (the
receivers') perspective, but from my perspective, no,'' Glenn said.
``I still feel I'm better and I have something to prove. Once I'm
out there for the long part of the season, I'll prove that.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said he soon will submit a plan to Carroll about how he
thinks he's best utilized in practice and in games. ``I have a plan
I will approach Pete with. If he likes it, fine; if he doesn't,
I'll do what Coach Carroll says.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn also wants to take on a leadership role. He's been a
talented player who has pretty much kept to himself. He's grown up
in the NFL with a locker right next to Ben Coates, who rarely
speaks to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my fourth year. I'm getting older. I've seen a lot and
been through a lot,'' Glenn said. ``And I feel I have a chance to
put my input on this team. Before I was quiet and didn't say too
much and now I know more of what's going on and the people here. We
have a great nucleus of guys that went to the Super Bowl. We have a
key group with talented DBs and Willie McGinest and receivers who
have been here a long time. Drew (Bledsoe) has made a great jump
from my rookie year until now. I'm excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Often kidding and smiling, Glenn was asked how many catches he'd
like to have by the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go with how many games,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
