<SLUG> BC-BBO-EEPHUS-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TED GRABBED AN EEPHUS PITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (The Globe will periodically look back at memorable midsummer
classics, leading up to the July 13 All-Star Game at Fenway Park.)
</P>
<P>
   If he threw it today, when it could be shown endlessly on TV
replays and dissected on the Internet, Rip Sewell's trick pitch
would hardly rank as a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1946, Sewell's ``eephus'' pitch, an exaggerated lob that
made it look like it was shot out of a mortar, was still known only
to a limited number of baseball fans.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Ted Williams _ ``a grim, determined, unshaven
Ted Williams,'' according to Gerry Moore of the Boston Globe _ gave
the eephus lasting fame when he hit one of them into the bullpen in
Fenway Park during the 1946 All-Star Game, won by the American
League, 12-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that was my first look at the eephus or oophus or
whatever you call it,'' Williams said after one of the most
memorable batting shows in All-Star history, one that included a
second homer, two singles, a walk, and five RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the greatest exhibition of hitting I've ever seen,''
said National League manager Charlie Grimm, whose squad had fewer
hits (three) than Williams did, and all three were singles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Williams said it couldn't compare with his game-winning
shot in the 1941 All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who would go on to win the pennant in 1946 before
losing the World Series in seven games to the St. Louis Cardinals,
placed eight players on that All-Star team. One of them was Johnny
Pesky, who said Williams was not in the batter's box when he hit
Sewell's eephus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one Sewell threw was high,'' Pesky recalled. ``The
crowd went `Oooooh.' You know how crowds are. That pitch went up
like 25, 30 feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Williams then moved up in the box, and the next one he hit it
out of the park, but he was out of the batter's box.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a front-page photo in the Globe shows that Williams's
right foot had crossed the white line marking the front of the
batter's box. Technically, Williams could have been called out.
</P>
<P>
   Pesky's recollection of the pitch sequence was a little hazy.
Sewell said he warned Williams in advance that he would throw the
pitch to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game, Ted said to me, `Hey, Rip, you wouldn't throw
that damned crazy pitch in a game like this, would you?' '' Sewell
would say afterward.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Sure,' I said. `I'm gonna throw it to you.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Man' he said. `Don't throw that ball in a game like this.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `I'm gonna throw it to you, Ted,' I said. `So look out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When Sewell threw his first blooper, he disguised it by
releasing it with the same motion as his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He swung from Port Arthur,'' Sewell recalled, ``and just
fouled it off the tip of his bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sewell advised The Kid that another was coming but missed
outside. He then surprised Williams with a fastball strike, then
came back with the eephus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good one, dropping right down the chute for a
strike,'' Sewell said. ``He took a couple of steps on it _ which
was the right way to attack that pitch, incidentally _ and he hit
it right out of there. And I mean he hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball landed in the American League bullpen, where it was
caught on the fly by Red Sox pitcher Mickey Harris, who never got
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the fans stood up and they went crazy,'' Sewell
recalled. ``I walked around the base lines with Ted, talking to
him. `Yeah,' I told him, `the only reason you hit it is because I
told you it was coming.' He was laughing all the way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a standing ovation when I walked off the mound after
that inning. We'd turned a dead turkey of a ballgame into a real
crowd pleaser.''
</P>
<P>
   According to newspaper accounts, neighborhood kids in Williams's
hometown of San Diego rushed to tell Williams's mother that her son
had hit a ``balloon ball'' out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's first home run in the game came off Kirby Higbe of
the Pirates and landed in the center-field bleachers. He also had
singles off Higbe and Ewell Blackwell of the Reds before coming to
the plate with the score 8-0 in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That pitch was really something to see,'' Pesky said. ``He
used it a lot in the other league. Comical is what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Truett Banks ``Rip'' Sewell, who hailed from Decatur, Ala.,
broke into the big leagues with the Tigers in 1932, then pitched
for the Pirates from 1938 until his retirement in 1949. A
6-foot-1-inch, 180-pound righthander, he won 143 games and lost 97.
Sewell, who died 10 years ago, was 39 years old when he faced
Williams, who was a month shy of his 28th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, Sewell would say later, was the only player ever to
hit a home run on an eephus pitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1357EST &QL; 
