u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-02 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN TARGETS THE STRIKE ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball season opens with a new and an old problem.
</P>
<P>
   The new problem is the strike zone and the technological
challenges it presents to network broadcasters. The old one is the
fine line between objectivity and boosterism among announcers.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN baseball producer Tim Scanlon said the recent controversy
over the strike zone prompted the network to investigate ways to
show viewers the differences in calls by umpires. But getting those
shots is difficult largely because of the distortions created by
present camera angles.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead shots show the ball in relation to home plate. Shots
from behind home or those from along the baselines show the ball in
relation to the batter. The problem is how to capture the ball, the
batter, and the plate in their true spatial relationship. Throw in
the different dimensions of ballparks, and producing a strike zone
standard for broadcasters is even more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon said ESPN will have some sort of solution in time for
playoffs. As it is, ESPN and Fox have improved their specialty
cameras, including ``maskcam,'' the tiny one that attaches to a
catcher's mask. ESPN has also tinkered with its graphics that give
bat and pitch speed, not to second-guess umpires' calls but to
illustrate the battle between pitchers and hitters.
</P>
<P>
   The old problem with homers in the booth resurfaced recently
when the New York Mets fired outspoken analyst Tim McCarver and
replaced him with Tom Seaver, who is also joining the team's
front-office staff. The move was considered to be a blow to
objectivity because McCarver, who had called Mets games for 16
seasons, was often critical of team management, coaches, and
players. Some Mets officials suggested that McCarver's criticism
reduced ticket sales. McCarver was subsequently hired by the New
York Yankees, but the issue caused an outpouring of support for
calling it the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McDonough, another candid announcer, has called Red Sox
games for the last 11 years and can't recall a time when ownership
questioned anything he has said on air. ``Without any fear of
contradiction, I can honestly say that I have never thought about
where my paycheck comes from when working a game,'' McDonough said.
``If all an announcer does is praise people, then it really doesn't
mean anything after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox announcer Joe Buck agreed. ``McCarver was true to how he
felt,'' Buck said. ``He didn't let his paycheck dictate what he
told viewers. He was just being honest. And fans can see right
though anything else. If you lie to them when things are going bad,
then they are not going to believe you when things are going
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that pulling for the home team is a bad thing. But there are
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally get turned off when I hear an announcer say `We'
need a hit or `We' have to score a run,'' McDonough said. ``But I
don't think there's any question that the fans know that I am
happier when the Red Sox win.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's 10th season of major league baseball coverage begins
Sunday night when Colorado plays San Diego in Monterrey, Mexico.
ESPN will have a tripleheader Monday starting at 4 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3790 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOPERSTOWN-SHRINE-HN     04-02 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOPERSTOWN-SHRINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITTING IT BIG IN THE MECCA OF BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: With COOPERSTOWN-IF-GO))  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ The point is made right away in the lobby,
just past where you walk through the stadium-style turnstiles. All
that needs to be said is done with a few jerseys, bats, balls and
box scores. Subtle it's not.
</P>
<P>
   These artifacts in the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum
are not of decades gone by, but of the season past. They belonged
to Sosa and McGwire and Maris, the stoic flat-topped ghost, and the
Great American Home Run Chase of 1998. That sound you think you
hear as you walk by are the sighs of relief of a game, industry and
town.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is back. Cooperstown is back. How far did it have to
come? Well, remember spring 1995? The regulars were still on
strike, and a group of has-beens, never-weres and out-and-out
dreamers were in major-league uniforms, a bunch of Garth Brookses
without the musical talent. Fans had grown justifiably cynical, and
even the place where we allow nostalgia to reign unchecked
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   We sometimes forget the mysticism for many that surrounds this
place on Lake Otsego in the village founded by the father of author
James Fenimore Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the village, the Hall, its designation as the
birthplace of baseball _ all of it is built on a fable. If you
believe Cooperstown really was the place baseball was born, ask
yourself this: Why is Alexander Cartwright, who codified the game,
enshrined in the Hall of Fame, but Abner Doubleday, the reputed
inventor, is not? The answer is, it doesn't matter. It never did.
As Milwaukee Journal writer Dan Chabot once noted: ``Lemmings head
for the sea. The swallows come back to Capistrano. The buzzards
somehow find their way to Hinckley, Ohio. The geese follow their
instincts south. And baseball fans go to Cooperstown and the
National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   But the strike of 1994 scarred Cooperstown. Attendance at the
Hall dropped 30 percent over four years. We were so bitter about
everything and everyone surrounding the game that even the most
dreamy-eyed had to admit it was and is a business first. Once
conceded, it took time, but those disgruntled fans are back
(attendance was up 16 percent last year over 1997). Cooperstown has
retained its place as a shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperstown is not a place to be studied, although surely it is,
as much as it is there to be absorbed. Start as you drive past the
lake, into the village and its stunning stream of Victorian homes.
Turn onto Main Street, and you are struck that, baseball aside,
this could be a picture-perfect Anytown USA, if Anytown USA still
had vibrant downtown Main Streets _ and more than 300,000 visitors
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Main Street, Cooperstown, with its endless baseball-related
shops, signs and pilgrims, and the sidewalks where Cobb and
DiMaggio and even the singular Babe once strolled. As a fan you
can't help but feel them, or at least try.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is a game dominated by vital ghosts,'' Richard Gilman
once said. ``It's a fraternity, like no other we have, of the
active and the no longer so, the living and the dead.'' To your
right, you catch a glimpse of The Sandlot Kid, a statue embodying
the myth, and Doubleday Field, the tiny old-style brick stadium
with wooden bleachers that always stood as a testament to
magnificence in simplicity, something the stadium builders of the
major leagues didn't catch onto until the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Then there it is, on the right, the National Baseball Hall of
Fame and Museum. Anticipation crests just before you go in, and see
the uniforms, bats and helmets of Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa. Stay
and soak it in, but not too long. You have just started.
</P>
<P>
   A first visit to the Hall is intimidating; three floors and
150-plus years to grasp, not to mention a library open to the
public (by appointment) which could fill a lifetime's research. It
is all indomitable. Don't try.
</P>
<P>
   Luxuriate in the little things. For example, linger in the art
gallery, whose sole consistent theme is subject, and may be the
only exhibit anywhere to feature works by Andy Warhol, Norman
Rockwell and LeRoy Nieman in the same room.
</P>
<P>
   Take time to decipher the box score of the longest game ever, a
33-inning marathon between Pawtucket and Rochester, a 1981
minor-league classic. Yes, those kids are Cal Ripken Jr. and Wade
Boggs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, save time for the Gallery and the plaques of its 237
inductees. But first for true laughs, ponder the evolution of the
uniform, particularly the 1976 Chicago White Sox concoction of
polyester shorts with a pull-over shirt featuring a collar akin to
an F-15's wingspan. That, kids, was the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Great American Home Run Chase (the name is
quasi-official), new exhibits include a tribute to the 1998 World
Series champion New York Yankees. New plaques will be unveiled late
this year to coincide with the annual induction ceremony that will
take place Sunday, July 25. It will feature one of the most
impressive casts in years: Nolan Ryan, George Brett, Robin Yount,
Orlando Cepeda, former umpire Nestor Chylak, Negro leaguer Smokey
Joe Williams and turn-of-the-century manager Frank Selee.
</P>
<P>
   This is a place of history, American history; therefore, the
triumphs are offset somewhat by the transgressions. Cap Anson may
be a Hall-of-Famer, but he is also the man most responsible for the
game's segregation (yes, there were black major-leaguers before
Jackie Robinson, albeit in the 1800s). From the Negro Leagues to
World War II to westward expansion, baseball mirrored a nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever wants to know the heart and mind of America,'' Jacques
Barzun wrote in 1954, ``had better learn baseball.'' This is where
you learn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
