<HEADLINE>
SPRING RITE FOR SKIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend Jack has not skied down Tuckerman Ravine on Mount
Washington for a few years, but still athletically trim in his
mid-60s, he could if he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   For some, though, the Washington trek is a spring ritual that
still rings as a college pilgrimage. And, it is one of those
experiences worth having once or twice, though few _ I am guessing
here _ repeat it very often. Perhaps once again as a midlife
statement.
</P>
<P>
   When Jack and his buddy from Brown went, a case of beer cost
about $4. They would pack all this beer with their skis and labor
it up the fire trail to ``Howard Johnsons.'' Then they would climb
up into the ravine where they stuck beer bottles in the snow, skied
for a while, and waited for midday.
</P>
<P>
   The spring sun at mile-high altitiude soon did its work, and
Jack and his buddy were able to sell their beer at the confiscatory
price of a buck a bottle. There are times, they knew, when no price
is too high for a cold beer, and the enterprise paid for their
trip, including gas and food.
</P>
<P>
   I have heard of other college kids selling beer at Tuckerman in
spring, but Jack had another move I hadn't heard of before, and a
sure comment on the passing times.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we skied,'' he said, ``we went into the woods and stuck
our skis in the snow against a tree. When we'd come back next time
_ maybe a couple of weeks _ we'd go in and get our skis. They were
always there.''
</P>
<P>
   Just try to leave your new $700 Volants leaning on a tree in the
woods when you leave the slopes at day's end!
</P>
<P>
   The times may change, certainly skis have, but Tuckerman Ravine
this spring is still the ritual for snow-worshippers the world
around. In fact, despite the so-so winter for snow at most of the
ski areas, Washington this spring promises to send forth excellent
conditions, according to Lewis Baldwin, trail information director
for the Appalachian Mountain Club in Pinkham Notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wednesday) was one of the best days in a long time,'' said
Baldwin. ``The sun warmed the snow up just enough so you could ski
from the summit all the way to the parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions vary day to day. Thursday, for instance, the
temperature remained just about 10 degrees cooler than Wednesday,
making the snow harder to ski on. A crust over the surface freezes
footprints and ridges that the skis can't edge through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go up there about five days a year on a good season,'' said
Doug Gary, who skis with his brother, Ray. ``The real heart of the
Washington season begins about mid-April and runs through the end
of the month.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, when some of the largest crowds show up, the sun gets so
intense that big sheets of ice and boulders get loosened in the
melting, and large crevasses open up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be dangerous late in the season,'' said Baldwin, who
works at the Pinkham Notch Lodge, where skiers and hikers can rent
rooms at a daily rate. ``The ice separates from rock in huge
chunks.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a young woman was killed by one such ice chunk as
it careened down the slope.
</P>
<P>
   Gary has climbed the mountain at least one day every spring
since his own Dartmouth days in the early 1960s. ``My father used
to tell stories about skinning up the mountains to ski in the '30s.
As crazy as it sounds, it all seemed kind of purist and romantic to
me. So whenever Ray and I make the climb up, we kind of share a
memory of Pop. Washington puts you in touch with the real early
days of skiing.''
</P>
<P>
   But if skiers these days are soft, looking for high-speed quad
lifts, groomed slopes, and a place to stop and sip hot chocolate at
the summit, who are all those skiers and boarders making the
mile-plus climb with a heavy pack, skis, and ski boots?
</P>
<P>
   ``Last weekend we had about a thousand skiers up there,'' said
Baldwin. ``On a really busy day there might be 3,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The very biggest day, he said, some 5,000 skiers made the
pilgrimage to skiing's holy temple, about the number who ski on
Sugarloaf on a busy day.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious bit of advice for neophytes is go with an
experienced skier, someone who has made the climb before.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person has only skied in a regular ski area, they'll find
this very different,'' said Baldwin. ``It's open and not
controlled. There are rocks everywhere, open crevasses, avalanche
danger . . . a lot of things skiers usually never have to think
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, the skill level begins with intermediates, and
ranges to expert, depending on how high a skier climbs and which
slopes he skis. And, despite the rawness of the surface, the most
daunting element facing Mount Washingtoneers is the changeability
of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what it feels like down below in the spring,'' said
Baldwin, ``it can always turn to midwinter up on the mountain.
People should bring plenty of clothes, food, and water in pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gary: ``You've heard it all before. It's the old Boy Scouts
`Be prepared.' The first time you ever get caught up in the exposed
areas without enough clothes, you never forget those two little
words again. They loom mighty large on Mount Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, said Baldwin, the avalanche danger is low on the
mountain, but climbers should check with either the Forest Service
or AMC both for avalanche danger and local weather.
</P>
<P>
   For information call (603) 466-2721, ext. 116.
</P>
</TEXT>
