<HEADLINE>
COOPERSTOWN: IF YOU GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ The quaint town is in fact a giant theme
park, from its diners with baseball wallpaper you would have killed
for as a kid to the shops that offer everything related to the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is not Disneyfied. Cooperstown can be enjoyed for what
it is, a comfortable upstate New York village built for strolling
its sidewalks, without even mentioning the B-word.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, here is a novel notion: You can go to Cooperstown, not
like baseball and actually find something else to do. In fact, it's
not even all that hard.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a stop at the Hall is recommended, 888-HALL-OF-FAME,
or www.baseballhalloffame.org. But if not, start with the Farmer's
Museum, 607-547-1450, one mile from the center of town. A working
replica of a 19th-century farmstead, the museum features skilled
artisans and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   The Fenimore House Museum 607-547-1400, a 1930s Georgian mansion
with terraced gardens overlooking Otsego Lake, features annually
rotated American art.
</P>
<P>
   Glimmerglass Opera, 607-547-2255, in season July and August,
offers world-class music.
</P>
<P>
   For another European taste, try the Brewery Ommegang,
800-656-1212, where Belgian beer is brewed.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperstown is the home of baseball, but a half-hour away is a
rival: the National Soccer Hall of Fame, 607-432-3351. But no one
claims soccer was born in Oneonta.
</P>
<P>
   For more information contact the Cooperstown Chamber of
Commerce, 607-547-9983, or visit its Web site at
www.cooperstownchamber.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
