<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABUSE SYNDROME DEFENSE ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They went to one bar, and another, followed by another. One
drink became two, became three. And as so often happened in
Kathleen Barrett's nine-year marriage, the conversation with her
husband, the entire night, quickly descended into the throes of
another bitter fight.
</P>
<P>
   Bitter enough, in fact, that sometime around 1 a.m. Jan. 23, her
husband stormed out of the Kihei Restaurant in Walpole, Mass.,
saying that he would walk to the couple's Foxborough home however
many miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen became nervous, even scared. She got into their blue
Toyota sedan and launched her search for him along the winding,
darkened roads of these southwestern suburbs. In the town of
Norfolk, a police officer saw her swerve over the middle line of
Union Street, pulled her over, and arrested her for drunk driving.
</P>
<P>
   That seemingly routine arrest on the backroads of a leafy town
now serves as the inauspicious start of a potentially landmark
legal case that is already attracting national attention. For the
first time in anyone's memory, a defendant to a lesser crime _ in
this case, drunk driving _ has injected a variation of the
controversial battered women's syndrome, taking her plea for help
to a jury of her peers.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's decision? First, the contrasting cases.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, a 35-year-old floral designer, argued that she was
never drunk on the roads that night. Rather, she harbored a
horrible secret about her relationship with her husband _ a secret
common to too many women in too many households where no one would
ever suspect anything was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Barrett's lawyer, Victor Sloan, told a six-person jury
last month that his client was a longtime victim of domestic abuse.
As Kathleen Barrett drove in her search, she feared that her
husband would arrive home to their mint-colored house after a long,
cold walk and beat her anew. As she was driving, she wasn't drunk,
but frightened, unable to properly operate the car or pass a field
sobriety test because of fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for impairment wasn't the alchohol,'' said Sloan.
``It was something else that affected her mind. It just so happened
she was a battered woman for nine years of marriage. That affected
the way she drove, the way she did the tests. She wasn't
concentrating. She was just worried about getting out of there soon
and finding him.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument was, in many ways, a novel and brilliant twist on
the so-called battered women's syndrome, which allows female
defendants to pursue a strategy of self-defense, including evidence
of prior beatings, in cases in which they have killed their abusive
husbands or partners. In 1994, the state Supreme Judicial Court
specifically gave credence to the strategy, ruling such prior
evidence of abuse is admissible.
</P>
<P>
   Battered women's advocates agree wholeheartedly. ``The issue of
domestic violence colored and affected something she did,'' said
Sylvia Guthrie, director of development for Jane Doe Inc., a
coalition of advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan was able to support Kathleen Barrett's case of abuse by
pointing to a prior restraining order. When the case went to trial
on March 18, her husband, Daniel, also had two counts of assault
pending against him from an incident on Feb. 21. The alleged
victims: his wife, Kathleen, and their son. Daniel Barrett did not
return a telephone call Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, stuck in the awkward position of prosecuting the
wife for drunk driving and her husband for assault, pursued the
case for a variety of reasons. First, Kathleen Barrett had a
previous drunk driving conviction and risked becoming a recidivist
menace. Second, she refused to take a breath test. Third, the
police at the scene believed she was drunk, even if their method of
testing was ridiculed by Sloan in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts, as we saw them, included someone who failed several
sobriety tests,'' said Norfolk District Attorney William Keating,
who earned a strong reputation in fighting domestic abuse as a
state senator. ``We thought there was enough evidence there. There
was a crime to be pursued, and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   They had a one-day trial in the old district court here before
the highly respected Judge Daniel Winslow. The implicit question:
Have we gone too far as a society of victims where actions no
longer have consequences because it's always someone else's fault,
or are we finally, rightfully opening our eyes to the complex
realities of modern life?
</P>
<P>
   The jury's verdict: not guilty. Kathleen Barrett has filed for
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
