<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRICE OF FECKLESS LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Endgame.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the war in Kosovo is over. The Serbs have won. By
this time next week, most if not all of northern Kosovo will have
been ``ethnically cleansed.'' Shortly thereafter, through
diplomatic back channels, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
will initiate a ``peace conference.'' And President Clinton will
take whatever he can get and get out.
</P>
<P>
   NATO aerial assaults will have greater success as the weather
improves. But the bombing lacked intensity at its commencement and
has never carried with it the credible threat of ground assault.
Absent that threat, mobile Serbian forces have been able to conduct
their slaughter at will.
</P>
<P>
   At the peace conference, Milosevic will be happy to spit back
territory in southern Kosovo that he neither cares about nor needs.
He'll call it a concession and perhaps throw in the kidnapped US
infantrymen as a gesture of ``good will.'' Clinton will take that,
too. He cut and ran in Somalia. He'll cut and run in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of any other outcome is increasingly remote.
Even if the president goes forward with the deployment of ground
troops, the Pentagon would insist (and properly so) that he do so
in massive numbers. It would take months to put together an
operation involving 200,000 or 300,000 US troops.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Serbian troops would be entrenched in Kosovo,
would have mined every inch of border and would control the high
ground at every strategic location. The cost in US lives to recover
such heavily fortified territory would rise accordingly. President
Clinton is unlikely, to say the least, to stake his sacred approval
rating on such a protracted military commitment. His motto has
always been: ``Better to spin than stand.''
</P>
<P>
   And everybody knows it. This week brought the spectacle of some
of the president's top military and national security advisers
bickering over who is responsible for the debacle. The director of
the Central Intelligence Agency, ranking officers at the Pentagon,
high-ranking officials at the State Department, and top personnel
at the National Security Council all engaged in the finger-pointing
and blame assessment.
</P>
<P>
   According to news accounts, the president fully expected the
bombing campaign to drive Milosevic back to the bargaining table.
When it instead only intensified the genocide, Clinton was left to
complain of bad weather and bad luck. There was no Plan B. There
was only Plan A and Plan A squared.
</P>
<P>
   There will never be a Plan B. In an interview with CBS News, the
president insisted that despite the bad weather and the leisurely
pace of the sorties, the bombing campaign would eventually turn the
tide. ``I have embraced a strategy here that I believe has a
reasonably good chance of succeeding. Maybe even a better chance
than that,'' he said, ``knowing that we have more and more steel,
and will, and determination, and unity, from all of our NATO
allies.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's spin seemed almost delusional, in light of what
has been published in his local newspaper. The Supreme Commander of
NATO forces, US General Wesley Clark, said publicly this week that
the aerial bombardment campaign by itself could not turn the tide.
Meanwhile, NATO's supposed steel and will were such that it took
eight hours of intense negotiations to approve a stepped-up bombing
campaign, something that should have been approved from the start.
During those negotiations, according to published reports, it was
clear to all involved that NATO would never reach agreement on the
deployment of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton chose to commit the prestige of the United
States and some of its best men and women to help alleviate almost
unimaginable suffering in the Balkans. It was not in the national
security interest of the United States to do so, but he did it
anyway because he believed that it might forestall a chain reaction
of events that could pose a direct threat to peace in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable men and women can disagree about his decision, but it
was not irrational. Having made it, however, Clinton failed to meet
its requirements. He now imagines that it will all work out in the
end. His sycophants, fearful of his wrath, concur.
</P>
<P>
   And so the disaster unfolds. Milosevic has already accomplished
most of what he set out to do. He now begins his exit strategy,
which is to get the US out so that he might regroup and reconfigure
his forces for the next campaign. Clinton has no exit strategy. He
must take what he is given,
</P>
<P>
   which, if Milosevic is smart, will be just enough for Clinton to
spin as stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   The watching world will learn a new lesson, which is that the
iron fist of the United States doesn't pack much punch. Homicidal
gangsters have hamstrung the most powerful military force in human
history. This is Clinton's national security legacy. This is his
bridge to the 21st century. This is the cost of feckless
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
