<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3802 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICAID-CUTOFF-1STLD     04-02 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-CUTOFF-1STLD-WRITETHRU-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER WELFARE RECIPIENTS LOSING HEALTH INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 4)   (EDs: FIXES the word health in 9th graf and CORRECTS spelling of
Yacknin's name in last graf.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a painful, crippling disease, Eva Amey of
Elmira, N.Y. got herself off welfare more than a year ago and has
become a teacher's aide working with handicapped high school
students.
</P>
<P>
   Amey, 32, earns $5,756 a year and lives with her three children
and second husband, a local highway department worker, in a
two-room apartment. Her medical bills often run $500 and sometimes
$1,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The bills weren't a problem as long as she remained on Medicaid,
the joint state-federal that serves 36 million low-income people.
Federal law permitted Medicaid recipients leaving welfare for work
to keep the benefit for a year.
</P>
<P>
   But a paperwork snafu ended her Medicaid coverage last October.
By the time Amey got a lawyer and appealed, she found out her
year's worth of Medicaid had expired. Limited medical insurance
through her school-aide position would hardly make a dent in her
costs. With the salary of her husband, a temporary worker with no
health insurance, and child support from her first husband, Amey's
family of five has $22,491 a year to live on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cutting down on my medications,'' she says, adding that
she takes pills for her fibromyalgia, a muscle and
connective-tissue disorder, ``only when I can't stand the pain
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make a choice between seeing the doctor and
eating. If I get sick, it's `OK, do I go to the doctor or pay the
bills? Eighty dollars to see the doctor _ to me, that's the
groceries.''
</P>
<P>
   Health care advocates fear there are many more people like Amey.
They say tens of thousands of ex-welfare recipients now in the work
force are poised to join the ranks of the 43.4 million Americans
who have no health insurance whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unintended consequence of welfare reform is that a large
number of low-income people (who go from welfare to work) are being
rewarded by losing their health care coverage,'' says Ron Pollack,
executive director of Families USA, an advocacy group that
concentrates on health issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of people moving into jobs wind up in
entry-level positions with low wages and few benefits,'' Pollack
adds. ``The majority of those receive no health insurance. So when
they lose Medicaid, they lose coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Families USA is conducting a survey of working former welfare
recipients who have lost Medicaid, and Pollack says the number will
be at least in the tens of thousands and maybe higher.
</P>
<P>
   Amey's situation is a measure of the rough headwinds that former
welfare recipients encounter when they leave the rolls. With
prodding from the states that were undertaking their own
experiments, Congress enacted a welfare overhaul in 1996. The law
limited recipients to two years of public assistance at any one
time and five years over a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and congressional Republicans have hailed the
sharp declines in the welfare rolls _ 7.9 million people are now on
welfare; in 1993 the number was 14.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But health care advocates argue that the vulnerability of these
new workers and their families often is overlooked in the rush of
headlines celebrating the success of welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barriers that people with low wages face in trying to cope
with everyday living _ whether (paying for) childcare, health
insurance or basic transportation _ are just amazing,'' says Diana
Rowland, executive director of the Kaiser Commission on Medicaid
and the Uninsured, which tracks low-income people's access to
health care..MDRV/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   Health-plan coverage for the poor is ``where our system of
employer-based coverage is eroding, and public policy is not
filling the gap,'' Rowland says.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a
Washington-based advocacy group, 15.8 million working parents have
incomes at or below $27,300 a year, which is twice the
government-set poverty level for a family of three. Of those, more
than a third _ 5.4 million _ were uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the federal government is getting the word out that
time-limited Medicaid is, in fact, available to those leaving
welfare for work. Before the 1996 law, Medicaid coverage came
automatically with welfare. But the law separated the two programs,
leaving many recipients entering the job market with the belief
that Medicaid no longer was available.
</P>
<P>
   Many state and local welfare agencies did little to inform
recipients that they still qualified for Medicaid. So last month
the U.S. Health and Human Services Department sent a letter to
state and local administrators, encouraging them to disseminate and
process Medicaid applications without delay.
</P>
<P>
   A new federal initiative, the Children's Health Insurance
Program (CHIP), approved by Congress as part of the 1997 Balanced
Budget Act, offers states money to expand Medicaid for poor
children or to create a separate health program for them.
</P>
<P>
   And some states have found creative ways to extend Medicaid
coverage. Connecticut, Delaware, New Jersey and South Carolina have
received federal waivers to give welfare-to-work families an extra
year on Medicaid. Vermont has authority to offer an extra year
above that _ a total of three years _ for some families.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Eva Amey and thousands more like her continue to
fall through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Yacknin, a lawyer with the Greater Upstate Law Project in
Rochester, N.Y. who has represented Amey, is lobbying the New York
legislature for a new program called Family Health Plus, which
would use the state's estimated $1-billion-a-year-for-25-years
share of tobacco-lawsuit settlement money to extend health
insurance to low-income, working adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are scrimping on food,'' Yacknin says. ``They're
in a worse position than when they were on welfare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
