<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-02 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI HAS MUCH TO PROVE ABOUT HIS LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If death and taxes are the only certainties in life, the death
penalty and tax cuts are the only certainties so far in the
Cellucci administration.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the House of Representatives defeated the governor's
bid to reinstate capital punishment. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   This is a governor who is still trying to prove he has vision,
backbone, and clout. Unfortunately, he has been relying on the
wrong issues to argue his case.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci scored points with the capital punishment crowd and
took his licks from Cardinal Bernard Law. ``I didn't expect to be
called a sinner,'' he says with a slight smile, when asked about
Law's recent remarks about ``well-informed Catholics'' who support
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   He stands to be called worse if he doesn't switch soon from
campaign issues to governing issues.
</P>
<P>
   The endless debate over capital punishment and a skirmish with a
cardinal who is as PR-savvy as any politician have little do with
the everyday demands of real governance. Throwing down the gauntlet
on a large income tax reduction is not exactly an exercise in
political courage either.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci says he is ``putting my leadership and reputation on
the line'' by threatening to lead a petition drive for a ballot
question to cut the state income tax to 5 percent. But championing
a tax cut is another easy, voter-friendly cause.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci got off to a slow start after election day and never
really gathered positive momentum on Beacon Hill. He looked weak
against state legislative leaders and his own appointees, such as
the state board of education and the board of trustees of the
University of Massachusetts. Headlines blare sorrowful news about
children caught in so-called houses of horror that fall under the
purview of his Department of Social Services.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, he continued to talk death penalty and tax cuts.
He seems trapped by the mindset that prevailed during the two terms
he served as lieutenant governor under former Governor Weld. Then,
the bad guys were obvious: They included Governor Dukakis and the
Democratic leaders who let state spending spiral wildly out of
control. Whatever went wrong was blamed on them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, who is to blame for whatever is wrong? After nine years of
Weld and Cellucci, the simple answer is: Weld and Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   But governing shouldn't be about blame, and it is never about
simple answers. It should be about choices and making the ones that
collectively improve our lives. Sometimes it is about telling
people what they don't want to hear and following through on it.
That is leadership.
</P>
<P>
   It is not too late for Cellucci to show some.
</P>
<P>
   He will argue, of course that tax cuts improve people's lives.
But relatively speaking, what he is talking about doesn't change
much or improve much.
</P>
<P>
   In life and in government, saving money isn't an ultimate end in
itself _ is it?
</P>
<P>
   We save for our children's education. We save so we can build a
dormer or repave a driveway. We save for a vacation or a rainy day.
If you are a governor, you save to build schools, repair roads and
courthouses and to provide services for the youngest, the oldest
and the poorest.
</P>
<P>
   What Cellucci seems to miss is that people want and expect
government to spend money to fix what is not working. They don't
want government to waste their money or spend all of it. But they
do want their children to go to safe and modern schools. They want
to drive on roads and bridges that are not falling apart. They want
the youngest and the oldest citizens to be treated with dignity.
And some of us, although not all of us, feel an obligation to share
what we have collectively as a society with those who have much,
much less as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Give the governor his due. He is making good on his campaign
rhetoric when it comes to the death penalty and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   When does he make good on his pledge to be our leader?
</P>
<P>
   Asked about it, he points to his stand on the Logan runway as an
example. He says he won't back down from the controversial
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am listening to the neighborhoods and I understand their
concerns. I am listening to the mayor. We have to share the
air-traffic burden. But we need a fully functional Logan,'' the
governor says.
</P>
<P>
   If he folds now on the runway, Cellucci would be folding on the
business community and on the vast majority of Massachusetts
residents who don't have to weigh the need for a more efficient
Logan against the aggravation of having an airport as a next-door
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Folding would not be wise for a governor who still needs to
prove he has vision, backbone, and clout. Sticking with the runway
would be a start in showing some leadership. But there is still a
long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
