<HEADER>
A3805 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-02 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IGNORE THE CRITICS AND FINISH THE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My fellow Americans: Get a grip.
</P>
<P>
   The headless chickens of the political and media establishment
are going bananas. We're running out of cruise missiles! The
weather is too cloudy over Serbia! We should have anticipated the
Serbs' Plan B was Kosovo-wide massacre! They're burning our flag on
TV!
</P>
<P>
   The nay-saying and second-guessing in the wake of NATO's bombing
campaign in the crumbling remains of what used to be Yugoslavia is
a panic reaction to a very grim and unpredictable set of
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the United States was ill prepared for war. No, it won't be
short and sweet and casualty-free. Yes, the Clinton administration
was weak on preparation for what we now face. No, the NATO exercise
that turned into a full-fledged war is not a neat little package.
</P>
<P>
   But let's take a deep breath here. Slobodan Milosevic's
Yugoslavia is an imploding mess of a country. Everything he tried
to seize by force _ Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia, now Kosovo, maybe
Montenegro and Albania
</P>
<P>
   next _ has blown up in his kisser. Can the massed forces of 19
western democracies, spearheaded by the mightiest military
technology in history, defeat a poor, faction-ridden country the
size and population of Ohio? Can the 700-plus million people of the
NATO nations slap
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan silly? I think the odds are in our favor.
</P>
<P>
   We can save Kosovo without invading Serbia; we took back Kuwait
without occupying Iraq. It may yet take ground troops and tanks
shipped through Greece. But give NATO's warplanes three or four
clear nights, and Belgrade begins to look like Baghdad after a
rough week. What happens when that extra US Navy carrier group
arrives offshore? More pulverizing of what we can find of
Milosevic's forces will certainly commence.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those opposed to the NATO military action claim the
justification of ending Serb atrocities in Kosovo is insufficient
because we didn't intervene in Cambodia against Pol Pot or in
Rwanda to stop black-on-black genocide. That line of reasoning does
not persuade me. For reasons of geography and history, the NATO
move on Kosovo is prudent, even necessary. That has nothing to do
with the skin color of the victims; melanin content did not dictate
NATO's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's international aid minister, Clare Short, was
positively withering when she figuratively dismembered the Tories'
Shadow Secretary in Parliament after he tried to accuse the Labor
government of making a bollocks, as the Brits say, by screwing up
the war, the diplomacy, and the relief effort. Fragging your own
leaders when things seem to be going wrong is not limited to any
one nationality, it appears.
</P>
<P>
   But that's democracy in action, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, the US Congress is in Easter recess for two weeks,
meaning we are all spared having to wade through their blather.
Coming off the impeachment debacle, the manufactured uproar over
Chinese spying, the thin gruel of sexual scandal and talk show
trivia, having our solons weigh in on serious business like life or
death would leave them overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   In their place we have the talking heads of TV, who toss out
their gloom-drenched predictions with unabashed fervor, despite
their dismal record in dissecting the politics of the last year.
From OJ to Jon-Benet, from gays in the military to horniness in the
White House, the TV claque natter on.
</P>
<P>
   Chowderheads and flannelmouths who could not pick out Kosovo on
a map assure us with practiced ease that things are going to hell
rapidly and no good can come of this. The 12-men-and-a-woman
running for president are grumpily evasive on the hard question of
being willing to put NATO ground troops at risk, with the
glittering exception of Senator John McCain of Arizona, the former
Navy combat pilot and POW.
</P>
<P>
   In plain and gutsy language, McCain says ``we have to win . . .
whatever it takes to win,'' and if that requires ground troops, so
be it. More bombing, says McCain; start ``turning the lights out in
Belgrade'' if need be. McCain knocks Clinton for being
``feckless,'' ``where our mission is confused and our exit strategy
is a complete mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   On that score, he is echoed by Bill Bradley, the only Democrat
opposing Vice President Gore, who's locked into whatever Clinton
does as commander-in-chief. Bradley, who raised an eye-opening $4
million in just three months, says ``serious questions'' are
unanswered about Clinton's policy.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Governor George W. Bush, who has time to raise $6 million
in campaign money, interview supplicants, and watch stock car
races, is tongue-tied. He lost standing by ducking the
what-would-you-do question. Steve Forbes, Lamar Alexander, and Dan
Quayle are scorching about Clinton, predictable in supporting air
strikes, and stoutly oppose sending ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, who trails only Bush in the polls, is for the
administration policy. She has to be; her husband is strongly for
it, and her fledgling candidacy could not survive a public rift
with Old Bob. Opposing America's involvement in the NATO war are
Pat Buchanan, whose oft-brandished talk-show bellicosity seems
confined to our trading partners; and US Representative John Kasich
of Ohio, who mocks Clinton. Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire,
Gary Bauer, and Alan Keyes all object to US policy as well. The
country is divided and confused. What we need is a week of
cloud-free skies over Kosovo, some steady nerves in NATO capitals,
and the resolve to finish what Milosevic started.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
