<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-WALK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT LANDING `ON THE MOON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``A Walk on the Moon,'' the counterculture and the Catskills
collide, with devastating results for a middle-class Jewish family
in the summer of 1969.
</P>
<P>
   These were interesting times (as in the old curse, ``May you
live in interesting times'') and the film never lets us forget it,
because otherwise we might mistake the story for a simple domestic
tragedy. No, this is a tale of major cultural transition.
</P>
<P>
   The changes eating away at the film's Kantrowitz family are old
standbys: hippies, Woodstock, the moon landing and similar
phenomena that are beloved of pop historians and lend themselves to
nice visuals.
</P>
<P>
   Director Tony Goldwyn and writer Pamela Gray place no heavy
demands on the audience; all is spelled out with excruciating
clarity. When mildly unhappy Pearl Kantrowitz (Diane Lane) meets
handsome, free-spirited Walker (Viggo Mortensen) while her
husband's away, you don't need tarot cards _ another of the film's
timely references _ to foresee the result.
</P>
<P>
   The Kantrowitzes are having their annual getaway at a funky
Catskills resort, a modest paradise of small bungalows, cornball
entertainers and occasional visits by traveling vendors, such as
the ``Ice Cream Man'' and the ``Blouse Man,'' who sells clothing to
the vacationing women.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Pearl is her ready-to-break-loose 14-year-old
daughter, Alison (Anna Paquin), her 5-year-old son, Daniel, and her
prescient mother-in-law, Lilian (Tovah Feldshuh). Husband Marty
(Liev Schreiber), a TV repairman who had hoped for bigger things in
life, is on hand until called back to work in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is played for affectionate laughs, as a
``MASH''-style announcer informs the vacationers that the ``Knish
Man'' is on the grounds; a woman friend of Pearl's wonders if she
should frost her hair; and some naked hippies briefly invade the
resort's lake, to the consternation of the strait-laced family
folk.
</P>
<P>
   As Alison takes a sudden interest in boys, Pearl _ who became
pregnant at 17 and has never slept with anyone but Marty _ starts
feeling a little itchy herself. She accepts a tie-dyed shirt from
long-haired, quietly sexy Walker (he's the blouse man) and they are
soon frolicking in their birthday suits in a nearby pond _
picture-perfect, of course. All is played out against a soundtrack
(Jefferson Airplane, Richie Havens, Jimi Hendrix) evocative of
paisleys and peace symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Well, nosy Lilian figures out the affair, and she's upset. When
Alison finds out, in a hokey scene actually set at the Woodstock
festival, she's even more upset _ moms aren't supposed to paint
their bodies and writhe with attractive strangers. And when Marty
finds out (tipped off by helpful Lilian), he's extremely upset,
hurls a milk carton against the cabin wall, etc. He's been
disappointed too, how could she do this? Pearl seems diminished by
her experiment with free love.
</P>
<P>
   OK, everyone's mad at her, she doesn't know what to do about
Walker's invitation to run off with him, and to top it all, her boy
is attacked and horribly stung by some highly symbolic wasps.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is not for me to reveal, except to say it strains
belief.
</P>
<P>
   Though short on subtlety, ``A Walk on the Moon'' does offer the
consolation of some decent performances (not surprising, as Dustin
Hoffman's company produced it). Lane (``Wild Bill'') is
surprisingly affecting in what could have been a pedestrian role _
why should we care about this essentially selfish person? The
talented Schreiber (the ``Scream'' horror fests) comes into his own
after Marty discovers his wife's betrayal. He's a decent guy whose
main consolation in life, his family, is suddenly shattered, and
the actor capitalizes nicely on the showcase offered by Marty's
grief and anger. Mortensen has little to do other than look
dangerously seductive; Feldshuh is an old pro, and Oscar-winner
Paquin is fine as the budding teen.
</P>
<P>
   Director Goldwyn (the grandson of MGM founder Sam Goldwyn)
clearly knows the milieu, but doesn't rise above the heavy-handed
material. He knows how to work with actors, but not with audiences,
who deserve a little more trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1427EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
