A3863 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GULF-POW-HNS &LR;      04-02 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-POW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GULF POW ADVISES FAMILIES TO `KEEP THE FAITH'' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARMINA DANINI  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Melissa Coleman, the first American woman taken
prisoner during the Persian Gulf War, doesn't pay much attention to
the news. So when her mother told her Wednesday night about the
three U.S. servicemen who had been captured by Yugoslav forces,
Coleman said, ``Oh, goodness, here we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about these three men, I was saddened to see
someone going through it again,'' said Coleman, who now lives in
San Antonio with her husband, a government employee, and their two
children. Known then as Melissa Rathbun-Nealy, the native of Grand
Rapids, Mich., was 21 when she went to the Persian Gulf with the
233rd Transportation Company stationed at Fort Bliss near El Paso,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   She and another soldier were on a supply mission near the
Kuwait- Saudi Arabia border Jan. 30, 1991, when Iraqi fire hit
their truck. Both were taken prisoner. The first servicewoman to be
a prisoner of war since World War II, she was held captive in Iraq
for 33 days. Coleman, who was wounded, later received the Purple
Heart, the Prisoner of War Medal and the National Defense Service
Medal.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman was taken prisoner by the Iraqis, Army flight
surgeon Rhonda Cornum. Cornum's husband, Kory, an Air Force flight
surgeon, said Thursday night that she is now stationed in Augusta,
Ga., and is in Australia this week and could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said she would tell the families of the three captured
U.S. soldiers in Yugoslavia _ Army Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone,
of Capac, Mich., Spc. Steve Gonzalez of Huntsville, Texas, and
Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez of Los Angeles _ to remain strong.
``Keep the faith, whatever their faith is,'' Coleman said. ``Stay
strong, think positive thoughts and don't believe everything they
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers captured this week were on patrol near the
border Yugoslav border as part of an international peacekeeping
force in the former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia. Yugoslavia
began court proceedings against three captured soldiers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, 29, recalled that her father, Leo Rathbun, had been
angered by initial reports that she was absent without leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until I had been released and someone who saw it on
TV called my dad that he calmed down,'' Coleman said. ``My dad
called Washington and asked if they were now going to declare me a
prisoner of war.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said her family was shaken by rumors that surfaced while
she was a POW that Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein was going to use her
as a human shield, and that she had been mutilated and decapitated.
``My dad's typical Irish, so he wasn't happy with the (U.S.)
government,'' she said, ``and I was highly upset when he told me
after I came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who was awakened shortly after 6 a.m. Thursday by a
call from the MSNBC cable news network and spent the rest of the
day on the telephone giving interviews, had another piece of advice
for the families of the three men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing with the media gets better with time,'' she said.
``Eventually, they go away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
