conflict. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DISCLOSURES _ WASHINGTOn _ Critics say that Pentagon anbd
Clinton administration statements about the weaknesses in U.S.
military preparedness _ like admitting to a shortage of cruise
missiles _ may stiffen Serb resistance. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-IRAQ _ BAGHDAD _ Iraqis are watching the drama in
Yugoslavia with special appreciation for America's military
strength. Having been roundly defeated in the Gulf War and still
subject to periodic U.S. air strikes, the Iraqis know full, well
the consequences of provoking an America's wrath. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO _ PEC, Yugoslavia _ Fears spread among
citizens of the pro-Western government of Montenegro Friday that
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is about to orchestrate a
coup. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0402 _ VATICAN CITY _ Vatican City remains ground
zero for the largest Christian denomination in the world, the
center of a separate ``country'' with its own government,
newspaper, radio station and publishing house and home to about
1,000 people. Decisions made here have changed the course of Europe
and the world. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Embargoed
until Sunday, April 4
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICISM _ To celebrate Easter, the holiest day of their
year, tens of thousands of Christians will gather outside St.
Peter's, the home church of a billion Catholics. With the year 2000
only months away, the festivities are a foretaste of a yearlong
birthday party celebrating 2000 years of Christianity. (White,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). Embargoed until Sunday, April 4
</P>
<P>
   ORVIETO _ You can see your breath in the sanctuary of St. Andrew
and St. Bartholomew Church on a drizzly Saturday night during Lent.
Half a dozen space heaters feebly try to battle the chill of a
temperature barely breaking the 30s as older women, in wool or fur
coats, gather on the hard, worn wooden pews to pray the rosary. The
church is one of hundreds of struggling congregations off the usual
path of tourists in Italy, the homeland of Catholicism. Although
some 80 percent Italians identify themselves as Christian and
virtually all are Catholic, Catholicism is often more a matter of
culture than of practice. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
Embargoed until Sunday, April 4
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet Focus page for the week. The layout is
now available)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TIMECHANGE _ Forget to spring ahead this year and there's a good
chance you'll be asleep in bed when Easter sunrise services are
being held. It's that time of year once again, when American's push
their clocks ahead and hour to gain an extra 60 minutes of
sunlight. But this year, Easter falls on the first full day of
Daylight Savings Time, and ignoring the clock could have some
spiritual consequences. (GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH GRAPHIC
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BOTANICAL _ MEXICO CITY _ The Spanish conquistadors
talked about suffering for months because they had to eat local
``weeds'' as they marched through Mexico nearly 500 years ago.
Today, at Mexico City's Botanical Garden botanists are reviving an
appreciation for this country's vast native plant life and its
nutritional and medicinal value. In addition to a huge collection
of agaves and cacti, the garden grows plants loaded with vitamins
or known to ease childbirth, stomach ailments and other troubles.
Workers at the garden often help themselves to leaves of one plant
to brew a tea that fights anemia. The garden is run by Mexico's
National Autonomous University, where researchers are also involved
in international projects to develop medicines to treat AIDS,
tuberculosis and other diseases -- research that combines high-tech
science with the knowledge of traditional healers. (Ferriss, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
