A3882 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIAN-AMERICAN-VETS-H     04-02 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-AMERICAN-VETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VA TO STUDY ALLEGED BIAS AGAINST ASIAN-AMERICANS IN VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The psychological wounds suffered by Vietnam War
veterans are well documented. But the traumas of Asian-American
soldiers _ fighting in an unpopular war against an enemy who looked
like them _ are just now emerging.
</P>
<P>
   They had to protect themselves not only from Viet Cong
guerrillas but also from racist abuse, both verbal and physical,
within their own ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discovered Asian-Americans had unique problems _
discrimination, getting beat up, getting called names, getting shot
at,'' said Lily Lee Adams, a Veterans Administration nurse who has
counseled numerous Asian-American veterans.
</P>
<P>
   To fully understand the race factors in the Vietnam War, the VA
is conducting its first race-related study, interviewing
Asian-American veterans in Hawaii, Guam and Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   The VA will spend $276,000 for the three-year study. It has
found 250 veterans and hopes to have a total of 300 by next month.
Results are expected this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although not all the veterans experienced discrimination _
officers and those of higher rank usually had no complaints _ the
effect on those who did was often overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some of them, their identity's crushed,'' Adams said.
``They've been American all their life, then they go into the
military and are told they're not American. Their whole view about
themselves is shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who is Chinese-American, was an Army nurse in Vietnam.
She said she often was mistaken for a Vietnamese prostitute by
other Americans in the compound.
</P>
<P>
   When David Oshiro, who is Okinawan-American and grew up in
Hawaii, lay wounded and bleeding in Vietnam, his fellow Americans
were reluctant to put him on the helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to whip out my dog tag and say, `I'm an American,''' he
said. ``They'll get all the black and white guys before they get
the Asians out.''
</P>
<P>
   Oshiro, now 50 and a resident of San Rafael, Calif., served in
the elite Special Forces and said he had a good relationship with
all the soldiers in his unit, but that soldiers from other units
were not as enlightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been called `gook' more times than I care to think
about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While he was at basic training, a sergeant asked him and several
other Asian-Americans to dress up in black pajamas, the get-up of
the Viet Cong, to show recruits what the enemy looks like. Oshiro
refused.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1501EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3906 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS &LR;      04-02 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS QUESTION MICHIGAN MAN ABOUT TEXAS KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Federal agents investigating the disappearance of
atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair have had extensive talks with Gary P.
Karr, a Michigan ex-convict charged last week with a federal
weapons violation, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At his detention hearing, the FBI agent testified that they
interviewed Mr. Karr at his home for about 10 hours and the next
day for a few hours,'' Richard Helfrick, a federal public defender
who represents Karr, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their characterization of those interviews was that Mr. Karr
was cooperative with regards to matters relating to Texas involving
homicides,'' he said by telephone from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Helfrick, however, declined to say if Karr has admitted any role
in any slayings. He said Karr has not made any deals to cooperate,
nor have federal prosecutors extended any offers.
</P>
<P>
   Karr, 50, and David R. Waters, 52, were arrested last week after
teams of federal agents and Dallas County deputies searched Karr's
apartment in Novi, Mich., and Waters' apartment in Austin, Texas.
Agents allegedly found two loaded pistols in Karr's apartment in
the Detroit suburb and 119 rounds of ammunition in Waters'
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Both are ex-convicts and were charged with being felons in
possession of firearms or ammunition. Following the raids, Waters'
lawyer, Patrick Ganne of Austin, quoted a federal prosecutor as
saying others were already giving damning evidence against his
client.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said a bunch of people are rolling over on him (Waters) and
implicating him in the murder of the O'Hair family,'' Ganne said of
Assistant U.S. Attorney Gerald Carruth of Austin. Carruth has
declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Karr and Waters are being held without bond. The March 24 raids
occurred as federal agents in Chicago and Fort Worth, Texas,
questioned other individuals about the O'Hair case and about the
coincidental disappearance of a Florida man named Danny Fry.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray, and her daughter Robin Murray
O'Hair vanished from San Antonio along with $500,000 in gold on
Sept. 29, 1995. O'Hair had risen to prominence more than three
decades ago in the wake of federal court battles to remove prayer
and Bible reading from public schools. In recent years, she ran a
cluster of atheist organizations in Austin with her two adult
children.
</P>
<P>
   Fry went to Austin in 1995, and like the O'Hair family, spent
September in San Antonio. On Oct. 2, 1995, three days after the
O'Hair family vanished, his headless, handless body was dumped on a
riverbank near Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant circumstantial evidence, including telephone and
financial records, suggests the two cases are related, and that
Waters was a common link. Waters was O'Hair's former office manager
in 1994 and in 1995 pleaded guilty to stealing $54,000 from them.
He knew Fry in Florida years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family members say Waters induced Fry to move to Texas for a
lucrative deal in mid 1995. Waters has denied knowing anything
about the O'Hair disappearance or Fry's death.
</P>
<P>
   Waters also has apparent links to Karr, having served eight
months in the same Illinois prison during the mid 1980s. He also
apparently contacted Karr after his release from prison in May
1995, Helfrick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he (Karr) got out of prison, I think he was trying to put
his past behind him, and go forward, and that if anything, Waters
injected himself into Karr's life,'' Helfrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Karr and Waters have extensive records that include violent
crime. Last week Karr was charged in Austin with another federal
crime, receiving stolen property in excess of $5,000. The complaint
states only that the crime occurred in October 1995 and involved
interstate transport ``from Texas to Florida and elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit explaining the stolen property charge is sealed
and federal officials have declined to comment on it. Karr's lawyer
said no attempts had been made yet to extradite him to Texas from
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still sitting here in the Wayne County Jail. I don't see
anything happening here for the foreseeable future,'' Helfrick
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
