<HEADER>
A3935 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT'S-BULLY-BOS     04-02 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT'S-BULLY-BOSS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE BALLMER: THE BRAWN _ AND BULLHORN _ OF MICROSOFT  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This colorful 900-word ``separate buy'' profile of Bill Gates'
right-hand man is from the current (week beginning 3 April 1999)
Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Gates is often compared to John D. Rockefeller, but the
closer parallel might be between Steve Ballmer and John D.
Archbold, the co-pilots of Microsoft now and Standard Oil 100 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both got to know the industry titans in their early days,
Archbold as a surrogate son and court jester, Ballmer as a college
housemate and poker buddy.
</P>
<P>
   And both took over daily operations at a time when their company
was fighting a crucial antitrust battle, the first in 1897, the
latter in July last year.
</P>
<P>
   Archbold proved to be exactly the wrong choice to head Standard
Oil. He financed overseas expansion by keeping domestic prices
high, inflaming public opinion and fueling the political pressure
to break the company up.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer is about to be put to the same test.
</P>
<P>
   He has just made his first big move as Microsoft's president,
designing the long-awaited restructuring the firm announced on
March 29.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will no longer be organized around products such as
operating systems, but rather around customer groups: IT managers,
wired employees, developers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer hopes this will inspire programmers to write the
software that customers want _ not products dictated by the
mushrooming Microsoft bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable that Ballmer would want to undertake such a
reorganization. Before he was promoted, he spent six years as
Microsoft's chief salesman. It was Ballmer and his team who took
the telephone calls from angry customers who complained again and
again about software that is difficult to install, crashes
regularly and has too many unwieldy features.
</P>
<P>
   What is more surprising is that he has been given the chance.
When Ballmer gets excited, it's time to unpack the earplugs.
Dressing down subordinates, he can be heard echoing through the
air-conditioning vents at Microsoft. His maniacal shouting has
already resulted in throat surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer's verbal outbursts have also hurt his company's
reputation. Shortly after the Department of Justice began its
latest battle with Microsoft in October 1997, he bellowed at
reporters: ``To heck with (Attorney-General) Janet Reno.'' A few
weeks later at a trade show, he screamed ``What the consumer needs
is more, more, more Windows.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he regrets those comments, and wants to ``stop saying
stupid things.''
</P>
<P>
   But when this big, balding man starts gesticulating wildly to
make a point, one minute a tyrant, the next a little boy, you
wonder whether his efforts to tone himself down can possibly last.
As Gates says, Ballmer ``exudes exuberance.''
</P>
<P>
   This huge personality has undoubtedly shaped Microsoft's
corporate culture _ more, some even argue, than Gates himself.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the company in 1980, after marketing cake mixes at
Procter &AMP; Gamble and dropping out of Stanford University business
school, he has become a sort of rapid intervention force.
</P>
<P>
   Without his relentless salesmanship, the software firm would
have been much less commercially successful. He regularly called up
customers who had chosen competitors' products _ sometimes, it is
said, with dire threats.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly that alone should have disqualified Ballmer from the
top job at Microsoft at a time when it is accused of being a
reckless monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   And he is a rum choice to teach superaggressive Microsofties to
play by the rules _ something the antitrust proceedings have shown
they need to learn.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft is officially declared a monopoly, an unBallmerish
restraint will become essential. Should the court go further and
order ``structural'' remedies of the kind the Department of Justice
would like _ perhaps including the forced licensing of Windows to
competitors _ Microsoft would have to reinvent itself.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a more favorable legal outcome, Ballmer faces
difficult times ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer fanciful to suggest that Microsoft's big,
fully-featured computer-operating systems could go the way of IBM's
all-conquering mainframes. This is, in part, its own fault.
</P>
<P>
   To protect and expand its monopoly, it has added ever more
features to Windows, turning it into a hairball of software.
Development of Windows 2000 is already more than two years behind
schedule, because bugs multiply as fast as Microsoft's programmers
can splat them.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the world is no longer going Microsoft's way.
Televisions, telephones, and portable organizers with mini
operating systems threaten the hegemony of the Windows-based PC;
Linux, a rival operating system, is gaining ground; firms are
starting to rent both software and processing power.
</P>
<P>
   Money is moving from software to services, where Microsoft has
little worthwhile experience. It has, for example, invested huge
sums in its consumer websites, and made no money.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer seems to be aware of this weakness, moving his office to
the division that produces online services.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft still has time to shift its amazingly lucrative
business, and nobody should underestimate the intelligence and
energy it will bring to bear when it decides it has to.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ballmer is the right person to drive Microsoft over the
bumpy road ahead is another matter. He has the brutality and
insider knowledge to impose painful choices. Yet should Gates
withdraw further from the day-to-day running of the company,
Ballmer may lack the techie credentials necessary to carry
Microsoft's talented engineers into new fields.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest danger, though, is that Ballmer channels his
terrifying dynamism into a fight to the finish for Windows. If he
does, he will go down in history as the Archbold of the digital
age. &QL; 
