 Friday, April 2, 1999    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following
stories for Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call
Susie McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about
Houston Chronicle sports stories, please call 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: KOSOVO-NATO; BKN-ROCKETS; BBN-ASTROS,
TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN; SPACE-STATION; and ECUADOR-SLAYINGS.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ President Clinton calls for the
immediate release of three captured American soldiers and sends a
new aircraft carrier group to join other NATO forces in the
escalating conflict with Yugoslavia. By BENNETT ROTH. (Photo
available on NYT database of townsfolk in Huntsville, Texas,
putting yellow ribbons around trees in support of captured U.S.
soldiers.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ They had been playing with fire all
season long, and the Houston Rockets finally got burned Thursday
night against the Utah Jazz. The Rockets have had trouble holding a
lead throughout the season, and it caught up with them against
their longtime rivals. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (San Antonio) _ The Houston Astros are expected to
make a decision on Ken Caminiti's status for Opening Day and settle
the final roster. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN (Houston) _ We look at tennis legend Rod
Laver, who is being honored at a ceremony at the River Oaks Country
Club in Houston. DALE ROBERTSON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FACES-OF-WAR (Washington) _ Images of captured American GIs
tormented by Serbs are flickering across the nation's TV screens,
putting a U.S. face on a distant war. The spectacle raises public
awareness of American involvement in the Balkans and increases the
pressure on President Clinton to send troops _ or quit and suffer a
humiliating defeat. We look at the history of American captives in
foreign conflicts. By STEWART M. POWELL and ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID-CUTOFF (Washington) _ Despite a crippling disease, Eva
Amey of Elmira, N.Y. got herself off welfare and is working as a
teacher's aide. But she earns only $5,756 a year and, because she
is now employed, has lost her Medicaid benefits. With doctor bills
averaging more than $500 a month, she often can't afford to see the
doctor or buy medicine. Health care advocates say there are tens of
thousands cases like Amey's. By DAN FREEDMAN. (1stld-writethru
filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION (Houston) _ The United States will offer Russia
another $100 million in an attempt to keep the international space
station project on schedule. Ostensibly, the money will purchase a
three-person Soyuz capsule and other gear. But the real objective,
according to NASA administrator Dan Goldin, is to keep the more
crucial Russian contributions to the new station from slipping
further behind schedule. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-SLAYING (Quito, Ecuador) _ Unlike neighboring Colombia
and Peru, Ecuador has never been plagued by death squads, powerful
guerrilla armies or drug-cartel terrorism. Thus, the murder of
Jaime Hurtado, a Marxist congressman, has left Ecuadoreans baffled.
The government blames Colombian paramilitaries. Others suspect the
police. Regardless, the slaying has shattered the illusion of
Ecuador as a safe haven from regional violence. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ America's intervention in
Yugoslavia raises questions once more about our national interest,
our humanitarian obligations and our leadership in international
organizations created as a result of our conviction that collective
security is essential to peace. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed
Wednesday.)
</P>
