<HEADER>
A3939 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV04     04-02 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV04-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS' 401(K)S SEEM HEADED IN THE RIGHT DIRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 04, 1999)  
 (Eds.: Includes correction of previous column.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are in our mid-forties and both of us work for
the same non-profit employer. We both put 10 percent of our pay
into our 401(k) accounts, and a percentage of this is matched by
our employer. Together we earn $62,000 a year. My wife has been
there for five years and has $20,000, all of it invested in
Fidelity Growth and Income fund. I have been there for two years,
and have $4,800 in my account, all of it in Fidelity Contrafund. I
also have $2,000 in a regular IRA. Except for a few shares of
stock, the 401(k) accounts represent out main retirement nest egg.
We just refinanced our mortgage, which now is to be paid off over
15 years. Is our portfolio diversified enough? Will we have enough
to retire when we reach age 65? Should I convert my IRA to a Roth,
or should I roll it into the 401(k)?
</P>
<P>
   R.T., Eugene, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's begin with the critical question: Will you have enough
to retire? To a large degree, that depends on how much is that
unspecified percentage that your employer adds to those 401(k)
accounts. Let's suppose that your employer matches by putting in 50
cents for every $1 from yourself or your wife. If that were the
case, and if contributions remained at current levels for 20 years,
and if you achieved average annual portfolio returns of 10 percent,
you would amass a pool of $737,280. If your employer's contribution
is 25 cents for each $1 you contribute, the pool would be $644,449.
If your employer quit contributing entirely, you still would amass
$551,619.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume that among those three projections the middle
ground is closest to your situation, so you'll have a $644,449
pool. If you invested that money in a fixed-income pool that
produces an average yield of 6.5 percent, it would bring you
$41,889 a year. That works out to 67.6 percent of your current
income stream -- which is roughly what most people figure they will
need in retirement. Moreover, if you'll qualify for Social
Security, so much the better; in fact, in all likelihood quite a
bit for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the ugly part -- inflation. If you had $41,889 in the
year 2019 and inflation averaged 3.5 percent annually between now
and then, it would have the same buying power as $21,051 in today's
money. You would need $83,350 to buy the same goods and services
that $41,889 buys today. And to produce an income stream of $83,350
you would need a little more than $1.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are several factors working in your favor. One is
that you're likely to get raises during those intervening 20 years,
and if you continue contributing 10 percent and if your employer
continues to match your higher contributions, the pool would be
larger than projected above. Second, there's always the possibility
of Social Security. Third, although you consider the few shares of
stock insignificant at this point, since you didn't specify their
value I couldn't plug them into the formula. (I did add the IRA
in.) If those shares are worth $500 and their growth tracked that
of the rest of the portfolio, you could add $3,363; not a terribly
big deal, but it helps.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, the projection above presumed that you
maintained all of your principal, withdrawing only its yield.
Certainly in the later years of retirement, there is no problem
with people slowly depleting their capital -- you just do a
projection of a very high life span such as 100 years and then
figure how much you might withdraw so that if you live to be 100,
you'll have one things -- a letter from the President. What you
won't have is money, but most people are willing to make that
modest bet against themsleves.
</P>
<P>
   Is your portfolio diversified enough? What diversification? Both
Fidelity Growth and Income and Fidelity Contrafund are domestic
large-cap funds with their portfolios representing a blend of
growth- and value-oriented issues. The growth and income fund is
probably more conservative, carrying a below-average risk score
from Morningstar Mutual Funds (compared to an average risk rating
for Contrafund) but at bottom they're mighty similar.
</P>
<P>
   If I were you, I would leave about 60 percent of each 401(k)
accounts in your current holdings, and spread the remainder out
evenly among a mid-cap fund, a small-cap fund, an international
fund, and a health care fund. That presumes, of course, that your
401(k) has a menu of investments sufficiently broad to allow such
moves. If not, get as close as you can, perhaps using a balanced
fund such as Fidelity Puritan if you can't find anything in one of
those categories. And since very few 401(k) plans offer sector
funds, rather than rolling the IRA into your 401(k), why not roll
it over into a Rollover IRA invested in Fidelity Select Health Care
fund?
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would appreciate it if you would look at my investments.
I'm 62 years old and will retire in 12 to 30 months. If I do work
30 months, I should have enough money to live on just relying on my
pension and Social Security. I want my investments to provide
enough money to take care of car expenses, travel and inflation --
perhaps $16,000 to $20,000 a year. I list the holdings on a
separate sheet. I also have property in Florida which I plan to
sell, expecting proceeds of about $50,000. Where should I invest
it? Should I start consolidating the funds I already have?
</P>
<P>
   R.G., Kingston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. What can I say -- you've done it right. Even though your list
seems imposing, it boils down to 20 accounts spread over 15
different investments. After making some guesses (such as how a
variable annuity is invested) and treating all balanced funds as
50/50 stocks and bonds, I came up with $140,750 on the fixed-income
side and $88,850 in stock investments.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose you take that $50,000 and use it to build your
position in Fidelity Puritan. That would take your stock position
to a little more than $40,000, and would leave you with $165,750 on
the fixed-income side. That would be sufficient to provide you with
$897 a month without invading principal, presuming you achieved an
average 6.5 percent yield from the fixed portfolio -- a likely
assumption since your holdings are dominated by mortgage
securities.
</P>
<P>
   Let's also suppose that your needs work out to $18,000 a year,
or $1,500 a month. What would happen if you simply withdrew $603 a
month from the stock portfolio? Nothing horrible. If you got only
6.5 percent returns from the stocks, you would stand still. If the
stock side did better, you would see some very tidy growth. How
tidy? Well, if you achieved average 10 percent returns and made
those withdrawals, the stock portfolio would grow from $113,850 to
$380,777 over the course of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   This certainly isn't the fast track, but it's a nice
conservative approach to a portfolio that's more than ample to meet
your needs, so I see no risk to change from your current
conservative orientation. And unless you find tracking the
portfolio troublesome, I see no problem with having your money
spread among 15 different investments. In fact, the only change of
any sort that I would suggest is, of course, to get that $11,000
out of the credit union where it's earning 3 percent and get it in
a mutual fund money market fund, where you might see returns move
to the 4.5 percent area. This would mean have very little loss of
liquidity. And since I'll let you keep $5,000 loafing in the bank
at 2 percent, you'll still have a way to get emergency cash fast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CORRECTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In last Sunday's column (March 28), I recommended that an
investor buy Vanguard Health Care fund, relying on what turned out
to be outdated information in the summary issue of the Morningstar
Mutual Funds reports. The fund was closed to new investors several
weeks ago. As I have often said in this column, Vanguard Health
Care is my favorite fund in the health care category, focusing
primarily on stocks of pharmaceutical companies and medical
equipment companies (rather than on health care delivery and
biotechs). Fidelity Select Health Care is an excellent proxy for
the Vanguard fund, and now for most people it is the best choice in
the category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
