<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEAPORT-SECURITY-NYTR     04-02 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAPORT-SECURITY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMISSION TO INVESTIGATE SEAPORT SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y., Calif., Texas, La., S.C.)  (mk) 
 By CATHERINE HOLLINGSWORTH   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most vacationers who board cruise ships see
bustling ports simply as a gateway to fun and sun. But federal
authorities say seaports can be paradise for criminals.
</P>
<P>
   For thieves looking to quickly export ill-gotten gains or nab
valuable shipments of designer clothes, computers and other
high-end goods, ports are a popular destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crooks know the system very well and know the cracks in
the system,'' said Ed Badolato, chairman of the Washington-based
National Cargo Security Council. ``Crooks have too much access to
shipping records. That's why crime has skyrocketed through the
roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Cargo theft costs companies an estimated $10 billion a year.
Over the decades, it has gone from pilfering, say, a case of
liquor, to conspiring to intercept entire loads of merchandise. The
scheme often requires an organized effort with help from truckers,
dock workers or other insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Taking note of this growing problem, President Clinton intends
to establish a national commission to combat seaport crime and beef
up port security.
</P>
<P>
   The Graham Commission on Seaport Crime and Security, named after
Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., who originated the idea, is scheduled to
be unveiled in the coming weeks when members of Congress return
from recess.
</P>
<P>
   The president was immediately receptive to Graham's plan when
the two men first discussed it last May, said an aide to Graham.
</P>
<P>
   After several visits to Florida's ports, Graham noticed a
recurring set of problems related to seaports, the staffer said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cargo theft, the commission will explore drug
trafficking, terrorist activity, illegal car exports, smuggling of
illegal immigrants, exchange of counterfeit money and imports of
banned food.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin will lead the
presidential commission and appoint up to 25 members from federal
agencies, according to Graham's staff. The panel will make
recommendations to Clinton on improving maritime security.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Graham wanted to introduce legislation dealing with
cargo theft but it was too difficult to set standards for entities
governed by an array of local, state and federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Many local port authorities are recognizing the need for better
security and are planning such basic improvements as better
lighting, restricted access to yards and more thorough background
checks, Graham's staffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Most cargo theft occurs at major ports in New York, South
Florida and Southern California in a region Badolato calls the
``Bermuda Triangle,'' where 80 percent of the cargo disappears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drugs have basically driven the movement to make the ports
more secure,'' said Mike Sinclair, chief inspector for the U.S.
Customs Service at Port Everglades in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that the Everglades port and the Port of Miami
were the main entry points for drugs, he said. Now agents are
seeing narcotics turn up more often at ports in Houston, New
Orleans, and Charleston, S.C. The mere proximity of a port can make
some cities vulnerable to crime such as auto theft, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Seaports handle 95 percent of U.S. trade but some port
executives say they rarely see cargo theft.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kornegay, executive director of the Port of Houston and
chairman of the American Association of Port Authorities, said, ``I
don't think it's a big issue with us.''
</P>
<P>
   He said losing a couple of shipping containers a year out of the
thousands the port handles is ``pretty low. We have pretty tight
security.''
</P>
<P>
   (Catherine Hollingsworth reports from the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
