   MAGICIAN-BURIAL (New York) _ Monday at 10 a.m., David Blaine, a
fin de siecle version of Harry Houdini best known for his
friendships with the Hollywood fast crowd, will be buried, for a
week, on the banks of the Hudson River. By Kevin Bisch.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   JERSEY-CHIC (Undated) _ For many nonresidents, the words ``New
Jersey'' conjure up sights and smells of the northern stretch of
the New Jersey Turnpike _ tank farm after pipeline after brewery.
But these days there is the whiff of something sweeter in the air.
A lot of creativity is rising from the tomato patches and the tacky
strip malls, the Pine Barrens and the parking lots to the immediate
west of New York. By Frank DeCaro.
</P>
<P>
   COMMISH-SOCIAL-WHIRL (New York) _ In the midst of the political
crisis surrounding the killing of Amadou Diallo by four
plainclothes police officers, New York City Police Commissioner
Howard Safir sped across the country in a corporate jet and
schmoozed with biggies at the Academy Awards. As might have been
predicted, he was lambasted. But Safir was upholding a longstanding
tradition that came with his job: Upon becoming commissioner, he
had automatically joined the social A list, with all its
blandishments and career-threatening temptations. By Alex
Kuczynski.
</P>
