<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3982 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF     04-02 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 CRIME
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY MARILYN STASIO
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Perfect beauty takes many blinding guises in A SIGHT FOR SORE
EYES (Crown, $24), a suspense novel by Ruth Rendell that is itself
a flawless piece of craftsmanship. But to the tormented characters
who obsessively pursue their objects of desire -- including a
redheaded woman, a mint-condition Edsel and the reflection of the
beholder's own face in the mirror -- the worship of beauty leads
directly to murder and madness.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell charts a harrowing collision course for two
preternaturally beautiful teen-agers: Teddy Brex, an unloved child
who grows up to be a sociopath, and Francine Hill, an overprotected
child who grows up to be his ideal victim. Life has taught Teddy
that people are ugly and unkind; but since ``looking at beauty took
away pain and hurt,'' no deed committed to acquire that beauty is
too cruel or too crazy. Teddy may be twisted, but in the author's
bold, imaginative view he is sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching back a generation to get more traction for her macabre
love story, Rendell takes a ruthless probe to every person (from
Teddy's emotionally arrested parents to the faceless stranger who
murdered Francine's mother) who had a hand in shaping the psyches
of this ill-met pair. Spare and unforgiving, these incisive
character studies illuminate the darker corners of Teddy's and
Francine's family histories without dimming the originality of
their bizarre lives.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Pigeon, the intrepid park ranger who has braved forest
fires, underground rockslides and killer mountain cats in Nevada
Barr's wilderness mysteries, nearly caves in to the urban terrors
of Manhattan in LIBERTY FALLING (Putnam, $23.95). Keeping vigil by
day at her sister's hospital bed, Anna flees by night to national
park grounds in New York Harbor, where a ranger friend is putting
her up on Liberty Island. Although there's no escaping the
``flotsam of noise and tension'' that washes up from the city, Anna
finds a kind of peace accompanying Lady Liberty's attendants on
their nightly rounds and prowling the abandoned hospital buildings
on Ellis Island -- until a young girl falls from the Statue of
Liberty and one of the rangers starts seeing ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   Barr keeps her distance from the wildlife on the mainland
(wisely, since her impressions of Times Square are way out of date)
to concentrate on those loner types who live on islands and work
the late shift. Although Anna has some quietly moving scenes with
such characters, she's more in her element on her nocturnal walks
through the crumbling buildings and rank gardens of Ellis Island.
Barr writes with hypnotic lyricism of these decaying ruins, where
``Nature was taking back what had once been hers'' by pushing green
shoots up from the mold. It isn't the Grand Canyon, but to a
naturalist like Barr, the place is teeming with life.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwestern Indians in Kirk Mitchell's CRY DANCE (Bantam,
$23.95) are pretty amazing. They can tell at a glance which of the
550 extant Native American tribes a person belongs to, and they
know every inch of the tribal territories that span the Great Basin
region of Arizona, Nevada, Utah and California. Uninitiated
readers, however, might have some trouble distinguishing among the
Havasupai, the Chemehuevi and the Paiute -- or just figuring out
where they are in this involving but unfocused story.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody understands money, though, and we get the picture when
a string of mutilation-murders coincides with secret land deals
being struck by some shady Indian entrepreneurs for a multitribal
gambling casino. Emmett Parker, a weather-beaten Comanche
investigator for the Bureau of Indian Affairs, also sees the
connection, but his concern for a pretty rookie partner working
undercover as a casino dealer distracts him from deciphering the
cryptic message of the mutilations. (Let it be said that ``loss of
face'' has quite a different meaning for an Indian.) Although the
overplotted and overpopulated narrative doesn't give Emmett much
chance to examine his feelings about his mixed heritage, there are
plenty of strenuous treks through rugged terrain to show us what a
superb tracker he is -- and what a great guy to keep around for
next time.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an opening that gives away the killer and an ending
that flies over the top, JITTER JOINT (St. Martin's, $21.95) is a
fine, prickly first mystery from Howard Swindle, a Dallas newsman
with a nose for offbeat dramatic situations. Jeb Quinlin, a
homicide cop nursing an alcoholic death wish, is shanghaied by his
estranged wife and fed-up captain and packed off to ``whisky
school,'' occasioning some heartfelt writing in strong scenes set
on the detox ward and in the group therapy sessions run by a
sadistic psychiatrist. Midway through Jeb's treatment, someone
starts killing present and former patients of the Dallas clinic,
and the detective is yanked out of rehab to chase down this lunatic
before he gets to Jeb's new girlfriend -- or to Jeb himself.
Swindle's tensed-up style adapts well to the action scenes on the
outside, and Jeb shows the steel (and the right kind of cowboy
boots) to keep his macho image intact.
</P>
<P>
   Lovejoy, the cheeky hero of Jonathan Gash's exuberant comic
mysteries, is back on the con game in THE RICH AND THE PROFANE
(Viking, $22.95). Antiques dealer, restorer, forger and sometime
thief, this jack of rogues takes on yet another persona when he
impersonates a pop music impresario and produces a splashy variety
show on the English Channel island of Guernsey -- clever cover for
an ingenious art fraud that draws the suckers like flies. How
Lovejoy got to Guernsey is another funny story, which begins with
his chivalrous attempt to teach a young woman how to steal an
Edwardian necklace from an auction house and leads to the
inevitable schemes to ``rescue'' Chinese bronzes, Victorian cookie
tins, Rockingham pottery and other gorgeous goods from their
undeserving owners. After almost 20 years of doing business on the
dodgy side of the trade, Lovejoy is still a love and the joy he
brings to his work is undiminished.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
