<HEADER>
A4007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHONE-NYT &LR;      04-02 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC CHIEF'S LETTER RAISES CONCERN ON MERGER PLANS FOR AMERITECH AND
SBC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a rare public step, the chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission encouraged the Ameritech Corp. and SBC
Communications Inc. Friday to help draw up terms that would promote
competition so the commission would approve the companies' pending
$62 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   William E. Kennard, the FCC's chairman, said in a letter to the
chairmen of the two local telephone companies that ``at this stage,
I have serious concerns'' about whether the deal would serve the
public interest. But he gave no indication that he would prefer to
reject the merger outright, a move that many communications experts
continue to consider highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Kennard seemed to indicate that there was
no way that the commission would approve the deal without
conditions. Referring to the prospect of a drawn-out, adversarial
proceeding about the merger before an administrative law judge _ a
step the commission has not resorted to recently for a major merger
_ Kennard wrote, ``Among the actions which the commission could
take are to set your application for a full hearing or to approve
it with conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said the commission's staff wanted assurances that the
merger would not interfere with the companies' ability to open
their networks to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most surprising aspect of yesterday's letter was
that it was made public at all. People close to the commission said
Friday that the FCC traditionally had tried to shield its talks
with companies whose mergers it is considering from the light of
publicity, believing that privacy fosters candor.
</P>
<P>
   But that strategy has opened the commission to criticism in the
past. After the commission approved the 1997 merger of the Bell
Atlantic &UR;  &LR; Corp. and the Nynex Corporation subject to
pro-competition conditions that were negotiated largely in secret,
some of the commission's critics accused the FCC of using the
merger-review process as a tool to advance its regulatory agenda in
ways it could not otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive, perhaps, to those criticisms, Kennard seemed to want
to dispel any perception of the commission's merger-review process
as a mysterious ``black box.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department approved the Ameritech-SBC deal without
conditions last week. Some communications experts in Washington
said last night that it was unlikely that the FCC would sign off on
the merger, with conditions, before late summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity to put forth the many benefits of this
merger and to address the questions raised by the commission,''
said Lisa Kim, an Ameritech spokeswoman. ``The Justice Department
has found that the merger does not violate the antitrust laws and
we are confident that the FCC will approve this merger as well.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Another merger of phone giants ran into a stiffer rebuke Friday.
Virginia regulators rejected the merger petition of Bell Atlantic
and the GTE Corp., saying the companies did not provide enough
evidence that their deal would not hurt consumers. The companies
now have to provide more information to the regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
