<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LAVENDER-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 TALES OF THE LAVENDER MENACE
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Memoir of Liberation.
</P>
<P>
   By Karla Jay.
</P>
<P>
   Basic Books. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; OUT OF THE CLOSET AND INTO THE STREETS
</P>
<P>
   BY STACEY D'ERASMO
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It is a particular feature of being gay or lesbian that politics
and desire are intertwined. ``An army of lovers,'' goes the slogan,
``cannot fail,'' which may or may not be true, but it certainly
makes for a more interesting army. When we march, we cannot pretend
that it is in the service of some disembodied principle: our bodies
are on the line, literally. Since the coming of AIDS, that quality
has only intensified, but long ago, in the days just before and
after the Stonewall uprising in 1969, lesbians and gay men pursued
liberation with the fervor of homesteaders. They built a new world
out of themselves: their bodies, their desires, their flaws.
</P>
<P>
   One such revolutionary was Karla Jay, a more or less nice Jewish
girl from Brooklyn who graduated from Barnard College in 1968.
Though congenially leftist, in 1968 she was more concerned about
starting work on her doctorate; she had had female lovers, but she
had had male ones, too. She lived on the Upper West Side and had
two cats. ``Tales of the Lavender Menace'' is her memoir of the
relatively small slice of time -- 1968 to 1972 -- during which she
was transformed, like a Sapphic Cinderella, from an ordinary
bisexual college girl into a fabulous radical lesbian activist, a
veteran of consciousness-raising, demonstrations, media takeovers,
radical infighting, orgies and a dizzying rate of personal and
social change that evidently entailed having lots and lots of sex.
The doctorate-bound Karla Jayne Berlin who primly hoped, in 1968,
that the Columbia takeover ``would remain an isolated incident''
was by 1970 the self-named Karla Jay, who was planning with several
others to take over an entire California county and turn it into a
gay homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Like plants blooming in time-lapse photography, the legendary
radical feminist and gay liberation groups of the era bud, flower
and fade with tremendous rapidity: the Redstockings, Witch,
Radicalesbians, the Gay Liberation Front. Fully prepared to
overthrow everything on the planet in 1968, they were nearly all
extinct by 1970. Jay's calm descriptions of the often extraordinary
goings-on are duly inspiring, and not infrequently hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   From the feminist Ti-Grace Atkinson, who seriously counseled
celibacy until the revolution arrived, to the vigilant
cross-dresser at the first Gay Pride March in Los Angeles who
``planned to carry a rifle under his skirt,'' Jay and her fellow
travelers rarely met a wild-eyed prophet they didn't like.
Anything, to them, was possible. When Jay meets a man at a march
who is wearing ``nothing but a lacy pair of red underpants'' and
says he's the minister of the Psychedelic Venus Church, which
conducts orgies, her response is to go live with him for a while
and experience his interesting theology. But for her, too, the
utopian impulse passed. By 1972, Jay was back in graduate school,
co-editing (with Allen Young) the now-classic anthology ``Out of
the Closets: Voices of Gay Liberation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay generally strikes a fair-minded eyewitness-to-history pose,
but her deeper theme is the pleasure and sadness of mutability. She
exuberantly writes that after 1968 ``my former self was gone,
unrecognizable even to me.'' However, in the epilogue she confides
that today she feels ``little connection'' with the freewheeling
person who existed between 1968 and 1971. In flash-forward, we
learn that previously radical companions are now careerists or
crazy or dead. Jay herself is currently a professor of English at
Pace University, whose ``drugs of choice'' are Motrin and caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts of her rollicking past are thrown into poignant
relief by the book's memorial, recuperative feeling. ``History is
so precarious,'' she writes, ``it could hinge on one careless trip
to the laundry without first checking the contents of the pants
pockets.'' This, then, turns out to be the story of the radical who
saved what she found in her pockets, and wrote it all down.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Stacey D'Erasmo's first novel, ``Tea,'' will be published in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
