<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ELEGY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ELEGY FOR THE DEPARTURE
<TEXT>
<P>
   And Other Poems.
</P>
<P>
   By Zbigniew Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   The Ecco Press. $24.
 &UR; THE KING OF THE ANTS
</P>
<P>
   Mythological Essays.
</P>
<P>
   By Zbigniew Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   The Ecco Press. $22.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THE POET IN THE GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   BY RICHARD EDER
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1950's, when the Stalinism of Poland's Communist
government began to soften and exit papers became easier, a young
poet named Zbigniew Herbert traveled to France and Italy to visit
such monuments of Western art as Chartres and Amiens cathedrals,
the Lascaux caves, the hill towns of Tuscany and the rich
Renaissance remains across Provence and southwestern France. Armed
with an outdated Baedeker, Herbert was a starving man hurling
himself upon a feast.
</P>
<P>
   A gentle upbringing had been shattered when Herbert was 15 and
the Germans invaded. He spent the war years in the resistance. Then
came the abstract rhetoric of postwar Communism and the
constrictions of its concrete gray reality. It was like the
household of some meanly penitential pastor: all grace and no meal.
For a growing poet the starvation was less in the hunger than in
the grace's dead words.
</P>
<P>
   History shapes our language, and often by the law of unintended
consequences. The iron ideologies of the Soviet Union, along with
the real iron that enforced them, gave rise to a poetry of
extraordinary amplitude. Our own non-ideological amplitude, by
contrast, has tended to narrow poetry down, however accomplished.
``Truth'' and ``Beauty,'' a century and a half after the Romantics,
bear expired shelf-life labels and seem unsalable in our domestic
literary market. But some Russian, Polish and Czechoslovak poets --
in particular Osip Mandelstam and Herbert -- found a special genius
for making all but indistinguishable the line between the sublime
and the homely, the abstract and the material. If their writing is
oddly accessible to translation, perhaps it is owing to their
remarkable ability to name universals by naming particulars. (In
these new Herbert volumes, as in previous ones, John and Bogdana
Carpenter use the gift of plainness to render into English a poet
who was at once plain and polychrome -- notable, as Seamus Heaney
wrote, ``for the extremity and equanimity of his recognitions.'')
</P>
<P>
   Herbert's voracity in launching himself upon France and Italy
was expressed, with an irony that is never far from his passion, in
the title of the essay collection he wrote in the years following
-- ``Barbarian in the Garden.'' After the years of leaden rhetoric,
the voracity was still for ``Truth'' and ``Beauty'' -- but verified
now by the landscape, the architecture, the art, the sun. Older at
30 than many of us are at 50, Herbert also knew the blood that ran
beneath the beauty, and the destructive arrogance that truth
assumes. Heaney again: ``He has seen more broken columns with his
eyes than most literary people have seen in their imaginations.''
Above all (it is the rift out of which his poetry flowed), while
drawn to the soaring of large ideas, he knew how dumb and deadly
they turn when unmoored to the particular.
</P>
<P>
   In the poetry of the decades to follow he would write of
exterminations of all kinds -- of the spirit even more than the
body. He used allegorical satire with whiplash grace; the more
cutting because of its moments of forbearance. The essence of his
poetry, though, is something else: a small phrase with the
expansive radiation of a split atom.
</P>
<P>
   Two collections -- ``Elegy for the Departure'' and ``The King of
the Ants'' -- have been published in translation eight months after
Herbert died, perhaps an artery or two away from a Nobel. ``King of
the Ants'' is 11 prose variations on Greek myths, most of them
speaking out for the underdogs. There is a nice sketch of Atlas
forced to do the drudge work of holding up the heavens. As the gods
-- read the privileged -- would say, ``Someone must do it.'' It is
minor Herbert, on the whole, though the poet's wit and moral bite
are evident.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Elegy'' is major Herbert. Its four sections draw
chronologically from his early, middle and late writing. Some of
the short prose pieces in Part 3, written in the 1960's, seem
facile, even whimsical. Here and in several of the earlier poems it
is as if Herbert's cutting instrument were incising a substance
softer than his customary granite. Yet some of the poems written in
the 1950's remain memorable. They call up the rending losses of
war, but even here they do it not head on but by an examination of
small obliterations. Here, to a vanished (dead?) woman:
</P>
<P>
   you left an embrace like a superfluous sweater
</P>
<P>
   a look like a question
</P>
<P>
   our hands won't transmit the shape of your hands
</P>
<P>
   In another poem he depicts children playing, pigeons alighting
on a poet's statue. War comes:
</P>
<P>
   the children on our street
</P>
<P>
   had a difficult death
</P>
<P>
   pigeons fell lightly
</P>
<P>
   like shot down air
</P>
<P>
   That shot-down air: it is not just pigeons that war destroys but
the world.
</P>
<P>
   There are splendid poems in the middle sections; notably a
dialogue between a son and his father at the father's funeral. The
dead father worries about expense, about how the son will manage;
he tells him where money and jewels are squirreled away:
</P>
<P>
   this is how our dead
</P>
<P>
   look after us
</P>
<P>
   they warn us through dreams
</P>
<P>
   bring back lost money
</P>
<P>
   hunt for jobs
</P>
<P>
   whisper the numbers of lottery tickets
</P>
<P>
   or when they can't do this
</P>
<P>
   knock with their fingers on the
</P>
<P>
   windows
</P>
<P>
   The last section, written in the later years, contains some of
Herbert's most spacious work, a welling up of vitality and variety.
There is a tarantella of a poem about Tolstoy fleeing family and
keepers at the end ``with great bounds /
</P>
<P>
   his beard streaming behind.'' There is a somber, perfectly tuned
image of the Emperor Hirohito, history's wildness departed,
laboring over a
</P>
<P>
   tanka about the state railroad. There is the unsparingly
registered loss of ``Prayer of the Old Men'' -- ``when the children
women patient animals have left /
</P>
<P>
   because they can't bear wax hands . . . we listen to sand
pouring in our veins /
</P>
<P>
   and in our dark interior grows a white church /
</P>
<P>
   of salt memories calcium and unspeakable weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the majestic and intimately piercing testament of ``A
Journey,'' its Cavafy-like stoicism enjoining the willingness to
adventure, then to renounce and finally to depart:
</P>
<P>
   the clock stops and from now on hours are black white or blue
</P>
<P>
   they absorb the thought that you lose the lines of your face
</P>
<P>
   what answer can an eroded
</P>
<P>
   inscription give to thistles
</P>
<P>
   give back the empty saddle with no regret
</P>
<P>
   give the air back to another
</P>
<P>
   And there is the precise and expansive ``Elegy for the Departure
of Pen Ink and Lamp,'' in which he recalls the steel pen points of
his childhood:
</P>
<P>
   outlet of the critical mind
</P>
<P>
   messenger of soothing
</P>
<P>
   knowledge . . .
</P>
<P>
   in a box of the storekeeper
</P>
<P>
   you were like a fish waiting
</P>
<P>
   for me
</P>
<P>
   in a school of other fish . . .
</P>
<P>
   I put you respectfully in my mouth
</P>
<P>
   and for a long time felt on my tongue
</P>
<P>
   a taste
</P>
<P>
   of sorrel
</P>
<P>
   and the moon
</P>
<P>
   After recalling all the particulars that our world has lost, he
concludes that he has never trusted the spirit of history,
``dialectical beast on a leash led by slaughterers,'' or the ``Huns
of progress galloping over earthly and heavenly steppes.'' He has,
he says,
</P>
<P>
   very little left
</P>
<P>
   objects
</P>
<P>
   and compassion
</P>
<P>
   Drawing
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Richard Eder writes articles and book reviews for The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
