<HEADER>
A3986 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ELECTRICAL-NY     04-02 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ELECTRICAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE ELECTRICAL FIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Kerri Sakamoto.
</P>
<P>
   305 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   W. W. Norton &AMP; Company. $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; UNAVOIDABLY DETAINED
</P>
<P>
   BY ELIZABETH HANSOn
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THE internment of Japanese-Americans after the bombing of Pearl
Harbor has been written about widely, but Americans may not realize
that during the same period the Canadian Government sent more than
20,000 Japanese-Canadians to camps in the eastern sections of
British Columbia and to sugar beet farms in Manitoba and Alberta.
The injustice continued after the war, when internees were given
the choice of settling east of the Rockies or being deported to
war-ravaged Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Kerri Sakamoto's first novel, ``The Electrical Field,''
considers the effect
</P>
<P>
   of the internment and its aftermath through its portrayal of the
life of a middle-aged woman, Asako Saito, who settles in a bleak
suburb of Toronto after leaving the camp where she and her mother,
father and two brothers had been detained.
</P>
<P>
   The story, told by Miss Saito (as she is known to her
neighbors), is set in the 1970's; she lives in an old farmhouse at
the edge of a field filled with huge electrical towers, a
depressing contrast to the lovely coastal town in British Columbia
where she grew up. Miss Saito's mother and older brother have died,
and she spends her days caring for her bedridden father as well as
her younger brother, Stum. Nearby live other nihonjin, or
Japanese-Canadians, including Yano, who is trying to organize the
others to demand redress; his Hiroshima-born wife, Chisako; and a
wild young teen-ager, Sachi, and her mother, Keiko.
</P>
<P>
   As Miss Saito goes about her self-sacrificing daily routine, we
see her struggling with the ``sense I'd carried for as long as I
could remember, that I must look after everyone, as I had all my
life.'' She accepts her duty yet clearly resents it as well; she
must feed and change her father as if he were an infant -- the
father who in his younger days was often drunk and who beat her
beloved elder brother. Miss Saito focuses her maternal urges on
Sachi and even spies on the girl's sexual tumbles with Yano's son,
Tam. Loneliness is Miss Saito's constant companion, and she fears
losing Stum to his girlfriend, who is not nihonjin.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we learn that Chisako has been murdered, along with her
lover, Donaldson Spears. Much is made of the fact that Spears is a
hakujin, or white person, and that in the course of falling in
love, Chisako bloomed in a way that Miss Saito both envies and
fears. When Yano takes his two children and disappears, we are led
into the mystery of where they have gone and who killed Chisako. In
the process, we learn secrets about Miss Saito's past and the truth
about the death of her elder brother.
</P>
<P>
   Sakamoto, a Canadian of Japanese descent, clearly knows the
world Miss Saito inhabits. With virtuosity, she describes domestic
rituals like the washing of rice or the serving of green tea. And
she uses subtle images -- particularly shoes, removed to wlk
through damp grass or left on inside a neighbor's home -- to remind
us of the nuances of many Japanese customs. The characters'
conversations are filled with Japanese words, left unitalicized to
indicate how completely they have been incorporated into the
Japanese-Canadians' English. Sakamoto also conveys well the hatred
and suspicion Miss Saito and her neighbors feel for the white
world, their practice of hiding real feelings behind a cordial
exterior and their submission to the unrelenting force of a sense
of shame.
</P>
<P>
   Reading a novel with a first-person narrator is a bit like
strapping yourself into a seat next to a voluble stranger for a
transcontinental flight. You hope your seatmate has an interesting
story to tell, or at least an interesting way to tell a dull one.
Unfortunately, after spending time with the dour Miss Saito, some
readers might be tempted to put on their headphones and feign
sleep. She is a survivor, but not a plucky one. Her interactions
with the other characters sometimes seem melodramatic, and her
combination of resignation and neediness becomes annoying. Her
story, though suspenseful, can be confusing as well, since the
narrative moves back and forth between distant memories and events
in both the recent past and the present.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of ``The Electrical Field'' lies in its portrayal
of the world Miss Saito inhabits. It is a world in which the
enormous towers marching ``like giants past the houses'' are a
constant reminder of the powerful forces that restrict her -- just
as firmly as the fences of that wartime camp.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Hanson is the translator, with Yukiko Tanaka, of
``This Kind of Woman: Ten Stories by Japanese Women Writers,
1960-1976.'' She teaches Japanese at Seattle University.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
