NYT-04-02-99 1647EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3987 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-KINDNESS-NYTS     04-02 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-KINDNESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE KINDNESS OF CHILDREN
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Vivian Gussin Paley.
</P>
<P>
   129 pp. Cambridge, Mass.:
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University Press. $18.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; WHEN THEY WERE GOOD
</P>
<P>
   BY ANN HULBERT
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Learning by doing,'' John Dewey memorably taught Americans, is
children's way. The corollary -- that a teacher's day should be
full of ``doing by learning'' from her busy charges -- is a
progressive lesson that has proved harder to appreciate or to put
into practice. Teachers have nightmares of losing control and
collapsing in exhaustion if they truly let children's inventiveness
shape their curriculums. Principals and parents have visions of
monkeys taking over the zoo. Perhaps the rare teachers who do
manage to make every day at school an unpredictable yet purposeful
adventure in mutual education deserve to boast about it. Certainly
it is these progressive wonders who have written the most, and
often the best, accounts of the hubbub behind the classroom door
and the bureaucrats' abstract rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Gussin Paley has occupied a secure but comparatively
obscure place among a surprisingly male company of these American
teacher-writers. Herbert Kohl, Jonathan Kozol and Robert Coles,
among others, were earnest idealists who found wisdom among
schoolchildren in the late 1960's and promptly began producing
books about the experience. By now they have won near-guru status
as witnesses to the wisdom of innocence. Paley was busy teaching
then, too, but she didn't begin writing until the late 1970's, and
over the years she has kept a more modest profile. ``The Kindness
of Children,'' as the title reveals, marks her self-conscious bid
to join the inspirational preachers. If the book feels strained,
that only helps to highlight the secret of Paley's previous
success: she is not a moral proselytizer but a born teacher. And as
her earlier books prove, that is the loftier vocation in any case.
</P>
<P>
   Paley's distinctive canvas until now has been smaller in scale
than that of some of her socially crusading brethren. Her titles
convey the stay-at-home instincts of a teacher whose hearth (and
heart) is in her classroom: ``Boys and Girls: Superheroes in the
Doll Corner'' (1984), ``The Boy Who Would Be a Helicopter: The Uses
of Storytelling in the Classroom'' (1990), ``The Girl With the
Brown Crayon: How Children Use Stories to Shape Their Lives''
(1997). Paley's best known book is probably ``You Can't Say You
Can't Play'' (1992), named after the rule she debated with her
students and then posted in her kindergarten class at the
Laboratory School on the campus of the University of Chicago, where
she taught until her recent retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Paley has always known, and often worried, that her wonderful
little classroom is no microcosm of the real world. But she has
also been convinced that she has found a universal domain of
``fantasy and friendship'' in her doll corners, and above all on
the rug that has served as a stage for the ``story playing and
storytelling'' that have ``become the curriculum of any classroom
in which I am the teacher.'' For Paley has been a teacher with a
faith, not a lesson plan: a faith that through the shaping and
sharing of stories comes comprehension for children -- and comfort
and inspiration for them, and for her. ``Children do not pretend to
be storytellers; they are storytellers,'' she has written. ``It is
their intuitive approach to all occasions. It is the way they
think.''
</P>
<P>
   And it has become the way she thinks, too, turning her into a
writer as well as a teacher. Paley's method is to weave intimate
stories about her story-filled classroom. The vignettes that result
are ideally suited to her subject. Her classroom scenes, by
capturing with precision the 3-foot-high child's-eye view, bring
down to earth what risks sounding like a romantically sweeping
credo about salvation through narration. Actual kindergartners
swapping tales makes for more interesting and credible confusion
than that. In Paley's pages, the familiar chatter of childhood
becomes a quilt, scrappy but well sewn together, of journeys into a
world that bewilders but also beckons children to join it.
</P>
<P>
   Paley has long and admirably resisted touting the tales as
therapeutic exercises. Nor does she render pat diagnoses of, say,
the girl who always tells the mother-baby stories, the boy who
specializes in bad guys, much less the boy who is a helicopter all
day long. Her restraint has made her a teacher's writer rather than
a pontificator or a prescriber. Whether she homes in on a troubled
child like Jason the Helicopter, or on a charismatic leader like
Reeny, whose passion for the children's author and artist Leo
Lionni swept up an entire class for a year, Paley peddles no cures
or easy miracles. Her tireless curiosity (she writes down stories,
tapes them, transcribes the tapes and mulls over the results) has
gone hand in hand with humility. ``Clearly,'' she concedes on
plenty of days, ``we do not understand most of what motivates the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Kindness of Children,'' however, Paley has succumbed to
the temptation to hold forth as ``something besides a
schoolteacher,'' and has taken a spiritual rather than a clinical
turn. She borrows her epigraph from Rabbi Yehuda Nisiah -- ``The
moral universe rests upon the breath of schoolchildren'' -- and
proposes a kinship between her reliance on storytelling and the
Hasidic tradition of inspiring virtue by spreading tales of holy
men ``performing mitzvot, good deeds.'' She herself professes
surprise at her impulse to stray from ``the secular classroom'' and
its language, wondering, ``Have I moved to a new place where
Scripture motivates the discourse?'' But as that slightly arch
question suggests, she is not displeased by her new grandiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what Paley is really peddling is a kind of self-help
simplicity -- an ``All You Need to Know You Learned in
Kindergarten'' with a progressive education. In place of Robert
Fulghum's hokey, heartwarming ``notions,'' as he calls his parables
about ordinary life, she has packaged together soul-strengthening
tales from unusual classrooms. Gone are the daily minutiae, the
jostle of small bodies and distinctive personalities that helped
show how stories can work to draw a class together and lead
children out of loneliness, not forever but for part of a day.
(When the Girl Who Would Be a Mommy gets Jason to forget his
whirring blades and be her baby, the drama is more stirring for
happening so quietly amid the daily commotion.) In ``The Kindness
of Children'' Paley instead showcases a collection of much more
polished gems about children's ``spontaneous acts of goodness,''
which she has gathered and retold as she goes about her emeritus
career of lecturing and visiting schools.
</P>
<P>
   The tales in themselves are often quite moving -- the paraplegic
boy radiant at being included in a pretend game of ``store''; the
tough boy who whispers saving advice to a child on the brink of
collapse; the girl who is suddenly overwhelmed with a feeling of
generosity on a crowded bus. But Paley's insistence on the
momentous significance of being deeply moved by the tales, as she
claims her audiences are, can't help make the scenes of story
sharing seem stagy and self-congratulatory. Where once she crouched
and listened on the rug, now she soars to the clouds, proclaiming
one cooperative moment ``a great and mysterious event,'' another
instant of bonding ``a work of art.'' Her mission, she now
discovers, is God's: ``To give someone a role to play -- a lost
baby, the suffering mother, the virtuous sibling -- is akin to
offering new life to a wandering soul. If this feels like a
spiritual moment, why not call it that?''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Paley briefly senses that she has perhaps failed
to appreciate the potential for facile uplift in her endeavor. ``It
does not occur to me that this new role I've given myself proceeds
too smoothly. No longer am I tested each day as I was in the
classroom. There it was quite impossible to cover my mistakes;
here, upon this podium, the illusion of virtue comes easily.'' Her
zeal for ``good'' stories has meant that she skirts over dark ones,
she realizes with discomfort as an audience of adults recounts
memory after memory of childhood cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   But she is rescued from this confrontation with the limits of
her inspirational morality by a surge of sentimentality. ``The rock
upon which the moral universe depends'' is to be found in
children's narrative play, Paley declares, exulting that ``these
spontaneous storytellers create little homes for one another where
everyone can imagine playing a role and no one is left out.'' Yet
children are also ``passionately pedantic literalists,'' as Lionel
Trilling once pointed out. By kindergarten they have already
discovered that conquering fears and finding true companionship
rarely follow the storybook course they act out on the rug. They
have told their teacher that, and much more, over the years, and
she always listened -- until her turn came to do most of the
talking.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Ann Hulbert is the author of ``The Interior Castle: The Art and
Life of Jean Stafford.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
