<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3988 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MONICA-NYTSF     04-02 1677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MONICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MONICA'S STORY
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Andrew Morton.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 288 pp. New York
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THAT WOMAN
</P>
<P>
   BY MICHAel Oreskes
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For those who argue that American culture is collapsing in on
itself, hollowed out by self-indulgence and narcissism, ``Monica's
Story'' will be an original source document. To say that the basic
plot is now familiar, overly familiar, would be, to quote Barbara
Walters in a related context, the understatement of the year. But
in this fairy tale retelling by Andrew Morton, whose best-known
previous Lifetime Channel treatment was the biography of Diana,
Princess of Wales, one factor emerges: the complete absence of
grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   No one, not Monica, not her dueling parents or her enabling
aunt, and certainly not the president of the United States, ever
says no and means it. The words ``self-worth'' and ``self-esteem''
are sprinkled through this text. But no one seems to talk about
responsibility or consequences or discipline until Monica looks
back at the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not blaming him for what happened,'' she says of her
boyfriend-in-chief, ``but it was just too much. It was too much of
an emotional burden for someone my age. If I had really understood
everything I would have seen him more as a president than a man,
and I would have realized the ramifications of ever telling anybody
about it.'' Remarkably, she still doesn't regret kissing, only
telling Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   For those who were hoping we would learn something new, not just
about Monica but about Bill Clinton, there are only teases here. If
you followed this saga as a soap opera, as I did, there are few
fresh details, and none you won't have read about already. If you
followed it as a constitutional crisis (I'm enough of a
compartmentalizer to include myself here, too), the insights are
mostly obvious, or wrong. For all the ink that has been spilled in
the past year, there is still reason to want to read a book-length
treatment by someone with direct access to the participants. The
story has left us with some substantial questions unresolved, and I
do not just mean why she didn't destroy the dress (she kept it,
uncleaned, in large part out of a characteristic slovenliness,
Morton argues).
</P>
<P>
   For a generation now, politicians and journalists have been
wrestling with how to measure and describe the importance of
something called character in choosing a leader and what role, if
any, private behavior has in predicting public conduct. Jack
Kennedy was lionized, but Ted Kennedy and Gary Hart were judged
unfit for the top office. The country ``knew'' who Bill Clinton was
in some subliminal way. But is the lesson of the Lewinsky matter
that more attention should have been paid to the state of his
marriage and his treatment of women? Or, in effect, is that exactly
the proposition that the country after a year of torment has
rejected? This is an important subject, and a pressing one, as Al
Gore, George W. Bush and the rest ready their runs to succeed
Clinton. What questions should be asked, what standards applied to
these men, and women, who would be president?
</P>
<P>
   There were warning signs with Clinton, and he proved utterly
reckless. But while he was a reckless man, to borrow Monica
Lewinsky's distinction, he has been a highly cautious and
relatively conservative president, to the repeated frustration of
the Democratic Party's traditional base. So perhaps his private
character tells us little of his public life.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, his manifest disability with the truth is
noted by Monica here just as it has been noted in his public life.
She is far from the only one to feel betrayed at some point or
other: Democrats saved Clinton for their own good, and perhaps for
the country's, not because they like or trust him.
</P>
<P>
   Long before we had ever heard of Monica S. Lewinsky, Mario M.
Cuomo, a character study in his own right, told me that Clinton's
inability to resist women was a reflection of a core weakness that
could be seen in many aspects of his life. My own encounters have
left the impression of a politician more interested in winning a
visitor's smile than respect for raising a tough issue between
them. ``He reminded me of my mom,'' Lewinsky says of Clinton,
``because like her, he was an ostrich, putting his head in the sand
because he didn't like confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of adult supervision does not seem to be quite the
point Morton set out to make when he takes us through Monica's
growing up in Beverly Hills. She was a willful 2-year-old. But most
2-year-olds are willful. What is striking is how she always got
what she wanted. No, Monica, the reader wants to scream, you cannot
stay in the swing after dark. No, Monica, you cannot cut the
sleeves off that dress. No, Monica, you cannot cavort with the
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, an oncologist, appears as the self-acknowledged Dr.
No who tries to insist that Monica have a modest, religiously
appropriate bat mitzvah instead of a Beverly Hills extravaganza.
But her mother takes Monica's side, the extravaganza is held, and
soon thereafter her father has an affair with his nurse and leaves
the scene, only to reappear after the scandal breaks as what Monica
calls her ``rock of Gibraltar.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton's neo-Hegelian view suggests that history is shaped by
eating disorders. This was the case for both Diana and Monica, he
notes (although not as far as we know for another of his subjects,
Daniel arap Moi, the president of Kenya for two decades now). And
he reports an exchange in which Clinton seems to pour out his inner
pain over having been a pudgy kid. ``Monica came to know the man
behind the public mask, a flawed figure riddled with doubt and
wrestling with guilt, yet emotionally needy, vulnerable and
ultimately alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps she did, but we really don't. Despite her privileged
perch, Monica via Morton offers us little new insight into this
contradictory figure. For someone so infatuated by a president, she
seems utterly naive and generally uninterested in the work of
government. Matters of state pass in the background, important only
for how they affect her ability to see or talk on the telephone to
Handsome. She stops for not a sentence to ponder that the budget
collision and ensuing Government shutdown, which created the
opportunity for their first tryst, was also the start of Clinton's
political revival.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of an American soldier in Bosnia comes across in
Morton's retelling as grist for an emotive come-on line: '' 'You
have no idea what a gift it is to me to get to spend time with you
and talk to you,' he told her. 'I cherish that time we spend
together. It's very lonely here and people don't really understand
that.' Misty-eyed with emotion, and with the news of the American
soldier's death fresh in his mind, he went on to tell her about the
difficult decisions he had to make. 'I've been sick about it,' he
said. 'It's really hard to know that someone died because of your
executive order.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Morton seems not to have thought very deeply about the meanings
of his story. He takes a variety of broad and not very
discriminating swipes at ``the mass media'' when what is really
interesting are the fault lines and schisms that this past year has
revealed. He condemns Kenneth Starr repeatedly and judges George
Orwell right: ``The story of the intern and the president
illustrates how easily the modern high-tech state can dissect and
destroy not only individuals, but the basic building block of
society, the family.'' Setting aside Monica's own disregard for
Clinton's family, the threat from an overzealous prosecutor
predates the Internet age (see: Hugo, Victor, Novelist). The more
interesting thought to have emerged from this past year is not, as
Morton argues, that Orwell was right but that Aldous Huxley was
right. The real danger is not from the concentrated power of the
state but from the diffusion of media voices so cacophonous and
filled with trivia that they drown out everything more important
for a civil society to function.
</P>
<P>
   Morton's portrait of Monica's life inside the media frenzy has
moments of fascination. She sits obsessively in front of her
television watching her own life and love affair dissected,
discussed and debated. The woman who formed her image of family
life from ``The Brady Bunch'' honed her legal thinking by watching
``Burden of Proof.'' At one point, incognito, she takes a cousin on
a sightseeing tour of Venice Beach, Calif. A woman walks up to her
and says, ``You look just like Monica Lewinsky, only thinner.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is clearly a rush job, thus a testament to modern
culture. Getting it out quickly, to capture the lucrative but
perhaps fleeting moment, produced many errors, both typographical
and substantive. Henry Hyde, for example, is not a senator and Newt
Gingrich was not a member of the Judiciary Committee. Monica
Lewinsky and the people around her made a lot of bad judgments. But
when they released this book they distributed it to bookstores
before letting reviewers have it. That meant some reviews,
including this one, did not appear until the book had been on sale
for weeks. That was smart.
</P>
<P>
   There is still an important book to be written by someone with
political insight into what this past year teaches us about the
connection between character and leadership. Perhaps it was unfair
to think this might have been that book. If she's not running for
the Senate, maybe Hillary Rodham Clinton will write it for us.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Michael Oreskes is the Washington bureau chief of The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
