<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MERWIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE RIVER SOUND
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poems.
</P>
<P>
   By W. S. Merwin.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf. $23.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; POETIC JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   BY MELANIE REHAK
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Poets, by nature, are incapable of living the unexamined life.
No detail is too small, no sound in the night too muffled, to
register. From this gradual accumulation of minutiae, this keen
awareness, poems emerge. That such gathering should be evident in
W. S. Merwin's latest contribution to his enormous body of work is
no surprise -- he's had a great deal of practice, not to mention
success, over the past five decades. Beginning with the Yale
Younger Poets Award in 1952, Merwin has received almost every
poetic honor available in this country and has published dozens of
books of poetry, prose and translations. But despite his post at
the Academy of American Poets and his stewardship of the Yale
Younger Poets competition, he remains largely apart from public
literary life. Instead, he lives in Hawaii, far from the fray. He
tends his garden of native palm trees, and he listens.
</P>
<P>
   What he hears, however, has changed in timbre, if not in tone,
over the years. Even as a young man, Merwin wrote poems in the
elegiac mode. He communicated, in book after book, a sense of the
ordinary grieving that accompanies daily life -- missed
opportunities, fiery political and personal defeats (he opposed the
Vietnam War and has long been an environmentalist), the frustration
of failing to capture a poem that deigned to show a glimpse of
itself: ``Coming late, as always, /
</P>
<P>
   I try to remember what I almost heard,'' Merwin wrote in his
1963 collection, ``The Moving Target.'' All this was backlit by a
greater kind of agony, a haunted quality brought on by a history of
deaths in the family, starting with Merwin's maternal grandparents,
who died early, leaving Merwin's mother an orphan, and a brother
who was born and died before Merwin's own birth in 1927. He
wrestled with these ghosts; at times they dragged him away from the
present with which he was so urgently involved.
</P>
<P>
   But age brings with it a desire to review one's life and,
perhaps more important, to make sense of it. Now that Merwin has
reached his early 70's, the long-gone family members have settled,
for the most part, into a larger continuum of ancient voices.
They're just one part of a past that reaches back over eras and
that Merwin unravels in ``Testimony,'' the cornerstone of ``The
River Sound.'' The poem is part history of loss, part last will and
testament. At the outset, the poet is rightly concerned about the
wisdom of his undertaking: ``I am not certain as to how /
</P>
<P>
   the pain of learning what is lost /
</P>
<P>
   is transformed into light at last.'' But nonetheless he attempts
precisely this transformation, laying out narratives of his
childhood, his parents' lives and deaths, his grandparents' deaths
and his older brother's few short minutes on earth. Then he holds
forth on his current marriage and the subsequent happiness of his
later years.
</P>
<P>
   When the poem, which runs nearly 60 pages, isn't telling a
story, it offers up observations -- much like those found in many
of the book's short poems -- on the arbitrary nature of language
and on the vastness of the time-space continuum, and it provides
reports from the existential front, such as
</P>
<P>
   we see the comet
</P>
<P>
   in the northwest as the stars come
</P>
<P>
   saying the name we have for it
</P>
<P>
   now which is nothing like its name
</P>
<P>
   in lost languages
</P>
<P>
   and ``under this roof I listened to /
</P>
<P>
   the singing of their ancestors /
</P>
<P>
   forbears these voices never knew.'' Merwin takes his time
considering the dead and the living, and he devotes extra space to
his wife, whom he adores and with whom he marvels at
</P>
<P>
   the way our days together
</P>
<P>
   suddenly are there behind us
</P>
<P>
   ours still but somewhere else before
</P>
<P>
   we believed they were leaving us
</P>
<P>
   or understood how they could go
</P>
<P>
   like that.
</P>
<P>
   When he eventually gets around to bequeathing things --
particular moments and qualities of light on certain street corners
-- to various friends and relatives, there isn't much he's left
out, and probably a lot he could have. The family chronicles are
evocative, and it's clear that the poem serves a cathartic purpose
for its author. But the endless amazement at the universe wears a
bit thin; by revisiting his awe so frequently, Merwin lessens it
somewhat for his readers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, ``Testimony'' is moving in its earnestness and in
the scope of its endeavor. It is especially affecting when
considered alongside another poem here, ``Lament for the Makers.''
Where ``Testimony'' deals with family, ``Lament for the Makers''
gives credence to the burden that every poet carries, the
responsibility of being part of another kind of history. There are
memories to be kept alive, and Merwin does his duty with love.
Dylan Thomas, Sylvia Plath, Louis MacNeice, W. H. Auden, Robert
Lowell, Howard Nemerov and Elizabeth Bishop, among others, step
forth to be acknowledged, or just step forth. These are the poets
Merwin grew up with, in a sense, many of whom departed early. ``One
by one they have all gone,'' he writes,
</P>
<P>
   out of the time and language we
</P>
<P>
   had in common which have brought me
</P>
<P>
   to this season after them
</P>
<P>
   the best words did not keep them from
</P>
<P>
   leaving themselves finally
</P>
<P>
   as this day is going from me.
</P>
<P>
   And neither will the best words keep Merwin from leaving,
something he seems to know quite well. Much of ``The River Sound''
is given over to worrying about the failure of words -- so much so
that at times it's tempting to skip ahead and see if he comes up
with any answers. Perhaps it's that Merwin wants to settle the old
debts to confusion and ignorance that we all have before it's too
late. But really, he's performing what James Merrill knew was the
most important task of all, taking care of the ``need to make some
kind of house /
</P>
<P>
   Out of the life lived, out of the love spent.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Rehak is a freelance writer and poet. Her work has
appeared in Partisan Review and The New Republic. bk109 h07 1088
03-29 11:47 tii-z re MERWIN 933783 1066 1999 04 04
</P>
