<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BARNEYS-NYTSF     04-02 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BARNEYS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE RISE AND FALL OF THE HOUSE OF BARNEYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Joshua Levine.
</P>
<P>
   William Morrow &AMP; Company. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; SHIRTSLEEVES TO SHIRTSLEEVES
</P>
<P>
   BY JENNIFER STEINHAUER
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There are three kinds of people who might find a book about
Barneys New York, the store that began as a men's discount suit
outlet and eventually grew to serve cafe society, a ``must read.''
The first kind is the fashionistas themselves, who might revel in a
comprehensive chronicle of, for instance, how the designer Azzedine
Alaia decided which stores he wanted to sell his trendy goods to in
the 1980's. Then there are those who are truly interested in the
retail industry and all its corporate finance and marketing
trickery. Finally, there are the six or seven people who are dying
for a heaping dish of dirt on Gene Pressman, one of the two
grandsons of the store's founder, who helped drive the business
both to the top of fashion's radar screen and into financial ruin.
Joshua Levine may be a member of all three groups, but none of them
are particularly well served by ``The Rise and Fall of the House of
Barneys,'' which details the history of the store, its fall from
grace three years ago and the wheeling and dealing that eventually
led to its salvation, its founding family's visions of greatness
and role considerably scaled down.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion followers will enjoy the anecdotes about Fred Pressman,
Barney's son, and his obsessions with the finding the perfect
glove. But their eyes will surely glaze over the endless pages of
financial data, which include dense details on eight months of
short-term loans and constant references to gross margins and net
earnings. Close followers of the retail industry might appreciate
the details of accounting games, as well as the tale of how the
store came to dominate a small segment of the luxury market. But
much of this, alas, has been reported before. And the handful of
people who actually care about the sex lives, personal grooming
habits and less-than-charming peccadillos of the Pressman siblings
will here find only a soupcon of detail, ranging from the mildly
interesting (who knew that Gene had such a great golf game?) to the
vulgar, unattributed and not terribly illuminating.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one wonders how Levine became so obsessed with his topic. No
doubt about it, Barneys' bankruptcy filing in 1966 caused the
fashion world to teeter nervously on its spiked heels. And the
Pressman family has been a colorful one; Barney Pressman was one of
the true great New York garment merchants, and his store was the
destination for men's wear bargain seekers in the second quarter of
the century. His son, Fred, and his grandson Gene have been
credited with discovering many an important design talent and for
having the smarts to begin selling women's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of the day, Barneys is no Neiman Marcus, no Saks
Fifth Avenue, not even, in terms of importance to American retail,
a Sears, Roebuck. Although Barney Pressman founded the store in
1923, roughly the same time Neiman set up shop, it was not until
the late 1980's that Barneys branched out in the city and around
the country, bankrolled by the Isetan Company of Japan, with which
it would bitterly part in the 1996 bankruptcy proceedings. The Saks
name is known in the nation's remotest reaches, while Barneys plays
splendidly well on both coasts, and that is about where it ends.
Few working men can get away with the sorts of cutting-edge
fashions the store carries, and few women can afford or fit into a
size 6 from an avant-garde European atelier.
</P>
<P>
   Barneys' Chapter 11 filing and flirtations with foreign buyers
drew attention from the news media not because of the store's
importance in the global retail world but because of what it had
come to symbolize. With roughly $350 million a year in sales, it
was a speck of dust on, say, the floor of Wal-Mart, but its fancy
brands, celebrity following and chic black shopping bags were all
part of something profoundly New York. See a picture in In Style
magazine of some Hollywood confection doing her shopping? She is
probably walking out of Barneys. Hear of cool new cosmetics line?
It may be available only in Barneys. Tall woman, good haircut,
expensive shoes, job on Seventh Avenue? Barneys shopper.
</P>
<P>
   This book is at its best when it captures some of that excess.
Look here for the details of Barneys' expansion to Madison Avenue
in 1993, which included decorating an entire department of the new
store with goatskin and laying Carrara marble tile by tile into the
center of the main floor. Read about buying trips to Europe, where
characters out of a modern-day ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' run about
in crazy outfits buying fabulous clothes. Confirm all your deeply
held suspicions about the markup on the clothes and the disdain the
help has often shown for its customers.
</P>
<P>
   But there are irritating lapses in the narrative. Connie Darrow,
for instance, who was the general merchandise manager in women's
apparel, is described in great detail. Then, one day, she is simply
gone. Darrow in fact ended up at Prada, but you never learn that
here. There is also something slightly odd in Levine's emotional
investment in his subject. While Levine, a senior editor at Forbes,
seems charmed with Barney and Fred Pressman and their legacies,
this sentiment is matched with an intense distaste for the youngest
Pressman boys, Bob and Gene, who were until recently co-chief
executives of the company (Gene is constantly called arrogant and
spoiled). Yet tales of family infighting, bitter personal acrimony
and reckless spending are only too common in family businesses,
especially, it seems, when the business is retail.
</P>
<P>
   If the story of Barneys' bankruptcy is more than a footnote in
the history of 20th-century retailing, then Levine may just have
cornered himself a market. But the fact that a family -- enthralled
by the deep pockets of Japanese investors -- built a hih-end
clothing mini-empire, took their show on the road and flopped,
fighting all the way over whose fault it was, is not the ``Yiddish
theater Euripedes'' that he claims. So there are fewer Barneys
stores now than there were a few years ago. The Pressman brothers
have had their wings clipped. Vulture investors now more or less
own the company. This is not the stuff of tragedy. It's really just
business.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Steinhauer, a metropolitan reporter for The Times,
covered the retail industry, including Barneys, from 1995 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
