<HEADER>
A3993 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SOPRANOS-NYTS     04-02 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SOPRANOS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 The Sopranos
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Alan Warner.
</P>
<P>
   324 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $24.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; CHOIRGIRLS
</P>
<P>
   BY CHARLes Taylor
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If the Scottish novelist Alan Warner weren't so gloomy, he might
be a profanely raucous farceur. There are moments in Warner's third
novel, ``The Sopranos,'' when all hell feels ready to break loose.
The title refers to the teen-age choir members of Our Lady of
Perpetual Succour School for Girls. At large for a day in the big
city while they wait to represent their school at a national
singing competition, the five girls do everything they can to bring
disgrace upon it in the meantime. Already noodle-kneed from the
spiked soda they swig on the bus ride down, Orla, Manda, Kylah,
Chell (for Rachel) and Fionnula hit the city just in time to
receive Warner's blasphemous version of a sign from above. Looking
out the window of their rehearsal room, they see a couple
unashamedly having sex in broad daylight. Welcome to the promised
land.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of ``The Sopranos'' follows the girls' pilgrimages to
the shrines of pubs and McDonald's and French Connection as they
seek the sacraments of booze, clothes and sex. The ostensible
reason for their trip -- the singing competition -- is treated by
them as no more than an annoyance. The girls just want it to be
over in time to get back to their port town and hook up with the
submarine crew who are sure to be frequenting the local disco, the
aptly named Mantrap.
</P>
<P>
   The most likable thing about Alan Warner is that he's on the
side of these girls. It's refreshing to read a novel loaded down
with teen-age drinking, smoking, swearing and the urge for sex
(more than sex itself) and be spared the moralizing that usually
goes along with these activities. He's amused by his unholy choir,
but he also knows how important a Big Mac, or a new pair of Doc
Martens or a shot of flaming Sambuca is to them, and he refuses to
condescend. There's nothing new about the tribalism inherent in
their rituals, like the way they all crowd into the ladies' room at
McDonald's to trowel on makeup, and to swap their school uniforms
for too-short skirts, Wonderbras and platform shoes. But their
back-and-forth dialogue, with each interjection scrambling madly
over every other, captures both the vitality and the deadly
seriousness of their preparations.
</P>
<P>
   As a writer whose own sensibility has been formed by rock
culture (his novels are loaded with references to songs and bands),
Warner is predisposed to sympathize with the hellions and
troublemakers, even if that causes him to caricature the book's
adult authority figures, like the nun Sister Condron (inevitably
called Sister Condom). He understands that pop culture and consumer
culture are predicated on a promise of freedom, of release from
everything that's dutiful, drab and ordinary. He honors these
girls' belief that the freedom they seek is waiting for them in
purchasing a new skirt, buying another round of drinks, sleeping
with the next boy, even if he knows that belief is an illusion. Not
knowing it's an illusion is what keeps the sopranos in a state of
disreputable grace. Warner is in love with the idea of youth
itself, and pained by how fleeting it is. Early on he writes of his
quintet: ``They've youth; they'll walk it out like a favorite pair
trainers. It's a poem this youth and why should they know it, as
the five of them move up the empty corridors? We should get shoved
aside cause they have it now, in glow of skin and liquid clarity of
deep eye on coming June nights and cause it will go . . . After all
what do we amount to but a load of old worn-out shoes?''
</P>
<P>
   But hopelessness is a different thing from melancholy, and the
sense that there's nothing but hopelessness waiting for these girls
assumes a greater hold as the book goes on. ``The Sopranos'' takes
place in the same desperate, shabby port town as Warner's first
novel, ``Morvern Callar.'' In that book, the divide between young
and old didn't feel quite so great, largely because the heroine, in
her mid-20's, was beginning to recognize her own fate in the
fag-end lives of her elders, the endless work and worry about money
relieved only by nights at the pub. Warner still hasn't solved the
problems that dogged ``Morvern Callar,'' chiefly the inevitable
capitulation of character to the intractable forces of society. We
want something better for the strong, back-talking heroines he
creates than the bleak, numbed-out lives he appears to think are
their only prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Warner is also still prone to the sort of showy grotesque
episodes that the most famous current Scottish writer, Irvine
Welsh, tries to pass off as evidence of his transgressive refusal
to compromise. There's an unfortunate extended episode in which one
of the girls attempts to have sex with a terminally ill young man
in his hospital bed. And as soon as Warner mentions an animal, you
can be sure it will die a horrible death. The unexpected problem in
``The Sopranos'' is a sort of creeping sentimentality. Warner seems
to be buying sympathy for his characters by revealing that one has
cancer and one comes from a home so poor the family can afford only
one tub of hot water on bath nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' is as different from the book that preceded it,
``These Demented Lands'' (a novel whose hallucinatory prose recalls
William S. Burroughs and which has the feel of a sinister, vaguely
medieval bacchanal) as that book was from ``Morvern Callar.''
Warner is admirably nonrepetitive. He's also one of the most
frustrating talented writers around. ``The Sopranos'' finds his
strengths still waiting to overcome his weaknesses. Warner's
portrait of squalid Scottish port town life is grimly believable.
Too believable. He needs to take the leap of faith one of his
heroines does when she kisses the girl she has a crush on in full
view of her friends as the lights go up in the Mantrap. The
conviction Warner puts into that relationship, the implicit belief
that the chance the girls are taking is worth courting the
small-town gossip they'll face, belies his implicit message that
the promise of youth must inevitably be snuffed out. Warner's not
listening to all that his characters say. If you want to know where
that promise is in ``The Sopranos,'' it's in her kiss.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Charles Taylor is critic at large for the Internet magazine
Salon.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
