<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3997 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CLINTON-NYTSF     04-02 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CLINTON-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 Uncovering Clinton: A Reporter's Story.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Isikoff.
</P>
<P>
   402 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Crown Publishers. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; ALL THE PRESIDENT'S WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   BY TOM GOLDSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If such a thing is possible, Michael Isikoff may be an
investigative reporter too tenacious, too eager and too focused for
his own good. What so marks the changed media landscape of
Washington in the 1990's is that Isikoff's formidable reporting,
not the publication of his work, became the engine that drove the
story of President Clinton's sexual indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   Just knowing that he was making inquiries affected the behavior
of key participants, both inside and outside the White House. From
grand jury testimony released last fall, it is clear that Kenneth
Starr, the Paula Jones legal team and even the President himself
made decisions based on what they knew or suspected about what
Isikoff knew. By mid-January 1998, as the Monica Lewinsky affair
became public knowledge, Isikoff was so deeply enmeshed in the
various stings and plots and investigations that, he writes in
``Uncovering Clinton,'' his how-I-got-the-story book, ``almost
anything I did was going to dramatically change the events I was
trying to cover.'' Isikoff, in other words, was so far ahead of his
competitors that he became part of the story. And it is one of the
ironies of his substantial career that he was scooped on his
biggest exclusives.
</P>
<P>
   While still at The Washington Post in 1994, he delved deeply
into Paula Jones's allegations that Bill Clinton, then Governor of
Arkansas, had asked her for sex in a Little Rock hotel room.
Isikoff bristled at the slow, careful editing of the story. After
shouting at an editor, he was suspended for insubordination. His
suspension was covered in The Washington Times, and conservative
groups took out advertisements, including some in The Post itself,
demanding that the paper publish his findings. Shortly after his
story was published, Isikoff departed for Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   There, in 1997, he was working on a story that Clinton had
harassed Kathleen Willey, but before it appeared, Matt Drudge, the
Internet gossip columnist, reported that Isikoff had been holding
back on publishing just such an item.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for many months Isikoff knew, from Linda Tripp, of the
liaison between Clinton and a young White House intern. When he was
ready at last to publish news of Starr's investigation into whether
Clinton had an affair with Monica Lewinsky and obstructed justice
by trying to cover it up, his superiors at Newsweek showed
admirable caution on deadline and held up publication. Isikoff was
scooped again by Drudge and then by his former colleagues at The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, it has been Isikoff who has received the
credit -- or blame -- for ferreting out the unappealing hidden side
of the President.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncovering Clinton'' sets out in lucid, largely chronological
fashion how he got his stories. He forcefully defends his behavior,
which has come under attack from other journalists and Clinton
partisans. It is hard to render an absolute verdict on the
propriety of his actions based just on his book, for it decidedly
presents one (admittedly one unusually knowledgeable) person's
version of reality. But Isikoff makes a plausible case -- perhaps
the best case that could be made -- for continuing to pursue a
story that could possibly have brought down a President. At times,
as he acknowledges, sometimes directly, sometimes opaquely, Isikoff
became too immersed in his story.
</P>
<P>
   Books in which reporters take center stage are a special genre.
In ``All the President's Men,'' Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein
describe a colleague: ``She knew that she was about to become part
of the story -- a situation that is congenitally distressing to
reporters.'' As it was to Isikoff, who was ``inspired'' by Woodward
and Bernstein as a college student (he does not say where he
studied, one of the many details about his personal life that the
reader doesn't learn). He expresses dismay, even bewilderment,
about his role. In the course of tracking down the Willey story, he
discovered that the President knew he was working on it long before
it was ready for publication. Isikoff remembers wondering, ``What
in God's name was I in the middle of?'' Several months later, as
Linda Tripp and Lucianne Goldberg tried to orchestrate Clinton's
downfall using Isikoff as their vehicle, he began, he says, ``for
the first time really, to feel strange myself about what was going
on -- and what I was doing.'' He realized something ``that should
have been apparent much earlier: I was in the middle of a plot to
get the President.'' Like Woodward and Bernstein, who freely
acknowledged their mistakes and their ethical lapses, Isikoff
confesses to error and to crossing the line of proper reporting
while trying to negotiate ``treacherous and uncharted territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Isikoff is particularly proud that he declined to listen to the
Tripp-Lewinsky tapes while Tripp was still taping. He was offered
the opportunity months before Starr had even heard of Lewinsky,
but, he writes, he did not want to ``become part of the
process.''Had he agreed to listen, he says, ``for all intents and
purposes, I would have been writing Tripp's script. I would have
become her partner in the betrayal of Lewinsky.'' Shortly
thereafter, he chides himself for advising both Tripp and Lucianne
Goldberg that it would be ``really stupid'' to peddle a book by
Tripp because she ``would only have to testify about it.'' At this
point, he says he realized, he was ``too involved to avoid
influencing the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in recounting a tense standoff with Jackie Bennett,
Starr's chief Washington deputy, Isikoff sounds more inquisitor
than reporter. Bennett, Isikoff says, wanted Newsweek to hold off
on the story of the special prosecutor's Lewinsky investigation in
return for ``an even better story down the road.'' This is how
Isikoff recalls the conversation: ``We need to know everything you
know,'' Bennett told him. To which he replied, ``Look, you guys are
the ones that need to cooperate with me.'' It was, Isikoff
concedes, ``a form of blackmail. I was threatening to make him look
really bad if he didn't give me information.''
</P>
<P>
   Isikoff is careful to document his rationale for his hot pursuit
of the President. In the beginning, in 1994, the issue for Isikoff
was not whether Clinton had ever committed adultery. Rather, it was
more fundamental: ``a continuing pattern of reckless and even
compulsive behavior that, if true, would almost surely affect the
course of his Presidency.'' Then, in May of that year, Clinton
hired a high-profile criminal defense lawyer. ``The fact that the
President would hire Bob Bennett to represent him against the
claims of Paula Jones bestowed official legitimacy on a story that,
until then, The Post had been afraid to touch,'' Isikoff says. And
when the Supreme Court unanimously rejected the President's claim
of immunity from civil litigation while in office, the Paula Jones
lawsuit became ``justification'' for publishing, he says.
``Clinton's sexual behavior was inevitably going to be front and
center.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not Watergate,'' Isikoff writes in his epilogue.
``But that doesn't mean it wasn't right to undertake the
enterprise.'' If journalism is the first draft of history, let him
have the last word on this second draft: ``There are no easy
answers here.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goldstein is the dean of the Columbia University Graduate
School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
