<HEADER>
A3998 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-EVENSONG-NYTS     04-02 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-EVENSONG-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 EVENSONG
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Gail Godwin.
</P>
<P>
   405 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine Books. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; WE'VE GOT COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   BY CLAIRE MESSUd
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Gail Godwin's new novel is a sequel not to her last book, ``The
Good Husband,'' but to its predecessor. Told by the young Margaret
Gower, ``Father Melancholy's Daughter'' was the coming-of-age story
of an Episcopal minister's child, set in a fictitious Virginia
town. That novel closed with a series of letters and diary entries
in which Margaret made tentative plans for her future, holding out
the promise of her as-yet-untried adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evensong'' is the novel of that adulthood. It is also a novel,
set on the cusp of the millennium, in which our society's anxieties
are played out in microcosm. Now in her early 30's, Margaret Bonner
(nee Gower) is herself a pastor, ministering to the congregation of
All Saints in the Smoky Mountain town of High Balsam, N.C. Her
husband, Adrian, 20 years her senior, is also a priest, serving as
chaplain and acting headmaster of a boarding school for troubled
children. Like Margaret's father -- the melancholic of the earlier
novel -- Adrian is a depressive, and at the outset of the book the
couple's marriage is in difficulty: Margaret, whose mother
abandoned her husband and daughter when Margaret was only 6, is
contemplating a similar escape.
</P>
<P>
   What impels rapprochement in the Bonner household is the
appearance of three unlikely -- and somewhat unwelcome --
characters. Grace Munger, a pushy evangelical manipulator who is
organizing an ecumenical Millennium Birthday March for Jesus, will
not accept Margaret's polite refusals to participate. She is more
imperious but less insinuating than Brother Tony, an 80-year-old
itinerant lay monk who lands on the Bonners' doorstep ostensibly by
accident but with no apparent intention to decamp. And finally
there is 16-year-old Chase Zorn, whose antics at Adrian's school
lead to his expulsion; for Chase, the Bonners' rectory is a last
resort before reform school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evensong'' takes place over the course of a few weeks in late
November and December of 1999 -- during Advent, ``that season of
spiritual expectation in the church calendar'' -- but its
flashbacks and anecdotes fan out to encompass much of Margaret's
and Adrian's lives. Readers unfamiliar with ``Father Melancholy's
Daughter'' need not be deterred: in the course of ``Evensong,''
Godwin provides a meticulous precis of the other book.
</P>
<P>
   Meticulousness and precision are, indeed, Godwin's greatest
strengths. In matters liturgical and clerical, her command is
impeccable. Godwin imbues Margaret with an authentically -- and
impressively -- broad range of religious references, from St. Hilda
of Whitby to St. Augustine to Andre Malraux. The novel is not,
however, mired in abstruse theological arguments. Like its
protagonist, it moves between Christianity's philosophical
considerations and its most practical concerns, and dwells
primarily upon the latter. Godwin's portrayal of the competitive
congregations and gossiping denizens of High Balsam is as astute as
her knowledge of church lore is comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of the novel, however, are less thoroughly
convincing. Godwin has produced a curious hybrid book, for which
the conceptual collision of Armageddon and small-town America is an
apt representation. While Margaret and Adrian and their friends are
so recognizable as occasionally to verge on banality, the three
catalytic characters who descend on High Balsam seem to have been
zapped in from some other America, mythical and cartoonish. The
absurdly named Chase Zorn, for example, is a Peruvian orphan
adopted by Radford Zorn, ``the happy hometown theme-park mogul.''
Grace Munger's histrionic evangelism (``I'm black and blue and
slain in the Spirit'') and her flamboyant character are parodic and
hence dismissible. And Tony -- whose story is integral to the plot
and hence not to be revealed here -- is Dickensian both in his
complicated history and in the few, broad traits that are used to
sketch his character (oddly dyed hair, an interest in homeopathic
healing, talent as a short-order cook).
</P>
<P>
   THE uneasy cohabitation of Margaret Bonner with these characters
reflects an unresolved tension in Godwin's work between the
literary and the popular, between a striving for truth and a desire
to entertain. Godwin's writing itself reflects this anxiety. There
are bursts of frankly terrible prose, some merely careless (``he
purred in his soft croak'') but some an uncomfortable marriage of
the pretentious and the colloquial, the novelistic equivalent of
middle-management-speak:
</P>
<P>
   ``I had given up trying to fight these reruns from days when
more things happened than I could absorb, or when too many enigmas
taxed my limited powers of discernment. I allowed the leftovers to
play themselves out, mutating into whatever they wanted to be next.
Meanwhile I tried to stay connected to a quieter part of me who
waited in the background for the cessation of all this outer
business. After the cessation sometimes came lucidity, in which a
different kind of communication could take place. More often it
didn't come: the day's noises and pictures rolled on and on, I got
sucked into the show, then would suddenly snap out of it with a
jolt, caught red-handed in the midst of some self-serving (or
equally extravagant self-defeating) reverie.''
</P>
<P>
   Veering from obfuscatory Latinate diction (``discernment,''
``mutating,'' ``cessation,'' ``lucidity'') to cliche (``snap out of
it,'' ``with a jolt,'' ``caught red-handed''), with an odd mixing
of metaphor along the way (can leftovers play themselves out, let
alone mutate?), this passage exemplifies the dangers Godwin faces
in attempting to render widely accessible her characters' more
complex thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Like Walker Percy, a fellow Southerner whom she could be said to
resemble in both her moral seriousness and her perceptiveness,
Godwin is not essentially a stylist. And yet, in spite of its
infelicities and occasional straining for effect, ``Evensong''
lingers in the mind. This has much to do with the honesty of its
portrait of a young woman struggling with life's fundamental
questions -- with faith and family, with the patterns that define
her own identity.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Claire Messud's second novel, ``The Last Life,'' will be
published later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
