<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4000 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BR     04-02 1510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Rather than claiming to have constructed a definitive history of
performance art, RoseLee Goldberg acts like a diligent film editor
or museum curator to assemble PERFORMANCE: Live Art Since 1960
(Abrams, $60), a collection of photographs of performance art.
There are shots of Marina Abramovic weeping as she scrubs cow bones
and Yasumasa Morimura striking a pose as Scarlett O'Hara. While
such images may be difficult to comprehend, much less to form into
a coherent narrative, Goldberg does isolate what the works of this
genre -- inspired by everything from classical theater to digital
animation -- share: origins in a world on the verge of information
overload, a world more and more coming to resemble an outlandish
theatrical event, a world devoid of stable definitions. And
although she has divided the images into such ostensibly tidy
categories as ``The Body'' and ``Identities,'' Goldberg ultimately
refrains from defining these inherently unclassifiable works; she
seldom goes beyond asserting that an artist's works ``have an
underlying social commentary'' or put forth a ``sophisticated take
on American society.'' Goldberg in fact works much like a
performance artist, allowing the images to speak for themselves.
``Performance,'' accordingly, mimics the culture that informs them;
readers are barraged with data and are subjected to a parade of
fragmented images in the place of real, firsthand experience. In
the end, Goldberg's self-conscious, anticritical stance is
admirably respectful to the spirit of performance, but one wishes
she had not forfeited eloquence to make her point. _ CHRISTINA CHO
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBERING SLAVERY
</P>
<P>
   African Americans Talk
</P>
<P>
   About Their Personal Experiences
</P>
<P>
   of Slavery and Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Edited By Ira Berlin, Marc Favreau and Steven F. Miller.
</P>
<P>
   New Press, $49.95.
</P>
<P>
   Following the turbulent failure of Reconstruction, much of white
America, both South and North, began portraying slavery as a
benevolent institution. To counter that pernicious view, which was
quite pervasive at the start of the 20th century, black scholars
began interviewing former slaves. While white historians dismissed
these narratives as unreliable or tangential to slavery's ``larger
meaning in American life,'' they inspired writers and folklorists
like Zora Neal Hurston, John Lomax and John Henry Faulk, as well as
a group of interviewers from the New Deal's Federal Writers'
Project, who spent much of the 1930's and early 40's traversing the
South, speaking with thousands of additional subjects.
``Remembering Slavery'' contains excerpts from interviews with
about 100 former slaves who testified to the terrifyingly arbitrary
nature of the peculiar institution (the book is accompanied by two
audio cassettes). These firsthand accounts describe the nearly
inconceivable violence to which so many slaves were subject. One
nurse recalls that when her charge injured his hand, her mistress
took a hot iron and ran it down her arm, searing her flesh. Another
woman remembers how her master hitched a slave to a plow and beat
him until he died. While the large number of passages shows the
diversity of slave experiences, and that there were indeed some
kindly masters, one wishes that the editors had included fewer
subjects with longer excerpts. This would have allowed for deeper,
individuated portraits of those who lived to tell of this most
disgraceful period in our nation's history. _ JOHANNA BERKMAN
</P>
<P>
   A NEARLY NORMAL LIFE
</P>
<P>
   A Memoir.
</P>
<P>
   By Charles L. Mee.
</P>
<P>
   Little, Brown, $24.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, Charles Mee, a 14-year-old high school football player
from Barrington, Ill., was stricken with spinal polio, a viral
disease with no known cure. More than 50,000 cases were reported
that year, mostly of young people who took sick during the summer
months. A national panic ensued. Cities closed pools and beaches;
families canceled vacations, boiled their dishes and avoided indoor
crowds. Children were warned against jumping in puddles, drinking
from water fountains and making new friends. The March of Dimes
became the country's favorite charity, spurring the vaccine
research by Jonas Salk and Alfred Sabin that all but eradicated the
spread of polio in the United States. In this elegant memoir, Mee
contrasts his painful experiences as a polio survivor against the
relentlessly optimistic backdrop of the 1950's. Unable to walk
without crutches, isolated from old friends, a disappointment to
his father, Mee found solace in books and in sleep. His new friends
came from the margins of society, where no one, he claims, is ever
quite whole. Mee, a playwright and the author of 15 books, endured
years of personal anguish, heavy drinking and drug abuse. It took a
long time for his rage to dissipate, and longer still to understand
that polio can't be beaten, only accepted. ``I am no longer
interested in recovery or restitution,'' he writes, adding, ``How
else my life might have been is unknowable; and the truth is, I
wouldn't change it for any other.'' _ DAVID OSHINSKY
</P>
<P>
   THE TWILIGHT OF THE INTELLECTUALS
</P>
<P>
   Culture and Politics in the Era of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   By Hilton Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan R. Dee, $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   After hard service in more recent culture wars, Hilton Kramer
turns in his new collection of essays to New York and the cold war
years -- to Alger Hiss and Whittaker Chambers, Lillian Hellman and
Mary McCarthy, Irving Howe, Philip Rahv, Partisan Review and The
New Republic. For many of this generation, their fashionably
progressive sentiments became what Kramer regards as a distinct
pathology. His epitaph for one old friend, Josephine Herbst, could
serve for most: however often Communist Party policy changed,
``when she was overruled and told, in effect, to shut up, she shut
up and she stayed shut up.'' Such writers betrayed their own
ambitions and harmed others: to mourn for leftists blacklisted in
Hollywood, Kramer writes, is to forget that Communists ruthlessly
blacklisted their own foes. He honors a few rare figures who he
thinks showed integrity: Lionel Trilling, Sidney Hook and Whittaker
Chambers, who made something Dostoyevskian out of his careers as
spy, reporter and Government witness. Other essays skewer Mary
McCarthy, ``a political pen for all seasons,'' who could play to
the mainstream of the 1950's, then change with the times and praise
what she called the ``virtuous tyranny'' of Ho Chi Minh's North
Vietnam. Two thoughtful pieces on Clement Greenberg recall that the
cold war era was also the moment when New York's painters eclipsed
those of Paris -- and suggest that the Abstract Expressionists, who
caught their culture's spirit without taking on its political
engagements, had learned something that the writers never could. _
ALLEN D. BOYER
</P>
<P>
   WHAT THE PEOPLE KNOW
</P>
<P>
   Freedom and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University, $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Reeves here plays the crusty reporter who revels in
journalism's romantic past and bemoans its uncertain future. Most
of the dangers he describes in ``What the People Know'' are already
familiar. Satellites and the Internet now allow for instantaneous
news; the reporter's traditional job -- finding, sorting and
evaluating facts -- has come to seem extraneous, a luxury for which
there is no time. And the corporate takeover of news departments
makes conflicts of interest inevitable. But Reeves, a syndicated
columnist and author of ``President Kennedy: Profile of Power,''
also blames his colleagues for the problems facing journalism. He
argues that reporters, filled with hubris after their Watergate
triumph, communicated a simple message about politicians: ``Throw
them out, despise them, they're irrelevant.'' And the public has
believed them. But by degrading their subjects so effectively,
journalists have made themselves irrelevant as well; why bother
reading a story with a Washington dateline if every politician is a
crook? To regain public attention, reporters now attempt to seduce
the populace with sex, sports and scandal. Of course, this effort
to titillate and entertain merely trivializes the profession
further. Reeves worries about the future of the republic bereft of
a vigorous, independent Fourth Estate, but in this book he is
really mourning the loss of a cherished life style, a life style
filled with glamour, excitement and the heady freedom to follow a
story wherever the truth leads. He worries that a new breed of
reporters will be forced to peck away at keyboards in the tiny
cubicles of international conglomerates -- just like everybody
else. _ DOUGLAS A. SYLVA
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
