<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4001 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEF     04-02 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: FICTION
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``All of my fingers have been broken from being stomped on,''
says T-Bird Murphy, the teen-age narrator of Eric Miles
Williamson's first novel, EAST BAY GREASE (Picador USA, $23). ``My
head's been knocked so many times, I wouldn't be surprised if I was
permanently stupid.'' Set in Oakland during the 1960's and 1970's,
this novel is a lively -- not to say wrenching -- contribution to a
seldom recognized genre: the Internal Combustion Novel. As in Harry
Crews's ``Car'' and Joseph Torra's more mystical ``Gas Station,''
the hero of ``East Bay Grease'' spends his days in an environment
that's so filthy nothing can ennoble it. T-Bird may be the best
trumpeter in the Jack London High School band and a pretty smart
kid despite all the hard knocks he's taken, but it would take a
miracle to get him out of the asphalt hell he inhabits along with
his mother, a bikers' moll, and his father, an auto mechanic and a
savage rube. Only in the sour air of the dockside bars, in
punishing work and in music does he find relief. Williamson so
convincingly depicts the cruelty of some of his characters that he
seems almost scared of them. The feeling is contagious. Yet when
T-Bird is finally ready for his shining moment soloing with Los
Asesinos, a Mexican-American band as brilliant as it is tough,
Williamson's writing becomes transcendent. His prose cuts loose in
torrid rhythms that evoke the peril and exuberance of jazz. _ SALLY
ECKHOFF
</P>
<P>
   THE UMBRELLA COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   By Bino A. Realuyo.
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine, paper, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   The ``umbrella country'' of the poet Bino A. Realuyo's first
novel is the Philippines, where Gringo, 11 years old, lives in
Manila with his family. Through Gringo's puzzled, apprehensive
eyes, the household is revealed as a pressure cooker of longing and
rage. Gringo's father, Daddy Groovie, is an unemployed construction
worker who dreams of escaping to ``Nuyork'' and visits his
disappointment on his wife and eldest son, Pipo. The rebellious and
flamboyant Pipo, who craves his macho father's approval, terrorizes
Gringo in his turn. Gringo's resigned mother spends longer and
longer hours at her Singer sewing machine, while his ``godmother of
words,'' Ninang Rola, curses and comforts volubly, but continually
warns that ``certain things are better kept than said.'' Indeed, as
Gringo observes, ``Silence had a way of creeping into our house.''
The adults explain nothing, neither private woes, like his mother's
bruises, nor social ills, such as the nightly curfew or the sexual
stigma that surrounds a hairdresser named Boy Manicure. Inevitably,
the violence within Gringo's household and in Boy Manicure's shadow
world erupts in forms that cannot be ignored, and Gringo must
choose whether to sacrifice himself or his brother to public shame.
The results of his decision are oddly anticlimactic; the story
closes abruptly with a half-anticipated departure and the
dissolution of the family. Nevertheless, Realuyo's lucid prose,
unencumbered by sentimentality or hindsight, lends freshness to the
conflicts of his somewhat familiar characters and color to a
setting both impoverished and alluring. _ LAURA MORGAN GREEN
</P>
<P>
   THE TALE OF A DOG
</P>
<P>
   From the Diaries and Letters of a Texan Bankruptcy Judge.
</P>
<P>
   By Lars Gustafsson.
</P>
<P>
   New Directions, paper, $11.95.
</P>
<P>
   Franz Kafka meets Italo Calvino in this new novel by the Swedish
writer Lars Gustafsson. In 31 first-person vignettes, a Jewish
bankruptcy court judge in Texas named Erwin Caldwell circles and
recircles around the revelation that his college mentor, the
philosopher-semanticist Professor Jan van de Rouwers, was not a
former Dutch resistance fighter as he presented himself but a Nazi
collaborator instead. When van de Rouwer's pajama-clad body is
discovered in Texas' Colorado River, Caldwell begins to confess to
strangers that he recently beat to death a stray dog which had
raided neighborhood garbage cans. This compulsive repetition
suggests a connection between the two events, and the judge
unconvincingly denies murdering the professor. Gustafsson, who
teaches at the University of Texas, uses the rising of the river, a
visit from Caldwell's stepdaughter and grandson, and excursions
into stores that sell books, health food and groceries as the
backdrop of this haunting and sparely told investigation into moral
bankruptcy. Unfortunately, the very British translation by Tom
Geddes makes it hard to believe that the narrator is a native
Texan. A checkout clerk at a supermarket operates a ``till'' ; his
grandson, suffering like Caldwell from insomnia, wanders through
the house at night carrying a ``torch''; when a local boathouse
burns down, the ``fire brigade'' is summoned. In a novel in which
the central question is the narrator's reliability, such jarring
lapses in language come between reader and an otherwise intriguing
story. _ GRETCHEN HOLBROOK GERZINA
</P>
<P>
   THINE IS THE KINGDOM
</P>
<P>
   By Abilio Estevez.
</P>
<P>
   Arcade, $25.95.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban poet and short-story writer Abilio Estevez's debut
novel is a hugely ambitious effusion of magical realist mythmaking.
The novel is set on the eve of the Castro revolution in an
abandoned Havana estate known as the Island, where more than a
dozen characters tell their stories in dizzying counterpoint. The
eccentric cast includes the crazed Barefoot Countess; a gay
bookseller named Uncle Rolo; a former opera singer and her mute
pastry-selling husband; a ``Wounded Boy'' who may or may not be St.
Sebastian, and the author himself, who occasionally intrudes to
suggest alternate narratives. Their stories crisscross in a flurry
of shifting pronouns and a constantly ambiguous mix of time and
place, replete with a Gothic creation myth centered on an
incestuous brother and sister. Estevez's prose is rich with
allusions to art and literature, and in David Frye's translation it
rolls in lucid, rhythmic waves. The disembodied, dreamlike
narrative serves its purpose: Estevez immerses us in history in
order to transcend it, shuffles the temporal in order to suggest
the eternal. As for the mixed identities of the multiple narrative
voices, Estevez explicitly invokes that eternal tale-teller
herself, Scheherazade. The freedom of art is set against the
confinement of political and geographic realities. But Estevez is
so intent on making the narrative earth disappear beneath our feet
that by the time the calendar flips to that fateful day of Jan. 1,
1959, when Castro's forces overthrew the Batista regime, you might
find yourself yearning for some old-fashioned modernism. _ JON
GAREICK
</P>
<P>
   THE TESTAMENT
</P>
<P>
   By John Grisham.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday, $27.95.
</P>
<P>
   John Grisham's 10th novel lacks both courtroom and sustained
drama, but it's nevertheless entertaining. ``The Testament''
introduces us to Troy Phelan, a thrice-married billionaire who is
disgusted with his no-good offspring, who have already spent the $5
million he gave each of them upon turning 21. Before committing
suicide, Phelan signs a surprise will that leaves most of his
fortune to Rachel Lane, his illegitimate daughter, who is a
missionary in Brazil. Nate O'Riley, a big-time litigator (and an
alcoholic habitually in and out of rehab), is dispatched to track
Rachel down. Here the action cuts from the colorful if cardboard
ingrate heirs and their sleazy lawyers to Nate's adventures in
Brazil's remote Pantanal region, where Rachel is believed to be
living among an isolated tribe of Indians. Oddly, it's these scenes
-- of indistinguishable tributaries, menacing storms and deadly
fevers -- that seem most authentic. Nate finds Rachel, is struck by
her simple existence, and realizes his own life needs work. Nate's
search for redemption, which might have become hokey, is quite
convincing. The big question -- what will Rachel do upon learning
she has inherited $11 billion -- is nicely resolved. But don't
expect eloquence. If you can ignore such ungainly sentences as
``Repellent was passed back and forth'' (in the middle of a killer
mosquito attack) and adjectives (darling, delightful, amazing) that
scream for a thesaurus, you'll enjoy Grisham's jungle adventure. _
CAROL PEACE ROBINS
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
