 (Editors: Following is a list of slugs and titles of the books
reviewed in the New York Times Book Review for Sunday March 28.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   ON THE COVER
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-NYTSF MORGAN American Financier. By Jean Strouse. Random
House. $34.95. In the Gilded Age, J. Pierpont Morgan bestrode the
financial nation like a colossus. Maybe two colossi.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   RIVER-NYTSF THE RIVER MIDNIGHT By Lilian Nattel. 414 pp. New
York: Scribner. $25. This first novel centers on a shtetl in Poland
and features four dynamic, slightly crazy women.
</P>
<P>
   KAFKA-NYTSF KAFKA'S CURSE By Achmat Dangor. 225 pp. New York:
Pantheon Books. $22. In this novel about South Africa after
apartheid, a man turns into a tree.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL-NYTSF SURVIVAL RATES Stories. By Mary Clyde. The
University of Georgia Press. $24.95. The characters in these
stories are decent folk, and often wish they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   TRUMPETS-NYTSF THE SOUND OF TRUMPETS By John Mortimer. 273 pp.
New York: Viking. $23.95. John Mortimer's lordly hero Titmuss
stumping for Labor? Oh, horror!
</P>
<P>
   BARNYARD-NYTSF LORD OF THE BARNYARD By Tristan Egolf. 410 pp.
New York: Grove Press. $24. In this first novel, an angry young man
wreaks vengeance on his small Kentucky town.
</P>
<P>
   DOG-NYTSF TEETH OF THE DOG By Jill Ciment. 216 pp. New York:
Crown Publishers. $22. A trip to a South Sea island turns
nightmarish when the heroine is forced to flee for her life.
</P>
<P>
   BLAM-NYTSF THE BOOK OF BLAM By Aleksandar Tisma. Translated by
Michael Henry Heim. Harcourt Brace &AMP; Company. $23. A novel from the
former Yugoslavia evokes a lost Jewish community just after World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   VALENTE-NYTSF ME, BY JIMMY (BIG BOY) VALENTE, GOVERNOR OF SOTA.
As told to Garrison Keillor. New York: Viking. $15.95. Garrison
Keillor's account of a former pro wrestler's career in politics is
fiction_sort of.
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM-NYTSF FREEDOM SONG Three Novels. By Amit Chaudhuri.
Alfred A. Knopf. $24. Three novels by a young writer less
interested in one particular story than in all the bits and pieces
of ordinary life.
</P>
<P>
   INTIMACY-NYTSF INTIMACY By Hanif Kureishi. 118 pp. New York:
Scribner. $16. Hanif Kureishi's self-absorbed hero agonizes over
leaving his partner and children.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   SPYMASTER-NYTSF A COVERT LIFE Jay Lovestone: Spymaster. By Ted
Morgan. Random House. $29.95. Of all the liberal anti-Communists,
Jay Lovestone may have been the most feared.
</P>
<P>
   DILLARD-NYTSF FOR THE TIME BEING By Annie Dillard. 205 pp. New
York: Alfred A. Knopf. $22. Annie Dillard poses an age-old
question: why does God permit great wickedness?
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NYTSF KAPITALIZM Russia's Struggle to Free Its Economy.
By Rose Brady. Yale University Press. $30. A sympathetic account of
Boris Yeltsin's attempt to reinvent the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   CLASS-NYTSF THE RISE AND FALL OF CLASS IN BRITAIN By David
Cannadine. 293 pp. New York: Columbia University Press. $29.95. For
three centuries, class has defined social distinctions in England.
</P>
<P>
   MAHLER-NYTSF DIARIES 1898-1902 BY ALMA MAHLER-WERFEL. Translated
by Antony Beaumont. Illustra ed. 494 pp. Ithaca, N.Y.: Cornell
University Press. $35. Early diaries of the future Alma Mahler
Gropius Werfel reveal a temptress in training.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
