<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4012 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-IRAQ-COX     04-02 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-IRAQ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRAQIS BECOME BEDFELLOWS WITH SERBS IN BATTLES WITH U.S. AND THE
WEST
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq _ Beleaguered Iraqis had been savoring some peace
and quiet while their new soul mates in Yugoslavia carried on a
battle against the West, but U.S. air strikes here Friday served as
a reminder that, while out of the international limelight, Iraq is
still within firing range.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. warplane attacks on two communications facilities in
Southern Iraq were the first since March 19.
</P>
<P>
   There were no deaths reported from the strikes, but they showed
American willingness to wage air campaigns simultaneously against
two countries. The attacks also fulfilled a vow from U.S. officials
that they would not ease up on Saddam Hussein amid the Balkan
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the air strikes were mild compared to bombing which was
especially heavy last December. And Iraqis seemed to relish their
relative safety, letting Yugoslavia _ what Western leaders might
consider an appropriate bedfellow _ top the world news.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fed up with being the center of events. We want to have
a quiet time,'' said Khudeir Al-Duleimi (CQ BOTH), editor of the
government-run Baghdad Observer.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's Yugoslavia coverage was on a large television in his
office, but Duleimi was preoccupied with a project he has
undertaken. He is writing a summary for the Iraqi Ministry of
Information of ``Endgame,'' a new book by former U.N. weapons
inspector Scott Ritter.
</P>
<P>
   These days, scaffolding envelopes the offices of Saddam
Hussein's Baath Party headquarters, which was destroyed by a series
of direct hits in December. A giant crater in a downtown avenue has
been filled and paved over.
</P>
<P>
   The government press center, where hundreds of reporters
gathered in December, is empty. And the so-called ``minders,''
government employees assigned to foreign reporters, stay home or
sit languidly in their lounges watching the events in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Al Rasheed Hotel, which has served as a sort of dormitory
for reporters when the Iraqi story has been hot, has been quiet,
save for a noisy anniversary party a few days ago for a television
station headed by Saddam Hussein's son, Odai.
</P>
<P>
   Ties between Iraq and Yugoslavia go back long before Saddam
Hussein's regime was isolated by economic sanctions in 1991. Many
Iraqis used to accept scholarships to attend Yugoslavian
universities and there is even a high school in Belgrade that
caters to Iraqis living abroad there.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the two allies are joined in their underdog battle against
what one Iraqi newspaper called the ``hollow hegemony'' of America.
</P>
<P>
   Western press reports state that the two governments are
exchanging information on air strike defenses, possibly even
meeting in person and swapping their military equipment.
</P>
<P>
   One Iraqi official said there is friendship, but not a military
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Iraq resisted (the United States), it encouraged others
to resist,'' said Naji Hadithi, a high ranking Iraqi information
ministry official who soon will become his country's ambassador to
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the economic sanctions facing both countries, he said,
they have learned that it is better to ``resist with dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO strikes are front page news here and the government
hosted a press conference where a Yugoslav embassy official talked
about the conflict. But, Iraqi press accounts are about the only
news most Iraqis get. The reports never remind readers that the
Kosovar Albanians who are the subject of Serb aggression are fellow
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqis, long suspicious of Western motives, do not seem to care
when this is noted to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``(NATO) says they are defending Muslims and fighting
Christians, but they are not. America just feels that any country
that develops itself needs to be knocked down,'' said Hassan Ali,
42, a retired soldier.
</P>
<P>
   One victim of a U.S. warplane strike in December said his Muslim
loyalties do not outweigh his concern for Serbian families
suffering as his own family did.
</P>
<P>
   Jassim Ghelan Zubeidi, 41, and his family have been watching the
news about Yugoslavia. ``It is as if they keep running a film of
what happened to us,'' he said. ``Innocent people are killed these
days for nothing except NATO's desire for expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   In a civilian upper class section of Baghdad in December, a
missile slammed through the bathroom wall of Zubeidi's seven
bedroom house, seriously injuring him and his 10-year-old daughter,
Susan.
</P>
<P>
   Zubeidi, who worked in Russia for several years and now imports
supplies under the United Nations oil-for-food sanction regime, has
healed and has rebuilt his house.
</P>
<P>
   Susan appears healthy and clearly recites songs she wrote in
Arabic about missile strikes. But, she still faces a third surgery
to repair a skull facture.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the U.S. ambassador to Jordan, Zubeidi recently
asserted a legal claim for $100 million in damages for the injuries
he says were inflicted on him, his daughter and their property by
American warplanes. He has yet to receive a response.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
