<HEADER>
A4035 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIAN-REFUGEE-2TAKE     04-02 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIAN-REFUGEE-2TAKES-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BOSNIAN REFUGEE STRUGGLES WITH IMAGES OF THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 4)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CELINA OTTAWAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If Anne Frank had survived the Holocaust and
lived to write another diary, she might have struggled with the
same questions that haunt Samira Huremovic.
</P>
<P>
   How do you reclaim a childhood from the rubble of war, the
darkness of hiding, the press of a gun against your chest? How do
you live after a part of you has died?
</P>
<P>
   Samira, 18, arrived in Albany two years ago with her family, the
latest additions to a small but growing Bosnian refugee community.
Her parents took jobs as housekeepers at a local hospital and the
family settled into a nearby second-story flat. Five days after
landing in the States, Samira started school.
</P>
<P>
   It is here in the halls of Albany High School, in the cafeterias
filled with the smell of sweet tomato sauce, in the computer
classes where she studies spread sheets that Samira is finding a
new life after Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   There are some 10 Bosnian refugees in Albany High School, enough
to fill a lunch table. They munch down their pasta, banter in
Bosnian and joke about the latest gossip at school. Samira responds
to the jokes with a smile that rarely reaches her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Their stories are being told all over again today, as President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia seeks to drive out the Muslim
ethnic Albanian population of Kosovo. It was Milosevic, then head
of the dominant Yugoslav state of Serbia, who backed efforts to
create a ``Greater Serbia'' in Samira's homeland, the former
Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   Samira Huremovic was born in 1980 in Srebrenica,
Bosnia-Herzegovina. She lived in a suburban development just
outside the main town. Her father worked in a battery factory. Her
mother was a housewife.
</P>
<P>
   The Huremovics' house was three stories of concrete block, the
usual building material for the area. Her grandparents lived on the
third floor. Samira shared the second floor with her parents, her
older brother Samir and her younger sister Merdina. The first floor
was a common area.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekends, Samira, Samir and Merdina would wander in the
nearby woods and fields to pick wild strawberries, apples and
cherries. Samira would play volleyball and soccer with her friends.
Boys and girls would play together, something Samira loved.
</P>
<P>
   Even then her brother Samir, four years her senior, looked out
for her. He would tell her to be careful, although he would never
give specifics. He explained that he didn't want other people
talking about her. And he talked vaguely about what it meant to be
a good Muslim girl.
</P>
<P>
   Samira knew what he meant and kept a safe distance from boys.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth grade, she studied biology, chemistry and physics.
She especially loved her biology teacher, a lanky Serb with a long
face and kind eyes. He had a collection of snake skins and bugs in
jars, fascinating stuff to a 10-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   This was peacetime Bosnia. She would play at her Serb friends'
houses and sometimes their mothers would offer her food. The
neighborhood parks were full of the voices of Serbian and Bosnian
children playing together.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign of war was the silence.
</P>
<P>
   One day in 1992, the stores closed. Samira's Serbian neighbors
left. The biology teacher disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't how Samira tells the story.
</P>
<P>
   She starts three years later. She speaks in the same soft voice
that moments before had been giggling about her Leonardo DiCaprio
poster. She starts at the end.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs had been encroaching on Srebrenica for years. Now they
were coming. The Bosnian border patrols had done what they could
and were beating a hasty retreat to woods.
</P>
<P>
   That night Samira and her family left their home and gathered
with their neighbors at a house near her old school. She said
goodbye to her father and brother, who were heading to the woods to
hide with the other men.
</P>
<P>
   We will meet you in Tuzla, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian nationalist soldiers had announced that women and
children would be put on buses. Samira was not sure where they
would be taken. Somewhere in the direction of Tuzla. All night she
and her mother and sister waited. Samira sat awake in the darkness,
wondering what would happen and praying for her father and
brother.In the morning, Serb soldiers rounded them up and started
to herd them onto buses. Samira's mother wrapped a scarf around
Samira's face to disguise her as an old woman. Be quiet, she told
her daughter, don't say a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Samira was 15. She lowered her head. The family approached the
guards. Her mother and sister were allowed to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The guard held his gun up to Samira's chest and blocked her way.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to push her into a group of teen-age girls who were
being separated from their families. Samira started to scream and
reach across the man for her mother. Then, without thinking, she
dropped to the ground and darted underneath the soldier's gun.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, he let her go.
</P>
<P>
   Samira would learn later that two of her cousins had been taken.
One was raped by five men that day.
</P>
<P>
   The buses carried Samira, the older women and the children to
the edge of the Serbian-controlled territory in Bosnia and then
released them deeper into the country. They joined the stream of
refugees on the road to Tuzla. She and her mother and sister walked
all night, careful to keep in the center to avoid land mines. The
road was littered with bodies of those who had fallen from
starvation or exhaustion and died.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuzla, Samira and her family stayed in a refugee camp and
then with the help of relatives settled into a small apartment.
</P>
<P>
   One day as they were eating breakfast at her aunt's house, a man
appeared in the doorway. He was thin, seemingly too thin to be
alive. And he was shorter than the father Samira remembered, as if
two weeks in the woods eating roots and leaves had shrunk him.
</P>
<P>
   They embraced him. Then her mother asked the question that would
become her constant thought.
</P>
<P>
   Where is my son? she said.
</P>
<P>
   Samira's father started to cry. They had been running away from
the Serbs, he said, when another man was shot. Samir went back to
help and got separated in the confusion. That was the last time
Mesan Huremovic saw his son.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
