<HEADER>
A4039 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIAN-REFUGEE-2NDTA     04-02 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIAN-REFUGEE-2NDTAKE-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
  
 ALBANY, N.Y.: x x x saw his son.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And what of the years before they left Srebrenica?
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Samira's eyes turn red behind her
glasses.``Those were the two hard years of my life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But what is there to say about the starvation? It's dull. It's
monotonous. It's boring.
</P>
<P>
   Samira shrugs her shoulders and stares silently at the wall.
Then she starts, her voice different this time. She speaks lower,
softer, fumbling over the memories.
</P>
<P>
   Her family had lived in the basement of their house for two
years during the war. Samira and her family relied on food rations
from peace forces and when those ran out, they baked bread from
pods they picked off of trees. Her dog Vucko died after a year and
a half. There was nothing to feed him.
</P>
<P>
   There were moments of peace when the residents of Srebrenica
would climb out of their basements. A boy played his guitar and
sang Bosnian pop songs. Samira and her friends would sing along and
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Samira smiled at the boy. He carved her name in his guitar. But
gunshots would drive them back to their basements.
</P>
<P>
   Samira doesn't speak much of her past to her new American
friends in Albany. They don't ask, and she doesn't volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   She and the other Bosnian children don't talk about it much
either.
</P>
<P>
   Instead she talks about the future, her plans for college, the
cute guy she met.
</P>
<P>
   ``I smile and laugh a lot,'' Samira said, walking between
classes. ``Sometimes it makes me feel better. But really I am sad a
lot of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sadness comes out at night. She prays for her brother before
she goes to bed. As she is falling asleep her thoughts are filled
with memories of him.
</P>
<P>
   Samira is careful not to speak of Samir too often in front of
her mother. Four years later, his name brings instant tears to Hata
Huremovic's eyes. When her mother speaks of the war, it is in
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``July 11,'' Hata says when asked about her experiences. ``The
day I lost my son.''
</P>
<P>
   A long pause. ``Thirteen days,'' she says. ``Thirteen days they
walked in the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the numbers that hold back Samira's laugh at the lunch
table. Thoughts of her brother dancing with her in the basement
haunt her. His face wakes her when she sleeps.
</P>
<P>
   In between lessons, she logs on to the Internet and searches for
information about Bosnian refugees. In front of the computer,
Samira seems to come alive, shoulders thrust forward in
anticipation, foot tapping out the moments till Bosnia.com's Web
site appears on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The logo appears. Samira's face breaks into a smile. She combs
through the pages, looking for her brother.
</P>
</TEXT>
