<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-SLAYING-$ADV4-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAYING SHATTERS ILLUSION OF ECUADOR AS A SAFE HAVEN FROM REGION'S
POLITICAL VIOLENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, April 4) 
(Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Castano) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ Tires sometimes are burned and Molotov
cocktails are tossed in the heat of anti-government protests, but
that's as violent as things usually get in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike neighboring Colombia and Peru, this South American nation
of 12 million people has never been plagued by savage death squads,
powerful guerrilla armies or drug-cartel terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the murder of Jaime Hurtado, a 62-year-old Marxist
congressman, has left Ecuadoreans baffled.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado, his alternate deputy and his bodyguard were gunned down
in broad daylight two blocks from the Congress building Feb, 17 in
Quito. As Hurtado lay bleeding to death on the rain-soaked
sidewalk, the assassin fled to Colombia, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   The Ecuadorean government blames Colombia's paramilitaries _
right-wing mercenaries involved in that country's long-running
civil war _ for the deaths of the three men. Others suspect
Ecuadorean police officers played a role.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter who ordered the hit, analysts say, Hurtado's
assassination shattered the illusion of Ecuador as a safe haven
from the region's political violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this can happen to a congressman, it can happen to
anyone,'' said Lenin Hurtado, Jaime Hurtado's son.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually unknown abroad, Hurtado was one of Ecuador's most
militant opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Born to illiterate parents, he grew up in an impoverished
village on the Pacific coast. With the help of an athletic
scholarship, he studied in the port city of Guayaquil and became a
lawyer. He was elected to Congress in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   A fervent Marxist, he founded the Popular Democratic Movement,
known by its Spanish initials MPD, which was closely linked to
Ecuador's clandestine Communist Party. He named his son after
Vladimir Lenin and christened one of his daughters Stalina.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had the charisma or the influence with the masses that
Jaime Hurtado had,'' said MPD leader Ciro Guzman. ``He was the most
important revolutionary of the Ecuadorean left in the last 20
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Ecuadorean Marxists never posed a serious threat to the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Leftist guerrilla groups such as Alfaro Vive Carajo were
dismantled by the end of the 1980s. A band of radical students
called the Popular Combatants tossed a stick of dynamite at the
U.S. Embassy in Quito last year, but few people paid attention.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado was never linked to any of these groups.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, admire the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, or FARC, Colombia's largest Marxist rebel group,
according to his son, Lenin. When the FARC opened peace talks with
the Colombian government Jan. 7, rebel leaders invited Jaime
Hurtado to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   That may have drawn the attention of paramilitaries, the
right-wing death squads that target guerrillas and their supporters
in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Aguirre, one of two suspects awaiting trial on
charges related to Hurtado's death, told police that paramilitaries
ordered the assassination, because they believed the congressman
was providing logistical support to the FARC.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the FARC has expanded operations into
Colombia's southern Putumayo state on the Ecuadorean border. The
guerrilla organization, which funds its insurgency, in part, by
abducting people for ransom, receives guns and uniforms through
Ecuador and often stashes kidnapping victims on the Ecuadorean side
of the border. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Colombia-Ecuador border region became even more important
to FARC leaders following military setbacks along their country's
frontier with Panama, another popular gun-running route, according
to Eduardo Pizarro, a guerrilla expert at the National University
in the Colombian capital of Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Colombian paramilitary units started migrating
toward the Ecuadorean border in pursuit of the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Castano, the leader of Colombia's main paramilitary
umbrella organization, told the Bogota newspaper El Tiempo last
month that one of his fronts includes 70 Ecuadoreans and is
stationed near the border.
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous group that ``supports'' the paramilitaries killed
Hurtado and would continue to operate in Ecuador, Castano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think that it probably was the paramilitaries''
who killed Hurtado, said one source close to the Ecuadorean police
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   If true, the assassination would mark the first paramilitary
attack in Ecuador and a widening of the Colombian conflict, which
has already spilled into Panama and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Paramilitaries have raided Panamanian villages and have gone
after Colombian guerrillas who kidnap and blackmail ranchers in
Venezuela. The troubles along the Colombia-Ecuador frontier have
prompted the Quito government to station 5,000 troops on its side
of the border.
</P>
<P>
   But some people insist that it would make little sense for
Colombian paramilitaries to target Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would they be that worried about Jaime Hurtado?'' asked a
Western diplomat. ``Given all the domestic support that the FARC
has in Colombia, any support provided by Hurtado wouldn't have been
all that important.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hurtado's radical views, his colleagues say that he
channeled his energies into electoral politics rather than armed
struggle. They suspect that disgruntled officers within the
Ecuadorean police force may have been involved in his death.
</P>
<P>
   Elsie Monge, a human rights activist in Quito, said Hurtado may
have earned the wrath of the police by promoting peasant takeovers
of land and by organizing anti-government street protests that
occasionally turned violent.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado ``was not a threat, but he was a permanent nuisance,''
Monge said. ``He was always questioning the power structure and the
exploitation of workers and peasants.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecuadorean police have denied involvement in the crime. But
Lenin Hurtado said that shoddy police work immediately after his
father's killing has raised questions.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred near the Congress and Supreme Court
buildings, which were teeming with security guards and police. The
mortally wounded Hurtado lay on the sidewalk for 15 minutes before
help arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman _ a Colombian known as Victorino _ boarded a
commercial flight to Colombia five hours after the crime, according
to police. One of the prime suspects, who might have shed more
light on the assassination, was gunned down by Ecuadorean police in
his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Aguirre, who remains in prison on charges connected
to the triple slaying, is a longtime police informant as well as a
former informant for the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration.
Aguirre admits that he was involved in the crime but claims that he
tried to back out at the last minute and that he tipped off police
hours before the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of intimidating leftists, Hurtado's death appears to
have galvanized them.
</P>
<P>
   Still angry about the killing, Hurtado's political party helped
mount a nationwide strike last month. Protesters clashed with
police, blocked traffic and forced the government to lower gasoline
prices and back down on other economic austerity measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a certain sense,'' said the Western diplomat, referring to
Hurtado, ``he's far more threatening dead than he was alive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
