<HEADER>
A4053 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-CHOCOLATE03-CO     04-02 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CHOCOLATE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Chewable supplement can help women get the
calcium they need
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chocolate is an essential part of a balanced diet.
</P>
<P>
   Really.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if it contains a hefty dose of calcium, as does Viactiv
Soft Calcium Chews, a new product that delivers 500 milligrams of
calcium concealed by chewy chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Ewww, you say. But the chews _ which come in two flavors, Milk
Chocolate and Mochaccino, actually taste pretty good. They're
certainly not Godiva, but Godiva chocolate has a lot more than 20
calories and 0.5 grams of fat per piece, which is all each chew
contains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like medicine, it doesn't taste like
medicine,'' said Dr. Nelson Watts, director of the osteoporosis
program at the Emory Clinic (Emory University, Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, calcium tablets, the most common supplementary
form, often taste unpleasantly chalky.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get a positive sensation when you put it in your
mouth,'' said Connie Weaver, who heads the department of foods and
nutrition at Purdue University in West Lafayette, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, who spoke on behalf of Viactiv's manufacturer, said the
product is ``a revolutionary concept to address those issues'' and
will encourage more women to consume adequate amounts of calcium.
</P>
<P>
   Mead Johnson Nutritionals, a division of the pharmaceutical
company Bristol-Myers Squibb, came up with the idea for Viactiv _
combining something many women crave with something many women need
_ after research indicated the vast majority of women older than 35
don't get enough daily calcium.
</P>
<P>
   Calcium deficiency puts people, especially older white women, at
greater risk for osteoporosis, a disease in which the bones become
extremely brittle and susceptible to fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors recommend that premenopausal adult women and
postmenopausal women who are taking estrogen should consume 1,000
milligrams of calcium per day, Watts said. That includes calcium
consumed via natural dietary sources, such as dairy products and
leafy green vegetables, so these women don't necessarily have to
take 1,000 milligrams of supplemental calcium.
</P>
<P>
   Women who are postmenopausal but not taking hormone replacement
therapy should consume 1,500 milligrams of calcium per day, Watts
said.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no evidence to suggest that dietary calcium is
superior to supplemental calcium, doctors would prefer people to
consume their daily calcium requirements through their diet.
They've learned that's unlikely, however, because even though dairy
foods are the best source of calcium, many adults are either
lactose intolerant or have fallen out of the habit of drinking
milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your habit has been to follow a diet that's not providing
adequate calcium, it's unlikely you're going to change your diet
radically enough to correct your calcium deficiency,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   People who have trouble digesting calcium carbonate should be
aware that Viactiv does contain this form of calcium. One solution
is to eat Viactiv with meals, or to try alternative forms of
calcium supplements such as calcium citrate.
</P>
<P>
   Calcium is generally better absorbed with food, so ideally
people should take supplements with meals. Those taking more than
one supplement per day should try to space them out. However, as
Weaver said, the important thing is to remember to take them in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the only time you'll remember to take a supplement is in
the morning, take it in the morning,'' Weaver said. ``But if you
can remember, space it out more so you'll absorb it more
efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   Viactiv retails for $1.49-$1.89 for a 12-pack or $6.69-$7.99 for
a canister of 60, slightly more expensive than other calcium
carbonate supplements. By comparison, a 100-count bottle of 500
milligram calcium pills costs about $6.99.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
