<HEADER>
A4057 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITH-WORKPLACE-COLUM     04-02 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR PRIVACY RIGHT MAY HAVE TO GIVE WAY TO PUBLIC GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The right to privacy is something most of think of as a
guarantee, one protected by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before the Internet, before personal information
became a commodity that is routinely bought and sold, before data
mining became a national pasttime.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phone conversations can be snatched from thin air. E-mail
correspondence is an open book for employers or clever hackers.
Marketers plunder databanks looking for information they can use to
sell you things. Even financial and medical records have unnerving
ways of getting on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy in the information age is increasingly difficult to
protect, let alone guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an exaggeration to say we're totally surrounded by
computers, and that computers watch everything we do,'' said Amitai
Etzioni, a George Washington University professor and former
adviser to the White House who explores how privacy rights and
responsibilities intersect in his book ``The Limits of Privacy''
(Basic Books, 1999, $25).
</P>
<P>
   ``We all currently live under the illusion that information
about us is stored in separate databanks,'' he said. ``In fact,
those databanks are all becoming linked into one overpowering
databank. In the 21st century, we will need to keep a very watchful
eye on how information about us is used and how it can be abused.''
</P>
<P>
   But the explosion of information about us has a potential
benefit as well. And it has raised a new kind of privacy question:
Given that we can now get information in ways previously never
imagined, does society have a responsibility to override privacy in
the interest of the common good?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the right to privacy collides with a major public
health or safety question, Etzioni said. Society needs to take a
``communitarian'' view of privacy, which means balancing rights
with responsibilities. In some cases, there may be a compelling
reason to invade someone's privacy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Medical records, for example, offer a classic case for debating
the right to privacy vs. the public good.
</P>
<P>
   Most people agree that unauthorized use of records is a
violation of privacy. If someone opens a file he's not supposed to
see and releases information he's not supposed to have, that's a
violation of privacy, Etzioni said. ``Most of those are isolated
incidents, and clearly an unauthorized use of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more concerning, however, is a less visible, but much more
widespread problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've found is there's a huge amount of authorized abuse
of medical information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Employers, for example, are frequently able to glean sensitive
health information about their employees in legal ways.
</P>
<P>
   While it's easy to see the harm that goes with such violations
of privacy, there also are cases in which protecting an
individual's medical privacy has a large social cost.
</P>
<P>
   Routine testing of infants for HIV, for example, offers a chance
to save lives. But it also violates the privacy of the mothers,
since it discloses the HIV status of the mother as well as the
infant.
</P>
<P>
   Society needs to have good criteria for determining when a
social good is more important than an individual's privacy. We
should only take steps to limit privacy if there is a serious and
well-documented problem. If withholding private information creates
a serious danger to the lives of others, for example, then society
has an obligation to consider using it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For infants with HIV, this is a no-brainer,'' Etzioni said.
Early treatment of infants identified as HIV-positive at birth can
reduce their chances of dying from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   A second factor to consider is whether the problem can be solved
some other way.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no other way to solve the problem without violating
someone's privacy, then you must find the least intrusive way to
collect the information.
</P>
<P>
   In certain industries, such as transportation, mandatory drug
testing is essential for public safety, he said. In the past, this
required people to produce urine samples in the presence of a
witness to ensure no one tried to cheat the test by substituting a
clean sample. This test can be made less invasive, however, by
simply measuring the temperature of the sample, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy is a right in our society, and one we need to protect.
But we also have to consider its costs.
</P>
<P>
   Information is giving us increasingly powerful tools, ones we're
just learning how to use, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting information is important. But so is using it
responsibly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
