<HEADER>
A4058 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-COWBOY-SPI &LR;      04-02 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-COWBOY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCUMBER'S `COWBOY WAY' LASSOS THE REALITY OF '90S LIFE ON THE
RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cowboy has the timeless allure of the tall skies of the
West. There may be no more lasting image of this region than those
lonely figures astride their horses crossing the vast landscape,
that romantic vision of freedom and solitude kept alive by
countless Western films, songs and, unfortunately, Marlboro ads.
</P>
<P>
   But David McCumber wondered if that image matched the reality of
a cowboy's life in the late 1990s. As the 46-year-old writer said
in a recent interview, ``I've always been interested in where the
Hollywood myth and the Montana reality of the cowboy intersected.
And the only way to find that, it seemed to me, was to go out and
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So McCumber, an award-winning journalist but an admitted
greenhorn of the first rank, signed on as a hand at a sprawling
Montana ranch 85 miles from his home in Livingston. He then spent
10 months doing the drudge work of hard labor and long hours. His
ranch time (precious little of it spent in the saddle) has resulted
in a fascinating new book, ``The Cowboy Way'' (Avon/Bard, 337
pages, $24).
</P>
<P>
   This is a keenly observed slice of ranch life today, a
hardscrabble antidote to cowboy myth. But McCumber's book is also a
quiet-spoken, even poetic hymn to the Western landscape, amid its
changing seasons and the camaraderie of those who still make their
living in the outdoors using their hands.
</P>
<P>
   It is a journey of many discoveries for a man who had spent much
of his life behind a desk as a writer and editor at newspapers and
magazines throughout the West, including founding Montana's ``Big
Sky Journal,'' which celebrates its state. Gone were McCumber's
days of management meetings and news-story decisions, replaced by
shoveling out stalls and caring for cattle, often with an intimacy
that seems almost parental.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to understand, by example and the lack of it,''
McCumber writes, ``the real cowboy ethos: Don't duck out on your
share of work. Don't make somebody else clean up your mistakes.
Take care of the animals and your fellow hands.''
</P>
<P>
   McCumber's account is written in first-person, but it is a
subdued first-person, by design. His focus remains squarely on the
ranch and its people, his subject rather than himself _ just as he
did in his well-received previous book that traced the
cross-country travels of a pool hustler, ``Playing Off the Rail.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because McCumber is a diligent observer, not a
dilettante, a writer committed to immersing himself in an
unfamiliar world in order to understand and portray its subculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immersing yourself is an invaluable way of gathering detail _
that's what floats the boat,'' McCumber observed. ``I enjoy finding
out everything about something and then communicating that to
people. That's the best way of reporting, whether you're covering
baseball or government. My particular pleasure is in finding little
pieces of the culture that may not be readily accessible to
everybody, but can be experienced. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a good friend once said to me, `The problem with
first-person reporting, in the George Plimpton model, is that it
comes in three flavors _ me, me and me.' I think you've got to
avoid that. Even though I'm writing in the first person, I'm trying
to write more about the world I am experiencing.''
</P>
<P>
   The cowboy world is not for the faint of heart or physique. The
long hours and hard labor lopped 40 pounds off McCumber's lanky
frame. And there was many an evening when he fell asleep with his
head on his laptop while compiling notes on the day's experiences
in the old blue trailer that served as his bunkhouse.
</P>
<P>
   His fondness for the ranch life, even with the hardships, still
is evident when McCumber talks about it many months afterward. It
is obvious that what started as a story ended up being a
life-altering experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out that I could do some things I never thought I
could, which is a pretty good thing to learn in the middle of
life,'' McCumber said. ``I found out that I could work using my
hands and my back, whether it was doing auto mechanics, mending
fences or baling hay. That gave me a real sense of accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also taught me that there are different ways of looking at
things. I am an environmentalist, a fairly ardent one, and I found
out that ranchers are also environmentalists _ they have to be;
they're in the grass business. The experience also taught me how
there are incredibly wonderful aspects of the cowboy life. There is
a lot of drudgery, backbreaking work, but also a transcendent joy.
Having fished and hiked and bird hunted, I thought I understood the
outdoors. But you can't truly understand the outdoors until you
have worked a piece of land. That's a much more profound experience
than recreating on it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCumber already has completed the experience that will be the
subject of his next book. He rescued an Edsel from a Montana farm
field and proceeded to drive it 20,000 miles on two-lane roads
around the outer edges of the United States. Mechanical problems
were surprisingly few, McCumber related, though the Edsel did
consume 280 quarts of oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
