<HEADER>
A4067 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMISH-SOCIAL-WHIRL-     04-02 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMISH-SOCIAL-WHIRL-ART-$ADV04-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOP COP: MAN IN BLACK TIE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., Pa., Fla.)   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the midst of the political crisis surrounding the
killing of Amadou Diallo by four plainclothes police officers, New
York City's police commissioner, Howard Safir, sped across the
country in a corporate jet, spent the night in a $700 Beverly Hills
hotel suite and schmoozed with biggies at the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   As might have been predicted, he was lambasted _ by editorial
writers and some public officials, who asserted that his trip
trivialized the shooting. But Safir was upholding a longstanding
tradition that came with his job: Upon becoming commissioner, he
had automatically joined the social A list, with all its
blandishments and career-threatening temptations. Like many of his
predecessors, Safir flits from opera premieres at Lincoln Center
(he showed up at ``Lizzie Borden'' on opening night) to black-tie
galas at midtown hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the situation in almost any other city in the United
States, the appointment to police commissioner in New York elevates
a onetime beat officer to a social stratosphere where the air _ and
the trophy wives _ are thinner than ether. Befriended by powerful
business executives who prize close connections to the police force
and celebrated by a city that embraces its noir crime lore, New
York's commissioners are regulars on the party circuit. William
Bratton, Safir's predecessor, even kept extra uniforms on hand at
all times: two pressed dinner jackets, one in his office and one at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton, who left the department in 1996, in part because of
questions about his acceptance of gifts of expensive travel,
remains a fixture on the social scene. He is invited to operas,
movie premieres and Oscar parties. ``But now I have to pay for the
tickets,'' he said. ``And I have the luxury of saying no.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Nachman, an expert on law enforcement-press relations who
lectures at the FBI Academy in Quantico, Va., regularly compares
notes with the police chiefs of most big American cities. He said
New York's treatment of its police commissioner is unique. ``It's
the only job in the world where, overnight, you go from clip-on
ties to Hermes ties,'' said Nachman, who is also a former editor of
The New York Post. (Police officers and officials, he noted, wear
clip-on ties so they can't be used against them as impromptu
lariats.) ``Soigne New York cleaves to its police commissioner in a
way no other city does,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton said that when he was police commissioner in Boston, he
was invited to fewer society events ``and more church socials and
more events in one-story concrete buildings.'' In New York, he
said, the commissioner goes to church socials and VFW picnics, but
is also expected to attend black-tie parties and to mingle with the
socially connected.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's reputation is burnished by the fact that the
Police Foundation, a charity that raises money for Crime Stoppers
and other police-related programs, attracts social and business
luminaries. Members of the board include Lew Rudin, the real-estate
developer; Richard Grasso, chairman of the New York Stock Exchange,
and Robin L. Farkas, a former chairman of Alexander's department
store.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Police Foundation draws the corporate community in a big
way, and with that comes the social,'' said Gregg Roberts, a vice
president of the foundation. The annual black-tie (or dress
uniform) dinner in February at Police Headquarters at 1 Police
Plaza costs $600 a plate. ``And it's a lot more fun than those
rubber-chicken dinners at the Plaza those guys are used to,''
Roberts said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Safir has close ties to the corporate community, including a
friendship with George Fellows, the president of Revlon, whose
guest he was at the Oscars. It is not clear whether that friendship
stems from Revlon's ties to the Police Department. (MacAndrews &AMP;
Forbes, the company that controls 83 percent of Revlon, employs
off-duty uniformed officers to guard its offices, and Ronald O.
Perelman, the owner of Mac-Andrews &AMP; Forbes, has a personal
security chief who was a deputy commissioner under Safir.) Safir's
trip is the subject of an ethics inquiry; he has said he did
nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Some accounts trace the origins of the socialite police
commissioner to Theodore Roosevelt. According to ``T.R.: The Last
Romantic'' (Basic Books, 1997), the social ascendancy of
commissioners began with Roosevelt in 1895, the year of his
appointment. He was out every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, being New York City police commissioner was by no
means a springboard to social prominence,'' said H.W. Brands, the
author of ``T.R.'' ``But the members of the Roosevelt family were
established members of New York society. So Roosevelt would go out
for dinner every night with his society friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt's peers ``all thought he was eccentric,'' Brands said,
but, he added, ``since then, the police commissioner's job has
taken on something of a social value.'' In other cities, the
commissioner's job is less geared toward society hobnobbing. In
Boston, said Sgt. Margot Hill, a Police Department spokeswoman,
Commissioner Paul Evans wouldn't think of watching the Oscars, let
alone attending them. ``If you said `Oscars' to him, he'd think of
Felix Unger's roommate,'' she said. ``If you were to do a story on
his social outings, you'd fall asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. McNeilly Jr., Pittsburgh's police commissioner, said
he was rarely invited to swanky social functions. But he said he
hoped to establish a police foundation similar to New York City's.
``And with that, I imagine that I, too, will have to be more
involved with the kinds of organizations and groups who are big
donors,'' he said. He would have to buy a dinner jacket, because he
doesn't own one.
</P>
<P>
   A prominent hostess who divides her time between New York and
Palm Beach, Fla., said that the sheriff of Palm Beach _ the
equivalent of the police commissioner _ is treated more like the
help than a potential dinner guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's because there's so much to buy from the police
commissioner of New York,'' she said, adding, sotto voce: ``Parking
permits.'' She was referring to the plastic police-issue cards that
some privileged New Yorkers, for reasons of security or by virtue
of great connections, place on their car dashboards so they can
park virtually anywhere. (In fact, they are not for sale.)
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, Safir's spokeswoman, had no comment about his
status as a socialite, nor would she discuss whether he had
exchanged clip-on ties for Hermes.
</P>
<P>
   But Bratton said: ``Hermes ties? I'd say I have quite a few of
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
