s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-4MANAGERS-ART     04-02 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-4MANAGERS-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR FUND MANAGERS WHO USED TECH STOCKS TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many mutual fund managers eked out small gains in the quarter
just ended, with the average domestic diversified equity fund
returning just 1.26 percent, according to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But funds in the technology sector broke out of the pack,
averaging returns of 16.35 percent. And some diversified stock
funds also leaped to the top rankings because of holdings in
Internet, cable and telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   The managers of four of the highest-ranked funds talked about
what drove their performance and looked ahead to the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bargains and Branches
</P>
<P>
   ``Our theme is how the Internet is changing our lives,'' said
Garrett Van Wagoner, who runs the $286.8 million Van Wagoner
Emerging Growth fund, the top American diversified stock fund for
the quarter, up 55.84 percent. (He also runs the category's No. 2
and 3 funds, Van Wagoner Micro-Cap and Van Wagoner Mid-Cap,
respectively.) ``People are hooking up on line, causing a
tremendous amount of data traffic growth across the country, and
many different technology sectors are benefiting from the
explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   His top ranking marks a sharp turnaround from his poor returns
in 1997 and early 1998. Van Wagoner said he had concentrated the
portfolio into just 45 stocks, but reversed course last March,
bringing the fund up to 115 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   After last year's stock market selloff, Van Wagoner bought some
semiconductor and communications stocks at bargain prices,
including RF Micro Devices and Transwitch. They proved to be big
winners in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   He also posted strong profits from telecommunications companies
that are competing with the old-line telephone companies. Among
these are Metromedia Fiber Network, which lays fiber strands in
metropolitan areas and sells capacity to providers of
telecommunications services, and Allegiance Telecom, which sells
bundled telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
   Van Wagoner has also been attracted by the content side of the
Internet. His biggest holding, a top performer this quarter, is
Onhealth Network, which runs a Web site that provides health and
fitness information. He is not taking profits on the stock, which
he says ``has a long way to go.'' But he is trimming some of those
other first-quarter winners, ``not because we think something is
wrong, but to be prudent,'' he said. ``Trees don't grow to the
sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by Biotechnology
</P>
<P>
   Neal Miller, who runs the $1.87 billion Fidelity New Millennium
fund, also went on a shopping spree after last year's market slump.
The fund rose 24.54 percent for the quarter, earning eighth place
among domestic diversified equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the performance came from biotechnology stocks. ``After
the honeymoon period with biotech companies eight years ago, they
have languished as a category,'' he said. ``Now, selective
companies are making great advances.'' One favorite is Immunex
Corp., which makes an arthritis drug recently approved by the Food
and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   He also made money in semiconductor capital equipment concerns,
which are recovering from the Asian economic crisis. ``Now, people
need more storage and faster products at the same time that fewer
people are producing them,'' he said. One favorite is Micron
Technology, which he said had tripled its market share.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet front, Miller likes CMGI Inc., a technology
investment company that helped develop Lycos and Geocities. Another
favorite is Real Networks, the leading maker of software that lets
computer users send and receive audio, video and other multimedia
services on the Web. ``Anything involving entertainment on the
Internet will probably use their product,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Cable-Cellular Mix
</P>
<P>
   Cable television stocks helped propel the $526.5 million WM
Trust II Growth fund into 12th place among American diversified
stock funds in the first quarter, with a return of 23.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable companies will be able to dramatically improve their
basic cable, video and TV offerings as they move from analog to
digital networks,'' said the fund's manager, Warren Lammert, adding
that they would be able to enter new businesses like voice
telephony and ``always on,'' or continuously connected, Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   Among his favorite stocks are Time Warner and United
International Holdings, which owns cable systems in Europe, Latin
America and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Lammert's biggest bet is in technology stocks, and his biggest
such holding is Nokia, an industry leader in cellular phone and
network equipment, which he said ``is benefiting from the growth in
cellular use.''
</P>
<P>
   His performance was also bolstered by Internet stocks (15
percent of the portfolio), particularly the bookseller Amazon.com,
as well as At Home and Excite, which are planning to merge. At Home
provides Internet services in partnership with cable companies;
Excite is the No. 2 Internet portal, after Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Looking Beyond the Net
</P>
<P>
   Despite its name, the Munder Net Net fund, which ranked third in
the first quarter among technology sector funds, with a gain of
54.10 percent, is not a pure Internet fund. ``We buy companies that
derive revenue or strategic significance from the Internet,'' said
Paul Cook, manager of the fund, which has $1.45 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   The fund invests, for example, in Ameritrade, which has a
successful online trading operation as well as a profitable
off-line brokerage business. On-line trading, Cook said, ``has a
lot of momentum because people are successful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the market reverses,'' he added, ``they might look for
investment help off line.''
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio also includes investments in electronic commerce,
which he expects to increase to 10 to 15 percent of all retailing
over the next 5 to 10 years; it now accounts for less than 1
percent. He particularly likes America Online, ``because the
relationships and deals it has struck with other e-commerce
partners make it a diversified way to get at the e-commerce
trends.''
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Verticalnet Inc., which creates Web sites that
provide information and online communication for various
industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
