<HEADER>
A4073 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTUND-INTERNATIONAL-     04-02 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTUND-INTERNATIONAL-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FUND MANAGERS FIND NEEDLES IN GLOBAL HAYSTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By RICK GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   South Korean beer. Japanese pinball. A globe-trotting British
cybergame adventuress who wears tight T-shirts and packs two
pistols.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign companies that make these products are small and
diverse, off the radar screens of many American investors. But the
forces behind the strong gains in their shares help explain why
international small-capitalization funds were an outstanding global
fund category in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Among portfolio managers who specialize in buying shares of
foreign companies, the most successful in the first quarter were
those who had researched and cherry-picked their way through
lesser-known equities, especially the stocks hurt by the
persistence of the Asian economic crisis and Japan's deep
recession. While international stock funds as a group rose 2.54
percent in the quarter, many small-cap international funds had
double-digit gains.
</P>
<P>
   These funds are volatile by nature and not for everyone. Many
suffered large losses when the Asian crisis began in mid-1997, and,
of course, it is unclear whether the advances in the most recent
quarter are sustainable.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how managers at three such funds view some of their
favorite stocks:
</P>
<P>
   Profits After a Fire Sale
</P>
<P>
   At the Oakmark International Small Cap fund, David Herro is
heavily invested in Asia, Australia and New Zealand. He said he
began to build up positions in those countries during the third
quarter of 1997; although the fund fell nearly 20 percent that
year, it rose 9.2 percent in 1998 and 24.59 percent in the first
three months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use a style that tries to buy good-quality businesses with
good-quality management at burnt-out prices,'' he said. When
markets were dropping in Hong Kong, South Korea and Thailand, he
added, ``most managers, to be frank, chickened out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this was a unique opportunity,'' he said. ``Rarely
do you get a chance to buy something at 10 to 15 cents on the
dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorite picks is Hite Brewery, a South Korean beer
maker that is the domestic market leader. Its shares have
quadrupled in value since he bought them and are up 80 percent so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
   At the worst of South Korea's difficulties, in early 1998, when
investors were dumping stocks, Hite shares were at 4,800 won, and
the company's market cap fell to $40 million. ``That's like five
Anheuser-Busch Super Bowl commercials,'' he said. ``You know that
isn't right.'' The market cap is now $148 million.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes the Hong Kong-based Giordano International, a
leading retailer of casual clothing in Asia. The stock rose 65
percent in the first quarter. Buying up Giordano shares, he said,
``was just a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Herro, based in Chicago, says the seven analysts on his team
spend about half their time in Asia, researching and visiting
companies. Contrary to many of his competitors, Herro said, he is
not afraid of wild swings in Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things turned around in the third quarter of '98 for us, based
on sticking with these companies instead of running,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinball Wizardry
</P>
<P>
   As its name implies, the Warburg Pincus Japan Small Company fund
is 100 percent invested in Japan, which has been struggling from
heavy bank debts and the worst recession since World War II.
Although that may sound like a recipe for disappointment and
disaster, its results suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   While the fund fell 1.09 percent in 1995, its first year, and
lost 13 percent in 1996 and 25 percent in 1997, it gained more than
12 percent last year and rose 35.81 percent in the first quarter of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is increasing excitement that perhaps Japan has turned
the corner, that the government has its hands around the key
issues, that perhaps the economy is near bottom,'' said Todd
Jacobson, associate portfolio manager. ``This has set the stage,
once the economy has stabilized, for exponential growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares in a diverse range of small Japanese companies already
have benefited from this expectation, he said, partly because many
started moving some time ago to cut costs and become more
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Among his favorites in this category are makers of pachinko
machines, a version of pinball that is as common in Japan as the
sushi bar. Jacobson said he liked Aruze, Heiwa and Sankyo
Company-Gunma, which are replacing many aging pachinko machines
throughout the country. Aruze's shares have risen 27 percent since
Jacobson began buying them in February. Heiwa has risen 38 percent
and Sankyo 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson also likes companies that are venturing into the
Internet, which is in the relatively early stages of development in
Japan. Unlike many American stocks in the sector, Japanese Internet
shares appear reasonably priced. Since February, when he bought
shares of JAC, a seller of used cars over the Internet, the
company's stock is up 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson, who is based in New York, says he and his colleagues
visit more than 500 Japanese companies a year. He spends at least
three months in Japan, sometimes going to four or five companies a
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a smaller-company universe, it is critically important to
do due diligence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Betting on Japan and Britain &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the T. Rowe Price International Discovery fund, Justin
Thomson also sees enormous potential value in small Japanese
companies that were battered by the country's slump. His fund,
which has about half its investments in Europe, began increasing
its Japanese holdings last October, to 25 percent from 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among his picks in Japan are Nidec, a provider of hard disk
drives for personal computers, and Nemic-Lambda, a maker of
switches and power components. Since hitting bottom in early
October, Nidec rose 64 percent and Nemic-Lambda climbed 140 percent
by the end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for increasing his exposure in Japan, he
said, is what he called the ``valuation effect'': some of these
stocks could not fall much further.
</P>
<P>
   The bet on Japan has paid off. After falling nearly 6 percent in
1997, the fund rose more than 6 percent last year and was up 15
percent in the first three months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson, based in London, said he saw a similar turnaround
trend among small British companies whose stocks fell sharply in
the third and fourth quarters of 1998. In his view, that was a good
time to be buying them.
</P>
<P>
   Among his favorite British picks is Eidos PLC, a game-software
company that created the best-selling Tomb Raider series and its
beautiful action heroine, Lara Croft. Since his fund bought Eidos
shares in the third quarter, they have nearly tripled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fantastic growth industry,'' he said. With the surge
in ownership of personal computers, the popularity of Nintendo and
Sony Playstation and the excitement over Sony's Playstation II, he
said, ``demand for high-quality games is very, very high.''
</P>
</TEXT>
