<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4074 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AURA-IMAGING-$ADV04-9     04-02 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AURA-IMAGING-$ADV04-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BODY SHOP FOR TUNING UP THAT FLABBY AURA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
(lh) 
 ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I have been called many things in my life, but I must
say, sunny has never been one of them.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine my surprise when confronted with a Polaroid of my
aura where my head and shoulders were suffused with a bright yellow
halo. ``Yellow corresponds symbolically to the welcome warmth of
sunlight,'' said the printout explaining the picture. ``Spontaneity
would best describe you.'' I had to laugh. If I could schedule a
sneeze, I would.
</P>
<P>
   I was examining my aura at the new Away Spa and Gym at the W
Hotel on Lexington Avenue, where the state-of-the-art services
include the chance to be attended to for two solid hours by someone
who never even touches you. Massage? Manicure? How passe. The thing
to do now is Aura Photographic Imaging and Analysis, followed by a
Color Hydrotherapy Wellness Bath and Pranic Healing. Which means?
</P>
<P>
   If you can't see it, we can fix it.
</P>
<P>
   These treatments are listed in Away's services under Alternative
Healing Modalities, though you don't have to be injured or ill to
partake of them. For most people, just getting through the day in
New York requires healing. So when they pay for someone to rub
their backs or feet or even their faces, for that matter, it's
understandable. But the body seems to have proved too mundane _ and
tangible _ a battlefield. Healing a person's spirit or the energy
surrounding the body is the industry's new horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Since the boom of the last five years increased the number of
day spas in Manhattan from 10 to 41, consumers are getting more
demanding _ and more easily bored. ``Spa goers have become more
sophisticated and are looking for new experiences,'' said Stephanie
Matolyak, the director of new business development at Spa Finders,
a reservations and marketing company for the industry. ``To keep
them coming back, day spas have to keep expanding their services.''
At some places, these are activities like henna tattooing and
applying hot stones to the body. At Away, it's aura imaging and
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   OK. Here's my question: If my aura is mostly sunny, with a
healthy dash of orange creativity and a thin rim of green growth
and healing, what needs fixing? It's not as if it were black and
blue.
</P>
<P>
   But logic doesn't seem to be among the modalities. Dressed in my
spa bathrobe and flip-flops, I was led to the tea bar and installed
in an easy chair with a cup of green tea. I breathed in that
peculiar spa smell: sort of like herbs, sort of like suntan oil,
sort of like Vicks Vaporub. It's like being on a tropical island
with an ear, nose and throat man.
</P>
<P>
   Iris, my practitioner, took me into the office of a sales
representative for my photo shoot. (They're a little squeezed for
space.) Iris fooled with a device labeled Aura Camera before
instructing me to place my hands on sensors atop two electronic
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   While my Polaroid developed, Iris took my printout, which came
from the machine attached to the sensors, and led me to a private
massage room while waiting for my color wellness bath to fill. We
examined the Polaroid together and she pointed out a faint wisp of
black inside the field of yellow, over my head. I started getting
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think I have a brain tumor?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, don't go there,'' she said cheerfully. ``The spot
means you are thinking of something or working on something that is
difficult and not finished.'' How did she know that? Iris said that
although she joined Away as a massage therapist, she was trained in
aura reading by a color therapist hired by the spa.
</P>
<P>
   The bath was an enormous whirlpool into which she poured a
bright green liquid. ``What is that?'' I asked suspiciously. ``Oh,
it's all natural,'' she assured me. ``You could drink it if you
wanted to.'' Why green? ``It's the healing energy around the edge
of the aura, which means it's coming to you, so we emphasize
that.''
</P>
<P>
   She turned off the lights so only two candles illuminated the
room. I laid my head back on a towel and tried to relax. I hate
baths. And in the dark, I couldn't see any color at all. When the
lights were back on, she handed me a smudged plastic strip into
which she inserted a magenta film. ``This is soothing,'' she
advised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it clean?'' I asked, which I could see offended her, so I
held it to my eyes feeling utterly foolish and thoroughly
unsoothed. Then we returned to our room for pranic healing, billed
by the spa as ``an ancient art of energy healing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now I should say that I once had my qi healed, meaning that
according to Japanese tradition, negative energy was expelled from
my body. In that instance, though I scoffed going in, my bad knee
was pain free for weeks. So I was initially optimistic reading the
literature given me by Iris, which said the word ``pranic'' comes
from the Sanskrit word for ``vital life force.'' Diseased energy
makes a person sick and appears on the ``energy body'' before
getting to the physical body. (And to think I ever worried about
silly things like germs.)
</P>
<P>
   As I lay back on a sort of hospital bed arrangement, Iris told
me to imagine a safe, beautiful place and to relax. She put on a
tape of someone repeating ``om'' and showed me a basin of salt
water into which she would dispose of my negative energy.
</P>
<P>
   I closed my eyes and imagined a beach. Then I peeked. Iris had
her own eyes closed and was concentrating mightily, making circular
motions with her hands, then a throwing-away motion over the water.
Her fingers made a whispering sound, and between that and the oms,
I did relax.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty minutes later it was over. That was it? Two hours and I
was going to leave without any human contact? She grinned. Most
people want some massage after the healing, Iris said, offering to
do a Swedish massage for half an hour. Deal.
</P>
<P>
   When she was done, I made my way to the front desk. The aura
imaging, bath, healing and massage, plus tax and a 20 percent tip,
came to $263.60.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It later occurred to me that the procedure should have included
a reshoot of my aura after the healing. But maybe it would have
looked the same. Or would it? I enlisted a friend's sister,
Deborah, to have hers photographed, too. Afterward, she called,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done anything so silly,'' she said. It turned out
that Deborah's aura initially looked like mine _ overwhelming
yellow, dash of orange. Having complained of a headache, she was
put into a blue color bath, which her practitioner admitted was
tinted with food coloring. When she said her headache was gone,
they took another photo that showed the aura had turned green and
blue. ``As soon as I was back on the street,'' Deborah said, ``my
head was pounding again.''
</P>
<P>
   I decided to call Aura Imaging Co., which manufactures the Aura
Camera, and got Robert Kaiser, a sales representative. ``How
exactly does it work?'' I asked. ``And why would a sunny aura need
to be healed?''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser explained that the camera was ``a biofeedback apparatus
that gives an electronic interpretation of what we believe the aura
would look like if we could see it _ there's nothing that exists
that can actually take a picture of your aura.'' So, what does it
do? It measures the electronic impulses on the palm, Kaiser said,
and then converts the information into an electronic frequency
displayed as colors or patterns. Oh.
</P>
<P>
   As for the yellow, Kaiser said it meant I was vibrant,
energetic, outgoing _ and stressed. He too, used to have a yellow
aura, he said, but now it was all blues and greens, which mean
contentment. What's changed? He laughed. ``I'm making a lot of
money now, so my stress level is way down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, so much for Sanskrit. In good old American capitalism,
green has always been for healing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
