<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, April 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday, nearly 2 feet of snow blanketed Flagstaff and the
adjacent mountains of northern Arizona as a powerful late season
storm swept through the Southwestern states. Saturday, the jet
stream disturbance responsible for the wintry weather will emerge
onto the Plains, setting the stage for a variety of inclement
weather.
</P>
<P>
   A stripe of heavy snow will occur from eastern Wyoming to the
western Dakotas with up to a foot of snow likely in a few locations
by evening. Snow may be especially heavy near the eastern slopes of
the Black Hills in South Dakota, where northeast winds ascending
the sloping terrain aid in further moistening the air. Meanwhile,
warm air intruding above a shallow layer of sub-freezing air will
cause a narrow corridor of sleet and freezing rain from central
Nebraska to eastern South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Very strong thunderstorms will erupt in portions of the eastern
Plains and Mississippi Valley where sultry air surging north from
the Gulf of Mexico intercepts an approaching jet stream
disturbance. A few of the storms should produce large hail and
tornadoes. Isolated potent storms may also ignite late Saturday
afternoon along a east-moving ``dry line,'' which is a boundary
separating humid air from arid air.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and chilly breezes will cover the Northeast seaboard
while farther west and south, partly sunny, warm weather affects
the southern Great Lakes and Ohio Valley. Elsewhere, high pressure
over the Bahamas will promote ample sunshine and warm conditions
near the Southeast coast and in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Equable Eureka
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, Eureka, Calif., set a record daily low of 46
degrees culminating the sixth coldest month of March at the
northern coastal town. Extremes are unusual at Eureka which has a
quintessential maritime climate, characterized by small temperature
variations from day to day and month to month. The average high in
January is 53.4 degrees, while the average high in September,
Eureka's warmest month, is 62.2 degrees. Eureka's equable climate s
due to prevailing winds from the west blowing over cool Pacific
waters that fluctuate little in temperature during the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1751EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
