<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JERSEY-CHIC-970(2TAKE     04-02 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERSEY-CHIC-970(2TAKES)-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY IS NO LONGER THE PUNCH-LINE STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday April 4)  
(rk) 
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``New York, let me take you out to New Jersey and bring New
Jersey back,'' the most popular woman in hip-hop shouted to the
sold-out Madison Square Garden theater on March 24. It was an
invitation Harrison Ford doesn't hear every day.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Jones had come to see Lauryn Hill that night, as did
Starr Jones (no relation), Natalie Portman, Casey Affleck and a
screaming throng. They heard Ms. Hill, 23, beckon her Garden
audience to the Garden State without a trace of irony or
condescension.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised (and still happily residing) in that part of
northern New Jersey called the Oranges, Ms. Hill actually likes her
home state. Her fondness is evident in her onstage patter and in
the childhood recollections of her song ``Every Ghetto, Every
City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New Jersey is the greatest place in the world,'' Ms. Hill
declared at a party after the concert. ``It's close enough to New
York, but you still have a backyard and some trees.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``It's a great place to raise kids,'' of which she
has two. As the singer, who was wearing rimless glasses and a
stone-colored parka, mingled with her well-dressed well-wishers
(Armani Fragrances sponsored the party), one had to ask what impact
her status as an out-of-the-closet Jerseyan might be having on her
home state's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   After all, ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' her first solo
CD, has sold five million copies and won the Grammy for album of
the year. Could it be that she is making it cool to be from New
Jersey?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Ms. Hill said. ``I hope I haven't made it
trashy.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows it's too late for that. New Jersey didn't become
a national punch line _ ridiculed as a repository of industrial
waste and bad taste _ without reason. The words ``New Jersey''
conjure up sights and smells for many nonresidents of the northern
stretch of the New Jersey Turnpike _ tank farm after pipeline after
brewery.
</P>
<P>
   But these days there is the whiff of something sweeter in the
air. A lot of creativity is rising from the tomato patches and the
tacky strip malls, the Pine Barrens and the parking lots to the
immediate west of New York. In recent years, an entire New Jersey
oeuvre has emerged in popular culture, with Ms. Hill just the
hip-hop tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   It has captured the attention of moviegoers, readers and couch
potatoes alike _ a post-Springsteen school that has rethought the
suburbs as a place of humor, color and intrigue. These works recast
New Jersey's little towns as Peyton Places with secrets in every
cupboard, and they raise the question: If the suburbs are so
boring, why is this stuff so fascinating?
</P>
<P>
   ``New Jersey has gone from a private shame to a juggernaut,''
said the playwright Paul Rudnick, who grew up in Piscataway.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Smith has lovingly explored slacker culture in his New
Jersey movie trilogy, ``Clerks,'' ``Mallrats'' and ``Chasing Amy.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Solondz, whose production company is based in Red Bank, has
made two films of suburban life, ``Welcome to the Dollhouse'' and
``Happiness,'' in which few characters may be enjoying the American
Dream, but none believe that Manhattan has a lock on cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of my friends can actually believe I live here,'' says a
character in ``Happiness,'' a writer played by Lara Flynn Boyle.
``But that's just because they don't get it. I'm living in a state
of irony.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, James Kaplan has written ``Two Guys From Verona,''
subtitled ``A Novel of Suburbia,'' which is just out in paperback.
It is about two middle-aged buddies who never sought to leave the
New Jersey town where they grew up, which has struck it nouveau
riche as the Dow cracks 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   All this from a state that ranks the Shop Rite ``Can-Can'' sale
among its cultural traditions. But more than anything, what has put
New Jersey on top lately is the HBO series ``The Sopranos,'' which
has taken off like a Trans Am down the parkway.
</P>
<P>
   Concluding its first season with Saturday night's operatic
finale, the show tells the story of a Prozac-popping Mafia don and
his two families _ his blood relatives and his bloodthirsty
cohorts.
</P>
<P>
   The series, which is shot on location in areas well known to its
creator, David Chase, and its star, James Gandolfini, both from New
Jersey, is the highest-rated drama on cable.
</P>
<P>
   In its 13 weeks, it has touched off the kind of enthusiasm among
hip audiences that ``Twin Peaks'' did nine years ago. If that cult
show was a Pacific Northwest riddle wrapped in a mystery inside an
enigma, ``The Sopranos'' is a suburban comedy wrapped in a mob
drama inside a cannoli.
</P>
<P>
   It's as much about New Jersey as it is about the mob. Each
episode is peppered with references to pastry shops in Nutley,
psychiatrists' offices in Montclair or formal wear places in
Paramus.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Falls of Paterson is both a beautiful and menacing
backdrop for the mob goings-on. And in Gandolfini, bearish and
balding at 37, New Jersey has found an unlikely sex symbol. His
portrayal of the sensitive (but murderous) don, Tony Soprano, is
central to the series' success.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intention is to present New Jersey as a place of contrasts,
like it really is,'' said Chase, who now resides in Los Angeles.
``I have a feeling that people think it's only a toxic dump. That's
why I include shots of the waterfall and the more bucolic scenes.
For such a small place, it has a lot of facets to it. And that's
only northern New Jersey. I wish we could go down the shore, but on
our budget we can't, sort of like when I was in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Clifton and North Caldwell, Chase said, New Jersey
seemed ``very exciting and very mysterious,'' not dull and
predictable as many New Yorkers like to believe. ``There's
something sophisticated about the place, strangely enough,'' he
said. ``I think there's a certain savvy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jenny DeMonte, the editor of New Jersey Monthly, said that
sophistication has crept slowly over the state in the last two
decades, as affluence has brought higher home prices, better
restaurants, more museums and upscale shopping. ``Have you been to
Short Hills mall?'' she said. ``It's outrageous.'' Ms. DeMonte said
that newcomers sometimes still labor under the state's tawdry
image. ``There are a lot of people who move out here to their big
house in Summit who are in denial,'' she said. ``It's as if they
don't really live in New Jersey. But after three or four years,
they realize not only is it OK, it's really great. We help them
work through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Working through their problems with New Jersey is what many who
once hated the state say they've done. Deborah Harry, the New Wave
goddess, is finally admitting _ after all the peroxide and
posturing of the 1970s and '80s _ that she's really just a
``tomato'' (her word) from Paterson, who spent her youth on ``this
section of street up in Totowa where all the slutty girls would
walk around and meet boys.'' So she confesses to an interviewer in
the March issue of Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of funny that I've come around to this Jersey
consciousness and appreciation of my Jersey background,'' Ms. Harry
is quoted as saying. ``You come through all these stages of trying
to be this and trying to be that, just to end up at a state of
learning to appreciate what you really are.'' Her new album with
her old group Blondie is called ``No Exit.'' She, however, is from
Exit 18 on the turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   If New Jersey chic is on the rise, Vanity Fair magazine gets
some credit for starting the ball rolling. A little more than three
years ago, it ran an article titled ``Garden State Babylon,'' which
listed, by turnpike exit, more than 120 celebrities, from Charles
Addams to Pia Zadora, who hail from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   It dubbed the state not only ``the most ravaged of the original
13 Colonies,'' but also ``the nation's leading exporter of
celebrities.'' Diverse ones, too, not just Connie Francis and Lola
Falana, but also Meryl Streep and Martha Stewart. For every Joe
Piscopo, Robert Blake and Bruce Willis, there's a Jack Nicholson,
Tom Cruise and Ed Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Stewart, the host of ``The Daily Show With Jon Stewart'' on
Comedy Central and a native of Lawrence Township, maintains that
the reason people make fun of New Jersey is because outsiders see
only the worst of it through their car windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the `Elephant Man' syndrome _ until you get to know him,
you don't know he's a pretty good guy,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   But he would have it no other way. ``Let people believe the
Hamptons are where it's at,'' he said. ``I would ultimately like to
find a place down the shore and live there. This area is more
comfortable to me than anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``54,'' last year's film about Studio 54, Ryan Phillippe
plays a naive New Jersey pretty boy plucked out of the crowd behind
the velvet rope to become a bartender at the disco.
</P>
<P>
   He falls for a soap-opera actress with the same roots, played by
Neve Campbell. The film portrays New York City as glamorous but
phony. New Jersey, by contrast, is mundane but fundamentally
decent.
</P>
<P>
   After he has witnessed the elitism, the drug taking and the
ruthless social climbing, he learns to appreciate his home state.
When federal agents close the disco, Phillippe is tossed out
shirtless into the cold, and wraps himself in a garbage bag. Ms.
Campbell steps out of the back of a limousine wearing a fur.
``Let's face it,'' she tells him. ``We're Jersey.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
