</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOLUTION IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The success of the Dayton peace accords, which ended the war in
Bosnia, may have led the United States and its NATO allies into
drawing wrong conclusions about Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   One of the myths of the Bosnian war is that the NATO bombing of
the Bosnian Serbs in the summer of 1995 caused them to sue for
peace. That so-called ``lesson of Bosnia'' was applied to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Bosnian Serbs had already been beaten when the
bombing came, with the US-fortified armies of Croatia and the
Bosnian Muslims rolling them up on a wide front. They had already
signaled their willingness to stand down if they could get their
own Bosnian Serb republic.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bosnia, Kosovo is a province of Serbia with great
historic and emotional symbolism. Slobodan Milosevic rose to power
on the issue of protecting the Kosovo Serbs, and they cannot be
sold out as easily as were the Bosnian Serb leaders, whom Milosevic
despised and wanted to undercut. Dayton offered Milosevic the
carrot of a Serb entity. The Rambouillet format offered only the
humiliation of a NATO occupation followed by Kosovar independence
within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with NATO's miscalculations and Milosevic's hideous mass
expulsion of Albanian Kosovars, the equation that existed at
Rambouillet has changed, and a similar agreement may no longer be
possible. An effort should be made toward a face-saving formula
that would scrap the diktats of Rambouillet and offer Serbia a deal
whereby independence for Kosovo would be put off indefinitely and
Albanian Kosovars could return under the protection of an
international force not made up of American, British, French and
German soldiers _ Greece, Italy, even Russia might play a role
instead _ and Kosovo's pre-1989 autonomy would be restored under
the leadership of Ibrahim Rugova, the Kosovar moderate.
</P>
<P>
   It is nauseating to have to make a deal with Milosevic, but what
is needed now are cool heads to stop the great tragedy that is
unfolding and prevent the tragedies that will come if the war
continues much longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1758EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
