<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENIUM-RELIGION-NY     04-02 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENIUM-RELIGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOCALYPSE WHEN?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apocalypse? Now? It depends who you're talking to. One in four
Christians believes that Jesus will return in their lifetime, an
Associated Press poll reported in 1997. The idea that the
apocalypse and the coming of Jesus will occur on Jan. 1, 2000 is
derived _ imperfectly, perhaps _ from the Bible, which nowhere
gives an exact date for the event.
</P>
<P>
   But Muslims, Hindus, Buddhists and Zoroastrians also have ideas
about end of the world. Ancient Greeks, Egyptians and American
Indians all had apocalyptic beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars say that Zoroastrianism, founded by the Iranian
prophet Zarathustra (or Zoroaster, as the Greeks called him) around
1300 B.C., laid the foundation for Judeo-Christian teachings about
the apocalypse. Zoroastrians ``taught that the world has a
beginning and an end and forms the field of a cosmic battle between
good and evil,'' between Ahura Mazda, the Lord of Wisdom, and
Ahriman, who is wicked, said James Russell, a professor at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   Zoroaster never specified a date for the world's end. But ``he
suggested it would end with the coming of a savior; and that the
world would then be cleansed of death and wickedness and people
would rise from the dead,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoroaster's followers later said the world would last 12,000
years; the final 6,000 years represent human history. ``The process
of apocalypse is played out over the final 3,000 years of the human
era with three saviors,'' said Russell. The final savior, and most
important, is Astvat Ereta whose name means ``righteousness
embodied.'' Like Jesus, Astvat Ereta had a miraculous birth; his
virgin mother was impregnated with Zoroaster's seed while bathing
in a lake.
</P>
<P>
   Zoroastrians believe the wicked will be judged and punished in
an ordeal of molten metal. Evil will be destroyed, and purified
sinners will be renewed for eternity. A minority of Zoroastrians
believe that humanity is in the final phase of the 3,000 years.
But, said Russell, ``Most Zoroastrians don't think about the end
too much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The date when the world absolutely ends is the spring equinox
of the 12,000th year from the creation of the universe,'' Russell
said. ``The problem is, no one knows exactly what year that was.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars say Zoroastrianism found its way into Old Testament
accounts of the apocalypse, which were supposed to console Jews in
their suffering. The Book of Daniel, for instance, offered hope to
Jews persecuted during the second century B.C. In the New
Testament, Jesus draws on the Old Testament Book of Isaiah to
describe his apocalyptic return. When Jesus failed to come as soon
as his followers had hoped, they focused on his eventual return,
which is described allegorically in the Book of Revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Islam generally ties the end of the world to the Second Coming
of Jesus, whom Muslems see as a prophet. ``The Trumpet shall be
blown,'' says the Koran, ``and the eyes of sinners will turn blue
with terror.''
</P>
<P>
   But Islam has never been preoccupied with the apocalypse, says
Peter Awn, a professor at Columbia University. Most Islamic
traditions affix no date to it. ``Only God knows when that will
occur,'' Awn said.
</P>
<P>
   As the end approaches, Muslims believe, there will be a period
of moral decay. The demons Gog and Magog (who are also in the Book
of Revelation and rabbinic literature) will break through a barrier
of iron and molten copper.
</P>
<P>
   A one-eyed figure, Dajjal, resembling the Antichrist, will bring
chaos and destruction. Eventually, Dajjal will be slain by Jesus,
Muslims say, and God will reward the good with paradise and condemn
the evil to hell.
</P>
<P>
   In the Shiite tradition of Islam (accounting for about 15
percent of Muslems), a savior, the Imam Mahdi, ``the rightly guided
one whose return everyone is waiting for'' and who is a direct
descendant of the prophet Mohammed, initiates the end time. The
majority of Muslims have a tradition of the Mahdi as a human
political and religious leader who comes every 100 years or so to
renew the community.
</P>
<P>
   In Hinduism, there are several cycles of time, hundreds of
thousands of years long, and there are several Doomsdays. Usually,
doomsdays are preceded by a period of moral decay. Eventually, the
world is destroyed by fire and flood. Most Hindus affix no date to
the end. Each cycle, or ``kalpa,'' has four ages. We are now in the
fourth age, the ``kali yuga'' age, said Wendy Doniger, a professor
at the University of Chicago. It is ``the lousy age.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinduism has many sects, but there is no figure exactly like the
Messiah, though Hindus consider Jesus a saint. ``Many comparisons
have been made between Christ and the Hindu deity, Krishna,'' said
John Hawley, a professor at Barnard College. Many consider him an
incarnation of the great god Vishnu. Krishna, said Hawley, is ``a
god of love who wishes to protect his devotees and to save the
world from destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu god Kalki, a looming presence, another incarnation of
Vishnu, is also an apocalyptic figure who will destroy the present
cosmos. Kalki is sometimes represented as riding a white horse and
carrying a sword, reminiscent of the horsemen of the apocalypse in
the Bible. ``Kalki draws down the curtain on time as we know it,''
said Hawley. ``And sometimes reopens it immediately to a period of
prosperity and peace, when the troublemakers are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinduism has no single day of judgment. ``By contrast, at the
end of an individual life you have a judgment figure holding a book
which contains an accounting'' of that person's life, Hawley said.
Hinduism has many heavens and hells. One hell has trees with leaves
of razor blades. But at the end of each doomsday cycle, the
universe, and all heavens and hells, are destroyed. Some Hindus
believe there are ``millions of years of quiescence in which the
god Vishnu sleeps,'' said Ms. Doniger, ``and he awakens and we all
awaken.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism teaches that the universe never begins or ends. ``The
cosmos we live in is only one of an infinite number,'' said Frank
Reynolds, a professor at the University of Chicago. ``There
definitely is an apocalyptic end to our world, by wind, fire or
water.'' But there is no date attached to the destruction of our
world, many Buddhists believe, and the universe endures.
</P>
<P>
   One Buddhist metaphor speaks of the afterlife as a passage into
heaven or hell or another human existence. The individual's destiny
is determined by karma, the effect of his deeds. This passage is
sometimes represented as a judgment, presided over by a divine
figure. There is no single judgment day in most Buddhist sects.
Heavens and hells are usually temporary states until the individual
is consigned to another rebirth. The goal is to escape suffering
and attain nirvana, a condition beyond being or nonbeing.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism contains varying notions of a savior: the historical
Buddha, Gautama, lived some 2,500 years ago. As time passes
Buddhism will decline. At the end of 5,000 years, ``Gautama's
relics will come together, he will preach a sermon, and then be no
more,'' said Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Some Buddhists believe that another Buddha named Maitreya will
establish an ideal society. ``There will be easier access to
nirvana,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain Buddhist groups have believed that Maitreya's coming
was imminent, particularly in periods of oppression,'' Reynolds
said.
</P>
<P>
   As in most religions, it is in times of chaos and moral collapse
that people long for a Messiah to relieve them from their pain and
suffering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
