<HEADER>
A4088 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAIN-JOURNALIST-2TAK     04-02 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAIN-JOURNALIST-2TAKES-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGING TESTIMONY HAMPERS MURDER INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 4)   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOTLAN, Mexico _ Inside a tiny jail cell in this small rural
town, two Huichol Indian men accused of killing journalist Philip
True have changed their story for a third time, confounding even
their lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   They now say they didn't kill the San Antonio Express-News
correspondent, and that they only briefly saw him hiking through
their village in the Sierra Madre Occidental mountains of Jalisco
state one sunny morning in early December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you the truth, I saw him walking by when I was
vaccinating my cows. That's all,'' said Juan Chivarra de La Cruz,
speaking from his cell. ``I never saw the gringo before in my life.
I didn't touch him. I didn't kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   True, 50, was on a 100-mile hike to photograph and write about
the Huichol Indians who live in remote villages along the rugged
mountain range that spans four western states: Jalisco, Zacatecas,
Durango and Nayarit.
</P>
<P>
   An experienced hiker and camper, True departed Nov. 29,
estimating the solo trip would last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   But he barely made it one-third of the way. His body was found
on Dec. 16, buried in a shallow grave after an agonizing, weeklong
search by relatives, friends, colleagues and the Mexican police and
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   He had been dead for about a week.
</P>
<P>
   Chivarra and his brother-in-law Miguel Hernandez de la Cruz were
arraigned in the death on Dec. 28 after the police said the men
confessed to strangling True, allegedly because they were angered
he was hiking and taking photographs without permission from the
local Huichol authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, they still admitted killing True, but they told
reporters and a criminal court judge that it was because the
journalist threatened family members.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm afternoon last week in this quiet Jalisco town of
16,000 people, Chivarra and Hernandez changed their story anew,
saying they confessed to the crime only because they were beaten
and tortured by men in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   For three months, dozens of reporters have travelled to this
remote corner of Mexico to question the two suspects about the
mysterious murder that has made headlines around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Chivarra said he had grown sick of talking to the news media and
vowed not to give any more interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go away! Leave!'' Chivarra shouted before sauntering back to
his cell.
</P>
<P>
   But Chivarra, 28, was curious. He was also glad for the
attention that relieves the monotony of prison life.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually returned to inspect the reporters, grabbing a pair
of black sunglasses from a guard and prancing for the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me money!'' he demanded, his hands gripping bars chipped
with blue paint.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez shyly peered from behind a wall, laughing at
Chivarra's antics.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of their lawyer on day last week, they officially
amended their initial confession, apparently alleging it was made
under duress, the judge in the case said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legally they have a right to do that,'' Judge Felix Enrique
Aguiar said. ``One of them said he had an encounter with Mr. True,
but obviously he is saying he didn't kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Chivarra and Hernandez said they were tortured into confessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit us a lot. So I decided to say, `Yes, yes, we did
it,''' Chivarra said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hung me by the neck from a tree,'' added Hernandez, 24,
who rarely speaks, deferring to his brother-in-law. ``If you are
hanging from a tree, you will agree to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They trapped us like cats,'' Chivarra said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' are uniformed authorities. Chivarra said they were all
the same to him: soldiers or the police, and he doesn't know which
arm of the law apprehended them.
</P>
<P>
   From their mountain ranch in the municipality of Mesquitic, the
two were taken to Guadalajara, the capital of Jalisco state. In
January, they were moved to Colotlan pending a ruling in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Colotlan was chosen because it is the nearest city to the crime
scene, which officials here say is about a three-day's drive away.
</P>
<P>
   Famous for its beaded leather belts made out of the agave plant,
Colotlan is 150 miles north of Guadalajara. It is accessible only
through narrow mountain roads that traverse the states of Jalisco
and Zacatecas, past canyons, cactus and grassy fields.
</P>
<P>
   Chivarra and Hernandez are in a rudimentary municipal cell
painted in blue and white, sharing space with five other men
charged with murder _ four of them Huichols.
</P>
<P>
   It is here that Aguiar will decide the fate of the two men.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been thrown into a bit of a whirl following the
reported discovery of True's journal, which had been locked up as
evidence along with a backpack and other True belongings.
</P>
<P>
   The diary, read by a Newsweek correspondent, apparently mentions
Chivarra's anger at True for not having approval from Huichol
authorities to travel through their land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks bad for a bit,'' True wrote, according to Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
