<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-FUNDING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET FLAP OVER FUNDING FOR DISABLED INTENSIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ Each day a health-care worker bathes and feeds
10-year-old Janelle Epps, who is developmentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The Olathe girl doesn't know that a budget debate raging in the
Legislature could threaten the quality of care she gets. But her
mother, Susan Epps, is painfully aware.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned and upset,'' Epps said. ``These services
are critical for my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   As the budget debate heated up this week, state welfare
officials cut off payments to many contract providers, including
Johnson County Developmental Supports, which provides Janelle's
health-care worker.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders in the Legislature labeled the action a
``scare tactic,'' and advocates for those with disabilities called
it political terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   For months, advocates have said that Gov. Bill Graves' proposed
budget for the Department of Social and Rehabilitation Services was
inadequate and could result in cuts in services for more than 330
developmentally disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Laing, director of InterHab, an organization that supports
people with disabilities, said the budget did not even provide
enough money to keep services going through June 30, the end of the
budget year.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to solve those financial woes, a coalition of
conservative Republicans led by state Rep. Phill Kline of Shawnee
and House Democrats on Friday cut about $50 million from Graves'
budget. But then they put $30 million of that back in the budget
for mental-retardation and mental-health services. Advocates for
those groups were jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   Social and Rehabilitation Services officials, however, said the
cuts included some funding for the remainder of this year, creating
a $29 million budget deficit that has forced them to stop provider
payments.
</P>
<P>
   A showdown is scheduled today when those budget changes are
debated by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   Graves called the changes a ``cheap theatrical stunt'' aimed at
disrupting an orderly conclusion to the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am truly disappointed that Democrats and a small group of
Republicans in the Kansas House have made a conscious decision to
hijack the budget process,'' Graves said.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Rep. Bill Reardon, a Kansas City, Kan., Democrat,
to accuse the governor of using ``theatrical tactics'' by stopping
provider payments and frightening those who depend on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take personal offense at the suggestion that this (budget
deal) is theatrical,'' Reardon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4095 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAIN-JOURNALIST-2NDT     04-02 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAIN-JOURNALIST-2NDTAKE-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
  
 COLOTLAN, Mexico: x x x according to Newsweek.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The authorities who first investigated the case in Guadalajara
and drew up charges against the Huichols said they knew about the
journal but didn't think it was important.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow waterproof journal is listed as one of the items
recovered from the scene. Others were True's passport, credit
cards, camping gear and two books, ``In Cold Blood'' and ``The
Right Stuff,'' among other items.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were dozens of papers in the backpack. We looked at the
journal. There was nothing important there,'' said one of the
prosecutors with the state attorney general's office in
Guadalajara, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But in Colotlan, prosecutor David Magdaleno Rodriguez did think
the diary was important and made an official motion to read it.
With the help of a translator, Rodriguez said he would pore over it
after it arrives from Guadalajara.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have yet to determine if the diary favors the
prosecution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said he would also request special fiber tests on the
neckerchief True wore. The Huichols said previously they choked the
correspondent with his own neckerchief.
</P>
<P>
   Under Mexican law, a judge has a year from the day of an arrest
to rule on a case, which is done by reading reams of evidence, not
through a U.S.-style trial. In this case, the evidence includes two
volumes of testimony, photographs and two varying autopsy reports.
</P>
<P>
   The two autopsies performed on True offer conflicting results.
</P>
<P>
   The first, conducted in December by Jalisco state coroner Mario
Rivas Souza, concluded True's death was a homicide from
strangulation.
</P>
<P>
   But a second autopsy performed in January by examiners with the
federal attorney general's office in Mexico City concluded True
died from edema in the lungs, an excessive accumulation of fluid,
and from a blow to the head. It also said True had exorbitant
amounts of alcohol in his blood.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the second autopsy have not been released, but Aguiar
allowed the San Antonio Express-News to read and photograph the
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two opinions. The federal examiners report is very
clear: there was no asphyxia.'' Aguiar said. ``The state medical
examiner, meanwhile, is categorical that death was due to
strangulation and hypothermia. So we have to determine who is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a Jalisco state penal code, a third opinion must be sought
when there are two varying accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Aguiar said the next step is finding a forensic specialist to
read the two autopsies and come to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of alcohol has been controversial because True was
known as only a moderate drinker.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts have noted that a body can produce alcohol after
death, especially if it has been outside and decomposing for some
time, as was the case with True.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very delicate case. That's why we have to act with
the utmost care and try to find a forensic specialist who is not
biased in any way,'' Aguiar said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The judge also said the case has been slightly complicated by an
appeal made by the suspects' new attorney, Juan Pedro Salas
Castillo, who is contesting the incarceration of the Huichols while
a judgment on the case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is very clear that a translator be present whenever
the declaration of an indigenous person is taken by the courts,''
Salas said. ``To this date, they have never had an interpreter ...
They speak Spanish, but not 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Salas said the meanings of certain words are different in
Huichol and in Spanish. An example, he said, is the word for neck.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the two had four court-appointed attorneys. Salas is
their first private lawyer, but it was unknown who or what
organization hired him. Salas declined to say.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded the case is becoming more difficult because of the
changing testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give me different versions. This makes it very hard to
defend them,'' Salas said. ``But historically this is because they
don't trust outsiders, they don't understand the law and they've
been abused throughout history.''
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators and neighbors who knew Chivarra
before his arrest, the suspect was known as a small-time thug who
stole farm animals from neighbors. One man who knew him in the
village of Amoltita said Chivarra, like many other Huichols of the
Sierra Madre, cultivated small plots of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   But Chivarra denied it, saying he would have been expelled from
the community under Huichol laws.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has no illusions about ever returning to his family.
Though court records say he had a pregnant wife named Yolanda who
reportedly witnessed True's slaying, Chivarra denied that as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not my wife. She's my aunt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chivarra said he thought he would never go free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I will die here,'' he said. ``I think they will kill
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
