<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDEN RITE CAN TURN DEVASTATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ From nearly 10 miles away, the orange glow could be
seen across the hills, and the first faint smell of wood smoke
filtered into the car.
</P>
<P>
   We knew immediately that one of the Ozarks' oldest seasonal
rituals was being played out. Along the back roads of our country
neighborhood, resident incendiarists had begun putting a match to
the springtime meadows and woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   They say it kills ticks, makes pasture. It does neither, but
custom and belief are more persuasive than fact. So each year, just
before greening, the fire setters are at work. Or if the spring is
wet and unfavorable for it, they might wait until autumn to torch
the land.
</P>
<P>
   One does well, in those seasons, to sniff the air at night
before retiring, and mark the direction of the wind. Because a
little grass fire, unattended, might find its way to timber. And
mounting up then, generate gale winds of its own, and come whirling
like an orange storm to consume everything before it.
</P>
<P>
   That's not hyperbole. It has happened. You may be sure it will
happen again.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of going directly to the cabin, we drove the gravel
byways to the west and north, where the burning lighted the night.
</P>
<P>
   The breeze of late afternoon had fallen, so the hazard was less.
The line of the fire could be seen creeping slowly down the faces
of the hills. Behind it, the ground was charred black, and hollow
den trees guttered like candles in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   In house clearings as we drove, sometimes we could see the
figures of men, silhouetted against the fire's glow. Had they set
the blaze? Or were they defending their woodland homesteads against
it? There was no way to know.
</P>
<P>
   I remember an April not many years ago _ three or four at most _
when a fire in that neighborhood raged over more than 6,000 acres,
out of control for nearly a week.
</P>
<P>
   The second night, it crested a ridge just to the south _ burning
high as a barn and roaring like some great animal as it advanced on
the house across the road. I could see the flames over the roof; it
came that near.
</P>
<P>
   Then, from nowhere it seemed, truckloads of men appeared with
backpack sprayers and rakes and somehow turned it back. Otherwise
it would have taken the neighbor's house and, vaulting the road,
burned my cabin, too.
</P>
<P>
   I know conservation and wildlife people insist there's a place
for fire _ managed fire _ in forest and prairie ecology. And I
don't doubt the truth of that. But still I fear fire for what I've
seen it do, and nearly do.
</P>
<P>
   The conflagrations that sweep across that reach of country are
not, for the most part, /{managed/} affairs. Some are set
maliciously, some for thrills. More often they escape through
carelessness, or by the rotten luck of a suddenly rising wind.
</P>
<P>
   They are a surviving relic from generations ago _ a time when
hills scalped for their timber were overgrown with a nightmare
jungle of sprouts. Lacking any mechanical or chemical means of
contending with that growth, the early Ozarkers resorted to fire.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday I met a young neighbor as he was leaving in his pickup
for work. He told me he'd fought fire until 2 o'clock in the
morning _ and showed it by his haggard look. When finally they'd
stopped it, he said, it was only two turns up the road.
</P>
<P>
   There are other ways now to clear the land and keep it open.
Much has changed. But cultural memory is powerful, and the habit of
seasonal burning is very old.
</P>
<P>
   Each spring, we smell that history on the night air, and pray
it's not too near.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
