<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 A little levity helps the bottom line  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Should we wonder why April Fools' Day and Fun at
Work Day are the same day?
</P>
<P>
   Naaaah.
</P>
<P>
   They're not related. Nobody's going to come up in the middle of
your Fun at Work Day party and say: ``Just kidding. Everybody back
to work.''
</P>
<P>
   What's that? You're not having a Fun at Work Day party? Well,
send out for a pizza, quick. Ask them to spell out ``fun'' with the
pepperoni.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies actually are having Fun at Work Day parties. If
you're driving by the Sprint building at 8140 Ward Parkway between
11 a.m. and 1 p.m. today, you'll see the parking lot beach party.
</P>
<P>
   That party and activities at other Sprint locations are little
interludes designed to relieve stress and keep morale up, said
Traci Mendez, Sprint marketing manager for new business development
and a Fun at Work organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Around the work world, more organizations are sending the
message that fun and work aren't mutually exclusive. At least, they
shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Weinstein, motivational speaker and author of /{Work Like
Your Dog/}, created Fun at Work Day four years ago. He wanted to
spread the word that you can take your work seriously without
always being sober about it. In other words, ``fun at work'' isn't
an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   Some workplaces didn't need Weinstein to tell them that a little
levity goes a long way toward enhancing productivity, and retaining
and attracting workers. There are work sites that build
celebrations into their workdays and encourage spontaneous
``disruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other workplaces desperately need a Fun at Work Day
infusion, though. I repeatedly hear of workers berated by bosses
who heard laughter coming from a cubicle or conference room. Oh,
no! They were laughing!
</P>
<P>
   If that's a workplace crime, give me the arsenic now.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent career planning seminar given by Les Griffen, who
several years ago entered the career counseling industry after
losing a longtime corporate job, he shared his process of
self-discovery, his transition from career ladder to
entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that he made less money than he used to but that
it didn't matter. He is having a blast. He loves what he does. It
doesn't even feel like work.
</P>
<P>
   People stuck in jobs they hate with people they dislike can't
imagine that work can be fun. It may take the kind of
self-discovery Griffen preaches. It may take the kind of
concentrated public relations gimmick Weinstein used to launch Fun
at Work Day.
</P>
<P>
   But the important message is that individuals can create their
own fun. If you're sure your employer would never allow fun _ my
sincere condolences _ Weinstein says it is possible to sneak some
in.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking rent-a-carnival here. We're talking little
gestures that slowly build atmosphere. Weinstein suggests ordering
(or bringing from your garden) a bouquet. Give it to a co-worker to
enjoy, with the understanding that in half an hour, he or she must
pass it on to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   After an eight-hour day, 16 persons will have had a
day-brightener for a while, plus the knowledge that someone else
appreciates them. And that's more fun than a lot of workers usually
get at work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
