<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4103 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-JONES04-COX     04-02 1783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-JONES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Astride two cities, Jomandi's Jones goes for `Slam' dunk
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's 10 a.m., his messages are waiting, he's looking
for his coffee mug, he's trying to get ready for rehearsal. Another
part of his mind is on the trip to Disney World he'll take with
Angeline, his 3-year-old daughter, as soon as ``Slam,'' his new
musical drama set in a nightclub poetry slam, opens Friday in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Another mellow day in the life of Thomas W. Jones II has begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, don't bother me with that,'' cries the director to a
Jomandi Productions staffer asking his decision on a business
matter. ``I'm Florida-bound, man! I got carnivals to go to! I got
bears to see!
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is being an adult,'' Jones adds, flopping down in his
chair in Jomandi's converted-warehouse offices in northeast
Atlanta, as if the day has already defeated him. ``I hate it!''
</P>
<P>
   Jones lets out a laugh _ he's kidding, of course. He's laughing
at his own expense, since his autobiographical ``Hip 2: Birth of
the Boom'' (1994) suggested that ``being an adult'' is a fairly
recent development in the life of this ever-cool, earring-wearing
bachelor of 42. Afro Jo, the Everyman character he portrayed in
that musical play, writhed in anguish when he learned that his
girlfriend had aborted their child. Seeing that play helps one
understand the depth of joy that Jones feels today, finally, as a
father, sharing custody of Angeline with her mother, his former
companion.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a chronic kidder, is also kidding
</P>
<P>
   about being overwhelmed. Having his mind in many places at once
is nothing unusual for this na-
</P>
<P>
   tive New Yorker who founded Jomandi with Marsha Jackson-Randolph
20 years ago. He's Atlanta's most versatile theater artist, skilled
as actor, director, playwright, composer and critical observer of
the art form. While plays that Jones has written and/or directed
for Jomandi since 1990 _ ``Wizard of Hip,'' ``Hip 2,'' ``Bessie's
Blues'' _ have been well-received in other cities, it's in
Washington that he's found his second artistic home. He simply can
do no wrong there. The Studio Theatre, a D.C. playhouse with a
racially mixed audience, invites him back again and again, gigs
that have earned him Helen Hayes Awards in the past and may again.
He is nominated as actor (in ``Waiting for Godot'') and director
(``Seven Guitars'') this year. The awards will be presented May 3.
He'll open ``Slam'' at the Studio on June 9.
</P>
<P>
   While Jomandi has had its share of letdowns at home in recent
seasons (``Keep the Faith,'' Jeff Stetson's bio-musical about Adam
Clayton Powell), Jones seems to get his warmest notices when he
takes Atlanta artists to collaborate with their D.C. brethren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington does not have a Jomandi (a theater run by, and
primarily for, African-Americans), and that's a great frustration
in a city with so many fine black artists,'' says Bob Mondello, who
covers D.C. stages for the weekly City Paper and the arts beat for
National Public Radio, suggesting that Jones helps fill a need for
black-written, black-directed work. ``Beyond that, Tom's simply a
critics' darling up here. Everything he does jumps off the stage at
you.''
</P>
<P>
   A tale of two cities
</P>
<P>
   It can be a bit disorienting, Jones says, after being praised by
The Washington Post and hobnobbing with D.C.'s arts luminaries at
the Kennedy Center, to return to Atlanta, where his accomplishments
are still a well-kept secret in some quarters, especially among
white audiences. He's not a local crossover celebrity on the level
of, say, Kenny Leon, artistic director of the much larger Alliance
Theatre. And yet Jones is arguably just as accomplished nationally,
earning his first positive New York Times review (for 1990's
``Wizard of Hip'' off-Broadway) the same year Leon's Alliance debut
was praised in Time magazine. In fact it was Jones who gave Leon
some of his breakthrough acting jobs at Jomandi in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than grouse about his visibility, Jones stays in
character and makes it a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can come back from D.C. and say to folks, `See? I'm not an
idiot!'' Jones cries, once again laughing at his own expense. ``I
have reviews! I am loved!''
</P>
<P>
   The Amherst (Mass.) College grad, a doctor's son who moved to
Atlanta as a teenager in the '70s and returned after college with
then-sweetheart Marsha Jackson to start Jomandi, says he's never
been seriously tempted to move to Washington despite his standing
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aside from the fact that I love Atlanta, I'd always rather do
something (premiere an original work) at Jomandi first, without the
pressure of that media spotlight,'' Jones says, sitting down with a
mug of coffee at the prop bar on ``Slam's'' rehearsal set. ``The
seduction (of larger cities) can be dangerous. I mean, if The New
York Times comes the first night and says it's a piece of
(expletive), then for the foreseeable future it remains (that) in
the eyes of the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, that infectious, nothing-rattles-me laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Back to his poet's roots
</P>
<P>
   Starting out on familiar, friendly ground is important for
``Slam,'' Jones says, for a couple of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   It profiles a group of itinerant poets _ ``spoken word artists''
ranging from an angry black male of hip-hop rhythm to an older
white woman with a lyrical bent _ and Jones is taking a huge risk
by writing all their diverse verse. Poetry was his first vocation,
out of college. But when he submitted some of his verses to poet
Sonia Sanchez, his professor and mentor, ``Her comment was, `Not
everybody has to write for a living, you know.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This memory brings another self-deprecating laugh from the
artist. But he's confident in his ability to capture eight
different voices. He's done his homework. Prowling poetry clubs in
Atlanta (Mekka, Red Light Cafe, Yin Yang Music Cafe) and other
cities, Jones was struck by the rhythmic riffs, the spontaneous
versification of controversial, hot-off-the-press issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody in the club might throw out an idea,'' he says, ``and
there's a competition, everyone improvises on it, like jazz artists
working a theme.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Chandra Currelley, who plays the role of the
proprietress of the ``Slam'' club, can trace the show's roots to
the '80s, when Jones listened to her _ the performer with the
larger-than-life voice and persona _ sing at Walter Mitty's, a
Midtown club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom used to watch my set from the corner table _ my table, I
called it, because he knew that's where I'd go to sit on my
break,'' she says with a chuckle. ``Mitty's was the kind of
intimate place where I'd have to be careful how I breathed or the
cigarette smoke from the guy in the front row would go right up my
nose!
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see Tom was computing something in his brain, even
while joking around,'' Currelley adds. ``He's grown as an artist
but in some way is still that same crazy Tom. One day he said, `I'm
writing a show for you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's a key to Jones' success: his ability to grow original
material organically, so to speak, from the talents around him. He
saw that Atlanta singer-actress Bernardine Mitchell was, physically
and vocally, the incarnation of Bessie Smith and voila _ ``Bessie's
Blues.'' He took specifics of his own life and _ boom _ created a
universal black male, Afro Jo, hero of ``Wizard'' and ``Boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Big changes, catching hell
</P>
<P>
   In just the past year, however, Jones has looked beyond the
African-American experience to examine its relationship to other
communities. In a sense, he's feeling a similar pressure to
``respond to a changing, multicultural America'' (his words) that
Leon and his mostly white Alliance board have struggled to
negotiate for the past decade. Jones and Jomandi co-director
Jackson-Randolph agreed that it was important to reach out with
last fall's ``Kiss of the Spider Woman.'' Not only was it a
production whose principal artists were Latino (with just one black
co-star), but its theme of homosexuality is, Jones says,
``especially controversial in the black community.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was not shocked by the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught hell,'' he says simply. ``I got lots of calls, split
about 50-50, with some people saying, `Hang in there' and others
saying, `How dare you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was undaunted, and ``Slam'' is the proof. Its eight poets
are white, black, Latino. They range in age from veterans of the
Beat Generation to members of the hip-hop generation. Their
subjects range from political power to sexual power (or both, in a
segment based on a ``stripper poet'' that Jones once witnessed).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about collision of cultures and ideas _ that's what's
so exciting about the poetry scene today,'' says Jones. ``I want
people to come to the show and examine their own dream cells.''
</P>
<P>
   THEATER PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Slam''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Friday ($25). 8 p.m. Wednesdays-Saturdays, 3 p.m.
Saturdays-Sundays. Through May 9. $15-$20; $7 students; $10 senior
citizens. Jomandi Productions at 14th Street Playhouse, 173 14th
St. N.E. 404-870-0629.
</P>
<P>
   THE JONES FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Background: Age 42. Raised in New York, moved to Atlanta in
his teens, educated at Amherst College in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At Jomandi Productions: Co-founded theater company in 1978
with Marsha Jackson-Randolph; they continue as co-artistic
directors. With a $1 million budget, the company offers national
tours, outreach programs and an October-May season at the 14th
Street Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jomandi credits: ``The Wizard of Hip'' (wrote and starred in),
a coming-of-age monologue that fused poetic language with rap
rhythms; ``Bessie's Blues'' (wrote and directed), an
impressionistic profile of blues singer Bessie Smith; ``Hip 2:
Birth of the Boom'' (wrote, starred in and co-composed), a pop-funk
musical sequel to ``Hip'' updating the concerns of the
African-American male.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Studio Theatre, Washington, credits: Jones is the only artist
to win Washington's Helen Hayes Award as playwright and director
(``Bessie's Blues'') as well as actor (``Wizard''). He is currently
nominated for best actor (``Waiting for Godot'') and director
(``Seven Guitars'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other awards: NAACP Phoenix Award for artistic achievement,
San Diego Critics Award for best director (``Spunk'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Opening in Atlanta this week: ``Slam'' (wrote and directed), a
jazz-funk portrait of a nightclub where the ideas of black, white
and Latin poets collide. New York and Washington engagements are
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
