<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLEQUILT-POWERS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The patchwork of a family treasure
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLATNA _ Americans rediscovered the art of quiltmaking in 1976,
during the bicentennial. That's when Joe Carter started hearing
about a quilt that someone in his family had made that was in a
museum somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The idea intrigued him, because growing up in Baltimore, all he
had known about his roots was that his mother, Janie Powers Brown,
had been born in Atlanta at Grady Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's mother told him that her people were gathering in
Athens because a researcher was trying to find descendants of this
famous quilter. But his mother never made it there, and while
Carter pestered her to find out more about the quilt, she never
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a seeker,'' explains Carter, who eventually moved to
Atlanta, where he worked with singer Curtis Mayfield and
established a civil rights organization called Creative Community
National Network for Youth and Family Survival.
</P>
<P>
   Today, on the anniversary of the murder of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr., Carter celebrates the legacy of civil rights
leaders who went before. He calls it Remnants Day, from the
biblical term for the people of God left behind in a foreign
country to continue good works.
</P>
<P>
   On Remnants Day in 1996, Carter received a newspaper article
showing some of his distant relatives with the Harriet Powers quilt
at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston. It was the quilt he had heard
about for so many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of like the Alex Haley situation in reverse,''
says Carter, 46. ``He found his history and wrote a book. And all
of a sudden, I walk into a situation where my
great-great-grandmother is quite possibly one of the most famous
quilters in the country. ... All of a sudden, we were brought into
the circle.''
</P>
<P>
   He organized a group of 10 Powers descendants to see her other
quilt, at the Smithsonian Institution's Museum of American History,
in the same section that houses the flag that inspired ``The
Star-Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   They stared at the quilt and saw in it the source of Carter's
songwriting ability, his sister's knack for sewing a wedding gown
without a pattern, his son's interest in making montages of sports
heroes, his daughter's interest in violin and dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like everybody saw something passed down to them from
her,'' says Joe Carter Jr., 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are part of a strong thread that has survived,'' adds Aisha
Carter, 22.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is awestruck that a Harriet Powers quilt will be on
display in Atlanta starting this week. But distance has not
diminished the power her work has exacted on his life. He's sure of
one thing, no matter where the quilts reside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harriet,'' he says, ``is still speaking to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Hiskey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4105 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIBLEQUILTS04-COX     04-02 1653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLEQUILTS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Historic quilt a feather in Atlanta's cap
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Freed from slavery at age 29, Harriet Powers moved
with her family to a small farm near Athens and began to stitch a
spiritual tapestry for herself and her loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   With cotton scraps of blue and brown, orange and white, she cut
out simple figures that even her three children could recognize
from the fiery sermons they heard every Sunday at the local Baptist
church. She depicted Jesus and Jacob and Job as silhouettes among
stars and circles, diamonds and crosses, arranging them in a
fashion much like the needlework of her West African ancestors. She
couldn't read or write, but told her stories in cloth and thread.
</P>
<P>
   Powers died in 1911, not living long enough to see her work
displayed in the Smithsonian Institution, well before she became
the most famous quilter in a country where that art form has become
a warm and touchable symbol of its melting-pot history. The two
surviving quilts made by Harriet Powers are so treasured by the
museums that own them that, despite constant requests, they are
rarely even photographed, much less lent out.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Powers' second Bible quilt will go on display at the
Atlanta History Center, where it will be on view for two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for people in the quilt world, no one understands what
a coup it is for Atlanta to get this,'' says Anita Weinraub,
co-curator of the ``Georgia Quilts: Piecing Together a History''
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time in a century that a Powers quilt has been
shown in her home state, although her descendants in Georgia
haven't felt distant from her. Even across the miles, they say, her
work continues to touch them spiritually. In her quilts, they see
the heartbreaking sacrifice of an illiterate ex-slave forced to
give up her greatest treasure. And by doing that, she saved it.
</P>
<P>
   Of sacrifice and salvation
</P>
<P>
   Harriet Powers' heroes were the biblical survivors, characters
such as Noah who had persevered through great crises. She featured
them prominently in her first quilt, which she called ``A Sermon in
Patchwork'' and proudly displayed in 1886 at a fair, near the
biggest watermelon and tallest corn stalk.
</P>
<P>
   A young white art teacher offered to buy the quilt for $10. But
Powers was adamant; her quilt was not for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, when economic depression fell across Georgia,
the 53-year-old Powers and her husband, Armstead, wrapped the
precious quilt in two sacks, loaded it into their oxcart and took
it to the art teacher's house.
</P>
<P>
   This time the woman didn't have $10; she could pay only $5.
</P>
<P>
   Powers didn't want to let the quilt go, but Armstead insisted
that they needed the money. So, with great heartache, she struck
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next years, she would return to visit what the teacher
called ``the darling offspring of her brain'' and would receive a
commission from a group of Atlantans to create a second, even more
detailed Bible quilt.
</P>
<P>
   One panel of the quilt shows the hand of God hovering over Adam
and Eve. And it almost seems as if providential guidance kept the
quilts miraculously preserved over the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The first guardian angel was the white art teacher, Jennie O.
Smith. She later marveled, ``I have spent my whole life in the
South, and am perfectly familiar with 30 patterns of quilts, but I
had never seen an original design, and never a living creature in
the patchwork, until the year 1886.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith persuaded Powers to tell her the stories behind the
quilt's 11 panels. She learned that Powers had room for only six
disciples in her Last Supper, and that she surrounded her Judas
with 30 green calico circles representing pieces of silver.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was clearly charmed. Satan, she noted, ``is not as I first
thought, a football player. I am sure I have never seen a jauntier
devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Those descriptions are almost as remarkable as the quilt itself.
Very few quiltmakers left behind any documentationabout the meaning
or inspiration behind their work.
</P>
<P>
   For four years during the 1990s, Weinraub traveled through
Georgia looking for historic quilts. She found more than 8,500, but
very few from the 1800s. Only about 3 percent were made by
African-Americans. Those facts make Powers' work even more
significant, apart from its providing an interpreted storyboard of
an oral tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of the beauty and value of Harriet Powers'
quilts,'' Weinraub says. ``We know what she meant by it all.''
</P>
<P>
   `We were just floored'
</P>
<P>
   In 1895, Smith displayed the Powers quilt at the Cotton States
Exposition in Atlanta's Piedmont Park, where it caught the eyes of
some Atlanta University professors' wives. They wanted such a quilt
as a gift for the chairman of their board of trustees, the Rev.
Charles Cuthbert Hall of New York. Through Smith, the women
commissioned Powers to make them a more elaborate quilt.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three years, Powers sewed 15 panels, expanding her
subjects to include celestial phenomena that happened before her
birth, such as a dark day caused by a forest fire in 1780 and a
meteor shower in 1833. She also depicted an olive-colored hog named
Betts that, legend has it, ran 500 miles home.
</P>
<P>
   Someone, whose name is unknown, recorded her interpretation of
these blocks on small pieces of cardboard, and they stayed with the
quilt as it was passed down to Hall's son, whose estate sold it to
folk art collector Maxim Karolik. In 1964, Karolik donated his
collection to the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston. That was about the
same time the executor of Jennie Smith's estate packed up her
Powers quilt and 18 pages of notes and sent them to the Smithsonian
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When the national museum's textile experts opened the box, they
immediately recognized it as a major find: the King Tut's Tomb of
American quiltmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just came in the mail and we opened it and we were just
floored,'' recalls Doris Bowman, a 35-year veteran of the
Smithsonian. ``It was so different from anything we had ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Many experts in the field talk about the two quilts as one
creation. ``It certainly has an aura about it,'' says Boston Museum
of Fine Arts curatorial assistant Lauren Whitley, an authority on
the quilt that's coming to Atlanta. ``That's what strikes me _ that
it was so prized to her and she wanted to keep it close, and the
most amazing thing is it probably wouldn't have survived if it
hadn't been sold. There must have been a special guiding light
looking out for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian's Museum of American History displayed the quilt
without knowing much about it. ``Made by an ex-slave named
Harriet,'' read its caption in the museum, where a young folklore
professor from the University of Maryland would drop by every
Saturday. Gladys-Marie Fry would sit on a little bench and ``visit
with Harriet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeared to have so many layers of meaning and different
elements, and I wanted to try to figure out what it meant,'' says
Fry, who launched the first academic study of the Powers quilts.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's research connected the circles, crosses and diamonds with
symbols used by the Kongo people of West Africa to celebrate
relationships between the living and the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an onion,'' Fry says. ``The outside peel, that was
Christianity. Under that are all these beliefs in the Kongo system.
And I think there's more to it. God only knows what's underneath
the rest of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as we speak, I envision her in heaven, smiling as we try
to break the code.''
</P>
<P>
   A treasure kept in a vault
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts in Boston has 35,000 objects in its
textile collection. The Powers quilt is the most popular of them,
and a thick file folder is stuffed with requests to reproduce its
image in textbooks, documentaries and even children's books. It has
never been lent out before.
</P>
<P>
   Whitley says the quilt's value places a heavy burden on the
museum to protect it for posterity. Staff members don white lab
coats and gloves whenever they handle it, because even a speck of
sweat could turn into a stain years later. After it is displayed,
the quilt is wrapped in acid-free paper and stored for at least
three years in a special vault kept constantly at 68 degrees and 50
percent humidity.
</P>
<P>
   A conservator from Boston will accompany the quilt to Atlanta as
it is shipped in a special padded canister suspended in a
custom-made wooden crate. In Atlanta, it will be displayed behind
plexiglass, in low lighting, with special ultraviolet filters to
ensure that the fragile cotton doesn't fade.
</P>
<P>
   Freeing this masterpiece from its Boston cocoon hinged on the
persistence and connections of Betsy Weyburn, former textiles
curator at the history center. An Atlanta quilt exhibit two decades
ago included a poster of Powers' work, but Weyburn wanted to do
better than that. A lot better.
</P>
<P>
   She had just helped the Costume Society of America put on a
meeting in Atlanta, and through that volunteer job she had met
Elizabeth Ann Coleman, the Boston museum's new textiles curator.
Weyburn knew the museum would view more kindly a request that came
from someone who was familiar and who could vouch for its
safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to be a crime that it hadn't been shown here,'' says
Weyburn. ``Sometimes I'm an eternal optimist. I knew it was a small
chance and believed we would get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, the Boston museum board approved the two-month loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't say no,'' Weyburn says, ``to sending it home.''
</P>
<P>
   Harriet Powers Quilt
</P>
<P>
   Friday through June 13. Part of the exhibition ``Georgia Quilts:
Piecing Together a History,'' continuing through Sept. 5. Atlanta
History Center, 130 W. Paces Ferry Road N.W.
</P>
<P>
   404-814-4000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
