<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4106 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDMADE04-COX     04-02 2581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDMADE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    North Carolina aims to prove art, economic development can mix
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asheville, N. C.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Anderson slows her long maroon Chrysler to a crawl in
downtown Waynesville. Unlike many small towns of 7,000, where the
action has moved from the old town centers to the strip malls,
downtown Waynesville is bustling. The search for parking is just
the first hint.
</P>
<P>
   She finds a spot just in front of a small newsstand chock-full
of newspapers from across the South and around the country, along
with periodicals such as Art in America and Opera News. It's the
kind of corner newsstand you'd expect to find in New York City, not
a small mountain town.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 58, bounds from the car. She draws a bright red
sweater coat around her shoulders and sets out on her favorite
circuit. First she clips over to the Burr Studio and Gallery, but
potters Dane and MaryEtta Burr aren't in yet. So it's on to the
Whitewoven Handweaving Studio and Gallery for a ``how's biz'' chat
with weaver Sheree Sorrells.
</P>
<P>
   Then down the street to check out a new gallery called Twigs and
Leaves that folks are buzzing about. ``Hi,'' Anderson says, hand
extended to owner David Erikson as soon as she enters the door.
``I'm Becky Anderson with HandMade in America. I've heard so much
about you.''
</P>
<P>
   Erikson's eyebrows pop up and he hurries from behind the counter
to greet her. ``I just put a letter in the mailbox for you moments
ago,'' he says. His wife, Kaaren Stoner, abandons her potter's
wheel in the back and practically stammers to explain, ``Your
organization is one of the main reasons we moved here.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple, who came from Ohio eight months ago, greet Anderson
as if a muse has taken form before their eyes. And to many artists
and civic leaders in Western North Carolina, she is just that.
</P>
<P>
   `Let's build on our culture'
</P>
<P>
   Though she makes no clay vessels, stitched quilts or hand-blown
glass, Anderson is a crafter nonetheless. Through her organization,
HandMade in America, she has shown how economic and cultural
development can be woven together into a new kind of community.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Haywood County, Anderson is a local farm girl who
grew up ready for challenge. She has tackled civil rights and
community development issues in South Georgia, East Tennessee and
Ohio. But she came back to North Carolina when she realized that
``who you are is where you're from, and where you're from is where
you are going.'' She says the line with a twinge of mountain twang,
then admits to stealing it from her brother, novelist Fred
Chappell, who is North Carolina's poet laureate.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 years Anderson worked as an industrial recruiter for the
Asheville Area Chamber of Commerce, trying to lure manufacturers
into the region _ virtually a mission impossible given the
mountainous terrain, poor or restricted roads, sensitive watersheds
and large swaths of national parks and forests that are off-limits
to development. Anderson began to realize, she said, that
``traditional economic and industrial recruiting simply (wasn't)
going to work for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   What might work, she realized, were pots turned and shaped by
clay-caked hands, rugs woven by the push and pull of a wooden loom,
and baskets of river cane reeds and honeysuckle vine laced by the
fingers of Cherokee and Appalachian makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make Western North Carolina the center of handmade
objects in the country,'' said Anderson, comparing it to the
development of Santa Fe, N.M., as a mecca of galleries and art
studios in the Southwest. ``We have about 20 million visitors a
year, drawn here by the beauty, the recreational activities like
hiking and rafting, the arts, the music and the crafts. Those are
our assets. Let's build on our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   So, six years ago, she founded HandMade in America, along with a
small group of like-minded business, civic and cultural leaders, to
help support and promote the estimated 4,000 artists and
craftspeople in Western North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson cultivated an appreciation of crafts in the process of
acquiring an eclectic collection of pieces ``that all have meaning
to me because of my connection to the person who made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her most prized possessions are two coverlets, one deep navy and
the other deep red, made by her grandmother, who raised the sheep,
made and dyed the wool and then wove the two large pieces, while
living on the Haywood County farm that Anderson still owns (and
farms tobacco on). One coverlet will soon hang on the wall of her
new office; the other will stay in the Asheville home she shares
with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger quarters are needed for HandMade because, in six years,
it has grown to encompass everything from helping artists get
small-business loans to helping towns find funds for such civic
projects as riverwalks.
</P>
<P>
   A weird form of tourism
</P>
<P>
   During the first two years, Anderson and company took stock of
the local crafts industry. An exhaustive assessment, which showed
that it accounted for $122 million in 1994, formed the basis of
HandMade's 120-page guidebook ``Craft Heritage Trails of Western
North Carolina.'' The popular book helps travelers and art lovers
find more than 100 home studios, galleries and other local
treasures.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time anyone in the region had tried to draw
connections between the weaver on her farm, the potter down the
road a bit and the art gallery in town. At first, said Anderson,
artists were reluctant. ``(Bringing) people onto private
property,'' she admits, ``is a real weird way to do tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   Artists were asked to list regular business hours, put their
names on their mailboxes and create exterior doors to their studio
spaces. The advantage, they were promised, would be more time spent
in their studios and less time selling their wares at craft shows
and fairs.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrells, the weaver in Waynesville, was among the early
skeptics, mainly, she said, because similarly ambitious efforts had
always met with choruses of ``no, that won't work'' from the wider
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, this has worked,'' said Sorrells, who works in a
second-floor studio on Main Street in Waynesville. ``Tourists, and
even some local folks, come up all 27 steps with that little book
in their hands.'' The result is more commissions from local people
and studio visitors ``than in the past 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The guidebook has surpassed all expectations. ``I lived in fear
that 25,000 copies of it would sit in the office for 25 years,''
Anderson said. But it sold out in 18 months, and a second edition,
with nearly 200 listings, was recently published.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson borrowed the idea from the National Trust for Historic
Preservation, which had created heritage trails in Wisconsin, Texas
and Tennessee. Because of her success, she's now in demand as
something of a heritage trail expert.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson recently traveled to Hawaii to advise on ``sugar
heritage'' trails and talked with Los Angeles residents as they
created a variety of trails focusing on ethnicity and architecture.
A contingent from Tibet recently stopped by Anderson's office to
learn more about the concept.
</P>
<P>
   Still more is in the works: HandMade is sponsoring a new
guidebook to garden and hiking trails, and the North Carolina
tourism office is working on trails for indigenous music and
Cherokee Indian heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Regional effort takes off
</P>
<P>
   Drawing connections did more than direct tourist to artist; it
helped draw artists together and connected them with schools and
agencies, with business and civic leaders. And then artists and
leaders from different towns began to talk, and soon a true
regional development effort was in bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Towns such as Bakersville, which had been left out of the first
book, began to call Anderson about how they could be included and
get help in their efforts to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson heard about how Bakersville and Mars Hill, an old
college town, were interested in putting their utility lines
underground. She knew that Marion, which was within an hour of both
places, was doing that.
</P>
<P>
   Chimney Rock wanted tourists at its namesake landmark _ a large
rock overhang with beautiful views of the mountains _ to linger
awhile. Anderson knew that neighboring Black Mountain, with its
historic college and business district thriving with craft shops
and galleries, had become a popular detour for recreational
visitors lodging in Asheville.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the towns were too small _ Chimney Rock only about 100
residents, Bakersville about 600 _ to have a city planner or
manager or the aid of the state's Main Street Program, which helps
towns of 5,000 people or more. So, in 1996, Anderson created the
Small Town Revitalization Program, with the financial backing of a
$450,000 grant from the Pew Partnership for Civic Change.
</P>
<P>
   The program started with six towns and is growing to 10. Matched
with larger, ``sister'' towns, such as Waynesville, the smaller
places learn how to solve specific community problems, whether it's
how to get street lamps on Main Street, build a walkway by the
river or write a sign ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has lined up training in grant writing and planning
issues and worked to expose the town leaders to an array of
resources. ``Of course,'' she notes, ``sometimes the trick is
convincing someone in Washington that a loom is an economic
development tool.''
</P>
<P>
   She spends so much time _ phoning up agencies from the
Appalachian Regional Commission to the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, dashing off to various meetings across the region and
toiling away on weekends writing grants and letters _ that she
recently told U.S. News &AMP; World Report magazine that her goal is
``to have a weekend all to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   `This isn't the mall'
</P>
<P>
   It's folks like Ronnie McKinney in Bakersville who see the
dividends of such effort. ``We actually had an entire busload of
people representing philanthropic groups across the country come to
Bakersville, thanks to HandMade,'' said McKinney, a retired
educator and town volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Bakersville has recovered from a flood with the help of
donations and volunteer cleanup efforts from sister cities, built a
trail beside the town creek and studied planning issues such as
burying utility lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to preserve this as a nice place to live and
avoid indiscriminate development with houses all over the
mountainside and strip malls,'' McKinney said. It's an all too
present threat. Within the past few months, Wal-Mart has announced
plans to build near Bakersville and neighboring Spruce Pine,
prompting a flurry of town meetings. Some residents are eager for
the convenience; others fear damage to locally owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``HandMade has helped us buy into the idea of developing the
arts and crafts that are traditional in this area, which will bring
visitors in, support the artists and the small businesses, and not
have a major environmental impact,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. Some environmentalists refer to HandMade's
efforts as ``industrial tourism'' and deride the concept because it
depends so heavily on bringing automobiles through the mountains.
Some of HandMade's heritage trails crisscross the Blue Ridge
Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the parkway was designed for cars. But now we know that
one-third of the pollution in our mountains comes from
automobiles,'' said Garrett Smathers, a member of the Western North
Carolina Alliance. ``We need to try to reduce that impact as much
as we can. The parkway is a very fragile umbilical cord between the
Shenandoah Valley and the Smoky Mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see a place for handmade crafts in economic development
as long as it avoids the ``tourist trap'' syndrome. ``There's no
need for us to create a Snuffy Smith village. And we don't want to
be Helen, Georgia,'' declared Ronald Huelster, executive director
of the Downtown Waynesville Association.
</P>
<P>
   Huelster believes in promoting what the town naturally has. And
since Waynesville joined the Main Street program in 1986, leaders
have made sure that local crafts and arts, along with antiques,
have played a major part in their promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the mall,'' said Huelster. ``This isn't Everywhere
USA. Here you can purchase something from an artist or craftsperson
and learn something about what went into the piece and who made it,
and that makes it different. That's the only way a downtown can
compete with a Wal-Mart.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking out small towns
</P>
<P>
   Stoner and Erikson were looking for an arts-friendly place to
settle when a friend told them about the guidebook. They ordered
the book from HandMade's Internet site, www.wnccrafts.org, loved
it, visited the region and began looking for a community to adopt.
Huelster's willingness to help _ ultimately finding the space for
their gallery and apartment _ was crucial in their choice of
Waynesville.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support of craftsmen was critical in our decision,'' said
Erickson. ``This is a community of universal support for art.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, artists have shown that they're more than
willing to return community support. They've built benches in
Bakersville and helped teachers in Waynesville devise ways to use
crafts to teach mathematics and science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists were undervalued as citizens,'' Anderson said. ``Now
they are on planning boards in these small towns. I like to refer
to my board as the ties and the tie-dyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, the various planning boards of HandMade and in the
towns are kicking out more innovative ideas every day. A new
program has been launched to create gardens that grow the raw
materials artists need, with the first at the North Carolina
Arboretum in Asheville. Abandoned schoolhouses are being renovated
to become incubator studios and apartments for artists, with the
first in Graham County likely to be opened this year. A computer
registry of the region's 4,000 artists is being compiled by
partners at Haywood Community College. And plans are under way to
build a pottery studio atop a landfill near Burnsville in Yancey
County, and use the landfill's waste methane gas to fire the kiln.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Anderson sees HandMade as the product of tradition
as much as the arts and crafts it supports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in this century, women in Western North Carolina did
just this very thing,'' she said, referring to institutions such as
the Southern Highland Craft Guild, the John C. Campbell Folk School
and the Penland School, which were all created (with large
influence by women) to promote traditional crafts and arts as an
important part of the cultural and community life in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson believes that, though the region could gamble on
hot-trotting high technology or try to lure more manufacturing, its
best bet is on what's already there. And what is there, ultimately,
is what more and more people want. ``There's a reason people are
moving from the big cities into our small towns up here,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She rattled off a few: to sit on the front porch and talk to
their neighbors face to face, not through e-mail. To hear the feet
stompin' with the music, not filtered through a computer. To spend
their time in the garden rather than in the car.
</P>
<P>
   And to ``put their hands on things made by hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
