<HEADER>
A4107 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-EASTER03-COX     04-02 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-EASTER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Message of Rebirth
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He has risen.
</P>
<P>
   Those three words shook the Roman Empire. They ignited a
worldwide religious movement. And they continue to grip billions of
people today.
</P>
<P>
   But 2,000 years after the followers of Jesus greeted one another
with this joyful proclamation, Christians disagree more than ever
about its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   As Christians worldwide observe Easter this Sunday (Eastern
Orthodox Christians celebrate it April 11), the central message of
Christianity's holiest day _ the resurrection of Jesus _ is coming
under increasing doubt.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of liberal Christians and scholars do not
believe that Jesus rose bodily from the grave. For them, the
resurrection is symbolic: Jesus' teachings live on despite his
brutal death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be irrelevant to me if we would discover the skeletal
remains of Jesus,'' said Marcus Borg, co-author of ``The Meaning of
Jesus'' (HarperSanFrancisco, 192 pages, $22). ``The central meaning
of Easter is Jesus is Lord and Jesus is a divine reality now one
with God.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are other Christians who say that belief in the bodily
resurrection of Jesus is essential to Christianity. What's at stake
with them is not simply an answer to an academic debate. It is the
very identity of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If how Jesus lived is all that matters and if Jesus simply
died like all other humans, (then) Christianity is nothing more
than imitating a dead guy from the past,'' said Luke Timothy
Johnson, a professor of religion at Emory University and author of
``Living Jesus'' (HarperSanFrancisco, 224 pages, $22).
</P>
<P>
   The biblical portrayal of Easter does little to clear up the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the crucifixion of Jesus, there were no witnesses to
Jesus' resurrection. The Resurrection stories vary from each Gospel
and, in some cases, contradict one another. For example, in the
Gospel of Matthew, Jesus appears first to Mary Magdalene. But
Luke's account says Jesus appeared first to Peter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the core of the Resurrection stories remains the same. They
proclaim that on the third day after Jesus was crucified, he
appeared to his disciples alive. The Gospel of John even depicts
Jesus eating with his followers and inviting one doubting disciple
to place his fingers into one of the wounds caused by his
crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   The Apostle Paul declared that the Resurrection is the axis that
the Christian faith revolves around.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if Christ has not been raised, our preaching is useless
and so is your faith,'' Paul declared in the First Book of
Corinthians.
</P>
<P>
   But John Dominic Crossan, a retired DePaul University religion
professor, argues that accounts of great men rising from the dead
were too common in the ancient world to spark a new religious
movement. Crossan, a leader of the controversial Jesus Seminar and
author of ``The Birth of Christianity'' (HarperSanFrancisco, 653
pages, $20), said the followers of Jesus probably saw an apparition
of Jesus after his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not pathological; it's part of the grieving process,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the disciples' reflection on their experiences with Jesus
before Easter that inspired them to proclaim Jesus as Lord after
his death _ not a vision of the risen Jesus, Crossan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had so integrated their lives with Jesus that it was
almost impossible for them to break with him now,'' Crossan said.
</P>
<P>
   Emory's Johnson said no ``poltergeist experience'' can explain
the birth of Christianity. Only an encounter with a ``living
Jesus,'' he thinks, can explain how the same terrified disciples
who deserted Jesus during his crucifixion became a group of
death-defying Jesus proclaimers within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Easter's message isn't that the example of Jesus' life lives on,
but that Jesus literally lives and is still experienced by people,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Christians say today is that Jesus is still powerfully
alive. That's why Christians gather. For classical Christianity,
Easter is not three days after the death of Jesus. It's every day
after the Resurrection,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Though debate swirls over the events surrounding the
Resurrection, a Newsweek magazine poll released this month said
that 88 percent of Christians still believe in the Resurrection.
Such belief, however, is interpreted in various ways.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Albert Wingate, the pastor of the Atlanta Unity Church
in Roswell, doubts that Jesus rose literally from the grave, but he
still believes in Easter because he said it teaches people that ``a
resurrection process is taking place in all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wingate said God raised him from his own death _ years spent as
an alcoholic before becoming sober.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beyond me how I can lay down my body and pick it up
again,'' Wingate said. ``But I can certainly see the times when I
was in that tomb of darkness. What really brought me out of it was
literally a resurrection when I realized half-measures weren't
going to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Tinsley, however, believes in Jesus' bodily resurrection.
For Tinsley, host of a radio gospel show on WVEE-FM (V-103), it
proves that if God would not desert Jesus on the cross, he won't
desert anyone else when they bear their own cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you step out on faith, God always gives you a platform to
stand on,'' Tinsley said. ``If you believe that, if you trust that,
you'll never fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his intensive study of Easter, Borg said it would be a
mistake to try to pin down what happened on the first Easter
morning. The Resurrection, like any sacred mystery, cannot be
explained with words, Borg said. Only faith will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we try to domesticate God with excessive certitude
when we insist that the tomb was really empty and God transformed
the corpse of Jesus,'' Borg said. ``But it points to a mystery that
escapes our ordinary language.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
