<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-COSTS-$ADV04-C     04-02 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-COSTS-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVO COST ESTIMATES: $400 MILLION AND RISING
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-COSTS-DATA. For release Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The NATO bombing assaults on Yugoslavia are costing
up to $40 million a day, and a prolonged air campaign will cost the
United States billions of dollars, military budget experts predict.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns over the expense of the Balkan conflict have been
secondary as the Clinton administration has confronted its growing
urgencies. Moreover, accurate cost estimates are all but
impossible, with the extent and duration of the military action
unknown and humanitarian relief costs soaring as hundreds of
thousands of refugees are forced out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the cost of the Balkan operation has been compared with
that of Desert Fox, the recent bombing campaign against Iraq. That
operation cost a ``guesstimated'' $500 million, said Chris Hellman,
senior analyst with the Center for Defense Information.
</P>
<P>
   Hellman put the cost of the Kosovo military campaign, which
began March 24, at $20 million to $40 million a day, nearly all of
which has been borne by the United States. That does not include
relief aid that the United States and other countries are rushing
into the region. President Clinton pledged Wednesday to send $50
million in emergency assistance for the Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The most evident costs are the tons of bombs exploded in the
region. Already, the U.S.-led forces have launched an estimated 100
cruise missiles, which cost $1 million apiece to replace.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest single loss, the downed F-117 Stealth fighter plane,
is more difficult to evaluate. The radar-evading fighter jet cost
$45 million when it was built in the 1980s, but the plane is no
longer in production, and the Air Force has no plans to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of sorties in the Balkans, none has been as
expensive as those flown by B-2 stealth bombers. The planes went
into battle for the first time, with flights of two planes carrying
their 16 one-ton bombs from their home base in Missouri across the
Atlantic on two successive nights.
</P>
<P>
   The planes cost $2.2 billion each. When the cost of the bombs
they carry ($63,000 apiece) are included, the B-2 bombing sorties
cost $1.6 million each, according to Hellman's estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the B-2 is also extremely costly to service and
requires about one week of maintenance for each bombing run. The
plane is so sensitive that it must be stored in a
climate-controlled hangar to protect its radar-evading surface.
</P>
<P>
   The costs of the planes and bombs would almost certainly be
overshadowed if the United States sent more troops into the region.
During the Persian Gulf war, most of the expense was in
transportation, housing, and extra pay for personnel, said Liesl
Heeter, senior budget analyst at the Center for Strategic and
Budgetary Assessments. The center has estimated that keeping 4,000
U.S. peacekeeping troops in Kosovo would cost $1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The expense of the current Kosovo conflict far exceeds the
Defense Department's budget, requiring the military to ``borrow''
from other defense operations until Congress approves supplemental
funding. As Heeter described it,
</P>
<P>
   ``They are taking money out of Peter's pocket to pay Paul. Then
they go to Congress and ask them to repay Peter.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers have consistently balked at setting aside a
contingency fund for war-making. ``Congress wants to retain the
authority to declare war,'' Heeter said, even as she acknowledged
that Congress has, in effect, turned over much of that power to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   A few months from now, the administration will request the extra
money for the Kosovo operation, and Congress will almost certainly
pass it. ``That's sort of the game that's played,'' Heeter said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the cost to the Pentagon will be counted not just
in dollars, but in how it affects the military's already struggling
efforts to recruit and keep personnel. A military action can
attract new recruits, but it can also repel them if the risks are
great, if the deployments drag on too long, or if the Pentagon
relies too heavily on some units.
</P>
<P>
   On this intangible cost, ``there's not a clear, neat answer,''
Heeter said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
