<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Saturday, April 3. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ Albania says the refugee
situation is ``out of control'' and ``catastrophic'' as tens of
thousands keep pouring in from Kosovo. The U.N. declares ``major
humanitarian emergency'' in northern Albania. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With map, photos and charts on refugee flows.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WEATHER (Undated) _ A general look at the weather in the
Balkan Peninsula and the extent to which it hampers NATO operations
over Yugoslavia. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ Slobodan Milosevic is riding above
the fray, while his army and his police are capturing (or
abducting) American soldiers, shooting down an invisible airplane,
and expelling ethnic Albanians from Kosovo in numbers beyond any
Washington policymaker's most embarrassing nightmares. While NATO
is pounding his country from the air, Milosevic, portly and
smiling, is meeting Vatican envoys, Russian delegations, moderate
ethnic Albanians and talking of peace. His military seems to be
withstanding NATO's might and his people, who don't especially like
him, are rallying around him anyway. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   MELISSA-VIRUS (Trenton, N.J.) _ Federal and state authorities
arrested a central New Jersey man Thursday night and and charged
him with originating the e-mail virus known as Melissa. By David
Kocieniewski
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy added jobs during March at
the slowest pace in more than three years, while the unemployment
rate unexpectedly fell. Payrolls expanded by 46,000 jobs in March,
well below forecasts and February's gain of 297,000 jobs. The
jobless rate declined to 4.2 percent from 4.4 percent in February.
Service-producing employment rose by 135,000 jobs in March, while
manufacturing employment decreased by 35,000 jobs and construction
employment by 47,000 jobs. Wage increases remained tame. By Sylvia
Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   NH-SCHOOL-TAX (Concord, N.H.) _ New Hampshire's school funding
crisis has now entered overtime. Despite marathon sessions,
lawmakers missed their court-imposed deadline of this Thursday to
come up with a new system, and no one here is predicting
confidently when or how it will all end. The Democratic governor
has vowed to veto any income tax, and teachers are beginning to
receive warning slips that next fall's jobs are in question. But
one fact has emerged clearly from the muddle: New Hampshire no
longer seems such a granite monolith of anti-tax sentiment. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
