<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT/FEATURE-BUDGET-B     04-02 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT/FEATURE-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release SATURDAY AMs, April 3, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONFLICT (Washington) _ Frustrated NATO officials say
Serb troops remain undeterred in their murderous rampage through
Kosovo, which has uprooted an estimated 634,000 ethnic Albanian
civilians. By Bob Hohler. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-THREAT (Podgorica, Yugoslavia) _ Tiny Montenegro, the
semi-autonomous Yugoslav province has avoided the bloody turmoil
most of this decade. Now it may be headed for a showdown with
Slobodan Milosevic. By Colin Nickerson. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DESTABILIZE (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Wave of refugees
threatens to destabilize Macedonia, Montenegro, Albania, even
Greece. By Kevin Cullen and Colin Nickerson. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VALLEY (Blace, Macedonia) _ Humanitarian groups openly
acknowledge that the plight of Kosovo refugees has become a crisis.
By Kevin Cullen. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ARABS (New York) _ The Muslim world has warily endorsed
the US-led air war against Kosovo, marking a shift from its
traditional opposition to America's military engagements. By Colum
Lynch. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Presence of a Russian ship in the
Adriatic will raise the risk of an unintentional confrontation
between NATO and Russia. By David Filipov. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-HACKERS (Undated) _ Russian hackers break into NATO
website, among others, to express disapproval of ``NATO
aggression.'' By Patti Hartigan. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLOCK (Undated) _ Resetting clocks this weekend is a minor
bother compared to the effect of the time shift on our bodies.
Scientists say circadian rhythms could take another month to return
to normal. By David L. Chandler. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-TRANSPLANT (Undated) _ As researchers prepare to post
five new studies of bone-marrow transplantation for breast cancer
on the Web April 15, a surgeon remembers his wife's two transplants
and her ultimate death. By Judy Foreman. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELLIS-COLUMN (Undated) -- The cost of feckless leadership: It's
over in Kosovo. By John Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANIMALS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Those new ``spot on'' flea and
tick-control products are great, but don't give them to the wrong
animal. By Vicki Croke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY (Undated) _ As the Melissa and Raytheon cases
show, despite an apparent veil of anonymity on the Internet, your
identity can be discovered if someone wants to. By Ross Kerber.
1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   MELLISS-ARREST (Undated) _ FBI arrests man in New Jersey and
charges him with originating the Melissa e-mail virus. By Hiawatha
Bray. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOC-REVOLUTION (Kansas City) _ The Revolution will be missing
four starters and the Kansas City Wizards three because of injury
when they meet at Arrowhead Stadium. By Frank Dell'Apa.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-BUCKS-CELTICS (Boston) _ By Michael Holley.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-COLLINS (Birmingham, England) _ By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   HKC-NCAA-CHAMPIONSHIP (Anaheim, Calif.) -- They call him Tricky.
And he is. He'll be a factor tonight when Maine faces New Hampshire
in the NCAA hockey championship. By Bob Monahan.
</P>
<P>
   MCDONOUGH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Injured Patriots running back
Robert Edwards will get all of the money coming to him from his
contract, even if he cannot play again. By Will McDonough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
