<HEADER>
A4119 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FACES-OF-WAR-$ADV04-H     04-02 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACES-OF-WAR-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISONERS OF WAR CAN COMPLICATE WHITE HOUSE DECISIONS IN WAR  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 4)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL And ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Images of captured Americans are bombarding the
American public once again, putting the bruised faces of GIs on the
distant war in Yugoslavia for the first time and potentially
affecting U.S. policy decisions there.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Yugoslav authorities to put the three captive U.S.
Army soldiers on trial is like to intensity U.S. interest in a war
that has previously seemed remote, confused and irrelevant to
American interests.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, President Clinton _ like the last five presidents
before him _ now must carve out foreign policy while tending with
newly inflamed domestic political currents.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Larson, author of a 1996 Rand Corp. study on U.S.
casualties and public opinion from World War II to Somalia in the
early 1990s, says prisoners of war and casualties ``rivet the
attention of policy makers, the press, and the public until the
issue is resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Enemy seizure of U.S. troops ``can backfire on adversaries,''
Larson says, adding: ``The expectation is that hostages or
casualties will lead to a decline in support. But in fact, in many
cases it tends to stiffen resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, public support for a military operation would
decline if the mission is murky and the price too high, according
to Joseph Collins, a retired Army colonel and former special
assistant to the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Former National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft, a retired Air
Force lieutenant general who served President George Bush at the
White House, said he favors an aggressive fight-to-win strategy in
Yugoslavia but is worried that American casualties may erode public
support for any sustained U.S. military operation.
</P>
<P>
   Scowcroft said news media coverage of family reaction to U.S.
casualties in Yugoslavia would magnify the emotional costs of U.S.
involvement there and contribute to public impatience.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News survey released on Friday found that 35 percent of
those questioned favored increased U.S. military action in Kosovo
in the wake of the soldiers' capture, 44 percent supported keeping
operations at their current level and 9 percent favored decreasing
U.S. operations.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-three percent of the respondents said that developments
in Yugoslavia were important to U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about the fate of the soldiers led to Clinton's decision
Friday to personally address their plight for a second time in two
days.
</P>
<P>
   The president abandoned evasive diplomatic legalisms to publicly
label the trio prisoners-of-war who are ``entitled to all the
protections that come with that status.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton emphasized: ``There is absolutely no justification for
putting them on trial or displaying them in public in violation of
the Geneva Convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the Geneva Convention, a formal designation
of the soldiers as POWs frees the Yugoslavs to legally hold the
troops until the end of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said the U.S.-led allied
offensive against Yugoslav forces would not be redirected in
response to the capture of Army Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24,
of Los Angeles; Army Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths
Creek, Mich.; and Army Spec. Steven M. Gonzales, 24, of Huntsville,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav authorities said investigators were beginning to
assemble evidence against the three troops with an eye toward
prosecuting them before a military tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Presidents Lyndon B. Johnson, Richard M. Nixon and Gerald R.
Ford were shadowed by questions over the treatment and finally the
release of American armed forces captured and held during and after
the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of 2,069 GIs missing in action in Vietnam, including
some who were being held by communist forces, remains a touchy
political issue in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   President Jimmy Carter saw his re-election drive in 1980
sidetracked by Iran's seizure of the American embassy in Teheran in
1979 and the subsequent 444-day captivity of 52 American diplomatic
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   President Ronald Reagan was faced with the kidnapping of
Americans in the Middle East by Islamic militants. Reagan became so
determined to get the hostages released that his top subordinates
launched an arms-for-hostages deal with Iran that triggered the
appointment of a special prosecutor and clouded the final years of
Reagan's eight-year presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dealt as vice president with the capture of Marine Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins _ and as president with the execution of Higgins
who was seized by Islamic militants in southern Lebanon in 1987 and
executed in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton endured a trial by fire at the outset of his own
presidency, when guerrillas loyal to Somali warlord Mohammed Farah
Aidid battled an elite force of U.S. Army Rangers in Mogadishu,
killing 18 soldiers, wounding more than 70 and capturing downed
Blackhawk helicopter pilot Army Chief Warrant Officer Michael
Durant.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent video footage televised nationwide in the United
States showed Durant's captors interrogating the frightened
32-year-old pilot. Aidid freed Durant 10-days after his capture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
