<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4140 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-TAX-ART-$ADV0     04-02 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-TAX-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BIG GAINS INCREASE THE BITE, MORE FUNDS TRY TO OFFSET TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic on performance of tax-managed funds on pre-tax
and after-tax basis is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ABBY SCHULTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tax-managed mutual funds _ those that seek to maximize after-tax
gains rather than gross returns _ are among the latest trends in
the fund industry. More than half the 22 such funds tracked by
Morningstar Inc. were introduced after 1996, and combined assets in
them have grown from $3.19 billion to $15.36 billion over that
period.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, tax-managed funds have been introduced by
American Century Investments, Prudential Investments and SunAmerica
Asset Management. The Vanguard Group has added a
small-capitalization fund to its lineup of three tax-efficient
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Although still only an investment niche, tax-managed funds may
be more than a passing fancy. Investors are paying more attention
to the effects of taxes on their investment returns, industry
officials say. That is largely because years of bull-market
performance, combined with last summer's steep sell-off, have
alerted them to the big capital gains tax hits they may need to
take.
</P>
<P>
   George Sauter, a managing director of Vanguard, said such funds
would gain popularity as more people understood the benefits of
tax-efficient investing. ``It's largely an education issue,''
Sauter said.
</P>
<P>
   The funds' popularity may well grow if the Securities and
Exchange Commission decides to require the disclosure of after-tax
returns in funds' annual and semiannual reports, an idea that it is
at least kicking around. Some investors would surely be startled by
the bite taxes take from their fund returns.
</P>
<P>
   As some tax-managed funds succeed in beating their plain-vanilla
rivals, they are beginning to generate some positive publicity. A
study done last fall by KPMG on behalf of the fund company Eaton
Vance found that funds with a history of tax-efficient management
performed better _ both before and after taxes _ than most general
domestic stock funds for the 10 years through Dec. 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, tax-managed funds _ which have benefited lately from
holding large-capitalization stocks _ returned a pretax 22.1
percent annually on average, for the three years ended Feb. 28,
according to Morningstar data, compared with 16.4 percent for the
average U.S. diversified stock fund. After federal taxes, however,
assuming that investors are in the highest bracket, tax-managed
funds had a far wider lead, returning 21.3 percent a year on
average over that period versus 13.6 percent for the average
diversified stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-managed funds generally share several characteristics.
The main idea of the funds is to minimize taxes by keeping
distributions of ordinary income, as well as capital gains, as low
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   When gains are taken, managers sell shares that will incur
long-term gains, taxed at 20 percent, over shares with short-term
gains, which can be taxed at rates as high as 39.6 percent. When
selling a stock, managers of tax-managed funds first shed those
shares for which they paid the highest price. That minimizes gains
and therefore taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when investors in tax-managed funds eventually sell
their holdings, they must pay capital gains taxes on the price
appreciation in their shares. But postponing taxes, especially
until retirement, when many people find themselves in lower tax
brackets, is the holy grail of tax management. Until then, the
tax-managed fund helps them pay less year to year. And they can
avoid much income from dividends and short-term gains entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Tax-efficient managers also offset capital gains by selling
losers, in a practice known as harvesting losses, by banking them
against any gains taken within the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the tax-efficient category, most mutual fund managers
may pay little heed to tax consequences. And why should they?
Virtually all of the industry's performance benchmarks, upon which
managers' pay is based, are set on a pretax basis.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring tax consequences can have dramatic effects, even for
investors in lower tax brackets, according to KPMG. It calculated
the after-tax returns of two hypothetical portfolios. The first, a
tax-managed fund, earned no annual income or short-term gains and
had long-term capital gains distributions of 1 percent a year. The
second, a conventional fund, earned annual income and short-term
gains equal to 3 percent a year and had annual long-term capital
gains distributions of 4 percent a year. Over 10 years, $10,000
invested in the tax-managed account earning 10 percent a year would
grow to $22,628. The same $10,000 invested in the regular account,
earning the same 10 percent a year, would grow to $20,738 for an
investor in the top tax bracket and $21,426 for an investor in the
28 percent bracket, KPMG said. And state taxes can take an
additional bite.
</P>
<P>
   Many advisers, as well as do-it-yourself investors, call
tax-managed funds a marketing gimmick and worry that their
portfolio managers may give short shrift to good stock-picking in
their efforts to minimize taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But the managers bristle at that assessment. ``It's not like I'm
sitting here with blinders on,'' said Terry Banet, lead manager of
J.P. Morgan Tax Aware U.S. Equity and subadviser of the new
SunAmerica Tax Managed Equity fund.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tax-managed category is growing, it is still small.
Eaton Vance and Vanguard are the only companies that offer a
variety of tax-managed funds with stocks of differing levels of
market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Lallos, an analyst at Morningstar, suggests that investors
look at a variety of funds, including some that are tax-managed and
some that are not. ``There are a lot of funds out there that are
pretty efficient even if they don't have `tax-managed' in their
name,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Portfolio turnover is often used as a rough estimate of a fund's
tax efficiency. But Morningstar publishes funds' after-tax returns
_ which are far more useful in assessing tax efficiency _ as well
as their potential capital gains exposures.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid duplication in their portfolios, investors should
understand how a particular fund achieves its tax efficiency. Some
funds, for example, are passively managed to a large degree. One of
them, Vanguard Tax-Managed Growth and Income, is similar to the
giant Vanguard 500 Index fund, which tracks the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index. The difference is that in the tax-managed fund,
Sauter and his colleagues deviate from their goal of tracking the
S&AMP;P as closely as possible to consider the tax consequences of any
purchase or sale.
</P>
<P>
   When Intel shares slid last summer after a disappointing
earnings announcement, the tax-managed portfolio sold some shares
at a substantial loss to harvest losses for the future, he said.
That was not done in the main Vanguard 500 Index fund, where ``100
percent of the focus is on tracking error,'' he said, referring to
the fact that index funds are concerned only with matching their
benchmarks as closely as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A more active route is pursued by Prudential Tax-Managed Equity,
which uses a quantitative approach. If the fund holds shares of a
bank stock that is falling, it might sell the shares and, with the
aid of quantitative models, find a similar bank stock with better
prospects, said James Scott, one of three managers of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take the immediate loss and hope to run the other one
into a long-term gain,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Another actively managed fund is J.P. Morgan Tax Aware U.S.
Equity. When considering a stock purchase, Ms. Banet, the lead
manager, asks whether the expected returns of a new stock will make
up for the tax cost of selling existing shares of a similar
company. If the tradeoff does not make sense, she considers selling
other stocks that she is holding at a loss. The strategy results in
a turnover of 32 percent, which is not particularly low, but that
is of little consequence because of the offsetting of gains with
losses.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual feature of the J.P. Morgan fund allows Ms. Banet to
pay investors who redeem shares totaling as little as $250,000 in
stock, rather than cash. By distributing stock, Ms. Banet has
avoided selling portfolio holdings with short-term gains _ a
strategy that would hurt the remaining shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid big redemptions, tax-managed funds try to attract
investors who plan to stay for a while. American Century will
charge investors in its new Tax-Managed Value fund a 2 percent
redemption fee for any withdrawals made in the first year. The fee
goes back into the fund, to help compensate shareholders for any
losses the fund would have to take from selling securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
