<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4141 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUNDS-WATCH-$ADV04     04-02 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUNDS-WATCH-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDS WATCH: A QUICK PATH TO PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, investors have had difficulty tracking closed-end
funds. While they could easily follow the tick-by-tick prices of
such funds on various markets, they could readily determine the
value of a fund's holdings only once a week, in newspaper listings
that disclosed the funds' net asset values as of Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Closed-End Fund Association, a trade group based in
Kansas City, Mo., is trying to address that issue by publishing the
daily net asset values of many closed-end funds on its World Wide
Web site, www.closed-endfunds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 386 of the 500 or so United States closed-end funds
make their daily net asset values available through the site, which
uses data provided by CDA/Weisenberger, a research firm in
Rockville, Md. The remainder of the funds report their net asset
values weekly.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
<P>
   Some Trimming at Invesco
</P>
<P>
   The Invesco Funds Group, based in Denver, is asking shareholders
to approve eight fund mergers and the closure of three other funds,
reducing the number of Invesco offerings by about 25 percent. The
vote is scheduled for May 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason is to simplify the product line and make it
easier for investors to choose,'' said Colleen Noth, a spokeswoman.
These eight funds would be merged with similar but larger funds:
International Growth, Small Company Value, Multi-Asset Allocation,
European Small Company, Asian Growth, Short-Term Bond, Intermediate
government Bond and Tax-Free Intermediate Bond. The three Invesco
funds that would be closed, Emerging Markets, Worldwide Capital
Goods and Environmental Services, have total assets of only $18
million and are in areas of the market that have not performed
well, she said; the company has no similar funds with which to
merge them.
</P>
<P>
   Invesco, a unit of Amvescap PLC of London, also plans to charge
a 2 percent redemption fee on assets pulled out of nine funds
within three months of purchase, beginning May 1. The move, which
is not subject to shareholder approval, is intended to shield
long-term investors from the costs created when market timers jump
in and out of funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAN M. ROSEN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
