<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PROSECUTOR-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE SMOLDERING UNDER KREMLIN SCORCHES PROSECUTOR AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Remember Yuri Skuratov, Russia's chief prosecutor? He's
the man President Boris Yeltsin tried to squeeze out of office and
whose job was saved by the upper house of parliament last month in
a resurrection that was suddenly overshadowed by the broadcast of
an explicit tape of his romp with two prostitutes on a
government-run television station.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Yeltsin dismissed Skuratov again Friday _ at least
temporarily _ this time because of his connection to a criminal
case deemed incompatible with the dignity of his office.
</P>
<P>
   So at a time when political passions are already inflamed by the
Balkan conflict, Russia seems about to be rocked by another murky
scandal. And once again, the issue will have little to do with sex,
crime or corruption, and much to do with the only real topic in
Russian politics: the recurrent, deadly serious battle between
Yeltsin and his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   With the debate on Yeltsin's impeachment set to begin April 15
in the opposition-dominated lower house of parliament, the stakes
keep getting higher. The Russian constitution makes it very
difficult to remove a president from office, but even a vote to
begin impeachment would reverberate through this weakened political
system.
</P>
<P>
   Now, by ordering Skuratov's dismissal again (this time only for
as long as it takes to complete the investigation into a charge of
abuse of office), Yeltsin has set the stage for another showdown in
the Federation Council, the upper house of parliament made up of
regional governors and administrators who were once his loyal
allies.
</P>
<P>
   But those days are over. Russia's regional bosses have already
sensed the shift in power away from the Kremlin and seem to think
nothing of defying the president.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction in the lower house to the president's order to
dismiss Skuratov was predictably explosive. Viktor Ilyukhin, a top
Communist Party deputy, accused the Kremlin of trying to stage a
coup d'etat, and of taking measures to declare a state of emergency
in Moscow. Another opposition leader answered by accusing the
Communists of trying to spring back to power, as they did in August
1991. ``We will beat you,'' shouted Aleksei Mitrofanov, a leader of
the Liberal Democratic party, pounding his fists.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, there were conflicting versions of why Yeltsin
moved so suddenly and so swiftly to dismiss Skuratov. Yeltsin's
decree was issued shortly after 8 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   According to one version, the decision was prompted by a
television interview with the 46-year-old prosecutor, broadcast on
Thursday night, in which he said he was ready to open a corruption
case against ``well-known'' figures in Russian politics who he said
had stashed illegal profits in Swiss bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gennadi Zyuganov, the Communist Party chief, who
has made Skuratov a crucial ally, the owners of 20 suspect bank
accounts include people in Yeltsin's inner circle, and the accounts
contain a total of about $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after he was restored to office last month, Skuratov began
the first public investigation to reach into the Kremlin itself.
Documents belonging to Pavel Borodin, the head of the presidential
administration's powerful property management office, were seized
as part of an inquiry into lucrative government contracts awarded
to a Swiss construction firm, Mabetex.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov last week held lengthy meetings with Carla del Ponte,
Switzerland's formidable prosecutor general, who has her own
interests in tracking down any illegal funds from Russia that have
been funneled into Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   But according to accounts that flitted across Russia's airwaves
and Web sites Friday, there was another reason for Skuratov's
dismissal, one having to do not with Swiss bank accounts but with
the sex video scandal.
</P>
<P>
   According to those accounts, Skuratov's relationship with the
two prostitutes was not a simple one-night stand, but rather a
lengthy affair involving trips to the Black Sea resort of Sochi,
all paid for by a businessman who, it is said, was under
investigation by the Moscow prosecutor's office and who used the
videotape as blackmail against the country's chief prosecutor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to a report issued Friday by the news agency Interfax,
a significant piece of evidence became available late Thursday,
when one of the two prostitutes in the video was interviewed by
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting versions are symptomatic of the most recent
phase of Russia's political wars, in which antagonists have reached
into their rich reserves of ``kompromat'' _ compromising material _
in attempts to tarnish one another.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised interview Friday, two of Yeltsin's top law
enforcement officials _ Vladimir Putin, head of the Federal
Security Service, and Sergei Stepashin, the interior minister _
said that Yeltsin's order to dismiss Skuratov was both justified
and constitutional. The investigation is being carried out by a
deputy Moscow prosecutor, they said, adding that Skuratov's
dismissal would not interfere with cases at the federal level.
</P>
<P>
   But after vociferous debate, the lower house of the parliament
on Friday passed a resolution challenging the constitutionality of
the president's order, and asking the upper house to review it as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Yeltsin succeeded Friday in winning the approval of
his fellow presidents in the Commonwealth of Independent States for
the dismissal of another troublesome figure, Boris Berezovsky, a
financier and political intriguer whose businesses have come under
investigation and who is said to have maintained close ties to the
Yeltsin family, in particular the president's daughter, Tatyana
Dyachenko.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky was not present at the commonwealth's summit meeting.
In fact, he was not even in Moscow. His plane, which left Paris on
Thursday, was denied permission to fly through Russian airspace and
changed course to Kiev, the Ukrainian capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can comment on events that don't contradict common sense,''
said Berezovsky in an interview with Interfax, as he sat fuming in
the Kiev airport, `'but I cannot comment on a lunatic asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, who is scheduled for questioning by the Russian
prosecutor's office, said that once he had missed the commonwealth
meeting, he was no longer in any hurry to return to Moscow. But he
denied reports that he would seek asylum in another country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell certain Russian politicians, `Do not even
hope''' for this, he told Interfax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
