<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-COX     04-02 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROWING FEARS THAT KOSOVO CRISIS COULD SPARK CIVIL WAR IN
MONTENEGRO
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro, Yugoslavia Despite efforts of the
government here to calm public anxiety, people in this tiny,
Western-leaning republic next to Serbia are bracing for war.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-led NATO air campaign against Serbia has heightened
tensions and fueled talk of a coup d'etat in this neighboring
state, which exists in an uneasy federation with Serbia to make up
present-day Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Britain said it had evidence that Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic is plotting a coup in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   A sudden government takeover or a protracted civil war between
pro- and anti-Serb factions in Montenegro would up the stakes in
NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia and possibly intensify
pressure on the United States and its allies to commit
</P>
<P>
   ground troops to the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to panic,'' Predrag Drecun, the government
minister for social welfare, told a news conference Friday in an
effort to allay fears.
</P>
<P>
   But government officials in Montenegro have said privately that
they suspect Belgrade could seek to take advantage of the NATO
attacks to seize control of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Milosevic, the Serb leader who heads the federal
government, replaced his army chief in Montenegro with a close ally
to command the estimated 12,000 Yugoslav army troops stationed in
Montenegro. Second Army Cmdr. Gen. Radoslav Martinovic was recalled
to Belgrade and replaced by the nationalist Gen. Milorad Obradovic.
</P>
<P>
   The move, coupled with an increased presence of interior
ministry troops on the street in Podgorica loyal to the
anti-Milosevic government of Montenegro, has raised concerns and
speculation that a coup could be imminent, or that the opposing
troops could enter into a bloody struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are afraid there will be a civil war,'' said
Nebojsa Vukcevic, manager of a rental car agency here in the
capital, Podgorica.
</P>
<P>
   For the West, Montenegro and its population of 680,000, has in
recent years represented an important toehold in the troubled
Balkans. President Milo Djukanovic, the liberal who heads the
ethnically-mixed republic, has put distance between himself and
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade and won Western support for democratic and economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Despite NATO attacks on federal Yugoslav military targets within
Montenegro, Djukanovic has declined to endorse Belgrade's
declaration of a state of war or exercise extraordinary control of
the media.
</P>
<P>
   His government also is struggling with the potentially
destabilizing influx of more than 20,000 refugees from the besieged
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The uneasiness in this relatively quiet corner of the Balkans
has been reinforced in recent days by assessments from the United
States and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have evidence to show that (Milosevic) is preparing a coup
against Montenegro,'' senior British Defense Ministry official
Edgar Buckley said Friday in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are watching the situation very carefully. All our options
are open,'' he added in remarks before a daily news briefing on the
NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said Friday that U.S.
support for Djukanovic is ``strong and unwavering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any attempt to overthrow the democratically-elected government
of Montenegro would only fuel wider instability and lead to deeper
isolation for Yugoslavia and escalate the conflict with NATO, `` he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro's main opposition party, the Socialist People's Party
(SNP), which is aligned with Milosevic, said Friday it was
committed to stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a state of war, any change in the authorities would
represent a revolution, a change brought about by violence and
civil strife. We want to avoid this,'' SNP vice-president Predrag
Bulatovic told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   But on the street, few were convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sitting on the top of a volcano here,'' said a local
aid worker and pro-democracy advocate.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
