Editors: The following stories on the opening of the 1999 major
league baseball season will move Saturday, April 3: 
(jt)  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BBO-SEASON (Undated) _ Even before the 1999 major-league
baseball season begins, it would seem that at least half of
baseball's teams are out of contention for no other reason than
budget constraints. A look at how they approach the game with that
in mind. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-SEASON-ONETIMERS (Undated) _ The major-league season starts
Sunday and, as is always the case, dozens of rookies will see
stardom looming before them. But for all their promise, at least a
few of them will become answers to a trivia question, appearing but
once. Then something _ injuries or fate or their own abilities _
will keep them from ever coming back. Countless ballplayers have
come up to the major leagues for the proverbial cup of coffee, but
only a few hundred have tasted the demitasse of a single game _
often at the end of blowouts or in the waning days of a losing
season. Most were standouts at every previous level of play. Some
bask in those memories. For others, their short careers still gnaw
at or embarrass them. By David Margolick.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-SEASON-GLOVES (Undated) _ Six million baseball gloves are
sold in the United States each year; maybe 2,000 end up on the
hands of major-leaguers. For most of these players, there is no
piece of equipment more important than their glove, which makes
sense: bats break and balls disappear into the stands, but a
player's glove is always waiting for him back on the bench. Last
season home-run balls got all the attention; it seems appropriate
now to give equal time to gloves. By Noah Liberman.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-SEASON-AMERICAN (Undated) _ Previews of the American League
teams, in order of projected finish. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-SEASON-NATIONAL (Undated) _ Previews of the National League
teams, in order of projected finish. By Murray Chass.
