<HEADER>
A4159 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WESTERN-RESOURCES-KAN     04-02 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-RESOURCES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN RESOURCES SUBSIDIARY'S SEC REVIEW SENDS STOCK DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Western Resources Inc. said Thursday that its
Protection One subsidiary would have to restate earnings for the
past two years after a review by the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement pushed Western's stock price lower and renewed
questions about the fate of its proposed purchase of Kansas City
Power &AMP; Light Co.
</P>
<P>
   Western's stock Thursday fell 1 3/16, to 25 1/2. The merger
agreement permits either company to stop the deal shortly before it
becomes official if Western's stock price is at or below 29 25/32.
</P>
<P>
   Western said it expected the stock price to go up as the merger
nears completion and it gets the necessary regulatory approvals.
KCP&AMP;L said it was too early to discuss how it would respond if
Western's stock doesn't rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't speculate what would be done, but everyone here is
monitoring that,'' said Pam Levetzow, a KCP&AMP;L spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The questions followed Thursday's announcement that Protection
One, a burglar alarm company that is 85 percent owned by Western,
was ordered by the SEC to restate its earnings. The problem centers
on how Protection One accounted for the costs of replacing the
monitored-security service's yard signs.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC order adds $6.9 million to Protection One's net income
in 1997 but decreases net income by $13 million for 1998.
Protection One's stock Thursday lost 2 1/4, to 4.
</P>
<P>
   The restatement will ripple to Western Resources' shareholders,
as 1998 earnings will decline from a previously announced 84 cents
per share to 67 cents per share. Western received a 15-day
extension from the SEC to file its 1998 financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling to some analysts was the SEC's decision to
further review Protection One's accounting of customer acquisition
costs over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC questioned whether the method was appropriate.
Protection One is in the process of buying Lifeline Systems Inc., a
health monitoring company.
</P>
<P>
   Michel' Philipp, a spokeswoman for Topeka-based Western
Resources, said it was an accepted industry practice to spread
customer acquisition costs over more than one year. Protection One
is working with the SEC to resolve the matter. A resolution could
be reached by mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the scrutiny of Protection One, Western Resources hasn't
soured on the company. It is a high-growth company and continues to
fit in Western's plans, Philipp said.
</P>
<P>
   Western recently has been more critical of regulatory efforts to
increase utility rate reductions, which the company has said hurts
its financial operations.
</P>
<P>
   David Wittig, Western Resource's chairman and chief executive
officer, on Thursday again raised the issue in a letter to
shareholders. He said the stock's recent performance, which is down
from a 52-week high of 43, was due to utility rate decreases that
cost the company $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, more cuts suggested by the staff of the
Kansas Corporation Commission would scuttle the merger with KCP&AMP;L.
The letter also urged shareholders to participate more in the
company's Dividend Reinvestment Plan, an effort to help maintain
the expected dividend of $2.14 per share in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Western's stock price, which is at its lowest level
in the past year, stirred more speculation about the KCP&AMP;L
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Fischer, an analyst with A.G. Edwards, said that anytime
Western's stock declined, the question was raised. KCP&AMP;L has told
analysts it will look closely at the numbers before completing the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   The merger agreement allows either Western or KCP&AMP;L to terminate
the deal a few days before it would become official if the stock
price is at 29 25/32 or below. Since regulatory hearings haven't
been conducted yet, the deal might not be wrapped up until later
this year or in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As crafted, the merger agreement benefits KCP&AMP;L shareholders
more as Western's stock rises. For each share of KCP&AMP;L stock, which
closed Thursday at 24 3/8, shareholders would receive one share of
Westar Energy. Westar Energy would be a separately traded entity
that would include the KGE, KPL and KCP&AMP;L electric utilities.
Nearly a year ago it was estimated that a share of Westar would be
worth $10 to $12.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, KCP&AMP;L shareholders would receive Western stock.
Originally that stock was estimated to be worth about $23.50 a
share, but the value varies depending on the price of Western's
stock. At Thursday's price, KCP&AMP;L shareholders would receive
Western stock worth $18.41 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Philipp, the Western spokeswoman, said the company's stock would
rise once regulators approve the buyout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger goes on,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1904EST &QL; 
