<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROUND OF APPLAUSE FOR THESE ECONOMIC HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ How did America get to 10,000 on the Dow Jones
industrial average and within 11 months of the longest economic
expansion in U.S. history?
</P>
<P>
   Who are the heroes of this saga? Who should get credit for
America's rise from the depths of despair two decades ago to the
heights of its greatest prosperity ever? It's hard to believe, but
as the 1980s dawned, the stock market was a disaster and so was the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Japan was booming, and it had become fashionable to hold it up
as an example of the new economic paradigm America had to embrace
if it hoped to ever regain its greatness. The received wisdom among
liberal academics and politicos was that future prosperity was
possible only with a partnership of government and private
enterprise. The concept turned on the notion that government should
be the steward of an industrial policy ensuring that winners got
first dibs on increasingly scarce capital.
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, America took the opposite path. The result was an
emphasis on deregulation, lower tax rates for income and capital
gains, and diminishing central bank intrusion in the financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, any hall of fame honoring those who made the most
critical contributions to the current prosperity should start with
a Democrat, not a Republican. President Jimmy Carter was, in
retrospect, the first key player. He got the ball rolling toward
deregulation. Most importantly, he took the first steps to free the
energy market from misguided regulatory constraints that caused
crisis-inducing supply shortages. Carter also created another hero
of the epoch when he appointed Paul Volcker chairman of the Federal
Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Volcker was a pivotal factor, because he broke the back of
inflation with his decree that the financial marketplace be allowed
to determine interest rates. Meantime, the Fed would mind monetary
policy with an eye toward noninflationary money-supply growth.
</P>
<P>
   An unsung hero was Rep. Bill Steiger, a Wisconsin Republican
whose late-1970s crusade to cut the capital gains tax rate resulted
in its reduction by nearly half.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Jarvis, a California tax rebel, also deserves
considerable credit for pushing his property tax relief initiative
over the top in his home state. In the process, he ignited a tax
revolt that spread eastward, state by state, until it hit the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The tax revolt brought with it a former governor of California,
Ronald Reagan, who arrived in Washington and became the first
president since John F. Kennedy to champion significant tax relief
for working Americans. The Reaganomics regime saw the marginal
income tax rate decline from 70 percent for the highest earners to
28 percent for most average taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Another hero has been Alan Greenspan, who succeeded Volcker and
has fought inflation as tenaciously as his predecessor. Greenspan's
regime built on Volcker's accomplishments and gave the economy
sustained price stability for the first time in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   The debt America owes these heroes for its continuing good
fortune can't be overstated. While the rest of the world is beset
by economic malaise and predicaments of varying degrees, America
remains not only an oasis of prosperity but also the world's only
remaining engine of growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
