s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SUNDERLAN     04-02 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SUNDERLAND-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN M. SUNDERLAND: KEEPING SCHWEPPES BUBBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John M. Sunderland, the elfin-faced chief executive of Cadbury
Schweppes, has always been afraid of heights and for years resisted
flying. Yet there he was last year in Interlaken, Switzerland,
donning para-gliding gear and leaping from an Alpine crag in full
view of a gaggle of underlings.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose, he said, was to help underscore the ``managing for
value'' strategy that he believes will transform Cadbury Schweppes
from a sleepy, opportunity-missing, ultra-British conglomerate into
a sleek, value-driven global powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to prove that you can do anything if you set your
mind to it,'' said Sunderland, 54. Nothing interfered with his
flight, he said, and he even managed a dignified landing _ though
asked later whether he had tried paragliding again, he replied,
emphatically, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the gathered executives seem to have gotten the message.
Profits at the Cadbury Schweppes candy-and-soft-drink empire rose 6
percent last year, and the share price skyrocketed as well. The
company has started to get the attention of Wall Street, which had
dismissed it as a weak, third-tier player that relied too heavily
on bottling agreements with rivals like Coca-Cola and and Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   Sipping every so often from a Diet Dr Pepper in a recent
interview in New York, Sunderland held forth on the importance of
setting a good example _ and on following the lead of one of his
idols, Margaret Thatcher, who fanned the flames of privatization in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``She demonstrated that change _ dramatic change for the benefit
of not just business, but society as a whole _ could be done if you
were committed to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mrs. Thatcher, he likes to shake things up in the name of
efficiency. For nearly two years he has been a Thatcher clone in
pinstripes, spreading across the company a message that exhorts
managers to be more accountable, adaptable and aggressive. And he
emphasizes increasing shareholder value (while making sure managers
are heavily invested in Cadbury shares, too).
</P>
<P>
   While such precepts may seem old hat to American executives,
particularly those at Coca-Cola (a company Sunderland knows well
and admires, thanks to a former bottling joint venture), they are
innovations at Cadbury. The company makes such quintessentially
British sweets as licorice allsorts, as well as Cadbury chocolates
and Dr Pepper, 7-Up and Schweppes soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Under Sir Dominic Cadbury, its chairman, Cadbury Schweppes spent
the first half of the '90s expanding beyond Britain, including its
purchase of the Dr Pepper/Seven Up Co., based in Plano, Texas, in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Sunderland is moving to solidify that expansion. First came a
joint venture in early 1998 that formed a bottling company
dedicated to Cadbury brands. Then Cadbury negotiated bottling
agreements with Coke and Pepsico that seemed to guarantee that
brands like Dr Pepper and 7-Up would be secure for several years.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Cadbury announced it was selling most of the
international rights to its brands, ranging from Dr Pepper to
Schweppes itself, to Coca-Cola. While the deal faces regulatory
hurdles and will likely take several more months to be completed,
it is worth $1.85 billion to Cadbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a somewhat neglected stock,'' said Caroline
Levy, an analyst who follows the beverage industry for Schroder &AMP;
Company. ``What they achieved last year took the market by
surprise.'' After rising 67 percent in 1998, the stock is down 11.6
percent so far this year, but Ms. Levy thinks it still shows a lot
of promise.
</P>
<P>
   Sunderland denied speculation that the Coca-Cola deal was but
the first step in his company's exit from beverages. After all, he
said, Cadbury has a 15 percent share of the American market. ``Why
on earth would we want to relinquish a position like that?'' he
asked. Still, many analysts expect the company to invest far more
heavily in its candy business than in soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Sunderland, who says he has 80 percent of his own net worth tied
up in Cadbury stock, grew up in Yorkshire and graduated from the
University of St. Andrews in Edinburgh with a degree in social
studies. He joined Cadbury's marketing department in 1968. Two
career high points, he said, were a stint in Ireland (he wears a
silver signet ring featuring Dublin's city crest) and his
orchestration of a merger of two English confectionery brands,
Trebor and Bassett. ``The satisfaction of creating something was
just exhilarating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his spare time, Sunderland, who lives with his wife, Jeannie,
outside London, likes to hunt partridge, grouse and quail. He is
often accompanied by one of his three sons, whose ages range from
20 to 29. With his children leaning toward professions far
different from his own, he has started referring to them as
``altruists;'' his daughter is a teacher, and one son is in
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   As for the kinds of acquisitions Cadbury might make once the
deal with Coca-Cola becomes final, Sunderland offers few hints.
Consolidating the independent bottlers in the United States is one
priority, but he says he sees the fragmented global candy business
as a bigger gold mine. ``I'm a great believer in serendipity,'' he
said. ``It got me where I am today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
