A4165 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CONCERNS-KAN &LR;      04-02 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CONCERNS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL GORE'S PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDACY HAS CREATED CONCERNS AMONG
DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The good news for Vice President Al Gore is that
after six years of laboring in Bill Clinton's shadow, he is
beginning to step out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the bad news, too.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore runs for president and begins to color in his own
personality, the early results have not been good. From boasting
about ``creating the Internet,'' to recalling how he used to
``clean out hog waste with a shovel and a hose,'' he has run into
ridicule lately as he's tried to define who he is.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all that, early polls continue to show him lagging
behind both front-runners in the Republican presidential race,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former Red Cross chief Elizabeth
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Are Democrats worried?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit of a growing feeling of a little sense of
urgency,'' said Steve Jarding, national political director for Sen.
Robert Kerrey, a Nebraska Democrat who once considered challenging
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore is going to be the nominee of our party, he needs
to step out of that shadow _ of Clinton _ pretty quickly. The
problem is not the poll numbers. The problem is what underlies
those polls. Is this an individual who has the capacity to rally
the American public? It really is the $64,000 question.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argue that the vice president's recent missteps will
be forgotten soon enough and are not the kind of pivotal concerns
that turn an election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is the best candidate for president that the
Democratic Party could ever find,'' said Joan Menard, party
chairwoman in Massachusetts and president of the State Democratic
Chairs Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every front-runner gets dissected and attacked, and better
that it happens a year out than during the primary season,'' said
Democratic pollster Mark Mellman, who has worked for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the first primary votes won't be cast until next year
and the presidential election is 19 months away. But Gore's biggest
challenge will be to energize Democrats who may feel somewhat spent
after manning the barricades so long for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What effect is the impeachment mess going to have on Gore and
whether Gore really can connect with the electorate like Bill
Clinton did are all questions Gore is going to have to answer,''
said James Slattery, a former Democratic congressman from Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has to master the tricky ballet of distancing himself from
the president and becoming more his own person, while hoping to
inherit a strong economy and a stable foreign situation. In a
recent speech to the American Legion, he mentioned Clinton only
once, a passing reference to his support for veterans' benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans believe that somebody, if not the president
himself _ whose post-impeachment public approval remains high _ is
eventually going to bear the cost of the Clinton scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore may be another in long line of Clinton associates who
pays the price for Bill Clinton's actions,'' said David Israelite,
political director for the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's strong backing and fund-raising potential are just two
of the advantages Gore will have in the Democratic primaries. He
has racked up early establishment support, with endorsements from
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri and Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Jarding said some Democratic activists believe that the best
thing that could happen to Gore is for him to face an aggressive
primary fight. He said Gore is an experienced politician with a
talented staff, but ``he needs to hone his own operation, his own
ideas, his own campaign. He's never done it on his own. That's what
has people a little bit on edge.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Democrat left to challenge Gore is former Sen. Bill
Bradley, who derides the vice president as a cautious pillar of the
old-line Washington establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley spent 18 years in the Senate, he portrays
himself as a Democratic outsider from a small town in Missouri _
Crystal City _ with ``a life before I got into politics.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether voters believe that ``a life'' as an NBA
star makes him more of a regular guy than Gore, who grew up the son
of a senator, lived in a Washington hotel and attended Ivy League
schools. Bradley went to Princeton and was a Rhodes scholar.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bradley's criticism that prompted Gore to wax nostalgic
about how as a youth, his father taught him to ``clear land with a
double-bladed ax...plow a steep hillside with a team of
mules...take up hay all day long in the hot sun...'' He then asked
whether ``Senator Bradley has had any of those experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   But his recollections only earned him attention like the
American Gothic cartoon parody on the front page of the Des Moines
Register.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans made great sport of Gore's gaffes. Of his claim to
cleaning up after hogs on his family's Tennessee farm, Republican
Party Chairman Jim Nicholson said, ``Mr. Vice President, with all
due respect, you're shoveling a lot more of it right now than you
ever did back then.''
</P>
<P>
   This rocky patch has created a degree of uneasiness, especially
when combined with the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Dole lead him in most surveys, even in California, even
among Hispanics, important factors for any Democratic victory in
2000. Of those Americans who count themselves as Clinton
supporters, a Pew Research Center poll noted, only a third said
there was a good chance they'd vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But for every poll that gives Republicans hope, history comforts
the Democrats. Gary Hart was ahead of President Bush roughly at
this stage 12 years ago. And Michael Dukakis, who won the
Democratic nomination the following year, led Bush by a healthy
margin, only to lose eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Mellman, the Democratic pollster, described the high approval
ratings of President Bush's son, George W. Bush, and Dole, wife of
1996 GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole, as ``idealized'' because
most of the people in those surveys had little or no idea about
what those two candidates stood for.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Gore's problem is his image. There have always been two
Gores, the public one, whose stiff image, even with his
self-deprecating jokes, often fails to inspire. Many say the
private Gore can be playful, with a biting sense of humor, or
plain-spoken with a take-no-prisoners style that the public rarely
sees.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, former Clinton aide George Stephanopoulos
describes a witty Gore who ribbed Clinton regularly. And in an
account of the early Clinton presidency by Bob Woodward, Gore,
frustrated with the president's waffling in budget talks, turned to
him and snapped: ``You can get with the ... program!''
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Cherny, the vice president's former senior speech writer,
said it's important that Gore reveal more of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he needs to do is go out there and tell his story,'' said
Cherny, who edits Blueprint, a centrist Democratic policy magazine.
``And that means not just details of his life, but what he stands
for, what he won't stand for, what are the public values and
principles that he holds. When the American people do get a full
sense of that, they'll respond favorably.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
