<HEADLINE>
AVERAGE PRICE OF GAS IN AREA UP ALMOST 34 PERCENT IN LESS THAN A
MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In less than a month, the average price of
gasoline in the Kansas City area has soared almost 34 percent,
including a 10 percent jump since last weekend. That's the biggest
jump since 1990, after Iraq invaded Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoyed unreasonably low prices in 1998; we probably won't
see that this year,'' said Mike Right of AAA Automobile Club of
Missouri, which tracks price trends.
</P>
<P>
   Right said a survey last Friday found that the area average
price for a gallon of self-serve regular unleaded was 96 1/2 cents.
When today's survey is compiled, Right said, the average price is
expected to jump to $1.06 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as March 5, the average price at area pumps was just
under 80 cents a gallon. The last time prices were in the $1-plus
range was last July.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan of the American Petroleum Institute in Washington
said several recent events had driven up prices at the pump,
especially in California, where some prices are around $2 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries
reached an agreement to limit production. Although such efforts
have faltered in the past because some members cheated and pumped
more oil than they pledged, Right said those renegades might adhere
this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of some of the severe economic problems that some of
the members are having because of low prices, I believe more of
them will stick with the program,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor driving up prices is a decrease in world
supplies, a naturally occurring cyclical factor, Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a fire at a West Coast refinery and mechanical problems at
another have slowed production.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may think that because those refineries aren't in this
area that it won't affect their prices, but that's not true,''
Shanahan said. ``It affects prices everywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
