<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBS REPORT SPURS BOND RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A smaller-than-expected increase in nonfarm payroll
jobs last month, in part a result of a decline in manufacturing
jobs, set off the bond market's best rally in four weeks Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a special holiday-shortened session, held to allow trading
after the 8:30 a.m. release of the March employment data, the price
of the 30-year Treasury bond jumped 1 2/32, to 95 1/32. The bond's
yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price, fell
to 5.59 percent from 5.67 percent on Thursday. The bond market is
normally closed on Good Friday, but trading Friday occurred until
noon.
</P>
<P>
   The rally came after a two-day sell-off that started with the
report of data from National Association of Purchasing
Management-Chicago and continued with the report of the National
Association of Purchasing Management. Both reports indicated that
manufacturing had not only ended its decline of the last year but
was rebounding strongly.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of an additional lift to economic growth, given the
already strong consumer spending, made many traders worry more
about the possibility of an interest rate increase by the Federal
Reserve later this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the employment data showed that manufacturing employment
declined by 35,000 jobs last month and was down by 374,000 since
March 1998. ``The employment report does tend to alleviate some of
the anxieties from the purchasing managers reports,'' said Kevin
Flanagan, money market economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said the March jobs data showed that ``at best, manufacturing has
just flattened out.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to calming fears about a surge in manufacturing, the
jobs report showed once again that the economy seems to be able to
grow strongly without generating inflationary pressures. One of the
key measures of wage inflation, hourly earnings, rose just
two-tenths of 1 percent last month, the same pace as in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we get another report saying the economy is strong and
labor is tight,'' said James E. Glassman, senior U.S. economist at
Chase Manhattan Bank. ``But there is no inflationary imbalance.''
The reason, he said, is that with the rest of the world's economy
growing sluggishly or worse, competition is preventing American
companies from making price increases stick.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts agreed that the low March job growth, which was
clearly held back by bad weather and was well below Wall Street
forecasts of 140,000, did not confirm that the economy was slowing
significantly from the torrid 6 percent pace of growth in the
fourth quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this uncertainty, interest rates are likely to remain
in their recent trading range, with long-term rates centered around
5.5 percent. They first jumped to this level in February after it
became clear that the economy entered 1999 at a much stronger pace
than expected and would not slow down quickly, as many Wall street
economists had forecast at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are elements of moderation coming through, but it is not
very compelling yet,'' said Glassman, whose forecast for the year
is one of the slower on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Fine said that consumer spending was still so strong that
barring a sudden collapse in the stock market, it would take some
time for the economy to slow significantly. He is forecasting 3
percent to 3.5 percent growth for the first quarter. He said such a
pace would normally be ``a little too rapid for the Fed.'' But
given that inflation remains in check and that the pace of growth
would be slowing, he said the Fed should be happy. ``If the Fed was
on hold before, this would give them more breathing room,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fine said that the Fed could not cut interest rates because the
economy was still too strong. But it cannot raise rates either, he
argued, because inflation is not a threat now and because of the
fragility of the global economy, with both Latin America and Asia
struggling to turn themselves around.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the performance of the futures contracts on the federal
funds rate, the Federal Reserve's target short-term interest rate,
some investors still think that the next move by the central bank
will be up. The yield on the contract for October has risen in the
last two days to 4.93 percent, which is almost a
quarter-percentage-point above the Fed's current 4.75 percent
target, which it left unchanged at its policy-making meeting
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
