<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRESIDENT OF COSTA RICA URGES U.S. TO WORK FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACE HOBSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ The United States should promote peace and
democracy by working to eliminate poverty and war, Nobel Peace
Laureate Oscar Arias said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a packed University of Kansas lecture hall, the
former president of Costa Rica warned that the current ethics of
war and greed would not suffice in the globalization of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world expects you to be not only an economic superpower
and a military superpower but a moral superpower,'' Arias said.
</P>
<P>
   Arias won the Nobel Peace Prize for brokering an agreement in
1987 that ended fighting in Central America. Since then, he has
devoted his life to promoting world peace, democracy and
demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of working for military security, Arias said, he works
for human security, which comes from wiping out illiteracy,
disease, poverty and environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy in Latin America is made unstable by poverty,
especially the widening gap between the poor and wealthy. Arias
said Latin America had the world's widest income disparity.
</P>
<P>
   War threatens democracy even more, Arias said. And greed often
feeds war, he said, noting U.S. arms sales around the world.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. interests are served by spending more money on foreign aid
_ not military aid _ to promote human security, Arias said. A
fraction of the world's military spending would feed each person on
the planet over 10 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Americans think the U.S. government spends more on
foreign aid than any other expense, the amount is truly negligible,
Arias said. United States gives $700 million in foreign aid to
Africa _ that's $1 for each person, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest challenge is for us to create a new ethics,'' he
said. ``You need to be a moral superpower.''
</P>
<P>
   His speech kicked off a three-day symposium on Costa Rican
democracy, peace and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   A country's citizens are responsible for the actions of their
leaders, Arias told the students. Once citizens push for the ethics
of peace, human security and democracy, the people will find
themselves transformed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we will create not only a better world but a new,
more compassionate people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
