<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRE-SEASON INJURIES PLAGUE REVOLUTION, WIZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Major League Soccer teams cannot be expected to be
in midseason form. But rosters are beginning to resemble those of
teams which have already experienced a long campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution will be missing four starters and the Kansas City
Wizards three because of injury when they meet at Arrowhead Stadium
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 21 players on the Revolution roster, only 15 will be
available, necessitating the callup of John Kerr from the Boston
Bulldogs. The Wizards will be missing goalkeeper Tony Meola (knee)
and defenders Scott Bowers (concussion) and Scott Uderitz (knee).
</P>
<P>
   So, the Revolution will likely continue in their conservative
mode, relying on the goalkeeping of player-coach Walter Zenga. Last
week, they held the Miami Fusion scoreless until the final four
minutes and, though Kansas City has one of the most explosive
lineups in the league, the Wizards have failed to convert in two
games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Injuries are a part of the game,'' Revolution defender Dan
Calichman said. ``But it's not as bad for us as some people think.
These are not major injuries. And what this does is gives other
guys the opportunity to step up and show what they can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City has some big injuries, too, especially Tony
Meola's. But we can't call each other up and say we'll play
sometime later, when everyone is healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Revolution misfortunes are a portent, they could be
facing a difficult season. Yet, the defensive organization was
impressive and Zenga was spectacular, though without seeming to
have overextended himself, against Miami. The Revolution lost in
the post-match shootout, but were rewarded by the fact that they
held the lead for nearly the entire game and deprived Miami of a
3-point win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have won the game, but it's okay that it finished
1-1,'' Calichman said. ``We are going to be in a similar situation
now, so we have to be smart. We have to pick and choose our times.
We lost another key starter and we are going away, so we have to
try and steal a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Revolution habitually surrendered late goals,
but those errors usually were tie-breakers. In fact, during the
1998 season, the Revolution held the lead for only 130 minutes of
games against Eastern Conference opposition before being eliminated
from playoff contention. So, to have led the Fusion for 88 minutes
last Sunday, after Giovanni Savarese's opening-minute goal, should
be considered an accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   But Savarese will miss this match after suffering a tibia bruise
and ankle sprain during a Wednesday scrimmage against the New
Hampshire Phantoms. Since Carlos Rocha had been waived the previous
day, the Revolution were left with two forwards for this game.
</P>
<P>
   There is little room to manuever since midfielders Imad Baba
(groin), Edwin Gorter (suspension), John Harkes (knee), and Kris
Kelderman (knee) are also out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened with Gio was crazy, a freak thing,'' Calichman
said. ``Their guys should have used better judgement, because Gio
had no chance to get out of the tackle. What happened to John
(Harkes) was he strained a ligament on his last pass of the day,
and Imad chose to have surgery in the preseason so he could be
ready four or five weeks into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to set our goals, now. Because we don't have our best
13 available, we have to come up with a different way to beat a
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
