<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-FLAHERTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN F. `RED' FLAHERTY, 81; WAS AMERICAN LEAGUE UMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John F. ``Red'' Flaherty, who called 'em as he saw 'em as an
American League baseball umpire for 21 years, died of complications
of a stroke Thursday in his home in Falmouth. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   During his long career in the majors, Mr. Flaherty caught his
share of slings and arrows. In 1954, when he was officiating at a
game between the Washington Senators and the New York Yankees, he
called a Senator ``out'' at home plate when he tried to score from
second on a single. Attending the game was President Eisenhower,
who yelled out ``No.'' Later in the locker room, Mr. Flaherty was
asked whether Eisenhower's displeasure made him rethink his
position. ``No,'' said Mr. Flaherty. ``It wasn't even close.''
</P>
<P>
   After one memorable game in Fenway Park on May 16, 1973, the
headline over a story in the Globe the next day read ``Flaherty
Calls Leave Detroit Laughing, Sox Weeping 'n Bleeping.'' Red Sox
slugger Carl Yastrzemski said Mr. Flaherty should be umpiring in
the Little League, not the Major League.
</P>
<P>
   And what is it like to go to work knowing you're likely to be
cursed out by one side or the other?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what it would be like when I went into umpiring,'' Mr.
Flaherty said in a story published in the Globe on May 22, 1973.
Like baseball, he said, umpiring goes in streaks. ``Sometimes you
go weeks without a beef and then you get one every other game,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm right, all the yelling in the world doesn't bother
me,'' he said. ``But, if I think I might had missed it, sure, I
have second thoughts. I worry about it.'' But he said he didn't
hold a grudge. ``You lose concentration if you think about past
arguments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Flaherty was born in Marlborough, Mass. and grew up in
Maynard, Mass. He graduated from Boston College High School in 1936
and attended Boston College before serving in the Marine Corps in
the South Pacific during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He became an umpire in 1952. He worked in four World Series and
three All-Star games before his retirment in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Jeannette C. (Thompson); a son, Peter of
Falmouth, Mass.; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
