<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-ART-825     04-02 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-ART-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO'S GROUND TROOPS: SENT FOR ONE MISSION, WAIT FOR ORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Lt. Charles-Philippe D'Orleans had no hesitation in
describing the 2,500 French troops deployed with him in Macedonia.
``They are highly mobile elite forces, the best we have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The troops are based in Kumanovo, a few miles from the border
with Kosovo, and are flanked by a heavily armored British regiment
of 4,000 troops, whose equipment includes 14 Challenger tanks and
several armored personnel carriers, and a 3,000-strong elite German
force.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the soldiers could provide the nucleus for any NATO
ground force that goes into Kosovo, whether to secure a limited
area for the protection of ethnic Albanians or on some broader
mission.
</P>
<P>
   But a British officer, Capt. Simon Worthy, said there was no
question of changing the troops' mission, ``to provide the vanguard
of a force that would only deploy in Kosovo in the event of a peace
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation of these NATO forces, who have been placed under
the operational control of a British officer, Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson
of the Allied Rapid Reaction Corps, appears to illustrate the
contradictions in the West's military plans. The forces are in
Macedonia to reinforce a Kosovo peace plan seemingly overtaken by
events.
</P>
<P>
   That plan, offering autonomy guaranteed by a NATO presence to
the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo, was put together in Rambouillet,
France, before the NATO bombardment began, more than 250,000
Albanians were driven from their houses by Serbian forces, and the
West's perception of President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia
switched from bully to butcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think we can get back to Rambouillet,'' Robert
Hunter, a former U.S. ambassador to NATO said. ``At this stage, I
am in favor of doing what is needed to win the war. We need more
aggressive air power and intensive planning for possible use of
ground forces to unsettle Milosevic and get across to him that he
will lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Western officials insisted that after an early review that had
found that 200,000 troops would be needed to invade Kosovo and that
the public would never support such a move no active planning to
use ground forces was under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would be crazy to say we would never use ground forces,''
Lt. Col. Christopher Deverell of the British Defense Ministry said.
``But it is basically nonsensical. There are no plans. The idea is
extremely remote and in any event, a suitable force would take
months to assemble.''
</P>
<P>
   The West's plan seems to consist of pursuing a military aim for
which there is scant, if any, successful precedent, dislodging an
army, the Serbian forces that are marauding in Kosovo, with air
power alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sure would have loved to stop the North Koreans or Saddam
with air power, but things don't work that way,'' a retired
general, Ed Soyster, said. ``If you're dug in right, you can
survive artillery, let alone air power. You can punish someone with
air power. But I don't believe you can stop an army.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, the pressure to use ground troops could
mount. The mission of the Western troops in Macedonia has already
changed once, from an ``extraction force'' for the 1,500 officials
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe who were
in Kosovo until the bombing began, to a force to carry out any
possible peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Recent Balkan history shows that such elite troops can easily
change hats. When a Rapid Reaction Force, made up mainly of British
and French elements, was sent to Bosnia in 1995, its mission was
portrayed as essentially helping to protect U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   But when NATO bombing of Bosnian Serb positions began in August
1995, the Rapid Reaction Force artillery was quickly put to use
against the Serbs. It proved devastating.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there are close to 12,000 NATO troops in Macedonia,
including 950 Italians, more than 200 Dutch troops, and 400 of
various nationalities attached to the Rapid Reaction Corps
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Those headquarters moved from Rheindahlen, Germany, to Macedonia
a few weeks ago, an action that clearly illustrates the scale of
NATO's new operations in Macedonia. In all, a force of 28,000 was
planned to carry out any peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the headquarters appears to suggest that the alliance
planned from the outset for a rapidly adaptable presence in the
area just south of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the European troops, 350 American soldiers in
Macedonia are maintaining a camp near the capital, Skopje, that
would be a staging area for a Kosovo deployment in the event of a
settlement. The three American soldiers captured near the Yugoslav
border are from that element.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that any move into Kosovo would have to be led
by the Americans. The Europeans have less traumatic fear of
casualties than Americans _ the French had 56 dead in Bosnia and
scarcely blinked _ but they also learned from Bosnia that if the
Allies do not act in concert, disarray ensues.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most readily transportable American forces in Europe are in
the Southern European Task Force, a 4,000-member airborne light
infantry brigade based in Vicenza, Italy; the 24th Marine
Expeditionary Unit in the Adriatic, with 2,000 troops and materiel
like attack helicopters and tanks, and the 1,000-members Special
Forces drawn from the Army, Navy and Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond those troops, the United States still has a large
military presence in Europe, although much reduced over the decade
since the Cold War ended. Whereas more than 300,000 American
soldiers were in Europe in 1989, just over 100,000 are stationed
there now.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. European Command in Stuttgart, Germany,
Capt. Tim Taylor, said the United States had 70,000 troops in
Germany, principally in the 1st Infantry Division in Wurzberg and
the 1st Armored Division in Bad Kreuznach. An additional 11,500
troops are stationed in Italy, 10,000 in Britain, and close to
7,000 in Bosnia, with smaller presences elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Of the troops, 65,000 are in the Army, 34,000 in the Air Force,
10,000 in the Navy and 1,000 in the Special Forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power in Europe is considerable,'' Hunter said. ``But you
have to decide if you are prepared to take risks. Right now we are
pursuing a very low-risk strategy, even in the air war. You also
have to decide if you want to get rid of Europe's last Communist
thug, Milosevic. And then you have to stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, D'Orleans' crack French forces in Macedonia
and other allied troops seem highly unlikely to move. ``There is
simply no support in NATO for a massive land invasion,'' said a
spokesman for the Pentagon, Lt. Col. Steve Campbell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
