<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4188 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DESTABILIZE-BO     04-02 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DESTABILIZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES SEEN AS A POWERFUL DESTABILIZING FORCE IN REGION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia -- Refugees fleeing marauding Serb troops
could destabilize or even topple the governments of Macedonia,
Albania and Montenegro, a spillover of the Yugoslav air war that
would amount to Slobodan Milosevic's revenge against those he
considers collaborators campaigning to destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   Already, ethnic Albanian refugees have put enormous strains on
Albania, Europe's poorest country; Macedonia, a poor country of
just 2 million; and even tiny Montenegro, the semi-autonomous
Yugoslav province thus far spared the bloody turmoil that has swept
the Balkans through most of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Milosevic blames Albania for fomenting
separatist sentiment in Kosovo, and for channeling money and guns
to the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army. The Belgrade regime also
resents Macedonia for quitting the Yugoslav Federation in 1991, and
it despises Montenegro's pro-western government.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro may be headed for a showdown with Milosevic that
could plunge it into civil war. Macedonians, meanwhile, fear the
90,000 ethnic Albanians who have arrived here since the NATO
bombing began will never leave, changing the ethnic mix so greatly
that the nascent democratic government will collapse.
</P>
<P>
   As for Albania, as one western diplomat put it, ``I never
thought Albania could get worse, but it has this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats, especially those from NATO countries, have
spent days reassuring the Macedonian government that they will
provide money to deal with the flood of refugees. Christopher Hill,
the US ambassador to Macedonia, has encouraged the government to
become more like western European nations, and worries the refugee
crisis will stunt democratization here.
</P>
<P>
   In Montenegro, the American smart bombs and cruise missiles
slamming into military installations and strategic facilities
across Yugoslavia are giving Milosevic the excuse he has long
sought to undermine the republic's own fragile new democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of a military coup intensified, fueled by a clampdown on
news broadcasts by Montenegro television and the replacement of the
commander of Yugoslav forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro's president, Milo Djukanovic, conceded his government
may be facing its most desperate hour as ethnic Albanian refugees
pour over from neighboring Kosovo and NATO air attacks fan the
flames of Serbian nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a serious and authentic danger that even our state
may disappear and burn down in violence,'' Djukanovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though NATO's warplanes have struck some targets in
Montenegro, the Djukanovic government has shown its disdain for the
authoritarian federal regime in Belgrade by refusing to acknowledge
the state of war proclaimed by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we do not like that a war is being waged against
Yugoslavia, of which we are still a part,'' said a senior
government official. ``But also we have some understanding of why
the West is acting against the illegal and vicious Milosevic
regime, and we are sympathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sympathies are no secret, and Belgrade's appointment this
week of a hard-line army general, Milorad Obradovic, to take
command of the 10,000 Yugoslav troops in Montenegro was seen by
many officials and analysts as a dangerous sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is sleeping at night. There is tremendous fear that
Montenegro will fall into the Balkans abyss,'' said Drasko
Junarovic, editor of the independent news magazine Monitor. ``The
next few days will be absolutely critical for our future as a free
place.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana warned Milosevic that NATO
would stop any attempt by Belgrade to overthrow the Montenegrin
government.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 600,000 inhabitants of Montenegro share the Orthodox
Christian faith and feel a strong ethnic bond with the Serbs who
dominate the rest of Yugoslavia. Similarly, Macedonians who make up
65 percent of this country's population are also Orthodox Slavs.
</P>
<P>
   Support for Montenegro's first democratic government, elected
only last year, has plunged precipitously since the Western air
offensive began, and pro-Serbian sentiment is plainly on the rise.
The Macedonian government fears its fragile coalition could
collapse if the refugee crisis worsens, as it likely will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every bomb that drops makes Montenegrins feel more loyal to
the Greater Yugoslavia,'' said Zoran Zizic, leader of the
ultra-nationalist Socialist People's Party, which supports
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, Montenegro government television had been
broadcasting news reports from CNN and other Western news media. It
was the only network in Yugoslavia providing viewers a glimpse of
the forced expulsions of Albanians from Kosovo by Serb paramilitary
forces, as well as a Western perspective on the NATO attack. But
under pressure from Belgrade, Montenegro stopped the Western news
reports, replacing them with government-controlled broadcasts from
Yugoslavia. There has not been similar censorship in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Many Montenegrins are furious at the air attacks and make no
attempt to hide their hatred for the Western reporters working from
Podgorica. Cars carrying armed young men coursed through the
capital with horns blaring in celebration of the capture of three
US soldiers by Serb forces Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans make war against our country, and we have captured
some enemy soldiers,'' said Zizic. ``That is natural in war. Why do
you Americans think only Yugoslavs can suffer in this conflict?''
</P>
<P>
   For Albania, Europe's poorest and least-developed nation, the
refugee crisis is a fiscal nightmare as well as a human tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   When the refugee flood began, there were only 4,500 beds left of
the 6,000 spaces created in refugee centers last year, when ethnic
Albanians first started fleeing Kosovo. Further, many of the nearly
24,000 refugees who arrived last year found apartments, but are
running out of money to stay in them.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Albania is not strong enough to handle a massive
refugee crisis, a senior Western diplomat said. The current
government, headed by 31-year-old Pandeli Majko, is seen by some
analysts as a caretaker regime, holding the country delicately in
place while rival politicians solidify their support.
</P>
<P>
   The disruption of a massive refugee influx could lead to unwise,
early elections, which would be ``out of the question,'' the
diplomat said. ``If you could call a country suicidal, that would
be it,'' the Western official said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Susan Milligan contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
