<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4189 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-02 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TIME TO GET SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ U.S. policy toward the terrorism of Slobodan
Milosevic has been constrained in the past by our public's wariness
of military involvement abroad. We remember Vietnam and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   But that political-psychological calculus may have changed, I
believe, under the impact of the Serbian atrocities in Kosovo. Most
Americans do not want to temporize with Milosevic. We want to
finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in his CBS interview with Dan Rather the
other night, said he ``would urge the American people ... to have a
little more resolve here.'' But the people are looking to the
president for resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Those terrified women and children stumbling out of Kosovo are
on our conscience now. When Rather observed in the interview that
Milosevic was winning in Kosovo, Clinton replied, ``We knew that
that would happen in the first few days.'' If he knew, why weren't
he and NATO prepared to act much more decisively?
</P>
<P>
   Decisiveness and commitment are crucial now. If we let Milosevic
complete his ethnic cleansing and genocide in Kosovo, it will be
the greatest human catastrophe in Europe since World War II. And it
will be the end of belief in NATO, a belief that has kept the peace
in Europe for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the steps that the United States and its allies
must take:
</P>
<P>
   1. Commit ourselves to the total destruction of Milosevic's
armed forces, no matter how long it takes. NATO bombers in the
first week carried out daily only a fraction of the sorties
undertaken in the Persian Gulf War. The intensity should be at
least as high as in the gulf, and this time the equivalent of
Saddam Hussein's Republican Guard must not escape. The bombing in
Belgrade must mean the targeting of command and control centers. We
should also quickly hit Yugoslav broadcasting facilities, a key
factor in Milosevic's power.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare to send NATO ground troops into Kosovo as a
protection force for the ethnic Albanians who have not yet been
murdered or expelled. Ten thousand troops can be there within days.
Others must follow as needed, perhaps 20,000 to 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   3. Begin supplying weapons to the Kosovo Liberation Army. This
cannot be a short-run answer to the Milosevic policemen and
paramilitaries who are terrorizing civilians; even getting guns to
the KLA will be difficult. But we have to start enabling the
victims to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   4. Announce that the United States and its allies are abandoning
the plan for Kosovo ``autonomy'' that was on the table in the
failed negotiations in Rambouillet, France. Milosevic's cruelties
have ended any possibility of Kosovars being ruled by Serbia. For
the next several years Kosovo should be policed and controlled
internationally.
</P>
<P>
   5. Commit the alliance to the return of all refugees to Kosovo.
The international community will have to feed and house them until
their homes and villages are rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   6. Call on the International War Crimes Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia to indict Milosevic and all others involved in his
crimes against humanity in Kosovo. The tribunal's prosecutors have
been remiss in not building a case against him long before now, for
the crimes he directed in Bosnia; and the U.S. government has
failed to give the tribunal the large amount of evidence it has
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Those commitments must be believed _ by Milosevic and by the
people of the United States and the other NATO countries. That
means that there can be no bombing pauses to let Milosevic reflect,
no return to fruitless diplomacy. Our terms must be clear and
unchanging.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has bet again and again that the United States does
not have the backbone to stand up against his viciousness and
guile. So far he has won. If he wins again, the price to this
country and the Western alliance will be devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is the man who has to prove that Milosevic is
wrong. If he speaks firmly and consistently, if he acts decisively,
he will have the support of the American people _ and of Congress.
Senate Republicans who matter, from John McCain to Richard Lugar,
are urging him to be tough.
</P>
<P>
   If Americans had the illusion that peace and human decency can
be defended in this world without pain and casualties, the illusion
is fading. What we need now is leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
