<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA'S FOOD NEAR END, AID WORKERS SAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The food scarcity engulfing North Korea will worsen in
the next two months because government rations, on which a majority
of the population depends, are running out and will not be
restocked until the summer harvest, a senior aid official said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now entering the most difficult months of the year,''
said David Morton, the U.N. aid coordinator for North Korea, at a
briefing in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two months, Morton said, much of the population
will have to depend on so-called substitute foods _ cakes or
noodles made from corn stalks, cabbage stalks or grass ground with
grain _ or on wild roots and grasses they scrounge themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The most acute scarcity will ease in June and July when potato
and vegetable crops are harvested, officials say, although the
country will remain chronically short of food.
</P>
<P>
   People in cities and towns tend to be the worst off in famines,
aid workers have found, especially if they rely for income on
industries that are now nearly idle for lack of fuel or raw
materials. Fewer than one-third of North Korea's people work on
farms, where there is often access to more food.
</P>
<P>
   Food aid from abroad, supplied mostly by the United States and
channeled through the U.N. World Food Program, is mainly directed
to young children in nursery schools and kindergartens, with some
going to hospitals. In a new push, aid agencies are trying to feed
more pregnant and nursing mothers and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But the aid can help only a fraction of the population and
offers no long-term answer, Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping alive a generation of children,'' he said. ``But
this is only a holding action.''
</P>
<P>
   As other foreign visitors to North Korea have, Morton described
a country where malnutrition has stunted most children and weakened
many adults, where hospitals and schools have no heat and little
food and where water supplies are unsanitary because there is no
chlorine for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Famine, defined as an extreme scarcity of food, remains a
reality for much of the population,'' a U.N. strategy paper
concluded last month. An unknown number of people, by some evidence
in the millions, have died as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Morton took issue with charges that have been made by some
refugees that much of the aid is being diverted to the army and
political elites. Those groups vastly prefer rice to the corn and
wheat in the aid program, he said, and national supplies meet their
needs.
</P>
<P>
   While U.N. monitors must travel with escorts and usually must
declare their destinations in advance, they visit all regions where
aid is given to see if schools and hospitals have received their
allotments. ``We believe, from what we see, that they are getting
the food,'' Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the country's agricultural production has been hurt by
floods and droughts, the famine's roots lie in the collapse of the
Soviet Union in 1991, most experts now believe, when North Korea
lost its major supplier of fuel, fertilizer, industrial inputs and
farm equipment. It has been unable to replace those supplies
through foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Per capita income fell to less than $500 by 1996 from more than
$1,000 in 1992, according to international estimates. Fertilizer
plants went idle, tractors had little fuel, irrigation pumps lacked
electricity and food production plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, fuel was so scarce that 90 percent of the country's
rice fields were not plowed after the harvest, the usual practice
to suppress weeds and pests. That factor alone will reduce the next
harvest by 12 percent, a North Korean official has said.
</P>
<P>
   Simply rebuilding agriculture will not solve the problem, Morton
said, because North Korea has limited arable land.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industrial country,'' he said. ``What it needs is
an economic revival.''
</P>
<P>
   But for both political and economic reasons, other countries are
reluctant to provide large-scale economic aid. So long as North
Korea refuses to make major reforms in its closed, Communist
economy, many experts say, such aid may only prop up the system
that helped cause the current famine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
