<HEADLINE>
UNEMPLOYMENT RATE AT 1970 LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation generated 46,000 jobs in March, far below the
scorching pace in recent months, an indication that the US economy
may be cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Department of Labor said Friday that enough new jobs
were added to push the March unemployment rate down to 4.2 percent,
its lowest level since 1970. The unemployment rate was 4.4 percent
in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone expects the economy and job growth to
continue to roar along as it has in the past,'' said Denis
McSweeney, New England's commissioner for the federal Bureau of
Labor Statistics, which releases the monthly unemployment report.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said several factors hampered job growth, ranging
from cold weather in March to Americans' preference for buying
low-cost imports rather than home-made goods, a trend that has
produced a record US trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The goods-producing sector, including construction,
manufacturing and oil companies, lost 89,000 jobs in March. Job
growth in the service and retail sectors, which have driven much of
the country's blockbuster growth, slowed markedly, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the 46,000 new jobs created in March, according to the
bureau's survey of business payrolls, were only a quarter as much
as a consensus of economists had predicted _ between 165,000 and
200,000.
</P>
<P>
   March job growth was the weakest it has been since January 1996
when severe snowstorms froze economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   In February, payrolls grew 297,000; that figure was revised
upward from a previously reported 275,000, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer new jobs may be fallout from an eight-year expansion that
has caused an acute shortage of workers, economists said. If
companies cannot find people to hire, they cannot create as many
positions as they would in a slack labor market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is now the longest peace-time recovery in history, and
what's happened is, at this point, pretty much anybody who wants a
job has already got one,'' said Nicholas Perna, chief economist for
Fleet Financial Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Eight million people in the nation now hold more than one job,
the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   The labor force _ the number employed plus the number of people
who are actively looking for work _ shrank by 455,000 in March.
</P>
<P>
   There were other signs of slowing. The average work week edged
down by 0.1 hour to 34.5 hours, while average hourly wages rose 3
cents, to $13.09, the bureau reported.
</P>
<P>
   March marked the second consecutive monthly decline in the size
of the labor force, according to a separate survey by the bureau of
US households, which the agency used to estimate the month jobless
rate. It has not seen a two-months' decline in years, though
economists said that it was too early declare a new trend has
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever dark clouds lurk in the data, William Cheney, chief
economist for John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., the economy
is still ``going extraordinarily well.''
</P>
<P>
   This state's economy continues to be strong, according to a new
index published by the University of Massachusetts. The index of
current economic activity increased by 5.8 percent in January, to
122.8. Last October, the index was 121.4.
</P>
<P>
   The index is based on Massachusetts employment and tax receipts
data.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recessions in Japan, Southeast Asia, Russia and looming
troubles in Latin America, Hancock's Cheney said the fact that the
US economy keeps growing ``does seem kind of bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   But he noted this growth has lured overseas investors to put
their money into the US investment markets. Indeed, a soaring Dow
Jones Industrial average closed above the 10,000 mark this week,
and market analysts attributed it partly to a steep rise in money
flowing in from overseas. Markets were closed Friday for Good
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When financial crises first broke in Asia in 1997 and continued
into 1998, Hancock's Cheney said, ``I was assuming it would be a
net drag on the United States but I hadn't foreseen this flight to
safety'' in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
