<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV04-B     04-02 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV04-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLD TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 4, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martin Feldstein is a public policy figure of the first
magnitude. He has been adviser to Republican presidents, but he
also presides over the National Bureau of Economic Research, a
non-partisan meeting place where economists seek to narrow
differences of opinion among business, labor, and government. He's
a college professor, who has taught introductory economics to
thousands of Harvard students. He is a mild, decent, and likeable
man, accustomed to building consensus.
</P>
<P>
   So when you find him making technically correct but otherwise
highly misleading statements in the newspapers, you know something
very interesting must be going on.
</P>
<P>
   Under the headline, ``Common Ground on Social Security,''
Feldstein wrote last week in The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``Repeated attempts to characterize the difference between the
Republican approach and the President's plan as a major ideological
clash are fundamentally wrong, based on either a misunderstanding
of what the Republicans propose or a desire to prevent compromise
in order to use Social Security as an election issue in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Decode that sentence and you have the key to undertanding where
the Social Security debate is headed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, between those who want to preserve the current system
pretty much as it is and those who want to change it all together,
the ideological chasm could scarely be deeper.
</P>
<P>
   The difference of opinion has to do with where Americans in the
21st century will choose to set the boundary between the market and
non-market spheres _ between the community and the individual.
</P>
<P>
   In one camp are traditionalists, who want to preserve pretty
much intact the ``three-legged stool'' of a retirement system that
evolved out of the New Deal reforms of the 1930s _ private savings,
company plans, and a realistic but hardly generous universal
government safety net.
</P>
<P>
   In the other are the reformers, personalizers, and privatizers
of one sort or another, economists for the most part, or
representatives of financial firms. They want to replace or at
least augment the collective system with a system of individual
accounts, designed to foster personal savings.
</P>
<P>
   The difference of opinion is captured nicely in the slogans of
the rival camps: Social Security vs. Personal Security.
</P>
<P>
   One thing upon which virtually all analysts agree is that the
Social Security system requires some kind of work. If taxes are not
raised slightly, or benefits cut, the system will cease to be able
to pay 100 cents on each dollar of claims, starting about 2034.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing at all were changed between now and then, the Social
Security system would pay only about 75 percent of promised
benefits, then and for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans see this both as a serious crisis and an opportunity
to change the system with a view to making it more of an engine of
economic growth. Democrats in general are seeking a technical fix,
though their plan .
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed a simple plan (with a complicated
rationale) in which about 60 percent of projected budget surpluses
in the next 15 years would be put aside to extend Social Security's
solvency until at least 2055.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve the actuarial balance over the full 75-year horizon
that has been the historical rule, some small further combination
of tax increases and benefit cuts also would be required _ but not
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan, which was designed for the most part by
Feldstein, would use the surpluses to create personal accounts
owned by individual workers. These would permit workers to pursue
higher returns in the stock market, though many details are up in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   When Feldstein says the differences between his plan and
Clinton's ``are not as great as they may seem,'' he is focusing on
two subsidiary matters they have in common to confuse the issue. It
is true that Clinton recommended investing some portion of the
Social Security trust fund on Wall Street, in hopes of capturing
some of the higher returns that have traditionally accrued to
stocks and stimulating national saving.
</P>
<P>
   It is true, also, that Clinton called for the government to set
up a system of individual retirement accounts for all citizens in
order to foster individual savings. But Clinton proposed to keep
such IRAs quite separate from the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton's proposal to have a semi-autonomous government
corporation accumulate large stakes in US companies through the
purchase of index funds is quite different from the individual
investments in stocks that the GOP plan envisages. Clinton's plan
for universal IRAs is also entirely secondary to maintaining the
integrity of the ``three-legged stool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What possible reason, other that partisan fears about
`tinkering with the system' is there for keeping the accounts
separate?'' Feldstein demanded to know.
</P>
<P>
   There, in a nutshell, is the deep difference of opinion exposed.
Traditionalists view all attempts to ``personalize'' Social
Security as ultimately destabilizing to the system itself. Once the
well-to-do are free to chase the higher returns for themselves,
traditionalists expect that support for the system of universal
benefits will erode. A profound force for equality and inclusion
will have been lost.
</P>
<P>
   The real difference of opinion, therefore, is not between the
GOP and ``the President's plan'' _ an inventive political document
from a lame duck who may be disproportionately concerned with his
``legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is between those who want to act now, and those who want to
turn the next election into a referendum on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
