<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AID-0403-COX     04-02 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AID-0403-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILITARY STEPS UP HUMANITARIAN EFFORTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    with COX-KOSOVO-MAIN
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- NATO and the U.S. military are stepping up their
aid for the thousands of refugees fleeing Kosovo, Lt. Gen. John
McDuffie of the Joint Chiefs of Staff announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military this weekend will begin flying 500,000 meals
to Tirana, Albania, and distribute them from there. Each meal pack,
from an army depot in Dover, Pa., contains one day's complete
requirements for one person.
</P>
<P>
   The meals are being airlifted because food stored in Pristina,
Kosovo, was destroyed, while other supplies are in warehouses in
Belgrade and Montenegro. Relief organizations are trying to shift
these supplies to where they are most needed.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military will also move tents, blankets, cots, and
sleeping bags already in Europe into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO already is sending C-130s loaded with food and other
supplies for the refugees, said Jamie Shea, a NATO spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie also said the 12,000-man NATO peace-keeping force in
Macedonia will help with the inflow of refugees at border crossings
and with humanitarian efforts. He said the number of refugees
entering Macedonia is expected to grow by 50 percent over the next
three days.
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of military forces in relief efforts came in
response to requests by several humanitarian organizations to
support the transportation and organization of relief materials.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, representatives from 15 aid organizations met with
President Clinton to discuss U.S. support of humanitarian efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bell, president of the relief organization CARE, said
ideas included:
</P>
<P>
   Additional support to countries accepting heavy flows of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging other nations to open their borders to refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Providing cargo planes to deliver supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Security for aid workers and refugees near the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one foresaw how rapidly the refugees would pour out of
Kosovo,'' Bell said. ``There is a substantial need for more staff
and more supplies on the ground more rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell said CARE has received $500,000 from Australia, $200,000
from the German government, and $200,000 from the William H. Gates
Foundation to support relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
