<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-AR     04-02 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MACEDONIA, THE STREAM OF REFUGEES FILLS A VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING to correct slug and add graphic note; no other
changes)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(ac) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ The valley hummed with thousands of voices,
the hillside and fields below shifted constantly with crowds of
people. Along the train tracks a steady line of stumbling figures
moved forward to join the human mass.
</P>
<P>
   Well over 10,000 refugees from Kosovo are camped here in the
open, just over the border, in Macedonia. They are still arriving
by the thousands, turning the fields into a sprawling refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   They have come from Kosovo's capital, Pristina, and other towns,
herded at gunpoint by the Serbian police into trains, trucks and
buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police ordered us out of the house,'' said Zenel Krasniqi,
an ethnic Albanian builder from Pristina. ``They put us in a line,
along with all the neighbors, and marched us to the railroad
station,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a night in the station with thousands of other displaced
people, under guard of armed police, they were loaded on a train
and sent to the border. On the Serbian side of the border, they
were ordered out and told to walk along the tracks into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone told the same story. Some arrived by trucks and buses,
most of them from Pristina, others from Urosevac, or Ferizaj as the
Albanians know it, a town of some 70,000 people south of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The flood into Macedonia, an estimated 90,000 refugees since
March 24, has completely overwhelmed the Macedonian authorities.
Soldiers were brought in to stem the flow along the railroad
tracks, and riot police armed with automatic weapons and wearing
flak jackets and helmets formed a barrier to block refugees from
the main road.
</P>
<P>
   NATO announced Friday that its soldiers would do whatever
possible to help with the influx of refugees into Macedonia and
look into what NATO could do to assist the U.N. High Commission for
Refugees in dealing with the crowds pouring in from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers admitted they had been taken by surprise by the
sudden rush of people in the last few days. ``We did not think such
a wave would arrive,'' said a Swiss representative of the Red
Cross, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   She estimated there were more than 10,000 refugees gathered, and
many more on the other side waiting to cross. NATO estimated the
number of people waiting to leave Kosovo on Friday at 25,000. And
one person who had driven to Macedonia estimated the line of
refugees waiting to get in by car was about five miles long. ``The
situation is getting dramatic, the Red Cross worker said. ``In one
or two days there will be people dying, the youngest and the
oldest.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one field hospital was working. Men struggled through the
crowd carrying an unconscious man into the tent, past a line of
women and babies. Old people sat on blankets outside.
</P>
<P>
   The police were enforcing strict controls to register the
refugees, but with only one table and one book, the line was barely
moving at the major border crossing. Refugees registering said they
had been lined up for seven hours, since before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Families arriving collapsed where they stood, lying down in the
field among their few belongings, huddling under blankets and
plastic sheets as rain began to lash down. Some made wood fires,
others were trying to build shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi was splicing a tree branch with a penknife, making
supports for a tent for his pair of tiny grandchildren asleep on
the ground. With his children, cousins, and elderly mother-in-law,
there were 15 people camped together on two square yards of earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never have gone if they had not forced us,'' he said.
He and his wife, Fatima Krasniqi, said they did not blame NATO for
their plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were happy that NATO bombs were falling; they were only
falling on military targets,'' she said. ``We were not afraid. We
even opened the windows to watch. If we did not have NATO, they
would have massacred all of us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Syled Baftia, a man of 84, half blind and nearly deaf, sat tall
and defiant on the ground among his family. ``They are putting
children out in the rain,'' he said of the Serbs. His family fled
to Pristina after Serbian troops burned their village last year, he
said. Now they had been forced from Pristina at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing good will come of the Serbs after this. They forced us
out of our property,'' he said. ``Those are our lands, my family
has lived there for 500 years. But Belgrade will never own
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   For now though, his family had nowhere to go. ``We are sleeping
here on the ground, nine people to two blankets,'' his son, Tahir
Baftia, said. ``We cannot survive this, with all these people.
Europe has only four or five days to decide something.''
</P>
<P>
   Just behind the Baftia family, stumbling, eyes dazed with shock,
came the new arrivals along the train tracks. ``Ferizaj,'' they
said, mumbling the name of their home town as they walked, their
heads bent, exhaustion in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   A family bumped an old woman along in a wheelbarrow, another
dragged a young handicapped boy in a wheelchair. A young man
staggered as he heaved his grandfather onto his back to carry him.
</P>
<P>
   They described an exodus of extraordinary proportions from their
home towns. Naser Dubova and his family had spent the last 10 days
moving from house to house as the police cleared whole districts.
Finally the police and paramilitaries caught up with them and told
them to leave. ```Go anywhere, but leave,' they said'' Dubova
recounted. The family then tried for three days to find transport
out of the town.
</P>
<P>
   They slept at the train station in Urosevac, and then as more
and more people poured into the station amid rising panic, they
fought their way onto a convoy of buses that the Serbian
authorities organized to take them to the border. From there the
police ordered them to walk along the railroad tracks into
Macedonia, warning them that both sides of the tracks were mined.
</P>
<P>
   Farther up the track, a last group of exhausted refugees had sat
down to rest. ``Are there police further along? Are they separating
the men from the women?'' they asked. They were already in
Macedonia, but were clearly terrified their ordeal would continue.
</P>
<P>
   Few refugees recounted stories of killings, although several
said they had seen two or three bodies lying beside the train
tracks on the journey. Most families seemed to have escaped
together, men, women and children, unharmed if traumatized.
</P>
<P>
   At mid-afternoon a train carrying six cars disgorged thousands
more refugees from Pristina into the field. They said there were
many more people still in Pristina waiting at the station for
transport out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
