<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-VALLEY-BOS &LR;      04-02 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VALLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLIGHT OF REFUGEES CONCENTRATED AT BORDER CROSSINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ When Hilman Gashi's aunt collapsed, partially
paralyzed, after an apparent stroke Friday, he put her in a
wheelbarrow and set off down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where to go, I don't know what to do,'' Gashi
said, as his dazed 63-year-old aunt, Fatima Bejrisa, sat squished
into the wheelbarrow, weakly holding the hand of her husband, who
trudged along on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Gashi's frustration and desperation captured the scene here at
the Kosovo border, where up to 30,000 people sat or stood aimlessly
in a huge field in an open valley, waiting to enter Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers and police held them back, occasionally clashing with
refugees who were not allowed to leave the valley even when a
relative or friend from Macedonia showed up to vouch for them.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian groups acknowledge that the plight of refugees has
become a crisis, with too many people and too little help for them.
If the crunch earlier in the week was in Albania, it has now
shifted to a country that is less willing to take in the surge of
ethnic Albanians fleeing Serb forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is chaos,'' said Karen Robbins, a field coordinator for
Care International. ``One person is collapsing in that field every
two minutes, but there are not enough local doctors. There's panic.
Every time food is brought into the field, there's a rush and a
riot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard by the Lepenec River, the exhausted, traumatized refugees
wait, sometimes for days, to get through. They sleep in the cold
open air, surviving on loaves of bread and water, though many say
they have gone days without food. The conditions are unsanitary and
people have no dignity, forced to urinate and defecate where they
can. The stench is growing by the hour, and aid workers are worried
about disease.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sea of people here, a sea of misery.
</P>
<P>
   A man sat with his wife and seven children, all of them weeping.
The man said his father had died as they waited at the border the
last two days. They had no way to bury him, so they left the body
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``What could I do?'' the man wailed. ``What could I do?''
</P>
<P>
   One father pointed helplessly to the bloody feet of his
3-year-old daughter. He said Serb police had ordered his family to
leave immediately or be killed, and in the confusion they had left
without her shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Another old woman was brought in by wheelbarrow, unconscious,
swathed in blankets, her face the shade of alabaster.
</P>
<P>
   Nain Berisa said he and his wife, their three children and his
68-yearold mother-in-law left Pristina, the Kosovo capital, on
Tuesday, as Serb forces went house to house in an apparent effort
to expel all ethnic Albanians. It took them four days to make the
60-mile trek. The last few miles took two days to travel, so
clogged were the roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent one day in the field, one day in General Jancovic,''
he said, referring the last town in Kosovo before the border. ``We
have had nothing to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   After finally getting out of the field, Berisa and his family
were humiliated by an angry Macedonian police officer who blocked
their way and screamed at them to turn back and board a bus to a
refugee center in Skopje, the Macedonian capital.
</P>
<P>
   The police officer's rudeness was telling. Macedonians are
frightened that the flood of refugees will destabilize their
country, which can barely look after its own 2 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees, said 90,000 refugees had entered the
country since the NATO bombing began, some 60,000 in the last two
days, and most came through the hellish holding center at Blace.
</P>
<P>
   The only bright spot, Ghedini said, was that it did not appear
that men had been separated from women and girls. Such separations
were common last week when Serb forces cleared out the western
Kosovo city of Pec, and sometimes have led to summary executions of
men accused by the Serbs of being members or potential members of
the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Ghedini said tens of thousands of people are still waiting to
get into Macedonia, a backup that was being exacerbated by the
Yugoslav government, which is using a train to haul refugees from
Pristina to the field at Blace. Some put the number waiting to get
into Macedonia at 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is we have no advance warning when another train
is going to bring in another load of people,'' said Ghedini.
</P>
<P>
   She said her agency had distributed 47,000 blankets, 40 metric
tons of food, and 26,000 loaves of bread to refugees sleeping in
the open over the last two days. But the distribution of aid is
uneven and often chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   Many refugees said they had not been able to get anything to eat
or drink for days. Among those who said they went hungry were
Afroditi Rexha and her 13-year-old sister Albina.
</P>
<P>
   It took the two sisters from Pristina five days to get over the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We left my mother and father and brother behind in Pristina,''
said Afroditi, 25, a fourth-year medical student. ``Maybe they are
here. I can't find them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rexha sisters fled with only the clothes on their backs.
Unlike many others, they know no one in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we will do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on humanitarian groups is enormous. Jo Hegenauer,
the mild-mannered head of the UN refugees agency in Kosovo, kicked
the iron gate of his office's compound in frustrated rage Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Hutton of Care International said aid workers are holding
round-the-clock meetings, trying to get more help to the refugees,
especially those cooped up in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to try megaphones, to try to get some
information to the people. That seems to be causing the panic.
People don't know why they're being held up in the field, what's
going to happen to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
