<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CHAUDHURI-INDIA-ART     04-02 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CHAUDHURI-INDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOVELIST IS RETURNING TO INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to delete release note and add photo note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MERVYN ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amit Chaudhuri is homesick, and so he is returning to India.
</P>
<P>
   Chaudhuri, 36, author of the recently published and highly
praised ``Freedom Song,'' a collection of three short novels,
arrived in England in 1983 as a student. He will be going back to
Calcutta, his birthplace and the ``city of dust'' of his fictions,
as an award-winning novelist, one The London Review of Books has
said writes ``better than just about anyone of his generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just miss things,'' Chaudhuri said on the telephone from his
home in Cambridge, England, where he is Leverhulme Fellow in
English at Cambridge University and unofficial writer in residence
at St. John's College at the university. ``It's something quite
physical. I miss the street life, the street noises, the light. The
fact that windows remain open and you can hear sounds coming from
inside. It's a part of my subconscious. Calcutta is depleted in
many ways _ there's a large outflow of the middle class to America
_ and it can exasperate and disillusion me. But the spell is still
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaudhuri's collection _ his first book published in the United
States _ is part of a resurgence of Indian writing in recent years.
Arundhati Roy's ``God of Small Things'' spent more than 30 weeks on
the hard-cover fiction best-seller list of The New York Times in
1997 and 1998. ``Hullaballoo in the Guava Orchard,'' a first novel
by Kiran Desai, won critical praise last year. New novels by Salman
Rushdie (``The Ground Beneath Her Feet'') and Hanif Kureishi
(``Intimacy'') are being published this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Michiko Kakutani, writing in The Times, called Chaudhuri's work
``wonderfully observed'' and said he was a ``gifted young writer
who has created an indelible portrait of India'' while ``leaving us
with a Proustian tapestry of quotidian moments recaptured and
remade as they loom large and astonishing in his characters'
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   In the three short novels, nothing much happens. In the first,
``A Strange and Sublime Address,'' which won first prize in the
1991 Betty Trask Awards in England as well as the Commonwealth
Writers Prize, a young boy from Bombay visits his aunt and uncle in
Calcutta; in the second, ``Afternoon Raag,'' which won two other
prizes, an Oxford University student copes with two unhappy
romantic relationships and recalls his days in India. In the third,
``Freedom Song,'' published by Alfred A. Knopf, two families deal
with life in Calcutta amid the city's Hindu-Muslim strife.
</P>
<P>
   The writing, Ms. Kakutani said, may seem casual, even artless,
but there is a hidden subtlety. His ``long, beautifully crafted
sentences,'' The London Review of Books said, ``give the impression
of being worked on for hours for no other purpose than to do
justice to the messy spontaneity of real life.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chaudhuri, it is that messy spontaneity, the irrelevances
and digressions that make up human existence, that primarily
interests him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the incidentals, the unexpectedness in everyday life,
the things the mind notes down not quite consciously,'' he said.
``In the life we lead, where we suffer and procreate and are happy
and have fun and are disappointed, the world outside is interwoven,
with us almost not having noticed it. You can be in a taxi and
you're on the way to the hospital because someone is dying, and
there's the smell of the taxi's interior and an old car horn or the
fact that you're passing a bank where you withdraw cash. The poetry
of the everyday is important, because it is so idiosyncratic. It
goes unconsciously into the making of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to his long, flowing sentences, he said, they are
the product of both reworking and time. ``It's not scratching them
out and writing them again,'' he said. ``It's the time I need to
distance myself. I can't pound out 500 or 700 words a day. I don't
know how writers do that. It's enviable. But often the changes are
deletions rather than adornments. The deletions allow the
sentences, the paragraphs, the story, to breathe life, to emerge
into their true shape. I delete the words that are hiding them,
covering them.''
</P>
<P>
   What he aims for, he said, is a portrait of people. ``India is
vast, and different parts have different problems,'' he said. ``In
Bombay it is excessive capitalism, Hindu fundamentalism and
right-wing politics. In Calcutta it's the opposite. Instead of
trying to attract investment in a global age it sometimes seems to
discourage it. Its problem is stagnation.''
</P>
<P>
   What attracts him, he said, is life amid change. ``Whether they
like it or not, whether they know it or not, the people are part of
a time in history,'' he said. ``They are making small movements in
their lives while being caught up in a larger current.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaudhuri was born in Calcutta in 1962 and raised in Bombay,
where his father, now retired, was a business executive. He made
frequent visits to relatives in Calcutta _ as does Sandeep, the
10-year-old at the heart of ``A Strange and Sublime Address.''
</P>
<P>
   From an early age, he said, he wanted to be a writer. ``I
wouldn't call it a profound desire,'' he said. ``I didn't have
anything I wanted to write about. V.S. Naipaul talks about wanting
to be a writer long before he had anything to write about. It's the
romance of writing. It got to me quite early.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaudhuri graduated from University College in London and
received his doctorate at Balliol College at Oxford University, the
setting of ``Afternoon Raag.'' He has also been Creative Arts
Fellow at Wolfson College at Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   His parents and other family members now live in Calcutta, he
said, providing another reason for his need to return. ``I'm quite
close to my parents,'' he said. ``I'm their only child. I also sing
_ I'm a north Indian classical singer _ and to keep in touch with
that I need to go back often. And my wife and I have an 8-month-old
daughter, and we want her to grow up in India.''
</P>
<P>
   His fellowship ends on Monday, and he decided not to apply for
another. He has in the last 15 years spent several months a year
back home, but England was always his base. Now his home will be in
India, with perhaps two or three months a year in England. ``It's
an experiment,'' he said. ``I'm going to write full time, which
will also give me time for my music.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, there is something else behind his decision. ``I
have met with nothing but kindness and generosity here and I feel
great warmth for the people,'' he said. ``But I'm a foreigner.
They're trying to make it a multiracial society, and on some levels
it works. But every time I have to enter immigration at Heathrow
Airport and show my visa and get asked questions, it's not a
particularly pleasant experience. It makes me realize that at some
level this is not where I belong.''
</P>
<P>
   His writing has been compared to Proust, but Chaudhuri says the
influences lie elsewhere, and are perhaps more related to his sense
of not really belonging in his adopted society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Proust could have filtered through from other writers,''
he said. ``I think more of Elizabeth Bowen and Katherine Mansfield.
I don't know if they were transformed by reading Proust, but they
too seem to deal with language and memory. It is more that they are
at a slight angle. Bowen is Irish and Mansfield is from New
Zealand.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused. ``Maybe that's what appeals to me,'' he said. ``Since
I myself am at a slight angle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
