<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-530&AMP;ADD-N     04-02 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BRIEFING OFFICERS, FACTS ARE SCARCE, POLEMICS ABUNDANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-WEATHER,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-MCCAIN.) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ For more than a week now, NATO civilian and
military spokesmen here have been giving daily briefings to
journalists from around the world. But these briefings are very
different from those that journalists got in Vietnam, the Persian
Gulf or Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO briefing officers tell almost nothing about what allied
warplanes are doing in Kosovo. Cloud cover and lack of an allied
presence on the ground has prevented them from obtaining precise
information, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what the spokesmen have been putting out is reams of
reports, often in polemical terms, about what the Yugoslav forces
have been doing to Albanian civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with some of the tens of thousands of refugees
streaming from the province have largely corroborated the
alliance's claim that they are fleeing Serbian thugs and brutal
police and army attacks, not NATO bombing. But spokesmen for the
command have also been churning out anti-Yugoslav polemics and
sometimes even rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Credibility in military news briefings is everything, and the
lack of it in the early days of the Vietnam war was one reason why
the American public soured against involvement.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of providing details on allied bombing missions,
spokesmen for the alliance here have been issuing heated daily
denunciations of the Yugoslav anti-Albanian campaign in Kosovo, a
campaign that the allied military command itself acknowledges the
bombing has so far been unable to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing the best we can,'' said the alliance's spokesman,
Jamie Shea of Britain, a gregarious European security specialist
with a Oxford doctorate in modern history who is normally a fount
of expert information on everything the alliance is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Operationally, it's sometimes difficult to get all of the
accurate information we need,'' he explained. ``We're aware of
this, and will do our best to increase the amount of information we
are able to give out.''
</P>
<P>
   But privately, civilians here at headquarters say their pleas to
the military for a more open policy have gone unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   And military officers here and in the field say that the
decision to provide as few operational details as possible is on
direct orders from the top allied commander, Gen. Wesley Clark of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was also Clark, other officials say, who authorized a
military spokesman, a spit-and-polish British air commodore named
David Wilby, to tell journalists on March 29 that ``reliable
sources'' had reported that professor Fehmi Agami had been
``executed'' in Kosovo along with four other prominent ethnic
Albanian leaders. Agami was a member of the Kosovo Albanian
delegation to the peace talks in France.
</P>
<P>
   Wilby was careful to qualify the report, and did not claim that
the alliance had any independent confirmation of the charge.
</P>
<P>
   But within a couple of days, other sources in Kosovo said Agami
was safe, as was Baton Haxhiv, another prominent Albanian
opposition politician in Kosovo whose death the commodore had
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Though nobody here knows for sure even now where the men are,
the episode did little for Wilby's credibility, or for that of the
alliance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since there is not much he or Shea has been able to say so far
about the details of the air campaign, they speak in generalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our adapted and responsible air campaign continues,'' the
commodore said Friday. ``Numerous infrastructure targets, including
bridges, were struck as well as several staging areas and
headquarters facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Maps and slides are equally vague. Clark, who briefed
journalists himself on Thursday, said the previous day's bombing
had hit Yugoslav army and Interior Ministry police forces in
Kosovo, and operational headquarters and support facilities
elsewhere in Serbia, but he did not identify any and gave no clue
about how many planes had flown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you that the weather conditions haven't been
everything we sought,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The military is always concerned about giving information that
could compromise the safety of pilots who have to brave
sophisticated anti-aircraft defenses, which may explain the
reluctance to reveal operational details.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my profession, you don't expect an invitation, and you
don't expect to send a calling card to say you're coming,'' as
Wilby, a Royal Air Force navigator, put it.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, asked why he had released hardly any information about
targets in the first days of the bombing, though the Yugoslav
forces who had been bombed presumably knew who they were, suggested
that he was inhibited by the diversity of the Brussels press corps.
Among the reporters who come daily for information are
representatives of two Serbian daily newspapers and a Serbian news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, this is as amazing. It is as if Iraqi journalists had
been allowed into the allies' briefings in Saudi Arabia on the war
in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   But one result is that anybody who wants to find out what the
allies have been doing, as opposed to what the allies think about
what the Yugoslavs have been doing, has to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, for example, it was a British military official in
London, Air Marshal Sir John Day, who disclosed that American B-1
bombers had been active on Thursday night for the first time. All
Wilby would say about that was, ``We are increasing the tempo and
effectiveness of our campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's close-mouthed policy means that he has effectively
surrendered control over public information about the allied
campaign to the British Defense Ministry and the Pentagon in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's bow-tied spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, is somewhat
more informative than Wilby has been, and because of the time
difference between Europe and the United States, Bacon often gives
the first details about operations that have not even begun by the
opening of the daily 3 p.m. briefing here.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's military subordinates in the field say they would love
to talk more about their exploits, but that they can't. So his
spokesmen, and the news organizations that depend on them for
information, rely instead on polemics and generalities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
