<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-KRAVIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAVIS TO SELL $1.5 BILLION IN GILLETTE STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Gillette Co. director Henry R. Kravis is preparing to
cash out _ again _ following the company's acqusition of battery
maker Duracell International Inc. 2 1/2 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette said Friday that units of Kravis' New York buyout firm,
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. have registered with the U.S.
Securities and Exchange Commission to sell 25.6 million shares of
common stock.
</P>
<P>
   That stake would be worth $1.52 billion at Gillette's closing
price of 59 1/4 on Thursday, the most recent day markets were open.
Following the sale, KKR's stake in Gillette will decline to 2
percent of the company's 1.1 billion shares outstanding, from 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The sale marks the second time that KKR has benefited from
Gillette's purchase of Duracell, the Bethel, Conn. battery maker in
September 1996. KKR originally purchased Duracell from Kraft Inc in
1988 for $1.8 billion, and in 1991,, took the company public.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, KKR's remaining stake in the firm was translated
into shares of Gillette. In early 1998, KKR earned $1.01 billion
after selling 10 million Gillette shares at $101 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. will underwrite the current offering,
Gillette said. The registration statement is needed to sell shares
to the public because Kravis remains on Gillette's board of
directors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
