<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-LAYOFFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON OUTLINES SEVERANCE TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Seeking to temper the pain of impending layoffs,
BankBoston Corp. Friday outlined measures designed to aid employees
who will lose their jobs when the company merges with Fleet
Financial Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, sensitive to its image among employees and the
community, said the severance terms it had created provided ``the
needed level of support for eligible employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston expect to lay off a total of 4,000 to 5,000
employees across New England as they combine to form the nation's
eighth-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand more staff members from both banks will find
themselves working for new companies when branches are sold later
this year to satisfy antitrust regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Under BankBoston's plan, employees who lose their jobs will
receive two weeks' base pay for each year of service.
</P>
<P>
   Additional supplements include 10 weeks' pay for those earning
less than $50,000 a year; 20 weeks' pay for those earning $50,000
to $100,000 annually; and 30 weeks' pay for those earning more than
$100,000 a year. Staff members will also receive payments ranging
from 4.3 to 8.7 weeks' salary.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston employs approximately 25,000 people, while Fleet has
about 35,000 workers. The banks expect to close a total of two
dozen branches, in addition to selling off, or divesting, around
270 branches throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has been criticized in the past for an aggressive layoffs
program following mergers. But the company said Friday that
severance terms for its own employees, to be announced at the
beginning of next week, would be similar to BankBoston's.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston also said staff members will get continued medical
and life insurance for a limited period of time. The company said
it would provide outplacement services, external job retraining, as
well as support for staffers seeking internships, stipends for
those interested in community service or nonprofit organizations,
and aid to budding entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   The plans do not cover staffers at BancBoston Robertson
Stephens, the company's San Francisco investment bank. Those
employees are covered under their own firm's plan. BankBoston's
severance plans also exclude part-time workers.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston won praise for its severance package terms when it
cut 2,000 jobs after acquiring BayBanks Inc. in 1996. It said the
plans announced Friday are similar to the BayBanks program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4217 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DOW-REACT-ART-2TA     04-02 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DOW-REACT-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPSCOTCHING AT 10,000, THE DOW GETS OUR ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Nev., Mass., Texas, Ill., B.C.)   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (ART ADV: Photo of Dave Franchi is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was easy to dismiss the Dow's close above 10,000 last Monday
as merely symbolic, just one more market milestone _ and a not very
enduring one at that, given the index's fall later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   But for many investors, the barrier-breaking close was a time to
reconsider their relationship with stocks. One thing was clear from
conversations with investors around America: The market these days
is on almost everyone's mind.
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA: Dave Franchi never used to spend much time thinking
about the stock market. A self-employed carpenter in Sparks, Nev.,
Franchi, 43, told his bank to deduct $525 a month from his checking
account to invest in some mutual funds recommended by a financial
planner, and left it at that. The money is meant to pay for college
for his two teen-aged sons and for his own retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Dow breaking the 10,000 mark, he is becoming
captivated. He has shifted his IRA to an investment that has
``higher risk but greater profit potential, since it's so bullish
right now.'' He is even thinking of taking a few thousand dollars
to ``dabble online.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good feeling right now,'' Franchi said. ``Whether it
will last very long, you never know.'' But his home-repair business
is thriving, so Franchi feels flush, and the long bull market has
raised his expectations. ``If I could do 18 to 25 percent this
year, I'd probably be pretty happy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JON CHRISTENSEN
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS: Kristin Todd yawned at the Dow's breaking 10,000:
``They'd been hyping it for so long, it was like, `Oh, it finally
happened.' It was a little bit anticlimactic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Todd, 34, a Boston public relations executive, and her
husband have been investing in individual stocks and mutual funds
for two years without relying on professional advice. Most of her
friends invest the same way. ``Maybe 10 years ago, you used to call
your stock broker, but now you're calling your friends, you
colleagues, and asking them for some financial advice.''
</P>
<P>
   She and two lunch companions agreed that the Internet had made
investing in stocks easy and fun, and though she knows there are
risks, she can't picture doing anything else with whatever spare
cash comes her way, including this year's tax refund. ``You trust
the stock market a little bit more,'' she said ``so you choose that
over something else.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVE SHAW
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Charlotte Kennedy, 43, a Houston bookstore employee,
remains fatalistic about the market no matter what milestones the
Dow hits. ``Ten thousand? So what? It goes up, and it goes down,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   After her mother died two years ago, Ms. Kennedy turned over
half of her inheritance to a broker to invest. ``People like me do
it because we heard it's how the other half lives,'' she said. ``I
don't look at what it's doing; I wouldn't even know how.''
</P>
<P>
   If the market tanked, she said, ``I'd be concerned but not
devastated. The way I see it, it isn't money I earned with my own
hands; I inherited it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By KATE MURPHY
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS: The market has Mark Caudill, 32, a violinist in
Somerville, Mass., uneasy. He has stopped putting new 401(k)
contributions into stocks because he thinks the market is in a
bubble and investors are losing touch with reality: ``My dad's
obsessed. Every night he watches the `Nightly Business Report' and
gauges his moods on how the market is doing. It's ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is peer pressure, Caudill said: ``People
feel like they missed the boat in the '80s, when anybody who had
any money made a lot. Now they want in.''
</P>
<P>
   It's only a matter of time, he thinks, before economic trouble
overseas bursts the bubble. ``As soon as all the rich people start
to feel the tremors, they'll pull their money out and take the rest
of us with them,'' he said. ``Everyone else rides along on their
coattails when it's good, and we really suffer when it's bad.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVE SHAW
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: When she heard about the Dow hitting 10,000, Elizabeth
Getteau's reaction was, ``OK, next.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of her savings are in her 401(k), 75 percent of which is
invested in stocks. Ms. Getteau, 28, also has ``a bunch'' of shares
in Continental Airlines, where she works as an accountant in its
Houston headquarters, and stakes in IBM, Walt Disney and Merck that
she inherited.
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation has no fear,'' she said. ``It's always gone
up.'' So last week, she organized an investing club consisting of
herself, her mother and her aunts, whose caution will
counterbalance her enthusiasm for risk.
</P>
<P>
   Though she thinks the Dow will level off for a while, she said,
``All of my tax refund is going to buy stock.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By KATE MURPHY
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS: George Herrmann, 42, a telephone company systems
analyst in Boston, was skeptical of the Dow's short-term staying
power: ``I actually think it's just a surge. Breaking 10,000
generated a lot of interest and that interest turned into impact. I
don't think it's going to stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   But he feels sure that technology stocks will lift the market to
new heights again before long, so he's leaving his 401(k) as is,
mainly in technology stocks and funds. ``As long as you're dealing
with technology, there is no limit,'' he said. ``If a company still
has fresh ideas, it's a sound investment.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVE SHAW
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS: Camilla Ashley, 56, a psychiatrist in Oak Park, Ill.,
a Chicago suburb, saw echoes of human nature in the hubbub over Dow
10,000. ``It's just a nice number,'' she said. ``People get
fascinated with the millennium and other nice numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The milestone hasn't altered her portfolio _ mainly stock mutual
funds _ but she sees other people behaving differently. ``People
definitely feel these days like the stock market is something that
they have to be a part of. We make it an obligation for ourselves
to be earning as much as possible, and not only do people have to
earn money, but their money has to earn money. I think that's too
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ashley has stopped putting new money into stocks, mainly
because she needs cash to pay a child's tuition at medical school.
``I'm investing in daughter futures,'' she joked.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANDREW BLUTH
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH COLUMBIA: Lorraine Moncur, 66, of Victoria, British
Columbia, has done well enough with her retirement investments, all
in stocks and mutual funds, that she can afford to travel. On a bus
tour with her sister and cousin, she stopped at the Carson Nugget
Casino in Carson City, Nev., last week. But the same bull market
that pays for a bit of recreational gambling has made her less
inclined to gamble on stocks. Instead, she is gradually selling
when she needs cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do this for fun,'' she said, gesturing toward the
surrounding slot machines. ``This is pure speculation. And I don't
speculate on the market anymore. I used to, but it can be
disastrous _ as bad as this,'' she said, with another pull on the
handle. ``And our luck here hasn't been as good as the Dow.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JON CHRISTENSEN
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA: Henry Wong, 41, keeps the TV above the bar in his
Chinese restaurant in Carson City tuned to financial news. He is an
active online trader in stocks and is more interested in how
volatile the market is than in how high the Dow rises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals of the market are basically the same whether
it's at 9,900 or 10,000,'' he said, ``but you make more money when
it's going up and down if you're trading. I don't buy stocks and
hold them; if it goes up a couple of points, I sell, and then I
wait for it to come down and buy again. I miss a lot of the growth
sometimes, but I'm not greedy. And if you're not holding a lot of
stock when the market goes down, you're usually OK''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JON CHRISTENSEN
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA: Katherine Kaplan can't escape following the market,
even though her own portfolio these days is all cash. Everyone else
in the family of this Los Angeles eighth grader seems to be fixated
on the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as she got home Monday, she heard about Dow 10,000 from
her mother _ who owns big industrials like Wrigley and Archer
Daniels Midland but avoids computer stocks. When Katherine tries to
watch MTV at her grandfather's house, she said, ``he walks in and
changes the channel on me, sits there for five minutes watching the
bottom of the screen roll by, shouts `Yes!' and hands me back the
control.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``He said he never thought he'd see 10,000, so he's
really happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are the grown-ups all stock-mad? ``Now that this weird
Monica Lewinsky stuff is over, people have turned off the talk
radio and are doing something more productive,'' she said. No
stocks for her, though: she's banking her allowance, hoping
eventually to buy a car.
</P>
<P>
   _ By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
