<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   High Income, No Tax: A More Exclusive Club
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans who made $200,000 or more, yet managed
to pay no federal income taxes, fell to 1,820 in 1996, down about
one-third from a peak of 2,675 in 1995, new IRS data show.
</P>
<P>
   An annual IRS report to Congress also showed that 36,759
taxpayers making $200,000 or more paid less than 15 percent of
their income in federal income taxes in 1996, the last year for
which data are available.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, the first year the report was issued, 85 taxpayers _
who can be married couples filing jointly or individuals _ paid no
income taxes despite making at least $200,000, the equivalent of
about $543,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly more than 1.5 million taxpayers had income of more than
$200,000 in 1996. That group is only 1.3 percent of all taxpayers,
but together they earned $806.6 billion, 17.8 percent of all
individual income reported to the IRS, and paid $228.1 million in
federal income tax, or 34.7 percent of individual income taxes that
year.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS report, in the winter 1998 Statistics of Income
Bulletin, did not specify how each of the 1,820 taxpayers avoided
federal income taxes in 1996, including the alternative minimum
tax, which was enacted in 1969 to thwart tax avoidance by the rich.
Many of those 1,820 filers, however, received significant income
from municipal bonds, which are generally tax-exempt. Also common
in their returns were unusually large medical and dental bills,
stakes in partnerships and corporations that pass tax liabilities
to their owners, and casualty or theft losses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And all but 160 in the group also escaped paying income taxes
anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Flocking to the IRS Site
</P>
<P>
   The IRS has been reaching out to taxpayers on the Internet since
1996, and this year, taxpayers are reaching back in record numbers.
From Jan. 1 through last Sunday, the IRS Web site was visited 573.6
million times, up from 231 million during the same period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The site, called The Digital Daily, covers topics like
regulations, deadlines and electronic filing of tax returns
(www.irs.ustreas.gov/prod/cover.html). But the centerpieces of the
site are the forms and publications to download and use, said Jerry
Conway, the senior technology adviser for the Digital Daily.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said the family of 1040 forms is the most popular part of
the site, followed by publications about new provisions like
benefits for higher education and the child tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Among new features in The Digital Daily are a W-4 form
calculator for figuring how much tax to have withheld from
paychecks, a section for owners of small businesses and an
education section that helps teachers orient students in grades 8
to 12 to the inevitability of taxes _ something for which many are
not prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``They work for three hours at $7 per hour and expect a check
for $21,'' Conway said. ``Taxes are a culture shock for them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHELLY FREIERMAN &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
