<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL BUSINESS BRIEFS: LIPPER, DORFMAN, WAGONER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, You're Famous; Now Get Back to Work
</P>
<P>
   He was the toast of the international banking community. But
not, on this occasion at least, for his financial expertise.
Kenneth Lipper, chairman of Lipper &AMP; Co., which manages $5 billion
for pension funds and wealthy individuals, shared the Oscar last
month for best documentary feature for ``The Final Days.'' Lipper
was co-producer of the film, which is about Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Lipper joined 20 other bankers _ including
Walter Shipley, chairman of Chase Manhattan Corp.; Frank Newman,
chairman of Bankers Trust; Toshio Morikawa, chairman of the
Sumitomo Bank, and David Li, chairman of the Bank of East Asia _
for a meeting of the International Advisory Board of the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York. As the dinner was under way in the bank's
banquet room, New York Fed president William McDonough raised his
glass to congratulate Lipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had prime ministers and presidents and kings in this
room,'' McDonough declared, ``but we've never had the winner of an
Academy Award.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipper was just as delighted by the comment of a tablemate: ``Oh
yes, we watched you in Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean that Lipper, basking in his colleagues'
accolades, was momentarily distracted from the market? Not a bit.
``I talk with my office at least 10 times a day,'' he said. ``The
market keeps me grounded, reminding me of how fast things, and
people, can go up, and then come down.''
</P>
<P>
   An Online Reincarnation
</P>
<P>
   Dan Dorfman's ability to move stocks has long been well known.
As a financial journalist for USA Today, CNBC and Money magazine,
Dorfman over two decades often sent stocks soaring with predictions
of takeovers or other news _ some of which actually panned out.
</P>
<P>
   That was before the Internet became the preferred medium for
spreading stock tips and before day traders were such a potent
force. Now, after a hiatus, Dorfman plans to return to his trade by
linking with an Internet tip service known as Jagnotes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dorfman was dismissed by Money magazine in 1996 amid reports
that securities regulators were investigating his relationship with
a stock promoter who later pleaded guilty to charges of securities
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Recchia, a spokesman for Dorfman, said last week that
``neither Dan nor his lawyer has ever been contacted by the
government seeking an interview'' about those matters.
</P>
<P>
   Dorfman suffered a stroke in May 1996. His contract with CNBC
expired, and he has since been largely inactive as a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Jagnotes started in 1989 as a fax service that compiled details
on equity research by major brokerage firms, but its $2,000 annual
fee was prohibitive for most individual investors. Jagnotes
recently went public by merging with a company that had publicly
traded stock but no operations and started a Web site offering
subscriptions for $9.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Dorfman will post a daily report on the site, and Gary Valinoti,
the chief executive, said he believes the service will be able to
charge ``Super Bowl rates'' to advertisers. A television deal for
Dorfman is also in the works, people close to the negotiations
said.
</P>
<P>
   For signing with Jagnotes, Dorfman has received long-term stock
options, Valinoti said. Dorfman's spokesman declined to elaborate
on Dorfman's compensation package. The share price of the company
soared from less than $1 to more than $20 the last two weeks, most
recently trading at $16.50. The move came before Dorfman's
employment was reported.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EDWARD WYATT
</P>
<P>
   Better Luck With Yukon &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G. Richard Wagoner Jr., the president and chief operating
officer of General Motors, invited scores of guests to a reception
at New York City's Grand Central Terminal on Monday night followed
by a party to celebrate the NCAA men's basketball championship
game. A former Duke University basketball player, Wagoner unveiled
two big sport utility vehicles, the Chevrolet Suburban and the GMC
Yukon, then sat down in front of a wide-screen television to cheer
for his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, however, was upset by the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   At breakfast the next morning, a determinedly upbeat Wagoner
said that henceforth, he might like to hear more about the Yukon
than UConn
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEITH BRADSHER
</P>
