<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ARABS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY NATIONS IN MIDDLE EAST BACK NATO EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Although there have been vocal protests around
the world against the US-led NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia,
there has been a notable silence in the Arab world, which usually
opposes US military engagements.
</P>
<P>
   The support reflects Islamic solidarity with a fellow Muslim
people under siege in the Balkans. But it is tempered by the fact
that the three other recent American military operations have
targeted Muslim states: Iraq, Sudan, and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans are bombing under the banner of protecting
Muslims,'' said Abdel-Barri Atwan, editor of the London-based Arab
language newspaper Al Quds. ``It would not look very nice if the
Arab world was opposing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan made The most vocal expression of support for NATO. On
Wednesday, the new leader, King Abdullah, recalled his ambassador
to Belgrade in protest and joined other Arab nations in pledging
humanitarian assistance to the Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Gulf region, state-controlled newspapers appealed
to the United States and its NATO allies to commit ground troops to
stop Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the only way to save the Kosovo Albanians,'' according
to an editorial in the Saudi newspaper al-Madina. ``NATO cannot
back away.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in Afghanistan, where US cruise missiles rained down last
year in an attempt to disrupt the operations of Osama bin Laden,
the Saudi businessman believed to be behind the bombings of two US
embassies in Africa, the ruling Taliban party said the use of armed
force is justified in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Taliban chief representative in the United States, Abdul
Hakeem Mujahid, said in an interview that the NATO air campaign was
not enough to stop the Serb onslaught, and said Afghanistan would
support the use of Western ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the NATO powers to prevent Serb brutality and provide
protection to the Muslims,'' he said. But ``we are afraid they are
failing in their mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Muslim countries themselves have been sending food but little
military support to the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The United States put pressure on the Kosovo Liberation Army to
refuse help from Islamic ``freedom fighters,'' and Washington has
pressed the Kosovars' allies, including Albania, to deport Islamic
militants from as far away as Afghanistan who are offering aid to
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But support for NATO action was far from universal in the Arab
world. President Mohammed Khatami of Iran criticized the NATO
airstrikes, voicing concern that it would spark even more violent
reaction by the Serbs. Still, he voiced little sympathy with
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say the public reaction of Muslim governments masks
deep misgivings about the use of Western military force.
Abdel-Barri said many in the Arab world wonder whether the United
States will target Iraq or Libya next, or encourage Christian
secessionists in southern Sudan to establish their own state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of reservation but no outright
condemnation,'' said Clovis Maksoud, a professor of Middle East
Studies at American University. ``The pattern of Milosevic's
behavior shields NATO from condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Iraq and Libya, the Arab world's most bitter adversaries of
the United States, have sided with Milsoevic, but won little
backing.
</P>
<P>
   Moammar Khadafy of Libya appealed unsuccessfully to a number of
Muslim and African organizations, including the Arab League and the
Organization of African Unity, to condemn the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, British officials accused Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein of supplying Yugoslavia with air defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen some of these Iraqi tactics already put into
practice over Serbia,'' said Britain's military chief of state,
General Charles Guthrie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4230 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-HACKERS-BOS &LR;      04-02 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-HACKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN HACKERS INVADE NATO COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Team Spl0it and f0bic are cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beavis and Butthead, the cackling cartoon characters, stare out
from a NASA Web page, their fists raised in a sort of virtual
protest. These familiar figures from American popular culture are
hardly the new image of the space agency: The site was hacked late
Friday by a group of Russian computer experts who also posted the
same message on a government Web site in Egypt. The hacked sites,
signed ``From Russia With Love,'' are scrawled with a profane
message denouncing NATO as well as a demand for allied troops to
``Go away from Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   While the real war in the Balkans wages on the ground and in the
air, another virtual war is being fought in cyberspace. In the past
few days, hackers on both sides of the conflict have been defacing
Web sites with electronic graffiti and launching programs designed
to slow down or crash their opponents' servers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the NATO server in Belgium was bombarded with
thousands of e-mails coming from Yugoslav hackers that overloaded
its Web site. Another group called ``Russian Hackers Union''
defaced a US Navy site.
</P>
<P>
   Hacking groups in the United States and Europe are retaliating
with their own graffiti. A coalition that calls itself Team Spl0it,
which includes an 18-year old American hacker, broke into several
Web sites and posted such anti-war slogans as, ``Tell your
governments to stop the war.'' Hackers on the West Coast are trying
to crack the Serb government site, although the server is said be
extremely secure and based in London. And the Kosovo Hackers Group,
a coalition of European and Albanian hackers, has erased at least
five sites and replaced them with black and red ``Free Kosovo''
banners.
</P>
<P>
   In what is being called the first Internet war, hackers are
emerging as electronic vigilantes. At the same time that
governments are inundating the Internet with propaganda and
individuals are using the medium to communicate, hackers have
actually taken the battle into their own hands, performing military
exercises with the click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``hacktivism,'' the marriage of computer hacking and
political activism. This form of protest has been around since
1995, when hackers became politicized to support convicted hacker
Kevin Mitnick. Most electronic civil disobedience is illegal in the
US, but this is the first time it has been employed during an
international conflict and there is no precedent that governs such
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Vatis, chief of the FBI's National Infrastructure
Protection Center, said through a spokesperson Friday that he had
no comment on the recent rage of hacktivism.
</P>
<P>
   In past international conflicts, governments have successfully
disrupted the telecommunications systems of their opponents. But in
the age of the Internet, this is the first time that private
citizens have been able to jump into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the harbinger of things to come,'' said Barry
Steinhardt, former president of the Electronic Frontier Foundation
and associate director of the American Civil Liberties Union.
``It's a free and open network. Parts of it are sealed off, but
it's a porous network. It's inevitable that you're going to get
vigilantes acting in an extralegal way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackers have traditionally objected to attempts to curtail free
speech, and American hackers are outraged by Serb government
censorship. One member of Team Spl0it, an 18-year old resident of
the East Coast who goes by the handle f0bic said in an e-mail
message that he and others decided to take action a few weeks ago.
``I, along with the rest of my team, decided to get the message out
of the Internet,'' he wrote. ``Our message was bright and clear:
Stop the war before we go to World War III.'' The Globe has
confirmed his existence, but he asked that his real name not be
used.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not consider our actions as `war-like,' '' he continued.
``We are not destroying information on sites. We are just trying to
educate people on the real stories, and this seems to be the only
way you can get attention.'' The group hacked the site of the
Cambridge City Council in England as well as other sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the respected Electronic Frontier Foundation, a
leader in Internet policy, has contended that hacktivism is illegal
and can be neither encouraged nor condoned. But that may change in
an international conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may want to reevaluate that in light of the historical
importance that civil disobedience has played as a means of
protest,'' said Alex Foster, the foundation's director of public
affairs. ``Does hacktivism change in a crisis situation? I don't
have an answer on that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster warned that ordinary citizens who are using the Internet
to communicate their own political opinions legally should be
careful, though. ``People in Serbia who are using the the Internet
for normal things like sending e-mail may be putting themselves at
great risk,'' he said. In China, for instance, the government has
cracked down on dissidents simply for sending e-mail that
criticizes the regime.
</P>
<P>
   Hacktivists in Kosovo could be in danger, Foster said. But US
and Russian hacktivists continue their cyberwar unabated and
unconcerned about repercussions. ``We are activists because we see
there are wrongs that need to be corrected,'' f0bic wrote. ``It
seems hackers are the only ones out there actually trying to change
the situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
