<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION TO ZEDILLO'S PRIVATIZATION PLAN WORRIES INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also MEXICO-UNREST, which in moving in the ``i'' category
code.) (DW) 
 By RICK WILLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ At a recent hearing on President Ernesto Zedillo's
proposal to privatize Mexico's electric power industry, government
workers who oppose the plan broke out singing Mexico's national
anthem.
</P>
<P>
   The music was off key, but the political grandstanding was
effective, embarrassing the initiative's supporters by cloaking
government ownership of Mexico's power plants and transmission
lines in patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   The incident underlined the struggle that Zedillo faces in
raising support for the privatization plan, which he says is
urgently needed to attract $25 billion in investments to modernize
and expand the country's power generation and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Since the president announced the initiative in February,
powerful unions and opposition party legislators have expressed
disapproval as have some members of his own Institutional
Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the two main opposition parties, who together control
the lower house of Congress, announced on March 26 that they would
delay a vote on Zedillo's plan until September. The president had
been urging legislators to vote before the current congressional
session ends on May 1; the constitutional amendments allowing the
initiative to go forward require a two-thirds vote.
</P>
<P>
   The political brawl that the president's proposal has stirred up
is starting to worry foreign investors, especially since it follows
a series of botched privatizations and scandals surrounding
government auctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one believes privatization will take place in Mexico
without a dirty deal,'' said George Baker, an energy consultant
based in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The changes Zedillo has proposed are radical only in the context
of Mexico's long protectionism involving its energy resources. In
fact, the country's electric-industry modernization lags behind
that in other Latin American countries. Brazil and Argentina, as
examples, have allowed private investment in electricity for most
of a decade.
</P>
<P>
   When he announced the initiative in a broadcast on Feb. 3,
Zedillo argued that without the investment of vast new amounts of
money, far surpassing government financial resources, Mexico's
power industry is unlikely to satisfy surging demand, and power
shortages could soon result. Demand for electricity in Mexico is
expected to grow 7 percent annually for the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   The president used his weekly radio address last Saturday to
promote his plan. ``We need private investment to take away the
brakes now on the electric industry, which brakes all
development,'' he said, adding that the government would continue
subsidies and rural-electrification programs under a private
system.
</P>
<P>
   Most industry analysts agree with the expectations of a sharp
increase in demand for electric power and say that the economic
consequences of doing nothing could be devastating. ``Repeated
power outages are costly,'' said Rafael Quijano, a Washington-based
energy consultant. ``If electric reform is not passed, the
government will have to spend more on electricity at the expense of
hospitals and public education.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed changes, the Federal Electricity Commission
would grant 30-year concessions to private companies to operate
power plants and regional transmission grids. The commission, one
of Mexico's largest employers, would become little more than a
small government agency.
</P>
<P>
   Energy in Mexico, where the anniversary of the 1938
nationalization of the country's oilfields is an annual holiday, is
a sensitive matter.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of privatization say that the government has
exaggerated Mexico's developing electrical shortage and minimized
the number of jobs likely to be eliminated by the plan. They warn
that a proposal to sell state-owned power plants today is likely to
be followed tomorrow by efforts to break up the state oil company,
Petroleos Mexicanos, or PEMEX, an icon in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents have put forward no clear alternative plan to
finance the expansion of the country's electricity industry.
</P>
<P>
   When electricity was nationalized in 1960, only 44 percent of
Mexicans had access to electric power. State-owned utilities have
over the decades since brought electricity to 95 percent of
households. But in recent years, state investment has been unable
to keep up with the industry's needs.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, changes in the law have allowed private companies to
build power plants, including the Merida 3 electric plant in the
Yucatan peninsula, one of the nation's largest.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's tenure ends in December 2000, and the presidential
campaign is heating up, complicating the political context for the
power initiative. Mexico has two electricians' unions that are
involved in the argument. One is firmly opposed to the plan. The
country's largest electricians' union is closely tied to Zedillo's
party and has taken no stand.
</P>
<P>
   The Party of the Democratic Revolution, the main leftist party,
almost immediately declared its opposition to the initiative. More
recently, Carlos Medina Plascencia, congressional leader of the
conservative National Action Party, which has supported most
privatization initiatives, criticized the power proposal as vague
and faulted the government for not detailing how it would regulate
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   More worrisome for Zedillo is that he appears unable to count on
solid support from his own party. Joel Estudillo, an analyst at the
Mexican Institute of Political Studies, said some party members,
``maybe many, will refuse to support electric privatization.''
</P>
<P>
   Public support for the sale of government assets in general is
eroding after a series of scandals, including accusations of
cronyism and fraud in the sale of state-owned banks and a
subsequent $65 billion bailout. The government also paid billions
to rescue a series of ill-planned private toll roads. In February,
after zigzags in the government's effort to sell the petrochemical
industry, an auction for one important plant failed to attract a
single bidder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2014EST &QL; 
