</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRIVAL OF RUSSIAN SHIP WILL HEIGHTEN TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Liman, the Russian frigate that set sail for the
Balkans Friday, is an unassuming reconnaisance vessel with a
100-member crew and no weapons. As warships go, this one will
hardly pose a military threat to the NATO force massed in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   But Liman's very presence, once it arrives in the Adriatic
sometime early next week, will raise the risk of an unintentional
confrontation between NATO and Russia. And the ship's political and
strategic effect on the fighting in Yugoslavia could be formidable.
</P>
<P>
   What worries US and NATO leaders the most is Liman's array of
electronic intelligence gathering gear, instruments that will allow
the Russian ship to carefully monitor the American-led alliance's
airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   How this information will be used concerns the allies, who claim
the damage done to Yugoslav lines of communication as one palpable
success of two weeks of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow, which has harshly condemned NATO's airstrikes but
avoided getting drawn into the conflict thus far, says the ship
will gather information for the Russian military only. Moscow says
it needs the information because the NATO attack in the Balkan
region is a matter of Russia's national security.
</P>
<P>
   But as Liman sailed Friday from the Black Sea Fleet's base in
the Crimean port of Sevastopol, Ukraine, questions remained about
what the ship will do after it passes Turkey's Bosphorous Strait
Saturday and heads into the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Russian vessel pass on information it gathers to help
Yugoslav air defenses better target NATO aircraft? Could the
information Liman gathers be used by Russia's traditional allies
and fellow Orthodox Christian Slavs, the Serbs, to thwart a
possible NATO ground assault? One veteran Russian military analyst
says ``da.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This changes the strategic situation in the region,'' said
Pavel Felgenhauer, defense analyst for the Moscow daily Segodnya.
``At the moment, the Serbs are like blind mice. But the Russian
ships will work 24 hours a day, listening to NATO pilots, ground
control, conversations at the airbases in Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are going to give this information to the Serbs,
especially in real time, the Serbs are going to know more about the
NATO operation than some NATO commanders do,'' Felgenhauer said.
``The Russians could know when a NATO pilot goes to pee. NATO will
never know what the Russians are picking up, what they are sharing
with the Serbs and what they are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most likely, they'll be sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington is taking this possibilty seriously enough that
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has already contacted Russian
Foreign Minster Igor Ivanov about the ship. Friday, Ivanov angrily
denied that any information would be passed on to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a totally absurd attempt to justify NATO failures,''
Ivanov said at a Moscow briefing. ``This ship will act only in the
interests of Russia's national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that we had put behind us the Cold War times when we
blamed the United States for everything and the United States
blamed Russia for everything,'' Ivanov added. ``You know, the times
of the `Evil Empire' and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   But the conflict over Kosovo has already flamed Cold War-style
passions in Russia. Military officials here last week said one way
Russia could help Yugoslavia would be by supplying the Serbs with
information from Russian satellites. And Russia's ambassador to the
United Nations, Sergei Lavrov, asked by a British TV station
whether such information was being exchanged, answered: ``I'm sure
that this is taking place and this is not something which is beyond
international law.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say the decision to send Liman, taken after
NATO rejected proposals made by Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic after talks Wednesday with Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov, is part of Moscow's effort to pressure NATO into stopping
its bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has frozen relations with NATO, but the government has
also resisted the calls of some politicians to extend direct
military aid to the Serbs, saying Russia has no interest in being
involved in a Balkan war. Meanwhile, a convoy of six more warships
_ armed warships _ is getting ready to sail from Sevastopol,
according to the Russian military.
</P>
<P>
   Russian ships in the region will cause tensions to rise just by
their presence, according to John Reppert of Harvard's Kennedy
School of Government, a former US military attache here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more psychological than anything else, that you become
aware that there is a ship operating in the area'' that is not part
of the operation, Reppert said. ``For ship drivers it makes things
much more complex when you are operating.''
</P>
<P>
   Reppert said Russian intelligence had the capability to help the
Serbs, but ``you've got a difference between their capabilities and
their ability to use them.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing if the Russian ship passes on information directly
to the Serbs, NATO reconnaisance equipment is bound to pick it up.
That could put Russia, already walking a tightrope in its relations
with the West, in a tricky situation. And NATO also has the ability
to block transmissions, or otherwise convince the ship to leave the
area.
</P>
<P>
   But that also raises the possibility of a confrontation,
something some analysts believe will ensure that Liman's
intelligence goes to Moscow only.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in Russia's interest that NATO fails,'' said Dmitry
Trenin, a retired Russian army colonel and an analyst on Russian
military affairs for the Carnegie Moscow Center. ``It is in
Russia's interest to stay on the side and gather information, but
it is in Russia's interest not to get involved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AID-BOS &LR;      04-02 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS BOOST IN AID FOR KOSOVAR ALBANIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling the humanitarian crisis in the Balkans
``grave,'' President Clinton Friday agreed to step up US efforts to
aid hundreds of thousands of Kosovar Albanians fleeing their homes.
</P>
<P>
   As relief workers braced themselves for more waves of refugees,
Washington pledged to fly 500,000 meals to the Balkans starting
Saturday, increase its $50 million donation made this week to the
United Nations and private aid groups, and help aid groups deliver
supplies to refugee centers.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements followed Clinton's meeting with private relief
organizations to assess the crisis and the US response.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be increasingly concerned about the plight of the
displaced people who are actually trapped inside Kosovo and are
under attack or certainly vulnerable to attack by Serbian forces,''
Clinton said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Relief groups made clear they are extremely concerned about the
estimated 345,000 people displaced from their homes but remaining
inside Kosovo. Since the airstrikes began, relief workers were
forced to abandon major stockpiles of food, medicine and other
supplies they were funneling to these internal refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has been very mindful of and responsive to
the humanitarian crisis,'' said Raymond C. Offenheiser, president
of Boston-based OXFAM America who attended the White House meeting.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea also announced a decision to deploy
allied forces in Montenegro to assist the ``refugee calamity''
engulfing the region.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, Macedonia, and the Yugoslav province of Montenegro are
already staggering under a refugee inflow of 220,000 since the
airstrikes began 10 days ago. And with tens of thousands more
massing along Kosovo's border, the Clinton administration and the
United Nations are scrambling to recruit other nations in the
region to take them in.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations formally issued such a request Friday, and
countries that may be asked for help include Italy, Greece, Turkey
and Bulgaria. ``The main concern right now is finding somewhere
else to move these people,'' said a State Department official.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers are facing a challenge in Albania, where the roads
are ``horrendous,'' the people are poor, and the land is full of
``banditry,'' according to reports filed to Hugh Parma, who is
overseeing the US Agency for International Development's disaster
assistance in the region.
</P>
<P>
   In Montenegro, where NATO has bombed Serbian police and military
targets, relief workers are jeopardized by an increasingly volitile
political situation, Parma said.
</P>
<P>
   And in Macedonia, government authorities periodically halt
processing refugees, reluctant to add to their already swollen
refugee population of 86,000.
</P>
<P>
   Chaos erupted on the Kosovo-Macedonian border Friday as aid
workers threw blankets and food to the estimated 30,000 refugees
herded by Serbian forces into a field smaller than the Boston
Common. NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said people are dying as they
wait in the cold and rain without shelter, medicine, or proper
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt helpless,'' said Shelley Beirouk, an aid worker with
Catholic Relief Service, in an interview from Tirana, Albania's
capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Parma's disaster team said aid workers were trying to hold a
meeting between Macedonian officials and private relief groups to
move the refugees into a controlled area within Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is enough food and money to cope with the crisis,
aid workers said they needed Washington to help them transport aid
and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about all the materials you need to build a brand new
city from the ground up,'' said Marge Tsitouris, director of CARE
International's emergency group. ``You need to build shelter, water
supplies, sanitation facilities, and then there are the simple
things you need like soap. It's an incredible task.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
