<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4246 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-TRANSPLANT     04-02 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-TRANSPLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR RECALLS `DISASTER' OF WIFE'S BONE-MARROW TRANSPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Gail Reines was a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, when she got worried she might have a breast lump, she
insisted on a mammogram. It showed a ``teeny'' lump, says her
husband, Dr. H. David Reines, now chief of surgery at
Newton-Wellesley Hospital. ``They told her not to worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gail insisted on a mastectomy. She thought she was cured.
</P>
<P>
   A year or so after she married David, who was then head of
trauma at the Medical College of Virginia, Gail felt a pain in her
chest. The cancer had spread to her spine and neck.
</P>
<P>
   She had a bone marrow transplant in Richmond, at age 39.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the cancer was back. By now living in suburban
Dover, Gail opted for a second transplant in Boston. It was ``a
disaster,'' says David. She died last year, at 44.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going through hell because you think it is your only hope is
not the way we should be doing things which can kill people,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   On April 15, researchers are expected to post on the World Wide
Web preliminary results of two American and three foreign studies
on the efficacy, or lack of it, of bone marrow transplantation for
women with spreading breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The data are still being analyzed and the studies are too small
and too short-term to be decisive. But there is widespread
speculation that the results will be disappointing or equivocal,
although longer studies may still show benefits for some women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have enough data or enough follow-up to be certain
about this procedure. It may be that it will be proven quite
helpful for some types of patient,'' cautions Dr. Steven Come,
director of the hematology-oncology units at Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center. ``We do have patients who are well. There is no
question there is some long-term survival'' with the treatment, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mixed results, 5,000 women a year now undergo
transplants and in some states have legally forced insurers to pay
for it.
</P>
<P>
   In a bone marrow or stem cell transplant, immune cells are
``harvested'' and stored before the patient has high dose
chemotherapy and radiation, which destroy the bone marrow while
attacking the tumor. Then, the stem cells are reinfused to rebuild
the marrow and immune system.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years so many women like Gail Reines declined to enter
clinical trials because they feared being randomized into a control
group that would not get a transplant that it has been hard to get
the data that could better inform such decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gail refused a randomized trial because the press and her
doctors made it look like a bone marrow transplant was the only
hope,'' David says.
</P>
<P>
   Gail's first transplant, at least in retrospect, was ``a piece
of cake,'' he recalls, though paying for it was not. ``She had a
policy with the city (for which she worked as an attorney), I had
one with the state and both policies specifically excluded bone
marrow transplant. So we had the city attorney, the mayor and
people in the governor's office trying to fix it for us, but they
couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, I worked in the hospital and they gave it to me at
cost. The doctors waived their fees,'' he says. The Reines paid
cash, $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gail was in the hospital, ``sicker than hell,'' for 19 days, he
says. Despite his medical training, David says he ``had to leave
the room. I was getting ill watching her. She was throwing up and
having diarrhea simultaneously. Everything was really nasty. I have
never been through anything quite like that.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to re-infuse her with the stem cells, David
was so upset he had to leave the hospital. ``The only thing I could
worry about was if someone spilled her cells, she would die. . . .
I had terrible nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail finally went home, ``bald and weak as a kitten,'' but over
the next few months, regained her strength. The Reines began riding
horses again. Soon after the transplant, in late 1992, they moved
to Dover.
</P>
<P>
   But the next four years would become a roller-coaster of
chemotherapy and radiation, as well as some good times and travel.
Her bones were so full of spreading tumors that it looked like her
``whole spine would collapse,'' David recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they acquired three Briards, French sheep dogs that Gail
loved, and began exhibiting in shows. ``We knew her life was
limited. We said, `Screw it. She had a dog she wanted to show in
France, so we went to France to show the dog.' '' The dog
eventually became the first American-born French champion.
</P>
<P>
   But in November 1996 a CT scan showed Gail's cancer was in her
liver. ``We knew that was a finisher,'' he says. They went to
France anyway for a dog show, but Gail got so sick she had to be
evacuated to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we had three choices _ do nothing, intensive
chemotherapy or another transplant. We talked it over and knew the
odds were terrible for anything,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Gail's team at New England Medical Center was ``incredible,''
willing to do, though not pushing, a second transplant, he says.
Gail was willing to ``do anything to stay alive, to stay with the
horses, the dogs and me.'' (Her doctor declined to comment for this
story.)
</P>
<P>
   The second transplant was like ``six weeks of being in
Auschwitz,'' says David. ``She damn near died on multiple
occasions.'' But she survived, and ``$280,000 and six weeks
later,'' went home in May.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Blue Cross Blue Shield paid because the treatment was
given according to a strict protocol, though not a controlled
study. She lived for another year in failing health, and died last
July.
</P>
<P>
   David Reines is ``not bitter, but I am sad. Women need to know
there are worse things than dying. We can't keep giving transplants
as a promise without data _ the emotion that must have pushed the
legislation to require the payment for transplants must be tempered
with reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want the `best' for our loved ones and ourselves, but
sometimes we are wrong about what's best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
