<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-UNREST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN CITIZENS REVOLT AGAINST THE TYRANNY OF DAYLIGHT SAVINGS
TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also MEXICO-POWER, which is moving in the ``f'' category
code) 
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUADALAJARA, Mexico _ Mexicans in the temperate plains of
midland Mexico are rising up to throw off what they see as an
intolerable abuse and usurpation by the national authorities in
Mexico City: the start of daylight savings time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 President Ernesto Zedillo used his executive powers to
order Mexico to set its clocks forward one hour in summer. This was
to save on the country's overtaxed energy supply and keep the
country in sync with the United States and Europe _ especially
their financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   To Zedillo it was an innocuous modernizing measure, but for many
Mexicans it was a major disruption. While the late sunset of summer
has virtually become a fact of nature to most Americans, in Mexico
it is an unsettling imposition that has stirred deep suspicions
against both the United States and the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the public's reasons for rejecting the time change are
practical. Millions of public elementary school students start
classes at 7 a.m. During the six months of daylight savings time
they have to travel to school without benefit of street lights,
which can be dangerous in a country suffering a crime epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   But many Mexicans are convinced that daylight savings time
undermines their health and sanity. A national poll by the
University of Guadalajara showed 53 percent believing that the time
change caused ``some type of biological alteration,'' including
drowsiness, headaches and ``more stress.''
</P>
<P>
   This year the approach of daylight savings time, which will go
into effect on Sunday, prompted local legislatures in Mexico City,
Guadalajara and Monterrey _ the country's three most important
cities _ to demand that the measure be abandoned. Three states _
Aguascalientes, Durango and Chiapas _ accepted the change but
immediately advanced the schedules for all schools and public
agencies, thereby defeating the basic energy-saving purpose.
</P>
<P>
   So far the only state to free itself from the national yoke is
Sonora. Officials there said they refused to be forced out of step
with their main trading partner, Arizona, which is just across the
northern border and does not observe daylight savings time. Federal
officials assented.
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion had its beginnings here in central Mexico, a
region long known for separatist tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't get used to it,'' said Ricardo Enciso Aguilar,
a lawyer who started the movement against the time change in
Guadalajara. He recalled the funk that came over him during the
first season of daylight savings time two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began having strange depressions,'' Enciso said. ``I felt
disoriented and went around half-asleep all the time. Mexicans are
not accustomed to such drastic change.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year in Guadalajara, Enciso's group collected 80,000
signatures against the change. In March he persuaded the Jalisco
state congress to call on Gov. Alberto Cardenas to defy the federal
government and stay with one year-round schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The astronomical and mathematical data indicate that there is
a real imbalance in our body clocks as a result of the time
change,'' warns the state legislature's declaration, adding that
people would be ``more attuned to the position of the sun'' if the
time change was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   But Cardenas, after conferring for hours with a top energy
official in Zedillo's government, backed down. Enciso said, ``We
are indignant that the governor assumed such a subservient attitude
before the central powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo Trevino, the director of a federal agency set up to
conserve energy, said that in two years, daylight savings time had
saved Mexico what it would take to burn 11 million light bulbs for
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saving nonrenewable resources with longer days,''
Trevino said. ``Unfortunately, not everyone perceives this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans are especially resentful because of a widespread belief
that the time change was adopted under pressure from the United
States. Some believe that Mexico agreed to the measure in a secret
clause in the North American Free Trade Agreement whose terms have
remained hidden from the Mexican people.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition is rising to the point of anarchy. In the state of
Michoacan, besieged authorities decided to let people choose
whatever schedule they wanted. Some schools and offices will open
at one hour, others an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   But Victoria Gutierrez, a mother who called in to a radio talk
show about the time change, said she preferred chaos to tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the government is telling us what time to eat, when to go
to sleep and when to get up,'' she said. ``And you think that is
not going to affect our well-being?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
