<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-600&AMP;AD     04-02 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS GOALS ARE STILL ATTAINABLE WITH AIR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-WEATHER, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Friday that despite the
continued campaign of repression by Slobodan Milosevic and the mass
exodus of refugees from Kosovo, the military and political
objectives of the Western allies were still attainable with an air
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have quite a good chance of achieving our
objectives of the return of the Kosovars to live in security with a
measure of self-government,'' Clinton told reporters Friday as he
made a hastily announced appearance in the White House briefing
room.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke before the announcement Friday night that NATO missiles
had hit downtown Belgrade, but he asserted that Milosevic, the
president of Yugoslavia, would pay ``a heavy price'' for his
repressive policies. And he added a plea for patience, saying that
the allies ``have a good possibility of achieving our mission with
the means that we have deployed.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, speaking early Friday evening to
reporters after a lengthy military briefing, said without giving
details that the air campaign was being ``escalated,'' adding:
``Milosevic has barely begun to incur the damage he will feel to
his military and police and the security apparatus by which he
keeps his dictatorship in power.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested that the framework of the failed peace talks
in France would still serve as the basis for any political
settlement, and that NATO _ and the United States _ would help the
refugees return to Kosovo and provide for their protection. For the
Kosovars to live with some degree of autonomy, he said, ``will
require, clearly, for some period of time, some sort of
international force that will be able to protect their security.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I think there will have to be some sort of security
arrangement in order for them to live safely. And then there will
have to be some sort of agreement that entails the autonomy to
which they are entitled.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, nine days into the NATO bombing campaign, Clinton
still seemed frustrated by the difficulty of explaining the
mission, its objectives and its ramifications. ``Everyone is trying
to get their hands around a very complex problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aides said the president showed up in the briefing room
Friday partly in response to requests by television networks for
fresh footage of him before he heads to Camp David for the weekend.
They also said they wanted to show him engaged in the Kosovo
conflict, which is occupying more than 50 percent of his time each
day, but at the same time they did not want to suggest he is in a
crisis or under seige.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the president is measuring his responses to the
Balkan war and also publicly engaging in other matters. He talked
at Friday's briefing about the new unemployment figures _ the
lowest since 1970. He is planning a trip to Philadelphia next week
to discuss health care. And he will be welcoming the Chinese
premier to Washington next week as critical talks continue on
China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls taken before the missile strikes Friday
showed that a bare majority of the American public supported the
airstrikes but most believed that NATO would not achieve its
objectives.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News poll taken Wednesday after three American soldiers
were taken prisoner by the Yugoslavs showed that 51 percent
supported the bombing and 34 percent opposed it. But a recent
survey by CNN, USA Today and Gallup found that only 41 percent
thought NATO would accomplish its objectives while 47 percent said
it would not.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton insisted Friday that Kosovo was not lost, but he also
focused on the humanitarian relief efforts that have been under way
there for a year. With images on television of refugees streaming
across the Yugoslav border, Clinton continued to try to dispel the
notion that the NATO bombing had escalated Milosevic's violence
against ethnic Albanians and prompted the exodus.
</P>
<P>
   He said that relief workers, whom he met with Friday, had told
him that the refugees supported the bombing and ``clearly
understand that that action did not provoke the attempt to remove
them from their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Asking other countries to help with the relief effort, Clinton
sought to use the plight of the displaced people to dramatize the
need for the continued airstrikes. ``There's no doubt that what
Milosevic wants to do is to keep the land of Kosovo and rid it of
its people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He brought with him to the briefing several government officials
to reinforce the idea that the exodus from Kosovo had been going on
for some time. Hattie Babbitt, deputy administrator of the U.S.
Agency for International Development, said of the exodus: ``It's
not a new phenomenon. There's a new urgency to it, there's a new
scale to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Taft, assistant secretary of state for population,
refugees and migration, called Milosevic's ethnic cleansing a
``pogrom'' and said that the government had been working with
relief agencies for more than a year to respond to the uprooting.
The United States has sent $91 million to the region since last
year, and Clinton authorized $50 million more on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's White House meeting, Peter Bell, the president of
CARE, said of Clinton: ``He is sensitive to the humanitarian
dimension of this crisis. We all know that this is just beginning
to unfold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
