<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WARNS SERB LEADERS NOT TO PUT U.S. SOLDIERS ON TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Frustrated by lack of information, Clinton
administration officials Friday warned Serb leaders against putting
three captured American soldiers on trial, and NATO missiles for
the first time struck government buildings in the heart of
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Although hampered by poor weather, NATO launched eight cruise
missiles from British and U.S. ships, targeting interior ministry
buildings in the center of the Yugoslav capital and setting them on
fire.
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO bombing continued through a 10th day, the refugee
crisis worsened in nations adjacent to Yugoslavia, indicating no
letup in the campaign by Serb troops to drive ethnic Albanians from
the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia is made up of the republics of Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Yugoslavia on Friday indicated Serb leaders were
gathering evidence to try three U.S. soldiers captured on the
Macedonian border. According to the Serb state-run news agency,
Tanjug, the investigating judge said court proceedings in Pristina
had begun and that ``more detailed information'' will be known
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the three soldiers _ Spc. Steven Gonzales
of Huntsville, Texas, Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez of Los Angeles and
Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone of Smiths Creek, Mich. _ must be
treated as prisoners of war, which accords them certain rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no justification for putting them on trial
or displaying them in public in violation of the Geneva
Convention,'' Clinton said. ``As long as they are detained, they
have the status of POWs and are entitled to all the protections
that come with that status.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that he held Serb President Slobodan
Milosevic and his government ``responsible for their safety and
well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   But having severed ties to Belgrade, the White House was
powerless to do much to help the captured soldiers. The State
Department asked the Swedish government, which has maintained
diplomatic ties to Yugoslavia, to relay the U.S. request that the
soldiers be released.
</P>
<P>
   But State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin said that the Swedes
``have not been able to obtain that access, and that is troubling
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House was also struggling to deal with the pressing
problem of the growing number of refugees from Kosovo that have
taxed the resources of surrounding countries, particularly Albania
and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that, in total, between 600,000
and 700,000 refugees have either been forced to flee Kosovo or have
been displaced within the country. They estimate that 36,000
refugees poured across the border on Thursday alone.
</P>
<P>
   This week Clinton authorized an additional $50 million in
emergency aid to relief organizations who are engaged in aiding the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also stressed that other countries must help the
United States in the humanitarian effort.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``we must be increasingly concerned about the plight of
displaced people who are actually trapped inside Kosovo and are
under attack or certainly vulnerable to attack by Serbian forces.
That is why our air strikes are now increasingly focused on
military targets there.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton and his advisers met with representatives
from humanitarian groups to endorse their efforts. He also said
that NATO will support their effort by providing transportation,
shelter and logistical support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the process of airlifting humanitarian daily
rations,'' said Lt. Gen. John McDuffee, lead officer at the Joint
Chiefs of Staff for humanitarian missions.
</P>
<P>
   McDuffee said that planes will begin airlifting 500,000 food
packets to Albania. The packets include biscuits, fruit bars,
peanut butter and pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Even as humanitarian concerns grow, Clinton has vowed to
continue the air campaign against Yugoslavia, but warned it will
not be a ``week or two operation.''
</P>
<P>
   While a number of lawmakers and military experts have said that
NATO will have to send ground troops into Kosovo to stop the Serbs,
Clinton said he was not ready to entertain that option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe that we have a good possibility of achieving
our mission with the means that we have deployed,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials intensified their attacks Friday evening,
striking downtown Belgrade for the first time in the air campaign.
Pentagon officials confirmed that NATO officials had hit the center
of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This operation is ongoing and there is no sanctuary,'' the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks, which took place around 1 a.m. Saturday Belgrade
time, hit the Serbian and Yugoslavian interior ministry buildings
and sparked huge fires.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium,
acknowledged that cloudy weather in the region has hampered the air
activity in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, NATO air commander David Wilby said that pilots
were able to hit ``the full spectrum of targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said most of the activity was concentrated in Kosovo, in
an effort to slow the Serb's campaign to remove ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numerous infrastructure targets, including bridges, were
struck to limit the ability of the army and the special police to
resupply their forces,'' he said.``We also attacked several staging
areas and headquarters facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilby showed a video of the destruction of a Serb army facility
that also was the base for a special police unit.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said that the bombing has not only
damaged the Serb military machine but also the average citizen of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in the last few days there have been shortages of
fuel and bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diesel has disappeared because its all going to the military
effort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shea also conceded the NATO military effort had not stopped the
refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing a crisis that reaches out,'' into the region,
said Shea. Showing up at the borders, he said , were ``families
with very little luggage, ladies in slippers, children with no
shoes and socks.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shea suggested that while Serbs had pushed women, old people
and children out of the country, they were rounding up men to be
used as human shields in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that NATO will continue its bombing over the Easter
weekend despite pleas for a holiday moratorium by the Pope. Senior
U.S. defense officials told The Associated Press that the aircraft
carrier USS Theodore Roosevelt was moving into the region and could
join the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will only stop when President Milosevic stops,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
