<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4263 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-600&AMP;A     04-02 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-600&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBLESS RATE FALLS, BUT COMPANIES ADDING FEWER NEW WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's jobless rate dropped in March to its lowest level
in 29 years, the Labor Department reported Friday, falling from 4.4
percent in February to 4.2 percent in the latest of many signs that
the labor market in the United States remains remarkably robust.
</P>
<P>
   But in a break from the feverish hiring of the last three years,
American companies added far fewer new workers to their payrolls
last month than had been typical lately.
</P>
<P>
   After creating nearly 300,000 additional jobs in February,
employers expanded payrolls by a mere 46,000 in March when a burst
of cold weather held down the usual seasonal upswing in hiring in
industries from construction and landscaping to fast food. Still,
hiring was nearly as strong as ever in most of the vast service
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for workers, particularly those at the bottom of the
ladder, the recent experience with sustained low unemployment _
joblessness has been at or below 4.5 percent for nearly a year _
has clearly started to deliver solid benefits. The 30-year trend
that has depressed pay and job opportunities the most for the least
educated and the least skilled seems to have stopped dead in its
tracks, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really exciting about this report is that our policies
are working well for the people who need it the most,'' said Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman. ``We haven't just touched them, we've
literally propelled them into the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a striking turnaround, the jobless rate among high school
dropouts fell to 6.1 percent in March, down from 7.5 percent in
February. A one-month change is not necessarily reliable, but that
is now half the jobless rate dropouts faced in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate for those with only a high school degree _
3.4 percent _ now resembles what used to be typical for college
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who used to be hiring college grads are
setting their sights lower,'' said David Wyss, chief economist at
DRI McGraw Hill in Lexington, Mass. ``Or if they were hiring high
school grads, they're saying, `I can get by with a high-school
dropout.'''
</P>
<P>
   Minorities are benefiting enormously from the heavy demand for
workers. Last month, for example, joblessness among Hispanics fell
to 5.8 percent, the lowest level since the Labor Department began
compiling statistics separately on the group in the early 1970s.
``The fastest growing population is taking real advantage of this
fast growing economy,'' Ms. Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   The rate for blacks was 8.1 percent, close to the historic lows
reached a couple of months ago. By comparison, the jobless rate for
whites was 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the unemployment rate fell in March largely because
of a sharp contraction in the labor force. (The unemployment rate
is calculated from data gathered from a survey of households,
different from the payroll statistics collected from employers.)
But the labor force had been growing about 50 percent faster than
its long-term trend of about 1 percent a year and seems simply to
have fallen back in line with the long-term pattern in March.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, the pause in job creation came as a reassuring
hint that economic growth was cooling from the super hot 6 percent
rate at the end of last year to a more sustainable pace.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it less likely that inflation might speed up or that
the Federal Reserve would be tempted to raise interest rates. The
stock market was closed for the Good Friday holiday, but the bond
market, in abbreviated trading, registered its relief by pushing
the rate on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond down to 5.59
percent from 5.67 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, signs that the labor market remains extraordinarily tight
abound. New jobless claims are running at unusually low levels,
help wanted advertising remains near its highs and a record
fraction of consumers are reporting that jobs are plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   One telling detail in Friday's jobs report: the number of people
who quit their jobs voluntarily jumped to 13.5 percent, the highest
rate in a year and a half and evidence that American workers are
feeling confident about their prospects of finding good jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, job opportunities varied widely from industry to
industry. A spring cold snap following unusually mild weather this
winter accounted for a drop of 47,000 jobs in the booming
construction business.
</P>
<P>
   The weather may also have been responsible for the failure of
fast-food chains to hire as many workers as they usually do at this
time of the year; that trimmed 48,000 jobs from eating and drinking
industry. Landscaping and other agricultural services were down
8,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Nardone, an economist at the Bureau of Labor Statistics,
said that the seasonal quirks should not be allowed to obscure the
broader picture. ``Outside the sectors that were affected by the
weather,'' he said, ``you had the same pattern of hiring that
you've been seeing for months.''
</P>
<P>
   As hundreds of layoff announcements over the last few months
foreshadowed, manufacturers are still tightening their belts. In
March, they trimmed another 35,000 workers from their payrolls,
bringing the total number of jobs lost to 391,000 over the last
year. That weakness seems, on the face of it, to contradict recent
reports from purchasing managers suggesting a broad recovery in
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, however, the dichotomy reflects ferocious price
competition, which is forcing manufacturers to clamp down on costs
in order to sustain reasonable production.
</P>
<P>
   Service companies, on the other hand, added 95,000 new
positions, close to the average of 112,000 a month over the last
year. Management consultants and engineers were in as much demand
as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Banks, brokerages, insurers and other financial services firms
added workers by the thousands. Health care companies, schools and
universities and movie chains, amusement parks and other
entertainment businesses did lots of hiring, too.
</P>
<P>
   For those wondering whether the good times can continue, one of
the most reassuring bits of news in the report was the absence of
any speed up in wage gains. ``The wage gains are surprisingly
tame,'' said Paul Kasriel, chief U.S. economist at Northern Trust
Bank in Chicago. ``If anything we've seen a slight deceleration.''
</P>
<P>
   The hourly pay of nonsupervisory workers _ admittedly a smaller
and smaller slice of the work force _ rose by 3 cents to $13.09 in
March, 3.6 percent higher than a year ago. Back in April 1998,
hourly pay had risen 4.4 percent over the previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with the measured change in the consumer price index
running at around 1.6 percent a year and other gauges showing even
lower levels of inflation, that's a solid gain in the standard of
living of average workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
