<HEADER>
A4265 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     04-02 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY PRESIDENT CANCELS PLANS TO BUILD ROSE BOWL PRACTICE
FACILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Los Angeles Galaxy President Tim Leiweke
canceled plans to build a practice facility at the Rose Bowl
because of the stadium's lack of movement in construction and its
added cost to build the new field in parking lot area H.
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke withdrew his proposal at a Rose Bowl Operating Committee
meeting Thursday night. He was not available for comment Friday.
Galaxy general manager Sergio Del Prado said Rose Bowl officials
wanted the Galaxy to pay the cost of replacing parking stalls, in
addition to picking up the bill for the practice site.
</P>
<P>
   There was also no word on when the practice site would be built.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we are very disappointed this didn't work out,''
Del Prado said. ``It is most disappointing to our players because
of all the promises we made to them and the coaching staff that we
would get this done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortuantely, this is something they have heard before and we
are back to square one and looking for alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   For a temporary training facility, Del Prado confirmed that the
Galaxy is looking at a vacant school in Altadena on Monday. Earlier
this year, the Galaxy toured facilities at Azusa Pacific University
and Mount San Antonio College. Prior to agreeing with the Rose Bowl
to build a practice facility, the Galaxy was leaning toward Mt. SAC
as a possible site.
</P>
<P>
   Since purchasing the team for $26 million last October,
billionaire Philip F. Anschutz has already provided the Galaxy with
a new weight room, office space and re-constructed locker room at
the Rose Bowl -- at an estimated cost of $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to build the new practice facility was estimated to be
in the $250,000 range. However, the Galaxy learned the Rose Bowl
Bowl wanted Los Angeles to pay an additional $200,000 to $250,000
to replace parking spaces that would be lost for UCLA football.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertain how long the team's tenure would last at the Rose
Bowl, Leiweke decided not to spend a half million on the project
when the Galaxy could conceivably leave and build its own stadium
in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (ROBC) could guarantee the price was a half million,
we may have been able to keep talking,'' Del Prado said. ``But
there was no idea where it would stop. It started at $250,000 and
kept getting higher and higher.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent developments have slowed negotiations between the
Galaxy and the Rose Bowl on a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, Rose Bowl general manager Dave Jacobs and Del
Prado said the Galaxy's plans are to remain at the Rose Bowl and
look for a new training facility. As for the future, anything's
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going forward with the contract renewal with the Rose
Bowl,'' Jacobs said. ``The length of our deal with the Rose Bowl
hasn't been finalized, but there are no plans for them to leave at
this point.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Galaxy signed a two-year contract, with three
option years to play in the Rose Bowl. The Galaxy and RBOC reached
agreement on a new contract earlier this year to complete the final
two option years and add a third, which the Galaxy could buy their
way out of for $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   That new deal is yet to be signed, however, meaning the Galaxy
is in the second option year of the original three-year-option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a new deal ready to sign but it included the practice
facility,'' Del Prado said. ``Now that that deal is off the table,
we have to start over all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke threatened March 20 that if the practice facility deal
fell through, he would ask out of the contract and take the team
elsewhere. That means the Galaxy could leave at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed to making this work (at the Rose Bowl),''
Leiweke said at the time. ``But if this takes much longer and if
they make us do more than we were supposed to, then guess what? We
have an out in our contract and we'll go build our own stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke will discuss the Galaxy's future Monday when the team
returns from San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   He has said all along that building a new stadium is a strong
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we move, we're building our own stadium,'' Leiweke said
last week. ``We're in a unique situation. We happen to have the
resources and expertise to build our own facility. For us to spend
$30 or $40 million dollars is nothing because we know we can make
it back. We're good at that. That is what we do for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Prado said Thursday's developments are a step in that
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a possiblity,'' Del Prado said. ``But it's
very premature at this point. I will say this, though. The Rose
Bowl has made good efforts to try and please us, it was more a
matter of city politics that binded them with the facility issue. I
still think they are good to work with and we'll explore
possibilities with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is a big difference between owning your own stadium
and going through the city. Those are the types of questions we
have to ask ourselves in the coming weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
