<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURED EDWARDS TO GET FULL PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is finally some good news on Robert Edwards. NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue and Players Association executive
director Gene Upshaw have reached an agreement by which the
seriously injured Patriots running back will be paid his contract
in full.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul and I have talked, and we've agreed to treat this injury
like it occurred in the Pro Bowl, even though he did not get hurt
playing in that game,'' said Upshaw. ``But he did get hurt playing
in an event connected to the game, and we're going to use that
theory to make sure this kid gets paid his money.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards blew his knee apart playing in a beach flag football
game in Hawaii two days before the Pro Bowl. He has had surgery,
and it is doubtful he will ever play again. Edwards had played only
one year on a five-year contract. Because his injury did not occur
in an NFL game, the league did not have to pay off Edwards's
contract. The Patriots, however, have already agreed to pay his $3
million bonus in full, and now the league will cover the rest of
his deal, which is approximately another $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to set up a special fund,'' said Upshaw. ``We did
the same thing when Reggie Brown from Detroit got hurt. Right now
we are going to take this (Edwards) thing year to year, because all
of us are hoping that he is going to be able to play again. But if
he can't, we will take it year to year, and when his contract is
over, we will see what we can do for him in terms of disability
(pay).''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a linebacker, was paralyzed from an injury suffered in a
regular-season game against the Jets two years ago. Edwards, thanks
to his lawyer, also has $2 million in insurance coverage, which he
will collect if he cannot play again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story about the Red Sox having the highest average ticket
price _ $24.05 _ is accurate but misleading.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have the smallest, and oldest, ballpark in the major
leagues, with 33,000 seats. The park does not contain an upper-deck
or the ``nose-bleed'' seats that cost less than $10 on average in
most parks, such as Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Factor in another 20,000 seats at Fenway Park for less than $10
and the Sox' average ticket price would be in the middle among the
30 major league teams. Only four teams in major league baseball _
the Red Sox, the Cubs, the Dodgers, and the Marlins _ own their own
stadium, which means the team is responsible for taxes, paying the
maintenance, and capital improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1981, the Red Sox have spent $80 million on capital
improvements at Fenway Park, which is like putting a tuxedo on a
pig. In other cities, the parks are owned by the city or county,
meaning no taxes are paid (Red Sox pay in full); and all
maintenance and improvements are paid by the public. Smallest,
oldest, private, taxes _ these are all major reasons why the Red
Sox are seeking a new stadium, plans for which are expected to be
announced before June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Red Sox will not wear any advertising on their
shirtsleeves this year and haven't had an offer from anyone yet to
make them change their mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based agent Brian Cook, who was in the news a lot here
two years ago when former Bruin Adam Oates was getting himself
traded to Washington, has been suspended by the National Hockey
League Players' Association.
</P>
<P>
   The memo sent to all hockey agents by the union claims that ``on
or about Sept. 2, 1997, Cook converted funds belonging to Adam
Oates/Center Ice Promotions, Inc., for his personal use.
Thereafter, he concealed his actions and falsely misrepresented
what had transpired to his clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``On or about April 9, 1998, and continuously thereafter, Cook
has acted to limit or thwart the NHLPA's inquiry into these
matters. Cook provided the NHLPA with false and misleading
information, documents, and materials, and failed to fully
cooperate with its investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   On or after Oct. 27, 2001, Cook may reapply for certification.
Efforts to reach Cook were unsuccessful. The phone company reports
that his phone has been disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is why schools want to get into the Division 1-A football
mix.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's basketball team, which just won the national
championship, gets virtually nothing in reward. The Huskies take
home $360,000, plus some expenses.
</P>
<P>
   But realistically, after their expenses, they will have hardly
anything left.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Syracuse, another Big East school, collected $5
million when its football team lost to Florida in the Orange Bowl
New Years Eve.
</P>
<P>
   As a conference, the Big East will take in $5.85 million, to be
divided among 13 teams the next six years, from the participation
of UConn, St. John's, Miami, and Syracuse in the NCAA men's
basketball tournament this year. The problem is that there are more
than 300 schools splitting the money in college basketball, and
fewer than 100 getting a piece of the action in football. Beyond
the money, the NCAA also gives participating schools scholarship
grants in aid, but like many other things involving the NCAA, the
basketball payoff system is convoluted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keep your fingers crossed for Malden's Kevin McGlinchey. He'll
find out this weekend if he is going to be with the Atlanta Braves
this season.
</P>
<P>
   McGlinchey is a great story. He was drafted three years ago out
of Malden High School, but the Braves' original offer was not that
much. So his agents from Woolf Associates, Greg Clifton and Jack
Coffey, took a gamble. They played him in a junior college in
Florida, where he pitched more than he had in high school, and
before the year was over, the Braves came up with a big bonus and
signed him before he could reenter the draft.
</P>
<P>
   McGlinchey sparkled in winter ball in Puerto Rico and in
exhibition games and figures to make the Braves' terrific staff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Providence Bruins have enjoyed a remarkable turnaround this
season. They already have 50 wins and, with 107 points entering
Friday night's game with Fredericton, are well on their way to the
best record in the American Hockey League. A year ago they won 19
games, and now they have staged the greatest reversal in the
league's 63-year history . . . Not true: Doug Flutie does not get
$6 million, as reported, from a made-for-television movie on his
life. The entire budget for the film will be $6 million . . .
Speaking of millions, John Calipari is in no rush to return to
coaching basketball. The former Nets coach will collect more than
$7 million on his contract with New Jersey . . . Jim Rice will
throw out the first pitch at the Red Sox' opening game in Fenway
Park. Rice will represent all of the team's all-star players over
the years, as Opening Day will kick off the All-Star celebration in
Boston this year . . . Bobby Orr will be the Grand Marshall for
this year's Hot Dog Safari, which raises more than $200,000 a year
for charity. The event will be held May 23 at Suffolk Downs, and
will attract more than 20,000 . . . One very smart West Coast
baseball man says that Mo Vaughn is in the best shape of his life
and, although he has not hit for power in the spring, will have a
big year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We're happy to read that Terry Glenn says he is ready to grow
up. It's about time. When Glenn broke his ankle last year, the
Patriots had to literally beg him to get surgery, which is why it
took him eight days to get to a hospital. They tried to cover it up
by saying he went to Columbus, Ohio, for a second opinion, when in
fact he was in his house here, refusing to come out. The team had
to send two employees to his house to tell him that if he didn't
get to the hospital for surgery, he was going to be fined $10,000 a
day. Those seemed to be the magic words, and suddenly surgery
seemed to be the right thing to do . . . If all of the people who
admired him as a player are on hand, the May 26 tribute to Bill
Russell, the greatest Celtic, will fill the building. If all of the
people he treated well while he played here attend, they could hold
it in a phone booth. This is why the people behind the gala
fund-raising event know they have to hit Boston businesses big to
make this work. It would be mighty embarrassing, with the
tremendous guest list headed by Bill Cosby, to have a couple of
thousand people sitting in a 20,000-seat arena . . . Quiz: Free
agency in baseball started in 1976. Since that time, the Yankees
have the best record in the major leagues, at 1,993-1,604. Who has
the second best?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a good yarn Fox Sports turned out the other night that
Michael Jordan was going to buy and play for Charlotte. Only one
thing wrong with that scenario: There's a league rule that says a
player cannot own any part of a team; he has to divest himself of
any ownership before he's allowed to play. Jordan has talked twice
with Hornets owner George Shinn, who is not popular in Charlotte at
the moment. He is willing to sell half of his stake in the team to
Jordan because he wants to get a new arena built, and he feels they
will do it for Jordan but not him. If Jordan buys a piece of the
Hornets, he will run the team. But don't look for Phil Jackson to
join him, either. Word in the league is that Jackson next year will
end up with either the Knicks or the Lakers, where he can make big
bucks. There aren't big bucks for coaches in Charlotte. Dave Cowens
just got out of coaching there because he was the lowest-paid coach
in the league . . . The NFL has sent a letter to all teams to get
ready for Y2K possibilities at the turn of the century. The league
schedule has final regular-season games being played Jan. 2. The
visiting teams, which usually arrive 24 hours before the game, are
being told to travel two days before the game, to avoid any
possible problems with airline travel. Also, teams are being told
to make sure they have backup systems ready at the stadiums for any
emergency situation. The Patriots are at home against Baltimore
that weekend . . . Quiz answer: The Boston Red Sox, with a record
of 1,911 and 1,691.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
