<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox acquires newsletters business
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cox Newspapers announced Friday it had bought a
leading producer of customized newsletters for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The company, CustomMedia, is based in Greenville, S.C., and was
founded by brothers Todd and Shane Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal were not disclosed. The Taylor
brothers will continue to run the business out of Greenville, said
company officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``CustomMedia fits right into our strategy of growing our
company through businesses that fit with our tradition of gathering
and publishing information,'' said Jay Smith, Cox Newspapers'
president.
</P>
<P>
   CustomMedia produces more than 4,600 different newsletters
monthly. Its customers are largely the owners of apartment
buildings, including 50 of the largest. Apartment building owners
circulate CustomMedia's newsletters to their tenants. In total, the
newsletters have a readership of more than 3 million, according to
the company.
</P>
<P>
   While remaining independent, CustomMedia will be studied by Cox
Newspapers to see how its business can be improved and expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to look at things we could do better,'' says
Brian Cooper, a senior vice president at Cox Newspapers. He said
that, for example, perhaps advertising could be added to
CustomMedia's newsletters.
</P>
<P>
   ``CustomMedia serves a market desirable to both newspapers and
cable operators,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers is a unit of Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises Inc.,
which also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
