<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good samaritan calls 5-year-old's rescue `a miracle'
 &HT;    By Jim Dyer and Will Anderson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the 5-year-old girl tottered down the wooded bluff
toward Malecio Heredia, the stranded trucker stepped away from his
rig and strained his eyes in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was slowly coming into focus as the sun dipped in the
western sky on the late afternoon of March 19. Heredia walked
closer to the rutted, red clay road near the Cobb County landfill
and started to feel queasy.
</P>
<P>
   The girl descended the hill _ gingerly placing her bare feet on
the rocks _ and Heredia noticed that the white and red warm-up suit
he thought she had on was really her thin, pale, naked body spotted
with blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dios mio,'' the 25-year-old Hispanic man muttered to himself.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny, blonde haired girl _ barely older than his own
daughter _ nervously looked over her shoulders, as if whatever she
was fleeing was still up on the bluff.
</P>
<P>
   Her curly locks were matted and disheveled and hung down over
her bloodshot eyes. Her body was covered with small cuts as if she
had just run through thorn bushes. She was bleeding heavily between
her legs.
</P>
<P>
   Her lips were so frothy and bluish-black from having been choked
unconscious that she had difficulty articulating her words. Yet for
Heredia, there was no need for her to say anything. He knew what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   The few English words that the native El Salvadoran picked up
from her mumbling corroborated his suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man ... a gun ... my bicycle,'' she said, again looking up
the bluff as if her assailant were right behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Heredia looked up the bluff, too, and then began to fear for his
own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK,'' he said, struggling to find English words to
comfort her. ``Nothing can happen now.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he grabbed his jacket from the truck to cover her, he
kept checking the surrounding woods.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the roads to get stuck on, he thought to himself. It
wasn't fair. He was a simple man hauling pipe to a construction
site and now he was going to get killed by some armed child
molester.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, Cobb County police would say that Heredia was
definitely in the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   How he and the young girl met on a lonely dirt road near Jim R.
Miller Park is a story of bizarre coincidences and a heinous act
from a man whom experts believe is local and may strike again.
Moreover, it's a tale of a simple trucker's faith in God and his
steadfast belief in divine intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Before that Friday, children played freely in the Wynforest
Apartments, a cluster of nine brick buildings just south of
Marietta, a suburb of Atlanta. Young boys and girls grabbed their
toys and played on the grass or rode their bicycles up and down the
sidewalks and through the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're close. You may not know everyone's name, but you know
them by sight,'' said Steve Bracken, a 39-year-old single man who's
been living in the complex for the past year. ``Nobody thought
something like this would happen to that little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who neighbors described as intelligent, friendly and
energetic, was pedaling her bicycle around the parking lot in front
of her apartment about 4 p.m. when a young white man in his late
teens or early twenties pulled up in a sports utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother had been outside with her and her younger
sister, but took the younger girl inside for just a moment,
neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you help me find a man?'' the stranger asked the girl on
the bike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know a man,'' the girl remembered answering.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next is sketchy, police say. Somehow, the man
coaxed the girl into his car and quickly drove off. Her mother
returned to find her daughter's bicycle on the ground less than 40
feet from the family's door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only took a couple of seconds,'' Bracken said. ``It's
amazing no one saw it happen. That guy really had (guts) to come in
here in broad daylight when any one could have seen him.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the car, the girl noticed a dark handgun beside the man's
leg and became nervous. As he drove west toward Jim R. Miller Park
and the landfill, he told her to take off her clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The girl remembered getting out of the vehicle in a remote
location near a trash can and being led into some woods. There,
police said, the man choked her unconscious and sexually assaulted
her.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, she regained consciousness and found herself
buried underneath logs, branches and leaves. After pushing the
debris off of herself, she headed south down a lonely dirt road on
a bluff that ran underneath a series of massive steel power lines.
</P>
<P>
   She walked south along the road, trying to escape from the man
who attacked her. Down below the bluff, a man stood next to a truck
stuck in the mud.
</P>
<P>
   Malesio Heredia's vanilla-colored jacket looked gray against the
girl's pale naked body, but he could sense it made her feel safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK,'' he kept repeating to her while he helped her into
the front seat of his truck. ``Nothing happen now.''
</P>
<P>
   But his feigned bravado was coupled with real anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   The girl kept looking back up the hill and making him nervous.
Somewhere out in the woods, deep inside the cluster of dirt roads
and rocky gulches that crisscross the landfill, Heredia was sure
the girl's assailant was lurking. The Hispanic trucker had to get
help and reached for his business radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have problem. Hurry. Come here right away,'' he called in to
his supervisor. ``Lost girl. Something happen to her.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew he wasn't conveying the seriousness of what had
occurred, nor the danger he felt. He tried to slow down, but he was
too nervous. No matter how hard he tried, he couldn't think of the
English equivalent of violar: to rape.
</P>
<P>
   He cast a reassuring look at the girl and then nervously peered
out into the woods for any sign of her attacker. He wondered if the
man was the same person who entered his rig an hour earlier while
he walked a mile to a restaurant to call for help. He returned to
find his duffel bag gone and fresh tire tracks running alongside
his rig.
</P>
<P>
   He wondered if the man had unsuccessfully tried to kill the girl
and asked himself, ``Is he watching us now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please,'' Heredia yelled back into the microphone, ``come
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few minutes, the waiting became too much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on,'' he told the girl and gently helped her out of his
rig.
</P>
<P>
   The short walk south to Callaway Road seemed to last an
eternity. Heredia thought about his wife and his 3-year-old girl at
home. Then he looked at the girl at his side and envisioned how
much emotional pain she would have to endure for the rest of her
life.
</P>
<P>
   The two reached the road just as police arrived. Heredia smiled
in relief. He felt like a life-saver, a quasi-hero who could relish
that both he and the girl had survived.
</P>
<P>
   But his jubilation was short lived. There was a great deal of
commotion and he was immediately separated from the girl. Within a
few seconds he went from being a hero to being the main suspect in
the girl's assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a white man,'' the girl told police seconds after
Heredia delivered her to them.
</P>
<P>
   But the strange circumstances, the almost freak coincidences
that brought the Hispanic trucker to that lonely dirt road and kept
him there for eight hours were too bizarre to believe. Police
impounded his truck and interrogated him until late that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to make sure he wasn't connected someway in the
crime,'' Officer Dana Pierce later said. ``He was in the wrong
place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Heredia sees the events leading up to his meeting with the
girl differently.
</P>
<P>
   The gates to the landfill were meant to be closed, he suggests.
He was supposed to look for a back entrance and find that dirt
road. His truck was supposed to get stuck in that exact location
and he was supposed to wait for eight hours for a tow truck that
would never come.
</P>
<P>
   ``God sent me there,'' the deeply religious man said. ``There's
no other reason I'd be stuck back there that long. It's really a
miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   After the girl's assault, Cobb County police were in full
throttle, scouring through the woods surrounding the landfill
searching for evidence. They interviewed friends, family and
neighbors of the 5-year-old victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police really made their presence known,'' said Bracken,
who is close friends with her parents. ``You could tell they really
hated what happened to her and wanted to catch this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   With the girl's assistance, an artist made a composite drawing
of the suspect, but because of her age, investigators are not
convinced the sketch is accurate. Detectives checked out similar
crimes in metro Atlanta and Georgia, but found none that appear to
be connected.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives have also used information from the statewide sex
offender registry in their search for a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Although Interstate 75 is less than five miles away from the
girl's home _ a fact that may point to a transient criminal from
another area _ police believe the man is familiar with the area and
may live in the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's somebody local,'' said Cmdr. Robert Hulsey, who
heads Cobb County's crimes against persons unit.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is because the man drove his young victim to a
remote, wooded area near the landfill, where ruts in the road make
driving difficult for most cars, except four-wheel-drive trucks and
sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Because violent stranger-on-stranger crimes against children are
so rare _ there's typically less than 200 a year nationwide _
police have contacted the FBI to help them profile the man.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in behavioral sciences and criminology disagree over the
suspect's motives and on whether his ultimate goal was homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Emilio Viano, a professor of criminology at American University
in Washington D.C., doesn't believe the man's goal was to kill the
girl.
</P>
<P>
   The elements of the crime point to a man whose fantasy is to
asphyxiate his victims while sexually assaulting them, Viano
contended. Such deviant sexual behavior _ often portrayed in
pornographic ``snuff films'' _ is not as rare as the general public
thinks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had intended to kill the child he may have used a tool,
a belt, cord, to strangle her permanently,'' he said. ``To me, that
she survived and only passed out, he wasn't paying close attention
to whether she was alive or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Patricia Kirby, a former FBI profiler and current
professor of sociology/criminology in Maryland, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   That the man covered the girl's body up shows he was convinced
she was dead and was disposing of the body, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other elements of the crime point toward a more seasoned serial
rapist/murderer who knew the area and carefully planned out his
actions, she said. The fact that he abducted the girl in broad
daylight from a relatively crowded apartment complex and used a
sports utility vehicle to reach the remote area suggests a well
thought-out plan, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not his first or last crime. It simply went too
smoothly to be his first time,'' she said. Kirby agreed with Cobb
County investigators that the man is probably local, but said he
may have left the area if he felt in danger of being apprehended.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is very dangerous,'' she warned. ``It's not going to
stop with this child.''
</P>
<P>
   All throughout Marietta and especially at the Wynforest
apartments, communities are making sure to watch out for suspicious
strangers and warning their children about the dangers of
approaching unknown people and cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is really looking out for each other,'' said Sandra
Griffin, who lives at Wynforest. ``When somebody comes in here who
doesn't belong, we get rid of them now.''
</P>
<P>
   The abducted girl has been released from the hospital and is
back at school.
</P>
<P>
   ``She still has spunk,'' Bracken said. ``At first, even though
she smiled, there was a sadness behind her eyes. But that's gone
now. She's doing all right. Her family has really pulled together
to make sure she comes out of this OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Ardery, an Emory University student, contributed to the
reporting of this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
