</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUCCO03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interest in concrete product building
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The residential market for synthetic stucco washed out
like a broken dam two years ago after consumers complained about
moisture intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   But before you could say ``plug the hole,'' a spate of
alternative products began filling it up. Their manufacturers have
been trying hard to sell metro Atlanta builders on other ways to
have the look and insulation qualities of stucco.
</P>
<P>
   None of the alternative products is new. Most have been staples
outside the United States for years, and all claim to offer
homeowners more for their money.
</P>
<P>
   These newcomers are willing to spend money _ lots of it _ to
grab a foothold in metro Atlanta, one of the nation's most
lucrative housing markets. Guess ``millions,'' and you won't be far
off the mark, says Richard Martin, who teaches construction systems
at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very unclear, because none of them is really willing to
release cost information,'' he said, explaining that besides
manufacturing and marketing costs, money is spent to get the
product to conform to Georgia building codes.
</P>
<P>
   Hebel AG, a German firm whose concrete-based product has been
used since the 1950s in residential and commercial projects
worldwide, is one of them. The self-insulating material is
fireproof, impervious to insects and all but soundproof. It will
not warp or rot. Lightweight and able to be nailed or cut with a
saw, the blocks and panels are used to frame a house. An exterior
finish _ such as synthetic stucco, stone or other veneer _ is then
applied.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company had to face two issues when it entered the
American market. One was the tremendous cost _ $30 million by some
estimates _ of building its facility in Adel to manufacture the
product, a system of autoclaved, aerated concrete blocks and
panels. Then, getting the product code-approved nationally involved
a three-year process costing more than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The other factor was builder resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came into this market with tremendous common sense,''
said Martin. ``You give them your drawings, they engineer the
system for you, and you go build it. But (in the United States) you
run up against our contractor process. ... The contractor is stuck
with the risk, and he is not about to try anything new.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hebel system replaces many of the materials, such as
insulation and wood framing, used in a typical house. It is also
more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   West Cobb County builder Glenn Miller paid about 8 percent more
than traditional framing for his own 2,700-square-foot house in
Macland Forest. At the same time, he was able to use less
insulation, drop the size of his heating/air conditioning system,
improve his fire insurance rating and cut maintenance costs.
</P>
<P>
   Hebel offers other benefits to owners with different concerns.
</P>
<P>
   One house, being built deep in the mountains to withstand a
feared Y2K Armageddon, was even tested to see if it was
bulletproof. It was, said Holli Clark, vice president of CLF
Contractors, which installs Hebel.
</P>
<P>
   Any consumer using these new products ultimately gets more for
the money, said Bill Olsen, president of Elite Cement Products,
which makes cementitious exterior coatings as well as tile grouts
and various mortars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hebel is far superior to any kind of wood or EIFS system,'' he
said. ``You have an 8-inch-thick wall as opposed to a 3 1/2-inch
wall. You have a more durable product, and no one in the industry
would question that. They would question the speed of erection and
the cost. If it were cheaper than wood, it would have the market,
no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another company seeking market share is Sider-Oxydro, a
30-year-old French firm whose only American plant is in
Hawkinsville, Ga. It makes an exterior finish product that is hosed
or troweled onto a house. The patented mixture of portland cement,
crystallized cellulose fibers and chemical additives is a one-coat
finish.
</P>
<P>
   According to marketing director Ivan Burgand, it is 3 percent
cheaper than brick. Local distributor Chris Lee added that is $1.50
to $2 per square foot less than the new EIFS, which costs about $7
per square foot. It is being positioned as an environmentally
friendly, next-generation product. This company, too, has had to
think out of the box to bring its product to the public's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent our money on trying to get builders to think
differently,'' said Chris Boyett, marketing manager for
Sider-Oxydro. ``We have probably spent $250,000 for advertising, a
Web site and brochures. We sat down with manufacturers ... and with
various installation groups, specifiers and architects.''
</P>
<P>
   But why is it so hard to court builders?
</P>
<P>
   ``Go look at the aqueducts in Italy. Think how little
construction has changed (since Roman times). It is a conservative
industry, driven by trying to control risks. . . . You have a
built-in propensity to resist change,'' observed Herman Oellerich,
chief operating officer of Hebel. ``You have an inordinate amount
of marketing overhead before you get accepted in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   To increase the number of Hebel houses in the Southeast from 600
estimated now to 60,000, the company is spending $450,000 for
advertising alone this year. It is holding frequent get-acquainted
workshops for consumers and contractors, hiring and training field
installation supervisors, and calling on custom builders like David
Chatham.
</P>
<P>
   Chatham, president of Chatham Holdings, one of Atlanta's oldest
and best-known builders, used Hebel to construct the 1995 Southern
Living Home Show model home.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie and Connie Saunders, owners of Custom Design Builders,
built a Hebel house in Bradshaw Farm in Cherokee County in 1997.
They have since used the product twice on high-end homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like it, our subcontractors adapted to it well, and we know
that the more we use it, the more price-effective it will be,''
said Connie Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   But even with parts of the industry becoming attentive to Hebel,
it will take awhile to break even. Oellerich guesses a decade.
</P>
<P>
   He cites manufacturing costs and sophisticated equipment, the
money and time related to having the product tested for compliance
with the building codes, efforts to market it to consumers but _
most of all _ achieving builder acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want,'' said Hebel Marketing Manager Mike Sweeney,
``is for Mr. and Mrs. Smith to walk into Chatham's model or
Wieland's model and say, `We love the layout of this house. Can we
build it with an Hebel system?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
