<HEADER>
A4273 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-BOS &LR;      04-02 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER OUTLASTS BRITISH OPPONENT HENMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, England _ Jim Courier is off the floor and rising,
arms flapping, as though he's trying to fly to the moon, or at
least chin himself on a girder far above the slate blue hard court.
However, gravity wins _ as he has just done _ and Jim comes back to
earth. Not mentally, though. He's still way up high, riding the
kind of victory that has been mostly out of reach in the years of
tumbling from global No. 1 to his present proletarian 54.
</P>
<P>
   This brilliant long-distance, greasy-grinder triumph over No. 7,
homeboy Tim Henman, had slithered through Courier's greedy fingers
four times. It appeared to be gone for good as their gripping Davis
Cup battle edged toward a fifth hour _ but Courier, with shots that
flamed like his hair, refused to let it go: 7-6 (7-2), 2-6, 7-6
(7-3), 6-7 (10-12), 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Five suspenseful, extremely high-quality sets, twisting and
turning like a Sherlock Holmes mystery by onetime Birmingham
resident Arthur Conan Doyle. Finally Courier got his man, although
it was anything but elementary.
</P>
<P>
   Enspirited by Courier's refusal, Todd Martin came on as cleanup
man for the United States Friday to mop Greg Rusedski even more
roughly, 6-4, 6-4, 6-2. Considered used-up goods until Pete Sampras
and Andre Agassi gave the team a pass, Courier and Martin posted an
astounding 2-0 US lead over Great Britain in the best-of-five
series, 1 point from the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over,'' cautioned US captain Tom Gullikson, recalling
1994 and a 2-0 lead blown at Sweden, Martin losing the decisive
fifth match to Magnus Larsson. Doubles Saturday (Henman-Rusedski
against Courier-Alex O'Brien) is followed by Sunday's reverse
singles.
</P>
<P>
   Condition bonkers. That was the atmosphere within The National
Indoor Arena, stuffed with 9,320 ravers (virtually all of them
British loyalists), awash in Union Jacks, Crosses of St. George,
and patriotic trumpeting and stomping as Courier hung on the
fifth-set ropes, 3-3, 0-30. His last, best opportunity seemed
dissipated when Henman muscled up and served out of two break
points (15-40) in the previous game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 0-30, Courier needed a point badly. He got it with one
of his patented backside-boogie forehands, sliding to his left to
deliver an inside-out ripper diagonally past Henman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a must,'' he remembers the shot that turned the match
and the day the way of the US. Three more points were his quickly.
Though Henman, the nifty, free-flowing 24-year-old shotmaker who
has lifted Great Britain from the tennis junkyard, would keep
serving tough to 5-5, Courier was feeling ``reassured'' by his
seventh game escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was serving big myself, and getting really pumped,'' he
said. ``I was thinking how much I was enjoying this, relishing
being part of such a great match _ win or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly it was over _ in a blink and a blitz of the last 8
points. Courier banged an ace, a service winner and swiftly was at
5-4. He swatted a forehand passer, and Henman double faulted for a
16th time, 0-30.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses of th 4-hour-12-minute extravaganza would agree with
Courier: ``A match I'll remember for 50 years _ the kind of match
that keeps an old guy (28) like me playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman feels similarly, ``But the memory will be greater for
him. I learned something about Davis Cup that I never understood
before. It's a new level, new intensity. This loss hurts worse than
my Wimbledon semifinal (to Pete Sampras) last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier reached back to his No. 1 year to sip some vintage '92,
and toast himself with a balanced blend of shotmaking. ``I've
screwed up some matches like this, but I've been here before.
That's important. I know how to stick in _ and today I had the
shots to go with it'' _ and fewer errors, 40-66.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, ranked No. 8 but a team man to the core, had skipped the
Lipton to rest himself and strained abdominal muscles for this
test. ``This is more important to me than any tournament. I had to
wait a long time for Jim to finish, but that was good. The more
anxious I get the better I play.''
</P>
<P>
   Theirs was largely serve-and-volley stuff, brief points, Martin
jumping on the No. 11 lefty immediately to break, and keeping
fierce-serving Rusedski down and distraught with consistent,
unnerving returns.
</P>
<P>
   He had seen that closing forehand of Courier's on the dressing
room TV _ ``It gave me a boost.''
</P>
<P>
   It made Courier airborne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
