<HEADER>
A4274 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELISSA-VIRUS-NYT &LR;      04-02 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELISSA-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.) 
N.J. SOFTWARE PROGRAMMER ARRESTED, CHARGED WITH LAUNCHING MELISSA
VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ After a global search for the author of the
fastest-spreading computer virus in history, investigators in New
Jersey arrested a 30-year-old software programmer Thursday night
and charged him with writing and launching the now-famous Melissa
virus.
</P>
<P>
   The programmer, David L. Smith, 30, was taken into custody after
FBI agents and officials from America Online helped investigators
from the New Jersey attorney general's office hone in on the
Internet access provider that was apparently first used to send the
virus, which has now infected more than 100,000 computers
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators then spent three days sorting through thousands of
customers' files and electronic transmissions from the provider,
Monmouth Internet Corp. of Red Bank, N.J., and determined that the
telephone line used to send the first copy of the Melissa virus was
wired into Smith's apartment in Aberdeen Township, according to
Attorney General Peter J. Verniero.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 26, when the virus was first uploaded to the
Internet newsgroup alt.sex from a stolen America Online account,
the Melissa virus spread like a malignant chain letter, invading
computer users' e-mail programs and sending itself to as many as 50
correspondents in each user's e-mail address book.
</P>
<P>
   Although Melissa was not as destructive as other viruses that
can destroy files or corrupt hard drives, technology experts say it
is an ominous threat to Internet commerce because it used a new,
and particularly efficient, method of transmission to replicate at
an extraordinarily rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that in the near future, viruses could spread
around the globe in a matter of an hour or two, and if it's a
destructive virus, do incredible amounts of damage,'' said Steve R.
White, senior manager of anti-virus research at IBM's Watson
Research Center in Hawthorne, N.Y. ``It's going to demand an entire
new way of combating them, new approaches and new technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Smith, who apparently named the virus after a
topless dancer in Florida, was a programmer for a software company
that writes code for AT&AMP;T, but they would not identify the company.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and acquaintances described him as a prototypical
computer zealot, a man who lived with his two cats and whose social
life seemed to revolve around the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Trautmann, who lives one floor below Smith in the Ken Garden
apartment complex in Aberdeen, said he rarely ventured out of his
apartment or spoke to neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very solitary person; he was a quiet neighbor,'' said
Ms. Trautmann, a quality assurance specialist at a software
company. ``I'd hear his modem go off once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The only person at the Ken Garden apartment complex Friday who
could recall conversing with Smith was a technician from the
Cablevision company, who three weeks ago asked him if he'd like
cable television installed in his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fellow said, `No, I'm always on my computer,''' said the
technician, who identified himself only as John.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who was arrested at his brother's apartment in Eatontown,
N.J., was charged with interruption of public communication, theft
of computer services and wrongful access to computer systems. He
was released on $100,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Distributing a computer virus is also a federal crime, but
Verniero said he doubted federal charges would be necessary because
the New Jersey statutes provided for a possible $480,000 fine and a
maximum prison sentence of 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's convicted, he will do hard time, ''Verniero said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smith was also charged with conspiracy to interrupt
public communication, Verniero would not say whether officials were
looking for other suspects. Some private anti-virus experts said
the so-called ``digital fingerprints'' on the code embedded in the
virus indicated there were at least two programmers involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Melissa virus was embedded into an e-mail attachment, and
designed to exploit a feature of the Microsoft Outlook e-mail
program, so that each time the infected document was opened, it
automatically sent itself out to as many as 50 other people.
Technology experts fear that other high tech saboteurs may use
similar techniques, known as worm programs, to transmit more
harmful viruses in the future, at speeds which far outpace the
current ability to prevent, detect or disable them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
