<HEADLINE>
IN THE STAMPEDE TO BIG STOCKS, SOME MANAGERS ARE LEFT BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (bl)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite some sharp ups and downs, the bull market in
large-capitalization stocks plowed forward through the first
quarter, confounding some money managers and rewarding others.
</P>
<P>
   The story was no different for the five managers who have built
hypothetical retirement portfolios for The New York Times: None of
their portfolios lost money in the quarter, but only three beat the
average return of 0.96 percent for diversified domestic equity
funds, as tracked by Lipper Inc. In comparison, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index of large companies gained 4.65 percent in
the period.
</P>
<P>
   The winner for the quarter, with a return of 4.56 percent, was
Sheldon Jacobs, editor of the No-Load Fund Investor in Irvington,
N.Y. Jacobs' portfolio was helped by hefty stakes in
large-capitalization stocks, and he expects more strong market
gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipate that the bull market will continue through the
second quarter,'' Jacobs said, because the factors propelling it _
low inflation, low interest rates and a strong economy _ are still
in place. ``I don't think that we have seen the highs for the Dow
this year,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Half of Jacobs' portfolio is invested in two funds: the Vanguard
500 Index, which mimics the performance of the S&AMP;P 500, and
Vanguard Total Stock Market Index, which has much broader holdings.
The portfolio also includes Vanguard Windsor II, a large-cap value
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs plans no changes to the portfolio, despite relatively
poor showings by some of his international stock funds. ``It's a
long-term commitment, so for a minor drawdown it's not worth doing
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The market bias toward large-cap stocks continues to hold back
managers with more diversified portfolios, including Harold
Evensky, a financial adviser in Coral Gables, Fla. Evensky took
fourth place in the quarter, with a portfolio gain of 0.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He remains a firm believer in asset allocation, although he said
that during the quarter, a sobering market adage from John Maynard
Keynes came to mind: Markets can remain irrational longer than you
can remain solvent.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Evensky also plans no changes to his portfolio.
``While value and small-cap stocks continue to buck history and
significantly underperform the handful of lottery winners driving
the S&AMP;P 500, I continue to believe in long-term investing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the hypothetical portfolios is tracked each
quarter by Lipper, which is based in Summit, N.J. It excludes sales
charges, transaction costs and taxes, because most retirement money
is held in tax-deferred accounts. The five managers can choose any
funds open to new investors and can shift money quarterly. At the
outset of the competition, in July 1993, they were asked to pick
portfolios intended to grow for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs remains the overall leader, with a gain of 140.15 percent
since the contest began. In that time, the five portfolios have
risen an average 111.99 percent, compared with a 227.71 percent
return for the Vanguard 500 Index fund.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Kobren, president of Kobren Insight Group and editor of
Fidelity Insight in Wellesley, Mass., took second place in the
quarter, with a gain of 3.11 percent. He was hurt by a 15 percent
position in Fidelity Small Cap Stock as well as a 25 percent
position in Fidelity Spartan government Income, which fell as the
stock market rose to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   Kobren, whose portfolio is made up entirely of Fidelity funds,
said that he felt uncomfortable investing only in equities with the
market at such high valuations. But given the portfolio's long-term
objective, combined with the economy's surprisingly strong showing,
an all-stock portfolio seems in order, he said. So he is selling
his bond position and buying a 20 percent stake in Fidelity Value,
which he said could be a big winner if the market broadens,
reflecting a modestly stronger-than-expected economy, better
prospects among industrial companies and the recovery of
beaten-down value stocks.
</P>
<P>
   He is also adding 5 percent to his position in Fidelity
Contrafund II; he said a quarter of that growth fund was invested
in technology, a modest level compared with some of its most
aggressive peers.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Brill, a San Diego investment adviser who advocates
``socially responsible'' investing, took third place for the first
quarter, with a gain of 2.64 percent. The return was bolstered by
big holdings in large-cap stock funds, including Domini Social
Equity, an index fund that is considered a socially responsible
proxy for the S.&AMP; P. 500.
</P>
<P>
   This quarter, he is replacing Calvert Capital Accumulation, a
mid-cap growth fund, with IPS Millennium, a growth-and-income fund.
He described the IPS Millennium fund manager, Robert Loest, as a
``New Age economist'' who uses a model called ``evolutionary
ecosystems mechanics'' to evaluate how changes in technology and
society affect the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Brill said the fund was not as widely screened for socially
responsible investments as others in his portfolio; its major focus
is on animal rights. IPS does not invest in poultry or fertilizer
companies, for example, because of environmental concerns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In last place for the quarter was Susan Dziubinski, who edits
the Morningstar Fund Investor. Her portfolio gained just 0.35
percent, hurt by its very limited exposure to large-cap stocks.
TIAA-CREF Growth and Income, her sole large-cap fund, which she
added in the last quarter, beat the S.&AMP; P. 500 by gaining 6.18
percent. But that was more than offset by holdings in small-cap
stock funds like Skyline Special Equities, which fell 11.83
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dziubinski, however, plans no changes to her portfolio,
which remains mostly entrenched in funds that buy small- and
mid-cap stocks. She expects the high valuation of the large caps to
take its toll eventually. ``I just can't justify putting money into
big stocks when the S&AMP;P 500's trailing price-earnings ratio stands
near 35,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
