u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      04-02 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDOUGAL WITNESS DESCRIBES PRESSURE FROM PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark.)  (js) 
 By STEVE BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Two parts of the wide-ranging investigation
of President Clinton converged here Friday, when a woman testified
in behalf of a former business partner of the president and Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Hiatt Steele of Richmond, Va., who says she was indicted
on charges of obstruction of justice and making false statements
after refusing to lie to a grand jury, was the final defense
witness for Susan McDougal, the former business partner of the
Clintons who says she was pressured to lie to another grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal's repeated refusal to cooperate with Kenneth
Starr's inquiry into the Clintons' personal and political finances
has resulted in her trial here for contempt of court and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele testified Friday that she believed she could have
avoided legal difficulty had she falsely corroborated the
accusations of Kathleen Willey, a former White House volunteer who
has said she was sexually harassed by Clinton in the Oval Office in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele said she had no knowledge of any such encounter but
initially supported Ms. Willey's account, at her request, in a
magazine interview. Subsequently summoned before a grand jury,
however, she disavowed her earlier statements despite what she
described as coaxing by Starr's prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said to me, `Couldn't it be this? Couldn't it be that?'''
Ms. Steele recalled, testifying that she was convinced she could
have avoided indictment by tailoring her grand jury testimony to
the prosecutors' liking. ``But it wouldn't have been the truth,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Willey's accusations were taken up by Starr in his
investigation of alleged efforts by Clinton to interfere with
attorneys for Paula Jones, the former Arkansas state employee whose
sexual harassment case against the president was settled last
November.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele's testimony was the latest twist in a trial that has
veered from the simple facts of Ms. McDougal's admitted, repeated
refusal to cooperate with a Virginia grand jury to a lengthy
examination of her motives for doing so. The defendant has insisted
that she feared a perjury indictment by Starr had she testified
before the grand jury without accusing the president or Mrs.
Clinton. In return, Ms. McDougal testified, the prosecutors
promised lenient treatment for her 1996 fraud conviction in the
Whitewater trial.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have sought to convince the jury not only that Ms.
McDougal's anxieties were contrived, but that she had information
relevant to the investigation unobtainable by any means other than
her cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr. has allowed Ms.
McDougal's attorney, Mark J. Geragos, to attempt to develop
``prosecutorial misconduct'' as a defense.
</P>
<P>
   That approach revealed, at one point in the trial, that a senior
aide to Starr had drafted an indictment naming Hillary Clinton even
without Ms. McDougal's testimony. And an FBI accountant assigned to
Starr conceded that no physical evidence could be found to tie the
president to improper transactions that are the core of the
Whitewater investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele was the latest in a series of defense witnesses to
complain that Starr's staff relied on heavy-handed tactics. She
testified Friday that federal agents assigned to Starr questioned
her adoption of a Romanian orphan, interviewed many of her friends
and relatives, including her daughter, and subpoenaed documents
from her accountant.
</P>
<P>
   Under vigorous cross-examination by Associate Independent
Counsel Julie L. Myers, Ms. Steele acknowledged receiving $12,000
for selling a photograph of Clinton, Ms. Willey and a third person
to three publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you proud of selling the picture,'' Ms. Myers asked
pointedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. I was ashamed,'' Ms. Steele replied.
</P>
<P>
   With equal firmness, Ms. Steele denied having expressed fears of
reprisal from the White House had she not changed her story before
the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of the White House or anyone connected with
them,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
