u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-525&AMP;A     04-02 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MUST CONSIDER TAKING SOME KOSOVO REFUGEES, WHITE HOUSE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-WEATHER, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-MCCAIN.) 
(mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senior Clinton administration officials say the
United States will have to consider accepting some of the hundreds
of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees who have fled Kosovo in
recent days, if only to encourage reluctant European nations to do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most conservative figures released by relief
organizations describe nothing short of a disaster along Kosovo's
borders, with the U.N. High Commission for Refugees estimating that
more than 79,000 refugees poured into Macedonia, Albania and
Montenegro on Thursday alone.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said Friday that it had received ``chilling
reports'' that an additional 200,000 people were being held in the
vicinity of the train station in Pristina, the provincial capital
of Kosovo, in preparation for a forced evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has demanded that the refugees be allowed to
return to their homes immediately and that President Slobodan
Milosevic abandon his brutal policy of ethnic cleansing in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that what Milosevic wants to do is to keep
the land of Kosovo and rid it of its people,'' President Clinton
said Friday. ``We cannot let that happen with impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials say they must plan for the
likelihood that most of the Kosovo Albanians will not be able to
return home anytime soon, and that they may remain wards of the
United States and its European allies indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Relief organizations in the United States said Friday that they
were pressuring the White House to make a public statement soon
raising the possibility that some of the refugees now crowding
along Kosovo's borders would be accepted into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The statement is needed, they said, to blunt the possibility
that other European nations would follow the lead of Germany, which
suggested Thursday that it was unwilling to offer asylum to any of
the Kosovo Albanians. The German deputy foreign minister said the
refugees should remain in the Balkans and not resettle in any part
of ``Western or Northern'' Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. has traditionally offered refuge, and we have the
resources to offer refuge,'' said Robert Carey, vice president of
resettlement for the International Rescue Committee in New York.
``We have to say that this is at least being considered by the U.S.
Whether we like it or not, the United States sets an example that
is followed by other nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials say an announcement that the
United States was willing to accept some of the refugees streaming
out of Kosovo would be premature and that the administration does
not want to undermine its central message to Milosevic: that the
refugees must be allowed to return home immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they said a plan to resettle at least some of the
refugees in the United States _ and much larger numbers in Western
Europe _ would have to be considered seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question we're going to be asked, and it would be very
difficult for the United States to say you do this _ you take these
people in _ but we're not going to,'' said a State Department
official, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Congress has imposed a ceiling of 78,000 on the number of
refugees who can be admitted to the United States from all nations
this year. A spokeswoman for the Immigration and Naturalization
Service said that 25,000 of those slots, or about a third of the
total, had been set aside for refugees from the Balkans. Of that,
9,300 had been set aside for refugees from Yugoslavia and its
former republics.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Friday that while it would be
difficult to persuade Congress to raise the overall ceiling for
refugees, the administration could admit several thousand Kosovo
Albanians to the United States by cutting the number of refugees
admitted from other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department announced Friday that Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott would travel to the Balkans this weekend to
urge nations in the region to accept refugees arriving from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not trying to resettle these people but hold them
temporarily in the region,'' said James Rubin, the department
spokesman. ``We are obviously working in a variety of ways with all
the front-line states.'' Talbott, he said, would ``try to encourage
everybody to do their part.''
</P>
<P>
   The department said it was also urging the Justice Department to
allow Kosovars already in the United States to remain here for at
least another year under a program in which they are granted
so-called temporary protective status and allowed to work. They
have been eligible for asylum under the program since last June.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department said Friday that it was preparing to step
up humanitarian aid to Kosovo refugees, with an immediate shipment
of 500,000 prepackaged meals to Albanians, and with tents, blankets
and medicine to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced earlier this week that he had approved an
additional $50 million in emergency aid to the refugees, raising
the total humanitarian aid package for Kosovo this year to $150
million. More than 400,000 Kosovars had been displaced from their
homes even before the exodus that began late last month.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Schwartz, the director of humanitarian affairs for the
National Security Council, reminded reporters at the White House
Friday that ``while the pictures of the suffering in Kosovo have
dominated the media over the past nine days, the suffering _ and in
particular, the terrible and large-scale population displacements
due to the horrors perpetrated by the Serb forces _ have been under
way for over a year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
