<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONFLICT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SLAMS GOVERNMENT BUILDINGS IN BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO launched the first, dramatic assault Friday on
downtown Belgrade, as American missiles rocked key government
headquarters, including the Ministry of Defense and the Ministry of
Interior Affairs, the Serb police agency that has masterminded and
carried out much of the murderous rampage against ethnic Albanian
civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Huge fires engulfed the sprawling buildings after nighttime
blasts shook the Yugolsav capital, which has become a symbol of
contempt for the NATO siege against President Slobodan Milosevic's
campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' _ forced expulsions of ethnic
Albanians from the separatist Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   The missile attacks, aimed at ratcheting up pressure against the
defiant Milosevic by ripping apart the heart of his hometown, came
amid new reports by NATO and American intelligence sources of the
alliance's failure to thwart the continuing murders and evictions
of Kosavar civilians by marauding Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   The reports indicate Milosevic is close to achieving his goal of
ridding Kosovo of ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of
the province's 1.8 million population. When his objectives are
accomplished, Milosevic is expected to call for a new coalition
government in the province, forcing NATO to reconsider the bombing
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, facing increasing public criticism
over the deepening crisis in Kosovo, recently won approval for the
pinpoint strikes in central Belgrade over the objections of several
NATO members, notably Greece and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite-guided missiles, which can be launched by B-52
bombers or Navy vessels, struck not far from Milosevic's
presidential palace. NATO officials indicated more attacks are
expected during the weekend, as calls by the Vatican for an Easter
ceasefire were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're striking at targets he uses to control the forces
responsible for ethnic cleansing in Kosovo,'' said Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours before the missile strike, the Kosovo crisis
deteriorated on several critical fronts, as heavy clouds continued
to stymie much of NATO's attack plan, the Serb purge of Kosavar
civilians heightened desperation throughout the Balkans, and the
fate of three captive American soliders grew disturbingly
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a massive, 10-day aerial assault, frustrated NATO
officials said the Serbs remain undeterred in their violent
crackdown on Kosovo, which has driven an estimated 634,000 ethnic
Albanian civilians from their homes. Communities throughout the
province have turned into ``ghost towns,'' said NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 200,000 refugees have fled Kosovo since the NATO
campaign began March 24, and there were reports Friday that Serb
troops have herded an additional 20,000 civilians to a train
station in Pristina to be forcibly exiled.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, for the first time since the
airstrikes began, acknowledged it was not fully prepared for the
crisis. ``I don't think anyone could have foreseen the breadth of
this brutality,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Women, children and elderly men account for the overwhelming
majority of the refugees. NATO officials said they suspect that
military-aged ethnic Albanian men who have not been executed are
being imprisoned in stadiums or dressed in Serb uniforms and used
as human shields at military bases.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged an aggressive response to the burgeoning
humanitarian disaster in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But several other developments raised concern about the possible
need for NATO ground troops, including reports that Milosevic is
planning a military coup in the Yugolsav republic of Montenegro.
State Department spokesman James Rubin also said the Serb military
has largely dismantled the Kosovo Liberation Army, the only force
that had provided any ground resistance to Milosevic's alleged
campaign of ethnic cleansing and genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The news came amid growing criticism in Congress of the NATO
campaign and a new declaration by Clinton that the United States
remains fully committed to the current strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognized when we started that this air campaign would not
be a week-or-two operation,'' Clinton said at the White House. ``We
must be determined, we must be persistent, we must be patient if we
expect to see this mission through.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the possible use of ground troops, Clinton said, ``I
still believe that we have a good possibility of achieving our
mission with the means that we have deployed.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's assessment left open the door to a possible
ground war in Kosovo, even as administration officials coped with
the unsettling task of conceding they remain in the dark about
three Army soldiers who were captured by Serb troops near the
border between Kosovo and Macedonia. ``We know precious little,''
Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   A Yugoslav judge ordered the first phase of a criminal inquiry
involving the prisoners, amid reports that the soldiers could be
charged with ``waging aggression,'' which carries a 15-year prison
term.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration assailed the proceeding as a
``kangaroo court,'' and relayed a demand through Swedish diplomats
that Milosevic permit the Red Cross to visit the captives: Staff
Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher
Stone, 25 of Smiths Creek, Mich., and Specialist Steven Gonzales,
21, of Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic gave no response. And despite reports that the Serbs
would allow the soldiers to call their families, no calls were
received.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the Pentagon has yet to formally determine whether
the soldiers, part of a reconnaissance team, were abducted during a
peacekeeping mission in Macedonia and were patrolling in the Kosovo
war zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
