<SLUG> BC-HKC-NCAA-UMILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMILE, UNH A PERFECT FIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Dick Umile, traveling salesman. Traveling
apparel salesman, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, just doesn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   Not even close. No offense to the profession, but it's not Dick
Umile. No way.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Umile knew it. His family knew it. Undoubtedly the late Bob
Kullen, then the hockey coach at the University of New Hampshire,
knew it when he invited Umile to join his staff in Durham prior to
the 1988 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me, `What do you think I should do?' '' said Rose,
his wife since after their sophomore years at UNH. ``I said, `What
are you, nuts? This has been your dream forever, to go back to
coach at UNH. If you say no, you may never get the chance again.'
''
</P>
<P>
   He said yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I got back for real cheap money, let me tell you,'' Umile
was saying Friday after a ceremony to honor Hobey Baker Award
winner Jason Krog. ``But it was at UNH. The only way I would have
come back (to college hockey) was to UNH.''
</P>
<P>
   Umile, 50, played at Melrose (Mass.) High School and then at UNH
and was the head coach at Watertown High for 10 years before
joining Mike McShane as an assistant at Providence College. He left
Providence to take the job selling clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of my family, marriage, stuff like that,'' Umile said.
</P>
<P>
   To be home more. To have a more regular schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem like it was him, to not be doing hockey,'' said
Kristin Haggerty, 28 and the oldest of three Umile daughters.
``Hockey is just a part of him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday night, Katie Umile, 22, was in a bind. She was in
California and the UNH hockey team was in Worcester playing
Michigan for a spot in the NCAA Final Four in Anaheim. And Katie
couldn't find the game on television. Couldn't get a score. Didn't
know if her father and his team were headed west, or were done for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   So she called her grandmother, Gloria Umile, who was home in
Melrose watching on TV while the rest of the family was at the
game. Called from a restaurant. Collect.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was crying,'' Katie said. ``She could barely tell me what
had happened. Then she said they won and that everyone was
standing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Umile grandparents, Gloria, 76, and Jim, 80, are back East
now and Dick talked with them after UNH's win over Michigan State
Thursday night. Friday, Gloria Umile called.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called at 5:30 this morning,'' Kristin Umile said. ``She
just couldn't wait to talk to us. She's his biggest fan. She was
crying. She's always crying. And my grandfather is like the mayor
of UNH. He goes to all the games there. He knows everyone there. He
loves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Proud parents. Passionate parents.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Umile is nothing if not passionate. Passionate about
family. Friends. His teams. The sport. UNH.
</P>
<P>
   And tough. He can be more bite-your-head-off than sound bite.
He's tough and competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Gordie Clark, a teammate at UNH and now the director of player
personnel with the New York Islanders, recalls Umile popping his
shoulder back in on the Wildcat bench.
</P>
<P>
   Watch him on the bench, said Ralph Cox, the leading scorer in
UNH history and a part-time scout for the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Umile is absolutely one of the best coaches in hockey,''
he said. ``I think what he does that a lot of coaches miss is that
during the game he has a strong emotional commitment. As a player,
you recognize that. On the bench, you see him walk down and talk to
players before they go on or after they come off. A lot of coaches
do the Xs and Os during the week and then get emotionally attached
to the referee or something during the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Time was, when Umile was maybe too emotional on the bench and in
the locker room. Too wound up; his players too much on edge.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true of Shawn Walsh, Umile's most fierce rival and
the coach of the Maine team that UNH faces for a national
championship Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn used to be the same way,'' said Bruce Crowder, once an
assistant under Walsh at Maine and now the coach at Northeastern.
``I can remember going down on the bench to Shawn and saying,
`Shawn, you're starting to make me nervous and I've been in a few
games. How do you think these kids are feeling.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, UNH beat the Massachusetts one night at the
Whittemore Center in the first round of the Hockey East playoffs.
Late that night, when he sat down to watch the game on tape, Umile
suffered a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up smoking and a family tradition _ fried meatballs
_changed his other dietary habits, and took up the exercise bike.
And adjusted his approach a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's mellowed in the right ways,'' said Brian McCloskey, one
of Umile's assistants. ``He's learned that if the edge is off, it's
OK. He doesn't feel like he emotionally needs to drive the kids. He
lets the kids provide the emotion. I think the kids have picked up
on that. If you're unsettled on the bench, your kids will become
unsettled.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as anything, Umile feels, he has changed as he becomes
more experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Back when he returned to UNH, he and Kullen were going to try
and turn the program around. But Kullen, who had had a heart
transplant, was ill and died early in the 1990 season. Umile took
over as head coach. UNH, which had closed out the 1980s with five
straight losing seasons, has now been to the NCAA tournament five
times in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, UNH made it to the Final Four for the first time
since 1982. Saturday the Wildcats play in their first championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bit more under control,'' Umile said. ``I let the
guys play. When I first got in there I probably put a little bit
more heat on the guys. You're more demanding. Now, I try to let
them play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing that hasn't changed much is Umile's ability to fire up
the troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``He starts talking about UNH and UNH hockey and the pride of
wearing the shirt,'' McCloskey said. ``He's a competitor, no
question about it. You see it and you wouldn't want to get in his
way. And I'm telling you the guys pick right up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a sophomore when Umile was captain, remembers well
watching him get the boys going.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the type of person who knew exactly what to say at the
right time,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   UNH defenseman and assistant captain Steve O'Brien plays his
last game for Umile and UNH Saturday. He, too, says Umile has
changed and grown as a coach in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   And he figures the coach will have some words of wisdom, maybe
some new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bleeds blue,'' O'Brien said Friday. ``He'll do anything for
us. He'll be ready to go. . . . You get chills because he's so into
it. You think you're up for the game and he's way up for the game.
It's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Umile, hockey coach. That's better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
