</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WEATHER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH WEATHER AND POLITICS HAVE REDUCED NUMBER OF AIR STRIKES
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic _ how weather affects the bombings _ is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There has been fog and rain over Yugoslavia for
most of NATO's 10-day air campaign, but politicians and their
assessment of public sensitivities have grounded just as many
bombing runs as has the weather.
</P>
<P>
   The allies' initial stated goal of stopping Serb forces that are
attacking ethnic Albanians, could have been approached in three
ways, whether the targets are tanks or supply depots:
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO can launch satellite-steered missiles from ships or
planes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fighter bombers, including F-15Es and F-117s, can attack from
high altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Or tank-killing A-10s can barrel in low and shoot up armor
columns with fearsome cannons and rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Foul weather, while not hampering cruise missile strikes, has
put a serious crimp in the high-flying jets, which need to see
their targets clearly to guide the bombs precisely.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to warplanes going in low, slow and hard,
American political leaders from President Clinton on down have
reined in commanders, fearing downed planes and casualties.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions, military officials said, field commanders
thought the military risk of low-flying attacks was acceptable,
only to be overruled by their civilian bosses who were driven by
what they perceive to be the political risks of losing an aircraft
and its pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO military commander, has tried to
work around the elements _ and the politics _ by asking Washington
and other NATO nations for Apache helicopter gunships and batteries
of field artillery and long-range rockets. But for other political
reasons, the request is snarled here and in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect military commanders are somewhat frustrated over the
limitations that are being put on them,'' said Gen. Charles Horner,
a retired Air Force officer who directed the 1991 Persian Gulf air
war. ``Quite frankly, it's gradualism versus overwhelming force.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the air campaign began, NATO's political leaders had
taken steps to crimp its scope. They established strict limits on
what risks pilots could take and how narrowly the targets had to be
defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any military action involves balancing the need to strike
targets quickly with the need to do it in a way that is safe as
possible to the pilots,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said
Friday. ``We want to keep the risk as acceptable as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The intersection of those restrictions with the weather has
forced commanders to cancel about 20 percent of their ground-attack
missions, the Pentagon said Friday, although other officials that
ratio is closer to half of all the combat flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said one Air Force officer involved in the
Balkans policy. ``This whole mindset of losing pilots is hurting
our ability to roll them back and use the full capability of air
power.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the technological advances of American stealthy
fighters, laser-guided bombs and satellite-steered missiles, all of
them intended to inflict maximum damage on an adversary with
minimal risk to pilots, the elements can upset that balance
relatively easily.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it should surprise military commanders. Virtually every
prolonged aerial campaign in Europe in World War II was hampered by
fog and rain, said Michael S. Sherry, a military historian at
Northwestern University. High-altitude B-29 bombing runs over Japan
were buffeted by the jet stream, forcing the warplanes to adopt
low-altitude, night raids, Sherry said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Balkans, clouds have blocked pilots from beaming their
lasers to targets on the ground to guide bombs to their targets.
Pilots can drop unguided bombs, as B-1 bombers did on Thursday,
hitting a staging area for troops, but that poses greater risks to
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   On only one day in the past 10 have pilots had optimal
conditions for bombing _ a cloud ceiling of at least 25,000 feet
and visibility of more than five miles. ``The weather has been
lousy, and that has had a big impact on the number of strikes we've
been able to carry out,'' Bacon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
