<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-BOGUS-REPORT-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN AN ANNUAL REPORT IS HAZARDOUS TO YOUR HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (bl)  
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another day, another new mutual fund. The number of fund
offerings has exploded in recent years, and the excuses that fund
companies give for starting them grow flimsier each day. More and
more portfolios are tied to eccentric stock indexes, obscure
industry subsectors and ever more esoteric investing styles. The
logical end? Following are excerpts from an imaginary annual
report:
</P>
<P>
   We at the Dysgenic Family of Funds share your disappointment
with our 1998 performance _ even as we remain confident that the
stellar returns of our index funds, which came close to matching
their appropriate benchmarks if sales loads, 12b-1 fees and
management expenses are ignored, amply illustrate the rewards of
patience.
</P>
<P>
   The growing interest in index investing, in fact, has prompted
Dysgenic to re-examine its offerings in this arena. After all,
investment professionals rightly caution that a single index fund
does not a balanced portfolio make.
</P>
<P>
   To help investors round out their holdings, we have developed a
variety of new index funds that nicely complement the old standbys.
They include these:
</P>
<P>
   THE BYPASS FUND invests 95 percent of its assets in a basket of
stocks that passively seeks to mimic returns of the little-known
Cholesterol Index, as developed by the Poughkeepsie Mercantile
Board. The fund's top 10 holdings for the most recent quarter
included perennial favorites like Outback Steakhouse, McDonald's
and RJR Nabisco, as well as firms engaged in the business of
providing cholesterol-control drugs, surgical devices and mortuary
services. The fund recently won approval from shareholders to
establish selected short positions, the biggest of which involves
the Roughage Company, a Midwestern chain of salad bars. The fund
believes Roughage is poised for hard times as freedom-loving
Americans throw off the stigma recently associated with charred
meat.
</P>
<P>
   THE MENCKEN FUND invests in the so-called Las Vegas 40 Index,
comprised of companies that subscribe to the theories of the late
investment guru H.L. Mencken (``Nobody ever went broke
underestimating the taste of the American public.'') The LV40
includes Bantam Rising Inc., a fast-growing maker of elevator
shoes; Foment + Mendacity Syndications, one of Hollywood's leading
distributors of daytime television, and the Veblenesque Tchotchke
Company, the world's leading maker and marketer of fine
collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOMEWORK FUND, which invests in a worldwide index of
companies weighted according to the performance of each country's
secondary school students on annual examinations of reading and
mathematics literacy. This is an enhanced index fund; it exercises
discretion in allocating a portion of its assets. Thus the fund's
management, in an effort to anticipate future market movements,
closely analyzes the results of similar tests administered to
elementary school children. (A special note: because of the
consistently poor performance of American students, the fund is a
good way to diversify overseas without abandoning the discipline of
indexing.) N addition to our index offerings, the Dysgenic Family
includes a number of new, actively managed investment vehicles, as
well as some proven funds with records dating back even before
1996:
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most noteworthy is the IMBROGLIO FUND, whose board
announced recently that it had reopened to new investors. Aimed at
those whose tolerance for risk is much greater than their interest
in profits, the fund seeks out investments that the fund's
management considers likely to be affected by class action and
other lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several years, the fund has established short
positions in tobacco, breast implants, lids for takeout coffee cups
and, more recently, gun manufacturers. To help it discover new
opportunities, the fund retains a contingent of lawyers who provide
pro bono assistance to litigants wronged, or allegedly wronged, by
publicly traded companies. (The fund anticipates working closely
with management of the new Bypass Fund.)
</P>
<P>
   Under its manager, Taylor Imbroglio, the fund has performed in
the top 75 percent of nondiversified, litigation-oriented funds for
the period from April 23, 1996, to Sept. 7, 1998, not counting the
cost of judgments against the fund's assets arising from the
day-to-day course of its activities.
</P>
<P>
   Imbroglio is confident that the largest of these judgments will
be reversed on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Also of interest to investors in pursuit of high returns is the
new PETRI-BUNSEN.COM VALUE FUND, which seeks to harness two of the
day's most powerful investment trends: biotechnology stocks and the
Internet. Although the universe of companies simultaneously in both
businesses is fairly small as this report goes to press, the fund's
management believes that its exponential growth is likely to reward
patient investors who seek opportunity before the thundering herd
tramples in after them.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the fund's most promising holding is Virulax, which
makes and markets viruses for sale over the Internet, and the
American depository receipts of Anthrax.net, a Cayman Islands
concern in a similar business. It should be noted that Anthrax.net
exemplifies the power of the Internet when combined with biological
technologies, in that it does a growing global business with just a
handful of employees, using the new medium to leverage its scant
assets into worldwide sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Dysgenic Family also wishes to elaborate on its reasons for
closing its most popular offering, the THONG FUND, to new investors
as of March 1.
</P>
<P>
   The family's leading performer the last two years, the Thong
Fund invests in companies that stand to benefit from Presidential
philandering, partisan politics and governmental gridlock. Top
holdings include firms specializing in DNA testing, as well as
publishers of tabloid newspapers and providers of temporary
staffing services to the offices of independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the fund has led to a ballooning of assets, which
management believes could be detrimental to the interests of
existing shareholders. Management wishes to emphasize that past
performance is no guarantee of future results, as there can be no
assurance that Presidential behavior, the legal and regulatory
climates and other factors will continue to provide favorable
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the performance of the fund for the most recent
quarter will be adversely impacted by the purchase of key-man
insurance coverage on the lives of Monica Lewinsky, Kenneth Starr
and Barbara Walters.
</P>
<P>
   Investors should also note that the venerable BUTKUS FUND, named
in honor of the defensive great of the Chicago Bears, is being
dissolved in the wake of a successful proxy campaign on the part of
dissident shareholders to change the fund's name.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bearish, defensive portfolio strategy of the fund
has been unfashionable for most of its 15 years of existence
(leading to its negative returns in that period), management of the
fund said in a statement that it ``regretted'' the new name, the
CUSTER FUND.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also lamented that ``the prevailing quick-buck
mentality of the stock market has made our remaining investors
insufficiently patient to stay with us even as events have begun to
prove our outlook correct in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain confident, however, that when the history of mutual
funds is written, the Butkus philosophy will be vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2059EST &QL; 
