<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ATTACKS YUGOSLAV CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: More to be filed) 
(See also: KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-WEATHER, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-MCCAIN.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO attacked the center of Yugoslavia's capital
Friday night, destroying two government buildings in Belgrade in
what senior officials here described as the start of an intensified
campaign to wreck President Slobodan Milosevic's military
hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   A barrage of eight cruise missiles _ fired from American
warships and a British submarine in the Adriatic _ struck after
midnight in Belgrade, or 6 p.m. ET, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon refused to disclose the targets hit Friday night,
but flames raged from two buildings near the Sava River in
Belgrade's core, the federal Ministry for Internal Affairs and the
Ministry of Interior. The buildings house the headquarters of the
paramilitary police forces that have orchestrated Milosevic's
yearlong crackdown against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in 10 days of attacks that NATO had struck
the center of Belgrade, a once-thriving capital that has slowly
withered under years of economic sanctions and diplomatic isolation
caused by Milosevic's policies.
</P>
<P>
   Although previous attacks battered military targets on
Belgrade's edges, the missiles Friday night struck with a
thunderous clap that shook the entire capital. Within minutes of
the first explosion, an enormous arc of flames soared hundreds of
feet into the air.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of casualties from Friday night's strikes was not
immediately clear, but the attack occurred in the middle of the
night, at a time when the buildings would presumably have few
people in them.
</P>
<P>
   The two buildings are close to other government buildings,
including a hospital. But it appeared that the cruise missiles _
each with a 1,000-pound warhead _ struck their targets with
pinpoint precision, leaving other buildings nearby still standing.
But Yugoslavia's deputy prime minister, Vuk Draskovic, said there
were ``many, many victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Militarily and psychologically, the strikes represented a
serious escalation of NATO's attack on Yugoslavia, making good on
the warning by NATO's commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, that there
would be ``no sanctuary'' for Yugoslavia's political and military
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week NATO gave Clark the authority to expand the
raids beyond strictly military targets in or near Kosovo. On
Thursday American F-15s destroyed a bridge over the Danube River in
the city of Novi Sad, and Pentagon and NATO officials have vowed
that more bridges and other targets in cities would be pounded as
long as Milosevic continued his repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's strikes came after nine previous days of bombing
had made only measured progress in slowing Milosevic's onslaught
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. Refugees continued to pour from
Kosovo into Albania and Macedonia, telling stories of atrocities
and forced expulsions from villages, towns and cities throughout
the province.
</P>
<P>
   The mushrooming humanitarian crisis along Kosovo's border _
where thousands of refugees have gathered, short of food and
shelter _ has put new pressure on the United States and NATO to
intensify its campaign, even if that meant considering the use of
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, facing sharp questions at the White House,
appealed for patience and expressed confidence that an air campaign
alone would be able to achieve NATO's military and political
objectives in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have strong allied unity,'' Clinton said. ``We have real
firm determination today in Europe that these objectives will be
achieved and we intend to stay after them until they are.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2101EST &QL; 
