<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KOPP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHELDON KOPP, 70, PSYCHOLOGIST WHO WROTE ABOUT SELF-ESTEEM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Md., Calif., N.J.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sheldon Bernard Kopp, a clinical psychologist and author of
books designed to bolster the reader's self-esteem, died Monday,
his 70th birthday, at Georgetown University Hospital in Washington.
He lived in nearby Silver Spring, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cardiac arrhythmia and pneumonia, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp, who practiced in Washington for 35 years, wrote 17 books.
Much of his writing was meant to guide readers in finding
importance in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   A book that got much attention was ``If You Meet the Buddha on
the Road, Kill Him,'' published in 1972. Like many of the others,
it was issued by Science and Behavior Books. In the book, Kopp
analyzed the ways in which people sought to recognize significance
and value in themselves, rather than rely on gurus. The book
remains available from Bantam's New Age imprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back to One: A Practical Guide for Psychotherapists'' (1977),
``Even a Stone Can Be a Teacher'' (1985) and ``Blues Ain't Nothing
but a Good Soul Feeling Bad: Daily Steps to Spiritual Growth''
(1992) are also in print. His other titles include ``The Naked
Therapist'' (1976) and ``An End to Innocence'' (1978).
</P>
<P>
   Kopp was born in the Bronx, N.Y., and graduated from Brooklyn
College in 1951. He received a master's in 1953 and a doctorate in
1960 from the New School for Social Research, then interned and
worked in New Jersey institutions and agencies.
</P>
<P>
   He was a clinical psychologist and acting department head at
Trenton State Hospital before going to Washington in 1961. He was
the chief clinical psychologist in the District of Columbia Adult
Mental Health Clinic before going into private practice.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp is survived by his wife of 46 years, Marjorie Ice Kopp;
three sons, Jonathan, of Novato, Calif., David, of Atlantic City,
N.J., and Nicholas, of Germantown, Md., and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4295 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-AUTOSHOW-A     04-02 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-AUTOSHOW-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTAIN UP: A RAZZLE-DAZZLE ROAD SHOW REACHES NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The previews are over and the glittering cast has
settled in for a nine-day run. It's not exactly the Great White
Way, but it's just a few long blocks from Broadway. And where else
in New York can one see so many cars that aren't yellow? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite New Yorkers' reputed preference for subway cars over
sports cars, the New York International Auto Show draws the biggest
crowds of the nation's four leading car shows. And since it is the
last of these, its displays include most of the future models and
design studies, known as concept cars, that were previously
unveiled in Detroit, Chicago and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The new-car news at the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center, where
the last New York auto show of the century runs through Sunday,
April 11, has been about bread-and-butter cars like a restyled Ford
Taurus and the first midsize Saturn. Still, there are plenty of
sexier models that made their debuts earlier but have not been seen
by New Yorkers, like the future Ford Thunderbird, the
Bauhaus-inspired Audi TT, the '30s-style Chrysler PT Cruiser and
the Cadillac Evoq, which heralds a new direction for General
Motors' luxury division. Among the other vehicles new to New York
are these:
</P>
<P>
   ASTON MARTIN DB7 VANTAGE
</P>
<P>
   This car's stats could have James Bond rethinking his defection
to BMW: 420 horsepower from a 6-liter V12 derived from Formula One
race cars, a top speed of 180 m.p.h. and 0-to-60 acceleration in
less than 5 seconds. Both a coupe and Volante convertible go on
sale next year; prices have not been announced.
</P>
<P>
   BMW 3-SERIES COUPES
</P>
<P>
   Following the introduction last year of all-new 3-Series sedans,
BMW has updated its 323Ci and 328Ci, which go on sale in July as
2000 models. Though the styling is similar, the two- and four-door
models share virtually no parts. BMW is also displaying a new M5,
which it calls the world's fastest production sedan, and modestly
restyled Z3 roadsters.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET SUBURBAN/GMC YUKON
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, General Motors introduced completely redesigned
full-size pickups. Now it is showing prototypes of full-size sport
utilities based on that solid new truck platform. The Yukon and its
Chevy counterpart, the Tahoe, get a third-row seat _ to compete
better with the Ford Expedition _ and side air bags. Styling of the
bigger Suburban, like that of the Tahoe/Yukon, is a bit more
rounded.
</P>
<P>
   INFINITI I30
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's premium division has restyled its midsize luxury car,
based on a redesigned Nissan Maxima, for 2000. The interior is more
roomy and horsepower from the V6 is up by 37, to 227. The I30 now
offers a navigation system connected to a 24-hour response center
for emergency assistance. Other new options include Xenon headlamps
and a rear sunshade.
</P>
<P>
   KIA KMS-4
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration that economy cars need not be dull, the South
Korean automaker showed a sharp-edged design study in the vein of
the Mercury Cougar. The KMS-4 features a glass roof and a solar
cell to power accessories. The four-passenger concept coupe has a
four-cylinder engine, transmission-shifting paddles behind the
steering wheel and a sporty suspension. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAZDA MPV
</P>
<P>
   This minivan gets some much-needed improvements: front-wheel
drive, sharper styling, various family-friendly features. Sliding
rear doors _ with power windows, an exclusive touch _ replace
hinged doors. The second-row captain's chairs slide together to
form a bench; they also fold and can be removed. The third-row
seat, like that of the Honda Odyssey, flips into the floor. Mazda
may later add all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES-BENZ CL
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz is showing its next high-end coupe for the first
time. Arriving in showrooms early next year, it will be offered as
the CL500, with a 5-liter V8; a V12 model will probably come later.
Mercedes is also displaying its flagship S-Class sedan, which is
about to go on sale. Lighter and less expensive than the previous
S-Class, the car is a technological wonder: There is a standard
navigation system, voice-recognition features and a ``smart''
cruise control that maintains a set distance behind another
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI ECLIPSE
</P>
<P>
   A new version of this sporty coupe has a low-slung front end and
prominent ribs along its sides. In keeping with the
``geo-mechanical'' design of Mitsubishi's concept cars, the Eclipse
has a machined look; the fuel filler cap, for instance, has a
riveted metallic appearance. The Eclipse goes on sale this summer.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN Z
</P>
<P>
   Though it made its worldwide debut in Detroit in January, the Z
concept car got a big lift in New York, where Nissan announced that
it would indeed produce a new version of the classic Z sports car
within three years. Nissan insists that the next rear-drive Z will
not be retro, but will have the ``design DNA'' and reasonable price
of the original 1970 Datsun 240Z. The powertrain has not been
selected; the show car has a 200-horsepower four-cylinder engine.
</P>
<P>
   OLDSMOBILE AURORA
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since its 1994 introduction, the car that set
a new import-fighting course for Olds is being revamped. The 2001
model is styled less dramatically, in line with the less expensive
Intrigue. Smaller and 300 pounds lighter, the front-drive Aurora
will offer a V6 along with its highly regarded 250-horsepower V8.
It will go on sale in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   SAAB 9-3 VIGGEN
</P>
<P>
   This new offshoot of the 9-3 series derives its name and badge
from an aircraft, the Saab 37 Viggen jet fighter. Its 2.3-liter
four-cylinder engine has been modified to produce 225 horsepower,
and the car has a new sports suspension and performance wheels. The
coupe goes on sale in limited numbers in May; convertible and
five-door models arrive in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   SATURN L-SERIES
</P>
<P>
   Having survived its first decade with a single set of small
cars, Saturn at last adds some new models. Based on the Opel Vectra
from Germany, the midsize L-Series (for large) is available as an
LS sedan, which goes head-to-head with the Toyota Camry and Honda
Accord, or a LW station wagon. Resembling the smaller S-Series and
bearing plastic body panels like all Saturns, the L-Series offers
four-cylinder or V6 engines. The new models go on sale this summer;
prices were not announced. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
