<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE03-COX     04-02 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pope bears burden of Good Friday into Colosseum
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Pope John Paul II will drag his ailing
78-year-old body into the Roman Colosseum tonight to bring a
message of hope to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Flooded by candlelight, in solemn procession, the pontiff will
make the exhausting pilgrimage to remember the crucifixion of Jesus
_ and proclaim its promise.
</P>
<P>
   Today is the anniversary of Jesus' death, the Friday Christians
call good. The faithful believe that tragic event triggered God's
offer of salvation for all.
</P>
<P>
   In a ritual laden with symbolism, the pope will mark the last
Good Friday of the second millennium amid the ruins of a stadium
built at the dawn of the first.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:15 p.m., he will walk to the Stations of the Cross,
stopping at each of 14 small shrines in the stadium built in A.D.
72.
</P>
<P>
   The devotion recalls events in the death of Jesus. The arena is
symbolic of the empire Christianity conquered and the persecution
the faithful endured.
</P>
<P>
   At each stop, the pope will mourn Jesus' suffering 2,000 years
ago and pray for those who suffer today.
</P>
<P>
   There is a profound spiritual link between the two, according to
Bishop Anthony O'Connell of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think that this might be the Good Friday _ with
Kosovo going on _ that there might be something to move us to be
closer to the spirit of Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Christians will seek to be near that spirit today by
walking the Stations of the Cross at services in their churches.
</P>
<P>
   Some will join processions that trace the way of the cross
through villages and towns in outdoor journeys.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous of those is the Via Dolorosa in the Old City of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stations of the Cross is a reminder, not only of what our
Lord did, but of our willingness to walk with him and share his
victory over death,'' said the Rev. William Hamilton, rector of St.
Andrew's Episcopal Church in Lake Worth. ``It strengthens me for my
own personal journey.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrims to Jerusalem began to commemorate the way of the cross
as early as the fourth century. No one knew the precise path Jesus
took to the place of his crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   But popular piety would not be denied. Pilgrims worked out
patterns to follow with stations along the way. The number varied
among different groups.
</P>
<P>
   The faithful brought the practice home to Europe by the fifth
century, according to Gary Poe, assistant professor of religion and
church historian at Palm Beach Atlantic College in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   European churches set up a devotional walk with stations for
those who could not travel to the Holy Land. By the 16th century,
the Franciscan order _ responsible for Holy Land shrines _
established what is now the traditional 14 stops.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the events recalled in the devotion are mentioned in the
Bible, but several come from pious tradition. There is no evidence
Jesus fell or that a woman, traditionally known as Veronica, wiped
his brow.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the solemn ritual has long honored these characters and
events: His trial and conviction, the three times Jesus fell under
the weight of the cross, the people, Simon, Veronica and Mary, whom
he met along the way, his crucifixion and burial.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, with his flair for the dramatic, was the
first pope to pray the Stations of the Cross on Good Friday at the
Colosseum.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium was built at the dawn of the Christian era and is
associated with the persecution of the early church. But there is
no evidence Christians were martyred there.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the persecutions in Rome occurred before the Colosseum
was built, Poe said. Martyrs in Rome, including St. Peter, probably
died in Nero's Circus, which was once near what is today Vatican
City. Others were killed in an arena called the Circus Maximus in
Rome.
</P>
<P>
   But the Colosseum had public shows, naval battles, gladiators
fighting and is clearly associated with the martyrdom of the early
church. And that's a powerful link to Good Friday, Poe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Colosseum could have connections with martyrdom, which is
considered to be akin to the persecution of Christ,'' Poe said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Colosseum was neglected during the Middle Ages, no
doubt because there was little evidence of Christian activity
there, according to Bruce Miller, head of the religious studies
philosophy library at Catholic University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were careful to preserve martyrs' sites all over the
place,'' he said. ``They did nothing with the Colosseum.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 18th century, popular piety brought renewed attention to
the crumbling structure as a possible place of martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   In 1750, Pope Benedict XIV ordered 14 Stations of the Cross set
up in the ruins of the Colosseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christ is the king of martyrs,'' Miller said. ``If you think
martyrdom took place there, then stations of his passion are
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence any one used them. They were torn down in
1874 by Italian troops who took Rome during the unification of
Italy, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II began what is now an annual tradition of
walking the Stations of the Cross at the ancient stadium. And, on
this day of shame and suffering, the pope shines the glare of his
fame on the shame and suffering of the world.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he has prayed for _ and brought attention to _
the crisis in Bosnia, Chechnya, Rwanda and Somalia. Kosovo will be
on his list tonight, O'Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   Separate meditations are written each year for each station.
Orthodox Catholics, Protestants, women and people of many races and
many countries join the pope on the annual pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   The faithful carry candles. The pope carries a small cross for
part of the journey in imitation of Jesus. He would do that longer,
but his crippled body will not cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a tough time walking,'' O'Connell said. ``But he's
going to continue as long as he can. He figures the Lord will give
him strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
