<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGETARIAN-JESUS03-CO     04-02 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGETARIAN-JESUS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Misguided groups claim Risen Lord as their tailor-made pitchman
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Poor Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Risen from the dead, he still can't escape the clutches of those
who misuse him. And they pervert the Easter proclamation that he is
Lord.
</P>
<P>
   One bizarre group insists that Jesus was a vegetarian and
argues, therefore, that everyone should be one _ as if Good Friday
and Easter Sunday existed to serve the meatless lobby.
</P>
<P>
   That's nonsense, of course, but it illustrates a dangerous,
popular _ and blasphemous _ way of treating the Risen Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Too many Christians make Jesus a pitchman for their pet slogan
and duck his clarion call to live from another reality.
</P>
<P>
   Today's astounding news is the glad shout that a servant is
Lord. A crucified Jewish carpenter _ noted for embracing the
outcast _ is raised to the right hand of God.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian New Testament insists that Jesus' unquestioned
loyalty to God is alone rewarded with eternal life. And that book
of faith invites the faithful to live as he does, not merely on
behalf of others, but specifically on behalf of others who are
unloved and powerless.
</P>
<P>
   But too often, one interest group or another demands that Jesus
be loyal to their prejudices, push their product or advocate their
narrow understanding of God's will.
</P>
<P>
   The People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA) are a
caricature of that dangerous tendency. They peddle their
questionable gospel of vegetarian truth by depicting Jesus, with
the halo of an orange peel, calling for a meatless kingdom. The
T-shirt is $16.50.
</P>
<P>
   The PETA Web page (www. jesus-online.com) brags that the group
is ``enlisting Jesus as it newest spokeperson ... ''
</P>
<P>
   PETA is a joke. The pattern is scary.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, good Christian folk have used the name of Jesus
to support slavery, discriminate against Jews, Protestants,
Catholics, blacks, women and, most recently, homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   They have done so in absolute contradiction of the clear will of
Jesus or in the face of his silence. And they have inflicted
enormous pain.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. J. Brabban, who teaches religion and philosophy at Palm
Beach Atlantic College in West Palm Beach, equates such behavior
with that of Judas, the apostle who betrayed Jesus with a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Judas apparently wanted Jesus to support the zealots who were
planning armed rebellion. He tried to manipulate Jesus into being
what he, Judas, wanted him to be. Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we try to do that, we become Judas,'' Brabban said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nations frequently and pompously claim that the Prince of
Peace is their champion in war.
</P>
<P>
   The mess in the Balkans pits both Orthodox and Roman Catholic
Christians and a community of Muslims _ all people of the same God
_ against each other. Each believes that God is on their side,
when, no doubt, he weeps for all.
</P>
<P>
   If Jesus is misused, God is often maligned.
</P>
<P>
   Some religious separatists in Israel so twist God's word that
only the faithful who believe and behave as they do are genuinely
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims in Afghanistan make the bizarre claim that God wants
women to be uneducated, unemployed, house-bound vassals who are to
come and go in silence.
</P>
<P>
   People of good will seeking the mind of God can disagree on
tough issues such as cloning human beings, when life begins and how
it should end.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the divine will is obvious, and the model for
authentic human life is clear.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim Koran, the Hebrew Bible and Christian Scripture
insist on the holiness of God and the dignity of the person.
</P>
<P>
   And, today, as Christians shout, ``The Lord is Risen,'' they
acknowledge a servant who died for those with little or no dignity
_ the poor and outcast.
</P>
<P>
   And they rejoice in the God who has given new and enduring life
to affirm that ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
