<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-ART-2     04-02 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-ART-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES ARE MAKING MORE MONEY AND EARNING LESS PRAISE 
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Mich., Ariz., Kans.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are truly boom times for the nation's airlines: Their
earnings are stronger than ever, and they flew a record 611 million
passengers last year without a single fatality. They did so while
maintaining their on-time performance and without a significant
increase in officially registered complaints.
</P>
<P>
   So successful, and yet, by many accounts, they have never been
so unloved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you fly, the more aware you are that there's a
pattern of indifferent service,'' said Carl Hughes, the president
of Fahey Bank in Marion, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has experienced exemplary service on flights, the
bad has lately outnumbered the good, he said. For example, it took
him 23 hours to fly from Columbus, Ohio, to Belfast, Northern
Ireland, last spring, rather than the usual nine hours, because of
a series of delays, cancellations and what he said was a lack of
concern from most of the six airlines he dealt with on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Many other travelers have tales of woe. The complaints, of
course, are not new: poor service, scant leg room, lost or
mishandled baggage, incomplete or misleading information about
delayed flights, overbooking and frustration with frequent-flier
miles that are easy to accumulate but next to impossible to use.
But recent air-travel fiascos _ the January snowstorm in Detroit
that trapped people on Northwest Airlines planes for hours and the
sick-out by pilots in February that at times caused more than half
of AMR's American Airlines' flights to be canceled _ have swung a
spotlight on passenger complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Congress and Vice President Al Gore have seized on the
issue. They have proposed doubling the maximum compensation for
being bumped from a flight, requiring that all tickets be
refundable within 48 hours of purchase and that airlines disclose
their cancellation and flight delay policies and tell how many
seats on flights are available for frequent fliers.
</P>
<P>
   They are pushing for changes even though few want a return to
full-blown airline regulation, abolished in 1978, and even though
Transportation Department statistics show that the number of
consumer complaints filed has remained steady in recent years and
was just 9,606 last year. (Critics, especially travel agents, say
few travelers bother to file complaints with the agency, which does
little more than categorize the complaints.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at all the numbers, I have to conclude the system
is working pretty well, considering its complexity,'' said Dean
Headley, an assistant professor of marketing at Wichita State
University in Kansas, who has analyzed the complaints filed last
year with the Transportation Department. ``The airlines do what
they promised, getting people from A to B. But passengers seem to
be saying, `We like what you do, we just don't like the way you're
doing it.'''
</P>
<P>
   In a University of Michigan nationwide survey of 2,000 adults
released &UR;  &LR; in February, airlines were ranked 31st (tied with network
broadcasters) among 34 industries in terms of customer
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, airlines are victims of their own success. More
people flying more places has taxed the air traffic control system
and jammed airports, causing bad tempers and frayed nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Hallet, president of the Air Transport Association, the
trade group for 23 U.S. airlines, contends that about two-thirds of
all delays are the fault of weather and inefficiencies in the
government's air-traffic control system, which handles, on average,
21,000 flights a day. The system, she said, is inadequate to handle
the existing traffic, much less the air traffic in the next decade,
when the number of passengers is expected to rise to a billion from
611 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the industry's image continues to take a battering. At
congressional hearings last month, passengers caught by the
snowstorm in Detroit told of being forced to endure more than seven
hours trapped in a plane without food, water or usable lavatories.
Travel agents at the hearings criticized airlines for selling
tickets for flights that were already overbooked.
</P>
<P>
   Some influential lawmakers are sympathetic. Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., who is chairman of the Commerce Committee, has sponsored,
along with Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., the Airline Passenger Fairness
Act, which would enable air travelers to find out whether the
flights they are booked on have been oversold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every American traveler has the right to the same kinds of
basic protections when they buy an airline ticket that they do at
the corner grocery store,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry contends that overbooking is a response to
no-show passengers. The number of extra seats sold is not
determined arbitrarily, industry officials say, but by tracking
historical data to determine how many passengers are expected to
show up for the flight. The number of passengers bumped from
flights has declined over the last five years, according to the
Transportation Department _ to 44,797 passengers last year (or 0.87
for every 10,000 passengers) from 60,636 in 1994 (1.27 per 10,000).
</P>
<P>
   There is similar legislation being pushed in the House by
Representative Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the House
Transportation Committee. Gore has also proposed ``passenger
rights'' legislation. Among other things, the proposals would
require airlines to tell passengers when and why flights are
delayed, canceled or diverted to another airport and to provide
information about all fares, including fares offered through e-mail
and on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Economic Strategy Institute, a Washington-based research
group, estimated that the proposed measure could cost airlines $6
billion in lost revenues and would result in higher fares, lower
industry efficiency and customer service. The industry earned $5.1
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, airlines executives contend that the measures are in
large part a product of political posturing, as officials seek to
gain exposure and win votes from disgruntled air travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the airlines' trade group, the Air Transport
Association, acknowledges that the industry needs to burnish its
image. It recently pledged to make efforts to see that passengers
get timely and accurate information about flight delays and
cancellations, and that travelers be quoted the lowest fare
available for which they qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely responding,'' said David Fuscus, a spokesman
for the trade group, ``as you tend to do when you have the vice
president and the head of the Senate and House committees that
oversee your industry making suggestions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pledges and statistics, however, may not be enough to assuage
some passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what airlines or what time I fly between New
York and Los Angeles,'' said Leslie Goldman, a book editor in
Manhattan who flies regularly, ``there's always a long, long wait
to get to the terminal after we land.''
</P>
<P>
   Ihor Chyzowycg, a soccer coach in Cincinnati, was with other
coaches on a plane set to fly to Florida when the flight was
canceled. ``People at the gate told us the weather there was too
bad to land, but didn't say why we were boarded and taxied out to
the runway in the first place,'' he said. ``And after we sat in the
airport an hour, they reboarded us on another plane, and off we
went without any more talk about the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of experiences have fueled suspicion that the
weather and mechanical trouble are often excuses to cancel lightly
filled flights, or to double up on later flights. Airlines
vehemently deny they do that, saying even a single cancellation
ripples throughout the system and is therefore more costly than
flying a nearly empty plane.
</P>
<P>
   Such suspicions are likely to linger, as long as airports are
crowded and airplanes are cramped, some experts say. ``There seems
to be a new level of expectations,'' noted Headley of Wichita
State, ``and it isn't sinking in to the airline industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For as good as air service is, the airlines have to understand
that perception is reality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
