<HEADER>
A4300 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STANLEY-DONEN03-COX     04-02 1492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANLEY-DONEN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The musical man: Stanley Donen
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Fred Astaire joyously dancing on the
walls and ceiling in ``Royal Wedding.'' Gene Kelly deliriously
splashing in the street puddles in ``Singin' in the Rain.'' Audrey
Hepburn gracefully spreading her wings and descending the stairs of
the Louvre in ``Funny Face.'' Cary Grant playfully soaping up his
wash-and-wear suit in ``Charade.'' Dudley Moore uncomfortably
jumping on a trampoline as a nun in ``Bedazzled.''
</P>
<P>
   What these indelible movie images have in common, besides the
ability to conjure vivid memories, is their creator _ Stanley
Donen. The chorus boy turned choreographer turned master movie
director will be honored April 10, three days before he turns 75,
for his lifetime achievements at the Palm Beach International Film
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting career citations has been Donen's prime activity
lately, typified by his special award at last year's Oscars.
Upstaging King-of-the-World James Cameron, Donen expressed his
gratitude by nuzzling the gold statuette, crooning ``Cheek to
Cheek'' and breaking into a surprisingly spry tap step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to show that I thought it was a lovely thing to
have,'' he says by phone from his high-rise apartment/office near
New York's Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the Academy had ever recognized his skills
and innovations as a filmmaker. ``I'd never won an Oscar, if that's
what you mean,'' he says sternly. Incredibly, Donen was not
nominated as director for any of his 27 feature films, including
some of the best musicals ever captured on celluloid.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he can still respect the Academy, he answers
puckishly, ``When people speak of an academy, I think of a group of
French men in robes, about six guys, sitting around a table. The
Academy is 6,000 people in the movie business. I don't mean to
demean them, but it's becoming a popularity contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he's not giving up his Oscar and says he's looking
forward to collecting the film festival's tribute, too. Will we get
a tap dance out of Donen? ``It doesn't just happen,'' he
admonishes. ``When I did it, it wasn't improvised. If I do it, I
have to know what's there and is there music and what's the place.
It's a whole big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival's artistic director, Mark Diamond, was taken aback
that Donen doesn't sing and tap each for acceptance speech. ``We
just assume he does that wherever he goes. Hopefully, he'll be
having such a wonderful time that he'll want to do a tap dance for
everybody. Because I'm sure that's what everybody will be
expecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Donen collects awards the same way he makes movies _
methodically and carefully, but with a twinkle and a verve that
make both processes seem spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him, as everyone invariably does, about the giddy title song
sequence in ``Singin' in the Rain'' _ perhaps the most buoyant two
minutes in movie history _ and Donen will talk about the
painstaking effort involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is carefully thought out. You work on it for a
minimum of a year, if not two years,'' he says. ``By the time
you're shooting it, it's worked out down to the tiniest detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Donen and his star, Gene Kelly, who served as co-director and
co-choreographer, experimented on the sound stage of a New York
streetscape, planning out the dance steps as well as the
choreography of the camera. Far more than others filmmakers of the
day, Donen understood that camera movement could be an integral
part of a musical number's flow. And the result of that meticulous
trial-and-error is what became the Donen touch, an underappreciated
quality called ``effortlessness.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't ask him about the Donen touch. ``Other people tell me
there's such a thing. I don't know what it is,'' he says.
``Sometimes I get upset that they see similarities in what I do.
While I don't want to complain, I like to be thought of as gifted.
I just don't want to be thought of as limited.''
</P>
<P>
   The other adjective that makes him even more aggravated is
``inactive.'' Gathering awards and doing a little dance is
gratifying, but it can't compare with getting back into the
director's chair. It has been 15 years since Donen's last feature,
``Blame It On Rio,'' a subpar dirty old man sitcom starring Michael
Caine and Demi Moore.
</P>
<P>
   But he's stayed busy. ``I wasn't willing to say `yes' ... to
what was proposed. But I never stopped pushing the snowball up the
mountain. In that period you call `inactivity,' there was very much
activity on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 12, the Donen drought ends when his film of A.R.
Gurney's WASP chronicle ``Love Letters,'' featuring Steven Weber
and Laura Linney, is broadcast on ABC. On stage, it was a
recitation of correspondence between the characters, from
kindergarten to old age. On screen, Donen has turned it into a
fluid journey, with a dash of his martini-dry sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the projects he has been shepherding since the
mid-'80s, ``Love Letters'' almost didn't happen. ``I was working on
it forever as a movie for theaters and then Universal was bought by
Seagrams and they canceled the picture. No other studio wanted to
make it either, so it lay dormant until it was possible to do it on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 60 years in show business, since he made his
Broadway debut in the chorus of Pal Joey at the age of 16, he's
never worked in television.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really conceived for television, in order to do it in
the very modest amount of time allotted and to do it for a very
modest amount of money,'' he says. ``We made it horrendously
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not helped Donen's career that the movies have turned
their backs on making musicals, that singularly American art form
at which he excelled, from 1949's ``On the Town'' to 1978's faux
double feature, ``Movie Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not being made because there's no group of people who
are making them, so there's no people to draw on to make them,'' he
notes. ``Another reason is they don't translate easily into foreign
languages. You can't dub Barbra Streisand's voice singing Spanish,
and those foreign markets have become very important. So everything
is conspiring against it, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is a vastly different place than the one young Stanley
Donen found in 1943, three years after leaving his hometown of
Columbia, S.C. Having worked as assistant choreographer to Kelly on
Broadway's ``Best Foot Forward,'' he followed his star westward at
a time when the movie musical was flourishing. Donen's first film
job was hoofing in the chorus of that same show, followed by
choreographing numbers alongside Kelly in ``Cover Girl'' and ``Take
Me Out to the Ball Game.'' By 1949, Kelly and Donen were
co-directing ``On the Town.''
</P>
<P>
   Donen scoffs at the prevailing view that Kelly would deal with
the staging of scenes and he would be in charge of the camera.
``Nothing is ever strictly divided. Everybody is mucking in to do
everything, or at least that's the way we did it.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to explain how the directorial collaboration worked,
Donen used to say, jokingly, ``If you substitute the word `fight'
for `co-direct,' then you have it. It wasn't always like that with
Gene, but it gradually came to be that, and eventually it came to
be impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Donen began directing on his own (and if you compare his work
with Kelly's solo direction, it's clear who was more talented.)
Donen produced such stellar work as ``Royal Wedding,'' ``Seven
Brides for Seven Brothers'' and ``Funny Face.'' After a two-picture
teaming with George Abbott on the movie versions of ``The Pajama
Game'' and ``Damn Yankees,'' Donen moved to London and began making
effervescent, European-flavored romantic comedies, such as
``Indiscreet,'' ``Charade'' and ``Two For the Road.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not return to the United States until 1975, when he made
a few lesser films, including the empty-headed ``Saturn 3'' and the
expensive failure ``Lucky Lady,'' with Gene Hackman, Liza Minnelli
and Burt Reynolds. Of local boy Reynolds, Donen says, ``He was
difficult. We didn't get along very well, but since then, we've
sort of made up and become friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Eternal romantic Donen has been married five times, including
actresses Marion Marshall and Yvette Mimieux, and divorced five
times _ most recently in 1994. Just as he remained optimistic about
marriage, so has he continued to pursue work.
</P>
<P>
   Donen says he looks forward to coming to Palm Beach and basking
in the warm sun and the adulation, but he's looking forward more to
reactions about his new film. For him, it is a calling card,
reminding the industry of his ability and availability.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I hope,'' Donen says softly. ``All we want is a
chance to do good work, that's what we're all looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
