<SLUG> BC-TIMECHANGE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attending church on time may require a bit of pre-Easter clock
tweeking
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service ATLANTA _ For all those churchgoers who
<TEXT>
plan to rise before dawn for Easter sunrise services, you may want
to get to bed an hour earlier.
<P>
   Daylight-saving time coincides with Easter for the first time
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   While some church leaders expressed confidence the faithful will
move their clocks an hour forward and make it to services on time,
others forewarned their flock.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Scott Hearn, whose 550-member Creekside United
Methodist Church is having a 7 a.m. sunrise service, reminded
members of the time change at Palm Sunday, Maundy Thursday and Good
Friday services. He published a reminder in the church bulletin and
put it on the church's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   As a bit of insurance, the minister said, he will e-mail
everyone over the weekend. ``Ninety-eight percent of our members
have e-mail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Atlanta's First Presbyterian Church, volunteers will have to
make sure they wake up in time to cook the grits and have the
coffee ready for about 400 homeless people who eat there at 6:30
each Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prayer breakfast will go on as usual,'' vowed the Rev.
Charles Black, associate pastor for community ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Eddie Long and the staff of New Birth Missionary Baptist
Church in south DeKalb County have faith that their faithful will
make it to the city's largest service. New Birth, which claims
22,000 members, usually has Sunday worship services at 6:30 a.m., 9
a.m. and 12:30 p.m., but has reserved the Georgia Dome for a single
Easter service at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kinda', sorta' forgot the time change,'' confessed Gregory
Mitchell, the church's director of media. But, he said, ``most of
our congregation is used to being up early for services. I don't
anticipate that much trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
