<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI AGENTS DIG ON TEXAS RANCHLAND; MAY BE SEEKING BONES OF MISSING
ATHEIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BOB MAHLBURG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FBI agents armed with a federal search warrant hauled digging
equipment onto a ranch in a remote area of South Texas on Friday,
apparently looking for the bodies of missing atheist leader Madalyn
Murray O'Hair and two relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Ranch owner Joanne Friend said she was startled when FBI agents
knocked on her door about noon on Friday and announced they had a
warrant to search for the three bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they were looking for bodies,'' Friend said. ``They
said they suspected they were there.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Mike Appleby in San Antonio confirmed that a
search warrant was executed and that the owners of the ranch were
not implicated. But he told The Associated Press, ``We're not
acknowledging that there was any digging or whether it's related to
the O'Hair investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Department of Public Safety spokesman Tom Vinger in
Austin told the Fort Worth Star-Telegram: ``We are assisting the
FBI, searching for evidence related to Madalyn Murray O'Hair at an
undisclosed location.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, her son, Jon Garth Murray, and daughter, Robin Murray
O'Hair, vanished from San Antonio in September 1995 along with
$500,000 in gold.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair gained prominence in the 1960s by successfully
challenging organized use of prayer in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Short, clerk at Quality Supply Co. in Camp Wood near the
ranch about 100 miles west of San Antonio, said that yesterday's
search was the talk of the town of 746.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows about it,'' said Short, who added that she had
seen digging equipment brought past the store and helicopters
flying overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt could have resulted from information gathered by
federal agents who spent more than 10 hours interviewing an
ex-convict jailed in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Gary P. Karr was arrested last week and charged with a federal
weapons violation. FBI agents testified at his detention hearing
that they interviewed Karr at his home, said Karr's lawyer, federal
public defender Richard Helfrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their characterization of those interviews was that Mr. Karr
was cooperative with regards to matters relating to Texas involving
homicides,'' Helfrick told the San Antonio Express-News in a
telephone interview from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Helfrick, however, declined to say if Karr admitted a role in
any slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Karr, 50, and David R. Waters, 52, were arrested last week after
teams of local and federal agents searched their apartments. Agents
are reported to have found two loaded pistols in Karr's apartment
in a Detroit suburb and 119 rounds of ammunition in Waters'
apartment in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are ex-convicts and were charged with being felons in
possession of firearms or ammunition and were being held without
bond Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Waters was the O'Hairs' office manager at their American Atheist
headquarters in 1994. In 1995, he pleaded guilty to stealing
$54,000 from them.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has denied involvement in the O'Hairs' disappearance or
the death of Danny Fry, a friend of his whose nude, headless and
handless body was found near Dallas soon after the O'Hairs
vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Friend said she has no idea why officials think the O'Hairs'
bodies are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just said they wanted us to know they were looking over
the property and we have nothing to do with it,'' Friend said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she knows of no connections between the ranch and
O'Hair or her followers.
</P>
<P>
   The family ranch is leased out most of the time, Friend said.
She is one of three daughters who each inherited a chunk of the
ranch from their father, John Wesley Cooksey. The mostly flat ranch
dotted with oak trees is on the east side of Texas 55 just south of
Camp Wood and about 35 miles from Uvalde.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, the ranch was swarming with FBI agents, U.S. Marshals
and DPS troopers, area residents said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was FBI at the gate and about 100 yards down the road
and it said FBI on the jackets,'' said David Falcon, manager of
Casa Falcon Restaurant in Camp Wood, who said he used to shear
goats on the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all just flat land,'' Falcon said. ``There's little
mountains, but you got to go way back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Friend said authorities did not give her any indication how long
they thought the search would last.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know, but they said they'd let us know when they're
through,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said the FBI has got a search warrant for the property
and they do not want us on it while they're searching.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Bill Hanna contributed to this report.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
