<SLUG> BC-MARINE-AVIATOR-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINE SENTENCED TO DISMISSAL FOR DESTROYING VIDEOTAPE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif, N.C., N.Y.)   (rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A military jury Friday sentenced the navigator of a
jet that severed ski lift cables in the Italian Alps last year,
killing 20 people, to dismissal from the Marine Corps for
obstructing justice by destroying a personal videotape he shot
during the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The jury at Camp Lejeune, N.C., imposed no prison sentence for
the officer, Capt. Joseph P. Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal is the equivalent of a dishonorable discharge for
an enlisted service member. The charges against Schweitzer,
obstruction of justice and conspiracy to obstruct justice, carried
maximum sentences of five years.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence, which could be appealed and eventually set aside,
makes it unlikely that anyone will go to jail in the accident,
which caused the ski lift's gondola to fall about 400 feet. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The pilot of the plane, which was on a low-level training
mission, faces court-martial on the same charges. But he is not
accused of destroying the tape, only removing it from his video
camera, taking it off the plane after an emergency landing in
Aviano and giving it to Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Marine Corps, Lt. Col. Ellen K. Haddock,
said it would be wrong to view the sentence pronounced Friday as
lenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``While that word `dismissal' doesn't sound like much, that is a
punitive discharge,'' she said. ``It's more than losing your job.
This is a felony offense, and it's a record.''
</P>
<P>
   Haddock added, ``This will stay with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Military officers and veterans said the dismissal would probably
bar Schweitzer from getting a job based on his 10 years of
experience with the Marines and as a graduate of the Naval Academy.
Schweitzer was an electronic counter-measures officer, and his role
on the four-seat EA-6B Prowler jet that crashed was mission
planning, navigation and communications with the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Under the sentencing, he will not be eligible for ordinary
veterans' benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y., pleaded guilty on Monday, the
day before his court-martial was supposed to begin. A jury was
empaneled anyway, because under the military justice system, the
defendant can choose whether to be sentenced by a judge or a jury.
</P>
<P>
   A secret part of the plea bargain assured that Schweitzer would
not be sent to jail. But the jury of nine officers did not know
that until after it completed its deliberations, which took a
little more than three hours Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal could be reduced or set aside by the officer who
ordered the court-martial, Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of Marine
Corps Forces Atlantic. Schweitzer could also appeal to the
Navy-Marine Corps Court of Criminal Appeals, which sometimes
reduces sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer had faced manslaughter and homicide charges after the
flight, but those were dropped after a different jury acquitted the
pilot, Capt. Richard J. Ashby, 32, of Mission Viejo, Calif., of
those charges. Ashby's court martial on the obstruction charges is
scheduled to begin in three weeks, and his lawyers have not
indicated that he will plead guilty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Schweitzer, tearful and remorseful, had testified on Thursday
night that he had never viewed the videotape, not having a camera
capable of playing it back. But he said he feared that the Italian
news media would use a shot of him smiling into the camera, which
he believed he recorded, with footage of the twisted gondola lying
on bloody snow. He also said he feared that Italian authorities
would misconstrue textbook low-altitude maneuvers as reckless
flying.
</P>
<P>
   He testified that he eventually tossed the tape on a bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer had bought the tape at a PX on the base and borrowed
Ashby's camera to make a recording on what was supposed to be one
of their last flights before rotating home from Bosnia duty to
Cherry Point, N.C. Ashby had testified that he never saw the
videotape again after giving it to Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by his lawyers and his parents and looking weary this
afternoon, Schweitzer told reporters, ``I was here to accept
responsibility for my actions and I respect the decision that was
made by my peers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My immediate plans,'' he said, ``are basically to wake up
tomorrow morning and not have to deal with this for the first time
in 14 months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
