<SLUG> BC-OHAIR-DISAPPEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIG IN TEXAS FAILS TO FIND ATHEIST FIGURE OR HER FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mich.)  (js) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal agents searched two remote sites in Texas
Friday, stepping up the search for the body of Madalyn Murray
O'Hair, the atheist leader who disappeared in 1995 with her son,
her granddaughter and $500,000 in gold coins, government officials
here said.
</P>
<P>
   After digging throughout the day, searchers had failed to find
any trace of Mrs. O'Hair, whose Supreme Court case in 1963 led to a
ban on organized prayer in the public schools. But the officials
said agents of the FBI and local authorities in Texas were hopeful
that they were finally close to a solution for the perplexing
four-year-old case.
</P>
<P>
   The officials would state no grounds for that hope, or explain
what had happened that led to the digging Friday. But the growing
activity in the case appears to have sprung from the arrest last
week of two men, one of them a former employee of Mrs. O'Hair's
organization, American Atheists Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The officials here said only that the digging had occurred at
two sites somewhere outside San Antonio. But The Associated Press
reported from San Antonio that the search was being undertaken on a
ranch about 100 miles west of the city, near the town of Camp Wood.
</P>
<P>
   The two men arrested last week are David R. Waters, the former
employee of American Atheists, who was seized when agents found a
large quantity of ammunition in a search of his apartment in
Austin, Texas, and Gary P. Karr, arrested when two loaded handguns
were found in his apartment in Novi, Mich. Waters and Karr served
sentences at the same minimum-security penitentiary in Vienna,
Ill., for an eight-month period in the 1980s and have been charged
under a federal law barring felons from possessing ammunition or
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who once managed an office for Mrs. O'Hair in Austin,
pleaded guilty in 1994 to charges of stealing $54,000 from her
organization. The $500,000 that disappeared along with Mrs. O'Hair
was withdrawn from an account belonging to the atheist group.
</P>
<P>
   Karr spent more than two decades in prison after a series of
crimes in 1974. He left prison in May 1995, four months before Mrs.
O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and her granddaughter, Robin
Murray-O'Hair, disappeared in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Waters and Karr have not been charged in connection with the
O'Hair case. But last week Waters' court-appointed lawyer said a
federal prosecutor had advised him that Waters was suspected of
being part of a plot to rob and murder Mrs. O'Hair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
