</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WEATHER-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-675(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH WEATHER AND POLITICS HAVE REDUCED NUMBER OF AIR STRIKES
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Subs for additions; second take is new.) 
 (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic _ how weather affects the bombings _ is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There has been fog and rain over Yugoslavia for
most of NATO's 10-day air campaign, but politicians and their
assessment of public sensitivities have grounded just as many
bombing runs as has the weather.
</P>
<P>
   The allies' initial stated goal of stopping Serb forces that are
attacking ethnic Albanians, could have been approached in three
ways, whether the targets are tanks or supply depots:
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO can launch satellite-steered missiles from ships or
planes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fighter bombers, including F-15Es and F-117s, can attack from
high altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Or tank-killing A-10s can barrel in low and shoot up armor
columns with fearsome cannons and rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Foul weather, while not hampering cruise missile strikes, has
put a serious crimp in the high-flying jets, which need to see
their targets clearly to guide the bombs precisely.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to warplanes going in low, slow and hard,
American political leaders from President Clinton on down have
reined in commanders, fearing downed planes and casualties.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions, military officials said, field commanders
thought the military risk of low-flying attacks was acceptable,
only to be overruled by their civilian bosses who were driven by
what they perceive to be the political risks of losing an aircraft
and its pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO military commander, has tried to
work around the elements _ and the politics _ by asking Washington
and other NATO nations for Apache helicopter gunships and batteries
of field artillery and long-range rockets. But for other political
reasons, the request is snarled here and in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect military commanders are somewhat frustrated over the
limitations that are being put on them,'' said Gen. Charles Horner,
a retired Air Force officer who directed the 1991 Persian Gulf air
war. ``Quite frankly, it's gradualism versus overwhelming force.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the air campaign began, NATO's political leaders had
taken steps to crimp its scope. They established strict rules on
what risks pilots could take and how narrowly the targets had to be
defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any military action involves balancing the need to strike
targets quickly with the need to do it in a way that is safe as
possible to the pilots,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said
Friday. ``We want to keep the risk as acceptable as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The intersection of those restrictions with the weather has
forced commanders to cancel about 20 percent of their ground-attack
missions, the Pentagon said Friday, although other officials that
ratio is closer to half of all the combat flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said one Air Force officer involved in the
Balkans policy. ``This whole mindset of losing pilots is hurting
our ability to roll them back and use the full capability of air
power.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the technological advances of American stealthy
fighters, laser-guided bombs and satellite-steered missiles, all of
them intended to inflict maximum damage on an adversary with
minimal risk to pilots, the elements can upset that balance
relatively easily.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it should surprise military commanders. Virtually every
prolonged aerial campaign in Europe in World War II was hampered by
fog and rain, said Michael S. Sherry, a military historian at
Northwestern University. High-altitude B-29 bombing runs over Japan
were buffeted by the jet stream, forcing the warplanes to adopt
low-altitude, night raids, Sherry said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Balkans, clouds have blocked pilots from beaming their
lasers to targets on the ground to guide bombs to their targets.
Pilots can drop unguided bombs, as B-1 bombers did on Thursday,
hitting a staging area for troops, but that poses greater risks to
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   On only one day in the past 10 have pilots had optimal
conditions for bombing _ a cloud ceiling of at least 25,000 feet
and visibility of more than five miles. ``The weather has been
lousy, and that has had a big impact on the number of strikes we've
been able to carry out,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the Pentagon wheeled out red, yellow and
green stop-light charts to show weather's effect on the operation.
Only one day in the first six was green, for optimal weather. The
rest of the chart was checkered with yellow lights (cloud ceiling
between 10,000 and 25,000 feet) and red lights (ceiling below
10,000 feet).
</P>
<P>
   In theory, fighter-bombers could dip in under the clouds, but
the best altitude for these warplanes is about 25,000 feet _ close
enough to identify and lock on targets, but out of range of most of
Yugoslavia's formidable surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Commanders prefer laser-guided bombs because of their accuracy _
and the reduced risk of causing unintended casualties on the
ground. Italy and Greece have been particularly worried about
attacks on targets in populated areas, causing strains in the
19-member alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Another handicap for the higher flying planes is that there are
no commandos on the ground, as there were in the Gulf War, acting
as spotters.
</P>
<P>
   The few times the clouds have cleared this week, military
planners scrambled to take advantage of the opportunity. On
Thursday, fighter-bombers attacked a motorized brigade that was
waiting to fill up with fuel. Bridges were struck to limit the
ability of the Yugoslav army and the special police to resupply
their forces.
</P>
<P>
   But the allies' main weapon of choice against ground troops has
done little but fly reconnaissance.
</P>
<P>
   These planes, the U.S. A-10 Warthogs, which can fire Maverick
missiles and 30-millimeter cannons from over a mile from their
target, have not been ordered to fly under low clouds to avoid
Serbia's menacing surface-to-air fire.
</P>
<P>
   Commanders say their pilots are willing to take greater risks,
but politicians fear that an American public conditioned to
low-casualty conflicts will not accept a steep death toll from the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and Congress are gun-shy about this very
sensitive issue,'' said Brent Scowcroft, a retired Air Force
general who was President Bush's national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The climate _ political and meteorological _ has forced NATO to
rely more heavily on missiles launched from ships and planes, as
well as bombs dropped from B-2 bombers, all of which satellites
guide to pre-programmed targets.
</P>
<P>
   But cruise missiles are effective only against fixed targets and
are expensive, costing between $600,000 and $1 million apiece.
Moreover, the Air Force is running low on air-launched missiles,
and industry officials say it will take weeks to convert
nuclear-tipped cruise missiles in stock to ones armed with
conventional explosives.
</P>
<P>
   To work around these weather obstacles, NATO is using unmanned
drones to reconnoiter the battlefield. An airborne
ground-surveillance plane, called JStars, can monitor large troop
movements. But Serb tanks and armor have dispersed in the hilly,
wooded terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Clark wants Apache helicopters because the region's mountainous
terrain is ideal for hunting tanks. Apaches can hover just behind
the crest of a hill, exposing only their radar to identify a
target. They rise quickly to fire off missiles from three miles
from the target, and pop back down to safety.
</P>
<P>
   The rocketry requested, the Multiple Launch Rocket System with a
range of about 18 miles and the ATACMS, a rocket system, with a
range of about 180 miles, attack air defenses.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark's request has been hung up on several political snags,
alliance officials said. These systems suggest a ground war more
than an air war, and would require approval from NATO, as well as
either Albania or Macedonia, where the weaponry would be based.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4318 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0403-COX     04-02 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0403-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO CARRIES WAR TO DOWNTOWN BELGRADE
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    with COX-KOSOVO-DISCLOSURE, COX-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
COX-KOSOVO-AID and COX-KOSOVO-IRAQ
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- U.S. cruise missiles struck a pair of government
buildings in downtown Belgrade Friday night, setting them ablaze
and taking NATO's ten-day-old bombing campaign to the heart of
Yugoslavia's capital for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade's state-run TV showed Serb police headquarters and the
nearby interior ministry in flames shortly after explosions rocked
the capital around 1 a.m. (6 p.m. EST).
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said U.S. naval ships launched
seven cruise missiles at the buildings, nerve centers for the
campaign of terror Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic is waging against
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are striking at targets in downtown Belgrade that are at
the core of his ability to command and control the troops that have
been used for ethnic cleansing in Kosovo,'' said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   State-run media in Belgrade reported NATOforces also struck an
army barracks in southeast Serbia and a major highway junction west
of the Kosovo provincial capital of Pristina. NATO has stepped up
its efforts
</P>
<P>
   in recent days to cut off key supply routes used to deliver fuel
and ammunition to Serb forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Serb prosecutors began building their case
against three American soldiers captured Wednesday near Kosovo's
border with Macedonia. Reports on the proceedings were sketchy, and
there was no word as to whether the soldiers appeared before
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials insisted the capture had not affected the
alliance's ongoing air campaign. More than 2,000 sorties in ten
days have failed to halt Yugoslavia's brutal campaign to rid Kosovo
of ethnic Albanians. That mission appeared well on its way toward
completion by Friday, with an estimated one out of every three
Kosovars having been forced from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, an estimated 200,000 Kosovar Albanians were jammed
around a railroad station awaiting forced deportation at the hands
of Yugoslav troops and local police.
</P>
<P>
   At least five trainloads of people _ all forced from their homes
under threat of execution _ were deported Friday from Pristina to
neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of others streamed by foot, car or tractor
across Kosovo's border into Albania, many braving a heavily-mined
field to make their way out of Serbia, Yugoslavia's main state.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 225,000 Kosovar Albanians have taken refuge in
Albania and Macedonia since NATO air strikes began March 24. They
fled Serb troops, local police and paramilitary thugs who have
shelled civilians, torched villages and executed people at will.
</P>
<P>
   Another 31,000 refugees have fled to Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned by the enormity of the humanitarian catastrophe, the
United States and its NATO allies announced a massive air lift,
starting this weekend, to get food, medicine and tents to refugee
sites the size of cities that have sprung up overnight along
Kosovo's mountainous border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are no longer facing an internal Yugoslav crisis,'' NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea said at alliance headquarters in Brussels.
``We are facing a crisis of the entire region, with far-reaching
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton reiterated his concern for the
treatment of the captured Americans, stressing that Milosevic would
be held accountable for their welfare.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials were still trying to learn where the men were
being held, and the State Department said Red Cross representatives
had been denied access to the men.
</P>
<P>
   The United States rejects Serb plans to put the men on trial for
unspecified charges of ``aggression,'' contenting such action is a
violation of the Geneva Conventions on the treatment of prisoners
of war.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated that there were no plans to send ground
troops into Kosovo, saying he intends to press forward with air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe that we have a good possibility of achieving
our mission with the means that we have deployed,'' Clinton said.
``We must be determined, we must be persistent, we must be patient
if we expect to see this mission through. And I am absolutely
determined to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   As he has in the past, Clinton stressed that the flood of
refugees from Kosovo were caused by an orchestrated campaign
conducted by troops under the authority of Milosevic, president of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that what Mr. Milosevic wants to do is to
keep the land of Kosovo and rid it of its people,'' Clinton said at
a brief White House news conference. ``We have to make sure that
Mr. Milosevic pays a heavy price for this policy of repression.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim ends)
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, cruise missiles fired from two U.S. naval vessels
struck the Yugoslav Interior Ministry and the Serbian police
headquarters in downtown Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In other action, the supersonic B-1 bomber was used for the
first time in the conflict, striking Serb tanks and troops at
several staging areas in central Kosovo, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   Among the forces targeted were units of the 243rd mechanized
brigade, a mobile infantry group that has spent much of the week
shelling civilians pinned down in a valley in southwest Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim ends)
</P>
<P>
   Other NATO attacks reported Friday were on Serb fuel and
ammunition depots and two military airfields.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said bombing runs continue to be impeded by poor
weather. But they insisted the air campaign was gaining traction
and that the cumulative impact of ten days of attacks was beginning
to hamper the Serbs' ability to continue their rampage across
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There have been signs, for example, that NATO attacks on fuel
and ammunition dumps and on bridges and roads have disrupted
efforts to resupply Serb forces in the field.
</P>
<P>
   At least one Serb battle group was sidelined early Thursday when
its vehicles ran out of fuel outside of Dakovica, a city near the
Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   Amidst NATO promises to continue escalating the campaign,
Pentagon planners were reviewing a NATO request to add 75
carrier-based warplanes to the effort.
</P>
<P>
   While no formal approval had been granted, the USS Roosevelt, a
nuclear-powered aircraft carrier with roughly 50 attack jets and
two dozen reconnaissance and support aircraft, was steaming toward
the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   The Roosevelt, expected to arrive in the region as early as
Monday, is scheduled to relieve the USS Enterprise, on duty in the
Persian Gulf. NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark has asked that the
carrier instead be assigned to the NATO mission against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't surprise me if the Theodore Roosevelt is vectored
into the Mediterranean in support of Allied Force for a while, but
there's been no final decision,'' Bacon told reporters, using the
name given to the NATO air campaign. ``It would give us additional
planes to help do the job that we're doing, which is to continue
with our systematic day and night attacks designed to choke off the
Serb military.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 220 American warplanes in the region now, part
of a NATO armada of more than 400 planes.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
