<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT &LR;      04-02 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-WEATHER,
KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-MCCAIN.) 
(rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMBAT
</P>
<P>
   NATO airstrikes hit the center of Yugoslavia's capital,
Belgrade, early Saturday, for the first time since the bombing
began on March 24. The Defense and Interior Ministries and the
Serbian republic's police headquarters were severely damaged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The strikes came hours after a NATO spokesman said 10 days of
missile and bombing raids had not prevented a terror campaign
against Kosovo's ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   A Navy aircraft carrier was heading for the Mediterranean Sea
and was likely to join the fight against Yugoslavia, Pentagon
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian reconnaissance frigate sailed from the Black Sea to
the Mediterranean to monitor NATO forces involved in raids against
Yugoslavia. Moscow said it would stay out of the conflict and not
share the intelligence data with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said that he still believed NATO could achieve
its goals in Kosovo without ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force B-1 bomber flew its first mission against
Yugoslavia on Thursday night, making the Yugoslav conflict the
first in which the Air Force has used all three types of
intercontinental-range bombers: the B-1, the B-52 and the B-2
stealth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES
</P>
<P>
   The continuing exodus of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo was
overwhelming the province's neighbors. The U.N. High Commission for
Refugees estimated that 298,400 refugees had entered Albania,
Macedonia and Montenegro since March 24. Another 12,485 had gone to
Croatia, Bosnia and Turkey, bringing the total to 310,885, or
one-sixth of Kosovo's preconflict population of 1.8 million.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRISONERS
</P>
<P>
   Serbian officials began gathering evidence for possible criminal
proceedings against three American soldiers who were captured along
the Macedonian-Yugoslav border on Wednesday and are being held in
Kosovo, the state-run Tanjug news agency reported. Sweden's
Ambassador to Yugoslavia forwarded a U.S. demand that the soldiers
be visited by the Red Cross and that they be released. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAV POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav police shut down B-92, Belgrade's most popular
independent radio station. Although the station's transmitter was
shut down late last month, B-92 still broadcast over satellite and
Internet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government of Montenegro, which opposes President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia, called for calm as rumors spread that army
units in the republic were preparing a coup. On Thursday Milosevic
replaced several generals in Montenegro with men loyal to himself.
</P>
<P>
   A leading Kosovo Albanian politician, Hashim Thaqi, announced
the formation of a ``government'' for the province headed by
himself and excluding followers of Ibrahim Rugova, Albanian
television said. The report came a day after Rugova was shown on
Yugoslav television in talks with Milosevic. Rugova was president
of the unofficial parallel government that Kosovo Albanians
established after the province was stripped of its autonomy in
1989.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OTHER DEVELOPMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, speaking during Good Friday rites in Rome,
compared the victims of the Kosovo conflict to the crucified
Christ. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main cinema in the Siberian city in Irkutsk said it was
pulling American movies and showing instead Yugoslav features to
protest the NATO airstrikes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Additional coverage of the conflict in Kosovo is available at
The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
