<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABIES-LEARNING03-COX     04-02 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABIES-LEARNING03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exploring a baby's learning curve
 &HT;    By Julie Bonnin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Baby and I face a television screen in a small
featureless room. We are sitting, she propped in my lap and me in a
straight-backed wooden chair.
</P>
<P>
   Nap?
</P>
<P>
   Check.
</P>
<P>
   Belly full?
</P>
<P>
   Check.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetie Girl _ I mean, my daughter, Katie _ is ready to go to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Like the thousands of others who've participated in studies at
the Children's Research Laboratory at the University of Texas, this
little trooper's sacrificing a ride in the stroller, a game of
peek-a-boo _ all in the name of science.
</P>
<P>
   Think astounding baby feats: when and what infants first see,
how their first words float to the surface of a bubbling, babbling
alphabet soup.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of things being painstakingly measured at
CRL, perhaps the foremost lab of its kind for taking the stuff of
baby book entries and turning it into scientific data. That data
are important for a couple of reasons, says CRL director and
psychologist Leslie Cohen, who helped pioneer the techniques most
researchers now use to study babies.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing what infants are capable of at any given age helps
parents be better parents, giving them ideas about what game, song
or toy their child might enjoy and benefit from. And such research
helps parents and pediatricians identify problems early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's essential that you know what your baby's supposed to do
at different ages,'' Cohen says, ``so you can really enjoy your
baby's development or begin to recognize if there's some kind of
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A study of teen-age moms found babies whose mothers were taught
about infant development were healthier and more advanced. ``Their
mothers seemed to enjoy them more,'' Cohen says.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, public policy-makers are also interested in how
and when babies learn. Studies showing that early experiences have
a profound impact on the brain form the foundation for a statewide
initiative promoted by Texas first lady Laura Bush and by Texas
legislators lobbying for more money for programs for children from
newborn to age 3.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of findings about early childhood development in
the past decade has come about partly in response to medical
advances that brought more babies into the world with special
needs, Cohen says. But the research also dovetailed with the
emergence of the superbaby/superparent phenomenon in the 1980s.
Anyone who thinks flash-card parenting is a thing of the past ought
to talk to the people at CRL, who find themselves turning down
countless parents who want to submit their babies to infant IQ
tests. (CRL refers them elsewhere).
</P>
<P>
   Today's moms and dads can immerse themselves in parenting
information if they choose to, and many of them do. While knowing
little about how babies and children grow and develop isn't a good
thing, knowing too much, Cohen says, also has its pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can lead parents to feel that unless they're absolutely
perfect, their kids are not going to reach their potential,'' he
says. ``No parent is going to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for baby, no matter how precocious. Indeed, after a decade
or so of magazine covers proclaiming the braininess of babies,
there's been a bit of a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``People went a little too far in asserting that infants were
little Einsteins,'' Cohen says. ``Hold on a minute, babies really
do develop. They're not geniuses out of the womb. I give a talk
called, 'Babies may be dumber than you think.' I like to tell
parents, `Your baby is developing slowly for important reasons.
Enjoy that development.'''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what we're doing, Katie and I _ enjoying her
development while a graduate assistant records her reaction to
changing faces on a video screen.
</P>
<P>
   Ding. Ding. Ding. When the bell sounds, a flashing green dot
grows bigger and bigger. Then a pleasing female face framed by long
blonde hair appears.
</P>
<P>
   The bell rings again, followed by another face, this time a girl
with curly brown hair.
</P>
<P>
   Katie, herself a brunette, clearly prefers the second face,
proclaiming, ``Dah, dah,'' and clapping her hands when the young
woman reappears.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen, who is conducting this study, isn't interested in
facial preferences. He's trying to track when babies begin to
perceive faces in their entirety. As newborns, they don't see the
internal features of a face, only its outline.
</P>
<P>
   So Katie sees the first two faces over and over again, until her
interest starts to wane. Toward the end, instead of cooing with
delight, she's rubbing chubby little fingers in her eyes, thrusting
her head dangerously close to the floor to escape the interminable
ennui.
</P>
<P>
   But when the bell dings, Katie knows to take a look. And when a
face combining the internal features of one face with the outline
of the other appears, she perks up, looks longer. And there you
have it. If she couldn't see the eyes, nose and mouth, the melded
faces wouldn't mean much, would they?
</P>
<P>
   That's a conclusion I'm drawing. One of the caveats of
participating is that the researchers won't talk about how a child
(or the occasional adult drafted for studies about parenting) does.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen's study, which should be completed by summer, already
has shown that by 7 months, most babies gaze longer at composite
faces, the way adults do.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted with 64 4- and 7-month-olds and dozens more
infants whose results were thrown out because of fussiness or other
complications, is scheduled to be replicated with infants who have
spina bifida and with babies with brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Katie and I stand ready to do duty again. Our
participation took all of 20 minutes; the lab even provides sitters
for siblings. Informal, at-home observations about what she can and
can't do continue, of course. (Lately, she does a little dancing
baby routine when her daddy whistles a tune, and she's most
enamored with a large yellow and green plastic cup.) How much is
too much when it comes to stimulating a baby's brain? Cohen says
most parents know instinctively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important guideline is use your baby as a guide,'' he
says. ``If they're enjoying what you're doing, you're probably
doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babies have this natural tendency to want to learn, but they
have to build their knowledge step by step.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
