<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4328 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALVAGE03-COX     04-02 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVAGE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A new life for old things
 &HT;    By Nicole Villalpando
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Wrought iron gates with rust around the edges.
Pine doors with scratches from a dog. Fireplace mantels with
peeling layers of blue, yellow and white paint. Stained glass
windows with rippling rich-colored panes.
</P>
<P>
   These objects, once destined for the junk yard, are being
transformed into trendy garden accents, wall hangings and
furniture. Homeowners are rummaging through antique stores, used
building supply stores and flea markets to find the perfect piece
of history _ one that will give their homes a flavor different from
the high-tech, high-gloss, modern world they inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   Buying old houses and fixing them up has become the trendy thing
to do, but with the cost of renovation rising and not as many old
homes on the market, some are putting old pieces into new homes to
capture the warmth of an older home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole generation of baby boomers that want to live
in an old house,'' said Brad Kittel of Discovery's ``From the
Past,'' (CQ) a used building supply store in Gonzales. ``They want
nostalgia. They're bored with cookie-cutter homes.''
</P>
<P>
   With old materials, homeowners can fashion several different
looks. They can go funky by hanging old windows, doors and wrought
iron on the wall instead of paintings. Or they can go traditional
by fitting a new home with stained glass windows, long leaf pine
doors and an iron fence.
</P>
<P>
   Some people strip, sand and refinish old pieces to bring them to
their original state. Others, like D'Ette Cole, enjoy the look of
aged materials, complete with scratches, chipped paint and rust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really embrace the texture and patina of old pieces,'' said
Cole, owner of Uncommon Objects.
</P>
<P>
   She points to a a bookcase with paint that is ``alligatoring,''
a process that happens when paint crackles as it is exposed to
heat. ``That's hard to duplicate. To strip it would be a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think they are beautiful as they are. The history a piece
implies _ it's kind of like someone's lost treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right architectural antique can be like looking for
buried treasure, said Sebastian Simon, owner of L'Elysee Antiques.
``Part of the satisfaction is the hunt,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first places to start is local antique stores. Some,
such as Architects &AMP; Heroes and Pieces of the Past, specialize in
architectural antiques. Other antique stores may have a good
selection of one thing such as stained glass, but they may not have
a variety of other things. Shop around to become familiar with each
store's specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Attend events like flea markets, large garage sales and estate
sales. One large event, the Round Top Antique Fair, fills fields
with traditional and architectural antiques twice a year. The next
fair will be April 8-11. Call (409) 249-4042 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Look for large warehouses for used building supplies. In Austin,
Habitat for Humanity runs its Re-Store, which carries new and used
building supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for other used building supply warehouses may take you
out of town. Discovery's ``From the Past'' (CQ) offers 60,000
square feet of architectural antiques. Also look to bigger and
older cities such as Houston and San Antonio for such warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Look around old neighborhoods and get to know demolition
companies. Most architectural antique dealers find merchandise
through these companies.
</P>
<P>
   But locating architectural antiques in Texas can be more of a
challenge than in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is not an old state,'' Kittel of Discovery's said.
``There's not a lot of cool old stuff here.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas' supply also has shrunk as more people renovate old houses
instead of selling them for parts, Kittel said. Most local stores
look for merchandise along the East Coast and in the Midwest. These
regions have buildings that predated the Industrial Revolution and
provided havens for immigrant craftsmen from Europe
</P>
<P>
   Knowing where to look is one thing; understanding what you're
buying is another. Some antique stores stock both old things and
replicas. The first thing to establish is that the object is old.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should really examine it,'' said Marc Elson of Architects
&AMP; Heroes. ``Turn it upside down. It's going to have some type of
flaw.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, the quality of a reproduction won't be as good as
the original, Elson said.
</P>
<P>
   The weight of an object can be a giveaway. Today's doors are
made of thin veneer. Old doors are solid wood. Old iron also will
be solid.
</P>
<P>
   Old wood will show its age by the number of growth rings in an
inch. Old wood has 16 to 30 lines in an inch; new wood will have
four to five lines per inch. The lines also may have darkened with
age, and the wood will have a patina. Expect old wood to be much
harder than new wood.
</P>
<P>
   The type of wood also shows its age. Long leaf pine, a popular
choice among old wood enthusiasts, hasn't been used commercially
since the 1930s. Pitch pine, used in old European doors, was cut
down in Europe by the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you see, the more you develop a kind of sixth
sense,'' said Charles Durham of Durham Trading &AMP; Design Co. ``You
look at the patina in the wood and start to get a feel of how it
was built a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's the way a piece was put together that gives away
its age. Wrought iron fences that have welding marks can't be more
than 60 to 70 years old because that was when welding was first
used. Older iron will have rivets or the pieces will slide together
in slots. ``You see much more detail in older pieces,'' said Kathy
Johnson of Pieces of the Past. ``You also know that that design
can't be duplicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Old stained glass features unsoldered lead joints instead of
soldered aluminum joints. The glass itself will be rippled and come
in more vibrant colors than the new clear glass.
</P>
<P>
   As unique as each old piece is, so is the price. Shop around to
find reputable dealers and to become educated on what's a good
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Even among well-known dealers, prices can vary. Stained glass
sells in Austin for between $45 and $1,000. Doors can be as little
as $35 for a plain, interior door to as much as $5,500 for a pair
of Italian walnut-and-iron exterior doors. Iron gates go for as
little as $60 to as much as $2,500. ``It all depends on the
source,'' said Elson of Architects and Heroes. ``Have they spent a
lot of time back-roading to out-of-the-way places? Did they find it
here in Austin or was it shipped in from somewhere else? Did they
take a plane or did they drive a truck?''
</P>
<P>
   Dealers often look at what the item would cost today if it could
be replicated. Durham points to a set of walnut doors priced at
$5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could get these for less than $5,000 new,''
Durham said. ``I base it on a comparable set of new doors. And if
there's historical significance, that adds to the price.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of making the piece usable should be considered.
Refinishing a claw foot tub with rust spots may cost $350, the same
amount spent on finding one in better shape. Stripping an old door
may add $50 to $75 to the cost of the door. Some dealers will allow
clients to take a piece home to live with it for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to visualize pieces until you get them there,''
Elson said. ``It's a good thing to let people try it and give them
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Choosing the right piece becomes personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have a passion for what they buy,'' Elson said.
``Follow your instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
