</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES STEP FROM ONE NIGHTMARE INTO ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS lede to correct number of refugees leaving Kosovo Friday to
`more than 78,000'; subs 2nd graf to add Montenegro to 1st
sentence. ) (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-WEATHER, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-MCCAIN.) 
(ART ADV: A map showing the flow of refugees out of Kosovo is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JOHN KIFNER  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINI, Albania _ Hounded from their homes and herded by police
cars and tanks into columns that snake through the valleys of
southern Kosovo, the flood of refugees leaving the Serbian province
surged by more than 78,000 people Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1.8 million ethnic Albanians who lived in Kosovo, more
than 310,000 of them have made the journey in the last 10 days to
Montenegro and to neighboring countries like Macedonia and Albania.
NATO officials estimated Friday that some 600,000 refugees still
inside Kosovo are slowly making their way out, and many are
destined for Albania, which has already received more refugees than
any other country.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new refugees are expected to arrive over the next
several days at the tiny border crossing in this small mountain
town. Friday night, when the authorities closed the crossing here
at 9 p.m., long lines of refugees who were waiting to enter Albania
were forced to bed down in open, hostile Serb territory. As they
waited, the line grew constantly as Serb forces continued pushing
groups of refugees toward the border.
</P>
<P>
   But refugees from Kosovo are stepping from one nightmare into
another. Many have not had food or water for three or four days.
They have waited hours, even days, to get here, seeking safety,
shelter and food.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is precious little here. Food supplies are running
out. Water has been off and on during the day and electricity is
flickering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is out of control. It is catastrophic,'' the
Albanian information minister, Musa Ulqini, said Friday as the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees declared ``a major humanitarian
emergency in northern Albania. Even as officials from the UNHCR
held a two-hour emergency meeting Friday night, some 5,000 more
refugees crossed the border here.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Macedonia, 121,000 ethnic Albanian refugees have
streamed into the country, nearly 30 percent of them in the last 24
hours, increasing already-strained relations between ethnic groups
there. And, since last week, some 60,000 have made their way into
Montenegro, still a part of Yugoslavia but increasingly estranged
from its leader, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are witnessing up there is something we have not seen
in Europe since World War II,'' said Andrea Angeli, a spokesman for
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which is
helping coordinate the relief effort.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The small, ramshackle Albanian border town of Kukes, population
20,000, is being quickly overwhelmed by the flood of refugees
despite frantic efforts by Albanian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In an even tinier place, Kouma, with a normal population of
3,500, has swollen to 20,000 by taking in refugees from the Hass
Region, which straddles the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only the tip of the iceberg,'' warned Eugene
O'Sullivan, head of the OSCE observer team as he struggled to find
more sanitation facilities, medical care and food for the even
larger number of refugees that is expected. ``We are reaching a
crisis and it is going to get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Desperately needed here are more transport to ferry the
refugees, many of whom are on foot; food; a field kitchen, and
medical facilities to supplant the poorly equipped local hospital
where eight people have already died after the journey.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee problem is made even more difficult, O'Sullivan and
other aid workers said, because of the isolation of Kukes and the
surrounding area, which is reachable only by a single, crumbling
road that twists and turns dizzily over the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   It is about a six-hour trip from the capital, Tirana, in the
best of times, but now the narrow road itself is clogged with
refugees moving south, most of them in slow-moving farm tractors
pulling carts full of women and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kukes District, the situation has become absolutely
critical,'' Ulqini, the information minister, said. ``During the
night and up to this morning the influx of Albanians in need of
help coming from Kosovo has been extraordinary. The situation is
rapidly getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every household in town has taken in refugees,
sometimes by the dozens, with people sleeping on floors. Others are
packed along the cold concrete floor of a school, gathered in front
of a mosque or in a truck repair lot. Many of those arriving in the
past few nights have been sleeping in open fields, raising fears
among relief workers of cholera unless latrines are dug.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an emergency within an emergency,'' said Angeli the
OSCE spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the difficulty getting supplies here, the first
concern of the relief effort has been to move the refugees out of
the mountains and into tent camps or existing refugee shelters near
Tirana or the Adriatic Sea port of Durres.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian government mobilized buses in the first few days
and successfully brought many of the first wave of refugees out of
the mountains, but the effort has lagged in the past few days even
as the refugee flow has mounted.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, the Albanian government ordered all of its idle
trucks into the mountains to transport people. But even mercenary
cabdrivers from Tirana who hoped to make money carrying refugees
were dismayed by the broken and pot-holed road. ``If I had known
the roads were like this, I never would have come,'' one cabdriver
told a friend. ``Any money I make will go to fix the car.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been little advance planning among relief agencies for
the refugee crisis, apparently because, relief workers said
privately, when this year's budgets were being planned, the
agencies were lulled into the belief that talks between Milosevic
and the West would be successful. Such talks have rarely led to
progress in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
