<HEADER>
A4333 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BAFFERT-LADN     04-02 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BAFFERT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT AN IDEAL AMBASSADOR FOR HORSE RACING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The torch is still in Bob Baffert's hand --
burning like a junkyard blaze for thoroughbred racing's hottest
Triple Crown trainer.
</P>
<P>
   It may all turn to mere glowing embers before this summer is
through -- but for the past two years Baffert has been a wonderful
ambassador for a sport in need of a recognizable figure.
</P>
<P>
   He's charismatic, handsome, quote-worthy, and just happens to be
in position to become the first trainer in history to saddle three
straight Kentucky Derby champions.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure you say. What pressure?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go for four in a row, that's when the pressure
starts,'' Baffert joked recently.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Baffert sends out two of his Kentucky hopefuls as Prime
Timber and General Challenge meet a field of eight in the $750,000
Santa Anita Derby -- the same prep race that produced Baffert's
past two Kentucky Derby Champions, Silver Charm and Real Quiet,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Both Silver Charm and Real Quiet went on to win the Preakness,
giving Baffert a chance at racing's most coveted prize, the Triple
Crown. Both, however, came up short at Belmont. Silver Charm by a
half-length; Real Quiet by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on Baffert to win an unprecedented third straight
Kentucky Derby is not what one might think, however. The most
pressure he felt came when he took Silver Charm to Churchill Downs.
A year earlier he saddled Cavonnier to a second-place finish in the
1996 Kentucky Derby, losing a photo-finish to Grindstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of pressure on myself with Silver Charm
because I had just got beaten by a dirty nose (to Grindstone) right
on the wire,'' Baffert said. ``It was the most devastating loss of
my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once you win a Derby, especially two, it's different the
next time. If I was coming in here with three seconds in a row,
then I would feel heavy duty pressure. Guys would be asking `can
you get it done.' It's like the Broncos going to the Super Bowl all
those years. But now that I've got it, I can have fun now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what has to be done. You need a lot of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert insists all his recent success hasn't changed him, only
the people around him have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really changed,'' he said. ``They (the media) want
me to be (ready to talk) all the time. I'm trying to promote
racing, but I cannot be (available) all the time. And when I'm not,
they say `what's wrong with this guy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when I drive up to the barn and I see all these
camera's and I say `oh my God, here we go again.' I feel like that
movie Analyze This. Maybe I need a (shrink).''
</P>
<P>
   It has almost come to the point where Baffert is expected to
saddle a Kentucky Derby champion every first week in May. He has
raised the bar on himself by competing for the Triple Crown the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the fans) expect me to be there (Kentucky) and be
competitive,'' said Baffert. ``I have my little following and my
fans, but a lot of people don't think like the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the media puts that (pressure to win) out more than
anybody else. They expect me to win it (Kentucky Derby), but not
the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Silver Charm and Real Quiet finished second in the past two
Santa Anita Derbies before winning at Kentucky. Last year's Santa
Anita Derby winner, Indian Charlie, was another from the Baffert
barn.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert started this season with a handful of hopefuls for this
year's Derby -- but his realistic chances of sending a bonafide
contender to Kentucky may stem from today's race.
</P>
<P>
   He has two three-year-old fillies, Excellent Meeting and
Silverbulletday running at other tracks this weekend, but he says
both will likely skip Churchill Downs in favor of the Kentucky
Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Another promising three-year-old, Straight Man, suffered his
first loss recently and this year's winter-book favorite from the
Baffert barn, Exploit, was injured and retired following the Grade
II San Felipe Stakes with a chipped knee.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Baffert with General Challenge and Prime Timber,
whom he said could finish one-two in today's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they're at home at Santa Anita and that's why they're
running together,'' he said. ``It's possible they could finish
first and second, but Desert Hero might be a good horse and Bobby's
(Frankel) really high on Honest Lady. Overall, this is one of the
toughest years I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge will wear blinkers for the first time in his
first start since finishing fifth in the 1 1/16-mile Louisiana
Derby March 14 at the Fair Grounds for his only loss in four
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has dubbed General Challenge, ``The Rodman'' of his
barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how (Dennis) Rodman runs across the court, with all
legs, that's kind of how General Challenge moves,'' Baffert said.
``He didn't show up last time (finishing second) so that's when he
got the nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know he's (General Challenge) a gelding. He's got a
feminine side to him that Rodman can relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   His other hopeful, Prime Timber, has never been worse than
second in six career starts. In Prime Timber's last start, he beat
the previously unbeaten Exploit in the San Felipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Prime Timber would be the favorite (today) after his
last race,'' said Baffert. ``He ran an incredible race. He runs
that race back again he's a galloping winner (today).''
</P>
</TEXT>
