<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-SCHOOL-TAX-ART-2TA     04-02 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-SCHOOL-TAX-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL CRISIS CHIPS AWAY AT NEW HAMPSHIRE'S ANTI-TAX STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does this sound like the New Hampshire known for its ferocious
aversion to taxes?
</P>
<P>
   Polls have found that when New Hampshire residents are asked how
the state should respond to a court decision requiring it to end
its heavy reliance on local property taxes to pay for schools,
hefty proportions favor an income tax.
</P>
<P>
   The school financial crisis is now in overtime. Despite marathon
sessions, lawmakers missed their court-imposed April 1 deadline to
come up with a new system, and no one here is predicting
confidently when or how it will end.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled state House of Representatives passed
a bill three weeks ago that would have established a 3.5 percent
income tax. The state Senate, which turned majority-Democrat last
November for the first time since 1912, passed its own version late
last month, but the House backtracked last Tuesday and rejected the
Senate version.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governor, Jeanne Shaheen, true to her pledge to
resist sweeping new taxes, has vowed to veto any income tax _ a
veto that is not likely to be overridden. And teachers are
beginning to receive warning slips that their jobs may be in
question next fall.
</P>
<P>
   But one fact has emerged clearly from the muddle: New Hampshire
no longer seems such a granite monolith of anti-tax sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of only two states without an income or sales tax.
(The other is Alaska, which is entertaining an income tax proposal
of its own.) But the school-financing issue has brought out signs
that the ``Live Free or Die'' sentiment that is emblazoned on New
Hampshire's license plates, and that has long influenced the
state's first-in-the-nation presidential primary, may be mellowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to exaggerate the changes,'' said John Camobreco,
an assistant professor of political science at the University of
New Hampshire who specializes in state politics. ``But there are
significantly more people, I think, who sort of see that whole
`pledge' and the whole anti-income tax thing as sort of
antiquated.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``pledge'' embodies the essence of New Hampshire's anti-tax
sentiment. For state politicians, it is the pledge to oppose any
sales or income tax, and most candidates have taken the pledge
since the state's largest newspaper, the conservative Manchester
Union Leader, began insisting on it in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential contenders here are prodded to make a parallel
federal commitment to low taxes, and New Hampshire's tax phobia
thus translates into a national advantage for anti-tax candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But the pledge has come under such a heavy attack as the
Statehouse strives to solve its school-financing conundrum that
even a Republican state senator, James Squires, was quoted in The
Union Leader as saying that the pledge ``stifles our thinking and
diminishes our capacity for logic.''
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic state senator, Katherine Wells Wheeler, said New
Hampshire's tax structure ``for a long time was set by one
newspaper,'' referring to The Union Leader. ``All evidence
indicates that newspaper is losing its influence,'' she added, and
that ``is helping to allow people to think more independently.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax question has also brought to the fore the voices of
income tax supporters who normally kept quiet, said Fran Chapman,
chairman of the Granite State Taxpayers Inc., a taxpayers'
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened is some people were scared to talk about it,
and now they're saying, `Let's get out there and do it,''' Chapman
said.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to spur this debate was a decision by the New
Hampshire Supreme Court in 1997 that the state's system of paying
for its schools almost entirely locally, with spending-per-pupil
varying significantly from town to town, was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The decision threw this state of 1.2 million people into the
kind of dilemma that about 30 other states have faced. New
Hampshire is very much like the rest of the country, said Clark
Hubbard, a political science professor at the University of New
Hampshire, in that ``everybody wants good services and nobody wants
to pay for them.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a way, everything matters a bit more here, because this
is the staging ground for future presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard said that in next year's primaries, ``I wouldn't predict
a major backing away from the tax pledge just because it's almost a
cultural part of the primary now and so it has kind of a
traditional ring to it.'' But he added, ``It may be, over the next
couple of election cycles, that New Hampshire will no longer be
able to claim that special tax-exempt status, and will begin to put
less emphasis on taxes as a presidential issue.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The national candidates who are now starting to campaign here
will be stepping into the school-financing crisis at their own
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Shaheen, the state chairman for Vice President Al Gore's
campaign, said that Gore ``basically asked me what he should say,
and I said, `What do you think you should say?' And his response
was absolutely correct, that this was a local issue and should be
decided by the local people of New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   A yet unanswered question, however, is whether the candidates
will conclude that New Hampshire is perhaps not as
libertarian-leaning as they had thought, and will tailor their
campaigns accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The basis for such a conclusion is the idea that the income tax
sentiment is a sign of demographic change. For a generation, New
Hampshire has been the fastest-growing state in New England; its
population nearly doubled in the last 30 years as it transformed
itself from a farm-and-mill backwater to a high-tech powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Well over half the state's residents came from elsewhere, many
from places where they had become used to much heavier and
broader-based taxes. So the prospect of an income tax, the theory
goes, holds little terror for them.
</P>
<P>
   But a countertheory holds that the newer residents sought to
escape high taxes elsewhere, and so they are more likely to oppose
an income tax. State Sen. Beverly Hollingworth, a Democrat, said,
``When you talk to the native New Hampshire people, they are the
ones in general who support making change and providing for
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Wells Wheeler puts it this way: ``We're maturing. We're
realizing our social obligations. We're realizing we can't live
independently with just a barn-raising to help our neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Also influencing the discussion, some say, is the growing
emphasis on education, as demonstrated in polls showing it is the
No. 1 issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature has been examining dozens of plans for raising
the $1 billion or so to pay for public schools. Some have included
a statewide property tax; others have involved gambling taxes,
business taxes and entertainment taxes. New Hampshire already has
one of the highest property tax burdens in the nation, and much of
the discussion has focused on how best to shift that load.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts expect the Legislature to pass some kind of
solution in the next two weeks or so _ even if only a provisional
plan for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Though the court decision carried no explicit penalty for
missing the deadline, as of Thursday, the start of the new
financial year, it became illegal for towns to collect local
property taxes for schools. That means all kinds of possible
complications for the next school year, from hiring teachers to
sending out tax bills. School administrators look with dread toward
July 1, when money will run out unless the Legislature comes up
with a workable plan.
</P>
<P>
   The state's consideration of tax plans has frazzled lawmakers
but has provided a fabulous civics lesson at meetings and debates
throughout New Hampshire, said Chapman of the Granite State
Taxpayers. One forum was so lively it reminded him of a revival
meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Camobreco, at the University of New Hampshire, said that in the
end, new light may be cast on the nature of New Hampshire, but it
is important to be wary of ascribing major change to the state's
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there are people who voted for an income tax,'' he said.
``But they never would've gotten a chance to cast that vote without
the Supreme Court _ never in a million years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
