<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4342 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-02 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENCES CAN ALSO BRING FAITHS CLOSER TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year after a much-criticized Vatican document on the
Holocaust, Jewish and Christian scholars find even its weaknesses a
tool of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, on the brink of a week when Jews and Christians
were to remember and re-enact core moments of their faiths, it was
appropriate that Jewish and Christian scholars should gather to
discuss a document called ``We Remember.''
</P>
<P>
   That document's full title, of course, was ``We Remember: A
Reflection on the Shoah.'' When it was issued, a little more than a
year ago, by the Vatican's Commission for Religious Relations With
the Jews, the disappointment among many was palpable.
</P>
<P>
   True, the document was introduced by a moving letter from Pope
John Paul II, who called the Holocaust ``an indelible stain on the
history of the century'' and urged Catholics to ``purify their
hearts, through repentance,'' and to ``examine themselves on the
responsibility which they too have for the evils of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   The document itself called on Catholics to repent of Christian
contributions to the Holocaust, asking them to replace all traces
of Christian anti-Judaism with an awareness of their own faith's
Hebrew roots and with a new, mutually respectful relationship with
the Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spoiled seeds of anti-Judaism and anti-Semitism,'' the
document concluded, ``must never again be allowed to take root in
any human heart.''
</P>
<P>
   For many readers, though, both Catholic and Jewish, those
powerful appeals were undercut by passages that seemed worded more
to exonerate the church than to take responsibility or inspire
repentance.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if a heartfelt appeal had fallen into the hands of
legal experts whose job it was to protect Catholicism from the
theological equivalent of civil suits.
</P>
<P>
   That is probably not the way that Cardinal Edward Cassidy, the
Vatican official who signed ``We Remember'' as president of the
Commission for Religious Relations With the Jews, would express it.
</P>
<P>
   But at this week's consultation of scholars, which took place
from Sunday through Tuesday in Chicago and was co-sponsored by the
Cardinal Joseph Bernardin Center for Theology and Ministry and the
Tanenbaum Center for Interreligious Understanding, Cassidy gave
more than one indication of the Vatican gantlet his document had to
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest difficulty was the fear that if you say the
church has been wrong in the past, then it can be wrong today and
tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy offered that comment during a discussion of an aspect of
``We Remember'' that had stirred criticism: its distinction between
the church itself and its sinful members.
</P>
<P>
   In previous talks as well as in a public address during the
Chicago meeting, he maintained that this distinction was not meant
to shield the highest church authorities while pointing a finger at
the failings of ordinary Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The ``sinful sons and daughters'' of the church, he made clear,
could include not only laity but also popes, cardinals, bishops and
``even renowned teachers of faith'' _ whoever had fostered mistrust
and hostility toward Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was this distinction meant to avoid a kind of collective
responsibility, he explained, for just as Catholics understand that
they are linked to the merits of their saints, they are similarly
linked to the sins of their wrongdoers.
</P>
<P>
   That did not end the consultation's pursuit of the question,
however. The Catholic scholars recognized the weight of
longstanding images of the church _ mystical body, bride of Christ,
spotless lamb _ all pointing to a sinless, divine dimension beyond
the human weaknesses of its members.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish scholars acknowledged that there were analogous
mystical, transcendent understandings of the covenanted people. But
both groups remained troubled by the way such conceptions might
float above history and humanity _ and responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Did the distinction between the sinless church and its
potentially sinful members, one participant asked, not dissolve
corporate responsibility into individual biography? Did the
distinction, others asked, not leave unattended the harmful
influences no longer associated with any individual church members
but institutionalized and embedded in art, liturgies, popular
devotions, widespread teachings and church decrees?
</P>
<P>
   The group was just as unrelenting in its pursuit of other
aspects of ``We Remember'' that had raised objections: first, its
sharp distinction between Christian anti-Judaism and modern
anti-Semitism, especially Nazi anti-Semitism, with ``its roots
outside of Christianity''; and second, its unqualified defense of
Pope Pius XII, whose policies in regard to the Holocaust are still
contested.
</P>
<P>
   The very vigor of the discussion revealed a deep confidence that
Catholic-Jewish relations had taken a decisive turn and now stood
on a new footing. Opinions never broke down along religious lines.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the question was theological or historical, whether the
topic was anti-Jewish statements of the church fathers or Vatican
diplomacy in 1942, there was more convergence than divergence, more
search for precise, nuanced positions than for contrasting
extremes.
</P>
<P>
   And encouraged by Cassidy's obvious willingness to listen and by
the knowledge that Catholic-Jewish dialogue was now implanted in
many local centers, participants concluded that even the
shortcomings of ``We Remember,'' no less than its strengths, might
be turned to the good purposes of further probing conversations.
</P>
<P>
   There is, after all, a calm determination as well as an
acknowledgment of human limitation to be found in a phrase that
Rabbi Irving Greenberg, president of the Jewish Life Network,
offered to the consultation: ``After Auschwitz, there can be no
final solutions, even theological ones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
