<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BROWNS-770&AMP;ADD(2T     04-02 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-770&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CLEVELAND BROWNS RUSHING INTO EXISTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEREA, Ohio _ Al Lerner recently watched his first indoor
practice and nearly got trampled. Lerner, the billionaire owner of
the expansion Cleveland Browns, lingered on a sideline, his hands
in his pants pockets, when halfback Malcolm Thomas raced full speed
toward him.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Policy, the team's president and part owner, pushed
Lerner to safety. ``Al was reluctant to go,'' Policy said later,
``and I dragged him there. I said it would be fun. All I could
think of was visiting him at the Cleveland Clinic, his leg up in
traction, and he says, `For this, I paid $530 million?'''
</P>
<P>
   What Lerner saw of his huge investment were 73 men _ expansion
draftees, free agents and trade acquisitions _ in brown, white and
orange, scrimmaging with unusual ardor as cameras above one end
zone and at midfield recorded every movement of the
team-in-progress.
</P>
<P>
   In his first NFL head coaching job, Chris Palmer prowled the
artificial turf, windmilling his right arm, urging the players to
move faster, then faster. Running back Terry Kirby wondered about
the raw intensity of this first practice, in shorts and no pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shocking,'' said Kirby, a free-agent acquisition.
``This is March. Isn't March Madness supposed to be about
basketball? No, obviously this March Madness is football madness.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what Lerner, a 65-year-old banker, got for his $530
million on the first day of minicamp. ``Being involved in football,
sitting at the edge of my seat waiting for the first game, is all
good stuff,'' he said. Lerner is poker-faced; Policy, garrulous.
Lerner needed Policy's football acumen. Policy is enamored of
Lerner's desire to spend lavishly. They frequently set up each
other's sentences and thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are learning very quickly,'' Policy said, ``that you
have to know what you're talking about with him, and there's no
shame in saying, `I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   Once Lerner entered the Browns sweepstakes, he became the
prohibitive favorite. The wealthiest of the bidders, Lerner is a
friend of Commissioner Paul Tagliabue of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   As a limited partner in the old Browns, he counseled Art Modell
to take them to Baltimore as the Ravens in 1996. After a period of
public reproval for aiding Modell, he is adapting to the type of
public role he has never led as the chairman of the MBNA
Corporation, the nation's third-largest credit card lender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to walk in and out of restaurants or go to public
places,'' he said at a conference room table in Policy's office.
``Would I like to go back to my life of quiet desperation? I'd like
to, but it's OK''
</P>
<P>
   ``He isn't comfortable with it,'' Policy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do the drill,'' Lerner said.
</P>
<P>
   For a city that mourned and raged when Modell fled to Baltimore,
this team-in-formation will do quite fine. And Lou Groza likes what
he sees. Groza, the legendary kicker for the original Browns who is
now 75, watched the practice from a chair far from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a relative coming home,'' Groza said.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the new Browns and the Browns-turned-Ravens are
division rivals and will play each other twice a year. Their first
meeting is Sept. 26 in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The return of the Browns is an NFL success story in the modern
era of stadium-driven sports economics.
</P>
<P>
   It began with Modell's secret talks with Maryland officials,
escalated into angry protests that forced Modell's permanent exile
from Cleveland and provoked Capitol Hill hearings about franchise
relocation and concern that the NFL could do nothing to prevent
carpetbagging by teams.
</P>
<P>
   The saga ended with an agreement to reseed the Browns as an
expansion team, build a publicly financed stadium for $283 million
(with nearly all revenue going to the team) and orchestrate a
high-profile auction, which led to Lerner's buying the team for
what was then a record sum. (The $800 million sale of the
Washington Redskins to a group led by the New York real estate
magnate Howard Milstein is pending.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If you gave me a team for free in any other city, I wouldn't
take it,'' Lerner said. ``This is the only team I have any
intention to own.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a game played, every seat, luxury box and club seat in
the stadium is sold out. Combine the stadium cash with $58.1
million in network television money this year (and steadily more in
each year thereafter), and profitability looks imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make a profit,'' Lerner said. ``But do you produce a
return as good as a government bond? Not for a long time. But you
can't watch your T-bills play. This is a business, but it's not a
business. You have to win. It wouldn't be a success if it only made
money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The rebirth of the Browns introduces high expectations, which
Lerner is underwriting with his desire to spend what is necessary
for talent; to rebuild five outdoor practice fields and redo the
Berea headquarters for $2 million, and to restock a weight room
left empty when Modell left.
</P>
<P>
   But the hopes are fueled by the near-instant prosperity of the
previous expansion teams, the Jacksonville Jaguars and the Carolina
Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   After coming to life in 1994, they played in their conferences'
championship games the next season. Never mind that Jacksonville
and Carolina had nearly two years to prepare for their first
college draft and the Browns barely six months.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Browns are not guaranteed top draft picks in
their second season, as their expansion predecessors did. And never
mind that Lerner, Policy and Dwight Clark, the vice president for
football operations, have never built an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more difficult than I thought,'' said Policy, the
former San Francisco 49ers president, who has a 10 percent stake in
the team. ``Managing the 49ers during the '90s is entirely
different from what we're experiencing now. We had a structure in
place. We had to maintain, fine-tune and improve it. But it's
daunting to start from nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Browns, the future is virtually now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be competitive in Year 2 or 3,'' said Clark, whom
Policy brought from San Francisco and who has imported 12 former
49ers. ``We have higher expectations than the people outside this
building.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1999 win-loss record is of low priority, at least to the
architects,'' Policy said. ``We want to compete for the AFC Central
championship in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lerner: ``They have to be realistic. I don't. I want to win
every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, 49, who was hired for his teaching skills, started his
quest to become a head coach a year ago. He was a head coach at
Boston University and the University of New Haven, but an assistant
since then with the Houston Oilers, the New England Patriots and
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're close to 50, your options start to dry up,'' he
said, sitting in a rented black chair in his office. His work with
the Patriots and Jaguars, especially with young quarterbacks, was
known to other teams, but he was not on the top rung of Cleveland's
coaching candidates. Still, his ``token'' interview with Policy and
Lerner went unexpectedly well, and he was hired for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin, Palmer's boss from 1997 to
1998, advised him, ``Get going, you're already behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer knows about high expectations. He is reminded of them
when he sees how little time he has to invest the team with
chemistry and discipline and satisfy fans who have waited three
years to see their Browns. He knows it from the task of dealing
with his assistant coaches, most of whom he has never worked with.
He knows it from the bus driver who shouted at him, ``Take the
quarterback, it's what you know,'' regarding the April 17 college
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the real world,'' Palmer said. ``I go to lunch in
a place near here and you see a sign that says, `154 days until
Browns football,' and I can't enjoy lunch very much. We have two
years to win.''
</P>
<P>
   How quickly the Browns win may depend on whom they choose with
the expected No. 1 pick in the draft. It could be a quarterback,
like Tim Couch of Kentucky or Akili Smith of Oregon, or it could be
the Heisman Trophy-winning running back Ricky Williams of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That top choice _ and others _ would add to to the core built
through the expansion draft (with onetime Browns cornerback Antonio
Langham the main pickup), free agency (Kirby, free safety Marquez
Pope, offensive tackle Lomas Brown and defensive tackle John
Jurkovic) and trades (quarterback Ty Detmer, defensive lineman Roy
Barker and tight end Irv Smith, all from the 49ers, who were
clearing salary-cap room, center Dave Wohlabaugh and linebacker
Chris Spielman).
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of those quarterbacks can take us all the way, we have
to take him,'' said Clark, ``even if he goes through what Peyton
Manning did.'' But Clark remembers how Joe Montana broke in with
the 49ers under coach Bill Walsh: ``Bill had Joe watch until he
started for the first time in the middle of the second season.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch seemed like the Browns' certain choice until Smith's
workout with the team raised his profile. The Browns could deal
their top pick; New Orleans Saints coach Mike Ditka has offered all
his draft picks to leap into the first or second slot and take
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision on the first pick will affect me more than anyone
else,'' Palmer said. ``If it's a good pick, I get to stay a while.
If it's not, I don't. I just want to be the first Browns coach to
get a contract extension.''
</P>
<P>
   All he need do is mold Couch (or Smith) into a Lake Erie version
of Montana, take the Browns to the AFC championship game in 2001,
and turn Al Lerner's $530 million gamble into a sure thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
