<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SECOND FRONT IN THE BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 3:
</P>
<P>
   The torrent of refugees surging out of Kosovo has overwhelmed
the international effort to help them. If more assistance is not
rushed to the region by the United States and its European allies,
thousands of lives will be imperiled. President Clinton's pledge of
more financial aid for humanitarian organizations is welcome, but
the scale of the exodus requires the immediate mobilization of U.S.
and European governmental resources to transport water, food,
clothing, medicine and temporary shelter to the regions that border
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the upheavals of the Second World War has Europe
witnessed such a mammoth and sudden flood of refugees. In the last
week, more than three-quarters of a million ethnic Albanians have
been driven from their homes and villages in Kosovo by marauding
Serbian forces, and some 250,000 of them have already streamed
across the border into neighboring Albania, Macedonia and
Montenegro, another province of Yugoslavia. Tens of thousands are
backed up waiting to cross the frontier, huddled in the hills and
pastures without water and food in lines that extend 10 miles or
more back into Kosovo. The scenes in Albania of crying,
malnourished children, exhausted women clutching their infants and
old men reaching weakly for a slice of bread testify powerfully to
the urgent need for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus has put an unbearable burden on Albania, Macedonia
and Montenegro, three of the poorest lands in Europe. All three are
threatening to close their borders. As the number of refugees has
mounted in recent days, supplies of water and food have run short
in some places, and thousands of displaced people were left
yesterday without any help. Disease and death will soon stalk these
refugee encampments if aid is not available.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with relief organizations on Frirday, promising more
money and logistical support from NATO troops in Macedonia, but
this is not enough. Clinton must order the Pentagon to organize a
U.S. airlift of supplies to the region and send troops to the
border region to help distribute the aid and to construct temporary
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   European nations, for their part, must send assistance and
provide temporary sanctuary for some of the refugees. Britain,
France, Germany, Greece, Turkey and other nations cannot duck this
responsibility. Conditions in Kosovo will eventually improve and
the ethnic Albanians will be able to return home, but it may take
months to create the security and political arrangements for
repatriation. Until then, the governments of Albania, Macedonia and
Montenegro will need large infusions of financial assistance.
Montenegro is especially vulnerable because it is a relatively
independent and democratic republic within Slobodan Milosevic's
domain. He is already moving to assert greater control, and Serbian
forces may soon be headed there.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the brutality of Milosevic's troops, the conflict in
Kosovo has created a refugee crisis in the Balkans that threatens
to destabilize the region. Dealing with it, and preserving the
lives of hundreds of thousands of desperate people, are no less
important than crippling the Serbian military in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
