<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-1STLD-     04-02 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS GOALS ARE STILL ATTAINABLE WITH AIR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: subs to reorganize and rewrite; new quotes, details
throughout) 
 (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-WEATHER, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, As allied forces prepared their attack on downtown
Belgrade Friday, the White House warned President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia that he had ``barely begun'' to feel NATO's
bombers and cruise missiles attack.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to halt any public doubts after 10 days of on-again,
off-again bombing of Yugoslavia, President Clinton sought to assure
Americans that the campaign against Milosevic would succeed. The
bombing has so far done nothing to halt the Serbian advance through
Kosovo province and the flood of refugees into neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
   And the White House sent a clear signal that it was turning the
attack more directly on the Yugoslav leader and his high command.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic has barely begun to incur the damage he will feel to
his military and police and the security apparatus by which he
keeps his dictatorship in power,'' Vice President Al Gore told
reporters after a lengthy late-afternoon national security
briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, President Clinton, too, warned that
Milosevic would pay a heavy price for continuing his policy of
``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that despite the exodus of refugees from
Kosovo, the military and political objectives of the Western allies
were still attainable with an air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have quite a good chance of achieving our
objectives of the return of the Kosovars to live in security with a
measure of self-government,'' Clinton told reporters Friday as he
made a hastily announced appearance in the White House briefing
room.
</P>
<P>
   Gore described Milosevic's activity as so ``morally
unacceptable'' that the bombing would be so extensive, that a
political settlement might be moot. ``Whether or not a negotiation
with Milosevic is ever again possible,'' he said, ``that's an open
question, frankly, because he has perpetrated these horrible crimes
against humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Expressing confidence that the bombing would succeed, Gore added
of Milosevic: ``He has forced many of those people from their homes
before, and they have returned. These, too, will return.''
</P>
<P>
   The president spoke before the announcement Friday night that
NATO missiles had hit downtown Belgrade. Earlier this week he had
approved a target list for the NATO strikes that included
ministerial buildings and headquarters in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday afternoon Clinton suggested that the framework of the
failed peace talks in France would still serve as the basis for any
settlement, and that NATO _ and the United States _ would help the
refugees return to Kosovo and provide for their protection. For the
Kosovars to live with some degree of autonomy, he said, ``will
require, clearly, for some period of time, some sort of
international force that will be able to protect their security.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I think there will have to be some sort of security
arrangement in order for them to live safely. And then there will
have to be some sort of agreement that entails the autonomy to
which they are entitled.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the administration has been privately considering
a plan under which NATO troops would escort ethnic Albanians back
into Kosovo after Serbian forces there had been routed by bombing,
and would set up a self-governing enclave under allied protection,
NATO officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday Clinton still seemed frustrated by the difficulty in
explaining the mission, its objectives and its ramifications.
``Everyone is trying to get their hands around a very complex
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president is measuring his responses to the Balkan war and
also publicly engaging in other matters. He talked at the briefing
Friday about the new unemployment figures, the lowest since 1970.
He is planning a trip to Philadelphia next week to discuss health
care. And he will be welcoming the Chinese prime minister to
Washington next week as critical talks continue on China's entry
into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls taken before the missile strikes Friday
show that a bare majority of the American public supported the air
strikes but that most believed NATO would not achieve its
objectives.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News poll taken Wednesday after three American soldiers
were taken prisoner by the Serbs showed that 51 percent supported
the bombing and 34 percent opposed it. But a recent survey by CNN,
USA Today and Gallup found that only 41 percent thought NATO would
accomplish its objectives while 47 percent said it would not.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted Friday that Kosovo was not lost, but he also
focused on the humanitarian relief efforts that have been under way
there for a year. With television images of Kosovo refugees
streaming across the border with Albania and Macedonia, Clinton
continued to try to dispel the notion that the NATO bombing had
escalated Milosevic's violence against ethnic Albanians and
prompted the exodus.
</P>
<P>
   He said relief worker she met with Friday had told him that the
refugees supported the bombing and clearly understood ``that that
action did not provoke the attempt to remove them from their
homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Asking other countries to help with the relief effort, Clinton
sought to use the plight of the displaced people to dramatize the
need for the continued air strikes. ``There's no doubt that what
Milosevic wants to do is to keep the land of Kosovo and rid it of
its people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He brought with him to the briefing several government officials
to reinforce the idea that the exodus from Kosovo had been going on
for some time. Hattie Babbitt, deputy administrator of the U.S.
Agency for International Development, said of the exodus: ``It's
not a new phenomenon. There's a new urgency to it, there's a new
scale to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Taft, assistant secretary of state for population,
refugees and migration, called Milosevic's attacks on Kosovars a
``pogrom'' and said that the government had been working with
relief agencies for more than a year to respond to the uprooting.
The United States has sent $91 million to the region since last
year, and Clinton authorized $50 million more on Wednesday,
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
