<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-ADAMS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dooley had final say in hiring Harrick
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley made the
decision on hiring Jim Harrick as Georgia's basketball coach,
according to all parties involved in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley had the support of Georgia president Michael Adams. But a
flurry of media reports, relying on unidentified sources, described
a situation in which Adams made the decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be further from the truth, Dooley and Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he could see why some people might misconstrue his
involvement in the athletics department. For one thing, he's
interested in sports. ``And I also think that we have just had two
very high-profile situations,'' Adams said Friday. ``The possible
departure of (football) Jim Donnan (to North Carolina last year)
and the situation with the basketball coach _ both of which I hope
we don't have to deal with for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend less than 15 percent of my time on athletics,'' Adams
said. ``And the fact is, if you are the president of the University
of Georgia, you will spend some time on athletics, because some
situations have institutional implications as well as athletic
implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports that Adams had been heavily involved in the search and
in the job offer seemed to be reinforced Thursday night when Adams
and senior associate athletics director Dick Bestwick met reporters
to explain Harrick's stunning reversals.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley, however, was in Virginia on a long-planned trip with his
grandson. And it had been Dooley who decided late Thursday
afternoon that Harrick would become the Georgia coach, despite the
coach's change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported that Adams and Harrick and their wives had
a friendship when both men worked at Pepperdine University.
</P>
<P>
   By telephone from Virginia, Dooley said, ``Dr. Adams played a
significant role in that he knew Harrick the man. I only knew about
Harrick as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams was kept advised of developments from the beginning of the
search, shortly after Ron Jirsa was fired March 11, Dooley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He treated this like any other search,'' Dooley said.
``Certainly, as president he had a final veto, as he would with any
dean. He said he would like to interview the final two. I welcomed
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley declined to comment on reports that the job was offered
to another candidate before Harrick, but no one at Georgia has
denied it. Harrick made reference to it in his initial news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley and Adams interviewed Harrick at the Final Four in
Florida. ``In St. Petersburg, we had interviews, and I wanted him
there,'' Dooley said. ``That was my choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick said Friday that he saw nothing unusual about Adams
being present at the interview in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I interviewed at UCLA, and the chancellor was in the room
during the whole interview,'' Harrick said. ``I interviewed with
the president at Pepperdine. I interviewed with the president at
Rhode Island. So Im not surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick also said that Adams said little during the interviewing
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the only involvement Mike Adams had was getting my
name on the list,'' Harrick said. ``From then on, and in the
interview, he didn't say much at all. It was mostly Coach Dooley.
And I never had a phone call from Michael Adams; I had them all
with Coach Dooley. He was the point guy on it, and, as far as I
know, he made the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick called Adams late Thursday and said he had changed his
mind again, that he wanted the Georgia job if it was still his, the
university president said. But Adams said he told Harrick that he
would not make that decision, that Dooley would have to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that were not the case, I would not be athletic director,''
Dooley said Friday. ``And people who know me know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
