<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-HARRICK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harrick got `emotional about family'
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ One day after his flip-flop-flip on whether to
become Georgia's men's basketball coach, Jim Harrick was able to
stand Friday before a firing line of television cameras and
newspaper reporters at Stegeman Coliseum and make light of a
situation that wasn't very funny 24 hours before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I didn't make everybody in two states mad,'' cracked
Harrick, knowing full well he had. ``I'm sure some people have
called and asked, `Do you need psychological help?'''
</P>
<P>
   But Harrick turned serious when the questions turned to why he
accepted the Georgia position amid much pomp and circumstance, only
to back out less than a day later and bolt for Rhode Island. And
why, then, come back?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got emotional about (my family), and that's all it
was,'' Harrick said. ``I went back home. But when I got off the
plane, my family was waiting for me, and I talked to all three of
my sons and they said, `(Georgia) is the best place for you. Now
get on that plane and go back.' (Georgia was) gracious enough to
let me do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an emotional thing. If you have family, if you
have kids, you understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick returned to Athens late Friday morning and hit the
ground running. After a brief meeting with the coaching staff that
has been in place, Harrick spent much of the day on the telephone.
He said he called the Bulldogs' five signees for next season,
called four or five recruits and spoke to Jumaine Jones'
high-school
</P>
<P>
   coach, Rufus McDuffie.
</P>
<P>
   After a 25-minute news conference early in the afternoon,
Harrick was whisked to the airport by Georgia assistant coach
Michael Hunt. Harrick said he was bound for Michigan where he was
to attend the Magic Johnson High School All-Star Game Friday night.
He will return for the Naismith Awards banquet tonight in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick conceded that, even without his moment of indecision,
rebuilding Georgia's basketball program is going to be a monumental
task. From this season's 15-15 team, the Bulldogs lose five
seniors, and possibly sophomore Jones to the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a big job to do,'' he said. ``You always hope you
can do it in one year, but I don't know if we can do it that fast.
There's some freshmen point guards that are going to have to play,
and that's always tough in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick bristled when asked if his actions might have crippled
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this a long time, and I can handle whatever
recruiting is required,'' Harrick said. ``I recruited at UCLA for
eight years and Pepperdine for nine and Rhode Island for two, so
I'm well equipped for things like that. Anybody that wants to use
this negatively, that's fine. But we don't ever talk about other
schools or other coaches. It's always seemed to work out for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick also has a recruiting job to do among the Bulldogs'
returning players. After initially embracing Harrick's hiring, some
players seemed more wary on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disgusted,'' freshman D.A. Layne said of hearing the
news Harrick was returning to Rhode Island. ``I couldn't believe
it. My first reaction was hurt and disappointment. I'm confused,
but you just have to move on and think about it in a positive way.
I'm glad he's back now.''
</P>
<P>
   However, center Robb Dryden said, ``I don't think there will be
any doubts in any of the players' minds. We pretty much understand
what he was going through from his standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick said he thinks everyone will get over his inauspicious
start as soon as the season starts and the Bulldogs start out to
win games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first dunk we get,'' he said, ``people will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
