<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 ( js ) 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOBLESS RATE FALLS TO 4.2 PERCENT, ITS LOWEST LEVEL IN 29 YEARS
</P>
<P>
   The nation's jobless rate dropped to 4.2 percent in March, its
lowest level in 29 years, in the latest of many signs that the
nation's labor market remains remarkably robust.
</P>
<P>
   But in a break from the feverish hiring of the last three years,
American companies added far fewer new workers to their payrolls
last month than had been typical lately.
</P>
<P>
   AN ARREST IN THE MELISSA VIRUS CASE
</P>
<P>
   A 30-year-old software programmer, David L. Smith, was arrested
and charged with creating the Melissa virus, a computer virus that
has infected more than 100,000 computers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN PRIVATIZATION PLAN OPPOSED
</P>
<P>
   At a recent hearing on President Ernesto Zedillo's proposal to
privatize Mexico's electric power industry, government workers who
oppose the plan broke out singing Mexico's national anthem. The
patriotic incident underlined the struggle that Zedillo faces in
raising support for the privatization plan, which he says is
urgently needed to attract $25 billion in investments to modernize
and expand the country's power generation and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA IS INVESTING IN PUBLIC WORKS
</P>
<P>
   Beijing spent nearly $200 billion on public construction
projects last year, and plans to do the same this year.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN MAY END LIGHT-TRUCK VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Motors, Japan's second-largest automaker, said that it
might end its light-truck venture with DaimlerChrysler. Renault
bought a 37 percent stake in Nissan after DaimlerChrysler abandoned
plans to acquire a stake in Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   PUNITIVE TARIFFS MAY BE CONSIDERED
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. International Trade Commission found that a surge in
imports of low-priced carbon steel plate from Japan, South Korea
and four other countries may have injured American steelmakers
enough to warrant consideration of punitive tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK PRICES WERE MIXED IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Japanese stock prices closed mixed, with the shares of
export-dependent companies benefiting from the dollar's gains
against the yen. The Nikkei average of 225 stocks fell 37.37
points, to 16,290.19.
</P>
<P>
   A DEADLINE FOR CREDIT LYONNAIS BIDS
</P>
<P>
   Companies seeking stakes in Credit Lyonnais, the French
state-owned bank, will have until April 28 to put in bids for up to
10 percent apiece.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS WILL OPEN MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   Stock and most commodity markets were closed Friday in the
United States and many other countries in observance of Good
Friday. United States bond markets were open until noon. All U.S.
and most overseas markets will reopen on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
