<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Myanmar: Memorial for Activist's Husband
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people joined the Burmese pro-democracy leader Daw
Aung San Suu Kyi at her home for a ceremony to mark the death of
her British husband, Michael Aris. Officials had denied his
requests for a visa to visit her before he died of cancer.
Diplomats from the U.S., Japan and European countries attended the
ceremony, but there was no official Myanmar representative.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Carter Confident on Vote
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter, who will help monitor Indonesia's
general election in June, said he believed that the government and
military were committed to a free and fair ballot. He also said he
was confident the country's struggling economy would rebound if the
election is successful.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Scottish Poll Favors Labor
</P>
<P>
   A new poll shows that the Labor Party would beat the Scottish
National Party if the election for the new Scottish Parliament were
held today. In a survey of 880 Scots, 45 percent supported Labor,
32 percent backed the Scottish National Party, 12 percent supported
the Liberal Democrats and 10 percent backed the Conservatives. The
election is to be held May 6.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay: Seeking Trade Breaks
</P>
<P>
   The newly installed president, Luis Gonzalez Macchi, proposed
that the Mercosur trade union rewrite its rules to give Paraguay
and Uruguay new trade concessions. There was no immediate response
from Brazil and Argentina, the leaders of the union. Macchi's
statement was viewed as an expression of anger toward Argentina for
granting asylum to a retired general accused of ordering the
assassination of Vice President Luis Maria Argana.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Leftist Vote Annulled
</P>
<P>
   The main leftist party, Democratic Revolution, has annulled the
results of its March 14 internal elections, acknowledging the vote
was marred by the balloting abuses it has often accused the ruling
party of committing. The two candidates for party president who
finished in a virtual tie both criticized the annulment, but Andres
Manuel Lopez Obrador, the outgoing president, said, ``We'll do it
over: free, clean and democratic elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: 5 Held in Murders
</P>
<P>
   Five men, including several drivers of buses that carry women to
factory jobs, have been arrested in connection with sexual murders
in Ciudad Juarez. Authorities accused an Egyptian-born chemist in a
Juarez prison for rape and murder of hiring the men to commit the
murders in hopes that new sexual crimes after his arrest would
persuade a judge he was not responsible for dozens of previous
killings. He was convicted on March 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-AIGNER-NYT &LR;      04-02 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-AIGNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCIEN AIGNER, PIONEER NEWS PHOTOGRAPHER, DIES AT 97  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif., Conn., Hungary, France)   By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucien Aigner, a pioneer in candid news photography in the 1930s
whose best-known photographs include one of a rumpled Albert
Einstein in front of a blackboard, died on Monday in a nursing home
in Waltham, Mass. He was 97.
</P>
<P>
   In the '30s, photographers like Aigner, Erich Salomon, Alfred
Eisenstaedt and Robert Capa used the unobtrusive 35mm Leica to take
off-the-cuff pictures that were revolutionary at the time and that
hold a owerful immediacy more than half a century later. A reporter
and photojournalist for Az Est, a Budapest newspaper, Aigner left
for Paris in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 10 years he established a name for himself as an
enterprising photojournalist whose pictures appeared in
publications in Paris and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the small Leica, Aigner had the advantage of his height
(an unobtrusive five feet), enabling him to photograph where others
might have been too noticeable. He took striking pictures of
smoke-filled strategy sessions during the 1931 French presidential
election, for example, and caught Mussolini pinching his nose
during an international conference in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   A selection of his photographs was reproduced in a 1979 book,
``Lucien Aigner,'' published by the International Center for
Photography in New York as part of its Library of Photographers
series.
</P>
<P>
   A 1934 picture of ballet practice at the Paris Grand Opera will
probably remind the viewer of a Degas painting. But while the four
dancers strike beautifully casual poses, the expressions on their
faces vary from doubt to glee to faraway dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   Among Aigner's photographs of world leaders, his picture of
Emperor Haile Selassie of Ethiopia at the train station in Geneva
in 1935 is probably the most haunting. Selassie was to appear
before a League of Nations session to ask for help as his country
was being overrun by Mussolini's troops, and his face seems to bear
witness to all the sorrows of his country.
</P>
<P>
   Aigner's portraits are among his best images. There is a
delightfully unexpected profile of the pianist Paderewski, taken in
New York in 1941. He is sitting on a low chair reading a newspaper,
his figure in shadow, the sun shining on the back of his newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Aigner was born in Hungary, on Sept. 14, 1901. While working as
reporter for a Budapest newspaper, he was assigned to escort James
Abbe, an American photographer, on a photographic assignment. Abbe
offered his young tour guide a job in his Paris office. The job
didn't last but Aigner stayed on. In 1939 he moved to the United
States, where his work soon began appearing in such publications as
The New York Times, The Christian Science Monitor, Look, Coronet
and Pageant.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s, he became an announcer and eventually a
producer and director at the Voice of America. In the early '50s,
during the McCarthy era, he was forced to leave his job, and for
the next 20 years or so operated a portrait studio in Great
Barrington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Aigner gave up his portrait studio to concentrate on
cataloguing and indexing his 100,000 or so negatives. Half of them,
mostly taken in the '30s, were accidentally rediscovered in 1970
when he opened an old suitcase that his brother, the designer
Etienne Aigner, had taken from Paris during World War II. The
suitcase, abandoned in a Paris apartment that was taken over by the
Germans during their occupation of France, was rescued by the
concierge.
</P>
<P>
   Aigner is survived by four children, John Peter of Brooklyn,
Steven Andrew of Trumbull, Conn., Anne-Marie of Belmont, Mass., and
Katherine Veronice Collins of San Francisco; his brother of New
York, Paris and Cannes; a sister, Elizabeth Zentall of Laguna
Hills, Calif.; 10 grandchildren; and 3 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
