<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTRIGUING SUBPLOTS HIGHLIGHT SANTA ANITA DERBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The West's Kentucky Derby candidates meet
today in a race so contentious, top-ranked U.S. 3-year-old Prime
Timber is rated the third choice on the Santa Anita morning line.
</P>
<P>
   That's the plot for the 62nd Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the subplots that make this one of the more
intriguing editions of the $750,000 race _ the personalities, the
dirty dealing and the matter of sex (gender, anyway).
</P>
<P>
   _Honest Lady tries to be the fifth filly _ the first since
Winning Colors in 1988 _ to win the Santa Anita Derby. She's one of
four fillies around the country to be considered Kentucky Derby
prospects this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fillies are a cut above the usual,'' trainer Bobby
Frankel said. ``I think she can run with these (colts).''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel said Honest Lady and jockey Kent Desormeaux will have to
win ``or have a big excuse'' to go on to the Kentucky Derby. She
fought for the lead and finished a close fifth in the San Rafael
Stakes behind Desert Hero, Prime Timber and Capsized, all in
today's 1[-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel, a Hall of Famer for his success with older horses, has
run only two horses in Kentucky Derbies. He admitted a case of
Derby Fever is the reason he ``might be pushing'' Honest Lady.
</P>
<P>
   _Desert Hero tries to stay unbeaten in his first start for
trainer Richard Mandella, who took over when Saudi Prince Ahmed bin
Salman's Thoroughbred Corp. abruptly fired Wally Dollase in
mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, Mandella hadn't even seen videotape of his new
horse in action, though he liked what he'd read about Desert Hero's
resourceful victory in the San Rafael.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero is 2 for 2 in his brief career. Twelve horses have
taken undefeated records into the Santa Anita Derby and six have
won _ including Indian Charlie last year.
</P>
<P>
   As for Dollase, he's out of business at least temporarily and
the object of sympathy on the Santa Anita backstretch. Dollase is
declining public comment on his firing while haggling continues
over his Thoroughbred Corp. contract.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero is ridden by Corey Nakatani _ Dollase's son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   _Chris McCarron has a little extra incentive when he rides
likely pacesetter High Wire Act after being bounced from General
Challenge by trainer Bob Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stevens, Baffert's No.1 rider, replaces McCarron, who would
have taken his breach-of-contract complaint to the state stewards
if the trainer hadn't promised him attractive future mounts.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy resulted in a public argument Tuesday between
Baffert and McCarron agent Scotty McClellan, during which the
normally affable Baffert shoved the typically low-key McClellan in
the back.
</P>
<P>
   All parties say the dispute is behind them _ but it'll be the
story if High Wire Act pulls an upset. The gelding's wire-to-wire
allowance victory in February earned a 106 Beyer speed figure to
match Prime Timber for the career- high in this field.
</P>
<P>
   _The trainers span a range of personalities from proud D. Wayne
Lukas, the soon-to-be Hall of Famer who has a Santa Anita Derby
entrant for the 21st straight year in Charismatic, to unassuming
Lisa Lewis, the 29-year-old California newcomer who has built a
good reputation since opening a stable in Minnesota nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had only three 2-year-olds last year,'' said Lewis, whose
Capsized can improve. ``You compare that to a guy like Baffert, and
it's pretty amazing to think we've got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is the race's largest personality. He hopes to shoot for
a record third-straight Kentucky Derby victory May 1 after winning
with Silver Charm and Real Quiet _ each a Santa Anita Derby
runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's General Challenge is 3-1 and Prime Timber is 7-2, both
behind 5-2 Desert Hero on the track's morning line, which raised
eyebrows when it was announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't worry about stuff like that (the odds). But I
thought Prime Timber would be favored off his last race,'' Baffert
said, referring to the colt's victory over since-injured barnmate
Exploit in the San Felipe Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber's owner Aaron Jones said a representative of
Dubai's Sheikh Mohammed offered $6 million for the colt on Thursday
but ``I'm not about to sell him, not even for $20 million.''
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge has recorded fast workouts since being fitted
with blinkers following a fifth-place finish in the Louisiana
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the blinkers will help him focus,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   So many distracting side issues surround today's race, maybe the
rest of us should wear blinkers too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
