</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GOTTI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STOP HIM BEFORE HE'S BILLED AGAIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 3:
</P>
<P>
   In the years since Mario Puzo and Marlon Brando lifted their
imaginary mafia to the realm of myth, the gene pool of the real
five families has gotten pretty shallow. John J. Gotti proved that
making wise-guy talk as if federal wiretaps did not exist is really
not the smartest thing for a don to do.
</P>
<P>
   Now it looks like his son and accused heir, 35-year-old John A.
Gotti, is having trouble making ends meet despite the booming
economy. He has, in fact, done something that his alleged
predecessors in La Cosa Nostra would have found unthinkable. Gotti
the younger said to a federal judge, put me in jail, please.
Surprised prosecutors regarded it as an offer they couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Gotti, who is charged with acting as the head of
the Gambino crime family since his father went to prison in 1992,
cannot afford the $24,000 a month he had to pay for security guards
in order to stay out on bail. This development may say something
about the sociology as well as the economics of families associated
with organized crime. It is said that fear of prosecution and
competition from legitimate businesses have made it harder for the
old families to find smart help.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Gotti, now serving life without parole, was reported to
have been proud that his son chose to go into the family business.
Starting Tuesday, the son will have plenty of cell time to think
about whether that was an offer he should have refused.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
