<HEADER>
A4383 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-HULL-STARS-TEX     04-02 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HULL-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL'S ATTITUDE, EFFORT MIGHT SURPRISE BLUES FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier in the season, coach Ken Hitchcock said a trip to St.
Louis would help Brett Hull become an even bigger part of the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a rousing game against his former team in an arena he
helped build could aid Hull in severing his ties to St. Louis _ a
city he owned long before Mark McGwire came along.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull _ who signed as a free agent with the Stars over the
summer, ending an 11-year relationship with the Blues _ missed that
Nov. 21 game because of a bruised kidney. And with all of his
success this season, the return to the Gateway City for today's 2
p.m. game could be anticlimactic.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull doesn't need any gimmicks to separate himself from the
Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play for the Dallas Stars,'' said Hull, defiantly.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates support him, too. In fact, they say fans in St.
Louis might not recognize the new Brett Hull. He's no longer the
brash, ``floating,'' pure goal-scorer they toasted to the tune of
527 goals. Now, he's a hard-working, time-clock-punching, two-way
forward, who happens to score goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him work harder this year than I'd seen him work in
10 years playing against him,'' Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig said.
``Honestly, he's jumped right in, he's worked hard defensively,
he's really fit in. He might not be scoring 50 goals, but what he's
contributed defensively has been well worth missing 10 or 15
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Hitchcock: ``From a technical standpoint, he's a much more
responsible player than when we coached against him. He hasn't
wavered from the challenge that line faces every night. He hasn't
taken away from the focus of that line, he's actually added to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull, the man who once said he was able to score 86 goals in a
season by ``floating and disappearing'' on the ice, has become much
more visible. Along with Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen, Hull plays
on the Stars' top checking line. Hitchcock matches that line
against the other team's top offensive players, believing that with
the defensive ability of Lehtinen and Modano, they will outscore
the other team's top scorers.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days with the Blues, Hull would try to outscore
opponents, for example 3-2, by throwing defensive caution to the
wind. And that would backfire in the games where he didn't score
three goals. Now, he understands that by simply outscoring an
opponent's line, 1-0, he is helping the Stars win.
</P>
<P>
   You want proof? With 987 points in 801 career games entering
this season, Hull had a minus-20 rating for his career _ he had
been on the ice for 20 more even-strength goals than his team had
scored. Hull is a plus-18 so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a completely different game,'' Hull said. ``It was
difficult to adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hull, a right winger, has pulled it off. Not only has he
been defensively responsible, he has added 28 goals among 52 points
_ second-best on the Stars. What's more, he has done that in only
53 games (a pace for 43 goals in an 82-game season) and he has done
it while trying to adjust to a new team and playing the first 15
games as a left winger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made it work, he's shown he can score goals here,''
Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Hull isn't satisfied with his offensive output. But
then again, he never is. He said he measures his performance on
goals and points and would like to push the Stars _ who are in an
offensive slump _ to score more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can score in this system, but there's no emphasis on it.
You don't feel pressure, which I think is bad sometimes,'' Hull
said. ``You can't get lulled into `I don't have to score.' You have
to put pressure on yourself to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the fans in St. Louis are going to see a Hull that's not
so different after all. While he has adapted to the Stars'
defense-first system and has been a quiet force in the dressing
room, the goal-scoring, big-mouthed Brett Hull of old still bubbles
under the surface.
</P>
<P>
   And, believe it or not, nobody wants to take that away from
Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, emotion is a good thing in sports,'' Hull said wistfully.
``And a lack of it is terrible.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
