A4384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CITY-FILES-NYT &LR;      04-02 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CITY-FILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TIME TO UNLOCK CITY FILES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 3: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After two years of trying to wheedle ordinary data out of Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's City Hall, state Comptroller Carl McCall and his
auditors won an important victory this week in New York state's
highest court. The State Court of Appeals ruled that the
comptroller's office has the right to audit how the city has been
delivering its services in such areas as welfare, street cleaning,
parks and police.
</P>
<P>
   As a Republican running for re-election in 1997, Giuliani had
balked at the demand for performance audits by McCall, a Democrat.
The mayor labeled the requests for extra data as ``partisan'' and
gave McCall access only to financial records of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the hand of the courts ever more firmly on Giuliani's
shoulder after this latest in a series of losses on information
issues, City Hall is finally agreeing to open its files to the
comptroller's auditors. The delay might have served the mayor
politically, but it undoubtedly cost city taxpayers in unnecessary
legal bills. These are data that clearly should have been available
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Information has not come easily out of the Giuliani
administration except from a high-profile mayor who meets press and
public daily. That means a mountain of data must be funneled ever
upward to the mayor's office before it can spill into the public
domain. Thus, the comptroller is only the latest in a long line of
supplicants who eventually use a court order to pry open the city's
filing cabinets. Public advocates, citizens and media organizations
including The New York Times have been forced to file Freedom of
Information requests for the most routine city documents.
</P>
<P>
   A state Supreme Court judge ruled this week that the city's
Independent Budget Office can get information directly from city
agencies, rather than through the mayor's budget office. Public
Advocate Mark Green began over two years ago trying to review how
complaints against police were treated within the Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   After repeated stalls and two court orders, Green's lawyers are
expected to begin Monday looking at more than 700 cases. No
politician likes to pass out information that might be used by the
opposition, but too often at New York's City Hall the free flow of
information comes with an unhealthy delay and a costly legal bill.
The courts have affirmed that it is unacceptable for citizens and
the press to have to beg for information that clearly belongs to
everyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4386 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MEDIA-COMMENTARY-T     04-02 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MEDIA-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S UPPER CRUST NEEDS TO SPLIT TV PIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sport's version of ``Les Miserables'', otherwise known as Major
League Baseball, opens Monday, the first act in a compelling
theatrical spectacle wherein the have-nots attempt to launch a
full-scale economic revolution against the haves.
</P>
<P>
   Expect a lot of bloodshed but very little romance come curtain
drop, probably sometime around the end of the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   The first scene is already being played out. The game's
competitive imbalance is the focus of a little study group
featuring the likes of George Mitchell and George Will.
</P>
<P>
   They'll talk about ways to give Expos, Twins and Pirates fans
hope that their boys of summer have a chance come September. Enough
hope, at least, to keep them buying tickets. Like as not, that will
mean suggesting some sort of restraint on player salaries coupled
with a modified form of franchise revenue sharing.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect too much from this committee _ it doesn't even
include representation from the players' union, which we know gets
hives at the very thought of a salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   But know that something must be done and soon. Either that or
there will be a strike/lockout to make us forget 1994 when the next
collective-bargaining agreement expires, probably after the 2001
season option year. Should that happen, baseball itself might
expire.
</P>
<P>
   When all parties get serious, though, television revenue,
specifically local TV money, ought to be at the crux of the debate,
for there lies the economic disparity that mocks the game. Anything
else is just a denial of reality, a treating of symptoms instead of
causes.
</P>
<P>
   Take the new stadiums opening or planned from Seattle to
Cincinnati, from San Francisco to Pittsburgh. A new ballpark
guarantees a franchise increased revenue from ticket sales, club
seats and suites, concessions and parking. That's swell. But soon
every club will have a new stadium and the relative benefits a
small market wannabe might earn from the latest pleasure palace
will be minimized.
</P>
<P>
   The economic impact of local TV rights means $55 million-plus a
year to George Steinbrenner's Yankees, but only $2 million or so
annually to a Montreal or Milwaukee. That disparity won't go away
without a major structural overhaul that takes more from the haves
and gives more to the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball owners and executives look longingly at the NFL's
set-up, where franchises share equally in national TV contract
booty, the league's cash cow and the equivalent of baseball's local
TV rights deals.
</P>
<P>
   That creates a financial parity allowing even a tiny city in
northern Wisconsin to compete successfully on the field against the
largest metropolises in America.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Rangers president Tom Schieffer even
called NFL elders ``wise'' for agreeing to split up network TV
revenue way back when. And smart they were, for recognizing that
the value of the New York football Giants is ultimately diminished
if teams in markets the size of Green Bay are forced by finances to
take on the role of Washington Generals _ patsies for the big
markets' Harlem Globetrotters act.
</P>
<P>
   Well, here's news: It's never too late to wise up.
</P>
<P>
   Split up that local TV money. The current revenue-sharing
formula reallocates some local TV cash among the poor, but not
nearly enough to address the yawning competitive gap. The Yankees,
for example, keep about 80 percent of their local media dollars and
only a few million of their $55 million annual haul goes
specifically for low revenue teams.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, local media revenue should be redistributed more evenly
among all 30 teams. If everyone got the same amount, each team
would earn nearly $13 million per year and the existing disparity
among franchises would be reduced if not eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Big-market clubs would, of course, resist such a plan. They
would argue that they paid higher franchise fees for the right to
profit from the lucrative media markets in which they operate.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, they would look at the big picture. They would realize
that a Yankees game on TV doesn't have much value unless there is a
Pittsburgh or a Milwaukee to provide the opposition. Or, they would
remember the NFL model and consider the situation of a Jerry Jones.
The Cowboys owner could make a pretty good case that his club
generates more network TV revenue than the Cincinnati Bengals or
the San Diego Chargers. But he's willing to take one for the game.
</P>
<P>
   If that appeal fails, perhaps a simple buyout would work.
Baseball could collectively take out a multibillion-dollar loan and
buy the local TV rights of each of its 30 teams at fair-market
value. From the Yankees down to the Expos, each franchise would be
paid a one-time fee for those rights, whether that meant $500
million or $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   That done, Major League Baseball would own all local media
rights. All revenue from future local broadcasting contracts would
be split equally among the 30 teams. Then, the only income
disparity would come from differences in stadium revenues. At last,
even the have-nots would have hope.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CHURCHES-NYT &LR;      04-02 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHURCHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PARTISAN CHURCHES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 3:
</P>
<P>
   Religious groups that want to engage in partisan politics have
every right to do so, but they must play by the same rules as
everyone else. A U.S. District Court judge defended this principle
this week when he ruled that a church engaging in blatantly
partisan activities can be stripped of its tax-exempt status and
its right to receive tax-deductible contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The case involved the Church at Pierce Creek in upstate New
York, which a few days before the 1992 presidential election took
out full-page ads in USA Today and The Washington Times. The ads
warned, ``Christian Beware,'' and asserted that Bill Clinton
supported ``policies that are in rebellion to God's laws.''
</P>
<P>
   They also asked ``How then can we vote for Bill Clinton?'' At
the bottom of the page was a notice that the ad had been sponsored
by the church and its pastor, and that ``Tax-deductible donations
for this advertisement gladly accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax code states that tax-exempt status is available to
religious and charitable groups that do not participate in any
political campaign for or against any candidate. The New York
church brazenly violated that prohibition. Judge Paul Friedman
ruled that the IRS, in revoking the tax-exempt status, did not
violate the church's free exercise of religion or free speech. The
church can engage in partisan campaign activities, but it cannot
ask taxpayers to subsidize those activities.
</P>
<P>
   This case may also cause other churches to re-examine campaign
advocacy. A potential hazard are the millions of voter guides the
Christian Coalition distributes during election season. Some
churches have refused to pass out the guides for fear that they are
too partisan and could jeopardize their tax-exempt status. They are
right to be worried.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission has sued the coalition on
grounds that the voter guides were illegal campaign contributions
because they were coordinated with particular campaigns. The
coalition's own application for tax-exempt status is being reviewed
by the IRS, and the FEC suit that is pending could affect that
determination.
</P>
<P>
   The point of federal enforcement in both these cases is not to
silence religious organizations. The point is to make sure they
abide by federal tax and election spending and disclosure laws that
apply to others in the political arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
