<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELISSA-VIRUS-1STLD-W     04-02 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELISSA-VIRUS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.) 
N.J. SOFTWARE PROGRAMMER ARRESTED, CHARGED WITH LAUNCHING MELISSA
VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS throughout with updates and additional reporting.) (rk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ After a global search for the author of the
fastest-spreading computer virus in history, investigators in New
Jersey arrested a 30-year-old software programmer Thursday night
and charged him with writing and launching the now-famous Melissa
virus.
</P>
<P>
   The programmer, David L. Smith, 30, was taken into custody after
FBI agents and officials from America Online helped investigators
from the New Jersey attorney general's office hone in on the
Internet access provider that was apparently first used to send the
virus, which has now infected more than 100,000 computers
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the attorney general's Computer Analysis and
Technology Unit then spent three days sorting through records of
thousands of customers' files and electronic transmissions from the
provider, Monmouth Internet Corp. of Red Bank, N.J., and determined
that the telephone line used to send the first copy of the Melissa
virus was wired into Smith's apartment in Aberdeen Township,
according to Attorney General Peter J. Verniero.
</P>
<P>
   A law enforcement official who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said that the authorities had seized Smith's computer and
other records.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 26, when the virus was first uploaded to the
Internet newsgroup alt.sex from a stolen America Online account,
the Melissa virus spread like a malignant chain letter, invading
computer users' e-mail programs and sending itself to as many as 50
correspondents in each user's e-mail address book.
</P>
<P>
   By replicating and sending itself so rapidly, the virus clogged
and in some cases incapacitated computer networks at about 300
corporations, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Melissa was not as destructive as other viruses that
can destroy files or corrupt hard drives, technology experts say it
is an ominous threat to Internet commerce because it used a new,
and particularly efficient, method of transmission to replicate at
an extraordinarily rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that in the near future, viruses could spread
around the globe in a matter of an hour or two, and if it's a
destructive virus, do incredible amounts of damage,'' said Steve R.
White, senior manager of anti-virus research at IBM's Watson
Research Center in Hawthorne, N.Y. ``It's going to demand an entire
new way of combating them, new approaches and new technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said Smith, who apparently named the
virus after a topless dancer in Florida, was a programmer for a
software company that writes code for AT&AMP;T, but they would not
identify the company.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and acquaintances described him as a prototypical
computer zealot.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Trautmann, who lives one floor below Smith in the Ken Garden
apartment complex in Aberdeen, said he rarely ventured out of his
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very solitary person; he was a quiet neighbor,'' said
Ms. Trautmann, a quality assurance specialist at a software
company. ``I'd hear his modem go off once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who was arrested at his brother's apartment in Eatontown,
N.J., was charged with interruption of public communication, theft
of computer services and wrongful access to computer systems. He
was released on $100,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Distributing a computer virus is also a federal crime, but
Verniero said he doubted federal charges would be necessary because
the New Jersey statutes provided for a possible $480,000 fine and a
maximum prison sentence of 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smith was also charged with conspiracy to interrupt
public communication, Verniero would not say whether officials were
looking for other suspects. Some private anti-virus experts said
the so-called ``digital fingerprints'' on the code embedded in the
virus indicated there were at least two programmers involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Melissa virus was embedded into an e-mail attachment, and
designed to exploit a feature of the Microsoft Outlook e-mail
program, so that each time the infected document was opened, it
automatically sent itself out to as many as 50 other people.
Technology experts fear that other high tech saboteurs may use
similar techniques, known as worm programs, to transmit more
harmful viruses in the future, at speeds which far outpace the
current ability to prevent, detect or disable them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The investigation was one of a growing number of criminal
inquiries which raised uncomfortable issues about the privacy
rights of Internet users and the lengths to which Internet
providers may go to prevent the authorities from gaining access to
records of their customers' transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, which was exploring whether one of its own
accounts had been used to launch the virus, tipped off New Jersey
officials that the virus may have originated from a specific
Internet protocol address, which is a number that identifies a
given computer's Internet address, at a New Jersey Internet
provider, said Verniero.
</P>
<P>
   Mark R. Stevens, operations manager for Monmouth Internet, said
the company provided New Jersey investigators with a list of names
of 12 of its customers who on March 26 used that specific address
to send and receive information to the Internet. Among the
customers was David L. Smith, whose e-mail address was
Dlsmith(AT)monmouth.com, and who later canceled his account,
Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   The state police then tracked down the possible suspects by
using ``good old-fashioned detective work,'' said Verniero, who was
joined at the news conference by Gov. Christie Whitman. Both
Verniero and Whitman seemed to go to great lengths to praise the
work of the state police. The department has been the target of
widespread criticism in recent months over allegations of racial
bias.
</P>
<P>
   There was still widespread confusion yesterday about whether
Smith was actually the shadowy virus author known as VicodinES, who
has maintained a Web site on a Florida computer.
</P>
<P>
   At Verniero's news conference Friday, New Jersey law enforcement
officials said they believed that Smith had combined several
viruses including one created by VicodinES.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not Vicodin,'' said Paul M. Loriquet, a spokesman for
Verniero. ``He is not the Vicodin guy.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Richard Smith, an independent Cambridge, Mass.,
software developer who on Monday alerted FBI officials to the fact
that David Smith's name appeared in documents found on a
Florida-based Web site, said Friday that he still believed that
David Smith and VicodinES were the same person. He noted that in
early postings VicodinES said he was in Florida, and that
authorities said David Smith had moved to New Jersey from Florida.
In addition, he said he had found David Smith's name in the
documents posted to the Vicodin web site as far back as July of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   One document written about viruses by VicodinES and signed
``peace, VIC'' on July 5, 1998, contained a notation that listed
David Smith as the most recent author, said Richard Smith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-02-99 2307EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990402.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     04-02 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR HARRICK, AN HONOR THAT STINGS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spirit of rewarding deeds at the appropriate level, I
have come up with an annual post-season collegiate athletic award
of my own: the Great Barracuda Award.
</P>
<P>
   This award acknowledges the college coach who exemplifies the
most mercenary attitude toward athletes and a particular university
over the course of a season. The award takes its name from that
ferocious tropical fish that lashes out and attacks anything that
gleams.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural Barracuda winner is Jim Harrick, the former Rhode
Island head coach and a hands-down selection. Harrick secured the
award this week with a last-minute maneuver that left one
university looking foolish and left another to burn in the ashes of
its own ambition. I've watched Harrick for 15 years; this, by far,
is his best lowest moment.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Harrick, 60, ended a two-year stint at the
University of Rhode Island when he accepted the head coaching job
at Georgia. Or so it seemed. On Thursday morning, he called Michael
F. Adams, the University of Georgia president, and told him that he
had had a change of heart and was returning to Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Elated officials at Rhode Island subsequently arranged a spate
of happy welcome back meetings: Harrick would meet with Rhode
Island players at 5:30 p.m., with boosters at 6 p.m. and finally
the news media at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick stood up his players, and then at 6:10 called Rhode
Island officials to tell them he had changed his mind again and
decided to take the job at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the span of 24 hours,'' one school official said Friday,
``we went from disappointment that he was leaving, being stunned
that he was coming back, to disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick's explanation was that he got ``all wrapped up in my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is innocent in this deal. Rhode Island entered into a
shaky covenant with Harrick in May 1997. Harrick needed a job,
Rhode Island wanted to go big and big time, and Harrick was
available at a bargain price.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick had guided UCLA to the 1995 national championship but
was fired the next year on charges that he falsified an expense
report in order to cover up a potential NCAA recruiting violation.
</P>
<P>
   But there were misgivings from the moment his name was mentioned
at Rhode Island. Segments of the university's faculty were not
pleased. They felt that hiring Harrick would send out the wrong
message by a school that had already suffered from the exposure of
a 1992 gambling ring that involved athletes and an incident in 1996
in which members of the football team attacked a fraternity house.
</P>
<P>
   I was on campus when Robert Carothers, the Rhode Island
president, introduced Harrick that May afternoon. Carothers
prefaced his remarks by describing the coach as a hero who reaches
the pinnacle and then falls. ``There is a moment of recognition and
realization in which the fallen hero realizes his flaw and
expresses contrition,'' Carothers said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the preacher tuned into an unsuspecting flock, Harrick gave
Rhode Island his word that he would never leave for another college
job. In November 1997, two games into his first season with Rhode
Island, he said: ``I don't want another college job. Now you never
know what happens in the future. There might be somebody that comes
in and gives you something you absolutely no way can refuse. But
that's not going to happen to me in college. This is not a stepping
stone for me. I'm not in that era. This is a fresh start for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick took the Rams to the big time. They made the NCAA
tournament both seasons, and the first season he came within a
minute of reaching the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   After this season, Adams, the Georgia president, of all people,
told Harrick that staying at Rhode Island would be a mistake. Then
in the ultimate contradiction of this entire charade, Adams told
Harrick that Georgia wanted ``a coach who was committed to this
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Are you kidding me?
</P>
<P>
   Harrick never had that moment of recognition. Though Friday in
Athens, Ga., a contrite Harrick swore this was it. ``I can say this
has been an experience I don't want to go through again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick earned about $350,000 last season at Rhode Island. He
will make a reported $550,000 a year at Georgia _ plus $100,000 a
year if he completes his four-year contract. For Georgia fans, that
is a tremendous if. Just let the NBA come calling with one of those
multimillion-dollar contracts.
</P>
<P>
   This is the essence of the Barracuda: a ferocious fish that
strikes at anything that gleams _ or in this case, anything that
glitters.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow I get the feeling Jim Harrick will be my first two-time
recipient. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
