<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-HARASSMENT-     04-02 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-HARASSMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR HEARS A PERSONAL STORY OF POLICE HARASSMENT FROM HIS OWN
DEPUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DIALLO-KILLING) 
(DW) 
 By DAN BARRY   and KEVIN FLYNN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the height of the public furor over the police
shooting of Amadou Diallo, Deputy Mayor Rudy Washington _ the
highest-ranking black member of the Giuliani administration _ told
Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani that he had been harassed more than once
by police officers for what he considered to be racial reasons,
according to people close to the administration.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting last week that was attended by other top-level
aides, Washington gave examples of how he had been hassled, even
bullied, by the police. They included an episode in which the
deputy mayor's car was pulled over by the police in Queens, the
people close to the administration said. The confrontation that
followed was so traumatic, he told the mayor, that his wife began
to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Washington declined Friday to talk about what he told the mayor
or to share his reflections as the man who often accompanies
Giuliani on visits to Harlem and other black neighborhoods in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Friday night that he would abide by the deputy
mayor's wishes to keep their discussion private. `` ``But I can
tell you that it will be very useful in the analysis of this
situation,'' he said. ``He's exceptionally insightful.''
</P>
<P>
   Many black and Hispanic residents have long complained that some
officers are overly aggressive and even abusive in policing
minority neighborhoods. Since the Diallo shooting, those complaints
have intensified, with even businessmen, ministers and other
prominent black New Yorkers saying they have sometimes been stopped
or searched by the police without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's testimony was only one of dozens of personal
accounts that the mayor has heard since Feb. 4, when four white
police officers killed Diallo, a West African immigrant, in a hail
of bullets in the Bronx. Without referring to Washington, the mayor
said that these discussions _ with adolescent children and civic
leaders alike _ will be ``very valuable'' in his plan to improve
relations between the police and city residents.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the recounting of these incidents has been
upsetting, Giuliani answered: ``Of course they are. What you would
want the police to do is to always treat them respectfully. We have
tried very hard to teach them that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Giuliani said, he has asked those he has met
with to go back to those who ``try to create an exaggerated, false
impression of the police and to get them to deal with the police in
a more respectful way.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting at which Washington spoke out came during the week
when, in the face of growing criticism of his response to the
Diallo shooting, the mayor launched a major effort to reach out to
black and Hispanic leaders. It could not be determined Friday
night, however, whether the mayor heard Washington's account before
or after setting up those sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting death of Diallo has led to the indictments of the
four officers, ignited demonstrations and brought drastic changes
to the elite Street Crime Unit, to which the four officers belong.
It has also presented Giuliani with one of the most trying
challenges of his five-year tenure as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has struggled _ not always successfully, some say _ to
defend the Police Department while expressing empathy for black and
Hispanic residents who say that the police frequently harass them,
sometimes to the point of using excessive force. His aides say that
he wants to strike a balanced response that signals ``zero
tolerance'' for police misbehavior yet provides encouragement to
the majority of the city's 40,000 officers who do their job well.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a spokeswoman for Police Commissioner Howard
Safir, said Friday night that police officials were not aware of
any incident involving Washington.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   OPTIONAL CUT. STORY CAN END HERE.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Washington, 44, is a former general contractor who has waged
several unsuccessful runs for public office in Queens. Although he
is the most prominent black member of the administration,
Washington is not usually counted among the mayor's closest
advisers. Several of the city's black leaders said that while he is
generally well-liked, he has been an ineffective liaison to black
and Hispanic neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Details of his encounter with the police in Queens remained
sketchy Friday night, but people close to the administration said
that Washington told the mayor he felt bullied by the officer who
pulled him over, and he indicated that the treatment was related to
his race. It was not clear why the deputy mayor was pulled over.
</P>
<P>
   As Washington described it, the incident might have escalated
further, but a police official passed by, recognized him as a
deputy mayor and intervened. The people who described Washington's
account said he also mentioned other experiences, but further
details could not be learned Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that he has heard other disturbing accounts of
harassment over the last several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Rev. Floyd Flake, a prominent Queens clergyman
and former congressman who is one of Giuliani's leading black
supporters, said recently that he too had been insulted by police
because of his race. He recalled that a few years ago, when he was
still a member of Congress, a police officer in Queens used a
racial slur to address him.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said Friday night that Flake had mentioned the
incident to him. ``He shared with me his own incident,'' Giuliani
said. ``And he shared with me, in a generic way, descriptions from
his congregants that involved police officers stopping people and
not acting in a respectful way.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani cited one story in particular, told to him by the
mother of a child who had come with a youth group to discuss
experiences with the police. The woman told him that the police
stopped her, frisked her and then left, leaving her feeling
humiliated and angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after it was over, the female officer who was involved
came back to explain why she had done it and apologized,'' he said.
``That made a great deal of difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things that's missing,'' the mayor said.
``They don't often enough do that.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, he has heard of cases in which the police
stop and search innocent people during a crime investigation, but
then leave without an explanation or apology. ``So the person would
leave without any understanding of why this had happened,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
