</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-CRASH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman trapped by seat belt as passenger train bore down
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat and A. Scharnhorst
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As the Amtrak Silver Meteor charged
toward them, Michelle Fuente and Caroline Taveras had just enough
time to throw open the doors of the black Oldsmobile and race out
of the train's path. In the back seat, 19-year-old Jennifer Fuente
was trapped, struggling with her seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Fuente died Thursday night in the back of her parents'
Oldsmobile, as the force of the passenger train shoved the car
1,200 feet down the track, twisting it into the shape of a sickle.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Fuente _ Jennifer's 22-year-old sister _ had stopped
the Oldsmobile just before 8 p.m. in a westbound lane of Summit
Boulevard as the warning lights began flashing at the CSX railroad
crossing, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   Behind them, Pablo Valle, trying to beat the train, sped his
Ford Mustang toward the tracks as the crossing gates started to
come down, witnesses said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Valle's passengers tried to warn him: ``We said `Stop! Stop!' ''
said Julio Cordero, 12, who was in the Mustang's back seat, ``and
the boy in the front seat yelled, `Watch out!' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Valle misjudged the distance between the cars and the right
front of the Mustang clipped the left rear of the Oldsmobile,
spinning both cars into the train crossing, investigators said. The
Fuentes' car turned 180 degrees and came to rest on the tracks
facing east. Valle's car stopped about 50 feet west of the tracks,
facing northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer ``had time to get out, but she couldn't take the seat
belt off,'' Julio said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Highway Patrol investigators said it appeared Valle was
not paying attention, but they have not decided whether to file
charges, said Lt. Pembrook Burrows. It will take about a month to
complete toxicology tests and present a case to the state
attorney's office, Burrows said.
</P>
<P>
   Valle wasn't supposed to be on the road: His driver license has
been suspended since late last year after he failed to pay a
traffic ticket, records show. He has had several tickets since
then. He could not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Fuente, of Lake Clarke Shores, had minor injuries.
Valle, 33, of West Palm Beach and two of his four teen-age
passengers also were hurt, the FHP said. They were treated at St.
Mary's Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Taveras, 19, of suburban West Palm Beach, was more seriously
injured and was hospitalized at St. Mary's. She was in fair
condition Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
