<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S THOMAS WON'T RECEIVE RELEASE UNTIL NEXT WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC freshman quarterback Jason Thomas still
intends to transfer, but he will not receive his official release
before next week.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' parents met with USC athletic director Mike Garrett,
coach Paul Hackett, offensive coordinator Hue Jackson and
quarterbacks coach Ken O'Brien on Friday. Jason Thomas did not
attend the meeting because he had a class.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Hackett was hopeful that Thomas could remain
at USC, but his father said nothing had changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them Jason wants to leave. We're coming to a meeting
of the minds that they won't hold him back,'' Charles Thomas said.
``I got the impression they are grudgingly resigning themselves to
the fact Jason is going to leave but they want Jason to tell
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Thomas and his family are scheduled to meet with Garrett
and Hackett on Tuesday, and Thomas is expected to ask for his
formal release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to change anything,'' Charles Thomas
said. ``Jason isn't returning to spring practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what it would take for his son to stay at USC, Charles
Thomas said, ``Unless Hackett calls a press conference to say Jason
is going to be given a 50-50 shot to start at USC.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Thomas has said his son was unhappy after being told by
Hackett he would compete with Mike Van Raaphorst for the No. 2
quarterback spot. Thomas wants a chance to challenge starter Carson
Palmer in USC's spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett was still optimistic Friday about Thomas' situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very, very positive meeting,'' Hackett said. ``It was
about the state of affairs here how USC and Jason Thomas can be a
successful match. There's a digesting process going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Thomas said his son has not decided where he will
transfer. He did say that former USC coach John Robinson, currently
at Nevada-Las Vegas, has spoken to Jackson, and said the Rebels
were prepared to build their offense around Thomas if he
transferred to UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say Vegas would have as good a shot as anyone else,''
Charles Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   USC has informed Charles Thomas that it will not allow Jason to
transfer to a Pacific-10 Conference school.
</P>
</TEXT>
