<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WOODEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAND WINS WOODEN AWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If they had voted Tuesday, after Connecticut's
Richard Hamilton scored 27 points in the national title game, it
might have been different.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Wooden Award ballots were due March 22 _ before the
Final Four _ and Duke's Elton Brand was the the easy winner Friday
with 4,312 votes. Hamilton finished fifth (2,865 votes), behind
Utah point guard Andre Miller, Miami (Ohio) forward Wally
Szczerbiak, and Michigan State point guard Mateen Cleaves.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was no surprise. Brand, a 6-foot-8 sophomore
forward, has dominated the postseason awards as Duke dominated the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all mean a lot,'' he said, ``but some mean a little more
than others _ like this one, because of the players that have won
it before me and (having) John Wooden's name on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The finalists seemingly spanned the spectrum of college
commitment. Miller and Szczerbiak stayed through their senior
seasons, while Brand, Hamilton and Cleaves are considering early
departures for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone through school the conventional way,'' said
Szczerbiak, who with 23.7 points and 8.9 rebounds this season is
expected to be a top-five pick. ``I didn't start as a freshman and
... I broke out as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only this year was I vaulted into the spotlight and looked at
like a real NBA prospect. I had to stay, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not the case with Brand, also a likely top-five pick,
and Hamilton, whose draft value soared with his Final Four
performance. Both said they will discuss their options in the
coming weeks. Brand would be the first Duke player to leave early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in any rush, but it seems everyone else is,'' Brand
said.
</P>
<P>
   Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski will undergo hip replacement surgery
Monday and did not attend the award ceremony at the L.A. Athletic
Club.
</P>
<P>
   New award: Former North Carolina coach Dean Smith received the
inaugural Legends of Coaching Award for lifetime contributions. In
addition to winning two NCAA titles and coaching Michael Jordan,
James Worthy, Mitch Kupchak and Phil Ford, Smith was one of the
game's great innovators. He popularized multiple substitutions,
changing defense and the four-corners offense.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about reports that Jordan will play for the Charlotte
Hornets and Smith will become an executive with the team, Smith
said, ``I have no interest in moving from Chapel Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the Day: Miller, asked about the possibility of being
drafted by the Clippers: ``That's the last team I'd want to play
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the Day II: Wooden, asked about UCLA coach Steve
Lavin's new $578,000 contract: ``I've always said I don't think
coaches should receive more than heads of departments in college.
But if they'd given me more than $32,500 my last year, I'd have
taken it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
