<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4494 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD     04-02 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO STRIKES BELGRADE FOR FIRST TIME: INTERIOR MINISTRIES IN
FLAMES
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS 5th graf to add location of defense ministry and Army
headquarters buildings; 8th graf to change `REGIME' to
`GOVERNMENT';12th graf for details on launched missiles; 1st graf
after optional trim to add info on fuel rationing.)  (ac)  
  
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Cruise missile explosions shook downtown
Belgrade early Saturday morning, devastating both the Yugoslav and
Serbian Interior Ministry buildings and sending flames at least 12
stories high.
</P>
<P>
   A series of enormous blasts wrenched a rainy Belgrade awake at
about 1 a.m. Saturday, the first time in 10 days of NATO airstrikes
that the heavily populated center of the Yugoslav capital was hit.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters and emergency workers rushed to the area but seemed
unable to control the fires, which swept through the concrete and
glass buildings. Instead they struggled to keep the fires from
spreading to other buildings in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The two buildings face one another across Kneza Milosa and are
only a few hundred yards from a large university medical complex
that contains 4,000 of Belgrade's 5,000 hospital beds, according to
the city's deputy mayor, Milan Bozic.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav Defense Ministry and Army general headquarters are
farther up the street from the interior ministries.
</P>
<P>
   As the flames burned through the buildings, the street lights
along Kneza Milosa continued to function.
</P>
<P>
   The missile strikes made good on NATO's vow to bring the war in
Kosovo home to the Serbian and Yugoslav power structure of
President Slobodan Milosevic, but it was unclear whether they would
hasten an end to his war in the southern Serb province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It is the troops and police of the Interior Ministry who have
been most responsible for the war against the Kosovo Liberation
Army and for driving ethnic Albanian civilians from their homes in
Kosovo province. While NATO has been attacking police and army
units in Kosovo, this is the first attack on the central
headquarters of the security forces that are an important pillar of
Milosevic's government.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear if there were any people in the
buildings, after all of NATO's warnings over the past few days that
government buildings would be hit in downtown Belgrade. If there
were people inside, it was hard to imagine that they could survive
the conflagrations.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rainy night in Belgrade, with cloud cover, but the
cruise missiles are unaffected by clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian state television immediately began broadcasting pictures
of the destruction and the flames, video that was immediately
picked up and broadcasted around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said seven cruise missiles had been launched
from American ships and an eighth was launched from a British
submarine at an undisclosed target.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's attacks against air-defense systems and units in
Kosovo have so far failed to stop the Serbian offensive against the
ethnic Albanians, NATO officials have warned that its targets would
be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes marked a sharp escalation _ to Phase 3, as NATO
calls it _ in the campaign to force Milosevic to accept a
Western-drafted peace plan for nearly complete autonomy for Kosovo
that would include the introduction of nearly 30,000 NATO
peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, NATO forces blasted bridges, army barracks and other
targets, while Yugoslavia responded with television reports about
the three servicemen who were captured. To bolster Yugoslavia's
argument that the men were captured inside Kosovo, and not in
Macedonia, television showed interviews with villagers in
Slavujedac, on the Kosovo side, saying that the men's Humvee had
traveled through the town and did not stop when ordered to do so by
Yugoslav officers.
</P>
<P>
   The official Tanjug news agency quoted a Pristina official,
Jovica Jovanovic, saying that a military court has opened an
investigation into the case of the three soldiers, collecting
evidence to see if they should be brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
   There was no response to President Clinton's demands that they
be released, and no indication of where they were being held.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To gear up for hard times, the Yugoslav government said it would
start rationing gasoline and diesel fuel. Vehicle owners would be
able to get fuel coupons from the police.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Milosevic moved to control one of the few remaining
sources of independent journalism here, Radio B-92. B-92, which had
its transmitter disabled just before the bombs fell but which was
broadcasting on satellite and the internet, was silenced early
Friday morning. Police arrived and the general manager was fired
and replaced by a Milosevic loyalist, putting the station
effectively under government control. The staff was instructed to
go home and return on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the mandatory work rules in effect during this state of
war, the staff may be prosecuted if they do not work to the beat of
the new drummer. But the station's editor-in-chief, Veran Matic,
vowed at a press conference not to ``collaborate'' and said the
regime wanted to destroy one of the last symbols of a free press
here.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, a number of other independent newspapers and
radio stations were closed throughout Kosovo, as well as Radio 021
in Novi Sad, Serbia's second-largest city.
</P>
</TEXT>
